<HEADLINE>
STUDY LOOKS AT NURSING HOME COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With the nursing home industry facing greater
scrutiny, an arm of the Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. has
reported that the average cost of a nursing home stay in the United
States is $153 per day.
</P>
<P>
   But the study by MetLife Mature Market Institute noted big cost
variations for private rooms in different metropolitan areas. The
most expensive rooms can be found in New York City, where the
average cost is $295 a day. The least expensive rooms, at an
average of $90 a day, were found in Hibbing, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing home rooms in the Kansas City area were found to have an
average daily cost of $117, which made Kansas City the
16th-most-affordable metropolitan area in the 90-city study.
</P>
<P>
   The study also looked at the cost of home health care, which it
calculated at an average cost of $16 an hour nationally. Home
health care costs from licensed agencies ranged from an average of
$12 an hour in San Antonio to $24 an hour in Hartford, Conn. The
average cost in Kansas City was calculated at $16 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Deanne Lenhart, executive director of the nonprofit Kansas
Advocates for Better Care, based in Lawrence, said the nursing home
cost figures are relatively high because they are based on rates
for private rooms. But most nursing home residents in the United
States actually have semiprivate rooms, which are not as expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Lenhart said, the majority of nursing home residents
around the country have their costs paid for by Medicaid, the
state-federal health program for people who have used up their
financial assets.
</P>
<P>
   However, nursing home care still presents a financial burden for
many, Lenhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some places will nickel-and-dime you to death for charges on
certain things, because different nursing homes have different
definitions on what constitutes standard supplies or standard
care,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Lenhart said, some nursing homes charge extra to
serve residents meals in their rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The average stay in a nursing home is 2 1/2 years, said Sandra
Timmermann, director of the MetLife Mature Market Institute, in a
news release.
</P>
<P>
   The cost figures were released at a time when elderly adults
represent the fastest-growing segment of the U.S. population, and
more senior citizens and their families are having to make
decisions about long-term care.
</P>
<P>
   Timmermann said the cost figures could help consumers decide
where they should retire and whether they should obtain long-term
care insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The projected average cost for one person is $55,000 per year,
or $139,500 for the average 21/2 years, causing many families to
spend down their assets,'' Timmermann said.
</P>
<P>
   The study was conducted this year in the 48 contiguous states.
More than 435 nursing homes and 219 home health agencies were
contacted.
</P>
<P>
   There are 17,000 nursing home facilities in the United States,
with 1.8 million beds and 1.6 million residents, according to the
National Center for Health Statistics of the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Problems involving nursing homes have attracted wide attention
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials recently concluded that most nursing homes are
understaffed to the point that patients may be in danger. Kansas
and Missouri were cited among the states in which understaffing is
the most severe.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Missouri officials said low wages were
driving down the quality of care at Missouri nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Several big nursing home operators around the country have filed
for bankruptcy protection in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is recommending strict new rules that
would require thousands of nursing homes to hire more nurses and
nurse's aides.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing home officials have said it is unrealistic for the
government to specify minimum levels of staffing when they are
receiving what they characterize as inadequate payments under the
Medicaid and Medicare programs.
</P>
<P>
   Like hospitals and other health care providers, nursing homes
are lobbying Congress to restore money cut from Medicare in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
