<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVOLUTION-CAMPAIGN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE BENEFITS FROM EVOLUTION DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ During the last year, Kansas' flap over
evolution has represented a question of local control to some and a
statewide embarrassment to others.
</P>
<P>
   But for Linda Holloway's re-election campaign for the Kansas
Board of Education, it has meant one more thing: money.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, who led the board last August when it approved new
science standards omitting references to some aspects of
evolutionary theory, raised almost $90,000 in campaign
contributions from January through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That's nine times as much as Holloway, a conservative Republican
from Shawnee, Kan., raised when she first ran for the board in
1996. And it's more than twice the amount raised by her current
challenger, moderate Republican Sue Gamble of Shawnee, with
$36,000.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising by Holloway, 50, and Gamble, 58, makes their
2nd District race the most expensive ever for the state board.
</P>
<P>
   Contests for seats on the 10-member board usually attract little
or no attention. But this year, elevated by the battle over
evolution, races for the five seats up for grabs are as
high-profile as some congressional contests.
</P>
<P>
   The money flowing into the campaigns is proof of that, said
Burdett Loomis, a University of Kansas political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exceptional situation where you have national
attention being focused on this race,'' Loomis said. ``A lot of
people clearly found this an important issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway agreed. She said her successful fund-raising validates
her August 1999 vote on the science standards, guidelines for
teaching and testing..
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of support for what we did,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a lot of opposition, too.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble, a 13-year member of the Shawnee Mission school board,
raised almost twice that of the next most successful fund-raiser,
moderate Republican Carol Rupe of Wichita, Kan. Rupe is challenging
incumbent conservative Republican Mary Douglass Brown of Wichita in
the 8th District state board primary.
</P>
<P>
   By pulling in more money than Gamble, Holloway has reversed a
state trend _ moderates usually out-raise conservatives, Loomis
said.
</P>
<P>
   The money allowed Holloway to buy $35,000 worth of television
ads and an advertisement in a national Christian magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The figures come from state campaign finance reports the
candidates filed Monday with the Kansas secretary of state's
office.
</P>
<P>
   According to the reports, 37 Holloway donors ponied up the $500
maximum; 22 of those were from outside the 2nd District, which
includes eastern Johnson County, Shawnee and Lake Quivira.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one Gamble donors _ six from outside the district _ gave
$500.
</P>
<P>
   But Gamble said she was pleased nonetheless. She said she raised
as much as she expected to when she went into the campaign last
September.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble reported $29,175 in itemized donations, or those over
$50; $5,100, or 18 percent, came from outside the district. That
amount included $1,300 from outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very grass-roots,'' Gamble said. ``It's very hands-on.
It's very personal. I probably know 75 percent of these people that
have sent me money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble listed every donation on her form, even those less than
$50.
</P>
<P>
   Included among her more prominent donors is Linda Graves, wife
of Gov. Bill Graves, who contributed $100. Current state board of
education members Val DeFever of Independence, Kan., and Janet
Waugh of Kansas City, Kan. each gave the Gamble campaign $100;
board member Sonny Rundell of Syracuse contributed $75.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway received more than four times as much money from
contributors outside the 2nd District as Gamble did.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Holloway reported $43,980 in itemized donations. Of
that amount, $22,370 _ or 51 percent _ came from sources outside
the district, including $2,925 from donors outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   Her $89,632 total includes a $15,000 personal loan to her
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Among Holloway's more prominent donors is intelligent design
supporter Phillip Johnson, a University of California-Berkeley law
professor, who gave $500, and former state board member Kevin
Gilmore of Olathe, Kan., who along with his wife, Julie, donated
$1,000. The Discovery Institute, a national thinktank that espouses
intelligent design, gave the Holloway campaign $500.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway counts grass-roots support, too. She listed $30,447.12
in unitemized contributions _ those under $50.
</P>
<P>
   But the massive fund-raising could have a down side, even for
the winner of Tuesday's contest, said Mark Tallman, a lobbyist with
the Kansas Association of School Boards and a longtime state board
observer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it becomes more of just a national battleground over who is
in control, I don't think that's healthy,'' Tallman said. ``Is it a
deterrent (to future candidates) if they spend too much?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
