<SLUG> BC-SHOOK-LAWYERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM OF LAWYERS TO LEAVE BLACKWELL FIRM TO JOIN SHOOK HARDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A group of environmental lawyers at Blackwell
Sanders Peper Martin is leaving the firm and joining Shook Hardy &AMP;
Bacon, which has been busy trying to diversify its practice by
recruiting lawyers in hot growth areas.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which may consist of as many as nine lawyers, makes
up most of Blackwell's environmental practice group. The group
plans to hook up with Shook in the next few days and practice out
of the firm's Corporate Woods office in Overland Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Environmental law has been a very active area for us, but it's
an area where we haven't had the depth and strength we needed to
support a practice like this on a national level,'' said Robert
Grossman, a Shook lawyer who manages the firm's Corporate Woods
office.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell is wasting little time trying to fill the breach
created by the lawyers' exodus. The firm quickly imported an
environmental lawyer, Brad Hiles, from its St. Louis office and is
trying to recruit environmental lawyers from other legal shops in
Kansas City and elsewhere. The firm also hopes to persuade a couple
of lawyers to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's industry, attorneys are very mobile,'' said
Blackwell partner Dave Fenley. ``Firms who are growing will always
seek to find people from other law firms, just as we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell, with more than 300 lawyers, is the second-largest law
firm based in Kansas City and is best known for its corporate work,
particularly on behalf of long-time client UtiliCorp United Inc.
The firm has an active environmental practice and most recently
represented property owners in a class-action lawsuit involving the
Amoco refinery in Sugar Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Shook, with 460 lawyers, is the city's biggest law firm and is
widely known for its tobacco and pharmaceutical defense work. The
firm represents three of the Big Five tobacco companies, including
top cigarette maker Philip Morris Co., and has been one of the
leading industry defenders for four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Shook had never lost a tobacco case until a couple of years ago,
when the seemingly impregnable legal fortress constructed by Shook
began to crumble in the face of disclosures that the industry had
concealed the dangers of smoking for decades.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a long-term strategy to broaden its practice beyond
its mainstay tobacco and drug work, Shook in recent years has
ventured into a variety of growth-oriented practice areas,
particularly intellectual property, energy and telecommunications
law. The firm also has expanded geographically, opening several
offices abroad and in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Shook grossed $170 million in 1999, according to the magazine
The American Lawyer, good enough to rank 75th among the top
grossing law firms in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Although Shook, as an offshoot of its product liability work,
has handled major environmental matters _ including toxic tort and
propane gas litigation _ its environmental practice has been
relatively small. The influx of as many as nine lawyers doing that
kind of work _ in addition to the recent recruitment of a couple of
prominent environmental lawyers at its Miami office _ will more
than triple the size of its environmental department.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a continuation of our strategic plan to have national
capabilities in all significant areas of litigation,'' said Shook
managing partner Pat McLarney. ``Environmental law is a very active
area, and we saw this as an opportunity to really strengthen our
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading the group of lawyers joining Shook are Blackwell
partners David Erickson and Mark Anstoetter, who submitted their
resignations to Blackwell on Friday. Although they hope to join
Shook this week, Blackwell may not let them do so because their
partnership agreement has a 90-day notice provision.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Erickson and Anstoetter at Shook are Blackwell senior
counsel Sarah T. Sullivan and four to six associates.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers' departure comes about a month after six Blackwell
lawyers left the firm to form a new in-house legal department at
UtiliCorp. That group was led by Les Parrette Jr., who headed
Blackwell's international practice group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
