<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SHUT OUT EXPOS, 5-0 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ General Manager Steve Phillips sat comfortably in the
first-base dugout at Shea Stadium, answering questions about his
wishes and his hopes for making the New York Mets better. Phillips
never mentioned Curt Schilling's name, but he talked about a
specific starting pitcher who would immediately improve the Mets,
and it was obvious that he was referring to Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   Glendon Rusch is not Curt Schilling. When you mention Schilling
to Rusch, the 25-year-old Mets left-hander gets an innocent look
because he knows Schilling is in another echelon. Still, four hours
after Phillips discussed a superb pitcher without mentioning his
name, Rusch was the only pitcher worth mentioning in the clubhouse
on Tuesday night because he had just guided the Mets to a 5-0
victory over the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch's results were as impressive as those Schilling or any
other pitcher could have provided; on a night in which Rusch felt
listless, he still stopped Montreal on three hits over seven
innings. While Rusch did not have a crisp repertory and walked four
batters, as many as he had walked in his preceding six starts, he
pushed and plodded on this windy night until he succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a determined young man who wants to make his mark,''
Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``He works harder between starts to
get better. He's been a godsend for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to overlook how dependable Rusch has been at the back
end of the Mets' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, he came into the season with a 12-25 career record and
was not even guaranteed to be in the majors. Rusch is quiet and he
does not throw hard, but he has worked at least six innings in 15
of his 18 starts, he has allowed three earned runs or less 13 times
and he is a deceiving 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone would have predicted Glendon to be the
kind of pitcher he has been for us,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Rusch. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had confidence going into spring training,'' Rusch said. ``I
thought I could help the team. It's tough to predict what you can
do in a season. But I thought I could help the team every time out
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
