r n BC-SIERRA-TIMBERLAND-SFC     07-26 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-TIMBERLAND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMPANY HALTS CALAVERAS CLEAR-CUTTING PROJECT  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Facing increasing opposition to its plans to clear-cut
timberland in the Sierra Nevada, Sierra Pacific Industries has put
a moratorium on logging in Calaveras County and plans to reassess
its harvesting strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-day moratorium covers about 900 acres of proposed
clear-cuts near the small mountain town of Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   When Sierra Pacific began logging near Arnold earlier this year,
it galvanized fierce opposition from local residents and focused a
spotlight on the company's long-term plans for its land in the
Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Pacific owns 1.5 million acres of land in California _ 1
percent of the state's surface area. Its basic logging plan calls
for clear-cutting and replanting about 1 million acres of its
holdings during the next 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   The company maintains that its plans will actually improve
forest cover. Many areas that have already been selectively logged
one or more times will be converted into well-stocked stands of
young conifers, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists say the huge clear-cutting project will
destroy the biological integrity of the Sierra Nevada, turning vast
regions of rich, mature forest into tree plantations and driving
several endangered species of wildlife into extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the company's policies has swelled steadily in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Protests have been going on not only in Arnold, but also in the
watershed of the Middle Fork of the Yuba River on the border of
Sierra and Nevada counties. There, Sierra Pacific is logging 1,300
acres by a variety of methods, including clear-cutting.
</P>
<P>
   The two areas of protest represent different constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   In the Yuba watershed, the protesters _ who call themselves Yuba
Nation _ are similar to those who fought the Headwaters Forest
battle on California's North Coast: generally young, often
affiliated with uncompromising groups such as Earth First, and
disposed to guerrilla disruption tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a group of Yuba Nation protesters briefly occupied
Sierra Pacific's Grass Valley office complex.
</P>
<P>
   But in Arnold, real estate agents, small-business owners and
retirees are leading the fight against Sierra Pacific. They are
representatives of the ``New Sierra'' _ well-educated immigrants
from metropolitan areas, including the Bay Area and Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   In a reference to the two groups of protesters, Dan Tomascheski,
Sierra Pacific's vice president of resources, said the moratorium
decision was made after determining ``who had legitimate concerns
and who came from the environmental fringe and wouldn't be happy
unless we gave them the entire forest.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomascheski said Sierra Pacific will re-evaluate all the areas
the company was planning to log in the next three years. ``We'll
look at modifications that might be appropriate,'' he said, noting
that clear-cutting may be reduced in favor of selective cutting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have other harvest plans'' that have not yet been
approved by the California Department of Forestry and Fire
Protection, which oversees logging on state and private forest
lands, Tomascheski said. ``We'll be looking at those as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Alford, a conservation organizer for the Sierra Club who
has helped lead the opposition against Sierra Pacific in the Arnold
area, said the moratorium is extremely significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tiny mountain community unified against a giant timber
baron, and the giant blinked,'' Alford said. ``The reason this
means so much is that they have always thumbed their noses at their
critics. This represents a tremendous departure from their standard
way of doing things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
