<HEADER>
A3193 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLA     07-26 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN GETS A BREAK _ NOT THAT HE WANTED IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ For the Anaheim Angels' first 100 games, Mo
Vaughn's name could be found in the starting lineup without fail.
For game No. 101 on Tuesday night at the Ballpark in Arlington,
however, Vaughn's name was not in the starting lineup. Not at first
base, not as the DH.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong. Manager Mike Scioscia just decided it
was a good time to give Vaughn a break. Asked what Vaughn's
reaction was when told he wouldn't be in starting, Scioscia said:
``He looked at me like I had four heads.''
</P>
<P>
   He understands the grind of the whole season,'' Scioscia said.
``He's been on a mission to play every day. He is an everyday
player, but to me, an everyday player doesn't mean playing in all
162 games. Mo needed a day to catch his breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he understood. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taking care of all of us,'' said Vaughn, who began the
day hitting .298 with 25 homers and a team-leading 77 RBI. ``Nobody
on the ballclub will ask for it (a day off). Do I like it? No. I
want to play every day I can possibly play. I know it's best for
the team over the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's starting pitcher for the Rangers was Darren Oliver,
the same pitcher who hit Vaughn in the head with a pitch last week
in Anaheim. But Scioscia said: ``It's a day off, plain and simple.
It was my call, he did not ask for it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ More records for Erstad: Darin Erstad is having a
record-breaking season, and he added another in Monday's wild game.
Erstad had 12 outfield putouts, tying the major-league mark
accomplished 12 times previously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I celebrated by sleeping,'' Erstad said. ``I noticed by the
sixth or seventh inning I was getting a lot of fly balls. But when
I'm 50, I'm not going to look back on it and have a smile on my
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad remains on a pace to establish the all-time record for
hits in a single season. Going into Tuesday's game, he had 163 hits
in the team's first 100 games, a pace for 264. The major-league
record is 257, held by George Sisler of the St. Louis Browns _ set
in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   In order to break the record, Erstad needs to average 1.54 hits
per game in the final 62 games. Through the first 100, he averaged
1.63.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Pitcher Scott Schoeneweis was activated from
the DL after Tuesday's game and will start tonight. . . . Pitcher
Kent Mercker threw two innings of a simulated game Monday and says
he's ready to pitch in the majors. But Scioscia said he's ``very
close'' to a rehab assignment, but there's a chance he'll need
another simulated game. . . . Shortstop Benji Gil is expected to
rejoin the team today in Texas. He returned to Orange County on
Monday for the birth of his first child, a boy, Mateo Elijah Gil,
born Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
