<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     07-26 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CRUSH ORIOLES, 19-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Los Angeles Dodgers needed a shortstop this year
and they had Jose Vizcaino, but they wanted to give the job to Alex
Cora instead. When Cora floundered in spring training, the Dodgers
hired Kevin Elster, the twice-retired infielder and actor. And when
the Dodgers needed a second baseman, they didn't use Vizcaino; they
moved shortstop Mark Grudzielanek to the position.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Dodgers packaged Vizcaino and $500,000 in cash
to convince the New York Yankees to take him, in return for Jim
Leyritz. It's safe to say the Dodgers were sure Vizcaino couldn't
help them.
</P>
<P>
   But Vizcaino is helping the Yankees, substantively, wearing
protective goggles that no image-conscious high school student
would be caught wearing in gym class. Making his 13th start at
second base for the Yankees, Vizcaino slapped four hits and scored
four runs as the Yankees scorched the Orioles, 19-1, at Camden
Yards, their third consecutive triumph and 15th in 21 games. The
Yankees (53-42) are in first place by three games.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander Andy Pettitte became the team's first 10-game
winner, shutting out the Orioles for seven innings. Pettitte worked
almost without incident until the sixth, Baltimore loaded the
bases, but then Pettitte struck out Charles Johnson and retired
Will Clark on a grounder to first baseman Tino Martinez, who made a
diving stop and threw to Pettitte to close the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were in control by then, their lead in
double-digits. Bernie Williams crushed a grand slam and drove in
five runs, leaving him with 94 runs batted in, only 36 short of the
single-season record for switch-hitters, shared by Mickey Mantle
and Ken Caminiti. Derek Jeter had two hits, including a two-run
homer, and Paul O'Neill, Ryan Thompson and Clay Bellinger also hit
homers. The Yankees had 20 hits, a season high.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' offense has surged since the All-Star Game break,
compiling 90 runs in 13 games, an average of almost 7 a game _ more
than a run over their average in the first half of the season.
David Justice has added stability to the middle of the order;
Jeter, Williams and O'Neill have recently produced hitting streaks.
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino, batting barely over .200 when the Dodgers dumped him,
is hitting .348 for the Yankees, his average increasing 37 points
with his four hits tonight _ although none of the singles would
inspire awe from the likes of Ted Williams. Vizcaino beat out an
infield single to lead off the game, rolled a hit through the
middle in the third, hustled to first and beat out a grounder to
short in the fourth and slapped a single through the left side of
the infield in the sixth. In other words, the distance of his hits
combined wouldn't match one modest Mark McGwire home run.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees are more than satisfied with Vizcaino, who is
taking on a greater role than expected. They got him on June 21,
about a week after Chuck Knoblauch's three-error game against the
Chicago White Sox, and at the time, it seemed that he might play
late in games, taking over for Knoblauch when the Yankees were
trying to protect a lead.
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino doesn't have any errors in his 25 games, and the
confidence with which he catches and throws the balls is markedly
different from the way in which Knoblauch fields his position. More
and more, Torre has started Vizcaino at second base and used
Knoblauch as his designated hitter. If the Yankees cannot acquire a
front-line left fielder before the July 31 trade deadline, that
trend will continue, with David Justice playing left instead of
serving regularly as the D.H. Torre remarked before tonight's game
how solid Vizcaino had been, how steady.
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino started in place of Knoblauch tonight, after Knoblauch
felt soreness in his right elbow, and scored in the first inning,
on O'Neill's single. With the Yankees holding a 1-0 edge after two
innings, it appeared that Pettitte and Baltimore's Scott Erickson
(5-8) were settling in for a duel of sinkerball pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees added three runs in the third inning and four
more in the fourth, O'Neill drilling a three-run homer that
increased the Yankees' advantage to 8-0. Jeter slammed his homer in
the sixth _ his 10th of the year _ before the Orioles collapsed in
the seventh. The Yankees loaded the bases against Chuck McElroy,
and after two runs scored, Williams lined a grand slam into the
left-field stands, the ninth grand slam of Williams's career.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles' only run came on a homer in the eighth by B.J.
Surhoff, whom the Yankees are seeking to acquire.
</P>
<P>
   Torre cleared his bench for the last innings, using Wilson
Delgado at shortstop and Bellinger in left, and calling on Darrell
Einertson to throw the eighth inning and Randy Choate to pitch the
ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
