<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3196 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     07-26 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPORTING MUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's news-and-views edition of The Sporting Muse, dedicated
to all smack-talking, hamstring-grabbing sprinters:
</P>
<P>
   News: The U.S. Olympic track and field trials come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Huh? You mean I missed them?
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a statement on the status of track in America that
the trials could come and go with nary a buzz. Aside from a story
here or there about Marion Jones and the fastest tongues in the
West (all our male sprinters), the event barely registered.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a past generation, the trials was the kind of Big
Event that would dominate the attention of sports fans and the
media. Fans wanted to know about all of our great sprinters and
would speculate over how many gold medals America would win. We'd
all wince whenever the trials process, perhaps the most grueling,
desperate competition in all sports, would claim a superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Now? Track is deader than T. Rex. Quick now, name our gold medal
candidates in the 110-meter hurdles and high jump. Bzzz, time's up.
They happen to be Allan Johnson and Charles Austin, who also happen
to be the defending Olympic champs. Alas, the number of Americans
who know either, outside their immediate f would fit in a four-unit
apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   Who's to blame? Everybody. American track started to stagger in
the '80s because of mismanagement, but no one really noticed
because the '84 Games in L.A. were such a rush and the Ruskies and
their friends stayed home. We're just now noticing because there
are no stars out there to replace Carl Lewis and Jackie
Joyner-Kersee.
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee played its role by
overplaying its hand and putting the Games on an every-two-year
schedule. Summer is different than winter, yes, but it's still
diluted the special quality of ``the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes in the sports landscape has also played a role. Every
time a nouveau sport like soccer and women's pro basketball is
shoved at editors, programmers and fans, it comes at the expense of
other sports on the periphery.
</P>
<P>
   TV has done what it does best, which is aggravate viewers. NBC
goes from plausibly despicable coverage in 1996 to an all-delayed
TV schedule in 2000. And how are we supposed to become interested
in the top American athletes when the network devotes so little
coverage to the trials? Based on NBC's coverage the last week, we
have three track athletes, Jones, Michael Johnson and Maurice
Greene.
</P>
<P>
   The final shovel of dirt figures to come during the Games
themselves. NBC is geeked for big Nielsens, but the Sydney Games
will be contested in mid-September, when there is head-to-head
competition from baseball's pennant races and football. Plus, the
no-live TV policy figures to backfire. Fans who do care about
Olympic sport will get their information from the Internet, where
there are no deadlines, press runs or prime-time TV hours.
</P>
<P>
   Long before NBC gets around to playing their Olympic theme each
night, the real fan will know who won and what happened, and have
made a decision on whether they'll tune in, leaving NBC relying on
sports looky-loos with five hours to kill each night.
</P>
<P>
   My heart won't bleed for NBC, but it does for track, a great
sport that can't get a witness.
</P>
<P>
   News: Johnson, Greene blow tires in the 200-meter final.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Their fate is the best example of how fraught the trials
process is. Neither was particularly well-served by the pressure of
their ``rivalry,'' which was manufactured. Johnson's 19.38
200-meter world record notwithstanding, he is essentially a great
quarter-miler who can also run the 200. Greene is a great 100-meter
man who can sustain his speed over 200. Rather than spotlight each
for their strength, they got caught in a made-for-TV ``rivalry''
that was nonsensical.
</P>
<P>
   They both got what they deserved for so freely participating,
though I can't blame Johnson for letting it happen. U.S. track put
a lot of pressure on him to help them revive interest in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   News: U.S. track bullish on medal chances in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Tie me kangaroo down, sport, those projections are mad.
The best sprinter in the world isn't Greene, it's Ato Boldon from
Trinidad. Michael Johnson is odds-on to win the 400, but America
may not medal in any distance longer than 400 meters, male or
female. Regina Jacobs (women's 1,500 and/or 5,000) has the best
chance.
</P>
<P>
   America has produced the long jump gold medalist every Olympics
save three (1924, 1964, and the boycotted 1980 Games), but could
get shut out of medals entirely in Sydney. Our best field eventers
are Austin, Jones (even though her long jump technique is abysmal)
and Stacy Dragila, the world record holder in the relatively new
women's pole vault.
</P>
<P>
   News: NBA Players Association coming to terms with players
facing paying back 10 percent of income.
</P>
<P>
   Views: That's the result of the players capitulating to David
``union buster'' Stern on salary cap terms two seasons ago. Fearful
of the finality of a hard cap, instead agreed to an escrow tax and
rookie salary minimum.
</P>
<P>
   NBA bean-counters then rolled out numbers showing that 62
percent of all 1999-2000 revenue went to salaries, higher than the
agreed upon 55 percent maximum. Thus, the owners get rebates. That
sound you hear is Donald Sterling and his accountant having a good
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bleed too much for the players. They still had enough
change in their pocket to hold their annual meetings in the
Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   News: Tiger Woods wins fourth major and completes Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   Views: The ultimate record for Woods is Jack Nicklaus' mark of
18 major titles. Woods now has four at the age of 24. If he wins
just one a year from here on, he'll top Jack in 2015 at the age of
39.
</P>
<P>
   The real record to watch may be Nicklaus' 70 PGA titles. Woods
has won 21, including six already in 2000. If he averages eight a
year, he could break Nicklaus' mark before he's 30.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that could keep Woods from owning all the records
is his motivation. If he has everything he could want by the time
he's 30, what's the motivation to keep playing? By then, he'll
probably own Nike and a few other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he'll run for president, assuming he has the patience to
wait until he's 35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0011 </DOCNO>
