r f BC-IZONE-SALON-LADN     07-26 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IZONE-SALON-LADN </SLUG>
 
FUTURIST I ZONE SALON GOES BEYOND HAIRCUTS &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAM PARK 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Sebastian International, a prominent beauty care
products manufacturer, has taken its futurist philosophy a step
further by opening what it calls the ``salon of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12,000-square-foot i Zone -- the ``i'' stands for
individuality -- is designed on Feng Shui principles to create a
positive energy flow. Curved translucent walls allow soft light to
filter through. Three large waterfalls and musical sound zones
contribute to the effect.
</P>
<P>
   Salable art objects are scattered throughout the i Zone, and
purchases include informational time with the artist who created
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to give the customer more than just a hair
service,'' said Anthony Guthmiller, director of advanced learning
and i Zone creator. ``The physical service is secondary to who you
are as an individual. We want to go further into you -- not just
stay on the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Any consumer business in today's climate needs to incorporate a
special experience for the customer, Guthmiller said. The i Zone is
reaching for the next level beyond experience, which is
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   At the i Zone salon in Woodland Hills, customers are offered a
variety of services that go beyond the traditional ``beauty shop.''
They can get a 10-minute scalp massage as they decompress in the
shampoo area. They can also get a facial, a manicure, a makeover,
aromatherapy or a full-body massage, shop for cosmetics, buy a
cappuccino, access wellness information or surf the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A retail area called the Trucca Buffet features the Sebastian
cosmetics line. Shoppers take a special tray and slide it on a long
counter while making their choices -- much like in a food buffet.
Hair care products and logo items are also available.
</P>
<P>
   The i Zone doesn't want to be categorized as a day spa. It is
more fluid, Guthmiller said. Services are offered a la carte. The
objective is to provide a flexible environment where a customer can
spend pleasant hours, or just escape for a lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   Guthmiller said it is designed for individuals who have a
creative mindset -- who are forward-thinking and like to explore --
regardless of age or income group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will draw heavily from the (San Fernando) Valley, because
the Valley doesn't have as much culture and art as the people who
live here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The i Zone is not only for the front-line consumer: It's a model
to inspire other salons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is that salons will be influenced, to the extent that
we want them to copy everything they see here and stretch
themselves into a new area of consumerism that transcends a salon
-- to broaden who they are or who they perceive themselves to be,''
Guthmiller said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the i Zone area doubles as an advanced learning academy
for salon professionals. Classes are offered in traditional
subjects such as haircutting. But even with that, Sebastian
attempts to surpass the expected. Its classes can help salons spot
trends; relate art, language, fashion and design to create ``a
look;'' understand makeup for all nationalities; and push the
fashion envelope with classes in extreme makeup styling, including
techniques such as the use of face wax and cosmetic jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   The official grand opening of i Zone is set for Aug. 7, but
proceeds from all services sold during July go directly to the
Planet of Hope, a charitable organization that helps homeless
children and families.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 0039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
