<SLUG> BC-DUI-SHOOT-LADN </SLUG>
 
POLICE SAY SHOOTING WAS IN SELF-DEFENSE &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JORDAN SMITH 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In what investigators said Tuesday was a case of
self-defense, an off-duty LAPD sergeant fatally shot a neighbor
when police said the man tried to run him down after crashing into
at least 10 cars.
</P>
<P>
   Police said 13-year department veteran Sgt. Steve Ulrich killed
27-year-old Chris Oliver, a movie and television crewman, late
Monday when the officer went to investigate the sound of crashing
cars outside his home in the 23300 block of Friar Street in
Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's family and friends said he would never try to hurt a
police officer, and called it a case of a cop who shot too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his fingers are faster than his mind,'' said
20-year-old Jennifer Jacobson, a former girlfriend of Oliver's.
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich was at home just before 11 p.m. Monday when he heard a
vehicle collision outside, police said. He saw a white pickup truck
stopped at the intersection of Friar and Jackie Avenue, and
approached the car, asking the driver to get out, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Oliver accelerated the car in an attempt to run the
officer down, police said. Ulrich fired at least four rounds from
his 9 mm handgun, fatally wounding Oliver, who was pronounced dead
at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting took place in front of Oliver's home, and down the
block from Ulrich's home.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver reportedly drove his white pickup truck into as many as
10 cars on Victory Boulevard, Berquist Avenue and Friar before the
confrontation with Ulrich.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Jason Lee said they do not know why Oliver ran into the
vehicles, but tests will be run to determine whether he had been
using alcohol or drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Ulrich has been in Los Angeles Police Department's
ombudsman office for one year, but did not say how long it had been
since he worked as a street cop.
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich was off duty Tuesday, but could return to work as early
as Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on preliminary indicators, there is no reason to believe
the officer acted irresponsibly,'' said Lt. Horace Frank. ``The
investigation is ongoing, the nuts and bolts take time, and we're
still interviewing people.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's friend and neighbor, Mike Trentini, said he was at home
when he heard the sound of a crash outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it might've been a hit-and-run because I could hear
the squeal of metal as the car tried to drive away,'' Trentini
said.
</P>
<P>
   Trentini said he tried to catch the car and get a license plate
number by following the sound on his bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see Chris or anything but I saw the truck with its
door open,'' he said. ``Then I heard someone yelling, `Get on the
ground right now,' and it wasn't more than two seconds later that I
heard the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Trentini and Jacobson said they believe Oliver knew he was in
trouble for hitting the cars, but would've taken responsibility for
his actions. Both insist he was not violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Chris and I can't see him trying to hurt someone
deliberately,'' Jacobson said. ``He was probably scared and was
trying to get back to his house.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver worked as a grip for television and film productions, and
had recently gotten a new job, Jacobson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was happy. It was a fairly long-term job and that made him
feel secure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a family man, his son meant everything to him and he
wouldn't have done anything to jeopardize that. They didn't have to
shoot him, It could've been handled differently.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
