MARCHERS REV UP FOR DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Several hundred D2KLA protesters marched in
downtown Pershing Square on Tuesday to assert their rights to
demonstrate during the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters marched, danced and sang to celebrate a recent
court ruling that allows them to rally at Pershing Square and march
to Staples Center during the convention, which will run Aug. 14-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would now like to officially declare the retaking of
Pershing Square and our First Amendment rights,'' D2KLA spokeswoman
Margaret Prescod said.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters said they are concerned about the massive police
presence expected at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Don White, D2KLA coordinator of logistics, permits and legal
affairs, said protesters plan to use their own ``very, very large
and well-trained security team'' to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, 100 security people would be necessary at a
minimum,'' White said. ``We don't accept the concept that our
marches are under the control of the police. However, we will have
a well-trained security team who will monitor, usher and facilitate
our marches.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police Lt. Horace Frank said if security team
members carry weapons or protesters march without a permit, police
will take the appropriate action.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the event they refuse to follow lawful orders, we would
make arrests,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Zinzun, spokesman for the Coalition Against Police
Abuse, said protesters plan to use legal observers and cameras to
monitor the police during the protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe in the right to self-defense,'' Zinzun said.
``I'm not going to stand there and allow you to knock me upside the
head without defending myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters accused the Democratic Party of allowing major
pollution by corporations in areas with heavy minority populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this legalized killing of our children is happening, the
decision-makers in this country just stand by and do nothing,
collecting blood money for their campaigns,'' said Fidel Rodriguez,
community organizer for Communities for a Better Environment.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, a Los Angeles judge on Tuesday
extended the cooling-off period for Metropolitan Transportation
Authority bus and rail workers to Sept. 4, preventing them from
striking during the convention, MTA spokesman Marc Littman said.
</P>
<P>
   Littman said the MTA plans to reroute 17 Metro bus lines that
serve downtown near the Staples Center beginning Saturday because
of the convention.
</P>
<P>
