<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HEARD THE ONE ABOUT THE SHOES?  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I bought a pair of shoes. I always buy shoes
that way.
</P>
<P>
   I bought them at one of those factory outlet mystery malls.
Name-brand stuff is cheap there because the items have slight
factory defects, but you can never find the flaw, thus the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   You never see T-shirts there with two necks, or sunglasses with
the mirror lenses installed backwards.
</P>
<P>
   The shoes look fine. They're name brand. The heels are nailed to
the proper ends of the shoe bottoms, the shoelace holes are fully
punched, everything seems to be in order.
</P>
<P>
   Then I wore them to work. They squeak. Major squeakage, like a
squirrel being interrogated at a POW camp.
</P>
<P>
   New shoes sometimes squeak. But after several wearings, the
squeaking seems to be getting louder. Walking down a hallway, I
sound like two naked people wrestling on a Naugahyde couch.
</P>
<P>
   In the elevator, any slight shift of my weight causes eerie
sounds, like I'm prying open an ancient Pharoh's tomb. Or worse.
Fellow riders must fear that the elevator cables are about to snap
and send us plummeting into the Chronicle basement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry, it's just my shoes,'' I want to say, but I don't
like to talk in elevators.
</P>
<P>
   The squeaks aren't quick, but rather drawn out, not unlike the
sounds the Blob makes in the old Steve McQueen movie, ``The Blob.''
That evil gooey mass creaks as it grows and oozes, devouring
mankind.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes with squeaky shoes it's possible to walk around the
squeak, to limit the noise by slightly altering your gait, or
twisting your feet here and there. Not these shoes. Born to squeak.
</P>
<P>
   However, in experimenting I find that they don't squeak if I
walk on my tippytoes. As an added benefit, if I walk around that
way a lot, I might develop buns of steel, or at least of pig iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you might also throw out your back,'' a co-worker points
out.
</P>
<P>
   Curious expression, ``Throw out your back.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminds me of the old song, ``I Gave My Heart to the Junkman,''
which was prophetic, because that is probably what you actually do
with your old heart after you undergo a heart transplant.
</P>
<P>
   That's the shoe story. I'm glad I didn't buy a wallet.
</P>
<P>
   THE LONGER I don't have a cell phone, the more often I need a
pay phone.
</P>
<P>
   I am resisting the cell phone thing. This is not a personal
statement or philosophical stand. I just don't want to be hooked up
everywhere I go, like I'm on life support.
</P>
<P>
   The cell thing does get silly. People who climb Mt. Everest
carry cell phones. How romantic! You reach the top _ or ``summit,''
as the climbers call it _ and you get a call from Blockbuster
reminding you that ``Smokey and the Bandit'' is two weeks overdue.
</P>
<P>
   One man who died while climbing Everest was able to phone his
wife back home and say goodbye just before he froze to death. Fine,
I guess, but what if he'd gotten the baby-sitter?
</P>
<P>
   I don't want a cell phone, but it would be nice if the phone
people would leave a few pay telephones around for us phonosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of pay phones are being removed because supposedly they
are too often used by criminals, like prostitutes and drug sellers.
</P>
<P>
   I don't buy that. What self-respecting whore, pimp or crack
dealer doesn't have his or her own cell phone these days?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, driving around desperately searching for a pay phone,
I'm tempted to find a hooker and offer her five bucks to make a
call on her cell phone. Certainly there are more hookers in San
Francisco than there are pay phones.
</P>
<P>
   The few pay phones that remain generally are no day at the
beach. They tend to be sticky, stinky and on-the-blinky.
</P>
<P>
   And pay-phone companies, probably to cut costs, have shortened
the receiver cords so that you have to hunch way over as you're
calling, making you look suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, we can put a man on the moon but we can't invent a
pay-phone-directory holder that is even remotely functional. You
have to bend over so far to read the book that now the cord is too
short the other way. And half the listings are lost in the metal
binding apparatus, which could hold up a circus tent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a small price to pay for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   TWENTY FAMOUS songwriters picked the 10 greatest songs ever
written. The top three were ``In My Life'' (Beatles),
``Satisfaction'' (Rolling Stones) and ``Over the Rainbow'' (Judy
Garland).
</P>
<P>
   Stop right now and make your own list. Carry it in your wallet
with a note stipulating that these songs be played at your wake.
</P>
<P>
   Off the top of my head (where else?), I'm going with these
(artist, if I know it): ``Six Days on the Road,'' ``Take Five''
(Dave Brubeck), ``Guitar Town'' (Steve Earl), ``Love TKO'' (Teddy
Pendergrass), ``She Was Hot'' (Stones), ``Pancho &AMP; Lefty'' (Emmylou
Harris), ``Kansas City'' (Wilbur Harrison), ``Texas Flood'' (Stevie
Ray Vaughan), ``This Could Be The Start of Something Big'' (Steve
Allen), ``Don't Be Cruel'' (Elvis).
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, why should I dictate what people listen to at
my wake? Or select the snacks? I should be grateful to anyone who
bothers to show up, now I'm going to impose my music on them?
</P>
<P>
   It's not like my ashes are going to get up and dance. Play
whatever the hell you want.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
