<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONCS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS TO STAY WITH SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Several teams expressed interest in getting to know
Rashard Lewis better, even dangling lucrative contracts to grab his
attention.
</P>
<P>
   However, no one knew Lewis like the Sonics. And money was never
an issue, which is why the free-agent small forward ultimately
decided to stick with what he knows best.
</P>
<P>
   Citing his comfort level with the city, coaches and players,
Lewis made a verbal commitment Tuesday to return to the Sonics when
the signing period begins next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where I started, and I always knew Seattle was at the top
of the list,'' Lewis said in a telephone interview from his home in
Houston. ``The Sonics really showed me how much they need me, and
it made me feel good about staying. I'm glad (the free-agent
process) is over. Now I can start working out with my coaches and
prepare for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who turns 21 on Aug. 8, said he will return to Seattle
next week to sign a contract. Financial terms were not disclosed,
because the NBA prohibits deals before Aug. 1. It is believed that
Lewis will agree to a two-year deal worth at least $7.8 million _
the most the Sonics could offer. The package likely will give Lewis
an option to pick up the second year.
</P>
<P>
   After this contract expires, Lewis will become an unrestricted
free agent, and could receive the maximum reward: a seven-year deal
starting at $9 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics president Wally Walker acknowledged immediate
gratification when he received Lewis' phone call early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted with the answer,'' Walker said. ``Signing
Rashard was a well-publicized and stated priority. ... Rashard has
always made good decisions since we've been around him. Our
emphasis was what a great situation this is for him. I think he
recognizes that.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Lewis has panned out better than expected when
the Sonics took him from Alief Elsik High School in Alief, Texas,
in the second round of the 1998 draft, 32nd overall.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 10, 215 pounds, Lewis is expected to return in a
starting role at small forward. He earned the position ahead of
Ruben Patterson near the end of last season. Lewis put on a number
of eye-popping performances, including his 30-point, 12-rebound
game against Dallas on Feb. 9. His stock skyrocketed with strong
outings in four of five first-round playoff games against the Utah
Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've told me I can have the starting job as long as I keep
playing like I did last season,'' said Lewis, who is versatile
enough to play guard and power forward. ``Starting is important to
me to become the type of player I want.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have showered Lewis with affection since he became a
restricted free agent July 1. Each member of the coaching staff
visited Lewis at his home in Houston, while Walker negotiated with
Lewis' agent, Carl Poston.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis decided to commit after talking with his mother, Juanita
Goodman, and assistant coach Nate McMillan over dinner Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a good situation, knowing we have a good coaching staff
and good crop of young guys they're going to grow for the future,''
Lewis said. ``I grew really comfortable with coach McMillan and
coach (Dwane) Casey. They've helped me a lot, and I like being
around them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said listening to offers from Toronto, Orlando and Chicago
was simply a matter of ``looking at my options.'' The Raptors were
the only team Lewis visited. In the anticipation of losing swingman
Tracy McGrady to Orlando, Toronto was prepared to offer Lewis a
contract worth about $40 million over six years.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls inquired about Lewis as other top free agents turned
down their offers. The Magic courted Lewis in case McGrady did not
sign. Only Toronto, Orlando, Chicago and the Los Angeles Clippers
had enough money to exceed the Sonics' offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is going to come,'' Lewis said. ``I'm only 20 and I
have a long time to play in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
