<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3215 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CHENEY-VEEP-SFCHRON &LR;      07-26 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-VEEP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: BUSH PICKS CONSERVATIVE CHENEY AS HIS RUNNING MATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  The nation's worst-kept secret went public Tuesday when Texas
Gov. George W. Bush introduced former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney
as his running mate as the Republican presidential nominee.
<P>
   ``I believe you're looking at the next vice president of the
United States,'' Bush told a crowd of cheering supporters at the
University of Texas in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, a former Wyoming congressman and senior official in two
GOP administrations, made it clear early on that he won't fit into
the attack-dog role reserved for most vice presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to working with you, governor, to change the
tone in Washington, to restore a spirit of civility and respect and
cooperation,'' he said. ``It's time for America's leaders to stop
pointing the finger of blames &LR;  and to begin sharing the credit for
success.''
</P>
<P>
   The plea for a cease-fire did not register with Democrats, who
quickly jumped on Cheney's votes in Congress against the creation
of the Department of Education, against legal abortions and against
a ban on ``cop killer'' bullets.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview, California Sen. Barbara Boxer
repeated what will likely be the Democratic mantra on Cheney's
selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought Bush was going to move toward the center,''
she said. ``Instead, he picked someone whose record in the House
was far out of the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is a nice man, Boxer said, ``but I want to see someone
who will fight for people when they're hungry, sick or out of
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The former defense secretary has spent 25 years in public
service and is a well-known and respected figure in GOP circles.
His intimate knowledge of both foreign and domestic issues will
reassure swing voters worried that Bush's political expertise might
end at the Texas border.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney's biggest value to the Republican ticket probably
could be seen when he stood on the stage next to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Peering owlishly through his glasses, with lights reflecting off
his balding head, he looked every day of his 59 years. He also
appeared decades older and far more serious than the exuberant
Bush, who at 54 has the relaxed and casual manner of a man far
younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick is a grown-up and an adult,'' Ken Duberstein, former
chief of staff for President Ronald Reagan, said in a CNN
interview. ``He is a member of the governing class and adds to the
gravitas and seriousness of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney fills in the holes in Bush's resume, adding his expertise
in foreign affairs and his knowledge of the inner workings of the
nation's capital, said Sal Russo, a veteran Republican consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helps round out the Bush package; you can see him being
president,'' Russo said. ``While it's not an uproarious, dancing in
the streets type choice, everyone agrees that Cheney is solid. Bush
didn't hurt himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's selection also brought a sigh of relief to many
Republican conservatives, who were never comfortable with Bush's
father as president and were worried that the Texas governor would
choose a more moderate, pro-life Republican as a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question this is good news for conservatives,''
said Ken Khachigian, a GOP consultant and former speechwriter for
Reagan. ``To some point, you have to dance with the one who brung
you, and the governor wisely recognized the conservatives in our
party had a lot to do with his nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney originally joined the Bush campaign earlier this year to
run the vice presidential search committee. But the focus shifted
from the sought to the seeker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gradually, I realized that the person who was best qualified
to be my vice president was working by my side,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who was making a salary of $1.3 million a year plus
bonuses as head of a Texas oil services company, at first was
uninterested in joining the GOP ticket, but in July agreed to talk
it over with his family. By last Friday, the cat was out of the
bag.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the applause Cheney received from Republicans
Tuesday, no one was pretending that he is the dynamic, exciting
choice that Bush had been seeming to promise for months.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than take a chance with Arizona Sen. John McCain, who is
popular but unpredictable, or pro-choice Pennsylvania Gov. Tom
Ridge, Bush opted for Cheney, a safe, comfortable choice who will
attract little criticism from the party activists at next week's
convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   It was a choice based on personality and ability, not politics,
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pick Dick Cheney because of Wyoming's three electoral
votes _ though we want them and will work hard to earn them,'' Bush
said. ``I picked him because he is without a doubt fully capable of
being president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the easy pick in the vice presidential choice could come
back to haunt Bush later in the campaign, suggested Bruce Cain, a
political science professor at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Bush) missed a big opportunity by not going with a
riskier choice,'' Cain said. ``He opened up a whole line of attack
on his `new kind of Republican' promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is the pick of a confident politician who believes things
are going to keep going his way, Cain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the choice you make when you think you've already won,''
he said. ``If Bush was behind 7 points in the polls, I think he
would look more seriously at throwing the long pass.''
</P>
<P>
   While Cheney is a westerner, that might not be much help in
California, a state where Bush is trying to steal from the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's selection ``doesn't really carry a regional punch to
it,'' said John McGraw, state Republican party chairman, but ``he
brings leadership and integrity and honesty to the White House. A
lot of voters are striving to have that.''
</P>
<P>
   While his record on such issues as abortion, gun control and the
environment might not mesh with the feelings of many Californians,
McGraw said, voters really are asking if ``the Bush-Cheney team ...
(can) run this country effectively. They may disagree with Dick
Cheney on specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   Governor Gray Davis sees Cheney's selection differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a step backwards,'' Davis said of Bush's chances
in California. ``It would be an uphill battle anyway and this just
reinforces the more conservative aspects of Governor Bush's
platform.''
</P>
<P>
   While Vice President Al Gore's campaign characterized Cheney as
``a retro pick ... showing that Bush would take the country
backward rather than forward,'' it was also good news for the
Democrat's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush had made a surprise choice like former General Colin
Powell or New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, Gore could have
been forced to make a surprise selection of his own, Democratic
insiders said Tuesday. But with Cheney as the Republican pick,
Gore's options are wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore will now do what he was going to do all along,'' Boxer
said. ``He'll find someone in the mainstream of American
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney will make a day-long visit to Cheney's home
state of Wyoming Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writers Lynda Gledhill, Carla Marinucci and
Marc Sandalow contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
