<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAGNE'S WOES DON'T RILE GM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ If Los Angeles Dodgers right-hander Eric Gagne was
getting blasted in every start, general manager Kevin Malone might
be more inclined to burn a few prospects to get a
middle-of-the-road veteran starter.
</P>
<P>
   While Gagne is 1-6 and the Dodgers are 4-12 in his starts, the
club is taking solace in his ability to at least keep the team in
games. Gagne has allowed four or more earned runs in only four of
his 14 starts and has allowed the first run of the game 11 times.
</P>
<P>
   So while the high-priced Steve Trachsels and Ismael Valdeses and
Scott Ericksons of the world remain available, the Dodgers are
content with Kevin Brown, Chan Ho Park, Darren Dreifort, Carlos
Perez and even the rookie, Gagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to find out certain guys aren't available,
and the guys that are available, we're not sure it's an upgrade,''
Malone said. ``It's hard to find better than our starting five. At
any time we think Eric's going to have that type of game he's
capable of. He only made a couple of bad pitches (in his last
start). It's not like he's been real terrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are growing pains connected with development. And people
say, `Should you be developing at this time of the year?' Well,
you'd prefer not to, but we also know this guy can click at any
time and we've got five pretty good starters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers talked about converting right-handed reliever Matt
Herges into a starter to help the back end of the rotation, but
they have shelved that idea. Herges is 7-0 with a 3.26 ERA and is
tied with Terry Adams for the team lead with 40 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he's just too valuable where he's at,'' Malone said.
``He's so versatile. There's been talk, but I think we like him in
the role he's in at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Meeting in Florida: Dodgers officials met with Vero Beach
(Fla.) and Indian River County officials regarding the ``memorandum
of agreement'' as it relates to the ongoing negotiations to keep
the Dodgers spring-training home at Dodgertown.
</P>
<P>
   However, city and county officials decided to postpone a vote on
the matter after they requested some of the language be changed.
Instead, city and county officials are expected to vote Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the county commissioner's office is asking for a
public session for comment on the plan of purchasing the facility
and leasing it back to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Dodgers, at the urging of officials in Las Vegas,
have delayed signing the agreement so Las Vegas can make a
last-ditch pitch to attract six teams to a mega-complex, a team
official said. A Dodgers official said Las Vegas remains ``a real,
real long shot.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Dodgers manager Davey Johnson is impressed
enough with backup catcher Paul LoDuca that even when catcher Todd
Hundley returns from his fractured right thumb, it likely won't be
LoDuca heading to the minors. ``He's my fifth outfielder, my third
second baseman, (a) third baseman. I'd like to keep him and I know
how he feels about it,'' Johnson said. Instead, it is more likely
Chris Donnels would either return to the minors or be designated
for assignment when right-hander Gregg Olson returns in the next
few days. . . . When F.P. Santangelo is eligible to return from his
left-hand contusion, Dodgers officials have discussed sending the
struggling utility player to Triple-A Albuquerque for a few weeks
until Sept. 1 call-ups. He went 1 for 3 with a stolen base at
Single-A San Bernardino on a rehab stint. . . . Eric Karros' 17
homers at Coors Field are more than any non-Rockies player. ``It
just means I've played a lot of games here,'' Karros said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
