<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 COMMENTARY: IT AIN'T OVER TILL IT'S OVER   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of the collapse of the Camp David peace talks there
will be a great temptation to pronounce the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process over. That would be a great, great mistake. The truth
is, it has just begun. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton accomplished something very important at Camp
David _ and hats off to him for having the courage to try. He
brought the issues of Jerusalem, refugees and real territorial
compromise down from the heavens _ down from the airy mantras and
dreamlands where they have resided for 33 years _onto the
negotiating table. As one Palestinian negotiator remarked to the
Americans just before the Camp David talks broke up: ``This was
revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was right. In their talks, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel offered the Palestinians a real state in virtually all of
the West Bank and Gaza; he put forward a credible solution for the
Palestinian refugee issue; he offered Yasser Arafat a mosaic of
Palestinian administrative control and sovereignty over the Arab
areas of Jerusalem and Muslim holy sites. Arafat offered Israel
security arrangements that were unprecedented; he proposed
adjusting the 1967 borders to accommodate some Israeli settlements
in the West Bank; and he was ready to cede Palestinian sovereignty
over Jewish areas in the Old City of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Folks, none of these issues have been broached between these
parties before. Oh, op-ed writers broached them aplenty; think
tanks broached them aplenty. But the leaders never did. These were
all taboo issues, and breaking those taboos is a legacy Clinton can
be proud of, because it was the necessary condition for solving
these issues.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have been carrying around their positions on
Jerusalem, refugees and territory in a sealed box. At Camp David
the seals were opened, the issues were laid out and prospective
trades were made. And there were plenty of Palestinian negotiators
at Camp David who were urging Arafat to take the package on the
table, and plenty of Israelis ready to back Barak. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately Arafat, in the end, could not pull the trigger and
take what Barak was offering _ an offer the U.S. side felt went a
long way toward meeting Palestinian needs. This isn't surprising.
There is probably no way Arafat could cede any degree of Arab
sovereignty over East Jerusalem and the holy sites on the Temple
Mount without an Arab-Muslim consensus _ that is, without the
approval of Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Jordan and Morocco. And he
did not have that green light.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Clinton told Arafat that he was sacrificing the
future of his people for the approval of Arab countries and
Palestinian radicals who would sell him down the river in a second.
Arafat told Clinton he knew that. But he still couldn't pull the
trigger _ a sad reminder that the Palestinians don't not have a
state for nothing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is going to have to decide whether his loyalty is to the
Palestinian cause or the Palestinian people. If his loyalty is to
the Palestinian cause, he has left Camp David as a hero, and he
will no doubt receive high-fives all around the Arab world. If his
loyalty is to the Palestinian people, well, that's another matter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arabs and the Palestinian opponents of peace have always
been able to get the benefit of Arafat's compromises without taking
any political or moral responsibility,'' noted the Middle East
expert Stephen P. Cohen. ``The Arab states got a reduction in the
threat from Israel, but without ever paying the price of saying to
their people that we have truly passed to a new era. And the
Palestinian intelligentsia got land back, but they never had to get
their hands dirty. This never stopped Arafat before. But this time,
at Camp David, he has decided to do it their way _ putting dogma
before pragmatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to get around this,'' added Cohen, ``is for
Clinton to call the leaders of Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Jordan, Morocco
and Syria and say, `Guys, put up or shut up. There is no more free
ride here. Either you guys share the responsibility with Arafat _
and admit you are sharing Jerusalem with the Jews, who are also at
home there _ or you are leaving the Palestinians at the mercy of
the Israeli right, because Barak either won't be around or he will
be around saying that the Palestinians are hopeless.'''
</P>
<P>
   There is already tough talk coming from Palestinian radicals
about how they are going to declare their own state on Sept. 13, or
mount another intifada. Guys, here's some free advice: The days of
the intifada are over. The Palestinian police now have guns _ and
that changes everything.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The intifada worked for the Palestinians,'' observed the
Israeli political theorist Yaron Ezrahi, ``because they had stones
and the Israelis had guns and the Israelis could not really shoot
back, they could not use their superior force without restraint. If
the Palestinians use guns, there is no intifada option anymore.
This won't be defined as a people's movement with stones against an
army with guns. It will be defined as a war between two armies, and
Israel will use all its force without restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Palestinians used guns against Israeli guns
was in a place called Lebanon, and it ended with the PLO on a boat
to Tunis.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Israel, one can already hear the yapping on the
political right: Ariel Sharon and Natan Sharansky blathering on
about how they could get more for Israel and give up less. They
speak utter nonsense. The important thing about what Clinton did in
singling out Barak as having been willing to compromise, to a
degree that Arafat was not, was to signal that there is in the U.S.
view a level of Israeli compromise that is right and fair, and
beyond which Israel should not be expected to go. It is not just a
bottomless pit of giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a big push in Israel now to form a national unity
government, but thanks to Camp David it is going to be a very
different debate. Because the question will be on what basis
national unity will be forged. On the basis of the compromises
Barak tabled at Camp David, or on the basis of the Israeli right's
delusion that by just hanging tough with unrealistic positions the
Palestinian side will fold _ and there will be no price with
America, the Arabs or the rest of the world?
</P>
<P>
   The first Mideast peace talks at Camp David, in 1978, brought
the Arab world over the threshold of acknowledging that Israel was
there to stay, and it brought Israel over the threshold that
endless war was not inevitable. Camp David II has brought Israelis
and Palestinians up to a similar threshold, but not over it. It has
been clarifying nonetheless, because both sides now can see clearly
what their options are: Going forward means accepting the full
implications of sharing the land of Israel-Palestine and Jerusalem.
Going backward means a life on the barricades in which the future
of both peoples is completely uncertain. Most of all, neither side
can ever again return to the bliss of thinking that it doesn't have
a real choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
