<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Thurmont, Md.) _ News Analysis: The Israelis and
the Palestinians packed their bags and left Camp David empty-handed
and exhausted. Putting the best possible face on the failure,
President Clinton asserts that the Israelis and Palestinians did
break seven years of silence to conduct a discussion on emotional
issues like Jerusalem. He said that the parties made significant
progress on the core issues. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   AIRFRANCE-CRASH-CONCORDE (Undated) _ Bad luck has plagued the
Concorde, the world's only supersonic passenger jet, from the day
it began development as British-French joint venture in 1962. But
until Tuesday there was one area where its record, by modern
aviation standards, was pristine: safety. By Laurence Zuckerman and
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-SCHOOLS (Undated) _ A study released Tuesday shows that
math scores for students across the country rose in the 1990s,
suggesting that public education reforms have been effective at
raising student achievement. But a state-by-state analysis of test
scores and reform efforts provides a mixed picture for politicians
arguing over how best to spend education dollars. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   POPULAR-COLLEGES (Undated) _ Education column: Choosing the
``hot'' college may be fashionable, but it is often a terrible idea
for someone in search of a good education. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   KOREAN-ADOPTEES (New York) _ When Thomas Grover Masters was
adopted from Korea in 1959, his new parents were told that it would
be best if he could forget the world he left behind. Because
Koreans his age are the oldest group of international adoptees in
the United States, they have been the first to speak about growing
up unprepared to face a world that perceived them as Asian when
they saw themselves as American. By Shaila K. Dewan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY-ASSESS (Undated) _ News Analysis: In the most
momentous decision of his political career thus far, Gov. George W.
Bush took the least adventurous course possible and one that
several scholars called the safest choice of a political partner in
a generation. But the selection of Dick Cheney was deeply revealing
about Bush's approach to politics and to governing. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY-PROFILE (Undated) _ A profile of Richard Cheney. By Eric
Schmitt.
