   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PLATE-PAINTING (New York) _ Critic's Notebook: Some things you
don't miss until they're gone. The painted plate is one of them. It
was not too many years ago that no plate left a New York kitchen
until, like a subway car parked overnight in a railyard, it had
been decorated in drips, dots, dabs and hash marks. Now white is
making a comeback. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   CANADIAN-CHICKENS (Undated) _ Imported free-range chickens
processed by a new method are winning converts among New York chefs
and could be in supermarkets this fall. By Rozanne Gold.
</P>
<P>
   CHATEAU-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ The pretentious tone of the
title aside, ``From My Chateau Kitchen,'' by Anne Willan, is
accessible and reliable. Willan, the founder of La Varenne, a
cooking school, uses her home in Burgundy as La Varenne's summer
headquarters (the U.S. branch of the school is at the Greenbrier
resort in West Virginia). By Florence Fabricant.
