<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS, GLAUS NOT UP TO SPEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Bill Haselman's scorching line drive whizzed
past the glove of Anaheim Angels third baseman Troy Glaus into left
field Tuesday night, and with it went the game for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of an inning-ending double play, Haselman's hit led to a
three-run eighth inning for the Texas Rangers and a 9-6 victory
before 34,272 at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels rallied from a 5-1 deficit to tie the game at 6 on
Darin Erstad's RBI single in the sixth. It was still tied at 6 when
the Rangers' David Segui singled with one out in the eighth.
Segui's hit off Mike Holtz snapped at 12 a string of consecutive
batters retired by the Angels bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Petkovsek came in to replace Holtz and face Haselman. With
pinch-runner Scarborough Green going from first on the pitch,
Haselman's liner went past Glaus' left ear and into left field. Had
Glaus caught the ball, Green easily would have been doubled up at
first.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Green raced for third and Erstad's throw from left
field deflected off Green's helmet and went to the backstop. Erstad
was charged with an error, Green scored and Haselman went all the
way to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a bad read on it and I missed it,'' Glaus said. ``That's
the way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball was hit real hard,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia
said. ``I thought he had a bead on it. He just didn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad said he was surprised his throw came too late to get the
speedy Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw it at the glove and the next thing I know it skipped
out,'' he said. ``That play was crazy. He obviously runs faster
than I throw a baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   After an intentional walk to Dave Martinez, Gabe Kapler (Taft
High of Woodland Hills) ripped a two-run double to give the Rangers
a 9-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the ninth, Erstad came about 10 feet from a home
run to right-center field. Erstad had a single, double and triple
in the game, just missing hitting for the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get into that too much,'' said Erstad, who said he's
never hit for the cycle at any level. ``Especially after what
happened in the (eighth) inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz (0-2) got the loss and Rangers reliever Doug Davis (4-2)
earned the win. John Wetteland, one night after blowing a three-run
lead, pitched the ninth for his 26th save.
</P>
<P>
   Angels pitcher Seth Etherton had the worst start of his major-
league career, and it came one start after his best. Last week
against the same Rangers, Etherton gave up one run in 7 innings in
a 6-1 Angels win.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, he failed to go at least five innings for the
first time in his nine major-league starts. He gave up six runs in
3 innings. Of the seven hits he yielded, four were home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catalanatto led off the first with a homer, and one batter
later Rafael Palmeiro hit a two-run homer. In the third inning,
Rusty Greer hit a two-run homer, and in the fourth, Kapler hit a
solo homer. All six runs allowed by Etherton scored on home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a team the second time around can make it tough on
pitchers, especially young ones. But Etherton would not use it as
an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that big a deal,'' Etherton said. ``I didn't make
pitches, that's cut and dry. I didn't hit my spots and that's what
happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
