<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS GAIN GROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ There are things Adrian Beltre does that amaze, like
fielding bunts barehanded and throwing out a speedy runner like
Colorado's Neifi Perez.
</P>
<P>
   He also backs up on balls that would be double plays if he were
more aggressive, and puts pressure on himself to hit in the clutch.
Lately, the lack of the latter was getting to him.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers took the good and bad the 21-year-old
third baseman offers, and they used the good to continue their
charge toward Arizona. Beltre's bases-loaded single in the eighth
inning broke a tie and lifted the Dodgers to a 6-4 win against
Colorado on Tuesday night in a peaks-and-valleys kind of game for
Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (53-46) have won three straight and eight of their
last 10. They're within 2 games of the front-running Diamondbacks
in the NL West, the closest they've been since June 22, and within
1 games of second-place San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Beltre's) going to be a great player,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``He's a good player now, but he's going to be a
great player. It's just a few little things. This is the second
year I've had him, and I guess I just expect so much. The way he
handles himself, I expect him to be the true professional and know
all the intricacies of playing third.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Beltre's fielding error in the second inning on Ben
Petrick's grounder that led to the Rockies scoring three runs, and
he said that was on his mind in the later innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rockies reliever Jose Jimenez pitched around Eric Karros, who
hit a three-run homer in the seventh inning to tie it 4-4, to load
the bases and face Beltre, who was 2 for 15 with a homer with the
bases loaded. Beltre's troubles extended to runners in scoring
position. He was 5 for his last 30 with runners in scoring
position, but he singled to center to score Todd Hollandsworth and
Shawn Green and give the Dodgers a 6-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be the guy who was responsible for the first couple of
runs, and to see my chance to get the runs back and give Chan Ho
(Park) a chance to get his win . . .,'' Beltre said. ``When I saw
the bases loaded with two outs, I thought this was my big moment
and my chance to step up and fix what I did early in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Dodgers needing big efforts from their big three _
Kevin Brown, Park and Darren Dreifort _ in the second half of the
season, Park continued a run. They are a combined 6-0 in their last
six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Park (11-7) won his second straight and took over the team lead
in wins after allowing four runs (two earned) in seven innings at a
ballpark where he traditionally gets hammered. Park entered the
night with a 9.36 ERA in seven games at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   Relief was provided by Terry Adams and Jeff Shaw, who each
allowed two hits but no runs in scoreless innings. For Shaw, it was
his 15th save, but it came with some drama. And meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Walker and Tom Goodwin had one-out singles, and at that
time Mike Fetters began warming up. But Perez surprised the Dodgers
with a sacrifice, which Beltre fielded and threw to Karros for the
second out. It brought up Larry Walker, and brought a visit from
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'What do you want to do? Do you want to pitch around
him or go after him?' `' Johnson said. ``He said 'I want to go
right after him.' I said that was fine with me. I wanted to hear it
from him, and I knew that's what he was going to tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw retired Walker on a comebacker to end the game, but there
was also some significance with it. Shaw and Fetters are considered
co-closers at this juncture, mostly because Shaw is still
rebuilding everyone's confidence in him after he blew seven of his
first 20 save chances.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Johnson went to Fetters in the Dodgers' 4-1 win Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I was shocked (Monday) night and I was
shocked the day before,'' Shaw said. ``That's just me because I
expect to go out there in the ninth inning every night. That's what
I'm getting paid for, and that's what I've worked my tail off for
and I don't want to lose that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
