<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER GALAXY PLAYER INJURED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD GONZALEZ  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ With Cobi Jones and Robin Frasier playing with soft
arm casts and Kevin Hartman at home recovering from arthroscopic
knee surgery, Tuesday night's U.S. Open Cup game was a matchup of
MASH against Flash.
</P>
<P>
   Before too long, Los Angeles Galaxy midfielder and Olympic Team
hopeful Pete Vagenas would become the next casualty.
</P>
<P>
   But even with that, and with the core of its regular starting
line- up diluted by injuries, aches and the scalpel, the Galaxy
mustered enough fortitude to upend the A-League's San Diego Flash.
</P>
<P>
   Sasha Victorine's 50th-minute tally and and an insurance strike
in the 67th minute from Ivan Polic provided the depleted Galaxy the
ammunition it needed for a 2-0 victory over the Flash in
round-of-16 U.S. Open Cup action at San Diego Mesa College.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Galaxy advanced into the quarterfinal
round of the nation's oldest professional soccer tournament _ it
will face the San Jose Earthquakes on August 9th at a site to be
determined. MLS teams have now secured seven of the eight
quarterfinal-round berths, with DC United facing the defending U.S.
Open Cup champion Rochester Rhinos of the A-League tonight to
determine the final spot in the bracket.
</P>
<P>
   But the most pressing date on Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid's mind is
this morning, when he'll know the health status of Vagenas, who
crumpled to the field in pain after harsh contact with San Diego's
Geoff Huber in te 42nd minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a knock, it could be the Achilles' (tendon),'' said
Schmid, fearing the worst. ``It was right at the back of the ankle
and he said he heard something pop. It's bad timing for him (with
the Olympics coming up) and bad timing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   A sullen Vagenas had little to say afterward, also fearing his
Olympic Dream hangs in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really saying much until I know what it is,'' said
Vagenas, who played at St. Francis High and UCLA. His lower left
leg was heavily bandaged. ``It's hard to talk about. The ball
wasn't even near us. (Huber) just whacked me as we were running
along. He got me right near the Achilles and I heard it pop.''
</P>
<P>
   As ominously as the night ended, events unfolded well for the
Galaxy at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy controlled most of the run of play on the diminutive
field, threading balls which continaully perforated the lash
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Victorine, however, eventually got the only goal the team would
need early in the second half, one-timing a goal-mouth header of
Cobi Jones' corner kick past Flash goalie Tom Tate. Jones' service
was to the near corner of the goal box, where Victorine wriggled
free of two defenders to finish the set piece.
</P>
<P>
   Polic scored 17 minutes later on a counterattack keyed by
midfielder Mauricio Cienfuegos' alertness.
</P>
<P>
   It was Cienfuegos who gathered possession for the Galaxy near
midfield, then quickly spotted Polic run up the left side.
Cienfuegos passed to Polic, who beat one defender and shot from 30
yards out.
</P>
<P>
   Tate, who was well off his line, had the ball carom off his
hands before bouncing over his head and into the net.
</P>
<P>
   As if Schmid needed any more lineup worries, Polic was tossed
from the game in the 90th minute, with the referee ejecting him for
a strong tackle, his second offense of the game. As a result, Polic
will not be available to play in the team's next U.S. Open Cup
game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
