<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND HALF CARRIES SPARKS PAST MIRACLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Sparks struggled a bit early
on, but in the end they had too many weapons for the Orlando
Miracle.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks turned up the heat in the second half, beating the
Miracle 78-63 before 6,462 at the Forum Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks trailed by eight midway in the first half, but they
wore down the Miracle in the second half, leading by as many as 17
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're blessed we're a deep team,'' said Sparks coach Michael
Cooper. ``We have too many players that can start on any other
team. . . . Fatigue is going to be a factor for a lot of teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue was a factor for Orlando, whose bench contributed only
two points. On the other hand, Sparks reserves accounted for 17
points, with seven each from Allison Feaster and Nicky McCrimmon.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Leslie led the Sparks with 17 points, DeLisha Milton and
Tamecka Dixon had 14 points apiece and Mwadi Mabika had 11. The
Sparks improved to 21-4 to stay a half-game ahead of the Houston
Comets.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks trailed 24-16 midway through the first half, but
Milton scored eight points to get the Sparks back in the game. She
made two shots from 18 feet out and a four free throws to cut the
Sparks deficit to two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been struggling offensively as far as my outside shot
goes, but Lisa and coach (Glenn) McDonald have been working with me
to be consistent,'' she said. ``Tonight, it was working well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks regained the lead, 31-30, on a basket by Mabika with
two minutes to play. Lisa Leslie, who is on a tear from the free
throw, increased her streak to 48 with a pair. Dixon turned a steal
from Shannon Johnson into a score and scored again to give the
Sparks a 37-30 margin at the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to figure out what they were doing
defensively,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were running a triangle-and-two and that caught us off
guard in the beginning,'' said Leslie, who also had 11 rebounds and
four blocked shots. ``Once we adjusted that really opened it up for
us in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Milton and Leslie combined for 20 points in the first 20
minutes. Adrienne Johnson, who scored nine of the Miracle's first
11 points, had 13 at the half. She didn't score again. Cintia dos
Santos had 14 points for Orlando (14-11).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
