<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-ROD RETURNS, BUT MARINERS FALL SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He slapped the first pitch thrown to him for a double,
gloved the first ball hit to him for an out.
</P>
<P>
   But Alex Rodriguez still wasn't Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Back from a knee strain and concussion that put him on the
sidelines two-and-a-half weeks ago, the Mariners' All-Star
shortstop appeared stiff and tentative. He chugged around the bases
like Edgar Martinez. To resume his place in the galaxy, he's going
to need more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an adjustment,'' Rodriguez said. ``The body has its guard
up.''
</P>
<P>
   That's OK with the Mariners. They rarely break stride these
days, though their Jay Buhner-led finishing kick fell short Tuesday
night in an 8-7 defeat to Oakland before a crowd of 42,377 at
Safeco Field. Seattle's AL West lead was lopped to four games over
the A's, who try to narrow the gap even more in the series-ender
Wednesday at 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Lending to Mariners intrigue, Buhner slugged two home runs _
including his 300th _ to draw a long ovation, while Edgar Martinez
contributed his major league-leading 95th and 96th RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, Buhner unloaded his milestone, a two-run
shot over the center-field fence that was struck so hard the bald
outfielder stood at home plate and watched it disappear into the
night. The ball traveled 428 feet and pulled Seattle within one
run. The resulting ovation was so heartfelt, Buhner emerged from
the dugout and made a emotional curtain call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally overwhelmed,'' said Buhner, who traded a bat,
cap and a couple of gloves to the fan who caught the ball. ``I just
grabbed whatever I had and gave it to him. It was a pretty special
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had the tying run on base in the ninth as Rickey
Henderson slapped a one-out double, but he stayed there. The game
ended when Rodriguez flied deep to the right-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, all eyes were on the gimpy shortstop as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners didn't post their starting lineup until 5:30 p.m.,
two hours later than usual, uncertain if their superstar would get
medical clearance to play. With a trainer monitoring his every
move, Rodriguez took batting practice, loped around the bases and
backpedaled in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was ready to play,'' head trainer Rick Griffin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little apprehensive, but I'm eager to play,'' Rodriguez
said before the game. ``It's like getting on the bike for the first
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez can run straight ahead; it's circling the bases that
makes him step lightly. The knee hasn't experienced swelling in 10
days, but he's not ready to cut loose. He's been through this
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like last year, it was three or four days before he was
running well,'' reminded Griffin, referring to a torn knee ligament
that sidelined Rodriguez for six weeks early in the 1999 season.
``It will take a few days, then the adrenaline will kick in.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez initially had no problems swinging the bat, swatting
the first pitch from A's starter Gil Heredia into the left-field
corner, putting runners on second and third. He scored on Olerud's
homer as the Mariners took a 3-1 first-inning lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Rodriguez was responsible for Oakland's third
out, sliding to his left and gobbling up a Sal Fasano grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez struck out and grounded out twice in his next three
times up, leaving Henderson on second base in the middle at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   He botched his only other attempt in the field, letting Miguel
Tejada's hard-hit grounder get tangled in his feet in the fourth
inning. Rodriguez had a chance to throw the Oakland runner out, but
he pulled Olerud off first with his hurried effort, allowing the
A's second run to score. It was just the shortstop's fourth error
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners starter Aaron Sele, who lost his third consecutive
decision, also had problems with some of his throws. To start the
game, he could barely get one over the plate. The first two
hitters, Terrence Long and Randy Velarde, reached on singles, Long
scoring with the aid of a wild pitch. The next two A's, Jason
Giambi and Ben Grieve, walked on 10 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Sele (11-6) escaped major damage by striking out Matt Stairs and
inducing a double-play grounder from Tejada.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't quite so fortunate in the fifth inning. Jason Giambi
took Sele deep with a two-out, two-run homer just inside the
right-field foul pole, pulling the A's into a 4-4tie.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, the A's broke the stalemate with four runs and
sent Sele to the clubhouse, a two-out single up the middle by
Grieve barely eluding a diving Rodriguez and providing the go-ahead
score.
</P>
<P>
   In another week, the Mariners headliner makes that play. And
later, probably launches a game-winning homer over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
