<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 07:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3235 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i PM-CONCORDE-CRASH-0726-C     07-26 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 PM-CONCORDE-CRASH-0726-COX &HT;    INVESTIGATORS BEGIN PROBE OF FATAL CONCORDE CRASH; BODY COUNT
STILL AT 113
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GONESSE, France _ Working in a dull gray mist, investigators and
medical workers Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   began sifting through the blackened wreckage of a chartered Air
France Concorde that crashed near Paris minutes after take-off
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As attention turned to the supersonic aircraft's engines, the
airline said that its mechanics worked on one of the plane's
engines just before take-off. The airline would not say whether the
work was done on the No. 4 engine, the one that apparently caught
fire and streamed flames as the aircraft plunged to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said Wednesday that it would resume its Concorde
flights between London and New York, while Air France said it would
seek more information about the cause of the fatal crash before
making a decision. The two airlines are the only airlines to fly
the supersonic transports. The first British Airways Concorde
Wednesday took off from London at about 10:45 a.m. London time
(5:45 a.m. ET).
</P>
<P>
   Here in Gonesse, a small town north of Paris, forensic experts
were examining the charred bodies of the 113 victims _ mainly
German tourists _ to determine their identities. Relatives began to
arrive into Paris.
</P>
<P>
   A prayer service for the victims was held Wednesday at a chapel
in Hanover, Germany, on the grounds of the World's Fair. ``Today
Germany is shaken,'' Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said at the
service.
</P>
<P>
   The swan-like supersonic aircraft crashed into a small hotel
near Charles de Gaulle International Airport near Paris after one
of its four engines burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
   Nine crewmembers and 100 passengers were killed in the fiery
crash that sent smoke high into the suburban Paris skies for hours.
Also killed were four people at Hotelissimo, which was engulfed in
the blaze fed by the aircraft's full fuel tanks. Another 14 hotel
guests were hospitalized, police said.
</P>
<P>
   French television showed clips of the aircraft struggling to
maintain altitude with its left engines spewing flames. In images
that suggested the pilot's battle to keep aloft, the needle-nosed
plane banked before striking the hotel. The 45-room Hotel Relais
Bleu next door was unscathed. ne crash, told French TV that the
pilot seemed to be trying to turn the Concorde around. ``The pilot
realized there was an enormous problem and tried to turn around but
the plane fell straight down,'' she said. ``When it tried to
accelerate it caught fire behind. It fell directly on its wing. It
wanted to turn around and boom, it just fell. Everything was
shaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after midnight, investigators recovered the flight data
and cockpit voice recorders _ the so-called ``black boxes'' _ which
will provide vital data to help determine what caused the accident,
the first crash in the 30 years that the supersonic transport has
been flying. Officials said the recorders were damaged but
apparently functional.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the French and British investigators, the U.S.
National Transportation Safety
</P>
<P>
   Board sent at least one investigator from Washington because the
Concordes fly into New York.
</P>
<P>
   After the intense blaze that took firefighters hours to
extinguish, there was little recognizable in the wreckage early
Wednesday morning. However, a bit of the blue Air France logo was
visible on a piece of fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies were taken to a makeshift morgue set up at the
Jacques Brel amphitheater nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger list included 96 Germans, two Danes, one Austrian
and one American, as well as nine crewmembers, Air France said. The
American was a retired Air France employee, but the company did not
release a name.
</P>
<P>
   Among the eyewitnesses was Air France President Jean-Cyril
Spinetta. ``It seems there was a fire in one or more of the engines
on take-off,'' Spinetta told reporters at the crash scene.
</P>
<P>
   The crash did not appear to be linked to cracks found recently
in both British Airways and Air France Concorde jets. Air France
said this particular plane, in service since 1980, did not have
reported fissures.
</P>
<P>
   A former Concorde pilot told the BBC that he believed it would
take more than an engine fire to bring the plane down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have an engine fire you simply shut the engine down,
fire the fire bottles which put the fire out, dump fuel and come
down and land,'' John Hutchison said. ``The pictures I have seen
indicate something beyond a normal engine fire. That great long
plume of flame which is about as long as the airplane itself, a
couple of hundred feet, implies some sort of a catastrophic
failure, when the engine breaks up and blows apart.''
</P>
<P>
   British Airways and Air France _ the only airlines that fly the
Concorde _ grounded their fleets Tuesday and said they would wait
until Wednesday to announced whether they would resume operations.
</P>
<P>
   A symbol of Anglo-French cooperation, the first Concorde flew in
1969. With the crash, there are now 12 of the distinctive
delta-wing jets in the Air France and British Airways fleets. The
plane that crashed had flown 12,000 hours and had its last
mechanical checkup July 21.
</P>
<P>
   Police said three people on board the flight were under 18 years
sold. Five people on the ground were injured, police said. French
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, who visited the scene, said their
condition was ``good from a medical standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   British businessman Darren Atkins told SKY-TV News that he was
aboard another aircraft behind the Concorde on the tarmac. ``As it
accelerated down the runway the engine was already smoking,'' he
said. ``Before it started to take off the left-hand engines were
visibly on fire. They were burning very heavily. So much so in
fact, on the tarmac was some debris that had clearly fallen off the
engine.''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvie Lucas of Paris, who was at the airport waiting for her
children, also said she saw the plane on fire before it lifted off.
``We were waiting to hear the explosion because we thought it was
going to fall here (at the airport),'' Lucas told The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers had been on a trip meant to savor: champagne on
the Concorde, then a leisurely cruise on the MS Deutschland through
the Panama Canal to Ecuador. Tour operator Peter Deilmann said the
cruise, which had a total of 510 passengers booked, would not be
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional ad follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde, which crosses the Atlantic at 1,350 mph, has been
considered among the world's safest planes. Its only major scare
came in 1979, when a bad landing blew out a plane's tires. The
incident led to a design modification.
</P>
<P>
   The plane is popular with celebrities, world-class athletes and
the rich. It flies above turbulence at nearly 60,000 feet, crossing
the Atlantic in about 3 1/2 hours, much faster than regular
jetliners.
</P>
<P>
   A round-trip Paris-New York ticket costs $9,000, roughly 25
percent more than first class on a regular jet. A London-New York
round-trip runs $9,850. Air France officials have said in the past
that their current fleet was fit to fly safely until 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin, visibly moved, and French Transport Minister Jean-Claude
Gayssot visited the crash scene. ``It's a terrible moment,''
Gayssot said. President Jacques Chirac promised to pay homage
Wednesday to the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential spokeswoman, Agathe Sanson, said Chirac was leaving
the airport at the time of the crash, having just returned from the
Group of Eight major industrial nations summit in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Condolences poured in from all over, including German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder and President Clinton. ``I wanted to extend the
deepest condolences of the American people to the families of those
who are lost,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
