<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cell Phone Games seek competitors
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the feds have noticed that it's dangerous to drive and
talk on a cellular phone at the same time (well, duh), why not give
people who jabber while driving a competitive outlet to show off
that skill by holding a special Cell Phone Olympics?
</P>
<P>
   Not only would these games get these cyber yakkers off the
highway for a couple of weeks each summer, it would also give them
a chance to showcase their talents and give the rest of us a few
good laughs watching road stunts that usually just tick us off.
</P>
<P>
   We could hold the games at a NASCAR track, and dot-coms could
sponsor the entries.
</P>
<P>
   The Cell Phone Olympics would consist of events that require the
driver to perform several real-life tasks simultaneously at high
rates of speed while operating a cell phone. I'm sure you've seen
some of these games being performed in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the 18-Car Pileup Clean and Jerk, drivers would
have to drive a minivan full of screaming children, use the cell
phone to order a three-topping pizza, balance the checkbook on a
Palm Pilot and fire up the laptop to check today's stock market
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Has it ever occurred to the people who perform these daredevil
maneuvers that it might be simpler to pull off the road and call
from a parking lot?
</P>
<P>
   I'll tell you about the kind of unathletic oaf we're NOT looking
for to enter the Cell Phone Olympics. We're not looking for the guy
who was driving in front of me a few days back. This guy couldn't
even do two things at the same time _ that is, talk on a cell phone
and drive.
</P>
<P>
   This guy was sitting at a flashing red light while talking on
his cell phone. We were the only people at the intersection. Last
time I looked that up, a flashing red light meant stop, look, then
split. But this guy stopped, looked, talked and sat there. I was
beginning to wonder if he'd run out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, buddy, you ain't in a phone booth,'' I said loudly, with
my windows rolled up. (I'm pretty darned mean with my windows
rolled up.) Finally, to herd him out of my way, I honked. If I
hadn't honked, he might still be there, talking to his broker or
checking to see if his shirts were ready from the cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   There are any number of Cell Phone Games that I could suggest.
In the Hop, Skip and Careen, cell phone talkers would be required
to use their electronic mapping system to determine their exact
location (for example, a ditch next to the highway), call ahead to
make reservations at a restaurant, check their e-mail, buy a copy
of Harry Potter for junior on amazon.com, fix their hair and,
finally, cut somebody off for a parking place.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about the Cyberelay, in which speeding cell phone users
would have to steer the car while eating a breakfast taco without
spilling salsa out either end (no small feat by itself), make the
kids stop pestering the dog, and do their nails at 70 mph?
</P>
<P>
   If you've done this kind of work and you're pretty good at it, I
want you on my team because we're going to win several gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at 512-445-3606 or at
jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
