A3251 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN27-COX     07-26 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anne, Harry are doors to another world
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget The Patriot, Gladiator or any of the summer blockbusters.
In my family, the summer's command performance was the new
installment of PBS' ongoing Anne of Green Gables series.
</P>
<P>
   The timing couldn't have been better. With the arrival of the
hungrily-awaited fourth Harry Potter book, I had been thinking a
lot lately of Anne Shirley and my other childhood favorites. What a
glorious sight: kids sneaking off to midnight bookstore parties,
hunkering down for weekend readathons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be habit-forming,'' I thought as I watched my
12-year-old nieces compete to be the first to finish the ponderous
tome. Could the Harry hysteria carry over into a revived interest
in other children's literature?
</P>
<P>
   Bookstores and libraries have done their best to lure the
newly-spun bookworms to other classic children's tales, from A
Wrinkle in Time to The Chronicles of Narnia. One bookstore has
sponsored a ``Harry Potter Withdrawal Club''; libraries have posted
numerous ``If you love Harry Potter, you'll like this'' lists.
</P>
<P>
   None of the lists that I saw contained Anne of Green Gables. Too
old-fashioned, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Not for my family. Sunday night, at 8:55 p.m., EDT, my mother,
my sister Anne and I plopped ourselves in front of the TV for the
latest installment. In her youth Mom had been an ardent Anne of
Green Gables fan, a passion she passed on to the oldest and
youngest of her five daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Since Anne is named for the flame-haired, pigtailed orphan _
including a spelling with that all-important ``e'' _ she can hardly
be blamed for having a proprietary interest in the tale.
</P>
<P>
   She was dismayed to realize that the new episode had taken some,
er, small liberties with the original series by L.M. Montgomery.
Such as the entire script, in which a newlywed Anne searches
desperately for her husband, Gilbert Blythe, on the French front in
World War I.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you mean they made it all up?'' asked Anne indignantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they did,'' I said. ``Anne's children went into
World War I; she would have been well into middle age by then.''
</P>
<P>
   But hey, it's television, and even public television, perhaps,
is wary of the drama of the everyday, the poetry of the pedestrian,
that L.M. Montgomery so lovingly depicts. Instead, the classic
story had been transformed into a beautifully acted, beautifully
costumed melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   It struck me, in fact, that Harry Potter bears a greater
resemblance to the ``real Anne.'' Both children are orphans. Both
have an undeniable personal magnetism. Both, enduring cruelty and
emotional neglect during childhood, enter a whole new world at age
11 _ Anne to the enchanting Prince Edwards Island, Harry to the
enchanted Hogwarts School for Witchcraft and Wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   Anne pines for a ``a kindred spirit'' in whom ``I can confide my
inmost soul;'' Harry longs for magical spirits, or at least those
very unlike the ``Muggle'' _ non-wizard _ relatives who have reared
him with little respect and less affection.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to what makes both tales so universal, so
irresistible to children. The PBS folks didn't need to jazz up
Anne's story with battlefield scenes and missing husbands.
</P>
<P>
   There is drama enough in the quest for identity, for friendship.
There are battles enough in finding your way in the world.
</P>
<P>
   And that, more than any sorcery, is what keeps kids turning
every last page _ 734, count 'em _ of Harry Potter and the Goblet
of Fire.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope they don't wait till the next Harry Potter fix to
capture the same magic.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
