<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3253 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE0727-CO     07-26 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ancient oak's giving way shows the hand of fate
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I heard, within seconds of each other, two sounds that
rose above the roll of thunder and splatter of rain: crrrraaaack!
Whuuump! In the kitchen of our 110-year-old house, I felt a thud,
but it did not begin to prepare me for what lay in front of the
house.
</P>
<P>
   Illuminated by a fast-returning sun and lightning's persistent
flash, a giant hand cradled the garden, the most amazing sight I've
ever seen in a growing space. The big old oak next door, a tree
that probably predates the Civil War, had lost half of itself; our
side of the split trunk, always a concern, had fallen away,
brushing the top of our house, crashing into the wrought iron
fence, spreading across the driveway, reaching even the house
beyond ours. On what remained of the once mighty water oak, the
broken trunk jutted upward about 8 feet, a jagged reminder of the
once imposing half: bright wood with a telltale rotted heart.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the half-tree landed in the garden and on the sidewalk
and street. So much tree for such a small garden space. The oak had
become a grounded treehouse, complete with a maze of branches,
thickly leaved, fruited with new acorns that, for the past 11
years, rat-a-tat-tatted on our roof.
</P>
<P>
   So precise was the tree's placement that its lichened fingers,
some well over a foot around, rested right in the middle of the
postage-stamp-size garden, squashing some prized old friends, to be
sure, but apparently doing no harm to others. The cherry was
decapitated, but hydrangeas, azaleas, dogwood, redtip, a Japanese
maple remained unbroken.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just amazing that it missed so many plants,'' Lyn said
after recovering a bit from the shock of the sight. ``It's as if
that old tree was saying goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Our elation was short-lived. In removing the big hand last week,
apologetic tree people finished off the wrought iron fence and just
about destroyed the front garden: The tree didn't want to go.
</P>
<P>
   Melody Unger, our real estate agent, always quick on the quip,
noted that trees usually fall next door, not on their own property
(which means the victim's insurance pays). And she understood my
removing the for-sale sign: ``The house probably wouldn't show too
well with that tree lying in the front yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the fall, a sweet fragrance wafted, even through
the house. But it was more than newly broken wood; it evoked the
sensory pleasure of fresh-sliced watermelon, a soothing,
life-affirming counterpoint to the death and decay so evident in
the tree that, like so many oaks in Atlanta, has been dying
inwardly for years and whose falling apart was hastened by
debilitating drought and yet another violent blow-down.
</P>
<P>
   The July 12 fall-down was, of course, a Peeples Street
happening, bringing out the best in neighbors who brought awe,
sympathy and chain saws. It could have been much worse, we all
agreed. And we told stories of other lost trees, the oak across the
street, the pecan in our neighborhood parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Too, the fall-down brought out the best in carriers of letters
and newspapers; they navigated the maze. They delivered.
</P>
<P>
   This loss has brought much new light to house and garden,
pleasing some plants but disconcerting others. Disconcerting too is
the view from my office window upstairs; where I used to view the
twin towers of oak, I now see one trunk and a gash.
</P>
<P>
   More light may be on the way, as the great but weakened oak
seems destined for a saw-down; no one wants to know what will
happen if the tree's second half slams a house. In some ways,
that's a sad prospect, as that old oak had been a good part of my
gardening life, providing shade and many sightings of wildlife,
including flitting birds and cavorting squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the downed half lay drying, it continued to attract
birds that, under cover of thick foliage, hopped and chirped and
dashed about wildly. Perhaps they were confused at the familiar
tree's unfamiliar location.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they were doing what the tree and those of us who love
it have been doing in a big way lately: saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
