<HEADER>
A3254 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN27-COX     07-26 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The idea that veeps should excite is funnier than some
monologues
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Both George W. Bush and his running mate, Dick Cheney, are
Yalies.
</P>
<P>
   Bush got gentleman Cs at Yale where he was known to be something
of a party animal. Bush, at least, went straight through to get his
degree.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who already is getting roasted on late-night talk shows
for his lack of excitement, could make Bush's partying look like a
society tea party.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney got booted out of college twice for failing grades before
he finally settled down and breezed through undergraduate and
graduate school.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't sound like the man David Letterman, the host of
CBS' late-night talk show, referred to when he joked, ``So now
we'll get some of that Dick Cheney-mania.''
</P>
<P>
   Letterman joked, ``This might be nice to have someone in the
Oval Office whose arteries are hard, for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney suffered three mild heart attacks by the time he was 48.
He also had coronary bypass surgery in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Although doctors now give Bush's new vice-presidential selection
a clean bill of health, Jay Leno, host of NBC's late-night talk
show, joked about Cheney's former heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the time it took me to walk out here, Dick Cheney had five
more heart attacks,'' Leno said.
</P>
<P>
   The old ``funny-as-a-heart-attack'' routine always has 'em
rolling in the aisles.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be hard to make a living on Cheney jokes. The man
is not known as Mr. Excitement. He is known as Mr. Steady, Mr.
Reliable, Mr. Tough, Mr. Loyal, Mr. Brainy and Mr. Friend.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is a friend of the Bush family. He served in the
administration of President Bush, who also went to Yale. There's a
definite Yale connection here.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore went to Harvard where he made grades even worse than
Bush's gentleman Cs. Bush may have the loyal Yale vote wrapped up,
but Gore does not necessarily have the loyal Harvard vote in his
pocket. Bush also has a graduate degree from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Bush earlier said his vice-presidential choice would make ``your
eyes will light up with excitement.'' His choice of Cheney proves
how far removed Bush is from his party days at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   For those people who thought Bush should have chosen someone
with more excitement, few people can name anything exciting about
George Clinton, George Dallas, Dan Tompkins, Hannibal Hamlin,
Schuyler Colfax, Garret Hobart, Levi Morton, Charles Dawes, Charles
Curtis or Alben Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   These men were all vice presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Vice presidents seldom make a lot of difference either at the
polls or later in office. There are exceptions, of course, but the
job mostly requires staying out of the way and not doing anything
embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My country has in its wisdom contrived for me to the most
insignificant office (the vice presidency) that ever the invention
of man contrived or his imagination conceived; and as I can do
neither good nor evil, I must be borne away by others and meet the
common fate,'' wrote John Adams, the nation's first vice president.
</P>
<P>
   American humorist Finley Peter Dunne wrote that the vice
presidency ``isn't a crime exactly. Ye can't be sint to jail f'r
it, but it's a kind iv disgrace. It's like writin' anonymous
letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Texan John Nance Garner, who served two terms as vice president
under President Franklin D. Roosevelt, knew something about the
job. ``The vice presidency,'' Garner said, ``isn't worth a pitcher
of warm (bodily fluid).''
</P>
<P>
   Garner also said that once he left Washington, D.C., he would
never again set foot north of the Pecos River. He kept his word.
</P>
<P>
   If the public wants Mr. Excitement for vice president, Gore
might consider Bill Clinton as his running mate. Leno and Letterman
would love it.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the Senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
