<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS27-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS FILE 1 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com. Please include your name and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Mosquitoes in New York State have infected birds and people
with the West Nile Virus. Can the AIDS virus be spread by a
mosquito?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no evidence of such a thing ever happening, said
Kathryn Bina of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   When an insect bites a person, she added, it injects saliva, not
its own or a previously bitten person's or animal's blood. Thus,
even if the virus enters a mosquito, the insect doesn't become
infected and cannot transmit HIV to the next human or animal it
feeds on or bites.
</P>
<P>
   Since the onset of the HIV epidemic, that there has been concern
about transmission of the virus by biting and bloodsucking insects,
the CDC says in a fact sheet about HIV and AIDS prevention.
However, studies have shown no evidence of HIV transmission through
insects, even in areas where there are many cases of AIDS and large
populations of insects such as mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow fever and malaria, incidentally, can be transmitted
through the saliva of specific species of mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent item in Q&AMP;A listed several U.S. presidents who were
related to other presidents. Although it wasn't mentioned, I
believe Jimmy Carter was related to Presidents William Henry
Harrison and Benjamin Harrison. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: The book ``Facts About the Presidents'' doesn't mention this,
but it's possible that there was a relationship. Just not a close
one.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie Harmon, spokeswoman for the Carter Presidential Center,
explained that Jimmy Carter's first Carter ancestor in America was
Thomas Carter, who came to Virginia about 1635. There is
``uncertainty among genealogists'' regarding his background, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from Debrett's Peerage Limited believe that Thomas
Carter came from a prominent family with connections to British
royalty, Harmon said, adding: ``If this is the case, then later
generations would have been related to prominent Virginians such as
George Washington and the Harrison family. But we can't find if any
closer relationship has been established with the Harrisons.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Thomas, a historian at the Historic Preservation
Division of the Georgia Department of Natural Resources and a
genealogy expert, said any link between Carter and the Harrisons is
``very distant and unproved in the final analysis, and should not
be overemphasized.''
</P>
<P>
   Q : Some media reports said Sen. Paul Coverdell of Georgia was
the fourth-ranking Republican in the Senate, and others said
fifth-ranking. Which is correct, and what do the rankings refer to?
</P>
<P>
   A: The terms refer to elected leadership positions among the
Senate's Republican majority. No. 1 is Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott of Mississippi. No. 2 is Majority Whip Don Nickles of
Oklahoma. No. 3 is Conference Chair Connie Mack of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   After that, there's some disagreement about what comes next. On
his Web page, Policy Committee Chair Larry Craig of Idaho says he
has held the fourth-ranking position for years. A Coverdell aide
told the Atlanta Journal-Constitution that Coverdell's position _
secretary of the Republican Conference _ was considered the No. 5
position.
</P>
<P>
   Others in Washington consider conference secretary to be the No.
4 position, and most seem to have settled on No. 4 for Coverdell.
The Washington Post said Coverdell was expected to assume the
third-ranking post as conference chairman next year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Before Paul Coverdell, who was the last U.S. senator to die
while in office?
</P>
<P>
   A: John Chafee (R-R.I.), 77, who served 23 years in the Senate,
was the last. He died Oct. 24, 1999, of heart failure. His son,
Lincoln Chafee, was named in November to serve out the remaining 14
months of his father's term. Lincoln Chafee, mayor of Warwick,
R.I., had been running to succeed his father, who previously had
announced plans to retire at the end of his term.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In all the biographical information reported after Sen. Paul
Coverdell's death, there has been no mention of any religious
affiliation. Did he have such an affiliation?
</P>
<P>
   A: He was a Methodist.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have read that the only reasons organ donors are rejected
are because of HIV/AIDS and a form of hepatitis. I also have have
read that donors who are gay or suspected of being gay are rejected
automatically without regard to medical history and sexual activity
(or lack thereof). Organs from such donors are not even accepted
for tests. Is there any truth to this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Each potential donor is looked at on a case-by-case basis,
said Jeff Al-Mashat of the Georgia Coalition on Donation and
LifeLink of Georgia. He added: ``Homosexual activity among males
falls under the category of high-risk behavior, according to the
CDC. That does not automatically rule someone out for potential
organ and/or tissue donation.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since 1937, the Social Security Administration has been
issuing numbers in the sequence of 3-2-4 digits. When will we run
out of individual numbers using that system?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Social Security Administration says the current numbering
system will provide enough new numbers for several generations into
the future _ this despite the fact that more than 400 million
numbers have been issued, with 6 million more issued a year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was a child, the March of Dimes issued small cardboard
folders or cards that we used to collect dimes. It was a way to
raise money. What happened to that program?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although ``dime'' is still part of the organization's name,
and it's forever etched in people's minds, the March of Dimes seeks
larger contributions now, said spokeswoman Michele Kling at the
organization's White Plains, N.Y., headquarters. The campaign to
collect dimes in cardboard folders and in cans has been replaced by
WalkAmerica an annual event staged in some 1,500 communities
nationwide. People of all ages participate and ask friends,
neighbors and co-workers to pledge a certain amount of money to the
March of Dimes in exchange for their walk.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the March of Dimes organization evolved from ``March
of Time,'' a popular newsreel in the 1930s, Kling said. Eddie
Cantor, a popular entertainer, suggested to President Franklin D.
Roosevelt the idea of a fund-raising campaign that involved asking
people to send a dime to the White House. People sent in millions
of dimes, and they became symbolic of the campaign and the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, March of Dimes initiated the first concerted efforts to
save babies from birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who won the Spingarn Medal at this year's NAACP convention?
</P>
<P>
   A: TV personality Oprah Winfrey was awarded, in absentia, the
NAACP's highest honor at its convention in Baltimore earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The medal, first given in 1914, has gone to such people as
retired Army Gen. Colin Powell, author Maya Angelou, Supreme Court
Justice Thurgood Marshall, actor Bill Cosby, publisher Earl Graves,
the Revs. Martin Luther King Jr. and Jesse Jackson, and Myrlie
Evers-Williams, former NAACP chair and widow of Medgar Evers, who
also was given the medal posthumously in 1963. Evers was an NAACP
field director in Mississippi who was shot to death in front of his
home.
</P>
<P>
   The Spingarn Medal is named for Joel Spingarn, NAACP treasurer
from 1919 to 1930 and its president from 1930 until his death in
1939.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
