<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS27-FILE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS FILE 2 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is the protocal for flying U.S. flags at half-staff?
</P>
<P>
   A: As stated in ``The Flag Book of the United States,'' the
practice of flying the U.S. flag at half-staff as a sign of
mourning and honor for the dead has created some confusion in the
public mind.
</P>
<P>
   A 1954 proclamation issued by President Eisenhower establishes
the number of days the flag should be lowered as a mark of respect
after the death of major officials: 30 days for a president or
ex-president; 10 days for a vice president, chief justice of the
United States or a retired chief justice, or the speaker of the
House of Representatives; from the day of death until burial of an
associate justice, a Cabinet member, a former vice president, the
governor of a state, territory or possession, and a number of
others specified by title.
</P>
<P>
   The flag also flies at half-staff in Washington on the day of
death and the following day for a U.S. senator or representative, a
territorial delegate, or the resident commissioner of Puerto Rico.
And it flies at half-staff in a state from the day the governor or
one of the state's U.S. senators dies until burial.
</P>
<P>
   There also are occasional special presidential proclamations
calling for the half-staffing of flags, as in 1968, when the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr. was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``half-mast,'' by the way, is sometimes used, but in
general refers to flags aboard ships.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have been hit by lightning three times in the past year
and a half. It got only a tree the first two times, but the last
time it struck our house and set it on fire. Is there anything we
can do to prevent this?
</P>
<P>
   A: You should consider installing one or more grounded lightning
rods above your home, said meteorologist Gregory Forbes of the
Weather Channel. While they aren't foolproof, they tend to offer
about a 45-degree cone of protection to objects below them, kind of
like an electrical ``umbrella'' or shield.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, you were more unlucky than you realize, Forbes
added. Not every lightnes. The longer-duration current allows
enough time for the contacted substance to heat up to flammable
temperatures _ similar to the principle by which the elements in
your toaster heat up as the electrical current flows through them _
except there's a lot more current.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is Ralph Nader's status in getting on the ballot in all
the states?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``We've got about 29 in the bag,'' said Laura Jones of the
Nader for President campaign headquarters in Washington. She added
that the campaign expects to have him on the ballot in 45 states by
election day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do the Phillips screw and screwdriver get their name?
</P>
<P>
   A: Henry F. Phillips, a Portland, Ore., businessman with a
penchant for gadgets, invented the screw with the recessed cross in
1933, as well as the screwdriver needed with it. They were designed
for use on automobile assembly lines to hold tighter than slotted
screws when driven by automated, high-torque screwdrivers.
</P>
<P>
   As reported by The Wall Street Journal in 1988, General Motors
Corp.'s Cadillac Division was the first to give his invention a try
in the 1930s. And, as the newspaper added, ``The Phillips screw
took hold and never let go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillips Screw Co. actually never produced the screws or
drivers. Instead, it licenses others to do that under its patents.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips died in 1958 at age 68.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the story on world's fairs? Are they held on a regular
schedule? When and where are the next ones?
</P>
<P>
   A: Under the rules of the Bureau of International Expositions,
which regulates world's fairs, only one major fair can be held each
decade, and it can last no longer than six months. But the BIE also
approves smaller events that can be held more often.
</P>
<P>
   The first world's fair was the Great Exhibition of 1851 in
London. More recently, fairs have been held in many places,
including Okinawa, Japan, in 1975; Knoxville, Tenn., 1982;
Vancouver, B.C., 1986; Brisbane, Australia, 1988; Osaka, Japan,
1990; Seville, Spain, 1992; and Lisbon, Portugal, 1998. An
exposition in Manila, Philippines, originally planned for 2002 was
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Other current and future World's Fairs ``events'' listed on the
official Web site _ www.worldsfairs.com/events.html _ are the
Millennium Exhibition in Greenwich, England, all this year; the
Swiss National Exhibition in the Swiss cities of Biel-Bienne,
Murten-Morat, Neuchatel and Yverdon-les-Bains, May 3-Oct. 29, 2001;
Floriade, the once-each decade international garden show, at
Gemeente Haarlemmermeer, Netherlands, April 1-Oct. 15, 2002; and
Seto 2005, an expo in the Aichi Prefecture of Japan, March 25-Sept.
25, 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Information: World's Fair, Inc., P.O. Box 339, Corte Madera, CA
94976 (415-461-6695).
</P>
<P>
   Q: The label on a bottle of J&AMP;B scotch says ``By Appointment to
Her Majesty the Queen.'' What is this all about?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're thinking Queen Elizabeth II might enjoy the occasional
wee drop? Could be, but not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   That statement is a ``Royal Warrant.'' The queen's Web site _
www.royal.gov.uk _ says warrants are a ``mark of recognition that
tradesmen are regular suppliers of goods and services to the Royal
households.'' They are granted to people or companies that have
regularly supplied goods or services for a minimum of three
consecutive years to the queen; the duke of Edinburgh; Queen
Elizabeth the Queen Mother; or the prince of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Warrant holders represent a large cross-section of British trade
and industry (and a few foreign names as well), ranging from dry
cleaners to fishmongers, agricultural machinery to computer
software. There are about 800 Royal Warrant holders and about 1,100
Royal Warrants (some holders have more than one warrant).
</P>
<P>
   About J&AMP;B: If online, look at this site _
www.royal.gov.uk/faq/warrants/qlist.html _ and under the J list
you'll find Justerini &AMP; Brooks Limited, Wine Merchants, London.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Years ago, we used to attend the pageant ``Unto These Hills''
in Cherokee, N.C., every summer. I haven't seen it advertised or
mentioned lately. Has it been disbanded?
</P>
<P>
   A: The outdoor drama is by no means disbanded. It's in the midst
of its 51st summer season in a 2,800-seat outdoor theater in
western North Carolina. The season runs through Aug. 26.
Information: For tickets and dates, call 828-497-2111. General
information online: www.dnet.net/(tilde)cheratt/unto.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened to Robert Chambers, the so-called ``preppy
killer'' in New York? Is he out of prison?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. He is still incarcerated at the Auburn Correctional
Facility in New York. He is serving a sentence of 5-to-15 years in
the strangling death of Jennifer Levin in August 1986 after being
convicted of manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the New York Board of Paroles said Chambers
will not see the parole board again before December. The board
denied his bids for freedom in 1992 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers got his nickname because he was a prep school graduate.
His victim also attended exclusive schools. Chambers initially
claimed he accidentally killed Levin, 18, during ``rough sex'' in
Central Park. In 1988, he interrupted jury deliberations in his
second-degree murder trial to plead guilty to first-degree
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Former Atlanta Brave Denny Neagle was traded by the
Cincinnati Reds to the New York Yankees for four prospects,
including Double A third baseman and Michigan starting quarterback
Drew Henson. Is Henson one of those people who plays both sports?
</P>
<P>
   A: Henson is indeed a two-sport star. After he was traded from
the Yankees, Henson said the deal may force him to decide between
baseball and football.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who saw Henson as a top prospect since drafting him
out of high school in 1998, dealt the 20-year-old after he refused
to commit to one sport. As reported by the Associated Press,
Yankees owner George Steinbrenner was said to have offered Henson
as much as $3 million to stick with baseball, although Henson said
no dollar figure was floated. ``I am disappointed that I could not
stay with the (Yankees) organization,'' Henson told reporters after
the trade. He added that Steinbrenner was prepared to make him a
Yankee ``for life,'' but he wasn't prepared to make that
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations are high at Michigan for Henson to follow in the
footsteps of Tom Brady, who guided the Wolverines to a 10-2 record
last season. With Henson as the starting quarterback for his junior
season, the Wolverines are the preseason favorite to win the Big
Ten.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
