A3383 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-WALKER-COLUMN27-COX     07-26 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tis' the season for ozone, haze and political hot air
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ It's almost been too hot to think and too hazy
to see.
</P>
<P>
   We have five seasons in East Texas: football, winter, spring,
summer and ozone. We are now in ozone.
</P>
<P>
   Seems like one thing always does manage to break through
whatever artificial or natural barriers that might surround us,
though.
</P>
<P>
   Politics.
</P>
<P>
   It was interesting to hear the clarion call for the $1.8 million
in ``savings'' the city of Longview is claiming during the last
year. Oops, make that cost avoidance, or is it donations?
</P>
<P>
   Can you make out the new buzz? You have to pedal fast to keep up
with these great minds. By my calculations, once the city formally
accepts property that has been donated for new soccer fields, city
staff may get another break. Similarly to Heritage Plaza _ a
project originated outside city hall and funded through private
donations that represented $500,000 of the touted $1.8 million _
we'll apparently be able to count the value of the athletic fields
donation as savings, or cost avoidance or whatever the most
politically expedient term happens to be at that moment.
</P>
<P>
   On a wider political front, the fax machine has been spewing
forth some intriguing information from candidates for area
congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago we received a one-page fax trumpeting a
news conference to be held by Noble Willingham at which he would
announce his new energy policy, the ``Gas Price Stabilization
Act.'' Willingham is the GOP challenger to U.S. Rep. Max Sandlin,
who represents the First Congressional District of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil for debt'' it said. The ``Gas Price Stabilization Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Our reporter showed up at the appointed time as did one from the
Tyler paper, but Gregg County GOP headquarters was locked up tight,
not a soul there. Phone calls to the number listed on the
announcement (not the local
</P>
<P>
   GOP number) were answered by a recording saying the number had
been changed to another, but that the new number wasn't working
yet. A few days later we did hear from a party spokesman that they
had sent a fax to us canceling the event. Apparently both
newspapers' fax machines were on the blink at the same time. I
blame it on the ozone.
</P>
<P>
   More political haze followed:
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, we received another faxed notice, almost a
twin to the previous one, about a break-through wonderful new
energy policy, the ``Gas Price Stabilization Act.'' Same quotes and
everything. Same thing Noble, best known for his role in the TV
series ``Walker, Texas Ranger,'' apparently would have unveiled if
he had shown up.
</P>
<P>
   One slight change, though. This time the candidate's name on the
letterhead was Jon Newton, who is running against Congressman Ralph
Hall of the Fourth Congressional District. Newton showed up.
</P>
<P>
   I'm still wondering how he got the energy policy and Noble
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Turning toward the rest of our ozone-challenged state, I firmly
believe that Al Gore might be the best thing that could happen to
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Did you see how fast our projected budget surplus grew the
closer the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee got to San
Antonio?
</P>
<P>
   By golly, let's bring that boy back out here a few more times.
</P>
<P>
   It won't hurt Bush; he'll win Texas anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander's calculator was
shooting sparks refiguring an ever-growing surplus of money for the
newest state budget. That surplus went from $1.1 billion to $1.4
billion in just days, since news of a projected
</P>
<P>
   shortfall hit the streets and the Democrats started howling _
and George W. Bush began to be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore came to visit more often, we could end up being able to
afford a computer for every school child in Texas. Teachers could
have their health insurance and retirement all fixed up. Taxes
would plummet. We could maybe help pay for a summer lunch program
for hungry kids in Longview that lasts past June.
</P>
<P>
   What do those several thousand children who took part in the
nutrition program do for food the rest of the summer anyway? Did
anyone else wonder about that?
</P>
<P>
   Season's greetings.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, P.O. Box 1792, Longview, TX 75606. E-mail:
awalker(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
