<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION-UNDERWRITERS (Undated) _ Next week's Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia will feature prominent names
like Colin Powell, John McCain, Elizabeth Dole and, of course,
George W. Bush. But the names that won't appear center stage at
Philadelphia's First Union Center are the ones that will actually
pay for the convention _ names like General Motors, Microsoft,
PepsiCo and AT&AMP;T. Corporations are underwriting much of the cost of
both conventions. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I am not the sort of husband who
forgets wedding anniversaries, mainly because I'm allergic to
armor-piercing bullets. So I remembered that Cathy and I celebrated
our 12th recently. As I look back on the wedding itself, it taught
me a crucial lesson about marriage _ a common-sense principle that
employers ought to remember when hiring people. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   MERCURY-NEWS (San Francisco) _ The San Jose Mercury News entered
the competitive San Francisco newspaper market in earnest
Wednesday, with an edition tailored for the city promising local
news, a well-regarded business section and expanded listings for
arts and entertainment coverage. By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' CATEGORY)
</P>
<P>
   COPS-EXECUTIVE (San Francisco) _ San Francisco's independent
police watchdog agency has been unable to complete its
investigation of the 1998 shooting of an advertising executive
because of an uncooperative Police Department. Office of Citizen
Complaints Director Mary Dunlap said her investigation into John
Smart's Oct. 6, 1998, killing _ he was shot more than 15 times by
police as he tried to flee in his car _ had been repeatedly delayed
by lack of cooperation from the department's homicide and internal
affairs units. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   HEARST-HACIENDA (San Francisco) _ The showplace estate known as
the Hacienda, built by press tycoon William Randolph Hearst on what
is now Fort Hunter Liggett in southern Monterey County, may be
incorporated into the national park system under an unusual
arrangement between the Park Service and the Army. Hearst sold the
165,000-acre military base, including the Hacienda, to the Army in
1940. Now the National Park Service is interested in acquiring the
Hacienda along with 76 other buildings and 100 acres on the base
that the Army has declared excess. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-BEACH-BOY (Undated) _ In his youth, Brian Wilson was
famous for his competitive drive _ in his mind, he toiled against
wall-of-sound producer Phil Spector, the Beatles and his father.
But the man who led the Beach Boys is no longer ``Stalin of the
Studio.'' Still, his recent performances of ``Pet Sounds'' live
onstage are blowing minds; some rock critics have described the
shows as a religious experience. By HECTOR SALDANA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEN-ANNA-KOURNIKOVA (Stanford, Calif.) _ Just call it
Anna-proofing. There is a large window at the main entrance to the
Taube Family Tennis Stadium behind which the press room is located.
Last year, when Anna Kournikova made her Bank of the West Classic
debut, the area in front of that window was home to a veritable
throng of fans _ OK, men _ with their noses pressed against the
glass, knocking and waving as the Russian teen made her postmatch
remarks. This year, there is a small wooden picket fence extending
out about 5 feet away from the window and a security guard manning
the location to ensure against a repeat of Anna-mania. By MICHELLE
SMITH.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-HALL-OF-FAME (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _ Consider all the negative
axioms you hear about baseball stadiums today. And when you have
heard enough, come here, to Cooperstown. Come to its signature
stadium, Doubleday Field, where baseball is so revered that no one
would dare to complain about anything. By TIM REYNOLDS.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS (Stockton, Calif.) _ Nearly half an hour after
practice, with most of the 49ers in the locker room, Jerry Rice
runs 40-yard sprints and Terrell Owens runs pass routes, catching
balls from quarterback Jeff Garcia. ``These guys want to be nothing
less than the best,'' said George Stewart, in his first year as the
49ers wide receivers coach. By BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Let's play Republican role
reversal. See Dick pick George to run with instead of the other way
around. If Dick Cheney were nominated for president, he'd be too
conservative, have too bad a heart, be too aged for his 59 years,
and be too highly paid an oil-company executive ever to get
elected. So if a Cheney/Bush ticket would be a complete loser, why
is a Bush/Cheney ticket any better? By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
