<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GOP-CITY27-COX     07-26 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CITY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOUTH PHILLY AN EAGER HOST FOR GOP CONVENTIONEERS
 &HT;    Moving in (p) politics and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Yo! Republicans! South Philly is ready with the
cheese steaks and water ice and rock 'n' roll memories.
</P>
<P>
   The First Union Center, where the Republican National Convention
will be held next week, is located in the fabled neighborhood where
American Bandstand's original couples choreographed the Stroll and
the Bop. An Italian heritage lingers. Thursday night is spaghetti
night all across South Philly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocky'' ran the streets here, training for his first cinematic
title fight. Joey Bishop and David Brenner practiced comedy
routines on the corners. Fifties teen idols Frankie Avalon, Bobby
Rydell and Fabian grew up listening to local doo-wop groups and
eating soft pretzels on the sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   A strong sense of community has survived the decades since then,
said Barbara Capouzzi, a neighborhood activist. Families have
stayed, generation after generation, despite having the economic
means to move to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no place like South Philly,'' said Michael Italiano,
the third-generation owner of Pop's Homemade Water Ice on Oregon
Avenue, a few blocks from the new arena where the Republicans will
convene.
</P>
<P>
   Italiano's grandfather, Philippe, was the ``Pop'' who started
selling the fruit-flavored confections from a pushcart in 1932.
Eaten with a spoon, slushy water ices are a summer staple in an
area where food is a passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell the kids that even if they make $20 million, they'll
never eat better than they did growing up in South Philadelphia,''
said Italiano. ``First off, their mamas are all great cooks. Then
there are wonderful bakeries and delis on every corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Another local claim to culinary fame is the cheese steak hoagie.
It was 1930, said Frank E. Olivieri, when his great-uncle, Pat,
concocted the sandwiches of grilled beef and onions and melted
cheese on a long, soft loaf of fresh-baked bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``He dubbed himself 'the King of Steaks' because no one else was
selling them,'' said Olivieri, who operates Pat's King of Steaks,
still located at the intersection of Passyunk Avenue and Ninth
Street.
</P>
<P>
   But nowadays, cheese steak hoagies are sold on practically every
block in South Philly.
</P>
<P>
   If you want cheese, order it ``wit','' warned Frank DiCicco, the
Democratic councilman who represents the area. Four generations of
his family have lived on the same block.
</P>
<P>
   South Philly is where the Mummers live, said DiCicco. They meet
and practice year-round in clubhouses for their traditional
costumed parade on New Years Day. They'll hold a special parade
during the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the neighborhood has been home to a few
goodfellas, of course, and some blocks still look like a movie set
from ``The Godfather.'' But the narrow streets and neat row houses
are now decked out for the city's first national political
convention since 1948. A banner welcoming the GOP is stretched
across Passyunk Avenue, and state flags hang from the street lights
along Broad Street. Pink hydrangeas are blooming in tiny front
yards, and potted plants adorn well-scrubbed stoops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's welcome _ protesters, Republicans, Democrats,
reporters,'' said Italiano.
</P>
<P>
   But few of the 4,150 GOP delegates and alternates or 15,000
journalists and media technicians will be staying in South Philly.
Most hotels are located in the bustling, renovated center city or
in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The fenced-in Free Speech Zone, set up by police for protesters,
is in South Philly's FDR Park, near the First Union Center. Up to
20,000 demonstrators are expected, but their leaders have vowed not
to be confined to this ``protest pit.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention ``is definitely the talk of the town,'' said
Keith Henderson, 31, a taxi driver who has lived all his life in
Philadelphia. ``It'll be good for business, but there is a lot of
anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic city administration and Philadelphia 2000, the
host committee, have worked for months to use the convention
promote a revitalized Philadelphia and to show the visitors a good
time.
</P>
<P>
   In a city that hasn't had a GOP mayor for more than half a
century, local Democratic office-holders promised to wear T-shirts
saying ``Republican for a Week'' during the convention _ and then
to ceremoniously burn them at its conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Horticultural Society has arranged thousands of
flowering plants on sidewalks and storefronts in areas to be
visited by delegates and reporters. Municipal tow trucks removed
more than 30,000 abandoned cars from city streets. Volunteers have
scrubbed graffiti from walls likely to be seen by conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   At night, the Philadelphia skyline glows with red, white and
blue lights atop the twin glass towers of Liberty Place. At ground
level, a 60-ton sand sculpture of Abraham Lincoln reminds the
Republicans of their roots. Dick Clark has been booked to host two
American Bandstand-themed parties, with performances by
Philadelphians Rydell, Avalon and Chubby Checker. Fireworks will
illuminate the Delaware River.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of the sort of protests that plagued Seattle and
Washington during international trade meetings, the city council
passed an ordinance outlawing the wearing of masks by anyone
intending to intimidate or commit a crime. The anti-globalist
protesters often wear bandannas soaked in vinegar to ward off tear
gas, or all-black outfits with ski masks.
</P>
<P>
   But Philadelphia's image-molders suffered setbacks this summer.
First, the nation watched TV news videotape of police from the City
of Brotherly Love kicking and beating a carjacking suspect. The
Philadelphia Daily News put a photo of the incident on the front
page with the headline ``Welcome, America.'' Then an Amtrak
policeman shot and killed a homeless, deranged man after he
attacked another office with a chair in the 30th Street Station,
the hub of the city's rail transportation system.
</P>
<P>
   A strike by city workers was averted this week, however, and
spirits were up in South Philly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a friendly place,'' enthused Paul Giordano, whose family
has operated a fruit and produce market in the neighborhood since
1917. It's where somebody tossed an orange to Sylvester Stallone
(another South Philly native) in the first ``Rocky'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philadelphia is the biggest small town in the country,'' said
Giordano. ``It's a place where everybody knows everybody. It's a
town of distinct communities that all have names. We're in the
heart of South Philly. Then there's Queen Village, Society Hill,
Northern Liberties, the Old City, Fish Town, Chestnut Hill. There
are dozens of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I love Philadelphia?'' he asked. ``I adore Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.philadelphia2000.org
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
