<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3414 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BBO-HALL-OF-FAME-HNS &LR;      07-26 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HALL-OF-FAME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BASEBALL DREAMS COME ALIVE IN DOUBLEDAY FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM REYNOLDS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ For a moment, consider all the negative
axioms you hear about baseball stadiums today. Veterans Stadium is
rundown. Olympic Stadium has no atmosphere. Safeco Field is too
expensive. So on. And so forth.
</P>
<P>
   If you have heard enough, come here. Come to Cooperstown. Come
to its signature stadium, Doubleday Field, where baseball is so
revered that no one would dare to complain about anything.
</P>
<P>
   Hot dogs are cheap. Beer is not for sale. There isn't much
parking. The seats have no leg room.
</P>
<P>
   If you want amenities, go somewhere else. If you want baseball,
come here.
</P>
<P>
   Come here, where players actually mingle with fans before the
game and between innings. Come here, where pitchers never seem to
throw at someone's head, where no one flunks drug tests, where no
one's spikes come in too high while breaking up a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday Field is a park where the outfield fences are
ridiculously close to home plate _ 296 feet down the line to left,
312 to right, 336 and 350 to the left- and right-field alleys,
respectively _ and no one minds that, either.
</P>
<P>
   This is sacred ground, this place that has the sign out front
saying, ``Welcome to the birthplace of baseball.'' If baseball is
your religion, Cooperstown is your pilgrimage, and if you ever
played the game, Doubleday Field is your mecca.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians and Arizona Diamondbacks were here Monday,
playing the annual Hall of Fame Game at Doubleday Field, the
meaningless _ er, exhibition _ game that caps off every year's
induction weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't call it meaningless,'' Diamondbacks manager Buck
Showalter said. ``Call it an exhibition. No game ever played
anywhere is meaningless, especially here.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter should know. His managerial career started 22 miles
from here, in tiny old Oneonta, where he managed the Yankees'
short-season Class A New York-Penn League team in 1983 and 1984.
</P>
<P>
   That was a wonderful time for Showalter; his teams won more than
70 percent of their games, and he could come to the Hall of Fame
whenever he wanted. He didn't get paid much, but other than that,
is there a better managerial job in baseball, where you win every
day and then can visit the Hall every night?
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting four homers in the first round of Monday's annual
Hall of Fame Game home-run contest, Richie Sexson stepped out of
the batting cage and asked the people standing around: ``Can we
play here every day?''
</P>
<P>
   Former Indian Bob Feller turned to Sexson, the current Indian,
and said: ``No one's that lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Hear that, and know how this place is revered. Somehow, a tiny
brick stadium, where any crowd bigger than 10,000 almost literally
sends people to Susquehanna Avenue to watch the game, has captured
the hearts and minds of all who step inside its gates.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say that the ``Birthplace of baseball'' story is a
myth, that the cow pasture once owned by Elihu Phinney and known
today as Doubleday Field is not the birthplace of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Even if those historians are correct, it's doubtful that
Cooperstown's legacy will ever change. The place has an aura.
</P>
<P>
   Main Street has it. The Hall of Fame building has it. And
without question, the old cow pasture where youngsters come to feel
old and oldsters come to feel young certainly has it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in here,'' 2000 inductee Sparky Anderson says of
the Hall, ``you're in the house where you'll live forever.''
</P>
<P>
   And whether baseball was born here or not, Doubleday Field is
the house where the sport's roots will live forever, along with its
dreams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
