<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3416 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-MUSIC-BEACH-BOY-HNS &LR;      07-26 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BEACH-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BEACH BOY BACK ON FAMILIAR TURF WITH NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HECTOR SALDANA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brian Wilson's latest album, the two-CD ``Live at the Roxy
Theatre'' (Brimel Records), opens with the Beach Boys' gem ``The
Little Girl I Once Knew.'' And that is telling because he has
changed, too.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is not the genius we once knew.
</P>
<P>
   The man who led the Beach Boys, the group responsible for the
most all-American soundtracks of the '60s, takes his ``Pet Sounds''
concert Thursday to the Backyard, near Austin, Texas, one of the
stops in his current tour.
</P>
<P>
   In his youth, Wilson was famous for his competitive drive _ in
his mind, he toiled against wall-of-sound producer Phil Spector,
the Beatles and his father. The former Hawthorne (Calif.) High
School athlete concedes that part of him is dead.
</P>
<P>
   He is no longer Mike Love's ``Stalin of the Studio.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it went out of me. That went out of me a few years back,''
Wilson said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   But his recent performances of ``Pet Sounds'' live onstage (with
an orchestra in some cities) are blowing minds; some rock critics
have described the shows as a religious experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the people in the audience think it's great,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though he never surfed, and was actually afraid of the ocean (it
was his late brother, Dennis, who loved the sea), Wilson can't help
describing singing songs from the 1966 album, which sent shock
waves through the Beatles' camp, in salt-water terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a powerful surge, a very powerful surge,'' he said.
``It's very satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Wilson said the Beach Boys wouldn't have performed
``Pet Sounds'' live when the record came out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no, they wouldn't have wanted to,'' he said, explaining
that the band's teeny-bopper fans wouldn't have accepted it.
</P>
<P>
   He adds, however, that the boys had the talent to deliver the
songs in concert.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said being back on the road is ``a good move in a tried
and proven method.'' This is no ill-advised ``Brian Is Back''
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``My voice is fine, and my spirits are fine, too,'' he said.
``I'm in a good place.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is so into it that he signs autographs after shows.
</P>
<P>
   That's extraordinary access to a man who has been a recluse most
of his adult life and spent a depressed three years in bed in the
'70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked my head off,'' he said about doing interviews
during the current tour. ``It's fun to get into it. I like it!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got nothing to hide,'' added Wilson, who travels these
days with his wife and their adopted daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The early Beach Boys was his baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big project. It was a big, emotionally secure idea.
And then it just got rough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs, dysfunction and destiny took their toll. But even in his
darkest times, Wilson managed ``Sail On, Sailor,'' ``'Til I Die,''
``Do It Again'' and ``Darlin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's greatest influence remains the Four Freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I analyzed the harmonies,'' he said. ``And I realized that I
could do that. It gave me confidence. If I could copy a Four
Freshmen arrangement, then I could do anything on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   He collected Phil Spector records and took those famous singles
apart, as well. ``Yeah, I studied them. I really would study
them,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's ego was enormous in his heyday. The ``Pet Sounds''
track ``I Know There's an Answer'' was originally titled ``Hang On
to Your Ego.'' Still, he never felt he topped his heroes' music.
``It was never that way at all.''
</P>
<P>
   For his current tour, Wilson went through the Beach Boys'
catalog and handpicked the songs he wanted (including exquisite,
rarely performed tracks off Capitol Records' newly reissued
``Sunflower'' and ``Surf's Up'').
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that simple,'' he said. ``I made sure they were songs
that made me feel secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Will he continue to tour? ``I think so. We're going out in
September, too.''
</P>
<P>
   How does he balance the perfectionist and studio producer side
of himself with the shy live musician?
</P>
<P>
   ``That happened today, I had to let it go. The perfectionism in
me _ I had to let it go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and his brother, Carl, prayed together every day before
the making of ``Pet Sounds.'' What is the message now?
</P>
<P>
   ``The same as in the '60s,'' he said. ``A lot of spiritual love.
There's love in my band's voices and there's love in my voice, so
we're covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he plans to record a new album in October and writes
songs every day. On the outside, at least, it seems the surf is
indeed up.
</P>
<P>
   Musically, he's still into pop vocalists. ``I like Ricky Martin
and the Backstreet Boys,'' he said, adding that he's seen both acts
perform. ``I like their energy and their youth, their `youth-ness.'
They're good-looking guys.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contact Hector Saldana by e-mail at
hsaldana(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
