<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chutneys
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, many food trend watchers tapped chutney as the
accompaniment to watch in the new millenium. Chutney would become
``the next salsa,'' many said. Sure enough, chutney has been
popping up all over the pages of slick food magazines and in the
scripted recitations of white jacketed waiters in upscale
restaurants. Chutney this, chutney that. Chutney sounds a whole lot
more high brow than pickle relish or Aunt Cora's chow chow. But the
fact is, chutney is just a fancy (read British) way of saying
relish.
</P>
<P>
   Chutney which has been around forever came to England via India
where the word actually means relish. And what does relish mean?
According Websters....``an appetizing flavor..pleasing
taste...pleasure...enjoyment...zest.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is what chutney and relishes are all about. In the
chemistry of a dinner plate a little dab of chutney or relish can
be the catalyst that puts the taste buds on high alert and becomes
the counterpoint that ignites the flavors and textures of
everything else on the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Now that fresh fruits and vegetables are available year round,
chutneys and relishes no longer have to involve complicated canning
and preserving procedures. While chutney emerges into the culinary
spotlight, chefs everywhere are experimenting with an amazing
number of creative variations that can be made fresh and stored in
the refrigerator for up to three weeks. Chutneys and relishes,
after all are mainly chopped fruit and vegetables with vinegar and
spices added. The difference is primarily in texture.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the familiar cucumber, onion, carrots and peppers now
you will see chutneys made with banannas, tomatoes, blueberries,
strawberries, rasberries, peaches, pears, plums, apples,
cranberries, mangos, papaya, pineapple, cherrys and coconuts all
being used to accompany hot and cold meats, fish, shell fish, fowl,
egg, cheese and vegetables in a host of combinations.
</P>
<P>
   To get on the chutney bandwagon and add interest and surprise to
your cooking, check out these websites for some ideas and
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Drummond Farms at www.organicchutney.com/dfrecp1.html offers
some enticing organic chutney recipes with appropriate entrees that
include Salmon in Raspberry Chutney Marinade, Chutney Baked Pork
Chops and Roast Turkey With Apple Currant Chutney Stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   Scroll down at the Food Day site for a book review of ``Chutneys
&AMP; Relishes'' by Lou Seibert Pappas that offers some enticing
pairings and sample recipes that include cranberry shallot chutney
and cilantro corn relish. See
www.globalgourmet.com/food/foodday/fd1097/fd102897.html.
</P>
<P>
   From India, where chutney originated, see
www.ivu.org/recipes/indian-chutney/ for a savory list of authentic
Indian chutney recipes.
</P>
<P>
   There are chutneys for every season using seasonal fruits and
vegetables at www.hannibal.net/stories/091599/feagardengoods.html.
</P>
<P>
   For some imaginative recipes for hot weather chutneys and
relishes see www.mail-archive.com/hot-weather-recipe%40onelist.com
</P>
<P>
   msg00063.html
</P>
<P>
   SOAR lists 169 chutney recipes from apple to zucchini at
soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/chutneys/.
</P>
<P>
   Saving the best for last _ you don't even have to make the 70
recipes for chutneys, relishes, and salasas at Epicurious' Pick a
Pack of Pickles. Just reading the recipes _ which use everything
from mangoes and watermelons to pineapples and pears _ is enough to
make your mouth water. See
www.epicurious.com/eeating/e02pickling/pickledrecipes.html.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT/sally sams
</P>
<P>
   Spicy Tomato Chutney
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 1 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 1/4 to 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   This recipe originally accompanied Roast Beef, Basil, and Spicy
Tomato Chutney LaVash Sandwiches. It would pair well with grilled
fish or chicken, or would be a nice pasta topping.
</P>
<P>
   1pound vine-ripened tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, stem, ribs and seeds removed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chopped scallions, green parts only
</P>
<P>
   Chop tomatoes and bell pepper into medium dice. In a medium
saucepan, bring vinegars to a boil with sugar, salt, mustard seeds,
black pepper, and red pepper flakes, stirring occasionally. When
the sugar and salt are dissolved, stir in the tomatoes, pepper, and
scallions. Simmer mixture, uncovered, stirring occasionally, about
1 1/4 hours, or until thickened and reduced to about 1 1/2 cups.
Cool chutney completely. Chutney keeps, covered and chilled, 2
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: xx calories, xx grams protein, xx grams fat
(percent calories from fat, xx), xx grams carbohydrates, xx
milligrams cholesterol, xx milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Pineapple and Mint Chutney
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 3 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes or less, with 1 hour resting time
after preparation
</P>
<P>
   This is closer to relish than a chutney, as it is not cooked. It
is very fresh-tasting and is a crowd-pleaser. Can be used with
grilled fish or meat (pork tenderloin would be especially nice), or
as a small side offering.
</P>
<P>
   1cup loosely packed fresh mint leaves, rinsed, spun dry, and
chopped fairly fine
</P>
<P>
   1 (4 1/2-pound) pineapple, peeled, cored, and cut into 1/3-inch
dice
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup minced red onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar, or to tast
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl combine the mint with the pineapple, the onion, the
sugar, and a pinch of salt. Stir the mixture until it is well
combined. Let the chutney stand, covered, for 1 hour. The chutney
may be made 1 week in advance and kept covered and chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: xx calories, xx grams protein, xx grams fat
(percent calories from fat, xx), xx grams carbohydrates, xx
milligrams cholesterol, xx milligrams sodium, x grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
