<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Go bananas with big bowl of pudding
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along with her Mississippi Mud Cake recipe sent in response to
another reader's request, Jerrie Merritt of Blue Ridge included her
own plea for a banana pudding she recalls that is made with
condensed milk and served in a tall pedestal dish.
</P>
<P>
   This one, published a decade ago, makes a big bowl of dessert,
perfect for a hungry dozen.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Luscious Banana
</P>
<P>
   Pudding
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: about 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   1 (14-ounce) can condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 (3 1/2-ounce) package instant vanilla pudding
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whipping cream, whipped
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 dozen vanilla wafers
</P>
<P>
   3 medium bananas, sliced, dipped in lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Beat condensed milk, water and pudding until well mixed. Chill 5
minutes. Fold in whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Put 1 cup of pudding mixture in bottom of glass bowl. Layer
vanilla wafers, bananas and pudding, repeating until all
ingredients are used. Chill thoroughly before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 256 calories, 4 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 43), 34 grams carbohydrates, 46
milligrams cholesterol, 88 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Request
</P>
<P>
   John Ernest II of Story City, Iowa, has lost a favorite recipe
for what he calls Pork Snax. He says small balls of ground pork
were cooked and drained, then surrounded by biscuit dough from a
mix and baked on a cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
