<TEXT>
<P>
   Locate hard to find items
</P>
<P>
   By Marylin Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been looking for Physicians Formula Gentle Cover
Concealer Stick. Any idea where I can find it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Doris Brown, Covington, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We have you covered. Available at Ulta stores, we found this
yellow-toned concealer stick at the 3495 Buckhead Loop N.E.
location (404-266-3559). A 15-ounce tube is $4.29. Applied before
makeup, this concealer works to hide dark under-eye circles, even
out skin tone and conceal bruises.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find Cinch, the 2 in 1 cleaner for glass and
windows?
</P>
<P>
   _ Linda Warwick,
</P>
<P>
   Canton, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: It was a cinch to find Cinch. We discovered this cleaner at
the Big Kmart store, 2581 Piedmont Road N.E. (404-261-6900). A
32-ounce spray bottle is $2.69. A spokeswoman for the manufacturer,
Procter &AMP; Gamble, says it's also available at Kroger, Publix and
Target stores. In addition to cleaning ``windows to a streak-free
shine,'' Cinch takes a shine to appliances, chrome, stainless
steel, fiberglass and walls. And note: Cinch contains no phosphate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to find Barq's diet root beer. I see the regular
version but not the diet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laurie Thomas, Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another Barq's request: I'm having withdrawal! Since moving
to this area, I can't find Barq's diet root beer. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark McElroy, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Yet a third query: I am looking for Barq's diet root beer. I
don't have trouble finding the regular but the diet is almost
impossible to find.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cessie Walls,
</P>
<P>
   Peachtree City, Ga.,
</P>
<P>
   A: Lovers of Barq's Olde Tyme diet root beer will be delighted
to know their low-cal favorite is available at Publix, 7525 Roswell
Road (678-443-8980). Six 12-ounce cans are $2.09. The diet root
beer has also been spotted at Harris Teeter and Kroger stores in
Peachtree City. It was created in 1898 by Edward C. Barq Sr. in
Biloxi, Miss. Coca-Cola bought the brand in 1995. On the can,
Edward ``Sonny'' Barq IV offers a challenge to root beer drinkers.
He writes: ``When you taste diet Barq's, I think you'll agree it
might just be the best-tasting low-calorie soft drink you ever
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find Alexander Julian's perfume Womenwear? Every
time I wear it, I receive so many compliments. I hope it is still
being produced.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Chunn,
</P>
<P>
   Lithonia, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: What an aptly named perfume for women. We sniffed out your
request and came up with Alexander Julian's Womenwear at Ulta, 3495
Buckhead Loop N.E. (404-266-3559). Each of the teal-colored bottles
with an orchid top (2-ounce spray, $31.49) is crafted and glazed
individually by hand. Menswear designer Alexander Julian introduced
his perfume in 1991 as a sultry, floral blend highlighted by warm
amber notes, touches of cassis and passion fruit, and with a hint
of white musk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a facial soap I used years ago called
Cuticura. I have been unable to find it recently.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Hayes, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: We cleaned up on this request. Cuticura Medicated
Antibacterial Bar is available at Walgreens, 4371 S. Cobb Drive,
Smyrna 30080 (678-556-0570). A 3-ounce bar is $1.99. For years,
Cuticura has been the choice of dermatologists, since, says the
manufacturer, ``this non-comedogenic cleansing formula contains
non-drying ingredients to deep clean and remove excess dirt and oil
that may cause blemishes and acne.''
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
