<HEADER>
A3452 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-KITCHEN-CONVERSATION2     07-26 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-CONVERSATION27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strange but true: Grilled chicken and beer can a match made in
heaven
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicken is rarely the first thing that comes to my mind when I
think of firing up the grill. I flip a mean burger. I'm perfecting
the steak. And this summer I've had some success with finicky fish.
</P>
<P>
   But chicken? Boring. At least that's what I thought until beer
changed my mind. Or more precisely a beer can.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a sordid tale of drunkenness. In fact, I don't drink
beer at all. But I became so intrigued by the notion of ``beer can
chicken'' that I went right out and bought a six pack. Cook's
Illustrated _ the magazine that tests one dish a gazillion
different ways to discover the best preparation _ declares in the
August issue that ``beer can chicken'' is tops for grill-roasting a
bird.
</P>
<P>
   And when cookbook author and grilling guru Steven Raichlen was
in town, he demonstrated beer-can game hens for folks at Cook's
Warehouse. ``I don't know who did this first. But it sure has
captured the national imagination,'' said Raichlen. ``It is the
most succulent chicken you will ever taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, you take a can of beer and drink half of it (or
pour it out). Throw a pinch of your favorite dry rub into the
remaining beer. (You can also try lemonade in a can instead of
beer.) Some suggest popping an extra hole in the top with a church
key can opener.
</P>
<P>
   Next, massage a dry rub over a whole bird. Stick with a fryer
rather than a roaster, one about 3 1/2 pounds. Or go with Cornish
hens _ one for each diner. For the rub, Raichlen likes to mix a 1/4
cup each of kosher salt, black pepper, sweet paprika and brown
sugar. Try it or use your favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Heat up the coals or the gas grill. Be sure the grate is low
enough that the lid will close once the upright bird is placed on
the grill. Once it's good and hot, move the coals to one side or
turn off a burner to create a spot for some indirect heat. Place
the beer can on the grate (but not directly over the flame/coals)
and then ``sit'' the chicken on top of the beer. Simply lower the
cavity of the bird over the can. Use the legs to create balance if
need be.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the grill and allow the chicken to roast for about 70-90
minutes or until the internal temperature registers 165 degrees in
the breast area and 180 degrees in the thigh. (You do have a meat
thermometer, right? If not, put it on your grocery list.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This might seem like a totally goofy recipe, but there are
some real scientific principles at work,'' Raichlen explained. ``By
roasting the chicken upright, the fat drains off and the skin gets
crispy. Meanwhile, the beer is steaming the chicken from the inside
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the chicken is cooked, remove from the grill and let it sit
for about 10 minutes before carving. Then serve it with some of the
Coca-Cola Barbecue Sauce from Raichlen's ``Barbecue Bible! Sauces,
Rubs and Marinades'' (Workman Publishing, $12.95.) It's the real
thing, especially for real delicious chicken.
</P>
<P>
   COCA-COLA BARBECUE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   In a heavy saucepan, combine the following: 1 cup Coca-Cola, 1
cup ketchup, 1/4 cup Worcestershire sauce, 1 teaspoon liquid smoke,
3 tablespoons A.1. Steak Sauce, 1 teaspoon onion flakes, 1 teaspoon
garlic flakes and 1/2 teaspoon freshly ground pepper. You can
season additionally to taste. (I like a few red pepper flakes for
heat.)
</P>
<P>
   Bring the mixture to a gentle boil and then reduce the heat and
simmer about 8 minutes. Use right away or transfer to a large jar,
cover, cool to room temperature and refrigerate. This recipe makes
about 2 cups and will keep for a couple of months in the fridge.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
