<HEADER>
A3453 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PERGOLAS27-COX     07-26 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERGOLAS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arbors, pergolas reach new heights with lovers of the great
outdoors
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Michele Burns wants to savor her garden, she
simply looks up. In spring, wisteria drips its heady scent over her
outdoor dinner table and not long after, pink roses take center
stage. In summer, lush foliage forms a cool canopy for sundown
suppers, while in fall and winter, what's more romantic than
kicking back to gaze at the stars?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so great _ we use it all the time,'' Burns said of the
arbor, which forms a transition between her Atlanta home and
carport.
</P>
<P>
   Structures like hers are cropping up in back yards everywhere as
homeowners spend more time outdoors. Plenty still play it safe,
taking cover under the roofs of porches, pavilions and gazebos. But
a growing number are turning to open structures dating to ancient
times _ especially large arbors and pergolas _ that provide better
ventilation, a view of the sky and the fragrance of blooming vines.
</P>
<P>
   Arbors and pergolas afford not only shady retreats for relaxing
and entertaining but also the kind of structure, focal points and
transitional areas that yards and gardens so often need.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've really become the shaded outdoor living room,'' said
Brooks Garcia, an Atlanta garden designer.
</P>
<P>
   Pergolas _ typically a series of arches linked to form a
tunnel-like framework open on all sides _ have always been used to
frame a view, support climbing vines or provide shade. Arbors serve
the same purposes but traditionally are smaller and partially
enclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Both can be formal or informal, taking into account the style of
both the home's architecture and the garden's style. Some opt for
traditional white columns and latticework, while others prefer the
more natural look of weathered locust, as this sampling from
Atlanta-area gardens shows.
</P>
<P>
   Scaled-up versions
</P>
<P>
   Michele Burns' arbor in Atlanta serves various functions, yet
one thing's for certain: It's got scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wimpy about this one,'' said David Ellis, who
designed the garden.
</P>
<P>
   The arbor creates a focal point at the head of the swimming
pool, with green lattice supports rising from stacked-stone pillars
to a towering ceiling. Against its back white wall is a statue
flanked by gas lanterns.
</P>
<P>
   The structure also connects the house to the carport and so
provides a canopy in bad weather. Architect William Edwards and
Brad McGill of Ellis Land Design designed a circular pattern in the
lattice, which is repeated along the side of the carport and
adjacent cabana.
</P>
<P>
   And being partially enclosed, the arbor lends a safe bet for
poolside entertaining in all types of weather. Wisteria and New
Dawn roses, along with bluestone paving, blend the structure into
the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Making an entrance
</P>
<P>
   Gracey McKeown's rear garden needed bones. From her driveway,
the northwest Atlanta garden begged for an entrance. From her back
porch, it screamed for a focal point.
</P>
<P>
   Architect Keith Summerour created a pergola that gives her both,
with an Old World flare to boot. Tan stuccoed pillars support an
earthy brown-stained barrel roof ensnared with just the right
amount of wisteria _ not too much, not too little. Its bluestone
floor extends onto the adjacent pool's decking.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, oakleaf hydrangeas form a screen along one side and hide
the pool's mechanics. The other side is open to the rest of the
garden. A rustic iron chandelier lighted with votives dangles above
a teak bench, forming a romantic haven removed from the openness of
the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Think before you build
</P>
<P>
   Here are some points to consider when planning an arbor or
pergola:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Decide how you want to use the structure _ as space for
relaxing or entertaining, a focal point, a transitional area, a
simple support for vines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Choose a design in keeping with your home's architecture and
garden style.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Choose a size in scale with its surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Opt for simple designs with strong construction, especially if
the structure will support vines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Plan for access to the pergola, because pathways will need to
be integrated with the rest of the garden.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Avoid a central arch in a narrow garden, which can split the
space visually.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use only one arbor or pergola in a small garden.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Enclose arbors on one or more sides to create mystery in the
space beyond.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use overhead rafters to create privacy from neighboring
windows.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make pergolas tall enough _ 8 to 9 feet _ so vines won't be
intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use only wood pressure-treated with chemicals for posts
installed directly in the ground, because wood will rot without
concrete footings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use pine, fir or cedar if you plan to paint or stain the wood,
redwood for unfinished wood.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Count on spending $12 to $25 per square foot for a wooden
pergola.
</P>
<P>
   Source: ``American Horticultural Society's Practical Guides:
Arches &AMP; Pergolas'' (DK Publishing, $8.95)
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
