<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3454 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION2     07-26 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHOPPING DESTINATION: Hendersonville, N.C.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hendersonville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   sign at the north end of the Main Street shopping district
advises visitors they are entering an international peace zone.
</P>
<P>
   More like an international shopping zone, I'd say. This is a
great little shopping town.
</P>
<P>
   Main Street _ from Sixth Avenue on the north end to First Avenue
on the south _ is framed with shade trees, planters filled with
seasonal color and benches along wide sidewalks made for strolling.
</P>
<P>
   The town is chockablock with wonderful antique emporiums, gift
shops, galleries and great places to have a cup of gourmet coffee,
ice cream or a little something for the ol' sweet tooth.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what we found: Fabulous imported soaps and body-care
products at Banana Moon. Irish imports at one of the 16 stalls at
Portobello. Romantically feminine dresses and jewelry at
Honeysuckle Hollow. Manly-man outdoor gear at Sherman's Sports and
Army Store. Colorful nylon fabric whirligigs twirling in the breeze
outside at Narnia Studios. Fantasy costumes for kids at Dancing
Bear Toys. Great bargains on home decor at Biltmore Village Co.
Antique coral jewelry at Mehri &AMP; Co. Unusual wind chimes made of
recycled items by James Thomas Butler at Mountain Mark's Stepping
Stones Gourmet Coffeehouse &AMP; Gifts for the Heart and Soul (which
takes the prize for the longest business name known to man). And
everything else at Mast General Store.
</P>
<P>
   After two hours, we'd made it down one side of the street,
landing at the delightful Days Gone By _ the circa-1882 Justus
Pharmacy _ for soda fountain-style sandwiches and thick, creamy
milkshakes. (The fresh banana shake would have made a meal in
itself.)
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the midday heat (yes, unfortunately, it does get hot
even in the mountains), we slipped into the cool, dark Skyland Arts
Cinema Center for the 1:05 p.m. showing of ``Chicken Run.'' This
tiny movie house has bistro seating and a cafe menu featuring
pizza, other snacks and beer and wine.
</P>
<P>
   After a few more hours of browsing, we walked two blocks up Main
Street to the Waverly Inn, field headquarters for our shopping
foray. Later that evening, we headed back downtown for dinner at
Cypress Cellar and the Monday-night street dance. And, truth be
told, a little window shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, before leaving town, we checked out the bounty
of Henderson County at the old-fashioned Curb Market, which has
been in operation since 1924. A don't-miss attraction that's open
on Tuesdays, Thursdays and Saturdays, the farmer's co-op features
homegrown fruits and vegetables, flowers, baked goodies,
home-canned jellies and relishes and lots of country crafts,
including hooked and woven rugs, dolls, folk toys, quilts, afghans,
table linens _ and friendly vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the market, you'll see the homemade ice cream tent where
the putt-putt-putt of a John Deere tractor engine turns the churn.
Don't leave without trying a yummy cup of vanilla or whatever else
is available, which could be fresh peach, apple pie or orange
sherbet.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't I tell you this is a great little town?
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-85 north to U.S. 25 on the western
outskirts of Greenville, S.C. Travel north about 40 miles directly
into Hendersonville. It's about a 3 1/2-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most stores are open from 9:30 or 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays. A few stores are open Sunday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Parking on Main Street is free, but sometimes it's
hard to find an empty space. There are metered lots a block off
Main.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: At Visitors Information Center, 201 N. Main St.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most shops are accessible, but some are
small, with narrow aisles.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Visitors Information Center, 201 S. Main St. 9
a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Fridays; 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturdays-Sundays.
1-800-828-4244.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Days Gone By is an old-fashioned ice cream soda parlor that
serves breakfast, sandwiches, burgers and homemade chili. Most
items are $1.95-$4.95. Fountain treats include shakes and sodas
($2.95), egg creams ($1.75) and banana splits ($3.95). 303 N. Main
St. 828-693-9056.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other lunch options: Try Cypress Cellar for a taste of
southern Louisiana (321-C N. Main St., 828-692-6333). The
ladies-who-lunch do it at Lily's, which also serves high tea (542
N. Main St., 828-698-1922). Go Irish at Hannah Flannagan's Pub (300
N. Main St., 828-696-1665), Italian at Cafe Calabria (123 Fifth
Ave. East, 828-693-4440) and Middle Eastern at Majdi's Tent (502 N.
Main St., 828-696-8804). Get dependable sandwiches at Park
Deli-Cafe (437 N. Main St., 828-696-3663) and Three Chopt (103
Third Ave., 828-692-0228).
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   Two popular inns, both on the National Register of Historic
Places, are two blocks from the downtown shopping district. The
Waverly Inn, in the Innkeepers' Register, is known for its
afternoon social hours on the veranda and enormous breakfasts.
Rates: $109-$195. 783 N. Main St. 1-800-537-8195;
www.waverlyinn.com. Next door is the Claddagh Inn, a AAA
three-diamond property that brings a bit of Ireland to Main Street.
Breakfasts are bounteous here, too. 755 N. Main St. 1-800-225-4700;
www.claddaghinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   Hendersonville is hopping all summer. Here's a sampling of
what's happening:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The 41st Sidewalk Art Sale, featuring the works of more than
100 artists, is Aug. 4-5 on Main Street. Sponsored by the Art
League of Henderson County. 828-696-7926.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Music on Main Street concerts are at 7 p.m. Fridays through
Aug. 25 on the lawn of the historic courthouse downtown. Bring
chairs and a picnic supper. 1-800-828-4244.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Street dances _ an 83-year tradition _ are held 8-10 p.m.
Mondays on Main Street between Fourth and Fifth avenues through
Sept. 4. 1-800-828-4244.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  54th North Carolina Apple Festival on Sept. 1-4 features arts
and crafts, entertainment, sporting events and food downtown and in
the surrounding area. 828-697-4557.
</P>
