<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCURY-NEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN JOSE DAILY EXPANDS INTO SAN FRANCISCO MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Jose Mercury News has entered the
competitive San Francisco newspaper market in earnest, promising
local news, a well-regarded business section and expanded listings
for arts and entertainment coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco edition drops ``San Jose'' from the front-page
masthead, simply calling itself the Mercury News.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper is aggressively trying to gain a foothold in the
market, offering subscribers a month of free home delivery, and was
said to be providing copies to newsstands and stores at a wholesale
price of 5 cents, compared with 18 cents for the San Francisco
Chronicle and the San Francisco Examiner. (Mercury News officials
declined to confirm the price, citing competitive reasons).
</P>
<P>
   The launch comes at a time of uncertainty as San Francisco's two
daily newspapers await to see if a federal judge clears the way for
the Hearst Corp. to buy the Chronicle for $660 million and sell its
flagship Examiner to the publisher of a weekly newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury News is owned by Knight Ridder, which publishes 30
other daily newspapers. The Hearst Corp., based in New York, and
the Chronicle Publishing Co. are privately held.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really are making the paper available to a broader audience
at this point,'' Jay Harris, publisher of the San Jose Mercury
News, said Wednesday. ``I think the report we provide, not only in
the coverage of Silicon Valley, but the local news we'll offer on
San Francisco and a sophisticated report on state, national and
global affairs, will be of interest to people in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   The reception from the city's newspaper industry was less
enthusiastic. Two Chronicle editors, Allen Matthews and Michael
Collier, went to the Mercury News' San Francisco bureau and dropped
off two toy cable cars, bells and a pot holder ``for handling hot
stories,'' said Matthews, a deputy city editor.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a front-page story in Wednesday's Mercury News on
pedestrian safety in San Francisco, Phil Bronstein, the executive
editor of the Examiner, said: ``It's nice to see they've belatedly
discovered the pedestrian safety issue, but we've already been
covering that for, what, months?''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury News even got a taste of San Francisco's small-world
nexus of newspapers and politics when the city tagged six of its
new street sales boxes for being too close to curbs or
intersections, or lashed to bike racks or trees.
</P>
<P>
   News racks are monitored by Dan Brugmann, San Francisco's news
rack program manager, who is the son of Bruce Brugmann, publisher
of the Bay Guardian alternative weekly. Dan Brugmann said the six
boxes he cited, out of 20 the entire day, were average for one
publication.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury News executives said the launch had been planned for
several years, as part of an aggressive expansion plan that now
produces seven daily editions tailored to specific geographic areas
_ the counties of Alameda, San Mateo and southern Santa Clara, as
well as the Silicon Valley, Peninsula and Coastline. They have a
combined daily circulation of more than 290,000. Fewer than 2,000
papers currently are sold in San Francisco; officials declined to
say how many readers they hoped to attract.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder also publishes newspapers in Contra Costa County.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury News San Francisco bureau has nine editorial
employees _ six reporters, two columnists and a bureau chief _
compared with about 200 for the Examiner and 350 for the Chronicle.
Susan Goldberg, the managing editor of the newspaper, said there
would be a dozen employees there eventually. It is expected to have
a story about San Francisco on its front page most days, and has a
completely San Francisco-oriented metropolitan news section.
</P>
<P>
   The edition had been anticipated by the San Francisco dailies,
which each launched special Friday city sections and expanded their
business coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
