<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3470 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-26 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HIRING IS NOT MUCH DIFFERENT THAN MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Weddings can teach a crucial lesson about
marriage, a common-sense principle that employers ought to remember
when hiring people. But they usually don't.
</P>
<P>
   Because my wife and I were already older than 30 when we decided
to marry 12 years ago, it seemed silly for her parents or mine to
pay for the wedding. So we paid for it ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   When Mom and Dad are footing the bill, it's easy for couples to
think that they have an unlimited budget, and to chide their
parents for being cheap if they toss up the idea of cutting
corners. But if you pay for the wedding yourself, you have to sweat
the details. Which is more important: having tons of flowers or
live music? Do you want more guests or a nicer honeymoon? Or would
you rather save money and try to buy a house?
</P>
<P>
   You end up debating and compromising and setting priorities. And
guess what? An awful lot of being married involves debating and
compromising and setting priorities.
</P>
<P>
   In the workplace, the closest thing to a wedding is when
companies hire new people. You're making a commitment that isn't
always easy to break, one that can turn the next several years into
heaven or hell. And you're doing it with limited information.
</P>
<P>
   What paying for the wedding yourselves does is bring you from
fantasy into reality. You've already gotten to know your
prospective spouse, but the biggest decision you've made as a
couple might have been what to wear to the prom. Paying for the
wedding forces you to discuss things like money and goals and
friendships and appearances, things that married couples have to
work out.
</P>
<P>
   When you hire people, are you basing the decision on items of
substance or on prom outfits? Probably the latter.
</P>
<P>
   How much substance is involved in your hiring process? A couple
of interviews? Con men give great interviews. The applicant's
references? Even Adolf Hitler probably could have listed a few good
references. A drug test? Someone who's been in a coma for six
months might give a great urine sample.
</P>
<P>
   What does your hiring process do to check for what's really
important: All the stuff that comes after ``I do''? If you're a
boss, here are some things that fit into the category of ``I ought
to do'':
</P>
<P>
   Instead of falling in love with the sound of your own voice,
listen to what questions the applicants ask. Not everyone gives a
glib interview, but anybody who really wants a job will research
the company as thoroughly as possible, and ought to be able to come
up with some intelligent questions.
</P>
<P>
   If all you get are generic questions _ or no questions at all _
you don't exactly have a self-starter on your hands.
</P>
<P>
   If I had a little more nerve, just once in my life I'd interview
an applicant like this: ``Thanks for coming by,'' I'd say. ``So, do
you have any questions about our company?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, no,'' the applicant replies. ``Not really.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, thanks for coming by.''
</P>
<P>
   Give the applicants an assignment. Before your second interview,
ask the contenders to visit one of your stores or check out your
Web site, then share their thoughts with you. Who has the most
insightful comments? Who notices the mistakes that others miss?
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is to give them a business-related question
and ask them to write their answers to bring in for the second
interview. Who makes their points concisely? Who crosses all the
t's and dots all the i's?
</P>
<P>
   If speed is essential to your business, simply ask the
business-related question on the first interview. Either get the
answer orally or give people 15 minutes to write down their
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Another small assignment can be as simple as telling people,
``Give me a call back on Monday morning.'' Who does and who
doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   Ask your assistant or receptionist or security guard if the
applicant ever thanked them for their kindness. If they say no,
that's not a red light, but it's certainly a yellow one.
</P>
<P>
   Thanking people is a little thing, not something that draws the
spotlight. Then again, a marriage rarely succeeds or fails because
of those few hours that the couple spent in the spotlight on their
wedding day. Usually it depends on all those little kindnesses that
they either keep doing or stop doing, and how many more little
things they find to be thankful for each year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
