<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3471 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-USGYMNASTS-BOS &LR;      07-26 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USGYMNASTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAR RAISED IN US GYMNASTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The boot camps are done, the surgery rehabs
completed, the qualifying meets over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we are out in the open,'' said US women's gymnastics
coordinator Bela Karolyi. ``This is the time of the truth. There is
nothing to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   For the US gymnasts, the road to Sydney begins in the shadow of
the Gateway Arch this week with the national championships and
continues next month with the Olympic trials at the FleetCenter in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the math and the back-room politicking are done, six
men and six women will make the team. Except for four-time men's
champion Blaine Wilson, who's already been given a free pass to the
Games, nobody is certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea who's going to make the Olympic team,'' said
men's coach Peter Kormann, who'll be watching nearly a dozen
reasonable contenders in the prelims.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1984, when boycott holdovers like Bart Conner, Peter
Vidmar, Julianne McNamara, and Tracee Talavera turned up, has there
been such a crowd on both the men's and women's sides.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the Magnificent Seven (all but Kerri Strug and Amanda
Borden) who won gold in Atlanta are back to challenge their
successors, who are led by two-time national champion Kristen
Maloney, former titlist Vanessa Atler, and Elise Ray, the top
American finisher at last year's world meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``To try to make a team out of them, you can see what kind of an
attack I am having,'' said Karolyi. ``What a difficult decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Back when the top six finishers were locked in, there was no
decision to make. But the wild-card era, which allows countries to
use one-event specialists in the team competition, has changed
everything.
</P>
<P>
   So only the three women and four men (or top three plus Wilson)
with the best combined scores from nationals (40 percent) and
trials (60 percent) are guaranteed spots. The rest will be chosen
by committee as soon as the trials end Aug. 20.
</P>
<P>
   That's where resumes may carry some weight. Shannon Miller and
Dominique Dawes, both trying for their third teams at 23, have
virtually no chance to make the top three. But Miller won gold on
beam in Atlanta and Dawes the bronze on floor. If they can
recapture their old magic on even one event, they could bring an
apparatus medal home from Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, though, suffered a tibial stress fracture earlier this
month and may not even compete here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I want to do is go in unprepared and injure it
again,'' said Miller, who has won 16 Olympic and world medals.
</P>
<P>
   And Dawes, who's only been training since February, hasn't
competed in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Wilson, whom Kormann calls ``the Tiger Woods of
gymnastics,'' there's a mad scramble for places on the men's team,
which has managed to stay among the world's top six even while the
sport has been decimated at the collegiate level.
</P>
<P>
   Only Wilson, John Roethlisberger, and Chainey Umphrey return
from the 1996 squad. Roethlisberger, trying for his third Olympic
team at 31, blew out his knee two years ago. He'll make the team
one way or the other (if only as a lifetime achievement award).
</P>
<P>
   Jason Gatson, the once-rising star who made the 1997 world team
at 17, also blew out his knee at last year's nationals. If he's
back on form, he's on the squad.
</P>
<P>
   Who else? Sean Townsend, Stephen McCain, Yewki Tomita, and Jay
Thornton from last year's world team? Brett McClure and Guard
Young, who were 3-4 at last year's nationals?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more depth now,'' said Kormann. ``I wouldn't count
anyone out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOW THE TEAM WILL BE CHOSEN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The four men and three women with the highest combined scores
from this week's national championships (40 percent) and next
month's Olympic trials at the FleetCenter (60 percent) will earn
automatic places.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining two men and three women will be chosen by
committee at the end of the trials. Blaine Wilson, the four-time
men's champion, is guaranteed a berth based on past performance.
Gymnasts can petition for a spot based on injury or other unusual
circumstance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
