<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3472 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-MULLOY-BOS &LR;      07-26 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MULLOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKA'S MULLOY ON TARGET FOR OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SMITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Melissa Mulloy has got some serious range. She can hit the big
shot in a pressure situation. Her coach can count on her to score,
and she has a shooter's mentality _ keep firing, and never get
discouraged by a miss.
</P>
<P>
   Mulloy has all the tools to be a great shooter.
</P>
<P>
   That's why she was so highly recruited coming out of Masconomet
Regional High School in Boxford, Mass. three years ago. There were
stacks of letters and regular phone calls from big-time college
programs Kentucky, Xavier (Ohio), Marquette, and Wisconsin. But
when it came time to make her decision, the Middleton native
decided to take her skills to Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a wise choice. Mulloy has helped the
University of Alaska-Fairbanks win the last two NCAA championships,
and this year was selected to her fifth All-America team. In June
she earned the opportunity to shoot for an even bigger honor: a
gold medal at the 2000 Olympic Games in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her desire and her dedication are definitely what got her
here,'' said Randy Pitney, Mulloy's coach and the athletic director
at the University of Alaska. ``Frankly, this whole year I never had
a doubt in my mind that she (would) qualify for the Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulloy may sound like a hoop star. She's not. Mulloy doesn't
shoot basketballs from behind a 3-point line; she shoots rifles
from behind a foul line. She shoots for the University of Alaska's
women's rifle team, is a two-time All-American for the smallbore
(.22-caliber rifle), a three-timer for the air (pellet) rifle, and
one of 20 American shooters who will travel to Sydney and one of
three who will compete in the women's 50-meter three-position sport
rifle competition in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a really exciting experience,'' Mulloy said of
traveling to Sydney. ``There's a limit to how many people get to
go, and it's an opportunity that comes around only once every four
years. So it's pretty exciting I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of representing one's country may be exciting, but
emotions interfere in shooting competitions. Mulloy and the rest of
the roughly 15,000 people who shoot competitively in the United
States must remain calm when aiming at such miniscule targets.
Imagine trying to hit a bull's-eye smaller than a dime from 50
meters. That's the challenge that smallbore shooters face. Take a
pencil and make a mark on a piece of paper. Now imagine trying to
hit it with an air rifle from 10 meters. Not only does it take
remarkable aim to be a good shooter, but the rifle must be held
steady and trembling avoided.
</P>
<P>
   As in darts, shooters are awarded points for coming close to the
bull's-eye, but coming close all the time won't earn All-America
honors or a spot on the Olympic team. Mulloy, who placed 15th in
last week's International Shooting Sports Federation World Cup in
Atlanta, hits targets consistently because she has developed almost
complete control of her body. She can maintain a normal heart rate
despite the natural adrenaline rush that comes with a pressure
situation like shooting for the national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on the line and you get nervous, you feel your
heart beating fast,'' Mulloy said. ``You can see that movement
through the gunsight. You can see it bobbling all around. You have
to be able to control it. You have to be able to get your body to
relax quickly and get your heart rate down.''
</P>
<P>
   To develop such physical and mental discipline, it takes just
that _ discipline. Mulloy, a business major at Alaska, has a
demanding, five-to-six-day a week workout schedule that includes
aerobics, weightlifting, and visualization exercises. The
athleticism of shooters is tested by the degree of difficulty
involved in holding a 12 1/2-pound rifle for six hours, suppressing
nerves, and tuning out all distractions as they attempt to focus on
a microscopic target, all the while wearing a canvas or leather
jacket and pants designed to keep them as stiff as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney likens shooting to golf, except there's no timer in golf.
In the three-position sport rifle competition, Mulloy and the other
participants will have 20 minutes to fire 20 shots from the prone
position (lying flat on their stomachs), 30 minutes to fire 20
shots from one knee, and 40 minutes to fire 20 shots standing up.
</P>
<P>
   Shooters are allowed as many practice shots as they wish, but
the clock starts ticking as soon as they take their positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're making yourself concentrate,'' said Mulloy, this year's
NCAA air rifle champion who started shooting when she was 13 and as
a teenager spent many Friday nights in a shooting club rather than
a dance club. ``It's like trying to sit down and read a book in
front of the television.''
</P>
<P>
   Though shooting is more popular in Europe and Asia than it is in
the United States, Pitney doesn't think Mulloy will be overmatched
against marksmen who are used to hitting the bull's-eye in
televised competitions attended by thousands of fans. Mulloy's work
ethic and superb concentration skills, her coach said, are what
makes her such an accurate shooter. And those qualities will give
her a good shot at winning the gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a talent to focus on what she's doing,'' Pitney said.
``She doesn't get shook up about anything. She just puts on the
workclothes and does the job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the part that most people like,'' Mulloy said, ``is
that when you're down there on the line, it's just you, your gun,
and all your stuff. It's you that has to go down there and pull it
off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
