<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3473 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PYRAMID-SCHEME-BOS &LR;      07-26 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PYRAMID-SCHEME-BOS </SLUG>
  
 PYRAMID SCHEME COLLAPSES AMID ANGER
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   LEWISTON, Maine _ For a few weeks this spring, an electric
current of joy ran through sections of this mill city. Strangers
found they had something in common; debts miraculously cleared;
closely held dreams of trips or boats edged closer.
</P>
<P>
   What had changed in Lewiston was ``Changing Lives,'' described
by its organizers as a ``simple, natural activity'' that was
bringing participants thousands of dollars in cash with the morning
mail. Word spread quickly during the month of May, drawing hundreds
of Mainers into the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   To enter a ``Changing Lives'' group, a new recruit would pay
$2,000 to the person who had been in the group the longest. When
the senior members had collected $16,000, they left, allowing more
recent additions to replace them in the top spot _ and reap the
profits from the next group of recruits.
</P>
<P>
   But in early June Attorney General Andrew Ketterer put a stop to
``Changing Lives,'' declaring it an illegal pyramid scheme and
threatening participants with civil prosecution unless they
returned the money. Trading collapsed almost overnight. Within two
weeks, ``a lot'' of the money had been returned to its original
owners, Ketterer said.
</P>
<P>
   What's over for Ketterer, though, is not over in town.
</P>
<P>
   A month after ``Changing Lives'' broke down into a long list of
personal debts, some of the more intense participants described
communities laced with new grudges _ the kind of grudge that makes
people declare a boycott of their favorite restaurant, or look
suspiciously at a neighbor's new Harley, or consider moving to
Florida to get away from their wrecked friendships.
</P>
<P>
   Get Cheryl Breton talking about it and she starts fuming all
over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were your best friend and then all of a sudden they
were your worst enemy,'' said Breton, a Lewiston woman who owns
Custom Laminates . . . Plus. ``As it is today, I see these people
out, and it's like, `Don't even look at me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what Ketterer relied on in his attack on ``Changing
Lives'' was Maine's ``sense of community,'' he said. He believed
that once it became clear that trading had come to a halt, people
would decide it was more important to save their relationships than
to keep whatever money they had received. But the rounds of debt
collecting that began as soon as Ketterer cracked down were
anything but friendly, as petitioners trooped into their neighbors'
houses and offices demanding payment, and sometimes threatening
each other, according to participants.
</P>
<P>
   The wounds sustained when such a scam collapses, as they always
do, once the supply of new recruits has been exhausted, can fester
in a community for years, said Robert L. FitzPatrick, who studied
dozens of collapsed pyramid schemes for his 1997 book ``False
Profits: Seeking Financial and Spiritual Deliverance in Multi-Level
Marketing and Pyramid Schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't done by some clever confidence man,'' said
FitzPatrick, whose interest dates from his own involvement in a
failed scheme. ``If it was some sinister character who slipped into
town like the Pied Piper and lied to you, that would be one thing.
But it wasn't like that. It was your next-door neighbor. And you
recruited your brother-in-law. Now you've got to turn your finger
back on yourself, and who's going to do that?''
</P>
<P>
   The truth, FitzPatrick said, is that most people don't pay back
the money they've pocketed because they spend it immediately, and
most victims are too ashamed, or too hopeful, to demand their money
back and put a final end to the arrangement. Mike Gilbert, a
28-year-old restaurateur who brought the scheme from Lewiston to
South Paris shortly before its collapse, walked away with his own
lesson about human nature: People were far more likely to pay back
people they saw on a regular basis. While debts between people in
South Paris were cleared within a week, people from Lewiston, 40
miles away, refused to return cash to people they owed in South
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morally, they could care less,'' Gilbert said. ``They don't
have any problem taking money (from strangers).''
</P>
<P>
   Getting money back where it belongs after a speculative bubble
has burst is something like putting toothpaste back in the tube, as
the annals of mass behavior will attest. In his classic book on the
phenomenon, ``Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of
Crowds,'' Charles Mackay describes the stormy public meetings that
took place in 17th-century Holland after the crash of the market in
tulip bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   The most notorious recent pyramid scheme disaster was in
Albania, where pyramid schemes grew to involve some two-thirds of
the population. When they fell apart in 1996 and 1997, the public
wrath led to a violent uprising that brought down the government
and resulted in the deaths of some 1,500 people.
</P>
<P>
   In contemporary America, pyramid schemes are more likely to be
confined to small communities or what sociologists call affinity
groups _ networks with ties of trust _ and the permanent damage is
to relationships, said FitzPatrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complex ethical question. We're both implicated in a
scam. I got money and you lost your money, who's responsible? You
can see, talk like that is not so warm and fuzzy. The pyramid
scheme commercializes these relationships,'' he said. ``Most
relationships can't survive that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Lewiston and Auburn, participants who kept money are still
waiting to see if Ketterer carries through with his threats to
bring them to court under the Unfair Trade Practices Act.
</P>
<P>
   The most public fallout has involved police officers punished
for their involvement in ``Changing Lives.'' Two Lewiston officers
were suspended, one for 30 days and one for 60 days, after an
internal affairs investigation that involved 100 people, said a
police spokesman. Auburn police would not comment on the number of
officers punished, but said the officers were appealing the
decision. Breton _ a tanned woman with gold necklaces and bangles _
said the police department has been split over the ``Changing
Lives'' investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they run into a situation where there's someone holding a
gun to their heads, who's going to back them up? It's that bad,''
said Breton, who scrambled to pay a parade of creditors their
$2,000, but when money ran short, paid some $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   And 25-year-old Laurie Appleton still blames authorities for
putting a halt to one of the the best things ever to happen here _
a few weeks when ``people had these feel-good vibes'' and found
common ground with people from different income levels. She has
refused to return the $3,000 she netted _ ``Who's going to make
me?'' _ and assumes that anyone who claims to have returned the
money is lying.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you gave back 40 grand, where's the rest of it? Because you
made more than 40 grand,'' she said. With investigators from the
attorney general's office urging participants to name names, that
kind of distrust is everywhere, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are disliking their neighbors, there are people that
are no longer friends,'' she said. ``If someone happened to be seen
driving a new Harley, that money was from `Changing Lives,' for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Gilbert, for one, has become almost evangelical about the
evils of easy money. In the hectic weeks around Ketterer's
deadline, he raised between $120,000 and $130,000 to return to
people he had encouraged to invest in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of my employees that were involved, even our
salesmen for our food,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ketterer said he still intends to bring ``Changing Lives''
operators to court _ a move unprecedented in his six years in
office, although he takes action on three or four pyramid schemes
every year.
</P>
<P>
   In general, it is hard to call Lewiston-Auburn a chastened
community. A little more than a month after ``Changing Lives'' fell
apart, an area restaurant was still dotted with pale purple fliers
for Bigsmart.com, a Las Vegas-based business that Ketterer ordered
shut down this spring after determining it, too, was an illegal
pyramid scheme. Locals are buzzing about another scheme similar to
``Changing Lives,'' in which a $1,000 pay-in is transferred to an
offshore bank.
</P>
<P>
   One local man spent the days before the attorney general's
deadline scrambling to get receipts for the $11,000 he had received
from ``Changing Lives.'' Burned by that experience, he's learned
his lesson _ sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way: I'd never do it again,'' he said. ``Or if I
did, I'd do it so fast it would make your head spin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
