<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN'S OPTIMISM KEEPS INVESTORS HAPPY _ FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In testimony before Congress, delivered Tuesday and last week,
Alan Greenspan said everything was hunky-dory. Over the next few
days investors will get a chance to see if the Fed chairman's
optimism is justified.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, of course, didn't use the term hunky-dory. It isn't
technical enough. But the thrust of his testimony was about as
upbeat as anyone could have expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were three key questions everyone wanted him to
answer,'' said Mark Zandi, chief economist at RFA Dismal Sciences,
a Pennsylvania forecasting firm. Is the economy slowing down? Is
the slowdown for real? And finally, if the economy does slow down,
does the jobless rate have to rise beyond its current 4 percent
level to keep inflation in check?
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's answers _ yes, yes and no _ were just the ones
investors wanted to hear. Financial markets know that the economy
has to slow down from the torrid pace it maintained much of last
year and in the first quarter of this year. Continued strong growth
in the 5 to 6 percent range would have meant more inflation and
more Fed rates hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan noted that consumer spending has tailed off in recent
months, a development he attributed to higher interest rates, a
flat stock market, and higher oil prices. He said it was too early
to know if the slowdown would persist, but he suggested that it
might.
</P>
<P>
   In the question and answer session that followed, Greenspan made
perhaps his most significant statement. ``Do you believe you can
maintain price stability with unemployment at 4 percent?'' asked
Senator Connie Mack, a Florida Republican. According to the Wall
Street Journal, Greenspan said, ``I suspect yes,'' but added ``the
evidence is not yet of sufficient persuasiveness to convince
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   This may sound boring, but trust us, it isn't. In a speech in
Boston last month, Fed governor Laurence Meyer argued that the
jobless rate had to rise to the 5 percent range to assure stable
prices. Getting to that 5 percent level would require more rate
hikes, a major economic slowdown, and possibly a big stock market
correction.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say Greenspan's answer was much more market friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Ayers listened to Greenspan's testimony and came away
encouraged. ``He seemed to be saying that if the Fed is not
finished raising interest rates, they are close to being
finished,'' said Ayers, chief economist at FleetBoston Financial.
</P>
<P>
   In economics, theory quickly gets translated into practice. In
this case, the first tests will come this week.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the government releases the Employment Cost Index, a
measurement of wage and benefit gains in the second quarter. If the
strong economy is generating inflationary pressures, this will be
the first place to spot it. In April, the index showed big gains in
both wages and benefits, especially the cost of health insurance.
The news spooked the stock market and prompted the Fed to raise
interest rates in May.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the government will issue its first report on growth in
the second quarter. In the first quarter growth came in at a 5.4
percent pace. Forecasters expect something more like 3.5 percent to
4 percent this time around. A number in that range would be good
news for the stock market and Greenspan. A number considerably
higher than 4 percent would likely be greeted with alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get the slowdown we are looking for then the Fed can sit
on its hands for a while,'' said David Wyss, chief economist at
Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced the perfect soft landing is underway.
Some analysts believe the economy is just taking a breather before
revving up for another round of high-powered growth. They point out
that consumers are still feeling chipper _ consumer confidence rose
in June _ and people still have plenty of money to spend.
</P>
<P>
   In their weekly report on the US economy, a team of economists
at Goldman Sachs said there is more life left in the economy than
Greenspan suggests. ``We continue to think that rates will rise by
another 100 basis points in the next year,'' the Goldman economists
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Who is right? It's impossible to know. But if you were a betting
person, you'd put your money on Greenspan. Up until now, his
instincts about the economy have been on target. His faith in
technology, his belief that productivity is rising, and his
conviction that inflation is less of a problem than it has been in
the past have been borne out by the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   So don't worry and be happy _ at least until the next round of
statistics is released.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
