<HEADLINE>
JUMBO CDS COULD ENHANCE INVESTING INCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband has just passed away and I am wondering how to
best invest my money. I had a lucrative career, but left it to care
for him and now I need to be home to supervise the teenagers. I
will take a small job in September just to keep busy. I need to
live off some of the interest.
</P>
<P>
   A.P., Braintree, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Please accept my condolences on your husband's death.
</P>
<P>
   There are several routes that you could take _ one of which is
simply to do nothing. If you left the current balance in the money
market fund and withdrew $4,000 a month, until you reached age 59
1/2 and then can draw upon the IRA without penalty, you would still
have $143,551, presuming you realized average returns of 5 percent
from the Fidelity Cash Reserves account.
</P>
<P>
   But you could do much better by going to a series of CDs,
putting $100,000 each in a group of five-year jumbo CDs at
different institutions, where you could expect to get returns as
high as 7.91 percent. (That is the nation's highest rate for
five-year jumbos entering this week, offered by Capital One FSB of
Virginia, 800-564-7426.) If you made withdrawals of $4,000 a month
from these accounts, you would have $342,460 remaining at age 59
1/2. (However, those numbers won't be precise, because you will
have to settle for slightly lower rates for a few of the $100,000
accounts, and because you will need to renew the CDs at five-year
intervals _ and there is no predicting where interest rates will be
then.)
</P>
<P>
   A better tack you might take would be to assume that you might
realize $200 a week from your part-time work, so that you wouldn't
need to take withdrawals of the full $4,000 a month. If your
withdrawals were $3,296 a month and you realized that 7.91 percent
return, you would see no erosion of principal from your taxable
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that you would not have to worry too much if you make
a slight, or even significant, dent in the balance in your taxable
accounts by the time you reach age 59 1/2 is that if your IRAs are
properly invested _ that's to say if they are dominantly in stocks
or stock funds _ you should be comfortable in assuming a 10 percent
average annual total return from the IRA _ an assumption that would
take the balance to $1,572,010 by the time you reach age 59 1/2 and
can begin drawing upon them.
</P>
<P>
   Any way you fry it, you should be quite comfortable with the
resources at hand, which are sufficient to allow you a risk-free
portfolio for income and to leave the IRA accounts in growth
vehicles to provide for your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We hope to retire at age 63 and we currently contribute
$12,000 a year to our 401(k) accounts. What are our chances of
achieving this goal?
</P>
<P>
   R.H., Sharon, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. While of course you could do it, you might be cutting it
fairly close for future comfort. Even though you should have
something in the neighborhood of $1,750,000 by the time you reach
age 63, you would need to devote about 80 percent of it to
supplying an income stream.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the ugly numbers. I used an assumption of 9 percent
average portfolio growth to come up with a projected pool of
$1,756,194 in four years, including your $1,000 monthly
contributions. If inflation averages 3.5 percent in the next four
years you will need $103,277 at that point to support a current
$90,000 lifestyle, effectively eating up the lion's share of your
pension and Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course you might say that the numbers do work _ $1.4
million to supply the income stream and $356,194 to deal with
future inflation. That's true, but with the life expectancy of
Americans ever increasing, I would like to see more buffer.
Consider that if you delayed retirement until age 64, your
projected accumulation would be $1,933,245, and your pension would
probably be a bit higher as well. The difference between having a
$500,000-plus buffer against inflation and one of a little more
than $350,000 should be worth the extra year or toil.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative, of course, would be to step up your savings
during the next four years. Your current savings rate represents a
savings rate of a little more than 8.5 percent of your earnings,
which is hardly an aggressive level for people approaching
retirement. I like the balance of your portfolio, and if you want
to strive for that age-63 retirement date, my advice would be to
save more aggressively and to retain your nicely balanced portfolio
rather than to stretch for higher portfolio returns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
