<HEADER>
A3479 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CANADA-OIL-ART-BOS &LR;      07-26 1559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-OIL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 ATLANTIC CANADA STARTS TO BOOM FROM OIL, GAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A map is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland _ The voices clamoring for another pint
in the pubs off Duckworth Street carried the drawl of Texas, the
burr of Scotland, the lilt of Norway, as well as the salty brogue
of Atlantic Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The voices belonged to mudmen, roughnecks, geologists,
seismologists, drillers, and all the other swaggering toilers in
the gypsy trade of international oil, an industry starting to
transform the economic face of a region better known for ruined
codfish grounds, rusting shipyards, and hard luck.
</P>
<P>
   A petroleum boom is building off Newfoundland and Nova Scotia.
And many believe that vast reserves hidden beneath the cold
Atlantic waters hold not only a promise of prosperity for Canada's
poorest provinces but a big part of New England's energy future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deposits appear huge, and the gas and oil flows are
fantastic,'' said Brian Lee Crowley, head of the Atlantic Institute
for Market Studies, a Halifax-based economic think tank. ``But the
real magic ingredient is proximity to Boston and that huge, hungry
New England market.''
</P>
<P>
   Two offshore operations are in spectacular production _ the
just-completed Sable Offshore Energy project, with natural gas
flowing from six wells on the Scotian Shelf, and the three-year-old
Hibernia oil operation, rising from the North Atlantic's
treacherous ``Iceberg Alley,'' 195 miles southeast of
Newfoundland's Cape Spear.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the natural gas from the Sable fields will feed
New England's increasing appetite for the clean-burning fuel, while
much of the oil production from Newfoundland's offshore rigs will
go to US markets, primarily in the Northeast. Crude oil can be
shipped anywhere, but natural gas needs pipelines, so for decades
to come Boston will enjoy first crack at Sable's bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Newfoundland's next enormous offshore oil project,
the Terra Nova fields, 220 miles southeast of St. John's, is
nearing completion. And in Nova Scotia, scores of companies are
scouring the geological depths in an intensive search for lodes of
natural gas and oil.
</P>
<P>
   At least 15 offshore test wells are expected to be drilled in
the ocean waters off Nova Scotia in coming months, at a cost
approaching $1 billion. And the province has granted an
unprecedented 43 oil exploration licenses, while auctioning search
rights for tens of thousands of square miles of undersea territory
to oil and gas companies.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the industry is drawing fire from environmentalists
and some fishermen's groups, which contend that the exploration and
development of new fields is proceeding too quickly, putting a vast
marine ecology at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The protests have not ignited much public opposition to the
projects, and provincial government leaders note that oil companies
are operating under some of the most stringent environmental
regulations in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the big boys are crowding into Halifax and St.
John's to set up full-time corporate shop _ Mobil, Shell, Marathon,
PanCanadian, Husky, Irving, to name a few. And more players from
Houston, Calgary, London, and Amsterdam are swarming into the
historic seaports; no one wants to miss out on this party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlantic Canada is North America's next big energy frontier,''
said Debora Walsh, East Coast manager for the Canadian Association
of Petroleum Producers. ``The planets have come into alignment for
our oil and gas.''
</P>
<P>
   New England started reaping a share of the maritime energy
bonanza in January, as the first natural gas from the Sable
Offshore Energy fields started surging down the 653-mile-long
Maritimes &AMP; Northeast Pipeline through Nova Scotia, New Brunswick,
Maine, and New Hampshire before connecting to the United States gas
grid in Dracut, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Sable rigs rise from the ocean about 140 miles east of
Halifax. The $3.1 billion project takes its name from nearby Sable
Island, notorious as the ``Graveyard of the Atlantic'' because of
the hundreds of ships that have foundered on its shores and shoals
over the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   After seven months in full-tilt operation, the undersea wells
feeding into Sable's hulking Thebaud, Venture, and North Triumph
platforms are producing 400 million cubic feet of natural gas per
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's enough gas to meet the energy needs of a city of 2.5
million people,'' said Kimberley Gildner, a spokeswoman for Sable
Offshore Energy Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Geological Survey of Canada estimates that seabeds off
Newfoundland and Nova Scotia hold more undiscovered oil and gas
than even Alberta's famed ``oilpatch,'' for decades the only
world-class fount of Canadian petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a very few years, a significant percentage of Canada's oil
and gas is going to be coming out of the east coast,'' said James
B. Wooder, executive director of the Halifax-based Atlantic Canada
Petroleum Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is very much in its infancy here. There are still
fewer than 200 wells, most of them test wells, on the Scotian
Shelf,'' he said. ``That compares to more than 6,000 in the Gulf of
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scotian Shelf is the continental protrusion stretching off
the coast of the province. By some estimates, it may contain 18
trillion feet of natural gas in porous rock formations deep beneath
the ocean floor.
</P>
<P>
   The other focus of Atlantic Canada's great search is
Newfoundland's Grand Banks, fairly shallow but highly dangerous
fishing grounds, which, according to the Canada-Newfoundland
Offshore Petroleum Board, contain at least 2.1 billion barrels of
crude oil and 9.3 trillion cubic feet of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   First off the mark to exploit the trove was a consortium of
companies _ Mobil, Chevron, Petro-Canada, among others _ that built
the monstrous 735-foot Hibernia platform towering from the floor of
the Jeanne d'Arc basin, on the storm-ripped northeastern corner of
the Grand Banks.
</P>
<P>
   There were hoots, jeers, and environmental howls for the five
years it took to complete the $4.2 billion Hibernia project,
derided by many as a government-driven ``make-work'' boondoggle
meant to steal attention from the collapse of the province's cod
fishing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Then Hibernia came a gusher, surpassing all production
forecasts. The project's five wells are now pumping out 150,000
barrels of oil per day, a rate that will increase to 180,000
barrels later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Until the last decade, the quest for oil and gas off eastern
Canada was marked mostly by bad luck and false starts. The
country's first offshore well, Hillsborough No. 1, was drilled in a
quiet bay of Prince Edward Island in 1943 _ and came up dry.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1960s through the late 1980s, dozens of test wells were
sunk off Nova Scotia, with tantalizing results. Geologists were
convinced that mammoth deposits of gas and oil were concealed off
the eastern shores, but the quest for offshore petroleum is
extraordinarily expensive and the dangers are daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``On dry land, an exploratory well might cost $300,000.
Offshore, you're talking $30 million a pop, not exactly pocket
change even for the biggest of the big companies,'' Wooder said.
``And working hundreds of miles out on the ocean is a rather
riskier proposition than drilling a hole in some Alberta farmer's
field.''
</P>
<P>
   But the world's ever-growing thirst for oil and gas _ and rising
oil company profits _ has a way of making projects once written off
as insanely longshot gambles suddenly seem like prudent
investments.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is that the Shell exploration vessel MV Western
Monarch is conducting elaborate ``3D'' seismological surveys over
1,713 square miles of ocean on the far eastern edge of the Scotian
Shelf, firing bursts of energy whose echoes paint a detailed
picture of geological formations miles under the sea bed.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is, too, that the din of machinery reverberates over
Bull Arm, Newfoundland, a dockyard where 1,300 workers are
attaching topsides to the immense floating production, storage, and
offloading vessel that will serve the offshore wells of the Terra
Nova project. The project is still under construction but scheduled
to come into production next March.
</P>
<P>
   Husky Oil Ltd. soon will decide whether to forge ahead with the
White Rose field on the Grand Banks, estimated to contain even more
natural gas than the Sable find. Mobil and Gulf are beginning
probes of a potentially oil-rich corridor off the French possession
of St. Pierre and Miquelon, islands lying just south of
Newfoundland. And PanCanadian Petroleum has acquired 6,177 square
miles of undersea territory in 15 ``exploration blocks'' that it
plans to spend $48 million probing in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Nova Scotia and Newfoundland are fast becoming
important centers for oil technology and research; the two
provinces also boast the fastest-growing economies in Canada,
thanks mainly to the budding energy boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 2004, Newfoundland will be producing more than one-third of
Canada's light crude oil,'' Premier Brian Tobin said. ``That's a
magnificent shift from a few years ago, when it was zero percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
