<HEADER>
A3513 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-PORTLAND-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     07-26 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PORTLAND-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 PORTLAND, Maine: ... elite ranks.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fresh Samantha juices are the basis of the drinks at Fresh
Samantha Juice Bar. For the most part, they are pure juice and
fruit, not diluted with sherbet and yogurt and lots of ice. These
are smoothies to swoon over, particularly Passionate C, which
contains prickly pear juice, passion fruit, pineapple, banana, and
extra vitamin C. Owner Doug Levin loves coconut, so naturally
there's a coconut cream drink, which also includes pineapple and
orange juice, lime, and bananas. ``It's a tropical vacation,'' says
Levin.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the company's experiments begin here, and like most
other juice bars aiming for a health-conscious audience, this one
offers all kinds of add-ins like St. John's wort, ginseng,
echinacea, and wheat grass. Some of the best items are the
plainest, because the bottled juices are so good to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   This flagship shop (there's only one, with no more expected), a
short walk from Commercial Street, is decorated with the same
curly-haired happy little girl smacking her lips who appears on all
bottles of the company's juices.
</P>
<P>
   There is something of the elated child in Levin, too, who seems
genuinely mystified that he has the good fortune to own a
successful company. ``I'm not a good person with responsibility,''
he says. He is full of ideas, especially the good one he had when
he named his company after his daughter, Samantha, and when his
wife, Abby Carter, a children's book illustrator, began drawing a
cheerful cartoon version of her. Levin and Carter, both 39, founded
the company in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh Samantha juices have taken off up and down the East Coast,
with the company acting as its own distributor. All the juices are
highly perishable, and as a result, says Levin, ``this is a very
hard business to make money in. The only way to make this thing
work is to have volume.''
</P>
<P>
   So last February, Levin merged with the California-based Odwalla
company, the West Coast version of Samantha and one of the national
leaders in the business. Levin and Carter received about $25
million in stock; she will continue to do the illustrations, and he
becomes president of the new company. He's not sure what that
means. ``I'm becoming the queen of England,'' he muses.
</P>
<P>
   The Fresh Samantha juice factory will remain in Saco, where the
juices are made, and the label will stay the same. Levin and
Carter, along with Samantha, now 8, and Carter, 5, are moving to
San Francisco next month.
</P>
<P>
   The couple met as students at Wesleyan College. ``She took me
into a life of adulthood,'' Levin says. Before Maine, they lived in
Manhattan, where she was an illustrator at Gem Studios and he was
an art director for Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi. ``I worked on British
Airways, Con Ed, the Spanish tourism board, and a lot of cereals,''
he says, then adds, ``I can't even draw.'' He began his career as a
secretary at Doyle Dane &AMP; Bernbach.
</P>
<P>
   The couple moved to Maine to escape the frenzy of their New York
lives. Carter told Levin that she wouldn't move unless he had a
job. So he went to work for her parents in a newly founded sprout
business they ran from their basement. ``I drove a beat-up Chevy
truck and listened to the radio,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha was 2 when Levin, his in-laws, and his brother-in-law,
Michael Carter, a marine engineer, bought a local juice company and
started making carrot juice. Carter drew the cartoons of the little
girl, and pretty soon everyone who noticed the juice bought it. By
the end of last year, when Forbes magazine ranked it number 9 in a
list of ``100 Things Worth Every Penny'' (along with Bose radios, a
KitchenAid mixer, Parma ham, and Petrossian caviar), the company
had sales of $32 million.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who claims he wasn't destined to succeed.
Levin was raised in Brussels because his father got into a big
argument with his grandfather (Levin's father thought of the move
as reversed immigration).
</P>
<P>
   Both of his parents owned restaurants in Brussels, and as a boy
he washed dishes. Scrubbing pots, he says, ``I vowed I wouldn't get
into the food business.'' He didn't do well in the famously tough
French education system, so he was sent to Phillips Exeter Academy.
``My parents picked it because it was a snobby school,'' he says.
``Grim teachers, grim climate.''
</P>
<P>
   At Wesleyan, he hung out with a bunch of guys he describes as
``Peter Pan.'' He has barely squeaked out of that category. Now
that he's moving to San Francisco, he says, he thinks he should do
something about his ``worn-out, stressed-out, disheveled'' look,
and his ``crumbled shirt.'' In some ways, he likes the idea of
heading west. Ever since his childhood as an American abroad, out
of synch with the local culture, ``I've been obsessed with finding
the place,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He'll fly back and forth between coasts, returning to Saco to
check in at the juice factory. ``That's OK,'' he says. ``I like
being in motion.''
</P>
<P>
   His original mission to find peace failed. ``I went back to the
same stressful life I had in New York,'' he says, ``like a
boomerang.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Perry's Sidewalk Cafe Almost Famous Since 1994 is located at the
corner of Commercial and Moulton streets. Telephone 207-775-6747.
Perry Mogul operates his stand from 11 a.m. to 3 p.m. daily, unless
it's raining.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Standard Baking Co. is located at 75 Commercial St. Telephone
207-773-2112. Open Mon.-Fri. 7 a.m.-7 p.m.; Sat.-Sun. 7 a.m.-5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fresh Samantha Juice Bar is located at 15 Temple St. Telephone
207-828-5636. Open Mon.-Sat. 6:30 a.m.-5 p.m.; Sun. 6.30 a.m.-4
p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
