<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURLEY-BURLY; SHIPS TO SHORE; ROCK OF AGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most successful magazine startup of the '90s was In Style.
Spun off from People, In Style is part fashion book, part shelter
book, and all soft-focus celebrity celebration: just the place to
get up close and innocuous with your favorite personalities.
</P>
<P>
   The most talked-about magazine startup of the '90s was Talk,
Tina Brown's attempt to show that (having remade The Tatler, Vanity
Fair, and The New Yorker) she could start a magazine from scratch _
and have an equity stake, to boot. Twelve months into its
existence, Talk is . . . well, it's hard to say, exactly, other
than that it certainly hasn't been the buzz-generating, ad-heavy
smash trumpeted by all the launch hype.
</P>
<P>
   As chance (and lead times) would have it, In Style and Talk have
the same August cover: actress-model Elizabeth Hurley, fresh from
her breakup with actor Hugh Grant. The In Style Hurley looks dewy
and fresh, as if she'd stepped out of an Estee Lauder ad (turn the
page, and there she is in an Estee Lauder ad). The look is in
keeping with In Style's tone of unrelenting niceness. How nice? A
few years ago it showed Sharon Stone _ Sharon Stone! _ baking
cookies. It's a world so nice the reader could easily imagine
herself _ and make no mistake, it's female readers In Style targets
_ fitting right in and being part of the scene. The one problem
with In Style, from a circulation point of view, is that no dentist
in his or her right mind would ever put it in a waiting room.
Everyone in it is always smiling, and those teeth, those teeth,
they're all so perfect.
</P>
<P>
   The Talk Hurley looks like Mrs. Hyde to In Style's Dr. Jekyll.
In fact, she'd make you want to hide, she looks that louche and
gamy. Forget Estee Lauder. This woman's auditioning for the lead in
a low-budget version of ``The Jackie Collins Story.'' Inside,
there's a double-truck photo of a bikini'd Hurley sticking her
tongue out at a boa constrictor that rests (if that is the correct
verb) between her legs. Ho, ho, the reader thinks, we're in for the
good stuff now. ``Kids, go clean your room and leave me alone for
half an hour.'' But, no, Talk's Hurley _ or ``Elizabeth,'' as Mimi
Swartz delights in referring to her throughout _ is just as
girl-next-door-unobjectionable and (dare one say it?) as nice as In
Style's Hurley.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is Talk wants to have it both ways: to titillate
the reader while flattering the celebrity. During the palmy days
before Talk debuted, Tina Brown kept talking about her vision of it
as ``a cultural search engine.'' Here, too, one sees the wish to
have it both ways. ``Cultural search engine'' just sounds so
dynamic and up-to-the-minute, doesn't it, as if Brown's been
secretly editing Wired or something under an assumed name. Yet the
August Talk relies on that hoariest of editorial standbys, the book
excerpt _ not just one, but three (from Wayne Barrett's Rudy
Giuliani bio, Joe Eszterhas's ``American Rhapsody,'' and the
memoirs of interior decorator Sister Parish), and guess what: Two
of the books are already in stores, and the other's about to be.
Perhaps one editor's cultural search engine is another's
Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   A reader may or may not think much of what In Style does, but
what it does it does very well indeed. More to the point, it knows
exactly what it wants to do. The same cannot be said for Talk.
Might that have something to do with the fact that the most
talked-about startup of the '90s and the most successful fail to be
one and same publication?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From rehashings of Liz Hurley's love life to examining the
annual scavenging of more than 300 freighters and tankers on a
beach in southern India by desperately poor workers: It's hard to
imagine anything more different _ in life or print. It's also hard
to imagine anything more different in quality. William
Langewiesche's ``The Shipbreakers,'' in the August Atlantic
Monthly, is absolutely extraordinary journalism. Over the past
decade, India, Pakistan, and Bangladesh have come to dominate the
scrapping of obsolete ships. Langewiesche describes how. He also
describes, in mesmerizing detail, how a ship of many thousands of
tons will be beached, carved up, and sold for scrap. Nor does he
neglect to convey how hard, dangerous, and ill-paid the work is.
</P>
<P>
   This is about as good as reporting gets, but Langewiesche takes
it beyond the realm of facts to that of ideas, for there are moral
and political ramifications here that extend far beyond the Indian
littoral. Greenpeace has trained its sights on Alang (the location
Langewiesche writes about and, incidentally, the subject of a photo
essay in the August Wired) as a prime example of the First World
dumping its environmental sins on the Third World (the vessels
abound in hazardous wastes and other pollutants). Those same ships,
however, provide a livelihood to tens of thousands of Indians who
see Greenpeace, rather than the ships, as the unwelcome visitors
from the West. Scanting the position of neither side, Langewiesche
sets all this out in an exacting, unhurried prose. It's only July,
and who knows what weird misfires happen in the synapses of
National Magazine Award judges, but if ``The Shipbreakers'' isn't a
finalist next year, there's something wrong in this business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Runovers: Lori Robertson's ``Golden Oldies,'' in American
Journalism Review (July/August)' ponders aging rock reviewers
writing for newspapers. For ourselves, we propose as a cut-off the
birthdate of The New York Times' peerless Jon Pareles. But he's 46,
which almost makes him Britney Spears's kid brother compared to
81-year-old Jane Scott, of the Cleveland Plain Dealer. Talkin'
'bout whose generation?. . . Entertainment Weekly continues its
ongoing 10th anniversary celebration with a photo issue (July 28).
The images mirror the impact of EW itself: expert, weightless,
oddly impersonal. . . . Artnews (Summer) lists ``The World's Top
200 Collectors'' _ only, alas, alphabetically. Inquiring minds
would want to know how, say, David Bowie (``Modern art, especially
German Expressionism; contemporary art, especially British'')
stacks up against Melinda and Bill Gates (``19th-century American,
especially American Impressionism''). More pertinent, in this
season of Van Gogh a-go-go at the Museum of Fine Arts, is Timothy
W. Ryback's ``The So-Called Van Goghs,'' which relates the
questionable authenticity of a distressingly large number of the
artist's paintings. In passing, Ryback notes that a leading Italian
expert on the painter bankrolls his work with what he won on a game
show as a contestant answering questions about Van Gogh. Forget
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' Is the next big thing on
television going to be ``Live with Regis and Sister Wendy''?
</P>
</TEXT>
