<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   PERGOLAS _ When Michele Burns wants to savor her garden, she
simply looks up. In spring, wisteria drips its heady scent over her
outdoor dinner table and not long after, pink roses take center
stage. In summer, lush foliage forms a cool canopy for sundown
suppers. Structures like Burns' arbor are cropping up in back yards
everywhere as homeowners spend more time outdoors. Arbors and
pergolas lend not only shady retreats for relaxing and entertaining
but also the kind of structure, focal points and transitonal areas
that yards and gardens so often need. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ Within seconds of one another, I heard two
sounds that rose above the roll of thunder and splatter of rain:
Crrrraaaack! WHUUUMP! In the kitchen of our 110-year-old house, I
felt a thud, but it did not begin to prepare me for what lay in
front of the house. The big old oak next door, a tree that probably
predates the Civil War, had lost half of itself; brushing the top
of our house, crashing into the wrought-iron fence, spreading
across the driveway, reaching even the house beyond ours. Minutes
after the fall, a sweet fragrance wafted, through the house. But,
it was more than newly-broken wood; it evoked the sensory pleasure
of fresh-sliced watermelon, a soothing, life-affirming counterpoint
to the death and decay so evident in the tree that, like so many
oaks in Atlanta, has been dying inwardly for years and whose
falling apart was hastened by debilitating drought and yet another
violent blowdown. (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CLOSET-DOORS _ Few things make a bedroom seem shabbier than a
beat-up sliding closet door that's hanging crooked or that won't
open and close smoothly. A reasonably handy person can correct most
minor closet door problems fairly easily. And if the door is too
far gone or too ugly to save, replacing a closet door is also a
simple project. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 26.
</P>
