<HEADER>
A3518 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-PORTLAND-2TAKES-     07-26 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PORTLAND-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 NEED A GOOD HOT DOG? GET YE TO PORTLAND 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ When the sun is shining one day, and you're
burning to play hooky, go to Maine, eat your way through the Old
Port, and then walk it off on the Harbor Trail, which curves along
the ocean. Certainly one reason this city appeals is its proximity
to the water. Our port isn't as small, or as lively, but the
buildings are similar: 19th-century brick and granite warehouses
designed to serve a once-bustling seaport. The waterfront along
Casco Bay still works as a port, though fewer vessels come in. The
old buildings have been renovated, the cobblestones are still in
place, and among the usual tourist shops are some culinary treats.
Among them is a chatty hot dog vendor who has manned his corner for
six years, a juice bar that showcases one of southern Maine's hot
new companies, and a bakery with European-style loaves. To get the
full flavor of the Maine coastline, stop at a lobster shack on the
way home. We found one way off the beaten path on Chauncey Creek,
near Kittery Point. By the time you stumble into bed, you'll feel
as if you've been gone for days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perry Mogul can (and will) bend your ear. Fast-talking, funny,
incurably cheerful, and startlingly observant, Mogul operates
Perry's Sidewalk Cafe Almost Famous Since 1994, a mobile hot dog
stand. Once you've met him, you won't easily forget him. One day
when I was ducking out of the rain outside the Whip and Spoon (161
Commercial St.), which is on the same block, Mogul handed me his
umbrella so I wouldn't get wet. I had never seen him before passing
by earlier that day.
</P>
<P>
   Mogul, 37, turns hot dogs on his grill and passes the time of
day with a little commentary. You want to take a nice walk along
the harbor? Perry will map it out for you. You're wondering if it's
going to shower? Perry has a direct pipeline to the weather gods.
He pulls everything he uses out of an old Saab that has nearly
300,000 miles but won't give up. ``Oh, I'll be good,'' he says the
car tells him. ``Let's go another year.''
</P>
<P>
   The specialty here, of course, is hot dogs, and Mogul's are
terrific. He uses Best's Kosher brand, 1/4-pound hot dogs from
Chicago not well known in New England. Mogul smothers them with
grilled onions or hot sauerkraut. A dog and some real iced tea go
for $5. He also makes a grilled 6-ounce salmon sandwich with
horseradish sauce ($8, also with tea) and a hot potato knish with
grilled onions ($2).
</P>
<P>
   Everyone along Commercial Street knows Mogul, who operates his
kiosk seven days from 11 a.m. to 3 p.m. The hours are loose. If he
has hot dogs left and someone wants one, he fires up the grill.
``Hungry stomachs,'' he says, ``never forget being turned away and
sent somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Mogul doesn't open when it's raining, but because his livelihood
depends upon dry days, he watches the skies carefully. ``I've
become a meteorologist by feel,'' he says. ``I'm like a fireman _
ready to go down that pole.'' If it's rainy at dawn but clears up,
and he can get to Commercial Street by 10 a.m., he dashes out to
catch the lunch crowd.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago on a busy Saturday, his girlfriend called from
Brunswick, which is north, to tell him a northeaster was headed
south. Portland was sunny, without a cloud in the sky. ``I put on
my L. L. Bean Gore-Tex raincoat and told everyone, `Big storm's
coming.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He got lots of strange looks. ``Then I saw a black cloud, and I
thought, `Oh my God!' I took my condiments. I threw things into the
car. We got a severe wind and five seconds later the storm. In two
minutes there was flash flooding.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, to amuse himself and his customers, Mogul started using
a digital camera and now snaps pictures of them standing beside
him, then e-mails the photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Mogul will be operating as usual during Opsail 2000, which
features the Coast Guard's Tall Ships sailing into Portland harbor
July 28 to 30. Initially, he needed an expensive permit to bring
his stand to the corner that weekend. After contacting several city
officials to protest, he was given special consideration. After
all, he isn't coming out just to make a buck off the tourists. He's
always at his spot on Commercial Street. ``I'm the minister of
tourism,'' says Mogul.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We never got around to putting up a sign,'' says Alison Pray,
who is baking in an old warehouse, once a billiard hall, beneath
Fore Street restaurant. So you have to look hard for Standard
Baking Co. and walk through a parking lot to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Filled with salvaged pieces _ including a 7-foot marble counter
that was once in the local courthouse _ the bakery is stylish in an
understated way, with handmade French bread baskets holding
baguettes and rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Pray and her partner, Matt James, have been in this location for
nine months, making artisanal French and Italian breads, dinner
rolls, chubby half-baguettes, raisin and pecan rolls, brioche, and
a number of pastries. One of their outstanding breads, the country
boule, is made with an Italian technique. ``It has a French name
and an Italian process,'' says Pray, and the result is a flavorful
bread in which you can actually taste the wheat, with a moist crumb
and beautiful crust.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer the couple went to Paris and afterward began making
canneles (French for ``fluted''), rich little pastries that
originated in Bordeaux and are the rage in Parisian bakeries now.
They also make small but high gingerbread cakes with a lemon glaze,
Belgian chocolate brownies baked in shallow fluted paper cups, and
a range of croissants, including the classic crescent shape,
chocolate-filled croissants, and remarkable ``morning buns'' shaped
from a milky croissant-style dough that is rolled into sticky,
caramelized snails.
</P>
<P>
   Pray and James have been in business for five years. They used
to be down the road, next door to Street and Co. restaurant, owned
by former Brookline resident Dana Street. Street is a partner in
this venture, and he also co-owns Fore Street with Sam Hayward.
</P>
<P>
   All the Street-related establishments serve Standard bread, and
the baking couple also delivers to three dozen other local
addresses. This is a pleasing place, airy and so big that a rack of
cooling breads is dwarfed in the space. The couple, who began
baking in Brookline's Clear Flour Bakery, celebrated their fifth
anniversary in business recently. Clear Flour owner Abe Faber came
and did pirouettes in the baking area. ``You can dance here,'' he
told Pray and James. She says, ``We've never had this much space.''
</P>
<P>
   While they work to perfect their Old World breads, using
European techniques that require longer rising times, Pray and
James are sometimes surprised at how they're classified by their
industry. ``In the trade, we're known as `scratch bakers,' '' says
Pray. ``I never thought of us as that.'' Since so many bakeries are
``baking off'' yeast doughs and cookies they purchase frozen, the
``scratch'' category had to be established.
</P>
<P>
   If everyone who begins with real butter and cream is called
scratch, then there should be a category so exclusive that only a
fraction of the top bakers would be eligible. Pray and James could
join those elite ranks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
