<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3520 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ARTS-PIMP-BOS &LR;      07-26 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-PIMP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BAADDER OR FOR WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it 1970s nostalgia or simply a desire to vicariously live the
life of somebody who's baaad to the bone?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, the pimp (a.k.a. mack or mack-daddy) has
strutted his way into pop culture, complete with flashy cars,
Versace suits, fistfuls of cash, and two armloads of scantily clad
women. Call the aesthetic ghetto fabulous. And lately, it's been
making headway into music, film, and books.
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop heads have spent the last few months vowing ``I'll be
forever mackin' '' as they sing along with Jay-Z's crossover hit,
``Big Pimpin.' '' The 1973 film ``The Mack,'' which gave rise to
the slang, has been a hot video rental for years.
</P>
<P>
   Flip on E! Television's Video Fashion Weekly and you'll hear
Stephen Baldwin naughtily call the lush, peacock-colored suits of
British designer Oswald Boateng ``awesome when you want to go a
little extra sexy, a little extra flamboyant, a little extra
pimpy.'' And movie audiences are currently seeing the harsher side
of life as a mack-daddy in the documentary ``American Pimp.''
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to cause people to make like Marvin Gaye and ask:
what's going on? Vern L. Bullough, co-editor of the recently
published book of scholarly essays, ``Prostitution: On Whores,
Hustlers and Johns,'' thinks he has an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's giving a different interpretation of the pimp, who was
regarded as a lowest of low in the past,'' he says. ``He's not now.
He's really in there and belonging.''
</P>
<P>
   Turn on MTV and you'll hear Jamie, a roommate on ``The Real
World New Orleans,'' crow, ``I'm lucky. I'm a pimp.'' That's
``pimp'' in a positive ``I've got it all'' way, not pimp in the ``I
have women who sell sex for money'' sense of the word.
</P>
<P>
   It's an issue of reality vs. fantasy. And America's digging the
pimp fantasy at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like the way it sounds: `I'm a pimp. I'm a mack,' '' says
Too Short, a rapper who's fashioned a long, successful career
recounting pimp tales on his albums. ``Nobody's actually saying,
`I'm a pimp' and attempting to prostitute women.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't escape the harsh truths about the business in
``American Pimp,'' in which the subjects casually call their
prostitutes terms that are usually reserved for female dogs and
gardening equipment. The glamour of pimp life also faded mighty
quickly last month when a roving group of men felt empowered enough
to grope, poke, or stroke about 50 women after the Puerto Rican Day
Parade in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's misogynist,'' says William Eric Perkins, the
self-described ``godfather of hip-hop scholarship'' who's a
research scholar at the University of Pennsylvania. ``It creates a
culture and environment where these kinds of attacks will actually
be tolerated and condoned.''
</P>
<P>
   You've got to wonder how someone who makes a living in such an
unconventional way could even become hip. So hip that videos by
male artists don't seem complete lately without a bevy of women
clad in G-strings and bikini tops. So hip that Kid Rock, Snoop
Dogg, and menswear companies like Sean ``Puffy'' Combs's Sean John
borrow the mink coats, feather vests, and velvet suits that were
once the pimp's fashion domain.
</P>
<P>
   And you know something's going on if Madonna's appropriating the
look by wearing a lavish fur coat in the video for her upcoming
single ``Music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This generation is borrowing heavily from the blaxploitation
era,'' says Perkins. ``These (are) characters who live on the
margin, who live outside of traditional mainstream culture, who
challenge conventional authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Bullough, ``There's kind of a thing in culture now of
living halfway dangerously. One way you can do that is through
songs and music, finding borderline people. It makes you feel kind
of daring. It's a cheap way to get excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is pimping the pimp business sells. Just ask rapper Too
Short. He's putting out his 12th album, appropriately titled, ``You
Nasty,'' in September; six of his records have reached platinum
status without the benefit of radio airplay.
</P>
<P>
   Or consider the case of Iceberg Slim's novel ``Pimp: The Story
of my Life,'' a sort of bible of the aesthetic. About 5 million
copies have been plucked from bookstore shelves worldwide since it
became available in 1969, according to its publisher, Holloway
House. The novel will soon be made into a Hollywood film starring
actor/rapper Ice Cube.
</P>
<P>
   Too Short, 34, the son of two college-educated accountants,
became fascinated with the life the way most guys do: he read
``Pimp'' and gobbled up 1970s blaxploitation films like ``The
Mack'' and ``Willie Dynamite.'' Then, after his family moved from
Los Angeles to Oakland, Calif., he found himself in a Sodom and
Gomorrah-like high school where, he maintains, pimps and
prostitutes were his classmates.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1980s Too Short was incorporating lessons learned
from pop culture and real life into his lyrics. His bulging sales
showed he wasn't the only one intrigued with the business
colloquially known as ``the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys fantasize about. . .,'' says Too Short, launching into
talk too raunchy to print here. ``That's the alter ego of men _ not
all of them, but the large fan base out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Too Short, who appears as a ``pimpology'' expert in ``American
Pimp,'' uses gallows humor and funky beats to leaven his
misogynistic tales. ``Let's get this money/That's what I want you
for,'' he raps bluntly in the song, ``Call Me Daddy.'' ``Don't let
me wait too long/'Cause life is too short.''
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to Jay-Z's radio friendly ``Big Pimpin','' where
the chorus goes ``We doin', big pimpin', we spendin' cheese,'' or
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big pimpin', according to the song, is I'm just out having
fun, enjoying myself. . .spending money'' says Too Short. ``But if
you were doing big pimpin' you'd be making money because big
pimpin' is making cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   Too Short deflects any accusations that the current popular
flirtation with the mack instigates violence against women. He
blames Hollywood's relentless peddling of sexual images _ not songs
glamorizing pimp life _ for incidents like the one that happened in
Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that you've got this billion-dollar rap industry, people
are assuming that we're all uneducated, `They're the ones that are
corrupting society,' '' says Too Short. ``It's not the rap music.
Listening to Too Short does not make 12 guys rape somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, prostitution and pimping have been around much
longer than hip-hop. In ``American Pimp,'' some of the subjects
trace the origins of the pimp profession back to slavery and
Reconstruction. But Bullough, a clinical professor at the
University of Southern California, believes men began plying the
trade sometime in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that brothels, which until that point were often run
by women, became outlawed. Women took to the streets to earn money
and turned to men for protection.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, a surfeit of blaxploitation movies introduced
these anachronistic relationships to the masses. A decade later,
1980s comedies like ``I'm Gonna Git You Sucka'' and ``Hollywood
Shuffle'' sent up the image of the pimp.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Brown, a former pimp who now makes a living singing blues
in Los Angeles, isn't impressed with either the films or literary
output. ``They didn't portray the real deal,'' he says disdainfully
in ``American Pimp.'' But the works did engrave certain perceptions
about the mack into society's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``In black culture, a pimp was known as a flashy dresser who
could make his way in the white world successfully,'' says
Bullough. ``But in the white world, he was regarded as a vulture
preying upon innocent young girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither image is true, says Bullough, who calls pimps hustlers.
Nor, notes ``American Pimp,'' is the notion that pimps are only
black. In fact, they include white men like Dennis Hof, owner of
the Moonlight Bunny Ranch, a legalized brothel in Nevada, and
Playboy's Hugh Hefner, whom an interviewee in ``American Pimp''
admiringly labels ``the greatest pimp that ever lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Too Short talks about a new generation of pimps who drive
minivans and wear geeky clothing to avoid the attention of the
police. Of course, fans of Jay-Z wouldn't ever think of sporting
that kind of gear. After all, the current pimp aesthetic is all
about surface: big cars, fur coats, designer labels, alligator
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's high style,'' says Perkins. ``It's being ghetto
fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   So fabulous that, in March, Esquire magazine went so far as to
declare pimp style in style in its guide to popular culture.
Parents may balk, but it's enough to make any mack-daddy preen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
