<HEADER>
A3536 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-COPS-EXECUTIVE-HNS &LR;      07-26 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPS-EXECUTIVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLICE STALL INVESTIGATION OF KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco's independent police watchdog
agency has been unable to complete its investigation of the 1998
shooting of an advertising executive because of an uncooperative
police department.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Police Department admitted Tuesday that its
internal affairs probe of the officer-involved shooting death of
John Smart Jr. was still unfinished, even though a police awards
committee nominated the two officers under investigation for the
Gold Medal of Valor.
</P>
<P>
   Smart, 46, an executive of Interbrand, died of gunshot wounds on
Oct. 6, 1998, after officers Jason Sawyer and Ian Furminger fired
at least 13 rounds into his 1996 Mercedes convertible as he
allegedly drove toward them. The shooting came minutes after the
officers interceded in a struggle between Smart and a woman on a
city street.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Dunlap, director of the Office of Citizen Complaints (OCC),
said her investigation into the Smart shooting had been repeatedly
delayed by lack of cooperation from the department's homicide and
internal affairs units. Smart was shot more than 15 times by the
police as he tried to flee in his car.
</P>
<P>
   The OCC has yet to receive a report from the Police Department's
internal affairs unit on Smart's killing, and a report from the
homicide squad was sent in May, nearly 18 months after the case was
closed by homicide inspectors, Dunlap said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not delayed our investigation,'' Dunlap said. ``We
have worked hard, but we have not gotten the cooperation that we
expect under the City Charter.''
</P>
<P>
   Her complaints are not limited to the Smart investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have received no officer-involved shooting reports on Smart
or in any other shooting since October 1998,'' she said. This
includes more than eight cases, according to police records.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap said she had not been able to get an explanation for the
long wait for the homicide detail's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``After months of lobbying, letter-writing and door pounding we
received an incomplete report in May 2000,'' she said. ``My
understanding is that the homicide investigation was closed in
December 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap declined to discuss the contents of the report.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, police Chief Fred Lau questioned why it was taking
the OCC so long to study the Smart case after the homicide
investigation had cleared the two officers of criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, however, the police admitted Dunlap was correct about
the unfinished internal affairs report in the Smart case and in a
number of other shooting cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take responsibility for not providing full and complete
information that OCC is entitled to,'' Lau said. ``I was acting
upon information that was not completely correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officers, their union and attorneys representing officers
under investigation have long criticized the slow investigative
process of the OCC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a disgrace that it takes the OCC so long,'' said
attorney Jim Collins, a former police officer who frequently
represents officers accused of wrongdoing. ``These officers have to
live under a cloud for years, not knowing if they will face
charges.''
</P>
<P>
   OCC, created by voter initiative, investigates any citizen
complaint of police activity. Under the City Charter, the OCC
reviews all shootings by the police. The Police Department is also
required to share the results of its investigations with OCC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
