<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Thursday, July 27.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-CORPORATIONS (New York) _ Not so long ago the nonprofit
Roundabout Theater Company was performing plays for 150 people in a
supermarket basement. Thursday night, the company will open its
first show in its elegant new 750-seat theater. The showplace is
named the American Airlines Theater, in exchange for an $8.5
million payment from American Airlines. Patrons who contribute
$1,500 or more can relax over cocktails and Oreo cookies in the
Nabisco lounge (so named in exchange for $500,000). The rest of the
theater's subscribers can catch the sunset from the balcony of the
new penthouse lobby (name still for sale at $1.5 million). By Robin
Pogrebin. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-ANIMATION (New Orleans) _ Each year, SIGGRAPH brings
together the leading artists, companies, researchers, animators and
visionaries from the worlds of computer animation, virtual reality
and interactive technology _ and each year, one of the highlights
is the submissions from all over the world which are winnowed down
to be part of a computer animation festival. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-EUROPE-ART (Ljubljana, Slovenia) _ On Manifesta 3, the
European Biennial of Contemporary Art, where works by artists and
groups from European Union nations and the ``other'' Europe _
countries like Poland, Macedonia, Slovakia, Russia and Bosnia and
Herzegovina _ offer a snapshot of a Europe where the simple
political distinction of East or West has given way to a web of new
divisions. By Josephine Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   BAYREUTH-MUSIC-GERMANY (Bayreuth, Germany) _ Richard Wagner had
in mind that all things low and vulgar would be left behind at the
bottom of the green hill on which he built his opera house. After
124 years, the trees have grown and the myth of the Bayreuth
Festival with them. The annual summer event is with us again, and
on Tuesday featured ``Parsifal.'' By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   LIBERACE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``An American Boy,'' Darden
Asbery Pryon, who previously trained his analytical eye on Margaret
Mitchell and ``Gone With the Wind,'' is daffily intent on making a
scholarly study of Liberace, the performer famed for introducing
rhinestone-studded hot pants to Las Vegas. Reviewed by Janet
Maslin.
</P>
