<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3543 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-26 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S CHOICE DEMONSTRATES SENSE AND SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could cite any number of reasons why Dick Cheney was a great
choice for the Republican vice presidential nomination, but two
reasons stand out:
</P>
<P>
   _He is highly qualified _ not only to serve as vice president
but as president, should the need arise.
</P>
<P>
   _He is not John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's McCain-for-Veep boomlet was unnerving, to say the
least. It wasn't that I doubted the ability of presidential
nominee-to-be George W. Bush to resist McCain's devious,
last-minute bid to grab a spot on the GOP ticket; it was just ...
well, it was just that politicians sometimes make inexplicable
decisions at moments like this.
</P>
<P>
   It was at a moment like this, after all, that Bush's father
chose Dan Quayle as his running mate. Talk about inexplicable.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the governor of Texas is not prone to such campaign
weirdness, and he made a thoughtful, level-headed decision when the
time came to choose the individual who figures to be the next vice
president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas McCain's monstrous ego would never enable him to
graciously endure second billing in a campaign or in a Bush
administration, Cheney has the experience and the temperament to
carry out the responsibilities of both a running mate and a vice
president. He was White House chief of staff when Gerald Ford was
president; he was secretary of defense under President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is an able boss _ he's headed up a major corporation in
recent years _ but he understands that even bosses have bosses.
Obviously, George W. Bush believes that Cheney is a man he can work
with.
</P>
<P>
   And compatibility was one of Bush's top two criteria for a
running mate. First and foremost, the vice presidential candidate
had to be someone capable of taking over the presidency at a
moment's notice. After that, the major factor was the comfort level
between the running mates.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, not so long ago, when presidential nominees
picked their running mates on the basis of geographical or
philosophical balance, with little or no thought given to the
question of compatibility _ or competence, for that matter. All
that mattered was winning the election.
</P>
<P>
   But recent presidents have given vice presidents more
responsibility, have brought their seconds in command into the
inner circles of decision-making. That means that the president and
the vice president must get along with each other; must communicate
with each other; must respect each other.
</P>
<P>
   After carefully considering all the potential candidates for
vice president, Bush decided that Cheney filled the bill better
than any of the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked him because he is, without a doubt, fully capable of
being the president of the United States, and I picked him because
he will be a valuable partner in a Bush administration,'' Bush said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's opponents and detractors were quick to criticize the
selection of Cheney _ as they would have been quick to criticize
any selection that Bush made. Even if Bush had landed the
universally admired Colin Powell as a running mate, there surely
would have been those who found fault with the choice.
</P>
<P>
   But some Bush critics were so hard pressed to conjure up
objections to Cheney's selection that they resorted to the
preposterous charge that Bush is so insecure that he felt compelled
to team up with one of his father's ex-cronies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the opposite is true. By picking the man he believed
was best qualified despite that man's former association with Bush
the elder, Bush the younger demonstrated that he is secure enough
and confident enough to do the right thing even in the face of
certain criticism.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate who was truly laboring in the shadow of his
ex-president father would have gone out of his way to avoid being
linked with one of the father's top advisers. George W. Bush picked
the running mate he wanted and said to heck with the critics.
</P>
<P>
   That's leadership, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's see what Al Gore does about choosing a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
