<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-VOTERS-AARP27-COX     07-26 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTERS-AARP27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AARP RELEASES POLL, PLANS VOTER EDUCATION CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Family values and education are the most important
issues on voters' minds, according to a recent survey conducted by
the seniors organization AARP.
</P>
<P>
   Providing a prescription drug benefit for Medicare and
protecting Social Security follow closely behind, said Jeffrey
Love, AARP associate director of research.
</P>
<P>
   Among the general public, 27 percent of those polled selected
ethics and family values as the most important issue in determining
their vote for president. That was followed by 24 percent who named
education, 18 percent who chose Social Security and 10 percent who
said Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Among AARP's 30 million members, 35 percent of those polled said
Social Security was the most important issue to watch during the
presidential election, compared to 22 percent who listed ethics and
family values, 18 percent who picked Medicare, and 12 percent who
chose education.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that about half the population claimed they had
enough information to know where the candidates stood on the
issues, but less than half said they could distinguish between Vice
President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush on specific issues.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to inform elderly voters and draw attention to the
importance of senior issues, AARP, whose members are 50 or older,
is launching an ambitious voter education and turnout drive.
</P>
<P>
   Among the AARP's election activities will be:
</P>
<P>
   _ A 23-city, 20-state bus trip featuring AARP President Tess
Canja and other volunteers that will start in Philadelphia during
the Republican National Convention and end two weeks later in Los
Angeles during the Democratic National Convention. Along the way,
AARP will solicit cards from supporters of a prescription drug
benefit in Medicare. The cards will be given to Congress and the
White House this fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ Distributing voter guides and material reporting presidential
and congressional candidates' positions on issues of importance to
the elderly. The guides will be limited to the Democratic and
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Co-sponsoring the three presidential and one vice-presidential
debates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Co-sponsoring an online voter registration Web site,
``beavoter.org,'' where people can register to vote in all states
except New Hampshire, North Dakota and Wyoming. Since April, more
than 50,000 voters have registered on line through the site.
</P>
<P>
   _ Purchasing billboard and newspaper advertisements urging
Congress to pass a Medicare prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Extensive get-out-the-vote efforts to encourage and assist the
elderly to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seniors vote in greater proportion that any other age group,
and we vote on issues, not on personalities,'' said Horace Deets,
AARP's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   AARP: www.aarp.org/election2000
</P>
<P>
   BeAVoter: beavoter.org
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
