<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3583 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-CONVENTION-UNDERWRITE     07-26 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTION-UNDERWRITERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CORPORATIONS MAKE IT ALL HAPPEN AT PARTY CONVENTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Filed in ``f'' and ``p'' categories)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZACHARY COILE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next week's Republican National Convention in Philadelphia will
feature prominent names like Colin Powell, John McCain, Elizabeth
Dole and, of course, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But the names that will not appear center stage are the ones
that will actually pay for the convention _ names like General
Motors, Microsoft, PepsiCo and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations are underwriting much of the cost of the event,
which is expected to exceed $50 million, as well as the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   To the companies, the conventions a chance to get their name
before tens of thousands of delegates, public officials and
journalists. But critics say the contributions, which are not
limited by federal election law, are just another way for
corporations to exert influence over the nation's policymakers.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the eight biggest donors to the Republican convention
are telecommunications companies: AT&AMP;T, Verizon Communications,
formerly Bell Atlantic, and Comcast Corp. Each contributed $1
million, according to figures compiled by the nonpartisan Center
for Responsive Politics in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, telecommunications companies have important
business before the federal government. AT&AMP;T is battling federal
efforts to force it to open its phone lines to other Internet
providers. The Baby Bells still face resistance in entering the $80
billion long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   ``In years like this where their companies are heavily targeted
by potential legislation or regulation, they are more likely to be
active'' in giving, said Sheila Krumholz, research director for the
Center for Responsive Politics. ``There's a large potential for
harm if they don't participate or benefit if they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Other corporate donors have their own concerns. Tobacco giant
Philip Morris, which gave $250,000 to the GOP convention, is
nervous about the Justice Department's lawsuit against the tobacco
industry. Blue Cross/Blue Shield, which gave $100,000 for the
Republican event, has a major stake in any legislation affecting
health care.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations are not paying the entire cost of the Republican
convention. Philadelphia has contributed $7 million, while
Pennsylvania and neighboring New Jersey have given $10 million and
$3 million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest chunk has come from companies: an estimated $26
million. The host committee in Philadelphia has even ranked them:
$1 million contributors are ``platinum'' donors, $500,000 givers
are ``gold'' and $250,000 donors are ``silver.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the corporate giving comes as in-kind contributions,
free goods or services. Hewlett-Packard, for example, is donating
$250,000 worth of printers and work stations. When the convention
is over, the equipment will be donated to schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to be good corporate citizens,'' said H-P spokeswoman
Emily Fox. ``By supporting an important aspect of the political
process and promoting economic and educational development in the
host city, we think we're fulfilling that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most companies say their contributions aren't meant to influence
the political process, but to help market their products and
services.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Airways, official airline of the GOP convention, has
offered discounted airfares to delegates. The airline's $500,000
gift to the host committee was aimed at bringing attention to
Philadelphia, its third-largest hub, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our decision to be a participant with the Republican National
Committee was purely a business decision,'' said David Castelveter,
a U.S. Airways spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, official carrier for the Democratic National
Convention, also gave $500,000 to its host committee and offered
similar discounts to convention-goers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity to have those customers fly on United
Airlines and attract their business,'' said Kurt Ebenhoch, a United
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for both airlines said their sponsorship of the
political conventions had nothing to do with their pending $11.6
billion merger, which requires federal approval. ``I wouldn't want
to speculate about that,'' Ebenhoch said.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are giving to both parties. General Motors,
Microsoft and AT&AMP;T gave $1 million each to the Democratic and
Republican convention committees.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin, the world's largest defense aerospace company,
gave $100,000 to both conventions. As a company that does 75
percent of its business with the government, ``we try to be
even-handed and equal in our giving to both of their conventions,''
said Hugh Burns, Lockheed Martin spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the in-kind donations have been massive. SBC
Communications, the San Antonio-based telecommunications company,
has installed nearly 5,000 miles of copper wire and more than 350
DSL lines worth $1 million in and around the Staples Center in Los
Angeles, where the Democratic convention will be held. The
convention will cost an estimated $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity, in front of an international audience,
for the company to really distinguish itself,'' said Steve Getzug,
an SBC spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
