<HEADER>
A3585 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     07-26 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BROTHERS GARCIA' REFLECTS LATIN LIFE, MINUS STEREOTYPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By October, kid channel Nickelodeon will have managed to do
twice what the broadcast networks haven't even attempted in at
least a decade: air a series built around Latino families.
</P>
<P>
   Getting much of the attention but not airing until fall is
``Taina,'' a multigenerational series following the life of a
spunky 15-year-old girl who tries to balance the expectations of
her traditional Puerto Rican family with her passionate dreams of
fame and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   I'd suspect that the show's trendy urban core, musical numbers
and Latin pop culture wrapped around universal themes make it a
cinch to lure Nick's target audience.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hype for the ``The Brothers Garcia,'' which premiered
Sunday, was less spectacular, but it would be a mistake to judge
this series on a lack of water-cooler chat alone.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Jeff Valdez, the Los Angeles producer of Latino
English-language and bilingual programs, ``The Brothers Garcia'' is
a drama-comedy that puts you in mind of ``The Wonder Years,'' what
with its whimsical nature and how the show's protagonist offers in
narration his perspective on the world and how it's shaping him and
his tight-knit San Antonio family.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as an adult (it's the voice of John Leguizamo), Larry
Garcia (Alvin Alvarez) is recalling his quest as an 11-year-old and
youngest of the three Garcia brothers (Carlos, played by Jeffrey
Licon, is 13, and George, played by Bobby Gonzalez, is 12). Carlos
is the athletic one and George is the smart one, so Larry does what
he can to assert his individuality. Even if it gets him in trouble,
which it often does.
</P>
<P>
   Larry lives at home with his hardworking father, Ray (Carlos La
Camara), and mother, Sonia (Ada Maris), who are compassionate but
pragmatic when it comes to laying down the law of family values and
morals. No means no, and the kids have already been trained to
accept that fact and move on. Larry also has a fraternal twin
sister, Lorena (Vaneza Leza Pitynski), who always seems to be
around when he's up to no good. It drives him up a wall.
</P>
<P>
   The scrapes Larry gets himself into are the usual predicaments
kids eager to grow up often find themselves in, but thankfully, the
story lines aren't as trite as we've seen in similar family series
like ``Full House.'' In the episode sent for review, the boys put
on their own wrestling match when a short-term financial crisis
keeps them and their father from attending a professional wrestling
match.
</P>
<P>
   Future episodes include Carlos and George falling for the same
girl, Larry trying to break free from his role as the family's
baby, and Ray and Sonia putting a cap on TV-watching.
</P>
<P>
   One of the failings of programs centered on families of color is
that they are usually the result of commerce, not art, and
certainly not of a commitment to actually reflecting the world
children live in.
</P>
<P>
   Nick has been better than most, having previously presented
multicultural shows and some with predominantly black and Asian
casts.
</P>
<P>
   With ``The Brothers Garcia,'' Nick offers an engaging look
inside a Latino family that goes far beyond the stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
