<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of THURSDAY, July
27.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT AND CULTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-CORPORATIONS (New York) _ Not so long ago the nonprofit
Roundabout Theater Company was performing plays for 150 people in a
supermarket basement. Thursday night, the company will open its
first show in its elegant new 750-seat theater. The showplace is
named the American Airlines Theater, in exchange for an $8.5
million payment from American Airlines. Patrons who contribute
$1,500 or more can relax over cocktails and Oreo cookies in the
Nabisco lounge (so named in exchange for $500,000). The rest of the
theater's subscribers can catch the sunset from the balcony of the
new penthouse lobby (name still for sale at $1.5 million). By Robin
Pogrebin. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-ANIMATION (New Orleans) _ Each year, SIGGRAPH brings
together the leading artists, companies, researchers, animators and
visionaries from the worlds of computer animation, virtual reality
and interactive technology _ and each year, one of the highlights
is the submissions from all over the world which are winnowed down
to be part of a computer animation festival. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-EUROPE-ART (Ljubljana, Slovenia) _ On Manifesta 3, the
European Biennial of Contemporary Art, where works by artists and
groups from European Union nations and the ``other'' Europe _
countries like Poland, Macedonia, Slovakia, Russia and Bosnia and
Herzegovina _ offer a snapshot of a Europe where the simple
political distinction of East or West has given way to a web of new
divisions. By Josephine Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   BAYREUTH-MUSIC-GERMANY (Bayreuth, Germany) _ Richard Wagner had
in mind that all things low and vulgar would be left behind at the
bottom of the green hill on which he built his opera house. After
124 years, the trees have grown and the myth of the Bayreuth
Festival with them. The annual summer event is with us again, and
on Tuesday featured ``Parsifal.'' By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   LIBERACE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``An American Boy,'' Darden
Asbery Pryon, who previously trained his analytical eye on Margaret
Mitchell and ``Gone With the Wind,'' is daffily intent on making a
scholarly study of Liberace, the performer famed for introducing
rhinestone-studded hot pants to Las Vegas. Reviewed by Janet
Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOME &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``l'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-U.S.-TOILETS (Windsor, Ontario) _ Americans in search of
suburbia's new holy grail _ the kind of old-style, big-flush toilet
that Americans took as their birthright until 1994 _ now routinely
travel to Canada. In 1994, a federal water conservation law went
into effect, mandating that all new toilets use only 1.6 gallons a
flush. Now, border towns from New Brunswick to British Columbia
offer Americans what one Vancouver plumber has called Canuck
commodes. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   SALVAGED-HOUSE (Phoenix, Ariz.) _ The four-room,
2,400-square-foot house Patrick and Marika McCue are building here
is made from 75 percent salvaged material, including trusses
rejected from a ballpark, high-quality but scratched glass donated
by a house-building friend and surplus steel picked up at
junkyards. The walls are of poured earth, and the roof is a
polyvinyl tent fabric, hovering, lightweight and taut as a spider
web. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-HIGHWAY (Dateline to come) _ The scenery along the Ohio
Turnpike will never be confused with that along, say, the Pacific
Coast Highway or Blue Ridge Parkway. But weary travelers this
summer are encountering something that may compensate: a new
generation of service plazas is providing the amenities of home or
at least those of a decent airport terminal. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   NY-EAST-VILLAGE (New York) _ In 1978, Roland Legiardi-Laura
bought a loft in the East Village for $20,000. This May, his
building _ the former Tompkins Square Boys' Lodging House, the
oldest surviving structure built for the homeless in New York _ was
designated a city landmark, qualifying its owners for low-interest
loans to restore its facades. When that happens, the exterior will
finally reflect the remarkable transformation that has taken place
within. Today, in a neighborhood that sports new real estate
developments on almost every block, Legiardi-Laura's may be the
most unusual of all. By Marc Kristal.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIRCUITS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-LIBRARY-OF-COMMERCE (Undated) _ The Library of Congress is
charged with collecting the creative work of the American people.
But now the nation's creativity extends to Web sites, electronic
journals and magazines and CD-ROMs of every sort. And the library
is lagging in collecting and archiving that digital material,
according to a report released Wednesday by the National Academy of
Sciences. By Katie Hafner. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-DIGITAL-ORGANS (New York) _ In organ lofts throughout the
country, relatively inexpensive circuits and loudspeakers playing
digitally sampled sounds are taking the place of costly organ
pipes. By Anne Eisenberg. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CELLPHONES-RISKS (Undated) _ After several of the world's
largest cell phone manufacturers, including companies like Nokia,
Motorola and Ericsson, said last week that they planned to release
more information on the radiation levels of their devices, it will
be harder to ignore the debate over health risks and mobile phones.
By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ONLINE-CONCERT (Undated) _ The Digital Club Festival was
billed as the largest online music show ever, a milestone in
turning the Web into an entertainment medium. By Alisha Berger.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-BACH-ONLINE (Undated) _ On Thursday, using IBM technology
and timed to the 250th anniversary of Bach's death, the
Staatsbibliothek in Berlin and six other repositories of Bach
manuscripts will inaugurate online access to some of the composer's
documents, scanned and digitized from high-quality color slides. By
Glenn Garelik. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-BIKE-TRAINING (Undated) _ In the past decade, measuring
power output has become standard training procedure for many
top-level professional cyclists. Now SRM and a cycling electronics
upstart called Tune, based in Cambridge, Mass., are hoping that
lower-priced units for measuring power will make converts among
amateur cyclists as well. By Ian Austen.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-INTERNET-PERMANENCE (Undated) _ On the ever-shifting
Internet, what is on a Web site today could easily be gone
tomorrow. But a new publishing system developed by AT&AMP;T promises to
add permanence to information put on the Internet. By Daniel Sorid.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-WOMEN-COMPUTERS (Undated) _ A new study predicts that while
undergraduate enrollments in computer science will increase
rapidly, the proportion of women in that enrollment is unlikely to
rise. By Anne Eisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GAME-SNOOZLEBERG (Undated) _ Part puzzle game, part
slapstick cartoon, Sarbakan's Good Night, Mr. Snoozleberg is one of
the best games you can play on the Internet and one of the best
puzzle games of the last few years. By Charles Herold.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ I recently spent time with three
new portable DVD players and found that crowds of both men and
women would gather around when I had one on parade. Current
portable DVD players offer bright, clear video display, Dolby
Digital sound and batteries powerful enough for a double feature.
By J.D. Biersdorfer.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GEEK-NOTES (Undated) _ Short updates on technological
topics.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING (Undated) _ Buying custom-made jeans online.
By Michelle Slatalla.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Your questions on e-mail answered. By J.D.
Biersdorfer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   TOUR-DE-FRANCE (New York) _ A Sports of the Times column on
Lance Armstrong, who did a quick victory tour of New York
Wednesday, three days after winning the Tour de France for the
second consecutive year. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; OLY-SAMARANCH (Lausanne, Switzerland) _ On the eve of the
Summer Olympics in Sydney, an extended question-and-answer session
with Juan Samaranch, the head of the International Olympic
Commission. By Christopher Clarey.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES (Baltimore) _ Yankees at Baltimore, 7:05 pm
EDT. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-EXPOS-METS (New York) _ Expos at N.Y. Mets, 7:10 pm, EDT. By
Jack Curry.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-SARATOGA (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ Saratoga kicked off its
six weeks of summer racing Wednesday with the Schuylerville stakes
for 2-year-old fillies. By Joe Drape.
</P>
