<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT27-COX     07-26 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT BLASTS ANTITRUST JUDGE
 &HT;    Moving in the (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. told the Supreme Court on Wednesday
that the judge who seeks a fast-track appeal of his decision to
break up the company is prejudiced and should be removed from the
landmark case if it is sent back to him.
</P>
<P>
   In its 30-page brief, the world's largest software firm urged
the high tribunal to allow the U.S. Court of Appeals in the
District of Columbia to first review the issues, rather than
hearing them directly.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Microsoft launched a stinging personal attack
against U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who ordered
the breakup after branding Microsoft an abusive monopolist that
illegally used its huge power in the marketplace to stifle
competition and harm consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's ``blunt comments to the press,'' made both before and
after his final ruling June 7, ``raise serious questions about
(his) impartiality,'' the brief said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it added, they ``betray a misguided belief'' that the
government and 19 states, who filed their historic antitrust suit
26 months ago, ``were entitled to the remedy of their choice, no
matter how extreme, simply because they had prevailed on
liability.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's 11,000-word filing, accompanied by a 312-page
appendix, accused Jackson of having made 15 broad errors in the
course of the 78-day trial, any one of which, it argued, offered
ample grounds for an appellate court to reverse him.
</P>
<P>
   To this list, Microsoft's lawyers added three more alleged
errors that Jackson purportedly committed after the trial had
ended. They were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Entering ``a sweeping permanent injunction without an
evidentiary hearing on relief.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Imposing extreme and punitive relief unrelated to the
antitrust violations found.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Engaging in ``extrajudicial communications with the press
concerning the merits of these cases in violation of (federal legal
canons).'' Those rules, the brief said ``require that the judgment
... be reversed and, if the (case is) remanded, that (it) be
assigned to another district judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also accused Jackson of showing bad faith. He
allegedly did so by privately promising that in the remedial phase
he would ``replicate the procedure at trial with testimony in
written form subject to cross-examination'' _ only to subsequently
spurn Microsoft's plea that chairman and co-founder Bill Gates be
permitted to testify.
</P>
<P>
   A clerk for Jackson said the judge would have no comment on the
charges raised in the Microsoft brief.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A 1978 law opens the door for government-initiated antitrust
cases of ``general public importance'' in ``the administration of
justice'' to get direct Supreme Court consideration. The justices
are not expected to decide whether to assert jurisdiction before
October, when they are next due to convene.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said in its brief that ``the severity of the remedy
imposed and the significance of (the case) to the nation's economy
make it more important _ not less _ that (the appeal) proceed
through intermediate appellate review in the normal course.''
</P>
<P>
   That would mean turning the issue over to a seven-member panel
of appellate judges who work four floors above Jackson's courtroom.
Those judges have already signaled their eagerness to retain the
first crack on the appeal, a procedure that both Jackson and U.S.
Solicitor General Seth Waxman seek to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   In its brief, Microsoft held that the mid-level appellate branch
is far better suited than the nine Supreme Court justices in coping
with the 1,815 pages of written direct testimony, 13,466 pages of
trial transcript and 2,695 trial exhibits, much of which ``relates
to highly technical issues of software design.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department will reply to the Microsoft filing by
Aug. 15, and Microsoft will have a final chance to rebut the
government's views by Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: microsoft.com/presspass/trial/default.asp
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
