<HEADER>
A3623 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-TEN-ANNA-KOURNIKOVA-H     07-26 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ANNA-KOURNIKOVA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KOURNIKOVA ENJOYS HOLDING COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHELLE SMITH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Just call it Anna-proofing.
</P>
<P>
   There is a large window at the main entrance to the Taube Family
Tennis Stadium behind which the press room is located. Last year,
when Anna Kournikova made her Bank of the West Classic debut, the
area in front of that window was home to a veritable throng of fans
_ OK, men _ with their noses pressed against the glass, knocking
and waving as the Russian teen made her postmatch remarks.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there is a small wooden picket fence extending out
about 5 feet away from the window and a security guard manning the
location to ensure against a repeat. There will be no getting
carried away with Anna-mania in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova made her debut at Stanford Tuesday night in front of
a full house and a sizable contingent of the Stanford football
team, winning easily against Annie Miller, 6-1, 6-2, in just 48
minutes. But if Kournikova's presence caused a palpable buzz, there
were no signs of a frenzy _ only a couple of homemade signs
(including one that said ``I Play Hockey'' in reference to her
relationship with hockey stars Sergei Federov and Pavel Bure and
another bearing a rather suggestive proposition), a few whistles
and a dozen photographers with their cameras poised solely in her
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' Kournikova said of the crowd. ``I like playing
night tennis because it's such a great atmosphere. It's great when
the crowd gets into the match.''
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova is still the most famous tennis player in the world
who has never won anything. She has been on tour nearly five years
and is still without a singles title.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, her ranking has slipped appreciably this year. She was
ranked as high as No. 9, following a semifinal loss to Davenport in
early March, but she has fallen to her current ranking of 19 after
second-round losses at both the French Open and Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest flaw in her game, her lack of consistency, was
evident Tuesday even in an easy victory. Kournikova hit a slew of
stinging groundstrokes, strokes that make her competitive with the
best players in the world, but also managed to mix in a few costly
unforced errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was probably one of the most enjoyable matches I've
played in the last few months. I was really happy with my game
today. I didn't try to adjust to her game, I just kept playing
mine,'' Kournikova said. ``This is going to be a great time for me
to get some points, just play and move up in the rankings.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a onetime top 50 player, was playing her first match
after a two-year layoff because of injury and studies at the
University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't have to do much to win pretty easily,'' Miller
said. ``I was making tons of errors. When we did have a couple of
decent point rallies, she was more aggressive. I don't think I gave
her too much competition tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova's will probably play again on Thursday against
Canadian Jana Nejedly.
</P>
</TEXT>
