<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>

 DROP AND ROLL: FRIEND FIRED UP OVER DUMPLINGS
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
 By ART CHAPMAN
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend of mine, a Texas expatriate who is dodging the summer
heat at his retirement home in Oregon, sent me a note crying for
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help!'' it began simply. ``Before I attempt chicken and
dumplings again, I need a better recipe and perhaps some better
instructions on how to implement it. Didn't you go through a round
of dumpling recipes a few years ago?''
</P>
<P>
   He knew full well that I had. It was a tumultuous time. Those
who love dumplings dropped from a spoon into the hot broth
threatened to fricasse my fingers if I didn't stop telling people
to roll out their dough for flat dumplings.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides raised their rolling pins in anger when it was hinted
that a make-do recipe could include canned biscuits or flour
tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I ever have a bone to pick with you,'' one writer began.
``A pot of boiling broth and chicken meat with the addition of bits
of canned biscuit dough is NOT chicken and dumplings!''
</P>
<P>
   The words ``nasty'' and ``disgusting'' were bantered about.
</P>
<P>
   But my friend was willing to raise all these issues again,
because he had suffered an embarrassing setback with his own
recipe. His wife wouldn't let him pour the remains down the sink;
the retirement home is new, and the septic system unproven.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recipe I used called for only flour and water and parsley
flakes, which is also the way we used to make flour paste when I
was a kid,'' he wrote. ``As I recall, the paste tasted better.''
</P>
<P>
   Dianna Almaroad of Grapevine sent a recipe I used during those
turbulent times.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote: ``Sift about 3 cups of flour into a bowl and make a
well in the center. Add 1 cup of HOT broth, 1 tablespoon
shortening, 1 egg and 2 egg yellows. Mix until dough is stiff.
Chill a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flour board, divide dough for easier handling, roll out paper
thin and cut into 2-inch-by-2-inch squares.''
</P>
<P>
   Almaroad says to drop the squares into the boiling broth, but
don't stir. Just use a long-handled spoon and ``jiggle.'' When all
the dumplings are in, return the boned chicken, season and cook for
20-30 minutes on medium-low heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Little has happened in the world of chicken and dumplings since
those earlier stories. Almaroad's recipe has held up well. Those
who know how to make chicken and dumplings are held in reverence
and awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised on a farm and I learned how to do chicken and
dumplings,'' said Dorothy Hill, who with her husband, Pete, runs
Summerhill House at Sixth Avenue and Magnolia Street on Fort
Worth's south side. ``I don't have time for people who use canned
biscuits or flour tortillas.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill's chicken and dumplings are legendary in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Summerhill House is not a big restaurant: about a dozen or so
stools at the counter, one table and maybe three or four chairs
against the wall. The Hills have run the place for the past 29
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long do you have to be married before you stop fighting,''
he asked somewhat rhetorically of the noonday crowd. ``How long you
been married, Pete?'' someone asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-nine years,'' Pete answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not long enough,'' came the reply.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy and Pete don't really argue in front of the customers.
They simply spar a little _ a gig here, a jab there.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Pete is singing Dorothy's praises. ``She makes the
chicken and dumplings from scratch,'' he said. ``She rolls those
dumplings out so thin, they melt in your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what I came for.
</P>
<P>
   The chicken was several hearty chunks of pure breast meat _
tender and rich in taste. The dumplings held together just long
enough to get to your mouth, then they quickly dispersed in a silky
sheet.
</P>
<P>
   The broth, Dorothy said, is rich because she uses ``turkey
tails.'' ``You can't get them (just) anywhere,'' she said. ``I buy
them at Carnival.''
</P>
<P>
   Once she has boiled the turkey tails into a stock, she adds the
chicken breasts.
</P>
<P>
   The dumplings are made of flour, baking soda, baking powder, a
little shortening and several eggs. The secret ingredient, she
said, is buttermilk.
</P>
<P>
   The end result is wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ought to try her banana pudding,'' Pete interrupts. ``She
makes that by scratch, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Pete, let the man eat,'' Dorothy fires back.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a column on food for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Write him at the Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth 76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
