<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-STRAUB-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HORROR! WRITER PETER STRAUB CAN'T ESCAPE SCARY IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JEFF GUINN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Straub thinks of himself as a writer, not a ``horror''
writer.
</P>
<P>
   But Straub, who has written 17 books, remains best-known for two
titles that fall squarely into the horror genre: ``Ghost Story,'' a
classic spook yarn published in 1979, and 1984's ``The Talisman,''
co-authored with longtime pal Stephen King, the acknowledged modern
master of monster fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've pretty much accepted that people want to put writers in
some category,'' Straub, 57, said on a recent stopover in Fort
Worth. ``It's easier for them, despite all the times I have
deliberately not written about supernatural subjects. `Ghost Story'
labeled me as a horror writer in peoples' eyes, `The Talisman'
cemented me, and the (book I'm working on) will lend itself to
that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years after their first collaboration, Straub and King
are hard at work on what they're currently calling ``Talisman II.''
They e-mail parts of chapters back and forth, each adding new
material to whatever the other sends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always knew we'd want to continue working together,''
Straub explained.
</P>
<P>
   But they also have their own books to write and promote. Straub
is on the road touting ``Magic Terror'' (Random House, $24.95), a
collection of short stories whose subjects sometimes, but not
always, include things that go bump in the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``People complain that the language is too blunt, that the
violence is too extreme, but some of these stories are as harmless
as baby food,'' Straub said. ``I never want my work to be boring,
familiar or stating the obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   As a voracious reader, Straub is familiar with the work of his
bestseller list peers. And he has strong feelings about what does
and doesn't make a good scary novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the best writing of the genre, the author uses the power of
the unstated,'' Straub said. ``You give the reader's imagination
room to work. Give the reader all the information he or she needs _
a glimpse of the evil here, a sense of foreboding location there _
and then let the tension build into a sort of `aha!' moment when
everything comes together.''
</P>
<P>
   Best buddy Stephen King is the master of such moments, Straub
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not completely consistent, but when he's at his best he
mesmerizes readers,'' Straub said, citing ``The Shining.'' ``His
greatest strength is an immense imagination and a willingness to
take risks. Too many so-called horror writers have a successful
book, then are plagued with the fear it might be a fluke. So they
do the same things again and again, (either) for that reason or
because their abilities are limited to that level.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Straub's current favorite scary writers is children's
author J.K. Rowling, whose Harry Potter series features all sorts
of demon lords and wizards-in-training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm overwhelmed by what she has managed to do,'' Straub said.
``You can tell she's writing from her heart. What she does in those
books is to offer a very playful version of the classic English
school/ghost story, a boy off at school facing all sorts of
supernatural challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Straub is less fond of the later vampire/horror novels of Anne
Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was once the possessor of a lush, tropical style,'' Straub
said. ``It seems to me her work has become rather earthbound, less
flowing. I think it may be because she's writing faster. It seems
she has a new novel out every few months.''
</P>
<P>
   Straub's own writing schedule is more deliberate, though not
sedate. After ``The Talisman,'' he went into a four-year slump,
trying to come up with an idea for a novel that would be as
well-received as ``Ghost Story'' without mimicking it. ``Koko,''
which concerned a troubled, murderous Vietnam veteran, was
painstakingly written and rewritten one page at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But having to do it that way made me a better editor of my own
work, which made me a better writer,'' Straub said. ``I think I'm
still getting better as a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Talisman II'' _ Straub expects a different title by the time
the book is published by Random House in fall 2001 _ is challenging
and fun, Straub said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stephen and I have a funny, affectionate relationship, and we
decided to write books together the third time we met, which was
1979,'' Straub said. ``This second collaboration came about because
Stephen remembered something I said while we were doing the first
one, an idea I had. Being an honorable guy, since it was my idea _
I don't want to say what it was _ Stephen called and said we should
write it together.''
</P>
<P>
   Though King's in-your-face style is markedly different than
Straub's cerebral approach, the two manage to mesh well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's working on it now while I'm traveling,'' Straub said.
``My last time out, I expanded his last two paragraphs by 15 pages.
We just see what the other one has done and work from there. For
`Talisman I,' I set the tone by writing the first 50 pages. Stephen
loved that tone and did his damndest to match it in the next 50
pages. We work in a spirit of respect for each other. It's
enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   The enjoyment of writing ``Talisman II'' is tempered only a
little bit by the fact that it will only make more people think of
him as a ``horror'' writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm resigned to it,'' he said. ``My secret goal, all these
years, has been to create a whole literary genre that is defined by
my name _ the `Peter Straub' style of book. But I could write a
straightforward novel about a young couple in suburbia, nothing
supernatural, and the first line of every review would begin,
`Horror writer Peter Straub.'''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
