<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     49ERS COACH CONTENT WORKING WITH WIDE RECEIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ Nearly half an hour after practice, with most
of the 49ers in the locker room, Jerry Rice runs 40-yard sprints
and Terrell Owens runs pass routes, catching balls from quarterback
Jeff Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys want to be nothing less than the best,'' said the
observer, George Stewart, in his first year as the 49ers wide
receivers coach.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, after four years as the team's special teams coach, has
been entrusted with the San Francisco 49ers' most high-profile
unit. And it's clear from the smile on Stewart's face as he watches
Rice and Owens that there are parts of the job that are going along
just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Six-year receiver coach Larry Kirksey left the team in the
off-season to accept the head coaching job at Texas A&AMP;M. Kirksey
had a quiet, relaxed style. Stewart, on the other hand, is the most
demonstrative coach on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, after then-49er Iheanyi Uwaezuoke roused the
Candlestick crowd with a thrilling punt return, Stewart ran onto
the field, bumped chests with Uwaezuoke and sent the player
sprawling on his backside.
</P>
<P>
   During drills at training camp at the University of the Pacific,
Stewart often chases down his players after passing plays _
congratulating them for catches or for executing especially sharp
routes.
</P>
<P>
   He's also ready to offer constructive criticism _ with all the
force of his basso profundo voice. Due to a coincidence in
scheduling, Stewart used to meet with his special teams players and
review game films on Mondays next door to the room where coach
Steve Mariucci meets with the press in his day-after-the-game press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   After one particularly dreadful performance, Stewart was letting
his players have it _ his booming voice clearly audible beyond the
walls. Mariucci was asked how special teams had played in that
week's game. ``Let's just listen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment you do something wrong, he's correcting it,'' said
J.J. Stokes, the third regular veteran in the corps. ``And the
moment you do something great, he's the first guy running down the
field to congratulate you.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has 12 years of coaching experience in the NFL and, in
Mariucci's words, ``is a perfect fit'' with the team's glamour
squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some personalities, we've got some very veteran,
productive guys in that meeting room,'' Mariucci said. ``I needed a
strong coach to deal with them and keep them playing hard every
single game. . . . I didn't want to put some brand-new, young
whipper-snapper in that spot. It would have been difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, meanwhile, has eased right into his new role. It helps
that he spent the last three seasons sitting in the wide receiver
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition has been an easy one because of Jerry Rice,
because of Terrell Owens and because of J.J. Stokes,'' Stewart
said. ``They're very respectful.''
</P>
<P>
   He says each player is different. And his best may be the
easiest to coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Jerry Rice the first still burns,'' Stewart said. ``He's
never comfortable. . . . He's self-motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of his job will be to revitalize Stokes, who is coming off
another disappointing season. He wants to get Stokes back to the
form that made him a first-round draft pick out of UCLA in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a major university, as a receiver, he carried his football
team,'' Stewart said. ``There's no other player that I've seen in
college carry his team like J.J. did. I want to get him back to
that level.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that much of Stokes' value goes unnoticed. ``Terrell
scores touchdowns and he dances,'' he said. ``Jerry is the best of
all time. . . . Meanwhile, there's nothing flamboyant about J.J.
Stokes.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has 10 wideouts in camp, including second-year man Tai
Streets, who missed most of last year with an Achilles injury, and
undrafted rookie Chafie Fields, a Penn State product who is having
a great camp.
</P>
<P>
   And Stewart does whatever works with each of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all different,'' Stewart said. ``You have to be a
psychiatrist, you have to be a little bit of a con artist, you have
to be someone that's truthful, you have to be it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart watches as Rice trots over to join Owens in running
routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to continue what's been laid before me here,'' he
said, ``and hopefully to improve upon it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
