<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3642 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-MIGRATION-$ADV     07-26 1767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MIGRATION-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO'S FOX TO PUSH FRESH VIEW OF AN OLD PROBLEM: UNDOCUMENTED
WORKERS
 &HT;    (1200&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With chart information attached at end of story.
 &HT;    With MIGRATION-SIDE-$ADV30.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, San Felipe Torres Mochas is
about 65 miles north of the city of Guanajuato.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FELIPE TORRES MOCHAS, MEXICO _ Maybe God had a reason for
letting their son bleed to death in south Texas.
</P>
<P>
   So believe the grieving parents of Eusebio de Haro, 22, one of
the latest victims in a dangerous game of cat-and-mouse claiming
the lives of scores of Mexicans trying to illegally enter the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why doesn't the United States open its borders? Every day
people are drowning or dying trying to cross the desert. Maybe
someone will listen to us now,'' said Pasiano de Haro, whose eldest
son was killed by a rancher's bullet May 13 after he asked for a
drink of water about 40 miles inside U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of migrants like de Haro, and the phenomenon of illegal
immigration in general, is probably the most complicated and
bitterly disputed of all the constants in U.S.-Mexico relations.
The delicate subject could be headed for an era of fresh
negotiation when Mexican president-elect Vicente Fox travels to the
United States for high-level talks in August.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans largely view the United States as a two-faced nation,
eager to use cheap undocumented labor but indifferent to the perils
faced by those who swim the Rio Grande or trek through wilderness
to get into the country. Many Americans believe that Mexicans have
developed an unhealthy reliance on seeking U.S. jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is the former governor of Guanajuato, the state where de
Haro was from and a top source of Mexican legal and illegal
migrants. On July 2 Fox made history by toppling Mexico's
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which has controlled the
presidency here for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   A charismatic leader who is promising sweeping change when he
takes office s to meet President Clinton next month as well as
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush and his Democratic
rival Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Fox reportedly would like to ask the United States to consider a
dramatic increase in the number of immigrant visas it grants to
Mexicans annually. Last year, about 75,000 Mexicans were granted
legal residency visas to the United States, more than any other
country.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Fox suggested in a recent ABC News interview, Mexico
and its North American neighbors should aim for opening borders
completely to a free flow of labor _ like the European Union _ in
as little as 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see some Americans sitting at their house, watching TV and
hearing me, Vicente Fox, saying we're going to open up that border
to people. Wow! That's a shock. But, I think we will have wisdom if
we have a long-term view,'' Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive, said
in English.
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign, Fox lashed out at the PRI for failing to
generate enough jobs and relying on the United States as a ``safety
valve'' to release the pressure of high unemployment at home.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox is also a pragmatist who says immigration will be
impossible to stop until the profound wage gap between Mexico and
the United States is closed.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a member of the conservative National Action Party,
aggressively reached out to migrants while he was governor and
visited them in the United States during his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Countless towns in Mexico rely on the estimated $6 billion
migrants send home annually, a sum that's more than Mexico spends
on primary and secondary education.
</P>
<P>
   Here in San Felipe Torres Mochas, signs of money from ``el
norte'' co-exist with tradition. Trucks with Texas, California or
North Carolina license plates rumble past adobe homes. Donkeys tied
to posts eat corn from barrels just down the street from
hand-painted signs advertising Internet hook-ups.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of a 1986 law that imposed tougher sanctions against
hiring illegal immigrants, people in Guanajuato's villages say
undocumented Mexicans are still routinely hired by American
employers from the Canadian border to the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio de Haro, in fact, worked at a Texas furniture factory
and an Arkansas construction site shortly before he died near
Brackettville, Texas, trying to return after being deported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latino immigrants are making the United States strong. Why
don't Americans just recognize that?'' said Pasiano de Haro.
</P>
<P>
   Represented by American lawyers, de Haro filed a $15 million
lawsuit this month against Sam Blackwood, the rancher who shot his
son in the leg after Eusebio and a companion stopped at his house
and asked for water after crossing the border.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwood is accused of pursuing the men after they were spurned
and shooting de Haro, who bled to death before a sheriff's deputy
arrived at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwood has been indicted on charges of deadly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In the Guanajuato village of Nuevo Valle de Moreno, where de
Haro's death hit home, townsfolk said virtually every family has at
least one member working in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had problems finding a job or been asked for an
identification card once since I started going to the United States
when I was 14. The problem is getting there,'' said 30-year-old
Rafael Rangel, who opened a tortilla shop with money he earned
doing construction in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 200 people from his village of only a couple
thousand, Rangel said, are currently in Little Rock mostly doing
construction, yard or restaurant work.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's more dangerous than ever for migrants. The U.S. Border
Patrol's strategy of trying to deter migrants by forcing them into
more isolated areas has resulted in an increase in deaths - more
than 160 so far just this year, according to Mexican officials.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers on the Arizona border have been accused of ``hunting''
migrants, unlawfully detaining them at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   But pressure is building among various quarters in the United
States to own up to America's continued addiction to immigrant
workers. Arizona Gov. Jane Hull acknowledged a labor shortage in
her state that Mexican workers could help fill. Several bills are
floating in Congress to legally allow in more foreign farm
laborers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic boom in the United States has made it possible to
recognize that migrant workers are contributing. Even labor
organizations like the AFL-CIO are talking positively about migrant
workers. This is a parting of the waters,'' said foreign affairs
expert Rafael Fernandez de Castro of the Autonomous Technical
Institute of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez de Castro is collaborating with the U.S.-based
Carnegie Endowment for International Peace to develop possible
options for admitting more legal Mexican workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't wait to talk about this. The United States
economy could decline and migrant workers could become
scapegoats,'' Fernandez de Castro said.
</P>
<P>
   The 68-union AFL-CIO broke this year with a traditional U.S.
labor position that immigrants have a negative impact on American
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The organization is advocating another amnesty _ similar to one
passed by Congress in 1986 _ for the estimated 6 million
undocumented workers in the United States. But it doesn't support
starting a guest-worker program with Mexico; unions fear a special
program would be riddled with abuses and suppress wages and labor
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a sense that in this day and age there should
be something better than the status quo,'' said University of
California at Davis migration specialist Phil Martin. ``The problem
is there is no consensus on what that should be.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s the U.S. labor movement fought to end the
``bracero'' program, which started importing Mexican workers to
work on U.S. farms during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The program allowed employers to pay Mexican workers less than
minimum wages and routinely subjected them to unsafe working and
living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Farm labor advocates also have a dim view of the existing H-2A
program, which imports a relatively small number of foreign farm
laborers.
</P>
<P>
   With an abundance of undocumented workers arriving on their own,
agricultural employers in the West haven't really needed the H-2A
program, which requires employers to prove they can't find
Americans or legal residents to hire.
</P>
<P>
   But fueled by a surge in the South, especially in North Carolina
and Georgia, the numbers of H-2A workers rose from about 15,000 in
1995 to a record high of close to 42,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Another program that admits non-agricultural seasonal laborers
is the H-2B program, which has a cap from all countries of about
66,000 a year. Mexicans have been recruited under this program to
work in stables in Kentucky, Christmas tree farms in North Carolina
and crab-packing operations in Maryland, where labor violations
have been alleged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our basic position is that guest-worker programs don't work.
What they do is provide employers with vulnerable workers with no
political or economic power,'' said Bruce Goldstein of the
Farmworker Justice Fund in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary foreign workers have no right to bring families and no
right to seek legal residency, Goldstein said. None of the current
proposals for more guest workers call for those reforms.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, now the top user of H-2A workers, labor
advocates say employers have had union organizers and social
workers arrested _ a violation of civil rights _ simply because
they tried to visit employees in mandated company-provided housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK to want to legalize the flow of labor,'' Goldstein
said. ``But the legal framework offered right now is terrible. Our
view is that if this country needs workers, they should be allowed
in as immigrants with the right to become citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://migration.ucdavis.edu/
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------------------
</P>
