<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3643 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIGRATION-SIDE-$ADV30     07-26 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIGRATION-SIDE-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MIGRATION'S CYCLE OF SEPARATION, ABANDONMENT TAXES MEXICAN
SOCIAL WORKER
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With MEXICO-MIGRATION-$ADV30.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAQUERIA, Mexico _ For Carlos Hernandez it was that long year
alone he spent in Atlanta that really helped him understand the
hardship Mexican migrants suffer.
</P>
<P>
   A professional who once ran his own publicity company, Hernandez
didn't see his wife or small children once the whole time he was in
``el norte,'' the north, working as a house painter to pay business
debts that soared after Mexico's peso crashed in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hernandez drives an old Volkswagen bug over rutted dirt
roads in Mexico's Guanajuato state, bringing information to
mountain villages that send a steady stream of migrant laborers to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like going back 40 years in time in some of these
villages. In some towns, the women and the men still sit on
separate sides of the church,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Old-fashioned Catholic faith is strong in the rugged farm
country of Guanajuato, and many men and women still abide by strict
roles defined by gender. Hernandez, who works for a unique state
aid program for migrants, tries to help the families of migrants
cope with the strain of separation and _ too often _ abandonment.
</P>
<P>
   He also tries to inform migrants of the hazards they face, what
their obligations are under U.S. law and their rights should they
be detained or threatened.
</P>
<P>
   In late May, Hernandez was in charge of receiving the body of
Eusebio de Haro, a 22-year-old undocumented migrant who was shot
and killed by a Texas rancher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sent back in a black plastic bag with a few pesos in
it,'' Hernandez said, still bristling at the indignity.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in Vaqueria, a village surrounded by rocky fields farmed
with crude wooden plows and horses, Maria Abundez asked Hernandez
to help find her 20-year-old son in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   He's the oldest of the 14 children Maria, who is only 38, gave
birth to.
</P>
<P>
   Genero Medina, whose father left for California when he was a
child, asked if Hernandez knew where to find him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called a number and he wouldn't talk to us,'' Medina, now
25, said.
</P>
<P>
   Without any money from her husband, Medina said his mother had
been reduced to selling cactus fruit in nearby city streets to help
maintain the small children she still has.
</P>
<P>
   One of her older daughters is married to a migrant who also
appears to have disappeared, and Carlos Hernandez fears the cycle
of abandonment will repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women who are left behind have it the worst of all,'' he said.
``They have low self-esteem. They get depressed and start drinking.
We've discovered a number of babies born with deformities because
their mothers drank.''
</P>
<P>
   Migration from Guanajuato began in the early part of the last
century and is so ingrained here now it is futile for social
workers to try to persuade people from going with mere words,
Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   The state _ which is home to Mexican president-elect Vicente Fox
_ is trying to develop home-grown jobs in remote villages by
offering investment help to start clothing factories that can
employ wives and other women left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these factories have failed to take off. But the state
is pushing on with the project, trying to provide jobs where
virtually none exist outside of farming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of how many generations there have been of people who
found that the United States was the best option,'' Hernandez said.
``Some think if you don't go, you're not a real man.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
