<HEADER>
A3646 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HEARST-HACIENDA-HNS &LR;      07-26 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-HACIENDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HEARST RETREAT IN CALIFORNIA MAY GO INTO NATIONAL PARK SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Press tycoon William Randolph Hearst's estate
known as the Hacienda on what is now Fort Hunter Liggett in
southern Monterey County, Calif., may be incorporated into the
federal park system under an unusual arrangement between the
National Park Service and the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst sold the 165,000-acre property, including the Hacienda,
to
</P>
<P>
   the Army in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Now the park service is interested in acquiring the Hacienda
</P>
<P>
   along with 76 other buildings and 100 acres on the base that the
Army has declared it no longer needs.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1992, when Fort Ord was deactivated, Fort Hunter Liggett
was used
</P>
<P>
   principally by the Fort Ord-based 7th Infantry Division. It is
now managed by the U.S. Army Reserve Command.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst used the Hacienda as a rustic ranch getaway from his much
more elaborate San Simeon estate in the coastal mountains near
Cambria in northern San Luis Obispo County. Both structures were
designed by famed architect Julia Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Joint use of an active military base is highly unusual, National
Park
</P>
<P>
   Service spokesman David Barna said. ``The only thing I can think
of quite like it is the Minuteman Missile National Historic Site in
South
</P>
<P>
   Dakota,'' which opened last November, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Army Reserve has rented 14 rooms and served
meals
</P>
<P>
   at the Hacienda. The rooms range in price from $125 for a suite
to $28 for the five plain ``cowboy rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   A National Park Service study to evaluate the Fort Hunter
Liggett property was authorized in a bill sponsored by Rep. Sam
Farr, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Next week the park service will hold public hearings in King
City and Salinas to determine what kinds of uses people want for
Fort Hunter Liggett. The post is located 22 miles southwest of King
City and 80 miles south of Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   One question the study aims to answer is whether the Park
Service will be able to use any of the oak valleys and hills where
the Army reservists now train.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great collaborative approach for public access,'' said
Holly
</P>
<P>
   Bundock, regional spokeswoman for the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   The fort was named for Lt. Gen. Hunter Liggett, who commanded
U.S.
</P>
<P>
   troops in the Philippines in 1916 and 1917 and in Europe during
World War I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
