r e BC-TV-JANINETURNER-840(2     07-26 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JANINETURNER-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANINE TURNER TACKLES NEW SERIES AS A SINGLE WORKING MOM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MIKI TURNER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The message button on the phone in my hotel
room was illuminated when I woke at 8:30 a.m. That seemed very odd
to me, since I hadn't heard the phone ring during the wee hours of
the morning. What I discovered, however, after listening to the
recording, was that the person who had left the message was Janine
Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Turner and I had been trying to hook up for three days without
success to talk about her new Lifetime series ``Strong Medicine,''
a hospital drama that premiered Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Our first attempt failed last Friday when Turner and her 2
1/2-year-old daughter, Juliette, decided at the last minute to
spend the weekend with their three horses, three dogs, eight cows
and two cats at their ranch near Fort Worth. The following Monday
was unsuccessful because of Turner's hectic work schedule. But at 6
o'clock Tuesday morning _ in atypical Hollywood fashion _ the
gracious Texan called from the set and left a rather lengthy
apology on my voice mail that was filled not with excuses, but
realities.
</P>
<P>
   She was a single working mother who, at that moment in time, was
simply overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough s'plainin' for me.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, she left a plethora of numbers where she could be
reached during the day and added that she had asked the hotel clerk
to put the call through so it wouldn't wake me.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty, smart and considerate, too.
</P>
<P>
   When Turner, 37, and I finally did talk, it wasn't for very
long. She was between takes and only had about 10 minutes before
her next scene. Initially, the conversation was all over the map,
like two old girlfriends who couldn't wait to share the significant
and insignificant events of the past few days. When she learned I
was from Ohio and not the Lone Star State, the Lincoln, Neb.,
native and longtime Euless, Texas, resident turned on the Texas
charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I've ever met from Ohio has really great skin,'' she
said. ``I bet you have beautiful skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow. Pretty, smart and psychic, too.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation soon turned to baby talk. Turner is more than a
little delighted that she's able to bring her daughter to work with
her each day. Little Juliette has a playroom on the set and her own
personal trailer that her mom bought for her in Texas. ``It's all
pink with flowers and birds and lots of little girl things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really blessed to be in this place at this time,'' she
said wistfully. ``It's been a little crazy. I'm in a new house out
here, but I'm not in it because everything's still a mess. That's
why I wanted to go home. I feel grounded when I'm back in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big believer that if you don't take time to fill up your
soul, then you are kind of running on empty. You have to take time
to refill your well. Life is an important thing. I need a normal
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Life has rarely been ``normal'' for Turner, who began modeling
and participating in beauty pageants when she was 3 years old. Her
mother, Janice, was a former beauty queen who encouraged Turner to
take advantage of her God-given assets.
</P>
<P>
   At 15, Turner and her family moved to New York, where she signed
with the prestigious Wilhelmina agency. Even then, she longed for
her Texas roots and ended up returning to Fort Worth to finish high
school. Just before her graduation, Turner was cast as Charlene
Tilton's best friend on ``Dallas.'' That gig led to starring roles
on the late-night soap ``Behind the Door'' and the daytime drama
``General Hospital,'' where she played Demi Moore's younger sister,
Laura Templeton.
</P>
<P>
   Her career really took off in the '90s when she was cast as the
strong-willed Maggie O'Connell in the cult classic ``Northern
Exposure,'' a role that earned her a Best Actress Emmy and three
Golden Globe nominations. Next came a plethora of
movies-of-the-week and a handful of feature films such as ``Young
Doctors in Love,'' Sylvester Stallone's ``Cliffhanger'' and ``Leave
it to Beaver,'' in which she played Beaver's mom, June Cleaver.
She'll next be seen on the big screen this fall in Robert Altman's
``Dr. T and the Women,'' with Richard Gere.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
