<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-JANINETURNER-2ndTa     07-26 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JANINETURNER-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 UNDATED: Richard Gere. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It hasn't all been limos and borrowed diamonds from Harry
Winston, however.
</P>
<P>
   Turner was nearly broke on more than one occasion and had
several failed romances, including highly publicized ones with
former fiance Alec Baldwin, baseball player Mark Grace and
Juliette's still unidentified father, a man whom Turner says left
her when she was seven months pregnant. To this day, the mystery
man has never seen his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the drama, Turner has always managed to bounce back very
nicely by Hollywood standards. That is, she has never needed to
spend time at the Betty Ford Clinic, hasn't been involved in any
hit-and-run auto accidents and hasn't had to do 200 hours of
community service for indecent exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has truly blessed me,'' she repeats softly into the phone.
``The greatest gift is my daughter. When I look at her, I see an
angel. She is so good-natured and happy. She's just a tremendous
blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Juliette and Turner's love of Texas were two of the biggest
reasons she wasn't keen on re-establishing her career on a West
Coast soundstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like pulling teeth getting me to leave Texas,'' she
said. ``I told my agent not to even send me any hour shows because
I wouldn't consider them. I didn't want to leave home. I love
everything about Texas. It's like the movie `A Trip to Bountiful.'
Remember when Geraldine Page just wanted to go touch the dirt? My
whole family is from Texas _ my roots, my heritage. I'm just a
Texan in my soul. It's everything _ the birds, the crickets, the
heat, the people and the dirt. It's real.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest concern was Juliette. I did not want to uproot her,
and I was terrified of the time factor. Doing an hour series
usually means you're working from sunrise to sunrise. But it all
worked out. I'm off each day by 6 p.m., and the producers
understand what it's like to be a single mom. Also, I made sure
that my contract included time to get back to Texas. We've already
been back twice this month. In my mind, we're commuting.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her reluctance to leave Texas for Los Angeles, the
strength of the material, the opportunity to work for and with
Whoopi Goldberg (one of the show's executive producers, along with
Tammy Ader) and the complexity of her character convinced Turner to
take a dose of ``Strong Medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect both Whoopi and Tammy,'' Turner said. ``Plus, the
script had a lot of colors. It would have been hard to turn this
down anyway, because the role is so wonderfully written.''
</P>
<P>
   The series chronicles the challenges, victories and
disappointments experienced by two very different women who are
forced to reconcile their differences when they combine their
talents to run a women's clinic in Philadelphia. Turner's
character, Dr. Dana Stowe, is a sort of stuck-up, no-nonsense
surgeon from a prestigious hospital whose bedside manner leaves
much to be desired. Her partner, Dr. Luisa Delgado (Rosa Blasi), is
a hands-on physician who sometimes breaks the rules at the women's
free clinic she runs in South Philly. The two become colleagues
when Stowe's hospital asks her to determine whether Delgado's
struggling clinic is worth investing in.
</P>
<P>
   With their polarizing approaches to medicine, Stowe and Delgado
just can't seem to get along. In the pilot, it takes a visiting
doctor (Goldberg, who will make occasional guest appearances) to
get the women to realize that not only do they have something
special to offer their patients, but they can also learn from each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Stowe is a strong woman who is driven, but she has a lot
of conflict,'' says Turner. ``She has a lot of levels and
complexities. I think if you sign on to be a doctor and do doctorly
things, it can be rather boring. But I've really grown to
appreciate physicians and their ability to be not only academic and
scientific, but their ability to cope with patients' emotions. It's
all very stimulating.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
