<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODBYE, READERS, AND THANK YOU
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Every Good-Bye Ain't Gone.''
</P>
<P>
   I read that line _ the title of an essay by one of my favorite
writers _ ages ago, it seems. But I've thought of little else for
the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   As I remember it, James Baldwin penned the autobiographical
essay some 30 years after his voluntary exile from America to
France to do the thing he loved most _ write.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin explained his leaving, saying he simply had no choice.
And while in his own eyes his departure stank of betrayal, leaving
was the only way of proving and redeeming his love.
</P>
<P>
   But every goodbye ain't gone. That is, in essence, the sum of my
feelings as I write my final column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   Only, I've not lost my love of writing. I see my move to the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution as an opportunity to build upon it.
That's exciting.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, my mind is full of those of you who have
responded to my words, lifting me to a place I had not imagined
when my ninth-grade English teacher, Mrs. Turnage, told me I was a
gifted writer. In a funny kind of way, though, it has been your
encouragement _ and sometimes your anger and tears _ that have fed
my yearning to improve my craft.
</P>
<P>
   I had not intended to become a columnist, and certainly not in
this space and on this day of the week. I was simply filling a void
that had been left by someone who had missed a deadline.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote about the burning of the church I grew up in on an old,
winding, dusty road in Smithdale, Miss. Months later, when the
piece was named a finalist in the statewide Katie competition for
journalists, I was drunk with joy.
</P>
<P>
   By then, I'd been smitten with this column-writing bug, churning
out one a week amid my many other assignments. You had responded to
my stories, but this was different. We were connecting in a way I
hadn't thought possible. As I revealed more about myself and my
loved ones in my columns, you told me about you and yours.
</P>
<P>
   I was so very grateful when Executive Editor Jim Witt officially
asked me to write for these pages, first on Thursdays and then on
Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   That was nearly 200 columns and four years ago. Good years.
</P>
<P>
   This place and this newspaper have been good stops for me. But I
see an opportunity to move so I can grow personally and
professionally. I see a chance to go home, so to speak, to return
to my Southern roots, the place that inspired and nurtured my
writing from when, as a little girl, I used to string words
together on white notebook paper.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I can't help but ache for the people and places I will
leave behind. There's great shopping in these parts. I've had a
wonderful church family. My children got a great start on their
educations here.
</P>
<P>
   You and many of my colleagues here have provided me with a
nurturing support system. I don't take that lightly.
</P>
<P>
   You've affirmed for me what I think I've always known: that
hunger, hatred and love are the same wherever you find them, and
that no matter where you go, there's always something or someone to
love, to win or lose, to mourn or celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   But every goodbye ain't gone, is it?
</P>
<P>
   I take with me much more than I had when I arrived in 1990 from
Sacramento, Calif., not the least of which are the many memories
I've stored up from the people God has put in my path. I hope I
leave behind as much as I have been given.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
