<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY:
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monsters on wheels
</P>
<P>
   WACO _ If it twists the tongue, consider how it would tie up
Texas turnpikes.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, fortunately, it is the trucking industry that is
bottlenecked in its quest to open the nation's interstate highways
to monster rigs.
</P>
<P>
   The push to have these huge trucks on our highways has been
stymied thus far by Congress, which has put a lid of 80,000 pounds
on trucks on the interstate system.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen states, mainly in the West, are unaffected because
regulations allowing larger trucks were grandfathered in when
Congress set the lid on truck weight several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer some of those states lobbied Texas to join in a
resolution urging Congress to ``harmonize'' state standards. The
proposal was to allow continuous travel of triple-trailer rigs
throughout the West, including Texas. Gov. George W. Bush declined.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the four western states that do not allow the
triple rigs are California, Arizona, New Mexico and Texas. They are
the states sharing the Mexican border with increasing truck
traffic. They don't need more trailers on the trucks they already
have crowding their highways.
</P>
<P>
   Bush certainly ought to keep up the roadblock. Polls show a vast
majority of Texans oppose the big-big trucks, with their
road-hogging presence, their slow stopping time and the heavy wear
and tear they bring to our roads.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall the Texas Transportation Commission scrapped
recommendations of an Interstate 35 task force to consider opening
the crucial arteries to three-trailer, 26-wheel mammoths.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has no business opening its highways to triple-trailer
trucks until it can create lanes that segregate semi rigs from
passenger vehicles. As it is, the trucking industry essentially
wants to introduce to Texas highways the equivalent of freight
trains without rails.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible for states to seek exemptions from the weight
limit. Maine this year asked for it, and Idaho wants to do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Texas should steer clear of that idea. And so must Congress
drive with caution on the matter of increasing truck size. A bill
seeking to increase the cap on truck weights on interstates to
90,000 pounds has languished on the shoulder, unable to advance
through congressional committee.
</P>
<P>
   On the shoulder is where it should stay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
