<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BACH-ONLINE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DIGITAL LIBRARY UNITES BACH'S WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GLENN GARELIK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even among serious students of Bach, only the most privileged
ever hope to examine the composer's handwritten scores.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some of the manuscripts, once largely collected at
the Staatsbibliothek repository in Berlin, were scattered among
more than half a dozen archives after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars who received permission from those archives have had to
settle for viewing the manuscripts on black-and-white microfilm,
with its attendant vexations, or on photographs of microfilm; the
ink's corrosive effect and the ravages of more than 250 years have
left the originals perilously fragile.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, July 27, using IBM technology and timed to the
250th anniversary of Bach's death, the Staatsbibliothek and six
other repositories of Bach manuscripts are inaugurating online
access to some of the composer's documents, scanned and digitized
from high-quality color slides.
</P>
<P>
   The Bach Digital Library will make available a Web version
(www.bachdigital.org) and a version with a resolution so fine that
it can be used for study by specialists. To access the
high-resolution version, musicologists would still need to file a
request with the institutions.
</P>
<P>
   With clarity and color close to that of the originals, these
digital collections will have certain advantages even over visits
to the archives that hold the actual works, said Stephen Crist,
secretary of the American Bach Society and a professor of music at
Emory University in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   One example would be the score of the ``Well-Tempered Clavier,''
where one part of the original is in the Staatsbibliothek and
another is at the British Library in London. The Bach Digital
Library will eventually allow a visitor to view the entire score.
</P>
<P>
   The digital collection will also reduce the effort involved in
studying the manuscripts. Michael Marissen, a professor of music at
Swarthmore and author of several books on Bach, called it ``a great
improvement over those challenging-to-negotiate,
motion-sickness-inducing, hard-to-read, black-and-white microfilms
in research collections.''
</P>
<P>
   Since some of the musical pieces contain gigabytes of
information, and because of the high cost of digitization, the
manuscripts will not be housed on a single server, said the
project's technological leader, Volker Susok, of IBM Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Digital Library will constitute a ``lookup
service'' that contains general information and links but reroutes
requests to access individual pieces to servers at the institutions
that house the originals.
</P>
<P>
   To mark the start of the project, the Web site will post the
digitized image of the 180-page score of the ``Mass in B-Minor''
while television and radio stations broadcast a performance of the
masterpiece from the Thomaskirche, one of four Leipzig churches
that Bach provided with music from 1723 to his death in 1750.
Listeners will be able to follow along in the score.
</P>
<P>
   As for other pieces, Susok said, the library will have MP3
streaming capabilities, so that visitors to the Web site will not
just see the score of a composition but also be able to listen to
and compare sections of its performance under different conductors.
</P>
<P>
   The Staatsbibliothek is also contributing half a dozen more of
its several hundred Bach holdings to the digital collection,
including the Brandenburg Concerto No. 3. The Bach-Archive in
Leipzig is providing the program that accompanied the 1734 premiere
of the Christmas Oratorio _ a booklet containing the text of the
work in German and notes about the performance. A couple of
cantatas are being provided by the Bachakademie in Stuttgart.
</P>
<P>
   The project's other academic partners include the Saxon State
and University Library in Dresden, the British Library and the
Bibliotheka Jagellionska in Krakow, Poland.
</P>
<P>
   For scholars accustomed to reading aging microfilm and for
first-year students who keep their Bach in the piano bench, the
digital archive provides something else: a glimpse of music in the
master's own hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to their scholarly usefulness, the original Bach
sources are very beautiful, both for the artistry of Bach's
calligraphy and for the sheer immediacy of ink on paper,'' said
Daniel Melamed, a professor of music at Indiana University. ``The
closest we can come, physically at least, to Bach's creation of
this music and its first performance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
