<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3662 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-LATEBLOOMER-TEX     07-26 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATEBLOOMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 98, HE LEARNED TO READ. AT 102, HE'S BUILDING A NEW HOME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The sound of hammering and sawing rings out loudly on
Starks Avenue, a quiet street of old homes and vacant lots just a
few blocks from Malcolm X Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   George Dawson, 102 years old and still capable of walking at a
good clip, stands to one side of the door and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come right on in, come right on in,'' he says, holding out a
hand to his visitors in the familiar after-you gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Inside there are several men working, one sitting on the
fireplace in the living room, one out in the one-car garage. Dawson
enters, walking through the living room to the big bedroom at the
end of a short hallway. He looks out the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna be different, a better life,'' he says, looking
around at the room where he will put his bed, and out to the back
yard, where he plans to plant a garden. ``It's nice _ it's like a
brand new world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna have tomatoes and okra and everything,'' he says,
walking to the front porch and looking out at the lawn, which is
currently covered with building materials. ``And I'm gonna have a
big dinner right out here.''
</P>
<P>
   The world is full of proud new-home owners, but few have waited
as long as Dawson. You may remember his remarkable story: He
learned to read when he was 98, and then collaborated with
co-author Richard Glaubman to write his autobiography, ``Life Is So
Good,'' published last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson appeared on ``Oprah,'' met dignitaries and had one
journalist after another profile him. He lived in a four-bedroom
former duplex that lacked central heat and air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hot in the summer and cold in the winter,'' Dawson said
earlier this day in the lunchroom of the Lincoln Instructional
Center, where he polishes his reading and writing skills five days
a week. ``The foundation was going down _ termites were eating it
up. It was dilapidated. I couldn't get it fixed. The roof was
holding the house together.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting nearby, his son George Dawson Jr. takes up the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a geat deal of leaking,'' he says, noting that the
home was 40 or 50 years old and that his father had lived there for
about the last 15 years. ``The first idea was to remodel the house,
but everybody said it would cost more to repair it than to get a
new one built.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Gary Krupkin, who describes himself as a ``self-absorbed
lawyer'' and a big George Dawson fan. His wife, Roxanne, had
suggested he read ``Life Is So Good''; he did, and was so impressed
that he went and saw Dawson at a reading. He met Dawson, who
autographed a copy of the book, and Glaubman.
</P>
<P>
   Glaubman said that Dawson had never lived in a new house and
asked if Krupkin could help. ``I said sure. George is a cool guy,''
Krupkin said. ``Here's the story of a guy who saw the absolute
worst our democracy can deal out to anybody, and he has such a
positive outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   Krupkin's own home near White Rock Lake had been built three
years ago by the Starks Building Co. He contacted proprietor David
Starks and arranged a meeting with the Dawson family.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to use advance royalties from Dawson's book to fix
the old house, but now the money went into new construction. Dawson
moved his possessions (including his Bibles) into his son's house
in late April; his home was torn down and construction began in
early May.
</P>
<P>
   ``George didn't even have a bank account before he got his
advance,'' says Glaubman, a teacher who lives in Washington state
and first heard about Dawson through a reprint of a story published
in the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. ``He would cash his Social
Security checks at the grocery store.''
</P>
<P>
   The new brick house is 1,200 square feet; it has three bedrooms,
two bathrooms, central air and heat, a gas log fireplace and gas
stove. George Jr. says one of the bedrooms will be used as a
library, dedicated to the plaques his dad has received and the
photos that have been taken of him with famous people.
</P>
<P>
   Starks says the home should be completed around Aug. 10.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Krupkin and Glaubman are looking for donations
of furniture and appliances; construction of the new home pretty
much exhausted the royalty advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `George, we can move you anywhere you want,' and he
said he wanted to live there,'' Krupkin said. ``And any company
that donates something to his house, I'll make sure they get an
autographed copy of his book. He's shown kids in that neighborhood
they can be a success _ that's what this country needs. The world
should know this story.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawson says that moving into a new home is ``a fine thing to
do'' and that it'll be ``very nice'' once he's in and settled, and
that he hopes to live there the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear that kids are still what he cares about the
most; he still reserves his biggest smiles for them, like the
little boy he encountered in the lunchroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people just give up,'' Dawson said softly. ``They can
say, `Well, he was an old man but he kept on going.' No man should
give up as long as he's able to move. Every school I've been to, I
give 'em my view of life. I want to give somebody an understanding
of my living.''
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX:
</P>
<P>
   To help out:
</P>
<P>
   Dallas lawyer Gary Krupkin is coordinating donations for George
Dawson's new home. If you would like to help, call (214) 546-4279.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
