<P>
   INTERNET-PRIVACY (Washington) _ After years of piecemeal
proposals to safeguard personal information on the Internet,
leading senators, including John McCain, unveil legislation that
could dramatically boost the rights of consumers in cyberspace. The
bill would require commercial Web sites that collect personally
identifiable information to give consumers a prominent notice on
how that data will be used. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   SF-AIDS-FUNDING (Washington) _ Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., vows
to fight a 25 percent cut in San Francisco's federal AIDS funding
that unanimously passed the House early Wednesday. ``We cannot
accept the premise that our region should have to absorb this kind
of cut,'' Pelosi said, estimating that the city will lose $6.5
million over a five-year period if the measure is enacted. By JUDY
HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CUTS (Washington) _ President Clinton is expected to
challenge Republican leaders in Congress to deliver their tax-cut
legislation so he can veto the bills before the Republican National
Convention begins next week. By LETITIA STEIN.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CHENEY (Chicago) _ Vice President Al Gore and his
Democratic allies say Dick Cheney was often on the wrong side of
issues important to minorities when he was serving in Congress.
Texas Gov. George W. Bush tapped Cheney as the Republican vice
presidential hopeful. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY-PENTAGON (Washington) _ While Dick Cheney is best known
for his role in helping plan the 1991 Persian Gulf War, the former
defense secretary's cancellation of a $57 billion aircraft program
shows he was willing to make unpopular decisions and defy political
stereotypes. In canceling the plane, Cheney ordered the death of
the most expensive weapon program ever terminated by the Pentagon.
By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPBELL-ABORTION (Washington) _ Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., in
a uphill battle to unseat Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein, says he
will speak out strongly next week on the pro-choice side of the
debate over the abortion plank at the Republican National
Convention. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Casper, Wyoming) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and running
mate Dick Cheney visit Cheney's home state of Wyoming. By R.G.
RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HELEN-THOMAS (Washington) _ Where is Tipper Gore these days?
She's certainly not active in her husband's presidential campaign.
Instead, she's been hiking in the high Sierras and striving to keep
her life in perspective. It would be ``fabulous'' to be first lady,
but politics is only ``part of my life,'' she says. By HELEN
THOMAS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ While George W. Bush and Al Gore
await the cues that will summon them to stage center as America's
next president, Bill Clinton is traveling and performing as if he
were beginning rather than ending his tenure. You can bet that
he'll be active right up to Jan. 20. Clearly, he has no intention
of sneaking secretly out the back door of the White House. By
ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
