<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-RAYSCANNER-900(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANNER-CONTROVERSY) 
 CT SCANNERS CAN DETECT SOME HEART-LUNG PROBLEMS AND CANCERS IN
EARLY STAGES
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanied by X-RAY SCANNER-PATIENTS and X-RAY (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CAROLYN POIROT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``All that white stuff'' that showed up on his CT scan caught
Clint David totally off guard.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the 45-year-old Dallas lawyer was running 30
miles a week, lifting weights and playing tennis when an ultrafast
electron-beam X-ray scan indicated significant calcification in his
coronary arteries. An earlier exercise stress test gave no hint of
heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The same ultrafast CT (computed tomography) scanner at the
Cooper Clinic in Dallas found a tiny lung cancer _ too small to see
on a conventional chest X-ray _ in Annette Melton's right bronchus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had absolutely no suspicion at all,'' says Melton, 53, who,
after her doctor diagnosed high cholesterol, had put herself on a
low-fat diet, launched a walking-running fitness regime and started
taking vitamins with extra antioxidants.
</P>
<P>
   Her cholesterol had continued to climb despite her efforts, and
Cooper suggested an electron-beam scan to check whether the
cholesterol was damaging her coronary arteries.
</P>
<P>
   No heart disease was found, but the radiologist pointed out the
tiny mass in her lung.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to know if I smoked or had ever smoked or had asthma
or bronchitis, but I had not,'' says Melton, a marketing executive
for Compaq Computers in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   She took the report to a pulmonologist, who did another scan and
found the same 10-millimeter tumor. He did a biopsy and diagnosed a
low-grade malignancy known as a carcinoid. It was surgically
removed Jan. 11, 1999, and there have been no signs of cancer
since.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thoracic surgeon told me afterward that he had to give Dr.
Cooper an A-plus for finding that tumor. I only went in because I
was worried about my cholesterol,'' Melton says. ``I had no reason
to suspect lung cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Most hospitals and some diagnostic radiology centers now have
the powerful new X-ray machines that can detect coronary artery
disease as well as lung cancer and other abnormal lesions in the
chest and abdomen much earlier than regular X-rays. But not many
doctors are using them for general screening, at least not in this
area.
</P>
<P>
   Some imaging centers in other parts of the country are heavily
promoting spiral CT scans as noninvasive screening tests for lung
cancer. Smokers and former smokers who know they are at risk are
reportedly flocking to the centers that advertise the CT scans for
as little as $300.
</P>
<P>
   David says he only got a scan as part of his annual physical
because there is heart disease in his family.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the suspicious scan, a more sensitive thallium
stress test (in which a radioactive chemical is injected into a
vein before you walk on a treadmill or pedal a bicycle in order to
detect which areas of the heart may be damaged) showed a 90 percent
blockage in one of his arteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable. I walked into the Cooper Clinic expecting
congratulations for being in such good shape and left with an
appointment with a heart surgeon,'' David says. Three days later,
he was in the hospital undergoing balloon angioplasty to open the
clogged blood vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Both the spiral CT scanner and the electron-beam CT scanner use
ultrafast computers to analyze data from the 3-D images they make.
They are so quick, there is little distortion from breathing or
other movement, so they can detect very slight abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cooper Clinic, its two $2 million ultrafast electron-beam
scanners screen about 200 patients each week. Screenings and
medical interpretation cost $599 and are usually not covered by
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have picked up 80 malignancies including 33 kidney tumors _
renal cell carcinomas _ and six lung cancers in asymptomatic
patients, long before they developed any symptoms. We've found
hundreds of people with unsuspected coronary artery disease,'' says
Cooper, medical director of the Cooper Clinic and Aerobics Center.
</P>
<P>
   While the machines' ability to capture 3-D images is clearly an
advancement for medical science, patients should be aware that
another critical factor in these screenings is the experience of
the radiologist who interprets the scans. It's important to
consider where consumers are getting the scans _ and who's reading
them.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
