<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWECONOMY-INSURE-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE COMPANIES REDUCE RISK OF ONLINE BUSINESS DEALINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Wednesday, July 26, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 (Note to editors: Lia in lede is cq) 
 By DAVID RESS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED _ You've done it the Internet way: Met your customer,
shown your stuff, made your pitch, talked your terms, nailed your
sale -- all online.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as your million pounds of widgets sails toward Hong Kong,
the doubts hit: How do you know whom you're dealing with? What's
the risk that you're going to get burned?
</P>
<P>
   As e-commerce -- especially business-to-business dealing --
continues its explosive growth, these questions worry more and more
business executives. Insurers are stepping forward with some
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk is not just a 12-year-old in a black T-shirt with a
ring in his nose,'' said Emily Freeman, senior vice president of
Marsh Risk and Insurance Services. ``It's not just hackers.''
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out how to deal with the risk is critical if e-commerce
is to grow -- just as an idea from the gang at Mr. Lloyd's London
coffee shop made it easier for 18th century merchants to think
about sending fleets of vessels around the world. The men who
created the Lloyds of London insurance market reassured ship owners
by promising to cover losses from shipwrecks, in return for an
upfront payment. Today, Lloyds is the world's largest insurance
market, where the biggest risks around are covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurance is about facilitating commerce,'' Freeman said.
``That's why there's Lloyds of London.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurers are developing a number of ways to help companies deal
with the risks of the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, a new breed of insurance expert can consult with
companies about computer security, ranging from how to keep the
power from surging to how to keep the black-shirted 12-year-olds
out. They know about software that helps businesses learn who they
are dealing with online -- before that million pounds of widgets
heads for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   There's also an insurance-style approach to the risk that a
customer won't buy online. A surety bond Marsh is starting to
market gives e-tailers insurance that customers will be reimbursed
if the product isn't what was promised, wasn't delivered as
promised or wasn't a fair value. E-tailers who have the coverage
can post a logo on their Web pages. One of the selling points of
such programs is the hope that an easily visible guarantee will
encourage online shopping.
</P>
<P>
   More and more specialized policies are hitting the market,
agents and brokers say.
</P>
<P>
   With the rash of computer viruses in the past few years, for
instance, insurance companies have scrambled to offer coverage for
losses caused when Web sites crash.
</P>
<P>
   After hackers attacked some of the Web's most popular sites,
including Amazon.com, eBay.com and Buy.com, in February, shutting
them down for hours and costing untold millions of dollars, more
and more companies started looking for insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers are looking at a slew of other problems e-businesses
could face -- issues such as copyrights, libel and liability for
advertising and links to other pages.
</P>
<P>
   Kae Lovaas, vice president-technology of the St. Paul Cos., told
the Cyber Risk 2000 conference earlier this year that as the
Internet develops, businesses may start fighting over the market by
suing one another over copyright, patent and trademark issues.
</P>
<P>
   While St. Paul offers specialized coverage for high-tech
businesses, Lovaas said she believes such insurance for
intellectual property claims will be built into standard business
policies within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Chubb Corp., for instance, this year launched a new Internet
insurance policy that covers companies against claims for libel or
misrepresentation that could arise from Web sites, e-mail and other
online communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more companies disseminate information to the public via
Web sites and other media ... commercial businesses now have the
same liability exposures once reserved only for book publishers,
broadcasters and advertising agencies,'' said Leib Dodell, media
and intellectual property underwriting manager at Chubb.
</P>
<P>
   Chubb's approach is an ``all-risks'' coverage for Internet
activity, rather than the approach some insurers have been adopting
of coverage for specific perils.
</P>
<P>
   Dodell said Chubb believes it has a better approach, ``given the
uncertainty of the legal rules governing the Internet and the types
of legal claims that will be generated by Internet activity.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Because judges and legislators are still trying to figure out
the best rules for e-commerce, it is tough for insurers to decide
how much they need to charge e-businesses to cover legal liability.
</P>
<P>
   While insurers are pretty good about predicting how much drivers
will cost them in any given year and charging them that much plus
an allowance for a profit, there's not much of a track record for
them to use to set a price for e-commerce coverage.
</P>
<P>
   So for e-commerce, insurers don't look so much at claims
histories or legal judgments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at best practices,'' Freeman said -- that is, at what
the experts say is the way to fend off risks, ranging from hackers
to power surges to mysterious shoppers from Hong Kong. If a company
is making an effort, some insurers would be inclined to cover the
risk, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds hard, but some of this stuff is pretty basic,''
Freeman said. ``You monitor traffic on your site. You have intruder
alerts. Your staff isn't putting stickies with their passwords on
their desktops.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------- (David Ress is a staff writer with The Star-Ledger
of Newark, N.J.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
