u a BC-NUKE-DETERRENCE-NEWHO     07-26 2269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-DETERRENCE-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUCLEAR DETERRENCE, SECURITY UNDERPINNING FOR DECADES, MAY BE DYING
DOCTRINE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Wednsday, July 26, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With a graphic charting world powers' nuclear stockpile
and U.S. spending on strategic forces by year, and four photos, of
Trevor Foyston (NNS1), of Shad Skeen with the USS Henry Jackson's
missile tubes (NNS2), the Jackson's conning tower (NNS3) and
missile launch specialists Gregg Johnson and John Jenssen (NNS4)
 (Note to editors: Lia in lede is cq) 
 By DAVID WOOD  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE USS HENRY JACKSON -- Nestled snugly in the vertical
launch tubes of this black dreadnought gliding stealthily 600 feet
beneath the Pacific Ocean are 24 intercontinental missiles humming
with power and packed with thermonuclear warheads. At the turn of
three keys, the Jackson can begin launching enough destruction to
obliterate 1,400 cities the size of Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   Four U.S. ballistic missile submarines like the Jackson are
always on patrol. They lurk for months beneath remote seas, ready
on 15 minutes' notice to launch the weapons that could end
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only think about this every once in a while, but we have
the power to make it so we can't go home anymore,'' said Petty
Officer Trevor Foyston, 29, plotting a navigation course in the
Jackson's control room.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, this extraordinary power was justified in
apocalyptic terms: The United States faced a mortal enemy in the
Soviet Union. Each superpower's deadly weapons deterred the other
from attacking.
</P>
<P>
   But today, nuclear deterrence -- the underpinning of American
security for half a century -- may be a dying doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   What threat could warrant, these days, a nuclear retaliatory
strike that would incinerate millions of innocent bystanders? What
crisis should be resolved by risking ``making it so we can't go
home''?
</P>
<P>
   Even though deterrence has been the fundamental principle of
American security for 50 years, it is only a theory. No one knows
if it ``worked'' during the Cold War, or whether the nuclear powers
escaped annihilation through sheer luck. And no one knows that it
can work in a less stable world, one where emerging nuclear powers
are led by unpredictable, and in some cases arguably irrational,
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Deterrence, experts say, is in the eye of the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about nuclear deterrence is, we could have redwood
logs in here,'' said Senior Chief Petty Officer James Matthews, a
Jackson crewman, rapping his knuckles on the sub's fat steel
missile tubes.
</P>
<P>
   And with few solid facts, debate among policymakers seems to
ricochet from the far corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The likely consequences of nuclear war have no politically,
militarily or morally acceptable justification,'' former Air Force
Gen. Lee Butler, who retired in 1994 as commander of U.S. nuclear
warfighting forces, said at a 1998 press conference. ``The threat
to use nuclear weapons is indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice idea -- in a perfect world, say defenders of deterrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until the introduction of nuclear weapons, you could afford
to lose a war. Nukes changed that fundamentally,'' said Jack
Mendelsohn, a former U.S. arms negotiator who is executive director
of the Lawyers Alliance for World Security Laws, a pro-arms-control
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deterrence became the inevitable nature of relations between
nuclear states; it wasn't a choice,'' Mendelsohn said. ``And I
don't see any significant change. Nuclear states will manage their
relations by the threat of devastating retaliation, which is
deterrence.''
</P>
<P>
   No such arguments, pro or con, are heard aboard the Jackson. For
her 165-man crew, nuclear deterrence theory translates into a hard,
simple reality -- a monotony of six-hour watches, emergency drills
and launch rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   For 70 days at a time, the Jackson remains hidden, receiving
basic messages but transmitting not a word. The only people who
know its location are the men on the boat itself.
</P>
<P>
   America's force of 18 ballistic missile submarines is
impressive, as are their crews. But all U.S. nuclear forces sat out
an early test of nuclear deterrence in the new, post-Cold War
security environment.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fall of 1990, as tens of thousands of U.S. and allied
combat troops gathered in Saudi Arabia for the war with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about the potential for a devastating Iraqi chemical
attack, President George Bush and his top advisers met to thrash
out a policy to persuade Iraq's Saddam Hussein not to use chemical
weapons, and on how to respond if he did.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the United States issued a veiled warning. But no
explicit threat of nuclear retaliation was made or even considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among ourselves, we said if he used chemicals we would not
respond with nuclear weapons,'' said Brent Scowcroft, who was
Bush's national security adviser. Instead, the White House would
have intensified non-nuclear air strikes against Baghdad, Scowcroft
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush administration feared that the coalition against Iraq,
which included several Arab countries, would shatter if the United
States menaced a fellow Arab country with nuclear weapons. In other
words, the threat was politically unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States practices coalition warfare in the future,
as most experts expect, it might face similar political constraints
on its nuclear deterrence doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is targeting. In the case of Iraq, Scowcroft
said, it was hard to imagine a target that was both of immense
value to Saddam and would not involve killing a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   The same problem -- the balance of moral and strategic concerns
-- fuels arguments over how many nuclear weapons the United States
needs. No one can say with precision what will deter a foe. As a
result, some maintain, the Pentagon has taken the conservative
course, aiming too many weapons at too many targets and risking too
many civilian lives.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Blair, a former U.S. nuclear missile launch officer who is
president of the nonpartisan research organization the Center for
Defense Information, said the Pentagon believes that 3,000 nuclear
weapons, from the total U.S. stockpile of 5,500 weapons, are
necessary to ``deter'' Russia. ``Hundreds'' more, he said, have
targets in China, Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 1,100 weapons are aimed at Russian nuclear arms
sites. Many of the rest, he said, are unnecessarily targeted on the
disintegrating Russian army and on deteriorating factories idled by
the crumbling Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said the United States could deter Russia with ``far
fewer'' weapons by targeting only its most critical weapons. Many
strategists agree. But the Pentagon has historically refused to
discuss its targeting plan in detail.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the incident with Iraq suggests that Saddam was
considered so unpredictable, it was hard to know what would deter
his use of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a mystery why he didn't use them. We can only
guess,'' Scowcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   That issue -- precisely what it takes to deter a potential
adversary -- is also likely to become more complex in the decades
ahead. Clearly, the relatively stable U.S.-Soviet nuclear standoff
has evolved into a less stable situation, experts say. Consider the
following:
</P>
<P>
   -- The deterioration of Russia's non-nuclear military forces has
made it more reliant on nuclear missiles as the weapon of first
choice rather than last resort, said Pennsylvania State University
political scientist Steven J. Cimbala.
</P>
<P>
   -- U.S. officials believe Russia's 6,000 nuclear weapons are not
as tightly controlled as they once were, reopening fears about
accidental or unauthorized launch that deterrence couldn't prevent.
</P>
<P>
   -- The United States and Russia each keep about 2,000 of their
nuclear weapons on hair-trigger alert. Inside of 30 minutes, these
weapons could be launched and would begin detonating with the power
of 100,000 Hiroshima bombs, according to Blair.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Missile and nuclear warhead technology is spreading virtually
unchecked, according to a September 1999 Central Intelligence
Agency assessment. Even non-government groups could acquire nuclear
weapons, the CIA said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, India and Pakistan now brandish nuclear weapons
without benefit of the art of crisis management and restraint that
the United States and Soviet Union learned during their long
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   How deterrence will work in this environment is in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``As nuclear weapons and ballistic missiles spread to more and
more countries, you're going to have more and more adversaries who
understand each other's cultures less and less,'' said Cimbala.
</P>
<P>
   Baker Spring, arms analyst at the conservative Heritage
Foundation, said the United States and the Soviet Union during the
Cold War were ``like two scorpions in a bottle -- the dynamic was
clear and reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   But with six or eight nuclear powers, ``the dynamic has
changed,'' he said. ``Deterrence clearly has its limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Butler, the retired Air Force general, now declines to speak
publicly as he works behind the scenes toward a total abolition of
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But he has said that deterrence relies on a perfect knowledge of
how the other side thinks. And American understanding of Moscow, in
his view, was dangerously far from perfect.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, senior commanders like Butler studied the
personalities of their Soviet counterparts by name and habits, and
tracked their whereabouts every day. Soviet military writings were
dissected and discussed.
</P>
<P>
   But Butler, in a March 1999 article in Resurgence magazine,
wrote that this was all in vain.
</P>
<P>
   ``How was it that we subscribed to a strategy that required near
perfect understanding of an enemy from whom we were deeply
alienated and largely isolated?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than understanding each other precisely, he described the
two Cold War superpowers as ``groping fearfully in a fog of mutual
misperception.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts insist that there is a useful distinction between
``rational'' enemies, who can be trusted in a crisis, and those who
are irrational.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, Virginia Republican and chairman of the Senate
Armed Services Committee, said during a committee hearing May 23
that nuclear deterrence works between Russia and the United States
because there is in both countries ``a rational framework of
decision-makers.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that North Korea, Iraq and others are unpredictable
and ``irrational'' and thus cannot be deterred with nuclear
threats. That is why the United States must build missile defenses,
Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   A dissenting view holds that ``rogue'' leaders may be
unpleasant, but can be understood and deterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly Saddam Hussein is not irrational; he just has
different values and priorities,'' said Jerrold Post, a career
analyst at the Central Intelligence Agency who established the
CIA's Center for Analysis of Personality and Political Behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Post now directs the political psychology program at George
Washington University's School of International Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people talk about the irrationality of `rogue leaders,' I
often think they mean individuals who refuse to have their foreign
policies adhere to the ideas of the West,'' Post said. ``There is a
tendency to demonize those whom we don't understand clearly, and
that is unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of nuclear deterrence is entangled in another
issue.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of strategists believe that a key American goal
-- keeping other countries from ``going nuclear'' -- will be
unreachable as long as the United States clings to its own huge
nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason that the ranks of the nuclear abolitionists
were joined in 1994 by retired Air Force Gen. Charles Horner, who
commanded U.S. and allied air forces during the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard for us to say to North Korea, `You are
terrible people, you're developing a nuclear weapon,' when we have,
oh, 8,000 of them,'' Horner explained during a 1994 press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   None of this gets much conversation in the officers' wardroom or
the mess decks of the Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``These issues really aren't my business,'' said the Jackson's
skipper, 41-year-old Cmdr. Paul D. Ims Jr., whose cropped blond
hair and wire-rim glasses give him a boyish look. ``My business is
to be out here and to be a deterrent at the highest level of
readiness I can provide.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to firing the missiles, at least in practice, the
procedure is so intense and mechanical that it leaves little room
for introspection.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought when he squeezed the trigger that in an
actual launch would send 800,000 tons of thermonuclear explosive
streaking toward human targets, Lt. Randy Tupas, strategic weapons
officer, looked blank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking about anything, it was just sort of
automatic,'' he said. ``It's a reflex.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
