<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUGAR27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS URGED TO BUY LAND TO HELP ENVIRONMENT, SUGAR GROWERS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Buy land, not sugar.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Everglades Coalition urged Congress to do
Wednesday in response to the market surplus of sugar and the
decrease in its price.
</P>
<P>
   At a Senate Agriculture Committee hearing, the coalition, which
includes 42 environmental, civic and recreational organizations,
suggested that the federal government purchase marginally
profitable sugar-growing land in the Everglades Agricultural Area
instead of purchasing extra sugar to reduce the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition also urged Congress to phase out the sugar price
support program when it considers reauthorization of the farm bill
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal sugar price support program inflates the profits
of sugar farms in the EAA, distorts the economy of sugar making,
and provides an incentive for overproduction while destroying one's
of the nation's most valuable natural resources,'' said Shannon A.
Estenoz, co-chair of the Everglades Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government decisions to buy sugar simply encourages the growth
of the sugar surplus, and _ as an alternative _ the government
should choose to purchase land in the EAA, which would take the
land permanently out of sugar production and make it less
destructive to the Everglades.''
</P>
<P>
   Estenoz suggested that if the program was eliminated, ``marginal
sugar growing lands that are only profitable to farm because of
price supports would likely come out of production, thus reducing
the pollution into the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Sen. Dick Lugar, R-Ind., said Congress needs
to consider the option of making further land purchases from
willing sellers in the EAA with the savings that might result from
reforming the sugar program.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Farm Bill included $200 million to purchase lands in
the EAA to help restore the Everglades, Lugar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Everglades are dying because the natural flow of water has
been disrupted, and water that could be used to restore the natural
environment is being flushed out to sea,'' Lugar said. ``I believe
that sugar policy reform can play an important role in Everglades
restoration.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark D. Perry, executive director of the Florida Oceanographic
Society, told the panel that sugar growers have caused damage to
the Everglades through the diversion of the natural flow of water
and the introduction of pollutants such as phosphorus and
pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historiified.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., said the United States must support
sugar growers with more money or risk losing the industry
altogether, and that opponents of the sugar price support program
are referring to incorrect world sugar prices in their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The European Union spends 10 times more than the U.S. on the
sugar industry, and it is no wonder that they have gobbled up our
market share,'' Conrad said. ``Furthermore, those who suggest the
price of sugar in the U.S. is twice the world price are dead wrong,
because the United States has the third lowest sugar price in the
world next to Canada and Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Agriculture, Nutrition, and Forestry Committee:
www.senate.gov/ (tilde)agriculture
</P>
<P>
   Florida Oceanographic Society: www.fosusa.org
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
