<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3673 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-X-RAYSCANNER-2ndTake-     07-26 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-RAYSCANNER-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 UNDATED: reading them. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about the technology, but I am about the
interpretation of results,'' Cooper says. ``Interpretation is very
important. You must have a highly skilled radiologist, otherwise
you get a lot of false positives and false negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Such results can lead to more invasive testing or even
unnecessary surgery, or to an unfounded sense of security that
could cause a person to ignore symptoms when they begin showing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 60 places in the country, mostly free-standing imaging
centers, are promoting the scans as general screening tests. Some
of the `doc in a box' places shouldn't be doing them at all,''
Cooper says.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is whether the tests are helpful in predicting
disease. ``We are currently doing the research to determine whether
they are valuable in predicting future coronary events,'' Cooper
says.
</P>
<P>
   He has a $1.3 million grant from the National Institutes of
Health to complete a five-year study to determine whether early
fatty deposits and calcification correlate with future coronary
events, especially heart attacks, and whether finding them can save
lives. The study was started last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of screening for these lesions is gaining credibility
daily,'' Cooper says. ``I think this technology is futuristic _ a
giant step forward in the field of preventive medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   For detecting early lung cancers that may be missed by chest
X-rays, electron-beam and spiral scanners are equally effective,
judging from preliminary published study results. For coronary
disease, electron beam is better, Cooper says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have several cases where X-ray did not pick up lung cancers
that we found with the (electron beam). I believe it should be done
as a routine screening for anyone who has a history of smoking. If
a patient has a history of smoking or is a current smoker, we like
to have that CT scan done, and even if they are not smokers, we
like to have a base-line scan at age 40.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be the standard in the not-too-distant future, Cooper
predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Most Tarrant County hospitals have spiral CT scanners and use
them to stage cancers and check for metastasis or the spread of
cancer to other areas of the body, but no one is using them much
for screening in the Dallas-Fort Worth area except the Cooper
Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   In the state of Texas, a doctor's referral isn't required to get
a diagnostic test, such as a CT scan.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cooper Clinic, a quarter of the tests done are
self-referrals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can walk in and ask for one if you are paying for it on
your own, and most insurance doesn't cover them, anyway.'' Cooper
says. About 25 percent are referred by outside physicians who want
more information on how aggressively to treat a patient, usually
for high cholesterol. The remainder are from one of the 14
physicians on staff at the Cooper Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   A quick check with diagnostic imaging centers and hospitals in
Tarrant County found most able to do the scans, but not doing them
without a doctor ordering the test. Doctors are not ordering them
for general screening. The charge at one Tarrant County diagnostic
center is $906.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Clay Roberts, a radiologist at All Saints Hospital, says the
powerful new spiral scanners with bigger tubes and better computers
allow doctors to get a whole lot of data and process it in a
reasonable time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are replacing the old machines for everything _
diagnosing cancers, strokes, lots of different belly pains and
complex fractures,''says Roberts. ``But the new entrepreneurial
rage is to use it to screen for various malignancies in
asymptomatic, healthy people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Shyn, a radiologist at Harris Methodist Fort Worth,
says most hospitals are using spiral CTs, but not for screening
healthy patients with no symptoms of disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of using it for general screening is new. We have had
very few requests for a screening CT for lung cancer. We do them
all the time as follow-up when lung cancer is suspected because of
an abnormal chest X-ray or other test, but as far as screening
asymptomatic people. There has been very little in this
community.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
