<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-ELDERLY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENIOR GROUPS CALL CHENEY'S VOTING RECORD A 'DISASTER'
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During his decade in Congress, Dick Cheney compiled
a record of voting against elderly interests on Social Security,
Medicare and assistance programs, senior advocacy groups said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``His voting record on senior issues was a disaster,'' said
Bette(cq) Cooper, communications director for the National Council
of Senior Citizens. ``I haven't found one point where he could be
viewed as a friend of senior citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rother, director of legislation and public policy for the
non-ideological AARP, said the votes by Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
new running mate on a variety of senior issues ``could be one of
his biggest liabilities as a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Cheney was one of a handful of congressmen who voted
against the Older Americans Act and restoring minimum benefits to
Social Security recipients, Rother said, ``some of those votes
weren't even close, so he went out of his way to vote negative on a
number of issues that will come back and bite him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney served as a Republican House member from Wyoming from
1979 to 1989. During that decade, he compiled a cumulative score of
8 out of 100 on votes deemed crucial by the National Council of
Senior Citizens, which takes a liberal stand on senior issues.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, a spokesman for the Bush-Cheney campaign, said
Cheney acknowledged that many programs he voted against while in
Congress were worthwhile, but his primary goal was to reduce the
budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government was running an enormous deficit and he
was committed to reducing that and getting our fiscal house in
order before we committed ourselves to new programs,'' Bartlett
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the credit for the balanced budget and the surplus we
enjoy today were the work of congressmen like Dick Cheney to rein
in spending,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's campaign was quick to circulate a memo
to senior organizations highlighting some of Cheney's votes on
elderly issues.
</P>
<P>
   Among those were votes to raise the full retirement age for
Social Security to 67, cut Medicare spending by $13 billion over
three years, and oppose spending for the Older Americans Act, which
includes such elderly assistance programs as Meals On Wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Most senior groups said they were less concerned with Cheney's
vote to raise the retirement age, which was included as part of a
comprehensive package to save Social Security in 1983, than his
votes on benefits affecting the elderly poor.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Cheney was one of 20 House members who voted in
1981 against an amendment restoring minimum Social Security
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives you an idea where he is coming from, that he would
vote against restoring money to these people who had absolutely
nothing,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Cheney was one of a dozen House members who voted
against money for the Older Americans Act. In 1987 he was one of
seven House members who voted to cut $108 million from the act.
</P>
<P>
   That year he also voted against a $2 million demonstration
project aimed at providing home care to senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   On Social Security, Cheney was one of 39 House members who voted
in 1985 to limit annual cost-of-living adjustments to 2 percent for
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was one of 72 House members who voted in 1988 against a
bill, supported by the Reagan administration, giving catastrophic
coverage to Medicare recipients. The program was repealed a year
later after a backlash by seniors angered by its high cost.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Smith, director of legislative affairs for the United
Seniors Association, a group which takes a conservative stand on
elderly issues, said he had not analyzed Cheney's votes but noted
they occurred in a time of tight budget constraints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress was faced with a bunch of bad choices,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security was about to go bankrupt. We need to learn
from that lesson and reform Social Security now'' along the lines
offered by Bush to establish private investment accounts, Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Bush for president: www.georgewbush.com
</P>
<P>
   Gore for president: www.algore2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
