<HEADER>
A3679 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SISTERS-STRUGGLE0727-     07-26 4082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SISTERS-STRUGGLE0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sisters' shared memories make friendship strong
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Once there was a princess, and once she
had a party because it is the privilege of a princess to live in
that moment when she shines and glimmers and is the very heart of
her world.
</P>
<P>
   She was almost 60. She had wrinkles fanning from her sky blue
eyes and threads of gray woven through her blond hair, but on this
night she was eternal youth. The ruffled collar of her white satin
dress framed a face that glowed and blossomed into smiles. A halo
of blue flowers and ribbons floated on her downy curls, matched by
the corsage on her wrist, and on her feet were the glowing white
Cinderella shoes she kept glancing at, their iridescent glitter
winking at her as she crossed her ankles and swung her legs.
</P>
<P>
   It was her night, her singular moment, and she wanted everyone
who came to her party to know one thing: The woman in the pink
sweater, the one with blond hair and blue eyes just like hers, was
her sister.
</P>
<P>
   THE PARTY WAS KRIS' IDEA
</P>
<P>
   Kris is a positive person who thinks of what she can do for
others, especially her sister. Always her sister. Not because she
has to, but because she wants to. She's my sister, Kris would say,
and lists what Karen did for her through their lives.
</P>
<P>
   That's the complex and pliant and beautiful nature of
sisterhood, and theirs is a story of sisters.
</P>
<P>
   When Karen Anderson was diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease Dec.
29, her sister, Kris Potter, sat in the examining room with her and
listened to Dr. Joel Dean explain that when people with Down
syndrome get Alzheimer's, they decline quickly. There was a
possibility, he told Kris, that within 90 days Karen wouldn't know
her and that within six to 15 months she might need
around-the-clock care.
</P>
<P>
   A thousand thoughts darted through Kris' mind as he spoke,
worries and questions and a lifetime of shared memories with her
sister. She was going to lose Karen and she wasn't ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I thought, `Oh, no!' because her birthday is four
months away,'' Kris said. ``She's always loved her birthday and she
starts telling you every year right after her birthday, `My
birthday's coming up April 27th.' So in January we got to thinking
that it would be fun to do a party early. We wanted to make sure
she had a birthday party before she ... and we got to thinking
she'd think it was neat. She wasn't too hung up on it being a
certain time, so we looked at the calendar and thought, `Well, we
need to have it near Valentine's Day because she's just so full of
love and everybody loves her.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So Kris reserved the gymnasium of the LDS Church building for
the night of Feb. 12 and organized her family to assemble a party
for Karen's 60th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the party, a work crew of Potters and
Andersons pulled together all the evening's festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Karen was having her hair and nails done by a family friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got her a princess dress and Cinderella shoes, so it's
going to be so neat for her,'' Kris explained. ``This is just
something special we wanted to do for her because she's always been
there in the background and I wanted her to have a time where she's
the shining star.''
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY BACKGROUND
</P>
<P>
   Karen Marie Anderson loved fancy purses and beaded costume
jewelry. Kristina, her younger sister, was more interested in
sports and school activities, and their parents encouraged them in
their interests.
</P>
<P>
   The people they both became are reflections of parents. J. Albin
Anderson, their father, was born on a farm in northern Illinois,
one of 11 children whose mother died when he was 15 and the
youngest was 3. He was an exceptional student who earned a juris
doctor in 1938 from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   He met Janet Elder, who grew up on a farm near Pattersonville,
N.Y., in Boston and they married in 1932. Karen, their first child,
was born April 27, 1940, in Springfield, Mass., where Albin was an
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   She was born early, weighing barely 4 pounds and with physical
traits indicating she had Down syndrome. Much was unknown about
Down syndrome then, so doctors in Springfield referred the family
to specialists in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists told the new parents that perhaps their infant
daughter's condition had been caused by an eye infection that bored
through one side of her brain, so they gave her electroshock
treatments in an attempt to stimulate that side of her brain.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until years later that researchers discovered Down
syndrome is a condition caused by extra genetic material from the
21st chromosome that affects about one in every 1,000 children born
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It was common then for families of children with Down syndrome
to quietly send them to institutions where they spent their lives.
Karen stayed with her parents. Albin and Janet were prominent in
Springfield _ he was a successful attorney who was elected mayor,
and she was active in the community. They often had their picture
in the newspaper, and those photos would include their children as
their family grew.
</P>
<P>
   They smiled proudly and put Karen up front when pictures were
made.
</P>
<P>
   Kris was born almost three years after Karen and John three
years after Kris.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as she was old enough for a regular bed, Kris shared a
room with Karen until Kris was in high school. Their father built
them doll houses that looked like the white house with green trim
they lived in, and their mother made them new Easter dresses every
year.
</P>
<P>
   Before Kris started school, the girls played with their dolls,
their pets and their hula hoops and swung on the trapeze their
father built in the back yard. Karen could twirl and twirl, better
than Kris, better than John. Every Saturday they rode the bus
downtown with their mother to go shopping. In the summer they
visited their grandparents in New York, rolling like sausages down
the big grassy hill in front of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Poet Edna St. Vincent Millay said, ``Childhood is the kingdom
where nobody dies,'' and that's where Karen stayed.
</P>
<P>
   Kris and John got older, started school and joined basketball
teams and discovered the opposite sex. Karen learned to read and
write _ she could write her name in cursive _ and do things around
the house, which Janet patiently taught her. But her mind remained
6 as her body aged.
</P>
<P>
   The family moved to Grand Junction in 1954 because they had
driven through the area on a family vacation to California and fell
in love with it. They moved into a Palisade house in the middle of
a peach orchard, in back of which Albin built another trapeze for
Karen, and he started a legal practice that he worked at for 35
years.
</P>
<P>
   Kris and John started school, but there was nowhere for Karen to
go, so Albin began looking into what the state was required by law
to provide for its school-age children. He discovered that all
children, regardless of mental capabilities, were entitled to
education and, after talking to the school district, prepared to
file suit with the state calling for equality of education.
</P>
<P>
   In response, before the suit was filed, the school district
started the Whitman School for special-needs children and Karen
went there for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was really proud that she had her school, because (John
and I) went to school every day for several years before she got
to,'' Kris said. ``She was proud of what she got to do, and I guess
a part of her was trying to be like John and I and do things that
we did.
</P>
<P>
   ``A part of her probably realized that it was hard for her to do
things and I didn't think a lot about it until she was excited
about getting to do something that kind of mirrored what we were
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kris and John developed their own interests _ Kris in school
functions and academics and John in animals and the outdoors. In
sixth grade Kris met a boy named Bill Potter, who had the longest
eyelashes she'd ever seen, and went with him to the eighth grade
dance, but ended up dating his best friend through high school.
</P>
<P>
   At Palisade High School she got good grades, played in girls'
athletic clubs, was drill captain, president of the Future
Homemakers of America, newspaper editor, a member of a capella
choir and participated in student senate.
</P>
<P>
   She and Bill graduated in 1961 with the same grade point average
and in the top of their class.
</P>
<P>
   Kris and Bill got married Sept. 5, 1964; Karen was in charge of
the guest book at their reception. The newlyweds attended Colorado
State University, Bill studying psychology and Kris focusing on
home economics education and childhood development until she took a
12-month licensed practical nurse training program. She graduated
from the program and worked for a year in the labor and delivery
department of the Fort Collins hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Their daughter Kerry was born in 1968, the year Bill started
graduate school in special education, and Eric came 10 months
later. Derek didn't come along for nine years, followed by Wendy
and Rebecca. The family settled in Clifton.
</P>
<P>
   Karen was living with her parents and saw Kris and her children
frequently. The kids considered Karen another playmate, and Kris
occasionally caught them bossing her around more than they probably
should have.
</P>
<P>
   Karen also had different jobs through the years. She worked in
the kitchen at the Colorado State Home and did contract work for
Goodwill Industries and Mesa Developmental Services. On one job for
Goodwill, Karen assembled packets of small building parts for a
local company.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Kris and the kids went by to visit Karen at work and
Karen proudly showed them what she'd done and, even more proudly,
introduced Kris to everyone who worked with her, even those who
already knew Kris.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone at work knew about Karen's sister, because she talked
about Kris so much.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW LIFE FOR KAREN
</P>
<P>
   Karen came to live with Kris and her family on New Year's Day,
1990. Their father had died the previous year and it broke Karen's
heart. Their mother had died in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   At first the Potter's home was filled to bulging, with Bill and
Kris, four of their five kids and now Karen. The kids _ Eric was
attending Mesa State College, Derek was 11, Wendy was 9 and Rebecca
was 6 _ never complained. Karen shared a room with Rebecca, and
Wendy slept on the couch for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate my children,'' Kris said. ``I don't remember them
ever complaining and I'm sure it was harder for them. Of course, I
think they just accepted it _ try to help the family. And I've told
Bill a lot that he let Karen live here when he could have made it
not be nice or feel like I better find her a place, but he never,
ever did. He said, `She's our family and she needs to live here.
Why wouldn't we do it?' It was neat that he didn't think that was
anything different or unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the Potters were able to add some rooms on their house so
when Eric got married and moved out, the kids and Karen got their
own rooms. Eric and Derek fixed up Karen's for her.
</P>
<P>
   When she first came to live with Kris and her family, Karen went
to work every day at the Holiday Inn, where she vacuumed rooms.
Several years ago she retired because of a few health problems and
because she was becoming a little forgetful, so Kris registered her
in the Blossom View Day Care program.
</P>
<P>
   A bus picked her up in the mornings so she could spend the day
with her friends, playing bingo, going to the mall, making crafts
and watching movies. She came back on bus the in the afternoons,
and Kris was waiting for her.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few years ago, Kris took Karen trick-or-treating every
Halloween, dressed as a gypsy because it was her one chance to wear
lots of her beloved necklaces and bracelets at once. At Christmas
Kris would take her to see Santa Claus and when she saw him she'd
light up, she'd get excited, she'd just sparkle all over: ``(gasp)
Santa!'' She'd sit on his lap and give him a big hug. She never
thought to ask for anything big, just maybe a book or more jewelry
or a new purse.
</P>
<P>
   As she got older, she began forgetting things _ how to set the
table, an occasional name and, as the Alzheimer's progressed, how
to read, dress herself and write. Where once she filled notebooks
with the carefully printed names of family members, she devolved
into filling pages with circles.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Kris made an appointment and Dr. Dean confirmed what
she'd suspected, that Karen had Alzheimer's. Kris and her family
began doing things for Karen so that her last memories would be
good: They left the Christmas lights up in her room so she would
remember Christmas. They watched her favorite movies with her _
``The Happiest Millionaire'' and ``101 Dalmatians.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though her memory was fading, she always shouted ``Penny!''
during ``101 Dalmatians'' because Penny was the Dalmatian the
Andersons had when she was young.
</P>
<P>
   When Kris decided to have the party for Karen, friends
volunteered to make Karen's white satin top and skirt. Rebecca
organized the decorating. John's wife, Rhonda, made Karen's halo
and corsage.
</P>
<P>
   Kris made a special cake.
</P>
<P>
   It was going to be a happy memory for Karen and for everyone who
loves her.
</P>
<P>
   A SPECIAL KIND OF LOVE
</P>
<P>
   Mid-afternoon on Feb. 23, as Kris sat facing the front living
room window, talking about Karen and watching for her bus to arrive
from Blossom View, Kris said she was glad their parents raised her
to love Karen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when I see my girls having fun, sometimes a part of
me wishes I could do that, too, have that kind of relationship with
my sister. But she's always loved me and I've always loved her and
I've tried to treat her so that when she becomes a perfected person
she'll,'' Kris said, and paused to take a deep breath before trying
again, ``she'll still love me for being her sister.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the yellow bus pulled up, Kris hurried outside as the
doors swung open and Karen approached the top of the three steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Karen!'' Kris exclaimed, smiling, asking Karen if she'd
had a fun day and extending her hand for Karen to hold for
stability as she slowly came down the steps of the bus.
</P>
<P>
   'I KNOW SHE'S RUNNING AND DANCING'
</P>
<P>
   The milky afternoon sun shone through the Potter's living room
window on March 23, encouraging Wendy to feel optimistic about the
flowers she was planning to plant in front of the house.
</P>
<P>
   The blue living room couch was pushed to the center of the room,
facing the window, to make room for the hospital bed that arrived
in three pieces, which Bill helped assemble. Karen lay on it now,
under a blue-flowered sheet and a pillow covered in a Sesame Street
case, a mylar bumble bee balloon tied by a ribbon to the end of the
bed.
</P>
<P>
   On the previous Sunday, after watching ``Honey, I Shrunk the
Kids'' with Bill, Kris and Rebecca, she tried to get up to go to
bed and collapsed, unable to move. Bill picked her up and took her
to bed. The following morning she couldn't move but was still aware
and talked with Kris about the snow that fell during the night.
Kris called Hospice and they sent over a hospital bed and a
wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning she was catatonic and doctors told Kris Karen's
body was shutting down _ she couldn't eat or drink. Three hospice
workers came out daily to help Kris care for her sister. When they
first began coming in January it was hard for Kris ``because I had
always helped her and the last few years had been increasingly a
lot more help because she was starting to get forgetful and we
pretty much had to help her get dressed and undressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was becoming a lot more care but I never had thought about
somebody else doing it for me, and it was hard to give up part of
that care of her, for me, because at first I felt I was letting her
down. But it was a wonderful experience because she was able to
touch other people's lives. They felt by them doing things they
could do in their profession, it would give me time that I wouldn't
be getting to just spend with Karen and just do things that I could
do to give her love and comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning Karen stopped breathing for a short time ``and
I thought, `Breathe, Karen! Don't do this to me!' '' Kris said,
adding that Karen started breathing again. Wednesday was the first
day Kris felt like eating since Karen collapsed. It also was the
day she and John began talking about the inevitability of what was
happening.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning Kris went into the living room and told Karen,
``Good morning! It's Kerry's birthday and if you need to go today,
it's a beautiful day.'' But she waited. The hospice workers had
come by, then Kris' friend, Jackie Osborne, washed and curled
Karen's hair. Wendy ran her hands through the fresh blond curls as
she leaned by Karen at the end of the bed and remembered with her
mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that three-wheel bike she had?'' Wendy asked, and
Kris giggled. Karen rode that bike up F 3/4 Road then coasted back
down, through the stop sign, so when Kris and Bill heard honking
they knew it probably was Karen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was great Karen was out there getting exercise
but the kids came in and said Karen was coasting again,'' Kris
laughed. ``Finally the bike broke and Bill said, `We're not fixing
it!' ''
</P>
<P>
   After that, Wendy added, Karen got a baby stroller, which she
took out to the street and pushed as hard as she could in front of
her, trotting after it and pushing it again when she caught up. She
always seemed to push it in a straight line, Kris said, and it
never went in the ditch.
</P>
<P>
   ``And remember that time grandma called and said Karen flipped
her off?'' Wendy asked. Karen went through a phase in which she
waved at people with a different finger every day, and the day
Bill's mother, Arlene Potter, drove by, Karen was waving with her
middle finger. Wendy and Rebecca told her to wave with her whole
hand or don't wave at all.
</P>
<P>
   Kris listened as Wendy and John's daughter, Lorilynn,
reminisced, pulling out some supplies to brush Karen's teeth. She
dipped the cylindrical pink sponge on what looked like a lollipop
stick into a bowl of warm water and gently rubbed it across Karen's
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Karen responded by reflexively biting the sponge and Kris
laughed, ``Kar-en! I see you smiling, tricker.'' Then Kris used a
black straight comb to restore Karen's curls, rubbed Carmex on her
lips, put a pillow under her knees and straightened the maroon
soccer ball-print blanket over her feet.
</P>
<P>
   Then she stood just looking at Karen, listening to her labored
breathing and caressing her cheek with feather touches, quietly
murmuring, ``I love you. Thanks for being such a good sister to
me.'' Karen's eyes occasionally fluttered and Kris softly cooed,
``Beautiful blue eyes. Are you going to open your beautiful blue
eyes?''
</P>
<P>
   After that, Kris just held her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night John's son, David, and his wife brought by
dinner, then John came over at around 10 to sit with Karen through
the night so Kris could sleep. At about 12:45 a.m. he gently woke
her and said, ``I think she's passed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so neat he came because I don't think I could have
stood here and ...'' Kris said Friday morning, not finishing her
thought as she looked at the stripped hospital bed pushed against
the wall under the living room window.
</P>
<P>
   Walking across the sun-dappled front yard with a visitor, a
Kleenex clutched in her hand, Kris said, ``I think about what she's
doing today, free of all the burdens she took on to come to earth.
I know she's running and dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   A BLESSED LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Karen was buried March 27. The morning of the funeral service
breathed spring and inside Clifton Christian Church her family and
friends honored a life represented by the day.
</P>
<P>
   Her silver casket at the front of the chapel was adorned with an
arrangement of blue flowers, her favorite color. On a table covered
by a Holly Hobbie tablecloth in the foyer, Kris had arranged a few
mementos: the blue silk flower halo draped over the glittery white
Cinderella shoes Karen wore at her party, the princess from the top
of her party cake, framed pictures of her and red bead necklaces
and bracelets from her collection.
</P>
<P>
   During the service the Rev. Roger Ferguson cited the Beatitudes
_ blessed is Karen, pure in heart. After his remarks Kris and John
walked hand-in-hand to the pulpit and Kris stepped to the
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ``A month from today Karen would have been 60,'' she began, and
shared some highlights from Karen's life. She talked about a person
championed by their parents, one who treasured fancy purses, loved
fireworks and sledding but hated thunder, who frequently said her
eyes were blue like the sky and loved new clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Karen's legacy is her happy attitude and her love of
life,'' Kris said. ``She was always happy with what she was doing
and who she was with, and she had a really positive attitude. She'd
ask me what's for dinner every day and I'd tell her and she'd say,
`That's my favorite!'
</P>
<P>
   ``Karen had a beautiful spirit, she never judged people. It was
for us to learn patience, love and understanding from her.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Kris paused and John took her hand. ``We could not have had
a more perfect person in our lives. She loved us every day of our
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   John added he wished he had Karen's genuineness and her purity
of feelings. ``When you have a special sister die, it takes you a
while to realize what you learned from her.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen was buried that afternoon in Palisade Cemetery with her
family and friends standing nearby and the vast, clear sky overhead
as blue as her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Author Katherine Mansfield wrote, ``Remember you are always in
the heart _ oh tucked so close there is no chance of escape _ of
your sister.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember the time you tried to make me play baseball?''
Rebecca asked Wendy one afternoon in May. ``I'd never played it and
I didn't know how to hit a ball and you were like, `Try and hit it
this time' and I couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you just got frustrated so easy,'' Wendy explained. ``So
you'd go home crying, `They're trying to make me do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd always make me do all this stuff, pick out clothes for
me. I'd always ask you what to wear, `Does this look OK?' And at
school one time you made me roll up my pants because that's how the
style was. I was in, like, kindergarten.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the '80s!''
</P>
<P>
   Now memories like this are funny, not the tear-inducing
melodramas they were 10 years ago. Wendy and Rebecca relate to each
other more as adults, from lives that don't overlap like when they
were younger but with an intangible bond that's stronger. They
discuss it with Kerry over e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was away at college and Wendy and Rebecca were at home,
I was always afraid they'd get hurt,'' Kerry said. ``I was like
this little mother to them. But I think I'm learning more it's
their life and whatever they do is what they do. But I still hope
for the best for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``HAPPY BIRTHDAY''
</P>
<P>
   In the days and weeks after Karen died, Kris went through her
things _ her drawer full of beaded necklaces and bracelets, her
collection of purses, her doll house _ boxing some of them for
storage.
</P>
<P>
   Karen was buried in her princess dress but Kris kept the size 3
Cinderella shoes, even though her kids told her all they would do
is make her cry. She's done that anyway, and will for a while. On
Karen's birthday, Kris sang ``Happy Birthday'' to her.
</P>
<P>
   The princess' sister led her by the hand to the table where her
cake stood, white and perfect like a wedding cake with a figurine
on top who looked like the princess _ blue flowers in her hair and
an elegant white gown. Her sister made the cake for her, and her
nieces decorated the hall with brown, black and white teddy bears,
blue and silver balloons on ribbons and shiny, multi-colored
confetti 60s sprinkled on the tables.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody at the party wanted to kiss the princess' cheek and
tell her they love her, take her picture and say she looked so
beautiful. She smiled for everyone, but her sister knew what she
really wanted was a piece of cake, so her sister sliced one for
her, took the princess' hand and led her to a table where some of
her friends were sitting.
</P>
<P>
   The princess smiled and told people she saw, people who had
known her and her sister for 20 years or more, ``This is my
sister.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
