<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BARAK RETURNS TO FIGHT FOR SURVIVAL, ARAFAT TO CHEERS
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ While Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat returned from
the Camp David peace talks to cheers Wednesday, Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak came home to even tougher political challenges
than he faced before.
</P>
<P>
   Barak landed at Tel Aviv's Ben Gurion International Airport in
the early evening (Local Time), returning from 15 days of often
tense negotiations with Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some reported progress on the most important issues
separating Israelis and Palestinians, the two sides could not reach
any agreement beyond a joint statement saying they would keep
talking.
</P>
<P>
   For Barak's political opponents, who had opposed his going to
the summit in the first place, the failure was touted as
confirmation that he should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Even before his plane landed, according to Israeli press
reports, Barak worked the phones to rally potential allies against
parliamentary votes next week that could prompt new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Before more than 300 supporters outside his official residence
Wednesday night, he promised he would keep going despite the
setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that there are moments that you don't have the
strength and just want to throw everything aside,'' he said. ``But
we're not going to give up because the future of the state of
Israel depends on peace.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, and apparently appreciative of the show of
support, Barak stepped through his high-security guard contingent
to greet people in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Arafat returned to the Gaza Strip with widespread
support from Palestinians who were glad he did not buckle under
Israeli and American pressure to make a deal. They seemed willing
to wait _ years, if necessary _ for an agreement that will give
them sovereignty over key parts of Jerusalem, claimed by Israel as
its capital.
</P>
<P>
   Celebratory rallies were held in several cities in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip. Arafat pledged that he would continue negotiating
with the Israelis in an effort to capitalize on progress made at
Camp David, the presidential retreat in western Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The juxtaposition of the two leaders' receptions showed Arafat,
who U.S. officials indicated was not as flexible in the talks as
Barak, strengthened while the summit failure left Barak weaker.
</P>
<P>
   It also reflected the feeling among most Palestinians that they
are the weaker, aggrieved party and deserve to win back all the
land captured by Israel in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war. Barak's
apparent readiness to concede most, but not all, the land left
Palestinians feeling they would still be giving up what's owed to
them.
</P>
<P>
   But, on the Israeli side, split bitterly down the middle on
peace issues, Barak's flexibility sharpened the attacks of his
right-wing opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Their message: Barak's offers showed only that the Palestinians
do not want peace and they compromised Israel's bargaining position
as long as he is prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ehud Barak finally found out that what the right wing said for
years, 'that we don't have a partner for peace on the opposite
side,' was right,'' said Limor Livnat, a member of the Israeli
parliament in the Likud, the largest opposition party to Barak's
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave up too much,'' she said, adding that any time he
begins talks again, the Palestinians will hold up Barak's offers in
Camp David as the new starting point for the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Barak opponents plan votes on two bills next week that could
force early elections. Barak's governing coalition includes only 42
of the 120 seats in parliament and he was working Wednesday to win
back parties that had resigned when he went to Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Barak narrowly staved off a similar challenge in the parliament
just before the summit began, but his support may have slipped
since then.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli pollster Hanoch Smith said a survey last week of 500
voters showed Barak losing in a match-up against his predecessor
Benjamin Netanyahu, 38 percent to 30 percent with many undecided.
The poll had a margin of error of +/- 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Barak's residence Wednesday evening, the throng of
supporters vowed they would bounce back from the summit setback.
Police separated them from a small group of counter-protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People believe the game is not finished yet,'' said Barak
supporter Yaron Ram, 49, even as a raw egg, hurled by an unseen
opponent, struck his side. ``This is just halftime.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
