 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, July 27. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRFRANCE-CRASH (Gonesse, France) _ The Concorde that crashed
into a hotel near Charles de Gaulle airport on Tuesday, setting off
a fireball and killing 113 people, had been delayed from taking off
by last-minute efforts to correct problems with an engine _ the one
that caught fire as the plane took off. By Suzanne Daley. (With
graphic)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and the Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat each pledged to keep at
their halting quest for peace Wednesday despite the breakup of the
Camp David summit meeting. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-BUSINESS-POVERTY (United Nations) _ As top executives of
Shell, Nike and DaimlerChrysler filled a chamber where the likes of
Germany, India and Mexico usually meet to discuss global politics,
the United Nations on Wednesday recruited multinational companies
to help protect workers and the environment in places where
governments do not. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-V (Lubbock, Texas) _ The fifth installment of the
biography of George W. Bush: On his first race for Congress. By
Nicholas D. Kristof. (With photos NYT17, NYT18)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY (Casper, Wyo.) _ Gov. George W. Bush and his new
running mate Dick Cheney made a whirlwind visit to the vice
presidential contender's home state Wednesday, defending Cheney's
voting record and pledging that the ticket would ``restore
America's purpose.'' By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY-OIL (Undated) _ Four years after helping to win the
Persian Gulf war and defending the region's oil fields, former
Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney went from fighting for oil to
running a Dallas-based firm that he has helped transform into the
world's largest oil field services company. As chief executive of
Halliburton Co., Cheney has been able to rely heavily on the
high-level contacts in the Middle East and elsewhere that he made
as defense secretary to win business in the world of international
oil. By James Risen, Richard A. Oppel Jr. and Leslie Wayne. (With
graphic)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL-BUG-ZAPPERS (New York) _ Attention, alarmed citizens:
Are you less than completely convinced that truck-mounted sprayers
can zap every West Nile-infected killer mosquito? Do you fear that
rolled-down shirt sleeves, long pants, and socks are nothing but a
Maginot Line against the mosquito menace? Respect is being accorded
a virus that killed seven people in the region last year and
sickened 55 others. Mosquito repellent, citronella candles,
mosquito coils and mosquito nets ``are flying off the shelves,''
said a salesman in the crowded ``mosquito area'' of the Paragon
sporting goods. By Glenn Collins.
</P>
