<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3689 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CONCORDE-CRASH-0727-C     07-26 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCORDE-CRASH-0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ENGINE FOCUS OF PROBE, AS INVESTIGATORS SIFT THROUGH THE
WRECKAGE OF CONCORDE CRASH
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GONESSE, France _ The pilot of an Air France Concorde that
crashed Tuesday reported engine trouble minutes after take-off and
was apparently making a frantic attempt to fly the crippled
aircraft to a nearby airport, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth Senot, a French jurist conducting a judicial enquiry
into the crash, said tower controllers at Charles de Gaulle
International Airport radioed the Concorde's crew that they could
see flames at the back of the aircraft 56 seconds after it took
off. Air France identified the pilot as Capt. Christian Marty,
apparently known for skill and prudence as a pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The captain replied, 'fault in engine number two,''' Senot
said at a news conference. ``After that it seems the flames became
extremely large because (the fire) was once again signaled by the
control tower, and the crew replied that they were no longer in a
position to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The crew told the tower that they were heading for Le Bourget
Airport, four miles southwest of Charles de Gaulle. This would have
required a half turn rather than a full turn by the damaged
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was during this turning maneuver that it crashed on the
hotel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The supersonic transport lost power and altitude as the flames
poured from engines under its left wing and crashed into a small
hotel. All 109 passengers and crewmembers aboard the Concorde were
killed, as well as four people at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The plane struck the hotel and earth near fields of wheat and
corn near the suburb of Gonesse, about nine miles from central
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Air France reported that Marty asked mechanics
to make a repair to the engine that began spewing flames minutes
before take-off. Mechanics repaired a thrust-reverser in one of the
two portside engines before the Concorde took off.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the airline said engine No. 2 _ the interior
engine on the left wing _ was inspected and repaired at the pilot's
insistence even though the repair was not required for take-off.
The problem with the thrust-reverser, which is used to slow an
aircraft on landing, was detected after the plane arrived from New
York on Monday, Air France said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the pilot was told that the repair wasn't required,
he asked mechanics to make it anyway, the airline said. ``The piece
was immediately taken from a reserve Concorde,'' Air France said.
``The repair was carried out in 30 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Francois Brousse, the airline's spokesman, refused to speculate
on any relationship between the repair and the accident. ``At the
current state of the inquiry there is no way of knowing
</P>
<P>
   if this has any relation with the accident,'' Brousse said.
</P>
<P>
   While many experts have speculated that a single engine
explosion was probably not enough to trigger Tuesday's accident,
others said that it would be catastrophic if the explosion were not
contained. John Guntrip, a former British aviation accident
investigator, told Sky-TV News that such an event could damage
other of the aircraft's systems perhaps rendering it impossible to
fly. ``A total failure of a jet engine is a rare event, but this
looks like a major uncontained explosion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were examining the cockpit voice recorder and
flight data recorder _ the two so-called ``black boxes'' _
recovered from the aircraft early Wednesday morning. The voice
recorder can shed light on what happened because it records
conversations between the two pilots. The flight data recorder will
tell investigators about the physical condition of the aircraft, as
well as its speed and bearing.
</P>
<P>
   Even though British Airways resumed flying its fleet of seven
Concordes Wednesday morning, Air France said its five remaining
supersonic planes would remain grounded for now.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the crash _ the first in the Concorde's 30 year history
_ French Transport Minister
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Claude Gayssot told a news conference that he hoped an
analysis of data from the doomed Concorde's black boxes might be
available Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resumption of (Air France) Concorde flights could happen
in the next few days,'' Gayssot said.
</P>
<P>
   As the weather improved during the day, investigators combed the
charred crash site for clues. Typically, they will try to gather
together all the scattered engine parts to try to determine the
sequence of failure. The special metals used in jet engines are not
generally damaged significantly even in the extreme heat of such a
crash.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of 43 victims were taken to a Paris lab for
examination, police said. The rest were too severely damaged to be
easily moved, and remained at the crash site as emergency workers
picked through the blackened wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-six German passengers were killed in Tuesday's crash. The
overwhelming majority of the dead, they were headed to New York for
a luxury cruise to the Caribbean and, for some, on to the Sydney
Olympics. Two Danes, an Austrian and an American _ retired Air
France employee Christopher Behrens _ were also passengers. Nine
crew members died, along with four people in the hotel, including
two Polish hotel trainees.
</P>
<P>
   A special crisis center staffed by psychiatrists, counselors and
medical staff has been opened for relatives at the airport. About
100 family members were expected to come to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said in Germany that his nation was
in shock. Pope John Paul II sent condolences.
</P>
<P>
   One of the crash's survivors on the ground told reporters that
she was spared only because she had been assigned a room at the
front of Hotelissimo, which was engulfed in the blaze fed by the
aircraft's 100 tons of fuel. Alice Brooking, 21, a Cambridge
student, jumped out of a window on the hotel's second floor to
safety seconds after the accident. She had been on the phone with
her sister in England.
</P>
<P>
   She said that flames and smoke moved quickly through the hotel.
``It was like being in an oven,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Gonesse, a town of 20,000 brought unhappily to the
world stage by the crash, expressed a mix of sadness and gratitude
about what had happened. Coming out of a Toys ``R'' Us at a nearby
mall, Marie Hetru said she could not get over the crash, and the
prospect that it could have crashed into the center of Gonesse a
half-mile away.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would the number of dead be then _ maybe including me and
my children,'' she said. ``Of course it is terrible _ 113 people _
but if it wasn't for the pilot, it may have been much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonesse Mayor Jean-Pierre Blazy said the crash reflected the
miseries of the town's living near one of the world's busiest
airports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been saying for a long time that air traffic is
increasing too fast, that even with four runways, you can't safely
manage this amount of air traffic around Paris,'' Blazy said at a
press conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lived with planes for several decades and we don't
live in daily fear of a crash, but it's on our minds.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
