<SLUG> BC-X-RAYSCANNER-CONTROVERSY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALK-IN CT SCREENING CONTROVERSIAL
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanies X-RAY SCANNER)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANO, Texas _ He eats right, exercises regularly and
occasionally drinks a glass of red wine. Still, Kevin has known for
some time that the odds of maintaining a healthy heart are stacked
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his grandparents had open-heart surgery; a year and a
half ago, he was found to have hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   When a friend told the 36-year-old father of three about
HealthScan of Plano, a new medical imaging service, Kevin felt
obliged to have himself checked out.
</P>
<P>
   After a recent scan of his heart and torso, Kevin learned from
doctors that his heart is in good shape, his bone density normal.
</P>
<P>
   But they had some news he hadn't counted on: They found a large
tumor on his right kidney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is it looks like we found it in time, before
symptoms presented themselves,'' said Dr. Margaret Hansen, medical
director of HealthScan.
</P>
<P>
   HealthScan of Plano is one of many nationwide entrepreneurial
efforts to take advantage of new electron-beam CT scanners and make
them available to healthy consumers who are interested in
screenings for heart and lung disease, cancer, osteoporosis and
other conditions. The service takes about 30 minutes, does not
require a physician's referral and costs $695 up front (the service
is not covered by most insurance providers unless it is through a
doctor's referral). Walk-ins are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   There are four electron-beam CT (computed tomography) scanners
in the Fort Worth-Dallas area. Two are at the Cooper Clinic in
Dallas, another was recently purchased at the University of Texas
Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas, for research and clinical use,
and the other is at HealthScan.
</P>
<P>
   HealthScan President Gerald Friede says the screenings his
imaging center does are an important way for people to find out
about potential health problems that can be fixed with medicine or
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem with heart disease, for example, is there
is no early warning for about 50 to 60 percent of people,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   But other health-care experts are not convinced that the
screenings are good predictors of whether patients will have a
heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very controversial area,'' said Dr. Thomas Andrews,
director of the Dallas Heart Disease Prevention Project at the
University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center. ``Not everybody
who has a heart attack will have a positive scan, and certainly not
everybody with a positive scan will have a heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more data to know how to interpret the results,''
Andrews says. ``My personal bias is this will have an important
role in screening for coronary artery disease. The key thing is not
so much getting the scan but proper interpretation of the results.
That requires somebody who's got insight into what the scan is
saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Friede started HealthScan a little over a year ago after seeing
firsthand the benefits of the electron-beam CT. HealthScan now has
two sites. The other is in San Diego. Here in Plano, about 125
people come in for the $695 procedure each month.
</P>
<P>
   Three other clinics are under construction: in Houston; Orange
County, Calif.; and Pasadena, Calif. Those are scheduled to open
during the fourth quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
