u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     07-26 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST, HOME THEATER. NOW, LAPTOP THEATER. 
</HEADLINE>
   By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My friend Laura once pitched an article called ``Guy Bait'' to a
major women's magazine, for which she wanted to take nifty gadgets
into bars and see how long it took patrons of the male persuasion
to sidle over for casual conversation and a little technology
cruising. If portable digital videodisk players had been on the
market then, I suspect that she would have had the men sidling in
from 10 blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   I recently spent time with three new portable DVD players and
found that crowds of both men and women would gather around when I
had one on parade. Alas, I didn't have the similarly high
expectations for the players themselves. I had expected them to
have the visual kick of those square seat-back video screens on
transatlantic flights that let you squint through your own personal
showing of ``Stuart Little'' on an overnight flight to London.
</P>
<P>
   After testing several units, though, I must say that I was
wrong. The portable DVD players that you can get today offer
bright, clear video display, Dolby Digital sound and batteries
powerful enough for a double feature.
</P>
<P>
   There are many models and price levels to choose from in the
realm of portable DVD players, with the price of the high-end units
around $1,500 and lower-end ones about $700. With regular
home-based DVD players selling for as little as $200 in some
places, the hefty price tag of the portables may place them out of
the reach of many consumers. Owners of laptops with built-in or
added-on DVD drives may find the traveling DVD players to be
something of a moot point; the portable models are aimed more at
the dedicated home-theater enthusiast. All the portables I tested
could also be fully integrated with home theater equipment (for
most people without electrical engineering degrees, it is basically
the TV-VCR combo _ and maybe the stereo _ all wired together) or
used as a stand-alone player if you were on the go.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most appealing portable players is Panasonic's new
DVD-LV75 from its PalmTheater line. It costs about $1,400, and if
you read entertainment magazines, you have probably seen the
advertisements for it: a futuristic silver device displaying an
action scene from ``The Matrix'' (a film that was seemingly made
for DVD). At just over three pounds without the flat lithium-ion
battery pack that attaches to the bottom of the unit, the DVD-LV75
feels like it weighs less than the new ``Harry Potter'' book, and
it's definitely thinner. With the screen folded, it is less than an
inch thick and measures about 5.5 inches by 7 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD-LV75 has a 7-inch screen, which is one of the bigger
video displays available on a portable unit. The flat LCD screen
was sharper than I expected and was bright enough for me to watch
movies comfortably in a variety of lighting conditions. After
charging the battery, which the company says has a four-hour life
span, I made it all the way through ``Chinatown'' without any lag
in the unit's performance. Like all the portables I looked at, the
player comes with an AC adapter to charge the battery as well as
run the player without the battery pack attached.
</P>
<P>
   Once I adjusted to the screen's small size, I forgot about the
fact that I was watching the movie on such a tiny machine and
became absorbed in the film itself. I did notice that the battery
pack began to get warmer and warmer as the movie progressed, and by
the time Faye Dunaway said: ``She's my sister! She's my daughter!''
the whole player itself felt rather toasty. The heat wasn't
searing, by any means, but it was noticeable and enough to keep the
player from being considered a laptop model.
</P>
<P>
   The external speaker on the DVD-LV75 was adequate for the casual
viewer, but attaching a pair of decent-quality headphones was an
immense improvement. In addition to standard audio and video jacks,
the player has a port for an optical digital audio cable and an
S-Video output jack for high-quality display when it is connected
to a full-size television screen.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Electronics recently released a portable DVD player with
similar features. The Sony DVP-FX1 offers the 7-inch LCD screen in
the cinematic, wide-screen 16:9 (width-to-height ratio) format (as
opposed to the squarish 4:3 format used by most standard television
screens). The company says that its lithium-ion battery will last
up to four hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's model is roughly the same size as Panasonic's version. It
offers Dolby Digital sound and many of the same standard DVD
features like smooth motion scan, which lets users easily stop on a
specific frame of the film. The screen was also clear and bright
and nicely displayed the deep, saturated colors of the ``Wallace &AMP;
Gromit'' disk.
</P>
<P>
   The playback was smooth, even when I wiggled the unit to
simulate what a small child might do in the back seat of the family
minivan on a summer drive across America. Portable entertainment
for cars, boats and vans is one of the uses Sony suggests as a
reason for plunking down the considerable cash for one of these
machines. Sony's DVP-FX1 is priced at about $1,600, but depending
on how badly your children behave on long trips, it could be a
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   To help prevent the youngsters from running off and watching
movies that Mom or Dad may not approve of, Sony is incorporating
the Custom Parental Control System into some of its portable DVD
models. The system allows parents to control access to as many as
50 titles.
</P>
<P>
   If I had to choose between the Panasonic and Sony models, I
would give a small edge to the Panasonic, mainly because of the
slight price difference. Both are fine machines.
</P>
<P>
   There are less expensive options in the portable player market.
The screens on the cheaper models are generally smaller and the
overall design of the units is not as sleek and compact as those of
more expensive models. But for someone who doesn't mind having a
smaller screen and a bigger case in exchange for saving several
hundred dollars, a bulkier portable may make more sense.
</P>
<P>
   Aiwa's XD-DW1 player falls into that category. The company's
suggested price is $850, but the player can be found in stores for
$650 to $700. The screen measures 5.8 inches diagonally, and the
design is a bit clunkier than that of the more expensive
competitors. The active-matrix screen loses some clarity when
viewed from odd angles but looks fine head-on.
</P>
<P>
   The XD-DW1 has built-in stereo speakers and will play audio CDs
as well as DVD movies. It offers Dolby Digital sound and S-Video
output and comes with the cables you need to connect it to your
home entertainment equipment. For the price, the Aiwa XD-DW1 was
pretty solid, and not having the extra inch or so of viewable
screen area that the other two players provided didn't particularly
bother me when I was engrossed in ``The Seven Samurai.''
</P>
<P>
   People will have to decide whether the cost of a portable DVD
player is justified, and I can't honestly say I would buy one
myself if cost weren't a consideration, especially with home
players being so inexpensive. But I can see the appeal of a
portable for those who travel a lot, are serious cinemaholics or
who want to use a single DVD player in a variety of locales.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if I wait long enough, the prices might come down even
more. Remember how much an early Walkman cost?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
