<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TIPPER GORE: THERE'S MORE TO LIFE THAN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Where's Tipper Gore these days? She did a lot of
solo campaigning during the Democratic primaries but has dropped
out of the political picture in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   She recently went on a four-day hiking trip in California's High
Sierras with a girl friend and is planning to take another vacation
with her husband off the North Carolina coast during next week's
Republican National Convention when political opponents
traditionally lie low.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore made it clear in a 30-minute conversation that she
will hit the campaign trail again after the Democratic National
Convention in mid-August in Los Angeles. Meanwhile, she says she's
emotionally ready for the election outcome, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   It would be ``fabulous'' to be first lady, she said, because the
job would give her an even greater platform for her big causes _
ending the stigma associated with mental illness and helping the
homeless to get back on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, she does not intend to allow politics to
become all-consuming in her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my own life and my own interests, and I like it,'' she
says, a theme she repeated frequently during the chat.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore, who has played the drums since her high school days,
definitely marches to her own drummer. She doesn't fit the old
stereotype of a political wife and she captivated Washington this
spring when she banged the drums at a gay rights march.
</P>
<P>
   She also has occasionally turned up at Lafayette Square across
the street from the White House to get acquainted with some people
who are homeless _ and she even invited them to the vice
presidential mansion on embassy row. Her Secret Service agents take
it all in stride.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways her remarks are reminiscent of the women's
movement, stressing that she is her own person, more than just the
wife of Vice President Al Gore. Politics is part of her life _
``but not my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   She referred to her husband as her ``partner and best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to win,'' she said, but she is prepared ``to let
the reality play out.''
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledges that her husband has an image problem _ some
voters find him wooden and detached. But that perception is
``irrelevant'' and will change once voters get to know him, she
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe the starting point will be the convention''
in Los Angeles next month, she said. The campaign is in the
``warm-up stage and will all come together in the fall. You have to
trust the people.''
</P>
<P>
   If her husband has any problem connecting with voters, she says,
then the root of that problem is that he _ as vice president _ is
``supposed to be a team player and in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore appeared confident that, once the voters tune in, they
will be ready to cast their ballots for her husband over his
personable, but less experienced Republican opponent, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show Gore catching up with Bush, who still
maintains a light lead. Gore's strategists believe he will get a
``bounce'' at the Democratic convention in Los Angeles and in the
three October debates, a style of political combat that he has
mastered in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore, who once worked as a photographer for the Nashville
Tennessean, is a photogenic blonde beauty and an asset on the
campaign trail as an off-the-cuff speaker. She also finds time to
push her causes _ for example, she ran the White House Conference
on Mental Health a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the perennially tardy President Clinton arrived to deliver
a major speech at the conference, she jokingly commended him for
being on time for the first time in his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons and the Gores have been friendly throughout the
nearly eight years of the administration, unlike many other
presidential and vice presidential families.
</P>
<P>
   But word got around Washington during Clinton's impeachment
ordeal that Mrs. Gore was deeply upset over his affair with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky and wanted her husband to
distance himself from the political fallout.
</P>
<P>
   While Mrs. Gore has been keeping a relatively low profile, the
Gores' daughter, Karenna, has been much more visible. She often
appears by her father's side as an adviser in the vice president's
inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore has publicly discussed her own bout with depression
and has made mental health a more prominent public issue. ``I'm an
activist and an advocate,'' she says proudly.
</P>
<P>
   While some polls show Bush doing relatively well among women
voters, Mrs. Gore says she is confident that when women begin to
focus on the issues, they will know that her husband ``will fight
for their rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They will ``tune in and have a clear-cut choice,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She said she particularly worries about the rightward swing of
the U.S. Supreme Court on women's issues if a conservative
administration takes over the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the relationship between President Clinton and Gore,
she said Clinton ``has been a friend, has given good advice, has
been very helpful. He cares about the next president. He wants Al
to be president. I'm happy with his role.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
