<SLUG> BC-X-RAYSCANNER-PATIENTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU SMOKE, SHOULD YOU GET A CT SCREENING?
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanies X-RAY SCANNER)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An estimated 164,100 cases of lung cancer will be diagnosed in
2000, according to the American Cancer Society. An estimated
156,900 people will die of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year survival rate for all stages of lung cancer
combined is only 14 percent, but the survival rate increases to 49
percent for cases detected when the disease is still localized. The
problem is, only 15 percent of lung cancers are discovered that
early.
</P>
<P>
   Finding lung cancer early is believed to be a missing key to
combating this deadly disease, but until now, a reliable screening
technique for early detection has eluded medicine.
</P>
<P>
   With ultrafast CT, the body from the neck to the pelvis can be
scanned in less than 20 seconds _ a single breath-hold.
</P>
<P>
   The National Cancer Institute says preliminary studies of
ultrafast CT show promise in detecting small cancers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, adenocarcinomas, the most common lung cancer, can
be detected more readily with spiral CT than with a standard chest
X-ray, the National Cancer Institute says. However, the technology
may be less useful for detecting central airway tumors such as
squamous cell carcinomas, and rapid-growing carcinomas such as
small-cell carcinomas.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Burk, a Fort Worth pulmonologist who sees a lot of
patients with lung cancer, says spiral CT scans can detect tumors
many times smaller than those found with conventional X-rays, but
they will also show many abnormalities that are not cancer.
</P>
<P>
   These ``false positives'' can lead to much more risky and
invasive lung biopsies and even surgery that is unnecessary for
benign disease, Burk says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably is a place for these ultrafast scanner
techniques in screening, but we are still learning where it is.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Christine Berg, chief of lung cancer research for the
National Cancer Institute, estimates 20 to 40 percent of CT scans
of smokers will show abnormalities that are not cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The institute is designing a large study that should
conclusively answer whether spiral CT screenings do in fact reduce
the likelihood of dying from lung cancer, the gold standard for any
cancer screening test.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to start looking at patients with high-risk
factors for lung cancer _ family history, smoking, radon or
asbestos exposure, petrochemical exposure _ but that's not the
general community,'' says Burk. ``When you develop a screening test
in a high-risk population and then take it to the general
population, you get a lot more false-positive results. We need to
sort through and look at good predictors that tell us more
specifically who needs to be screened.
</P>
<P>
   Will Medicare and private insurance start paying for screening
scans anytime soon?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the $40 million question,'' Clay says. ``Medicare
didn't pay for mammography for a long time, until the data showed
it saves lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things are asymptomatic for a long time, and you
would like to pick them up earlier. Lung cancer is one of those
things, and screening for it is one of those deals waiting to
explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it is still in the domain of executive physicals,
but if I had a family member with a history of smoking and any
other risk factor, I would definitely consider CT screening well
worth the costs,'' Clay says. ``The problem is, it's a whole lot of
money for not much cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Carolyn Poirot
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
