<P>
   COLOMBIA-INTRO-$ADV30 _ With the highest murder and kidnapping
rates in the world, a raging civil war, the worst recession in
memory and plummeting public
</P>
<P>
   confidence in the army and the government, Colombia is facing
the most dire crisis in its history. Thousands of people are
fleeing the country, while human rights activists estimate another
1 to 2 million have been displaced internally by repeated attacks
by leftist guerrillas and right-wing paramilitary groups. We
</P>
<P>
   profile two groups _ kidnap victims and displaced people _ as a
window into everyday life in Colombia. (Williams, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-KIDNAP-$ADV30 _ BOGOTA, Colombia _ The families come to
the national radio station each week, clutching hand-written notes
they hope will somehow reach their kidnapped relatives. With an
average of 8 kidnappings a day, Colombia is a nation living in
fear. Leftist guerrillas and paramilitary groups have turned
kidnapping into a big business _ some 3,000 victims were snatched
last year - to raise money for their armies. We profile a few
families of kidnap victims who hope against hope they will somehow
see their loved ones again. (Williams, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-DISPLACED-$ADV30 _ BOGOTA, Colombia _ Libia Barahona
watched warring leftist guerrillas and right-wing paramilitaries
battle in her remote village for months, dodging bullets and hiding
with her five children. Finally, she fled, abandoning her small
store and restaurant, eventually making her way to Bogota, where
she is now homeless. Barahona is one more victim in the tidal wave
of 1 to 2 million Colombians - mostly rural peasants - displaced by
the country's civil war. Human rights activists fear the US aid
package may only increase the flow of refugees as poor campesinos
are forced out of the countryside by crop eradication programs and
the escalating war en
</P>
<P>
   guerrillas and the Colombian army. (Williams, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-MIGRATION-$ADV30 _ SAN FELIPE TORRES MOCHAS, Mexico _
Like millions of other young Mexicans, Eusebio de Haro set out for
the United States in May, confident he'd find work like he did
before. Instead De Haro was shot to death, allegedly, by an elderly
Texas rancher after he and another young man knocked on his door to
ask for water in a remote area near the Rio Grande. The option to
the United States for work is as deeply ingrained in De Haro's home
state as the Virgin of Guadalupe. But it is an option that appears
to be getting more deadly every day for those who choose to cross
the border illegally. Migration is
</P>
<P>
   probably the toughest of all issues between these two countries.
And Mexican President-elect Vicente Fox, who is from De Haro's home
state, has heightened the profile even more, suggesting more visas
for Mexican workers and working toward an open border for the free
flow of labor in as little as 10 years. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   With MIGRATION-SIDE-$ADV30 _ GUANAJUATO, Mexico _ Migration has
affected some towns in
</P>
<P>
   Fox's Guanajuato state where state social workers attend to
abandoned families and other problems. They're also encouraging
successful migrants to invest in communities to create jobs there.
These are towns that send construction workers to Arkansas,
laborers and harvestors to Texas and Georgia and others states. We
tell it from the perspective of a young social worker we watched in
action. (Ferriss, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   With information for locator map; chart on migration.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move on the NYT Wire.
</P>
