<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3719 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0727-COX     07-26 2166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Why oh Wyoming
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A day after taking his place on the GOP ticket, Dick Cheney
returned to public life with a visit to Wyoming, where he began his
climb to Congress, the Pentagon and the top of the corporate world
before being tapped as George W. Bush's running mate. The
Republican team's first stop after Bush's announcement in Texas was
Casper, where Cheney and his wife, Lynne, attended Natrona County
High School. Back at the school today, Cheney joked that if someone
had predicted Lynne would be back some day with the candidates for
president and vice president, everybody would have believed it.
``But they never would have guessed that it was going to be me,''
he said, to laughter and cheers.
</P>
<P>
   SHORING UP MINORITY SUPPORT
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore told minority leaders today that ``talk is cheap'' and
asked them to look askance at George W. Bush's efforts to win them
away from the Democratic Party. Gore's theme, in an appearance
before the board of Operation PUSH in Chicago, was that actions
speak louder than words. ``They have concocted a strategy of
phrases and photo opportunities to convey the impression of
inclusion and moderation,'' he said. ``I expect even more of it
when the Republicans gather in Philadelphia next week. I bet it's
going to be quite a show.''
</P>
<P>
   FOR GOVERNMENT SERVICES, SIZE MATTERS
</P>
<P>
   A new ABC News-Washington Post poll (3 percentage point margin
of error) finds that Al Gore is backed by 80 percent of blacks and
60 percent of Hispanics. George W. Bush was supported by 12 percent
of blacks and 35 percent of Hispanics surveyed. But Bush is
supported by 54 percent of whites in the poll, compared with 39
percent for Gore. Gore's advantage among the minority groups is
aided by their preference for more government services. Hispanics
and blacks said they favored a larger government with many
services, while two-thirds of whites favored smaller government
with fewer services. The approach to smaller government is a more
Republican point of view.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN KERRYING FAVOR
</P>
<P>
   John McCain said today that Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts
would make an excellent running mate for Al Gore. Speaking at a
news conference in Washington where he appeared with Kerry to
promote Internet privacy legislation, McCain praised Kerry's
legislative ability and service to his country as a fellow Vietnam
War veteran. Kerry had met with Gore at a fund-raiser the previous
evening, but declined to comment on his prospects.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-SQUATTERS SNATCH BUSH-CHENEY
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after George W. Bush announced his running mate,
Democrats were up with a Web site detailing Dick Cheney's
conservative voting record. The Democratic National Committee
gobbled up the site, www.bush-cheney.net, late Sunday and have
posted scores of votes he cast in Congress. The site is also
sprinkled with quotes describing Cheney as ultra-conservative,
anti-abortion and opposed to affirmative action. From ex-House
Speaker Newt Gingrich : ``Cheney's voting record was slightly more
conservative than mine.'' The Bush campaign complained that
Democrats were trying to deceive Americans by making the site
appear to be generated by Bush-Cheney supporters.
</P>
<P>
   THE ABILITY TO OPEN DOORS
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney's lengthy foreign affairs experience helped boost
the overseas reach of Halliburton Co., the world's largest provider
of petroleum support services. About two years ago, Halliburton
executives were having trouble getting a face-to-face meeting with
a top official in tiny, oil-rich Qatar. They had tried for months
to talk with the country's oil minister to discuss a potential
project. No response. No interest. No meeting. That was before
their boss, defense secretary during the Persian Gulf War, got
involved. ``Within an hour, the meeting was facilitated and set
up,'' said Halliburton's chief financial officer, Gary Morris, a
tone of wonder in his voice. ``Having access is a great thing.''
</P>
<P>
   OIL TO GREASE THE PARTY COFFERS
</P>
<P>
   With Dick Cheney at its helm, Halliburton Co. and its employees
have been generous supporters of the Republican Party. Donation
records show the oil services giant has given more than $1.6
million to federal candidates and the political parties since Jan.
1, 1991, virtually all to Republicans. More than half that money
has come since Cheney took over the company as CEO in 1995, the
Center for Responsive Politics reported. More than 91 percent of
the company's donations have gone to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S A TRADITION!
</P>
<P>
   Long before Dick Cheney's transformation from talent scout to
running mate, George W. Bush was relying on him and other veterans
of his father's presidency. Should Bush get to the White House,
Cheney as vice president surely would be joined by others from the
old Bush administration, in the Cabinet and top echelons of the new
one. Bush has talked of Colin Powell as a prospective secretary of
state, and the retired general has said he'd serve if asked. That
choice could be made in advance for campaign impact. While
Democrats might taunt Bush about the legacy of policy advisers,
there're likely to do the same thing. Presidential nominees always
have.
</P>
<P>
   STILL A PRETTY GOOD LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney has become very rich as a result of his work. Last
year, he earned $1.28 million in salary and $640,914 in other
compensation, as well as stock options that could be worth up to
$18.8 million, according to an analysis by Reuters. On May 31,
Cheney cashed in 100,000 shares of stock just as it neared a
one-year high, which resulted in a $5 million payout, according to
a Securities and Exchange Commission report. If Cheney is elected
vice president, he would earn $181,400 a year.
</P>
<P>
   POLLUTION ON BOTH THEIR HOUSES
</P>
<P>
   As soon as George W. Bush announced that Dick Cheney will be his
running mate, the environmental records of both candidates came
under attack from conservation advocates and Democrats. ``If George
W. Bush represents the biggest threat to the environment in the
2000 presidential election, then Dick Cheney is clearly the second
biggest,'' said Deb Callahan, head of the Washington-based League
of Conservation Voters. At the same time, Democrats went after
Bush's environmental record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   BALL'S IN GORE'S COURT NOW
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore retains ``a whole range of options'' in choosing a
running mate following George W. Bush's selection of Dick Cheney to
be his No. 2, Gore aides say. Gore has stepped up his ``very
private and dignified'' selection process, said Gore aide Mark
Fabiani. There was a lot of speculation that Gore would tap
Massachusetts Sen. John Kerry as his running mate, but former
Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell's name was on many lists as
well. Florida Sen. Bob Graham's big home state also made him a
contender.
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM PEOPLE LIKE CHENEY CHOICE
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Sen. Bob Graham of Florida say his chances of
becoming Al Gore's running mate improved when George Bush chose
Dick Cheney to join the Republican ticket. Graham's Democratic
supporters, according to the Palm Beach Post, are looking for any
hopeful sign because they're convinced that he can push Gore over
the top in the Sunshine State. A victory in Florida, they believe,
could be devastating for the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH BY 11 IN OHIO POLL
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, George W. Bush leads Al Gore by 11 percentage points,
47-36 percent, according to a new poll by Fox News/Opinion
Dynamics. The survey also showed Bush to be ahead in the state,
43-34 percent, when Ralph Nader (6 percent) and Pat Buchanan (5
percent) are added to the presidential mix. The survey had a 4.3
percent margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   PROPOSALS FOR THE DISABLED
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore unveiled a $2.7 billion package designed to bolster
programs for the disabled by opening the workplace and improving
home-care programs. ``There are millions of Americans who are held
back, not because they have a disability, but because that
disability is misunderstood,'' said Gore. ``They are not recognized
for the abilities they have.'' Aides said the package aims
specifically at opening the workplace to the disabled, citing
statistics showing that up to 75 percent of those with serious
disabilities are unemployed or underemployed.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH THE ONLY ONE LEFT NOW
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes finally dropped his own campaign for the Republican
nomination. Keyes won no primaries last winter and spring, but had
remained on the campaign trail spreading his conservative message.
Asked at an appearance in Boston if he still considered himself a
candidate, he said, ``I am not.'' But a campaign spokeswoman said
Keyes had not yet filed withdrawal papers with the Federal Election
Commission. Keyes said he supports Dick Cheney for vice president
because Cheney's anti-abortion views mirror his own, and that he'll
join other Republicans to unite behind the ticket at the convention
next week.
</P>
<P>
   GAY USED TO MEAN MERRY
</P>
<P>
   Gay Republicans strongly opposed to elements of the party's
platform are running into roadblocks erected by social
conservatives. Representatives of the Traditional Values Coalition
and the Family Research Council who met with Wisconsin Gov. Tommy
Thompson, chairman of the platform committee, said they were
assured they would be happy with the party platforhe bottom line is
the homosexuals want to neuter the Republican platform, and I'm not
sure that's going to happen,'' said Andrea Laferty, of the
Traditional Values Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   THE DISPLEASURE OF HIS COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Claiming a new TV ad linking him to Rick Lazio is misleading,
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan is demanding the Long Island
congressman have it withdrawn. Moynihan, whose retirement opened up
the New York Senate seat, is backing Hillary Clinton. The ad,
unveiled by the Republican Leadership Council, uses the words of
President Clinton to link Lazio and Moynihan, and relies on footage
of the president thanking Moynihan, Lazio and others at a ceremony
for their work on legislation to help disabled Americans. ``There
follows a composite photograph of the two of us, although we have
never, to my belief, been photographed together,'' Moynihan wrote
in his letter to Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC SOOTHES THE SAVAGE DONOR
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee is staging several low-priced
concerts to fill the party coffers, hoping to lure in new donors
willing to fork over just $50 or $100 rather than six-figures. To
aid the cause, Democrats are calling on the likes of legendary
singer Barbra Streisand, male group Boyz II Men and comedian Whoopi
Goldberg. ``We're going to make it exciting for them to give to the
DNC,'' said Peter Knight, who recently took over the party's
fund-raising. Previously, Knight was campaign manager for President
Clinton and chief of staff for Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLES OF THE RICH AND FAMOUS
</P>
<P>
   Fishing with House Speaker Dennis Hastert. Cocktails with
retired Gen. Colin Powell. Golf with a senator. Ringside drinks
with champion Larry Holmes or an afternoon with race driver Bobby
Labonte. That's for those who've donated five- and six-figure
checks to the Republican Party. In Philadelphia, there'll be
cocktail parties galore, luxury skyboxes, and countless events
offering the lure of casual access to Washington's power brokers.
The attraction is ``going to events that are not boring cocktail
events in nondescript locations, but events that give them a feel
for the city and our rich history and our culture,'' said Martin
Silverstein, a Philadelphia lawyer and GOP donor.
</P>
<P>
   PREGNANT WOMEN ON DEATH ROW
</P>
<P>
   In reaction to Al Gore's recent statement that pregnant women on
death man. No one has shown that the circumstance has ever arisen.
The sponsor of the bill, Rep. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen (R-Fla.), argued
that unborn children had committed no crime. Abortion-rights
advocates said the bill was intended to advance the cause of
abortion opponents by elevating a fetus to the status of a child.
The bill now goes to the Senate, where its future is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   PRO-ISRAEL CREDENTIALS
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton said U.S. aid to Palestinians should be cut off
if they unilaterally declare statehood. ``It must be clear that any
unilateral declaration of Palestinian statehood would be entirely
unacceptable and should be met with a cutoff of United States
assistance,'' she said in a statement after the Camp David peace
talks collapsed. The New York Senate candidate's position appeared
to go beyond what President Clinton has said in urging the Israelis
and the Palestinians to keep trying to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
