u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     07-26 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SHOPPING: A PERSONAL TAILOR FOR DENIMED MASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I panicked one day recently because I could not find my lucky
jeans.
</P>
<P>
   As I pawed through a pile of 10 other ill-fitting pairs _ the
ones with the button fly that is so hard to button, the ones that
shrank in the wash, the ones with the puckered waistband, the ones
that sag after a couple of hours of wear _ I realized that the last
time I felt so desperate was after I discovered that my engagement
ring had fallen out of my pocket while I was gardening.
</P>
<P>
   I hunted for two hours with a flashlight before I found the ring
in a patch of ivy. But finding a pair of jeans that fits right is a
slightly more difficult undertaking. So when I heard about
Interactive Custom Clothes Co., or IC3D, an online retailer that
offers customers the opportunity to build a pair of jeans perfectly
sized to fit their measurements for less than $100, I immediately
went to the IC3D site to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The home page welcomed me with the greeting: ``It's your
universe, wear whatever you want totally custom.'' This statement
conjured up a wondrous world that off-the-rack shoppers like me
have rarely glimpsed: a place where sleeves don't hang down over
hands, waistbands do not slide hipward and sleeveless shirts do not
gape open under the arms.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of owning such a wardrobe has become
increasingly rare since the advent of the mass manufacture of
clothing. Because that trend became firmly entrenched after World
War I, when all those factories that had been producing soldiers'
uniforms turned in peacetime to the fabrication of civilian wear, I
never thought I could do much to fight it. Instead, I just counted
myself fortunate not to have been alive to wear the formless,
waistless fashions of the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   But a return to tailor-made clothing makes sense in an era when
manufacturers of items as diverse as computers and automobiles are
building customized products from scratch to satisfy customers'
idiosyncratic desires for big hard drives and metallic paint
finishes. ``Apparel in particular is really ripe for mass
customization because everybody's body is unique and we have been
sacrificing when we buy off the rack,'' said Joseph Pine, the
author of ``Mass Customization: The New Frontier in Business
Competition'' (Harvard Business School Press, 1992).
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a growing number of online retailers _
Moda1to1.com, E-madeinitaly.com, Americanfit.com _ are selling
tailor-made clothing for prices that range from $100 for a dress to
$780 for a men's suit. Shoppers can point and click to choose
fabric, color and cut, then type in their measurements.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond merely creating jeans that are the right size, IC3D
offers customers the option of specifying every detail _ from
button color to fabric weight to the number of pockets to how wide
the ankle opening should be (the company's software can generate a
pattern accurate to one-tenth of an inch). This level of
specification does not come cheap, however; jeans cost from $70 to
$95 (including shipping) depending on the choice of fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Although this excited me at first, I soon realized that it was
going to be no faster than trying on 20 pairs of ill-fitting jeans
under the pitiless glare of fitting room lights. In fact, when I
clicked on my fabric choice, denim, 30 options appeared _ and I
didn't know what most of them were.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I could pick between stonewashed or ``raw,'' all right, but
did I want fabric that was ``ring-spun, left hand twirl,'' or did I
want ``a right-hand twirl?''
</P>
<P>
   It felt kind of like the way they built ``The Six Million Dollar
Man'' on television in the 1970s after the opening credits intoned:
``We have the technology. We have the capability to make the
world's first bionic man.'' Only in this case, the thread color
would be crucial to the outcome. What if I made a mistake?
</P>
<P>
   That is the biggest risk, of course, when shoppers try to design
their own clothes. ``Be careful, or else you might not like what
you get,'' said Robert Leeds, a lecturer in the marketing
department at the University of Southern Florida who worked for
years in the apparel industry. ``The fabric might feel scratchy.
Maybe you won't like the buttons. And don't forget there are
fashions in everything. Even in black socks, the number of ribs
changes from season to season. Are these jeans going to be
fashionable?''
</P>
<P>
   Skittish, I phoned Peter del Rio, the founder of Ic3d.com, who
reassured me. ``We are guaranteeing that they will fit right, and
if they don't, we will determine why and fix them,'' he said,
adding that in the four years the company has been selling online,
95 percent of customers are ``totally happy.''
</P>
<P>
   About half of the company's first-time customers avoid the
headache-provoking choices by opting for the site's Copy Cat
feature, he said, which prompts you to mail in your favorite pair
of jeans. The company creates a copy for you, then mails them back.
Or he suggested using the Denim Wizard feature to get started.
After asking five ``lifestyle'' questions like ``Are you more
concerned about fabric quality or low price?'' and ``What kind of
climate are you going to wear your jeans in?'' the wizard
recommends a denim for you.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I went with ``Riviera,'' described as a ``soft
perfect denim with no unique characteristics.'' Then I went
upstairs to my closet again, where I determined that most of my
jeans were sewn with orange thread and had copper buttons and five
pockets. So I chose those features, as well. Then I measured myself
in 11 places, including some (like ``front rise'') that I had never
heard of before. del Rio said not to worry too much; within an inch
of accuracy, the measurements should produce a pair of well-fitting
jeans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The total came to $85. When the jeans arrived, less than a week
after I placed the order, I followed the company's instructions and
washed and dried them before trying them on. The fit was perfect.
They are in fact the best-fitting jeans I've ever had. I have a new
lucky pair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
