<HEADER>
A3723 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPBELL-ABORTION-HNS     07-26 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CAMPBELL WILL PUSH FOR PRO-CHOICE PLATFORM AT GOP CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., said Wednesday he will
go to the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia next week
to speak out on behalf of abortion rights, a position sure to put
him at odds with the convention's majority.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell faces an uphill fight in his bid to unseat Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif. Voters in the state are heavily pro-choice; so
a prominent stand in favor of abortion rights amid a convention
dominated by anti-abortion Republicans could help Campbell
politically.
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell insists that California politics aren't guiding him
in his plan to champion the pro-choice position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truly, my purpose is to make sure that people see the
Republican Party as diverse as it really is,'' Campbell told
reporters at a luncheon meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell acknowledged that making a point of his pro-choice
views at the Republican convention is his best hope of inoculating
himself against any Feinstein attack that might materialize on this
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at it this way: If I went to the convention and was
silent, a fair criticism could be lodged against me for having been
silent,'' said Campbell, 47, a former law professor at Stanford
University.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he has sent letters to every pro-choice GOP House
member, senator and governor, urging them to make their views known
at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to speak at meetings of the delegation from
Pennsylvania, California and Illinois. Pennsylvania's governor, Tom
Ridge, is also pro choice.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he is trying to get an invitation to speak before
the New York delegation. New York's Republican governor, George
Pataki, favors abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Silicon Valley congressman said he has also asked to address
the entire Republican convention, but he admitted, ``I'm not
holding my breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he is working with pro-choice Republican activists
who want to delete strong anti-abortion language that is likely to
be approved by the conservative-dominated platform committee, as
well as the convention at large.
</P>
<P>
   The platform's abortion language, still in draft form, parallels
that in the 1996 Republican platform, which calls for a
Constitutional amendment outlawing abortion and makes no exceptions
for rape, incest of the health of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 abortion plank states: ``The unborn child has a
fundamental individual right to life which cannot be infringed. We
support a human life amendment to the Constitution and we endorse
legislation to make clear that the Fourteenth Amendment's
protections apply to unborn children.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell insisted he is not trying to create discord at the
conventon, but rather to promote an image of a party that is not
monolithic on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
