A3724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-HAIR0727-COX     07-26 1549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIR0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hair today, gone tomorrow
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Your average Neanderthals were patient
people. Patient and hairy. This is because they spent lots of hours
crouched in bushes waiting for a mastodon or buffalo to come by,
and it was in the days before Gore-Tex.
</P>
<P>
   It was cold, is the point, especially with all those glaciers,
and they needed something to supplement the mastodon robes they
wore. Back then, a woman liked a hairy man and, come to think of
it, a man liked a hairy woman. It meant they wouldn't lose a limb
to cold at an inopportune moment.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed. Now we wear layers. Scientists think the
earth is getting hotter. We have dressing systems. Which may be why
some people respond to body hair the way they'd respond to a
cockroach crawling on their necks: Get it off! Get it off!
</P>
<P>
   We don't really need body hair anymore. We're warm enough, so
the standard of beauty in many cultures has become smooth and
essentially hairless. Oh, we'll tolerate some hair, but only on the
right places: heads, for example, or Tom Selleck's chest.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, get thee hence, unwanted hair, we've got many ways to
remove you.
</P>
<P>
   A CLOSE SHAVE
</P>
<P>
   Most basically, there's shaving. Balanced on one leg in the
shower clutching a bar of soap shaving. Soft as a baby's bottom
shaving. Darn it, she used my razor again and now I'm bleeding
shaving. This is how you do it, son, shaving.
</P>
<P>
   Shaving. Thpbbbt. Shaving can cause skin irritation and ingrown
hairs, not to mention flecks of white toilet paper attached to the
skin by a dot of blood on some difficult-to-navigate place _ like
an ankle or neck _ that invariably gets cut.
</P>
<P>
   But in the short-term, it's also the cheapest option and the one
with which we're most familiar. We hit puberty and start shaving,
the mysteries of a razor unfolding like the new hairs we discover
daily. It's exciting at first _ fun, even, because we feel like an
Adult.
</P>
<P>
   Then it became a hassle. It involves things like shaving cream
and replacement blades and after shave. We try, and sometimes stick
with, different options: the Epilady (Remember how bad that hurt?
Yanking duct tape off would feel better.), Norelco products, the
Remington, anything, anything.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, we consider just not shaving at all, in protest of
our shallow, appearance-obsessed culture. That lasts about three
days. Sigh. Get the tweezers, our eyebrows are looking bushy.
</P>
<P>
   CREAMS NO CURE-ALL
</P>
<P>
   So we kick it up a notch to depilatory creams. Raise your hand
if your skin ever turned orange because you left the Nair on a
minute too long. It's more thorough, though, especially on the way
to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   There also are products _ such as Hair No More, UHA Sport and
DermaNude Hair Vanishing Cream _ that claim to seep into the hair
follicle and saturate the hair bulb, inhibiting hair growth. Prices
vary between $25 and $50 per container of product and results have
been reported as varied. But people are looking in many directions
for help in the war on unwanted hair.
</P>
<P>
   OW OW OW WAXING
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to waxing. Some facts about waxing:
</P>
<P>
   _ Leaving home-waxing kits in the microwave for too long is a
terrible idea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ow. Ow. Ow. Owwww.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hair must be at least a quarter-inch long for effective
waxing.
</P>
<P>
   _ After repeated treatments, the hair gets finer and thinner,
said Terri Kelley of About Face &AMP; Body Health &AMP; Wellness Day Spa,
and waxing hurts less.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a professional do the waxing, he or she will spread
a layer of warm wax on the target area, let it cool a little bit,
then peel it off. That's pretty much what happens if you do it
yourself. Since the entire hair is coming off, it takes weeks to
grow back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of times is more painful,'' Kelley said, but
added that she has as clients swimmers who get full-body waxes and
men who have their backs waxed. There are different waxes for
normal and sensitive skin, and the most common areas Kelley waxes
are legs, eyebrows, upper lips and the bikini area, though hair can
be removed from anywhere it grows, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fees for waxing can vary according to the type of wax used, the
training of the esthetician and the establishment where the waxing
is done. On average, however, full body waxes can start at $100,
back or chest waxes at $40, underarms at $25 and lips or chins at
$12.
</P>
<P>
   CURRENT ELECTROLYSIS
</P>
<P>
   Kelley also does electrolysis, which deserves a new paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   Electrolysis. Where to begin? Back in the day, decades and
decades ago when it was invented, all electrolysis was invasive,
meaning a needle is injected into each individual hair follicle,
conducting a galvanic current into the follicle and killing it.
</P>
<P>
   This method hurts quite a bit and, since follicles vary in
depth, its effectiveness also varies.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, a noninvasive technique was developed in which
a tweezer or a probe is used to deliver the galvanic current at the
base of the hair follicle. Estheticians spread specially formulated
gels on the hair first, gels that will coat the hair and allow the
current to be transmitted down the hair shaft to the follicle.
</P>
<P>
   The probe is held on one square-inch spot for 40 seconds while
the clients hold something to ground themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a fantastic breakthrough,'' Kelley said, ``but
it's not an overnight process.''
</P>
<P>
   Clients come back for treatments over a period of nine months to
a year, because hair grows in different stages and one treatment
won't get all the hair. Noninvasive electrolysis treatments can
start at, on average, $35 for the upper lip, $45 for the jaw, $90
for under the arms and $70 for the bikini area.
</P>
<P>
   FOLLICLE LASER SHOW
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, hair removal methods have advanced in amazingly
high-tech directions. Dermatologists now are using lasers and
intense pulses of light to get rid of unwanted hair.
</P>
<P>
   The laser hair removal technique was discovered as a side effect
of tattoo removal, in which a ruby laser not only removed the
tattoo but killed the hair around it. Based on that technology,
scientists and researchers developed increasingly more powerful
lasers with longer wavelengths of light that penetrate deeper and
are kinder to skin.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Dahlstrom, who co-owns Lasair, LLC, uses an 810
nanometer diode laser to remove unwanted hair on his patients. The
laser works by targeting pigment in the base of the hair follicle
and achieving photothermolysis, or thermal damage to the pigmented
hair follicle.
</P>
<P>
   The best laser hair removal candidates have dark hair and fair
skin, he said, because the laser targets black melanin, the skin
and hair pigment, which absorbs the heat from the laser and damages
the hair follicle. Tans, dark skin and blond hair can make laser
hair removal less effective.
</P>
<P>
   In laser hair removal treatments, Dahlstrom shaves the target
area and offers numbing cream because it can be an uncomfortable
process. The laser itself is computer-driven and scans a1 1/2-inch
square of skin every six seconds. The skin around the affected
follicles may become red and swollen, especially tan or darker
skin.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlstrom said an average of six to eight treatments are
necessary to get satisfactory cosmetic results, depending on a
patient's age, sex, hormone level, pigmentation and other factors.
He said laser treatments can be used on the face, bikini area,
underarms and most other areas where unwanted hair grows. Patienle
like a haircut. If it's reasonably priced it has value.'' For
example, he said, a laser treatment of the bikini area may be
between $50 and $80.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO-EPILATION SNAPSHOT
</P>
<P>
   Photo-epilation is the hair removal method most recently
approved by the Food and Drug Administration. Using an intense
pulse of one of the wavelengths of visible light, photo-epilation
targets the follicle without affecting the tissue around it, said
Peggy Hudgens of Plastic Surgery Specialists, P.C., who directs the
PhotoDerm program.
</P>
<P>
   Using a system of filters that sends light into different planes
of tissue, the pulse of light targets the melanin in the hair
follicle and quickly heats it, damaging the follicle. As with laser
hair removal, the ideal candidates for this treatment have dark
hair and light skin.
</P>
<P>
   Each flash of light covers an area of skin the size of a stick
of Trident gum, and is so quick that numbing cream for the skin
rarely is necessary, Hudgens said.
</P>
<P>
   She also said she does several test sites before doing a
treatment to see how a patient's skin responds, and does multiple
treatments over the period of a year for a 70 to 95 percent
reduction in the amount of hair on the target zone of skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never make anybody 100 percent hair-free,'' she said,
adding that patients will see an obvious reduction in hair growth.
</P>
<P>
   Which is the point, the goal of all this shaving and waxing and
plucking. It's not necessarily a vanity issue, Dahlstrom pointed
out, but a way to improve self-esteem. Unwanted hair can be
painful, distracting or embarrassing, especially with our stringent
standards of appearance.
</P>
<P>
   What we need is another Ice Age.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
