<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. files a brief arguing
why the U.S. Supreme Court should not hear an expedited appeal of
the federal court ruling that it should be split up because it is
an abusing monopoly. (Glass, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving on NYT wire in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-CADBURY _ Coca-Cola Co. is abandoning efforts to acquire
Cadbury Schweppes' beverage brands in Canada and Mexico. The brands
in both countries were part of a $1.85 billion deal struck in 1998
between Coke and London-based Cadbury Schweppes. The deal has since
been scaled back because of government antitrust concerns. (Seward,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   UPSAIR _ A subsidiary of UPS is testing a new technology that,
proponents say, can drastically reduce or even eliminate mid-air
and runway collisions. The experimental system known as ADS-B (for
Automatic Dependent Surveillance - Broadcast) also promises to
unclog aerial gridlock by allowing planes to safely fly closer
together and takeoff and land at shorter intervals. UPS will begin
equipping its own planes with ADS-B this year, and others including
FedEx, Airborne and DHL are likely to follow by the end of 2002
when all cargo planes will be required to carry collision avoidance
equipment. (Hirschman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AMSOFT _ American Software, an erratic company whose stock is
stumbling along at about $6, is hoping to fix its image on Wall
Street with one, and possibly two, IPO spinoffs. (McNaughton,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FURNISHINGS-SHOW _ Atlanta has snagged a prestigious commercial
furnishings show for 2001 and maybe beyond. NeoCon South is moving
to Atlanta after two years in Miami. In Atlanta's favor is its
central location and boom in development, which fuels this market.
The show is expected to draw between 3,500 and 5,000 people are is
considered moderate by convention industry standards, but it's
important because it is affiliated with NeoCon World Trade Fair,
which is held in Chicago and draws about 60,000 annually. It's also
one of the most important trade shows in the industry. (Poole,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
