u e BC-VH1-BANGLES-NYTR &LR;      07-26 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VH1-BANGLES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLES' TALE TO BE TOLD ON VH1 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL DeYOUNG   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The four members of the '80s rock band the Bangles last week
announced their reunion. At a Los Angeles press conference, the
group laid out plans for a 10-date tour in September, to be
followed by recording sessions for the first Bangles album since
1988.
</P>
<P>
   The Bangles broke up a year after that album, tired of the grind
of constant touring and tired of the in-studio bickering. But most
of all, they tired of defending their unity as the media, and to
some extent the fans, saw them as one singer with a three-member
backing group.
</P>
<P>
   The unity issue finally drove the band apart, according to an
upcoming installment of the VH1 documentary series ``Behind The
Music,'' scheduled to debut Sunday at 11 a.m. and be repeated at 9
p.m. and 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Bangles were not the first group to go their separate ways
at the height of their success _ just think of the Beatles, the
Eagles or Led Zeppelin _ but they were the first all-woman group to
do so. The breakup fueled speculation in a male-driven business
about insecurities, backstabbing and enormous clashes of ego.
</P>
<P>
   All more or less true, according to ``Behind the Music.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Peterson, Susanna Hoffs, Debbi Peterson and Michael Steele
were veterans of the Los Angeles club scene when they came together
through a shared love of the vocal harmonies of '60s groups such as
the Byrds and the Mamas and the Papas, and the short, to-the-point
songwriting of the Beatles and other British Invasion bands.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, the band _ first called The Bangs _ put out a single on
its own independent label and got it played on local radio.
</P>
<P>
   Rhythm guitarist Susanna Hoffs, who sang lead on the single, had
led a sheltered life with her wealthy parents in a trendy West
Hollywood neighborhood, and the Bangs' first live show was the
first time she had ever performed in front of a rock 'n' roll
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Sisters Vicki (lead guitar) and Debbi Peterson (drums), on the
other hand, had been gigging around Southern California clubs since
they were teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Bassist Michael Steele joined the group after the name was
changed to the Bangles. She had been the first singer and bassist
for the Runaways, the all-girl teen band assembled via audition by
a male entrepreneur. Joan Jett was that band's lead guitarist.
</P>
<P>
   The Bangles' first Columbia Records album, ``All Over the
Place'' (1984), was a favorite on college radio but didn't yield a
hit single. Each member sang an equal amount of the songs. Their
harmonies were thick and clever, and gave the album a cool,
appealing retro feel.
</P>
<P>
   It was Prince who gave the band the keys to the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Smitten by Hoffs' sloe-eyed beauty in an early Bangles video, he
gave them a song to record, which he wanted Hoffs to sing: ``Manic
Monday.'' Although several band members didn't care much for the
song, it became a huge hit and catapulted the Bangles into the
public eye.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the band, a rumor went around that Prince _
then one of the biggest stars in music _ was dating Hoffs. It
wasn't true, but it sold records, and it made the Peterson sisters
and Steele uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffs became a media darling. She was perceived as the Bangles'
``lead singer,'' even though she vehemently denied it every time
she was asked.
</P>
<P>
   The band's first No. 1 single, ``Walk Like an Egyptian,'' was
anything but celebratory, because Debbi Peterson didn't play or
sing on it, having been voted off the song by the band's producer.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``Behind the Music,'' the Bangles never recovered
from the ``Susanna is the star'' syndrome, and their second
chart-topping single, Hoffs' treacly ballad ``Eternal Flame,''
sealed their fate.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in management, record producers and other essentials
made things worse, and by the end, the Bangles say, the tension was
so thick you could cut it with a drumstick. Steele was physically
ill, and Hoffs took the opportunity to tell the others she wanted
out.
</P>
<P>
   After their acrimonious breakup, Hoffs launched a solo career,
which flopped, and after she married ``Austin Powers'' director M.
Jay Roach, and following the birth of their two sons, her
priorities changed. She began making overtures to the other
ex-Bangles about re-forming.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy. Not all wounds had healed, but they all
remembered with fondness the ease and beauty of their harmonies.
And the fun they'd had before it all went sour.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they say, it's different. With hindsight, they know
to take things slow, and agree on every, minute point. And they are
adamant that nothing _ money, ego, management _ will come between
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind the Music'' remains one of TV's best-researched and
best-written documentary programs. Although the Bangles' story is
all too familiar in rock 'n' roll, it's told here with style, good
taste and an excellent soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville, Fla., Sun is a member of The New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
