<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BOOK-REVIEWS0727-COX     07-26 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEWS0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Browsing the racks for books on looks
 &HT;    By Sharyn Wizda
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've ever admired the contrasting colors of a western-style
shirt or the fringed, embroidered splendor of a classic
country-and-western singer's jacket, check out ``Hillbilly
Hollywood: The Origins of Country &AMP; Western Style'' (Rizzoli,
$39.95). It features wonderful historic photos, many full-page, of
the clothes and the musicians who wore them _ Roy Rogers, the
Maddox Brothers, Lefty Frizzell, Johnny Cash _ as well as an oral
history of the style.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   I love Bobbi Brown makeup, I really do. And I know that if you
are a 15-year-old girl (or the parent of one), you probably won't
be able to resist getting a copy of ``Bobbi Brown Teenage Beauty:
Everything You Need To Look Pretty, Natural, Sexy and Awesome''
(Cliff Street Books, $25). Still, it's a little creepy. Call me a
reactionary, but some of these girls just have on too much makeup.
Beauty School 101 features a girl with major frosty pink eye
shadow, and a lot of the makeover girls look like slightly older
JonBenets _ beautifully done faces, but a tad inappropriate for
their ages. Brown does get points for peppering her text with
go-girl affirmations (i.e. Be exactly who you are! Supermodels are
freaks of nature!) and including sections on stuff like braces and
proms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   The thought of adding one more thing to your schedule probably
makes you want to run screaming from the room. Breathe easy. What's
suggested by spa guru Peggy Wynne Borgman in ``Four Seasons of
Inner and Outer Beauty: Rituals and Recipes for Well-Being
Throughout the Year'' (Broadway Books, $17.95) are activities
designed to help you cope with the stresses of everyday life.
Borgman's book is a pleasant synthesis of ideas for skin and body
care, healthful recipes and ways to incorporate soothing Eastern
meditation and other rituals into your life. There's nothing too
surprising in here (lighten up your moisturizer in the summer; eat
hearty stews when it's cold), but ``Four Seasons'' is still
refreshing to read _ and a much-healthier stress reliever than a
pint of Ben &AMP;Jerry's.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
