<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3746 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CHENEY-PENTAGON-HNS &LR;      07-26 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-PENTAGON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHENEY WAS A TOUGH BOSS AT THE PENTAGON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Jan. 7, 1991, with preparations in high gear for
war against Iraq, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney cleared his
schedule to render judgment on a top-priority matter that had
nothing to do with Saddam Hussein but which struck at the heart of
the defense chief's efforts to manage the unwieldy Pentagon
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was whether to continue with plans to build a
super-secret stealth aircraft, the A-12 attack jet, the Navy's
version of the radar-evading B-2 bomber. The A-12 was a $57 billion
effort in disarray _ not a single jet had been built but the
project was more than a year behind schedule and at least $1
billion over budget.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last-minute threats of layoffs from the manufacturers
and pleas from the Navy that the plane was its top priority and was
needed to replace older jets, Cheney killed the A-12 program. His
action stunned the military and sent a shockwave through the
defense industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon chief said he made his decision because ``no one
could tell me exactly how much more money it will cost to keep this
program going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we cannot spend the taxpayers' money wisely, we will not
spend it,'' he said.The decision had a personal dimension to it as
well. Only months before, Navy leaders and contractors had given
the defense chief glowing assurances the project was proceeding
apace, assurances that Cheney then relayed to Congress. He had put
his own credibility on the line with lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   But when Cheney found out that the Navy and contractors had
misled him, he ``was ticked,'' said Sean O'Keefe, then the
Pentagon's top financial official. ``He couldn't believe it, that
everybody had duped themselves into believing the A-12 was
salvageable.''
</P>
<P>
   The grisly saga of the demise of the A-12 underscores a Cheney
trait that was in full bloom during his tenure as President Bush's
defense secretary from 1989 through 1993: He was willing to make
unpopular decisions and to exert civilian control over the
military.
</P>
<P>
   His action earned high praise from the New York Times editorial
page _ what many conservatives view as the pinnacle of the liberal
establishment _ which dubbed him a ``hero'' for his ``medal-winning
act of courage'' in killing the A-12 program.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney also defied political stereotypes. Here was a
conservative Republican ordering the death of the most expensive
weapons program ever terminated by the Pentagon. He went on to
eliminate many other weapons programs while choreographing historic
post-Cold War reductions to U.S. defense budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney _ a former six-term congressman from Wyoming _ was named
Tuesday by Texas Gov. George W. Bush as his vice presidential
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   When the Berlin Wall fell in 1989, Cheney began challenging
long-standing U.S. defense policies that guided military spending
and assumed an all-out war in Europe and on the high seas against
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by then-Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman Adm. William Crowe
and later Gen. Colin Powell, Cheney prodded the military brass to
create the first post-Cold War strategy to focus on possible
regional conflicts rather than a colossal war against the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   One result was that Cheney oversaw a sweeping reduction in the
armed forces, paring the military by some 19.4 percent from a force
of 2.2 million in 1989 to 1.7 million by 1993. He also oversaw
large cuts in defense spending, which has fallen over 40 percent
since the end of the Cold War, with most of the cuts designed by
Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   He shut down production lines for the Navy's F-14 and the Air
Force's F-15 jets, the M1-A1 Abrams tank, an Army helicopter
upgrade, the Marine Corp's V-22 Osprey aircraft (later restored by
Congress), the Seawolf submarine and a Navy submarine-hunting
plane.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that angered many in Congress, Cheney proposed
shutting numerous military bases to save money. The reduced size of
the military no longer justified the excess bases, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Congress created the much-dreaded base closure
commission, a non-partisan body that selected bases for
termination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney was the guy who got the base-closure process up and
going, and people didn't like it,'' said John Hamre, a former
senior aide to Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., who at the time was the
chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to credit Dick Cheney. That was a tough
decision,'' said Hamre, who later became deputy defense secretary
in the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney also took bold personnel decisions involving top Air
Force generals, signaling his commitment to civilian control of the
military. In March 1989, shortly after taking over the Pentagon,
Cheney publicly rebuked then-Air Force Chief of Staff Larry Welch
for discussing with Congress possible changes to the
administration's strategic weapons mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gen. Welch was free-lancing,'' Cheney explained at the time.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1990, Cheney fired Welch's successor, Air Force Chief of
Staff Michael Dugan, for telling reporters about plans for the U.S.
air war against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was a ``skillful defense secretary,'' Hamre added. In the
months leading up to the Persian Gulf War, Cheney was particularly
adept at making the administration's case before Congress for going
to war.
</P>
<P>
   ``He effectively brought Congress along. That was a tremendous
accomplishment,'' Hamre said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be contacted at 202-298-6920 or via e-mailL
eric &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
