<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-R-PARMIGIANO-ART-2TAK     07-26 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-PARMIGIANO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO EVERY PARMIGIANO, A SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add art note.)   (editors: two optional sidebars at end of article)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT12 and 13 from 7-25 have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most people who buy Parmigiano-Reggiano never give a
thought to the variations in the way it tastes. Even I always
assumed the flavor differences had to do with the aging process or
the quality of the cheese itself. Parmigiano, after all, always
looks the same. Unlike Cheddars and chevres, it doesn't wear a
brand name or come in different shapes. It's one cheese, all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Or so I thought until last week, when I tasted
Parmigiano-Reggiano produced in fall, winter, spring and summer
side by side. I was amazed at how distinctive each one was: sharp
or sweet or herbaceous, or just intensely buttery like aged cheese.
One was not better than another _ they were just different.
</P>
<P>
   For only a few weeks in July, DiPalo's Italian specialty market
in lower Manhattan's Little Italy is able to offer these handmade
cheeses of all seasons, each two or more years old. The owner, Lou
DiPalo, and a few others like Richard Rogers of Rogers
International Ltd., an importer of specialty foods in Portland,
Maine, make a point of searching out cheeses from certain seasons
and celebrating their individuality. But they are the exception.
Each year, the differences in what is essentially the same cheese
become harder to distinguish.
</P>
<P>
   At a moment when Americans are becoming more interested in
nuances in cheese, the people in charge of guarding the sanctity of
Parmigiano-Reggiano are working hard to standardize it, to erase
the variations that different seasons bring.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, my tasting session at DiPalo's was eye-opening. The
seasonal differences in the cow's milk seemed very definitely to
affect the flavor of the finished cheese.
</P>
<P>
   When the spring cheese, with a slightly pink cast to its
delicate yellow center, was cracked open, its delightfully
herbaceous quality perfumed the air, though the fragrance
dissipated quickly. To me the spring cheese had the most complex
flavor. It was drier and more crumbly than the other cheeses. The
fall Parmigiano was rich and full-flavored, with a bit of bite at
the back of the mouth, the most balanced and polished of the
cheeses. The winter, which is lightest in color, was the most
delicate and sweet, with a nice mouth feel because it had more
butterfat. DiPalo provided two summer cheeses, both different, one
from the hills and one from the plains. These had the deepest
golden color, and the one from the mountains had the texture of
spring, the taste of summer: sharp with an almost acidic afterbite.
</P>
<P>
   What they all had in common was a flaky, slightly grainy
texture, the famous crunch that comes from the crystallization of
the amino acids in the milk as the cheese ages. The older the
cheese, the more grainy and crunchy. But a thin sliver of any of
the cheeses, held in the mouth, seems to melt.
</P>
<P>
   While the more pungent Parmigianos are better for filling
tortellini or ravioli and for grating, the others are better thinly
shaved on top of other ingredients or eaten in chunks out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Consorzio del Formaggio Parmigiano-Reggiano, the industry
group that certifies the authenticity of the cheeses, acknowledges
the existence of the seasonal variations that DiPalo celebrates and
I perceived, but says they are not as great as they once were
because the feeding of the cows has been standardized.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium insists that most differences in taste are due
more to variations in producers. In 1955 the consortium set down
regulations governing the way the cheese must be made. Those who
don't agree with the consortium say that while it may have gotten
rid of the really poor cheeses, it has also gotten rid of the
really great ones.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1984, authentic Parmigiano-Reggiano could be made only
between April 15 and Nov. 15. That made from November to April was
called vernengo. But changes in the breed of cow, the types of feed
and the method of feeding meant that Parmigiano could be made 365
days a year, a fact that the consortium officially acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with a few exceptions in the hills of the region where
the cheese is produced, very few cows are out in pastures grazing.
Instead, special grasses are grown and fed to them in the barns
where they are confined. Because the feed is the same for almost
all the cows, the cheese is far more uniform than anything
available before the regulations were set down.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many professionals can discern differences. Robert
Kaufelt, who owns Murray's Cheese in Greenwich Village, says he has
come to understand that the seasons do make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a tasting, and winter cheese is better than summer,'' he
said. Lou Todaro, who owns Todaro Brothers, buys only winter
Parmigiano-Reggiano, which he also thinks is the best.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Rogers of Rogers International buys spring and fall
cheeses only. ``We deal with cows that graze only on natural
grasses,'' he said. ``We emphasize a very narrow niche.'' Rogers
has also been buying some of the very small production from the
Razza Reggiana breed of cows, which used to provide the milk for
all Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese. The milk of the Razza Reggiana, or
vacca rossa (red cow), is much richer and higher in protein, and
the cheese can be aged much longer than that from the current herds
of Frisona Italiana, which are the progeny of Dutch Holsteins. Red
cow Parmigiano is also about 80 percent more expensive, Rogers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even chefs are often aware of seasonal differences. At Frank, a
trattoria in the East Village, Frank Prisinzano serves a plate of
two to four different seasonal Parmigiano-Reggianos with figs,
peaches or pears. And at Peasant, an Italian restaurant in Nolita,
Frank DeCarlo prefers the spring and winter cheeses and matches
them with food.
</P>
<P>
   Max McCalman, who is in charge of the cheeses at Picholine,
prefers the summer cheeses, although he finds any
Parmigiano-Reggiano a hard sell on his cheese board because diners
presume to know the cheese already.
</P>
<P>
   But Mario Batali, the chef at Babbo, does not see much
difference among the cheeses. ``In a blind tasting I can't tell
which season is which,'' he said. ``Spring cheese tastes more
herbaceous, but that's all I'm prepared to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Parmigiano-Reggiano, a raw milk cheese, has been made for at
least 700 years in a region of northern Italy that consists of the
provinces of Parma, Modena, Reggio Emilia and parts of Bologna and
Mantua. The district where Parmigiano is made has about 9,000
dairies and about 600 cheese makers. The only ingredients in the
cheese are milk, rennet and salt. The entire rind of each wheel of
authentic Parmigiano is imprinted with the name as the cheese is
being shaped, as well as the month and the year. Cheeses are aged
18 months to three years, sometimes longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing but good things to say about the consorzio that
protects the quality of Parmigiano-Reggiano,'' Pamela Sheldon Johns
writes in ``Italian Food Artisans'' (Chronicle Books, $24.95).
``But with big business comes standardization. More and more
dairies are forming cooperatives, and the independent
dairyman-cheese maker is becoming rare. With the disappearance of
the individual artisan goes some of the distinct differences
evident in the past, such as floral qualities in a mountain spring
cheese, or the rich, pungent character in a plains-produced autumn
cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johns goes on to say that fortunately, variations still persist,
because it is impossible to standardize artisanal products so they
always look and taste exactly the same, like Velveeta.
</P>
<P>
   In an introduction to a 1998 cookbook produced by the
consortium, Lynne Rossetto Kasper, an expert on Italian food, says:
``The secrets of Parmigiano-Reggiano's quality are found in its
inconsistencies. In a world of mass-produced sameness this cheese
is made by hand, usually only 8 or 12 wheels at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Topography also plays a role,'' she says, and ``cheeses from
the hills and cheeses from the plains are never quite alike.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview last week, Kasper was not quite so
complimentary, contending that the consortium had narrowed the
range of quality. ``Before 10 or 15 years ago there was lousy
cheese, middle-road cheese, high-good cheese and extraordinary
cheese,'' she said. ``In the '70s, it was not unusual to taste
something pretty special, and it was easy to find. The consorzio
got rid of the stuff at the bottom and discouraged the
extraordinary stuff, concentrating on the high good. They saw a
market that couldn't tell the difference between high good and
extraordinary. I think the quality has definitely gone down, and I
think it was stupid, because it commands a premium price and there
are so many alternative cheeses for people to buy today.''
</P>
<P>
   But the consortium maintains that standardization is necessary
to improve the bottom line. ``Americans and northern Europeans
equate consistency with quality,'' said Nancy Radke, the director
of communications for the consortium in the United States. ``It is
counter to artisan products, but in this industrialized world this
is a fact of life. There is a certain sadness that some of that
variation is lost, and with the European Union rules for hygiene,
cheese like this will become an endangered species.''
</P>
<P>
   Mario Zannoni, a sensory analyst for the department of quality
control for the consortium, defends the standardization. ``The
consorzio has reached a reasonably good quality,'' he said. ``A
portion of the production is considered very good. I'm not sure we
had extraordinary cheese before. I think we had very good cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is less variation between the seasons because of the
feeding standardizations. There is still an effect of the seasons
and of the ripening, but it is less than before. The variations are
connected more with the cheese factory than the seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   DiPalo, however, maintains that the seasons are the primary
reason for the differences and that the cheeses he chooses
celebrate the differences. ``I know,'' he said, ``because I have
cut thousands of pounds of cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   DiPalo, whose family has been selling Italian delicacies since
1925, is happy to acknowledge that he is a dinosaur. ``I'm very
traditional,'' he said, ``and I've taken it upon myself to search
out seasonal changes. It's an art that requires a lot of time and
patience on my part and the part of those who buy for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement to bring back the vacca rossa may be to his
benefit. Since 1990 a group of 10 breeders have been making cheese
exclusively with this milk, and DiPalo is expecting a shipment of
their cheese shortly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consorzio is making a big mistake conforming to the
plastic world,'' he said. ``They are telling you this is what you
like, this is what you are going to eat, but I'm going to continue
to look for cheeses with different characteristics.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBARS FOLLOW)
</P>
<P>
   SPRING, SUMMER, AUTUMN, WINTER: A Quartet to Make Vivaldi Sing &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By MARIAN BURROS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to experiment with seasonal variations in
Parmigiano-Reggiano, here are tips from Lou DiPalo of DiPalo's and
Frank DeCarlo, the owner and chef of Peasant:
</P>
<P>
   Top buttered steamed asparagus with shaved spring
Parmigiano-Reggiano, and run it under the broiler to melt and brown
the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Top paper-thin slices of bres-aola with shaved winter
Parmigiano-Reggiano on a bed of arugula; drizzle with extra virgin
olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Add grated summer Parmigiano-Reggiano to a frittata with onions
and peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Top very thin slices of prosciutto with slightly thicker slices
of winter Parmigiano-Reggiano over baby dandelion greens, and serve
with fresh figs drizzled with olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   As for complementary wines, DiPalo recommends Chianti or merlot
for fall Parmigiano-Reggiano, prosecco or pinot bianco from Friuli
for winter cheese, Dolcetto d'Alba for spring cheese. Summer cheese
is not good for eating out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGING A CHEESE BY ITS RIND
</P>
<P>
   By MARIAN BURROS
</P>
<P>
   Even if you cannot choose Parmigiano-Reggiano by the season,
here are some rules for getting the best available and storing it
properly:
</P>
<P>
   Look for the date and year the cheese was made, imprinted on the
rind. If the rind has ``X'' marks, the cheese has been rejected by
regulators because it did not meet their standards.
</P>
<P>
   Never buy grated Parmigiano-Reggiano: It loses its flavor. If
you grate cheese, use it within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Buy cheese that has been cracked into wedges, rather than
sliced, which changes the texture.
</P>
<P>
   Cheese should have a crisp but not very dry texture; the color
is not indicative of quality or taste.
</P>
<P>
   Ask for cheese that has been stored either at the proper aging
temperature or in a refrigerated case. At home, remove the plastic
wrap and let the cheese sit at room temperature for a few minutes;
then rewrap it with plastic film and cover with aluminum foil or
parchment paper. Change the wrap every time the cheese is used, or
at least once a week. Keep the cheese in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   If a piece of cheese has become old and dry, wrap it in a
moistened cheesecloth, cover with aluminum foil and refrigerate for
a day. Then, rewrap in plastic. If mold develops on the outside,
clean it off; otherwise, it will bore through the cheese and spoil
it.
</P>
<P>
   If you use the rinds to add flavor to minestrone or chicken
soup, wash the outside first.
</P>
</TEXT>
