A3759 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-ACTOR-FRANCHISE0727-C     07-26 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTOR-FRANCHISE0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Generation X TMEN
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Veteran British actors Patrick Stewart, Ian
McKellen and Christopher Lee have become franchise players.
</P>
<P>
   Ranging in age from 60 to 78, the venerable thespians have
scored recurring roles in multiple sci-fi and fantasy film series,
including ``Star Wars,'' ``Star Trek,'' ``The Lord of the Rings''
and ``X-Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 60, enjoyed lengthy stage careers with both the Royal
Shakespeare Company and the Royal National Theatre before coming to
Los Angeles in 1987 for the role of Jean-Luc Picard in television's
``Star Trek: The Next Generation.'' Stewart has continued the role
in three ``Star Trek'' films, with plans for a fourth to be
released Thanksgiving 2001.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Stewart has assumed the identity of ``X-Men's''
wheelchair-bound telepath, Professor Charles Xavier. The big-screen
adaptation of the classic Marvel comics series made $99.3 million
in its first two weekends, ensuring a succession of sequels.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart is contracted for at least one more ``X-Men'' film, as
is McKellen, who plays his evil nemesis, Magneto.
</P>
<P>
   McKellen, 61, is considered one of contemporary theater's finest
classical actors, particularly for his interpretations of
Shakespeare. Knighted in 1990, McKellen won a Tony Award in 1981
for his portrayal of Salieri in the Broadway production of
``Amadeus.'' He earned a 1998 Academy Award nomination for best
actor for ``Gods and Monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to playing Magneto, McKellen will star as Gandalf
the wizard in Peter Jackson's forthcoming three-part adaptation of
J.R.R. Tolkien's ``The Lord of the Rings'' trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   Legendary horror-film star Lee, 78, will play opposite McKellen
as the evil wizard Saruman. The first film is slated to arrive in
theaters December 2001. The second and third installments are
scheduled for December 2002 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, whose extensive Hammer Films credits include ``The Curse of
Frankenstein'' and ``The Horror of Dracula,'' also will appear as a
``charismatic separatist'' in George Lucas' second ``Star Wars''
prequel, now being filmed in Australia for a summer 2002 release.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a brief look at the status of each of the four film
franchises, from their official Web sites and other related
sources:
</P>
<P>
   ``STAR TREK''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Logan has been tapped to write the script for the 10th film
in the series, officially known as ``Star Trek X.'' Logan's
previous credits include 1999's ``Bats'' and work on the
screenplays for ``Gladiator'' and ``Any Given Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Producer Rick Berman told ``Star Trek Communicator'' magazine
that it will be ``a very action-oriented story that revolves around
a remarkable villain. A higher percentage of this film will take
place in outer space than in our previous films.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Frakes, who directed the last two ``Star Trek'' films,
in addition to co-starring as Cmdr. William Riker, may not be
available to direct the next installment. Frakes has a sci-fi
project, ``Clockstoppers,'' in development at Paramount. If that
film gets a green light, it could head into production the same
time as Star Trek X, according to Cinescape Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I would just be an actor, I guess, in the ``Star Trek''
movie,'' Frakes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``STAR WARS''
</P>
<P>
   The second Star Wars prequel began shooting on June 26 _ three
years to the day that ``Episode I `` started its shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Hales (''The Young Indiana Jones Chronicles'') is the
co-screenwriter for the second chapter in the Star Wars saga, with
director Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas is shooting ``Star Wars: Episode II'' using digital
cameras in place of film for most of the movie's live-action
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden Christensen, a 19-year-old Canadian actor most recently
seen in the Fox Family Channel series ``Higher Ground,'' has been
selected to play Anakin Skywalker in ``Episodes II'' and ``III,''
filling the role that was played by 8-year-old Jake Lloyd in ``The
Phantom Menace'' and 82-year-old Sebastian Shaw in ``Return of the
Jedi.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning cast members include Ewan McGregor (Obi-Wan Kenobi),
Natalie Portman (Queen Amidala), Samuel L. Jackson (Mace Windu),
Frank Oz (Yoda), Ian McDiarmid (Senator Palpatine), Anthony Daniels
(C-3PO) and, alas, Ahmed Best (Jar Jar Binks).
</P>
<P>
   Besides Lee, ``NYPD Blue'''s Jimmy Smits joins the cast as
Senator Bail Organa of Alderaan, a character briefly mentioned in
``Star Wars: Episode IV _ A New Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``THE LORD OF THE RINGS''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is shooting his three-part adaptation of Tolkien's epic
fantasy simultaneously, with New Zealand substituting for
Middle-earth. The three films have a combined budget of $130
million. Filming began Oct. 11, 1999 and continues through March
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and writing partner Frances Walsh adapted Tolkien's
trilogy along with Philippa Boyens and Stephen Sinclair. Jackson
and Walsh earned an Oscar nomination for ``Heavenly Creatures.''
Directed by Jackson, that film launched Kate Winslet's career.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to McKellen and Lee, ``The Lord of the Rings''' cast
includes Elijah Wood (Frodo Baggins), Ian Holm (Bilbo Baggins),
Sean Astin (Sam Gamgee), Viggo Mortensen (Aragorn), Cate Blanchett
(Galadriel), Liv Tyler (Arwen), Hugo Weaving (Elrond), John
Rhys-Davies (Gimli), Sean Bean (Boromir) and Orlando Bloom
(Legolas).
</P>
<P>
   The character of Gollum will be computer-generated, with a voice
supplied by Andy Serkis (''Topsy-Turvy''). Details on how the dark
lord, Sauron, is represented are sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the characters will speak in British accents. Jackson
also plans to utilize the different languages described in
Tolkien's books, with subtitles for those who don't speak Elvish.
</P>
<P>
   New Line Cinema has announced a major merchandising agreement
with Marvel Enterprises to supply ``Lord of the Rings `` toys and
products.
</P>
<P>
   A 36-year-old man was arrested in the theft of film clips of
Gollum and other secret special effects from Jackson's studio. He
purportedly tried to post them on the Internet. After a monthlong
probe, the man was charged with making a VHS copy of film footage
and money-laundering. The suspect's name has not been released.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-MEN''
</P>
<P>
   ``After a well-earned rest, the producers will regroup with Fox
next week to plan the ``X-Men'' sequel,'' McKellen reported this
week on his Web site, www.McKellen.com. ``Patrick (Stewart) and I
are contracted to take part.''
</P>
<P>
   However, ``X-Men'' director Bryan Singer and producer Tom
DeSanto have yet to sign for another film, according to Cinescape
Online.
</P>
<P>
   The mutant heroes enjoyed an X-cellent debut, making $54.5
million in the film's first weekend. It was the biggest July
opening ever, as well as the sixth-highest weekend gross and the
biggest nonsequel opening of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Singer has hinted that the next film may escalate the battle
between humanity and mutants with the addition of giant, robotic
Sentinels.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
