<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV13-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., AUG. 13, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: My unfinished basement has many exposed cold water pipes
running through and between the overhead beams.
 &HT;    During hot humid weather these pipes ``sweat'' and often drip
onto the basement floor and on furniture stored there.
 &HT;    Is there something you can suggest that I can do to prevent this
from happening?
 &HT;    A: The problem can be eliminated by covering all the pipes with
foam insulation.
 &HT;    This comes in a tubular, sleeve form that is designed for this
purpose and is sold in home centers and hardware stores.
 &HT;    Available in various sizes to fit different diameter pipes, the
easiest kind to install is the version that comes in sleeves which
are slit open lengthwise to simplify fitting them over existing
pipes.
 &HT;    These have self-adhesive seams, making them easy to seal
lengthwise along each seam.
 &HT;    The joints where individual lengths meet are sealed by wrapping
with duct tape or a seam-sealing tape available at the same store.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: We have a large porch awning that was custom-made and
consists of a fabric tightly stretched over aluminum strips that
support it.
 &HT;    After three years the material has stretched so much that the
awning is now leaking at the seams and allows water to drip through
onto my carpet and furniture.
 &HT;    Is there any way I can seal or waterproof these areas and
preserve the awning?
 &HT;    A: Most marine supply stores sell a waterproofing sealer for use
on boat covers and awnings.
 &HT;    Although I cannot say for sure, it is possible that this might
work on your awning. At least it is worth a try.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Several of my storm windows collect moisture on the inside of
the storm window _ between it and the prime window.
 &HT;    So much accumulates that it actually runs down and has caused
some wood rot at the bottom of one window frame. This only happens
on some of the windows, not on all of them.
 &HT;    Short of removing the storm windows, what can I do about this
problem?
 &HT;    A: The usual reason for this is a lack of adequate weather
stripping around the inside windows, at least those where this
occurs.
 &HT;    Warm moist air from inside the house seeps out around the edges
of the window sash and gets trapped in the space between the two
windows.
 &HT;    When this moist air comes in contact with the cold glass of the
outside storm window, the moisture condenses on the glass to form
drops of water that eventually run down the glass.
 &HT;    Increasing the quality or amount of weather stripping around
these windows will prevent moist air escaping from the inside, thus
eliminating the condensation problem.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Ever since I installed a new ball cock inlet valve unit in my
toilet flush tank we notice that just before the tank is full and
the inlet valve shuts off, it makes a loud hissing noise.
 &HT;    Can you tell me what could be causing this?
 &HT;    A: Some brands of ball cock are much quieter than others, so it
is possible that by installing a different model you will eliminate
this nuisance.
 &HT;    It's also possible that this can be caused by too much water
pressure in your system.
 &HT;    There should be a shut-off valve on the intake line under your
tank, so try closing this down a little _ it should help.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``INSULATING A PIPE WITH FOAM SLEEVE''
goes with this column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Sleeves of foam insulation slipped around cold water
pipes will keep the pipes from ``sweating.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
