<HEADER>
A3770 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-HNS &LR;      07-26 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SENATE UNVEILS INTERNET PRIVACY BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain and other leading lawmakers
proposed legislation Wednesday that could dramatically increase the
privacy rights of consumers using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, business should inform consumers in an open manner
how they treat personal information and give consumers meaningful
choices as to how that information is used,'' McCain, R-Ariz., told
a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, was joined by
Sens. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., John Kerry, D-Mass., and Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, known as the ``Consumer Privacy Enhancement Act,''
would require Web sites to post a notice describing:
</P>
<P>
   _ What companies are collecting information via that Web site;
</P>
<P>
   _ The types of information collected;
</P>
<P>
   _ How the information will be used;
</P>
<P>
   _ What security measures are in place to protect information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bill will arm consumers with information so they feel
confident they are making the right choices to protect their
personal information, and our approach does so without shutting
down the industry's potential for growth or choking the free flow
of information on the Internet,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, Web sites failing to abide by the law would be
fined $22,000 per violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surfing the Web shouldn't require you to share your life story
with the world,'' Boxer said. ``Internet surfers should know
exactly how companies will use the personal information submitted
to Web sites.''
</P>
<P>
   If the bill became law, for example, an on-line bookseller would
be required to let customers know that it is collecting information
on what they are buying, and then selling that information to
advertisers or other electronic retailers.
</P>
<P>
   With the issue of Internet privacy registering in the polls as a
top concern among Americans, Democrats and Republicans have been
pushing to find legislation that would reassure the public that
private information will not be misused.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen Internet privacy bills are being considered in
the House. In addition, several bills in the Senate contain
provisions for increasing Internet privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Both the presidential hopefuls, Republican George W. Bush and
Democrat Al Gore, have expressed support for a privacy law covering
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The debate generally divides along three lines:
</P>
<P>
   _ Should consumers have to ``opt out,'' informing companies that
they would rather not have their personal information divulged
elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   _ Should on-line companies have to ask permission first,
requiring customers to ``opt in'' to a consent agreement that frees
their information for use in the public domain?
</P>
<P>
   _ Or should the current system, in which information moves
through cyberspace virtually unrestricted, remain intact?
</P>
<P>
   Direct-marketing companies have always kept dossiers on consumer
habits in order to target people for specific products and
services. The Internet makes that process much easier and more
immediate.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who browse the Web now have their habits tracked,
thanks to small software files known as ``cookies'' that are
transferred from certain Web sites to the consumer's computer hard
drive while the user is on line.
</P>
<P>
   The cookies create a roadmap of the user's on-line browsing
habits, allowing companies to compile information on what the
consumer is interested in looking at and buying. Although cookies
can be removed from a user's hard drive, people who intentionally
disable their computer's ability to accept cookies are often denied
access to some Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The information gathered by using cookies allows advertisers to
know which users would likely buy their products. As a result, a
great deal is at stake for on-line companies, some of which have
based their success on the ability to gather consumer information
freely in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Many leading on-line companies, aware of concerns about
confidence, say they already take steps to ensure privacy and see
political motivations behind the current flurry of privacy
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Mahler, vice president of the Computer and Communications
Industry Association, a Washington-based consortium of Internet
companies, said many politicians are ``rushing'' to pass
legislation without considering the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the vast majority of Internet sites are free, but
they rely heavily on the money they make gathering and selling
marketing information on consumers,'' he said. ``If you take that
away, many Web sites will either go out of business or be forced to
start charging fees, something I don't think consumers would be
very happy about.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahler said on-line companies are developing their own
regulations that will ``balance'' privacy rights with the needs of
Web sites to make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel that people who understand the industry should be
the ones to come up with the rules,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
