<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-COMMENTARY-GARCIA27-C     07-26 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-GARCIA27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sanchez would put a new face on 2002
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the rhetoric politicians employ about change, they are
skittish as cattle before a storm when the status quo is truly
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a Tony Sanchez gubernatorial candidacy has local
politicos scrambling to rewrite their scenarios of the state's
future. Sanchez, a wealthy Laredo lawyer and businessman reportedly
worth $600 million, represents a threat to the establishments of
both Democratic and Republican parties.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a Latino who doesn't have to ask anybody's permission to
run. Here's a Latino who won't be impressed with lectures about
electability and the need to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   He's rich, and he's ready now. And he's not the kind of guy to
be overly concerned with who likes it. And that's what has
Democrats and Republicans alike reaching for the antacid tablets.
</P>
<P>
   Though Sanchez hasn't said publicly that he will run, he's left
tracks that Jose Feliciano could follow. He was traveling in
California last week, but close friends say that barring a
catastrophe, he will be running for the Democratic nomination for
governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility is a headache for Republicans and Democrats for
the same reason: He is a wealthy businessman who should be able to
excite Hispanic voters who have not voted in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is a businessman (banking and oil and gas, among
other interests), Republicans will have a tough time depicting him
as wild-eyed liberal. After all, he has and continues to be a
generous financial backer of Gov. George W. Bush, who appointed
Sanchez to the University of Texas Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is a businessman and a contributor to the governor,
liberal Democrats _ particularly the ones who love to tell Latinos
what's good for them _ will grumble that he isn't ``pure'' enough.
Or should that read ``poor'' enough?
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, though. A vato from the barrio isn't going to be
governor. That's a competition where you have to bring lots money _
yours or somebody else's _ to play.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it, a Sanchez candidacy would be a radical
departure from business as usual for both parties. Republicans
realize that growth of the Hispanic population in Texas means they
have to reach out to maintain control. Democrats have too long
taken the Hispanic vote for granted, and some are still slow to
acknowledge that the key to recapturing statewide offices lost over
the past several elections lies in that same growth.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican operative opined that a Tony Sanchez candidacy
would speed the state's political evolution significantly.
Hispanics will play a bigger role in directing the state's future,
he said, it's just a matter of time. Throw Sanchez in that picture
and you fast forward to that day.
</P>
<P>
   I always thought that it would be 10 or so years before a viable
Latino candidate for governor would emerge and that he or she would
likely be Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The Sanchez prospect obviously paints a much different picture.
</P>
<P>
   In the two decades since Raul Gonzalez, the first Hispanic to be
elected statewide, there has been an unofficial quota system when
it comes to holding office. Gonzalez was elected to the Texas
Supreme Court, and you can count on the fingers of one hand the
number of Tejanos who have followed him: Dan Morales, a Democrat,
was elected attorney general; Tony Garza, a Republican, was elected
to the Railroad Commission and Al Gonzales, another Republican, was
elected to Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The message from both parties seemed to be, ``We like y'all, but
not too many of you at the same time, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Below state level, things have been better but not much. It
won't take you long to count the number of Hispanics elected
countywide in Travis County _ which loves to proclaim itself the
capital of inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   So, Sanchez as a candidate will force big changes in the
political calculus up and down the ballot and across parties. And
with $25 million to $30 million of his own money to toss in the
race, he can buy a lot of calculators.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Sanchez is teaching operatives in both parties a
new phrase:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ay, dios.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
