<P>
   CLINTON-MIDEAST-0727 _ WASHINGTON _ As the dust settled
Wednesday from the collapse of the Camp David summit, it became
clear that this wasn't the final act in the long-playing drama of
President Clinton's quest for a Mideast peace deal. With a Sept. 13
deadline looming, Clinton and his aides pivoted to the challenge of
trying to help Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat build a consensus for compromise among their
respective people. Clinton has a few cards left in his deck, said
private analysts, including the prospect of dispatching a special
envoy such as Jimmy Carter, who has enormous cache across the Arab
world, to try to help bring Arafat closer toward an accord. (Deans,
Cox News Service).
