<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3773 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-COKE-CADBURY0727-COX     07-26 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-CADBURY0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke leaves Cadbury deal in Canada, Mexico
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Coca-Cola Co. is abandoning efforts to buy Cadbury
Schweppes' beverages in Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The brands in those countries were part of an original $1.85
billion deal in which Coke planned to buy Cadbury Schweppes'
beverages, except those sold in the United States, France and South
Africa. The drinks included Dr Pepper, Canada Dry, Crush and the
Schweppes line of mixers.
</P>
<P>
   But the December 1998 deal, which was former Chairman M. Douglas
Ivester's first major acquisition as head of the company, has been
plagued in some countries by government concerns over Coca-Cola's
market dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said we're committed to playing by the house rules
wherever we do business,'' Coca-Cola Chairman Doug Daft said
Wednesday in announcing the decision on Canada and Mexico. ``The
authorities in both countries have made their concerns clear, and
we are simply respecting those concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, Coke has scaled back the Cadbury Schweppes
acquisition, including in much of Europe, to allay those concerns.
The deal now covers 161 countries and is valued at about $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Daft, who replaced Ivester in February, has stressed that the
company wants to improve relations with local governments. He has
moved more decision-making away from Coke's headquarters and posted
his top executives in the territories they oversee.
</P>
<P>
   Beverage Digest Editor John Sicher said Coke's decision to drop
Mexico and Canada and get the Cadbury Schweppes deal behind it
reflects Daft's thinking that his company has ``bigger fish to fry
and bigger opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Daft wants to press regulators to approve deals
they don't feel comfortable with,'' Sicher said. ``He wants to put
pressure on his company to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   With Cadbury Schweppes brands, Coke's market share in Canada
would have climbed to 49.1 percent from 39.4 percent, vs. 34.3
percent for Pepsi, according to Beverage Digest. The rise in Mexico
would have been less dramatic _ to 72.6 percent from 68.4 percent,
vs. 19.7 percent for Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Conway, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said
that while the brands would have been ``terrifically
complementary'' to Coke's operations, ``it's not a negative that
they don't get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Rob Baskin said Coke and Cadbury Schweppes
still need regulatory approval in some countries but do not expect
problems. ``The deal is substantially complete,'' Baskin said.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin would not comment on whether Coca-Cola is considering
other acquisitions. There is industry speculation that the company
is weighing a stake in the SoBe line of herbal and vitamin-enhanced
juices and teas.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Coca-Cola's stock ended Wednesday at $58.57,
down 44 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
