<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3776 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BRIAN-WILSON0727-COX     07-26 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIAN-WILSON0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cruising just as fast as he can now
 &HT;    By Steve Uhler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Brian Wilson playing a gig in Austin happens
only slightly more often than Mozart playing a dinner show in
Branson, Mo. _ which is never.
</P>
<P>
   But after 35 years of lying low, the reclusive pop legend will
play at The Backyard tonight, which qualifies as a local musical
Event with a capital ``e.'' Backed by a crackerjack band that
includes members of Poi Dog Pondering and the Wondermints, Wilson
has toured the country this summer playing to appreciative _ and in
some cases, disbelieving _ sell-out crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Wilson? The leader and co-founder of the Beach Boys? The
pop prodigy who wrote such confectionery classics as ``I Get
Around,'' ``California Girls'' and ``Good Vibrations'' (all of
which he has been performing on tour), and who recorded 11 albums
in four years, all before he was 24? The clean-cut kid who conjured
a musical, mythical California of sun, surf, girls and cars that
persists in the world's collective imagination? The rock 'n' roll
auteur who was writing, producing and arranging his own records a
full year before the Beatles?
</P>
<P>
   Yup, that Brian Wilson. Or rather, those Brian Wilsons. Because
there are as many Brian Wilsons as there are stories about him _
and there are some very bizarre stories about him. His genius and
eccentricities are the stuff of pop-culture legend. He is the
Howard Hughes of rock. A notoriously shy recluse who suffered from
severe stage fright, Wilson stopped touring with the Beach Boys in
1964 after he had a nervous breakdown, and he has seldom performed
live since. But, after decades of troubled waters, the surf's up
again for Brian Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going great, going great,'' he says over the phone before
a sound check. Wilson sounds focused, energized and upbeat _ an
encouraging sign for those who have charted his tumultuous life.
``We're having a lot of fun. We're getting ovations, standing
ovations wherever we go. People love us. . . . They think we're
fantastic!''
</P>
<P>
   If said by any other rock deity, that statement would come
across as egomaniacal hyperbole, but from Brian Wilson, it sounds
strangely endearing and self-effacing. He seems genuinely surprised
and happy that audiences and critics are responding so warmly to
his against-all-bets return to performing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it,'' he says in that childlike delivery he
conveys in conversation. ``They're reacting to all the songs.
They're going bananas for everything!''
</P>
<P>
   His enthusiasm is infectious.
</P>
<P>
   'PET SOUNDS'
</P>
<P>
   In a savvy choice that embraces both his greatest artistic
success and most disappointing commercial defeat, the tour is
showcasing Wilson's epochal 1966 masterpiece, ``Pet Sounds.'' No
less an authority than Paul McCartney has called ``Pet Sounds''
``perhaps the album of the century . . . unbeatable in many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, ``Pet Sounds'' was a radical departure for Wilson and
the Beach Boys. Jettisoning the fun 'n' sun formula that had made
the group so successful, Wilson created a spiritual, complex album
about the fragile and ever-changing nature of love. The music of
``Pet Sounds'' (with lyrics by Tony Asher) is peppered with
timeless, breathtaking touchstones _ the wistful, upbeat optimism
of ``Wouldn't It Be Nice?,'' the spiritual incandescence of ``God
Only Knows,'' and the pure heartbreak of ``Caroline, No.''
</P>
<P>
   Although critics and musicians immediately recognized ``Pet
Sounds'' as a towering achievement, the album sold disappointingly.
``Capitol didn't believe in it at all,'' Wilson says, still
sounding wounded. ``They didn't have any faith in it.'' Instead,
the record company rushed into stores a Beach Boys greatest hits
album scarcely six weeks after the release of ``Pet Sounds,''
effectively snuffing out any commercial chance the record may have
had.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Pet Sounds,'' Wilson's life began to collapse under a
series of calamitous events. He spent months of studio time and
substantial dollars recording ``Smile,'' the much-anticipated
follow-up to ``Pet Sounds,'' only to abandon the project when the
Beatles released ``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band.'' His
father, Murry Wilson, sold the publishing rights to all of Brian's
songs, effectively denying his son millions in future royalties.
</P>
<P>
   A depressed Wilson retreated to his Bel-Air mansion, ballooned
to 300 pounds and stayed in bed for nearly two years. His 15-year
marriage to high school sweetheart Marilyn Rovell fell apart in
1979. Then came the notorious ``Landy Decade.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, an increasingly fragile Wilson was put under the
dubious care of behavioral therapist Eugene Landy. Originally hired
to wean Wilson from drugs, Landy burrowed his way into Wilson's
life, siphoning off his assets and taking co-writing and
co-producing credits for most of Wilson's solo work. As Wilson
tried to cope, his younger brother and original Beach Boy, Dennis,
drowned in 1983. Then, in an ugly court battle, cousin and fellow
Beach Boy Mike Love, who had written the lyrics to many of the
group's early hits, sued Wilson over songwriting royalties.
</P>
<P>
   It's fodder for a bad TV mini-series _ which is exactly what
happened earlier this year when ABC aired ``The Beach Boys: An
American Family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I saw it; I sure did,'' Wilson says. ``I thought it was
not that factual. I thought the characters were way out of line. I
didn't like it, personally. The guy who played me was way out of
whack.''
</P>
<P>
   A NEW BEGINNING
</P>
<P>
   Happily, things have turned around for Wilson. He married
Melinda Ledbetter in 1995; the couple has two new daughters. Don
Was filmed a well-received 1995 documentary on Wilson, ``I Just
Wasn't Made for These Times,'' that introduced a new audience to
his serious work. In 1996, Capitol issued a four-CD box set, ``The
Pet Sounds Sessions,'' which sold surprisingly well. And his 1998
solo album, ``Imagination,'' helped re-establish Wilson as a
still-vital artist.
</P>
<P>
   He even has a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're selling a live album over the Web site _
brianwilson.com. My wife handles it,'' Wilson says. ``It started
kinda slow, but it's picking up.''
</P>
<P>
   In six weeks, Rhino Records will re-release Wilson's first solo
album, 1988's ``Brian Wilson,'' featuring the lushly healing ``Love
and Mercy.'' ``I hope they promote it,'' he says. ``It could sell.
It's a good album. It really is.''
</P>
<P>
   For someone whose mercurial life has been so scrupulously
documented, Wilson has a refreshingly benign perspective on his
public image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people think of me as some kind of a little Junior
Maharishi, y'know? Like from the mid-'60s _ a peace-and-love kind
of person.'' And how does Wilson see himself these days? He pauses
before answering, without a trace of self-consciousness, ``I think
of myself as the bringer of good things to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Brian Wilson happy, at peace with his present as much as
with his past, and making great music under the stars on a summer
evening in Austin. Wouldn't it be nice.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
