<HEADER>
A3780 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-NEWBORNS-BOOKS-BOS &LR;      07-26 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWBORNS-BOOKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKING ON A BABY'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and l coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAPHAEL LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENNINGTON, Vt. _ Kristina Criss looked on with a cheek-to-cheek
grin as her son Seth devoured his new book, ``Pussycat Pussycat.''
</P>
<P>
   Someday, Criss's pediatrician said, the 6-month-old will
actually read the book, rather than chomping on its corners with
his toothless mouth. Regardless, Dr. Donna Miller said, the book
was a gift for Seth to do with as he saw fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this age, they're going to chew their books more than
listen to you read them,'' Miller told Criss, as Seth gurgled on
the examining table. ``You give him another few months, and he'll
be pointing things out on the pages.''
</P>
<P>
   Such are the scenes playing out across Vermont these days, a few
weeks into an ambitious, privately financed program that promises
every baby born in Vermont this year a small library of books. The
program, Born to Read 2000, comes in the form of a tote bag full of
children's books, a videotape instructing parents on how to read to
a newborn, and a list of other age-appropriate books.
</P>
<P>
   The packages, distributed at a baby's six-month checkup, will
likely make their way into more than 7,000 homes this year, said
Maxine Brandenburg, president of the Vermont Business Roundtable, a
group of 115 Vermont CEOs who dreamed up the program and provided
much of the more than $500,000 to put it together.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the program is that, when it comes to child
development, there's not much time to waste. Research into the
cognitive development of infants has shown that exposure to books
at a young age accelerates and aids a child's ability to speak,
understand, and read, said Dr. Paula Duncan, principal assistant to
the secretary of the Vermont Department of Health and a
pediatrician who helped develop Born to Read.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, the need to help parents expose their infants to
books is apparent in the findings of several recent reports.
According to the National Survey of Kindergarten Teachers, 28
percent of Vermont's kindergartners are ill-prepared to participate
successfully in school. One reason, specialists say, is that many
parents are incapable of preparing their children. About 12 percent
of Vermont adults are are illiterate and cannot read a children's
book, according to the National Institute for Literacy.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, developers of Born to Read 2000 say they want the program
to help acquaint parents with books as well. One last goody in the
tote bag is a voucher for another free book, which parents can pick
up at their local library. The idea is to get parents interested in
their public libraries, in hopes that they might like what they
see, said Grace Greene, children's services consultant for the
Vermont Department of Libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my perspective, the important part is for people to
understand that they have a lifelong supply of books in their
public libraries,'' said Greene, who developed the voucher idea.
``What we hope is the voucher will take people into public
libraries that would not normally go in. People don't always know
that there are materials for very young children in libraries, and
that material has grown tremendously recently.''
</P>
<P>
   Modeled in part after Reach Out and Read, an early childhood
literacy program developed in the late 1980s by doctors at the
Boston City Hospital, Born to Read 2000 is the result of more than
a year's worth of development and collaboration by Vermont
corporations, educators, public agencies, doctors, and librarians
on a level never before attempted.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Reach Out and Read, which requires participating
pediatricians to raise the money for the books, Born to Read
provides the books to the doctors. So far, however, the fledgling
program only has enough funding to provide books for babies born
this year, and only for their six-month visit, Brandenburg said. By
comparison, Reach Out and Read provides books to children at
various intervals until their fifth birthday.
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear whether enough companies and donors will
sign on to make Born to Read permanent, Brandenburg said, although
officials are busy trying to keep it going.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Born to Read 2000 has Vermont's literacy advocates
beaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those programs that you have dreams about,''
said Sally Anderson, executive director of the Vermont Center for
the Book, an affiliate agency of the Library of Congress that
promotes early literacy. ``You always hoped, maybe someday, every
child in the state will get a packet of books from the doctor, and
then it actually happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people across the state are working to ensure that
all the babies born this year will get their tote bag _ no easy
feat, given the patchwork of tiny hamlets that constitute the
majority of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Vermont Business Roundtable began
shipping out shrink-wrapped packages from the warehouse
distribution center of one company in the organization. Another
corporation produced the instructional video, and still others
orchestrated advertising campaigns that have barraged the public in
newspapers and on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so exciting because, all of the sudden, we had the
experience and the resources of the business community to help out
with early childhood education,'' Duncan said. ``It said something
to many of us, that if they could put in such an effort, the rest
of us could too. The response has been excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Duncan and others readily admit that Born to Read
may, in the end, do little to change attitudes among some parents
toward the importance of books and reading. After all, some said,
several parents may simply chuck the bag in the corner and never
glance that way again.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're really talking about with this program is changing
the culture, and clearly, that's an uphill battle the whole way,''
said Anderson, of the Vermont Center for the Book. ``As a one-shot
deal, skepticism of this program is certainly well-founded. Will
this book make any big changes? I doubt it. But it's a great start,
and we have to keep pushing forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
