<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3781 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MASS-UFUND-ART-BOS &LR;      07-26 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-UFUND-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (a and f coding)  
 COLLEGE STOCK PLANS UNDERCUTTING PREPAYMENT PACKAGES  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The anxiety began a year ago. Pardaman Bhan had just
finished paying off $170,000 in student loans, and the sting was
still fresh. Watching his 12-year-old son Aman playing soccer,
romping around carefree, he badly wanted to keep the crush of
college debt off of the boy's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel so burdened when you get out, that all you think
is, you have to make money,'' said the dentist. Only an aggressive
investment, he felt, would cover Aman's first tuition bill, and the
next, and the next.
</P>
<P>
   Bhan chose the U. Fund, a state-sponsored program of mutual
funds run by Fidelity Investments. The plan is one of dozens that
have sprung up nationwide since 1998, fueling a fast-growing $6
billion college-savings industry. College officials say the
programs have become the most popular way in years to pay for a
higher education, creating a whole new brand of financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``These savings plans seem to be the first kind to really
capture the attention of both politicians and the public,'' said
Philip C. Johnson, a financial planner who tracks aid issues.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity, in fact, has led to some unexpected
consequences. They're pulling families into the stock market for
the first time, but they're also siphoning money from another
savings vehicle once touted by former governor William F. Weld and
others. Called U. Plan, it is a tuition-prepayment plan that allows
families to lock in current tuition rates years in advance of
enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   New data show that after just 16 months of operation, the U.
Fund is outpacing Massachusetts' older prepayment program, the U.
Plan. This year's sign-up period for the U. Plan was the worst by
far: Only 4,700 investments were made in May and June, compared to
13,805 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year-old prepayment program has $102.6 million in
assets. The U. Fund has accumulated $192.3 million in little over a
year.
</P>
<P>
   As in Massachusetts, savings programs appear to be cannibalizing
the prepayment market from coast to coast. In the last two years,
34 states have created or developed savings programs. Only seven
states have similarly embraced prepayment programs during that
time, though there are 19 of them nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people are saving for their children to go to college
because of savings programs,'' said Pam Taylor, director of the
National Association of State Treasurers, which lobbies on behalf
of such plans. ``We don't care how it happens, as long as it
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Families are becoming more ambitious about preparing financially
for college, say analysts who study the savings market.
</P>
<P>
   More parents are putting away money earlier than in the past, in
part because taxes on savings and prepayment accounts are deferred
until the earnings are used. Several states exempt the funds from
taxes entirely, a proposal now under consideration in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The comfort zone with the stock market also appears to be
widening, observers say. Mutual funds still carry more risk than
the state bonds undergirding many prepayment programs, including
the U. Plan. But the potential payoff is far greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking at tuition going up at a slower pace than
what they can get in the stock market,'' said Joseph Hurley, the
founder of savingforcollege.com LLC, an Internet site that provides
advice on college savings. ``And states like the savings plans
because they don't cost anything. The states can hire an investment
company that can flip the cost, so it's cheap and easy to have
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Fidelity name on the U. Fund was a lure for Richard
Connolly, a Winthrop direct-mail marketer. He has invested about
$150,000 so far in U. Fund accounts for his three children _ money
he said he would be less likely to entrust to the government-run
prepayment program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd feel more confident with Fidelity than with any
state-managed program,'' Connolly said. ``Government management
isn't necessarily that which private industry is.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts officials say their prepayment program is a solid,
safe investment, but they add that changes in higher education have
diminished the luster of the plans.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition, for instance, has stopped soaring. Prepayment programs
sprung up in Massachusetts and elsewhere in the mid-1990s to offer
a hedge against tuition inflation after years of double-digit
increases. Sticker prices have been rising only about 5 percent a
year recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If tuition rates start to rise again and the markets aren't so
good, people may think that prepaid programs are more
advantageous,'' said Scott Prince, director of external relations
for the Massachusetts Educational Financing Authority, which
created both programs and runs the prepayment option.
</P>
<P>
   But some financial planners aren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Prepaying tuition limits parents' choices to Massachusetts
colleges and can become too complicated, said Andrew Schwartz of
Schwartz &AMP; Schwartz PC in Woburn, Mass. None of his firm's 1,000
clients has asked about the U. Plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dead in the water,'' Schwartz said of the prepayment
program. ``It's too intangible. If the person's child goes to
college in the state, it's a piece of cake because tuition's paid
for. But if not, it seems like a nightmare in figuring out how
you're going to get your money.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers also chafe at prepayment programs' restricted
benefits, which are mostly limited to in-state campuses. The
Massachusetts U. Plan is one of the most innovative because it
includes many private colleges, such as Boston College and Boston
University.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Bernard Pekala, BC's director of financial aid, said he
prefers the savings program as an investment, especially for
parents who have young children and may be eyeing an expensive
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for a family with a 5-year-old kid to be
that risk averse,'' Pekala said. ``If you have 10 to 15 years to
utilize the funds, the history of the market is that the investment
will perform much better.''
</P>
<P>
   An elite few, such as Harvard University and Williams College,
have resisted joining the prepayment program, despite pressure from
Weld and others. Officials at those schools cite concerns about
financial aid that puts families in the prepayment program at a
disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Under the formula that qualifies students for financial aid, a
dollar of prepaid tuition can reduce each dollar of possible aid.
MEFA has asked colleges to reduce a student's loan burden first,
when possible, before taking away grant money as a result of
prepaid tuition.
</P>
<P>
   The formula treats savings plans and most other investments more
favorably. For U. Fund savings accounts in a parent's name, for
example, only 6 percent is counted against a student's eligibility
for aid.
</P>
<P>
   MEFA officials and their colleagues elsewhere are lobbying the
federal government to change the aid formula to benefit prepayment
plans as well.
</P>
<P>
   For now, parents who considered both the savings and prepayment
options seem to be casting their lot with the savings plans.
</P>
<P>
   Bhan, who is also putting away money for his daughter, shunned
prepaying tuition because he didn't want his children locked in to
attending a Massachusetts college. Right now, he added, the stock
market seems both a safe and strong bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the children will have in mind when it's
time to go to college,'' he said. ``So I felt, the more the
options, the better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
