<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, July 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains will douse parts of New England on Thursday as
tropical moisture streams inland over a stalled front off the
Northeast coast. Thunderstorms will dot the broad shield of steady
rain, producing local downpours. The heaviest rains will probably
occur on the high ground of western and southern New England, where
tropical air originating 2,000 feet over the Atlantic rushes inland
and rises rapidly over the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated thunderstorms will erupt over the high Plains from
western Nebraska to eastern Montana as moist air flowing from the
southeast rises over the sloping landscape. A few storms may
approach severe levels, with hail and damaging winds in spots.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered thunderstorms will sprout over the upper Midwest as a
lofty pool of cold air moves overhead.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TROPICAL PATTERN
</P>
<P>
   If this were the heart of hurricane season, the current pattern
over the East Coast would cue forecasters to the threat of a
tropical storm coming up the Atlantic Seaboard. Even though the
tropical Atlantic will stay rather quiet Thursday, tropical rains
will still douse the Northeast. With a ridge of high pressure over
the western Atlantic and a trough of low pressure over the Midwest,
steering winds aloft will continue to blow from the tropics. With a
stalled front off the coast and areas of moisture-enriched low
pressure rippling slowly along it, flooding rains will occur. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
