<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3784 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-UPS-AIR0727-COX     07-26 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-AIR0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New UPS system could help planes avoid collisions
 &HT;    By Dave Hirschman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The vacationers aboard Campion Air Flight 903 to
Cancun, Mexico, never knew they were in danger.
</P>
<P>
   But on May 25, a few miles northeast of Atlanta, their chartered
B727 was converging with Delta Air Lines Flight 1919 at 33,000
feet. An air traffic controller had mistakenly put the two jets on
conflicting paths, and pilots in both planes blindly followed their
misguided instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Delta MD-80 was equipped with a collision
avoidance system that warned the crew in time to avert catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   But the close call over Atlanta, and scores like it each year in
the nation's increasingly crowded skies and airports, are drawing
attention to a new technology that, proponents say, can drastically
reduce or even eliminate mid-air and runway collisions. The
experimental system known as ADS-B (for Automatic Dependent
Surveillance - Broadcast) also promises to unclog aerial gridlock
by allowing planes to safely fly at close, evenly spaced intervals.
</P>
<P>
   ADS-B was launched in 1996 by UPS Aviation Technologies, a
subsidiary of Atlanta-based United Parcel Service Corp. UPS, the
world's largest transportation firm, plans to begin equipping its
own planes with ADS-B this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most surprising thing about ADS-B for a lot of people is
the fact that it actually exists,'' said Steve Alterman, president
of the Cargo Airline Association, a trade group that represents UPS
and others. ``This isn't some aerospace engineer's pie-in-the-sky
idea. It's here right now, and it offers near-term and long-term
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS hopes to sell ADS-B to passenger airlines, cargo carriers
and corporate and private aircraft owners around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``United Airlines has shown tremendous interest already,'' said
Alterman of the Cargo Airline Association. ``They have a situation
in San Francisco where they can't use parallel runways when it gets
foggy _ and that leads to huge delays. ADS-B could solve that
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, designers are marketing ADS-B overseas, especially in
remote regions where radar coverage is unreliable or nonexistent.
UPS officials say they are negotiating with foreign governments to
provide entire air traffic control networks based on ADS-B
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say they don't know how large the market for
ADS-B is going to be. The system's standards are open, so all
avionics manufacturers are free to build and sell competing ADS-B
products.
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITES REPLACE RADAR
</P>
<P>
   The current air traffic system relies on a patchwork of
ground-based radar to show the positions of aircraft as they
crisscross the country. And FAA controllers monitoring radar scopes
are the only ones with an overall view of the air traffic picture,
telling pilots the speeds, altitudes and headings they should fly
to avoid traffic conflicts and align their planes with runways.
</P>
<P>
   But ADS-B would fundamentally alter that arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The new technology uses Global Positioning System satellites _
not radar _ to pinpoint each airplane's location. And cockpit
instruments show pilots _ not just air traffic controllers _
real-time images of the traffic around them. The system enables
pilots to follow other aircraft at precise distances, a highly
desirable capability at hubs like Atlanta's Hartsfield
International Airport and UPS' air cargo facility in Louisville,
Ky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been getting maximum utilization of runways because
pilots haven't had the necessary tools,'' said Ken Shapero, a
spokesman for UPS Aviation Technologies. ``In a hub environment
where you have a lot of airplanes converging during periods of
intense activity, the ability to use runways more efficiently is
going to save huge amounts of time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   ADS-B works like this: Each plane carries a transmitter that
continuously broadcasts digital information about its speed,
heading, altitude and identity to other planes and data links on
the ground. Radio receivers in other aircraft pick up the signals,
and cockpit computers instantly turn them into pictures of the air
traffic scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Designers say ADS-B gives pilots easy-to-interpret information
about potential traffic conflicts and opens the door to a wide
variety of applications that have never been tried before.
</P>
<P>
   For example, FAA regulations usually require air traffic
controllers to keep airplanes at least five miles apart
horizontally during low-visibility conditions. In practice, actual
separation often becomes much greater and traffic backs up at busy
airports. Using ADS-B, pilots could ``see'' and identify other
planes, get in line behind them and maintain the proper spacing all
the way to the runway. And if a plane doesn't clear the low
altitudes or on runway surfaces. Also, their cost of $100,000 per
unit puts them out of reach for most corporate and private aircraft
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Air cargo carriers will be required to have collision avoidance
equipment by the end of 2002, and it's unclear whether upgraded
ADS-B systems will satisfy that requirement. Memphis-based FedEx
Corp. has decided to install airline-style collision avoidance
systems in its planes, then add ADS-B later. Bob Miller, president
of the Independent Pilots Association, which represents UPS fliers,
wants UPS to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safety items shouldn't be a buffet,'' said Miller, a B747
captain. ``Safety standards should be the same for everyone. We
don't want the airlines to be able to pick and choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilots who have flown with ADS-B say the system isn't perfect.
</P>
<P>
   The cockpit instruments only show detailed information about
other aircraft equipped with ADS-B. And some early tests revealed
that pilots of planes with ADS-B made more radio transmissions to
air traffic controllers _ not fewer as the system's designers
anticipated. Air traffic controllers in early tests also said they
were concerned about potential miscommunications since ADS-B crews
often repeated other aircraft call signs as well as their own.
(Example: ``UPS 402 will follow UPS 406.'')
</P>
<P>
   ADS-B equipment ranges in cost from $13,000 for small planes to
$100,000 for airliners with additional hardware and more stringent
FAA certification requirements. But if ADS-B gains wide acceptance,
the units could be produced in enough volume to substantially
reduce unit prices, UPS officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the CAA's Alterman says if other avionics
manufacturers pick up the technology, that is likely to drive down
ADS-B prices and speed new product development.
</P>
<P>
   ``ADS-B started out as a collision avoidance system, but it's
evolved into much more than that,'' Alterman said. ``It offers all
kinds of safety and efficiency enhancements that seem futuristic
today. But in 10 years we'll look back and all these applications
will seem obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
