<HEADER>
A3786 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-GAME-SNOOZLEBERG-     07-26 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GAME-SNOOZLEBERG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITTY WEB-BASED GAME USES FLASH TO ENTERTAIN  
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES HEROLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mr. Snoozleberg, sound asleep, walks in slippered feet toward
the lion's cage. If the cage door is closed, he will bump into it
and awaken, finding himself in his pajamas, miles from home,
confused and penniless. If the cage is open, he will walk into the
lion's mouth. And if he somehow gets by the lion, he still has a
couple of seals, a gorilla and several very prickly porcupines to
get past. It's a good thing you're watching out for the poor guy.
</P>
<P>
   Part puzzle game, part slapstick cartoon, Sarbakan's ``Good
Night, Mr. Snoozleberg'' is one of the best games you can play on
the Internet and one of the best puzzle games of the last few
years. It is one of many Shockwave games that have been created
using the multimedia animation tool Macromedia Flash, and one of
the precious few whose entertainment value rivals those of
commercial games.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Snoozleberg,'' the player is responsible for keeping a
sleepwalking diplomat asleep and alive as he wanders through
carnivals, back alleys, sound stages and alien spaceships. In each
episode, Mr. Snoozleberg has something important to do the next
day, so if he doesn't make it back into bed by morning, an actor
will not be presented with his award or there will be no one
available to negotiate with aliens. Mr. Snoozleberg is a very
important person.
</P>
<P>
   The premise of the game will be familiar to anyone who has
watched enough old Warner Brothers cartoons: someone who is
sleepwalking, in shock or witless walks through a dangerous area
like a construction site and is saved from death or dismemberment
by blind luck. As the sleepwalker is just about to step off the
edge of the building or be crushed under a cement block, a beam
will swing into place or an elevator will open its doors and
disaster will be averted. It is as though the hand of God reaches
out to save these cartoon characters.
</P>
<P>
   In Mr. Snoozleberg, you are that hand, dropping something heavy
on the head of a waiting alligator or laying a beam across the
space between two roofs before Mr.Snoozleberg can plummet to the
sidewalk. Do your job right and Mr.Snoozleberg will never know he
has been out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics of the game are simple and, for the most part,
involve nothing more than clicking on the right object at the right
time. If Mr.Snoozleberg is about to walk past the window of a woman
in her underwear, pull down the shade before she sees him and
screams. Don't pull it down too soon or it will flip up at just the
wrong time. Sometimes you'll have to move an object to a new
location or spin something Mr. Snoozleberg is walking on to
redirect him.
</P>
<P>
   Given the limitations of online games, it is remarkable how much
variety there is in this one. There are hundreds of ways in which
Mr. Snoozleberg's dreams can be interrupted. Slapstick cops,
troubadors and bumper cars are all laying in wait for the poor man,
and alligators seem to be lurking everywhere, driving garbage
trucks and exploring deep space, always ready for a snack. Some of
the ways in which Mr. Snoozleberg is awakened are quite
entertaining, and players may want to fail once at each puzzle just
to see what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Flash has become a powerful tool for Internet creativity. There
are increasing numbers of miniature movies, simple games and
elaborate Web sites all run by the Shockwave player, a free
download. The quality of these Shockwave products varies, and most
of the games are nothing but retreads of computer games from the
1980's, not worth the several minutes it can take to load a game
using a 56K modem.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking thing about ``Snoozleberg,'' and about
Sarbakan's other game, the excellent adventure game ``Arcane,'' is
how ambitious they are. It is common to see simple, dumb games like
``Cheesy Poofs,'' in which you slide an open-mouthed character from
the television cartoon ``South Park'' back and forth in front of a
steady stream of snacks, or ``Elvira Monster Smash,'' in which you
drop pumpkins on ghouls. But ``Snoozleberg'' is something else: a
complete game with simple but detailed graphics, catchy
cocktail-lounge music and many levels, each containing a large
number of puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   The better Flash games, like Leo's Great Day, are short, but it
takes many hours to complete ``Snoozleberg.'' You cannot play the
game without thinking that this is as good as any puzzle game you
can buy. ``Lemmings Revolution'' may have the latest in 3D
graphics, but ``Snoozleberg'' gives you the same degree of wit and
ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare to find Flash used to its full potential. For every
game like ``Good Night, Mr. Snoozleberg'' or ``Sissy Fight,'' on
which the designers have obviously spent a lot of time and effort,
there are a dozen simple, repetitive games that could have been
created in a week or less. It would be nice if more Flash designers
chose to create games of the caliber of Sarbakan's offerings.
Perhaps ``Good Night, Mr. Snoozleberg'' will be their wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   Good Night, Mr. Snoozleberg; an online game, available free at
sarbakan.com/snooz; for all ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
