<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-RAIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIL MERGER SLOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In validating a federal moratorium on rail mergers, a
three-judge circuit court was right to urge speed in developing an
updated set of policies for approval of further amalgamations. Rail
mergers have not always gone smoothly, but the basic logic of
combining some systems is sound and stands to benefit the economy
on a continental scale.
</P>
<P>
   Suspension of rail merger activity by the Department of
Transportation in March followed a proposal earlier this year _ and
abandoned last Thursday _ for marriage of the Canadian National
Railway with Burlington Northern Santa Fe, which would have
produced the largest rail system in North America, including the
first transcontinental system in this country (Canada's rails reach
from coast to coast already) and extensions into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   This merger and several others it would spawn would reduce
problems of interconnections between lines meeting end-to-end that
result in delays of long-haul traffic and complications in billing
and other operations. With properly crafted mergers, gains of this
sort can be achieved without diminishing competition.
</P>
<P>
   Railroads do compete with each other in majormarkets _ Norfolk
Southern with CSX Corp., for example, in the Northeast _ but
railroads' most serious competition comes from trucking, which
handles more than 80 percent of all freight. Rail's greatest
strength lies in hauling bulk cargoes like coal and grain, but
improved service should compete more successfully with trucking
with piggyback operations, faster long-distance service, and more
reliable delivery timetables.
</P>
<P>
   Suspension of mergers during the study by the Transportation
Department's Surface Transportation Board has added an element of
uncertainty to an already complex process of railroad evolution _
enough to end at least temporarily the Canadian National-Burlington
Northern Santa Fe negotiations. A coherent policy confirming the
principle of approving end-to-end mergers coupled with preservation
of competition between parallel railroads should permit them to
take place as market and financial conditions warrant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
