A3791 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-UNIRAQ-BOS &LR;      07-26 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-UNIRAQ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONITORING SADDAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Nations observers who had been monitoring the
distribution of food and humanitarian supplies in southern Iraq
have been absent from their posts since July 16, withdrawn because
of security concerns. The withdrawal followed the killing last
month of two people and the wounding of seven others by an Iraqi
gunman at the UN Food and Agriculture Organization's mission in
Baghdad. The effect, as described by the director of the Iraq
Foundation in Washington, Rend Francke, is to ``make a very bad
situation catastrophic.''
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the UN monitors was to offer a modicum of
protection for Iraqis, who are the most immediate victims of Saddam
Hussein's regime. Without UN observers in Iraq's four southern
provinces, families that have run afoul of the regime become even
more vulnerable to the punitive policies of the authorities.
Whereas UN monitors in southern Iraq had been able occasionally to
help families whose ration books had been confiscated, the absence
of monitors leaves Iraqis utterly exposed to the caprices and the
corruption of the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In much of southern Iraq, Saddam's Baathist regime resembles an
occupation force. At night, resistance fighters attack party
headquarters and secret police targets. One of Baghdad's methods
for controlling the population is to use food and medicine as a
means of rewarding the docile and punishing the politically
incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   Under the UN's expanded oil-for-food program, Saddam can sell
all the oil he can pump out of the ground. At current prices, his
regime will earn $18 billion this year. The practical meaning of
this arrangement is that the UN economic sanctions meant to force
Saddam to accept inspection and monitoring of his weapons of mass
destruction have become irrelevant. He continues to fight to lift
sanctions so that he, rather than UN monitors, will have the only
say on how to spend his oil revenues.
</P>
<P>
   UN monitors should return immediately to southern Iraq with
guarantees of their safety. And then the next US president will
have to come to grips with a Saddam retrieving his arsenal of
nuclear, biological, and chemical weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
