<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWING TO PRESSURE, JAPANESE REGULATORS POSTPONE BANK SALE 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japanese regulators Wednesday postponed by one month the
sale of the nationalized Nippon Credit Bank to a group of investors
led by the Softbank Corp., one of the world's largest Internet
investment companies.
</P>
<P>
   The delay came after some of Japan's most powerful politicians
applied intense pressure to the Financial Reconstruction
Commission, the agency responsible for overseeing the
rehabilitation and overhaul of Japan's debt-ridden financial
system.
</P>
<P>
   Hiromu Nonaka, the secretary-general of the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party and perhaps the most influential political figure
in Japan, is leading the push to force the agency to renegotiate
the contract to sell Nippon Credit, one of two large banks the
government nationalized at the height of Japan's financial crisis
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians object to a provision in the contract that would
allow the new owners of the bank to transfer back to the government
loans that lose more than 20 percent of their value for three
years. That provision was also part of the contract governing the
sale of the Long-Term Credit Bank, now known as Shinsei Bank, to a
group of investors led by Ripplewood Holdings LLC, a Wall Street
investment firm, and has kicked off a heated debate here about how
public money is used.
</P>
<P>
   Shinsei used the provision to shift 200 billion yen, or more
than $1.8 billion at current exchange rates, in loans to the Sogo
Co., a failing department store operator, to the government, thus
forcing the government to make a choice between spending public
money to rescue Sogo or pulling the plug on the company and its
9,900 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Since Shinsei and Nippon Credit are both creditors of a number
of visibly struggling companies, like the convenience store
operator Daiei Inc. and the building contractors Hazama Corp. and
Kumagai Gumi, the government will likely face the same tough choice
repeatedly _ unless politicians can somehow ban the guarantee
against further deterioration in loan values. Already, the
government is squirming to avoid making a decision on whether to
waive debts owed to the two banks loans by Hazama, which is
particularly troublesome because construction companies are among
the Liberal Democrats' biggest political supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This special clause was a complete mistake,'' said Yoshimi
Watanabe, a member of parliament who sits on the finance committee
in the lower house.
</P>
<P>
   Kimitaka Kuze, chairman of the Financial Reconstruction
Commission, insisted Wednesday that the agency would not change the
terms of the sale to Softbank and its partners, including the Orix
Corp. and Tokio Marine and Fire Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   He said the commission merely wanted to explain its reasons for
including the provision to the public. Bankers from Goldman Sachs &AMP;
Co., which managed the sale of Long-Term Credit Bank, and Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, which is handling the sale of Nippon Credit
for the government, have said repeatedly that without such
guarantees, there would be no sales.
</P>
<P>
   Kuze conceded that the delay in the sale, which was to have been
completed next Tuesday, came at the request of politicians, raising
further questions about the independence of Japan's financial
watchdog. ``It is true that I talked to Shizuka Kamei the day
before yesterday,'' Kuze said, referring to the ruling party's
policy chief.
</P>
<P>
   Kamei has joined Nonaka in pushing to change the laws governing
financial reform and the sale of bankrupt financial institutions.
In a television talk show on Sunday, Nonaka questioned the way the
commission has been guaranteeing buyers of failed banks against
further deterioration in loans. ``It's a big problem in the
Financial Reconstruction Law that measures for coping with
subsequent losses were not stipulated,'' he said, adding that the
ruling party would seek to put such clearly defined measures into
law during the special session of parliament that will begin on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any change in the law could be applied retroactively to
the sale of Nippon Credit remains to be seen. The Softbank group
agreed to a delay in the sale in the hope that some of the
controversy would die down, a representative from one investor said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Orix, however, made it clear that the investors
would not accept changes to the agreement. ``That provision is a
very important part of the contract,'' he said. ``It's difficult to
say what would happen if the government tries to remove that from
the agreement, but if that were to happen, there is a strong
possibility that we would pull out.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission's five-member policy board met Wednesday and
agreed that it must honor the original agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But politicians have already demonstrated a surprising ability
to force the commission to change course, despite the implications
for its independence. Two weeks ago, political pressure pushed the
commission to abandon overnight its decision to participate in a
plan with other banks to forgive some of the $17 billion of debt
owed by the Sogo Co. after Nonaka and others complained about the
use of public money for such a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   That about-face pushed Sogo into bankruptcy, setting off waves
of concern about the stability of the Japanese financial system and
the fragility of the economic recovery that are still reverberating
here. Now politicians are seeking ways to protect themselves from a
series of similar debacles, which could occur any time, given the
precarious finances of many of Japan's retail, construction and
real estate companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This argument of Mr. Nonaka's is one that has a lot of popular
support,'' Watanabe said. ``I think the Financial Reconstruction
Commission is in a lot of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had no concerns about how such a last-minute change
to terms of a deal that were finalized on June 30 might affect the
government's credibility. ``Already the credibility of and
confidence in the Japanese government has been lost,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
