<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FENWAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLPARK COMPROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The state political leadership, Mayor Menino, and John
Harrington, the Red Sox chief executive, deserve congratulations
for devising a compromise finance plan for a new Fenway Park in
Boston. The Legislature should approve the plan Saturday,
recognizing that the proposal represents a balance between the twin
needs to keep the team in the city and minimize cost to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The only cost for government not covered by a clear new source
of revenue is the $100 million the state will spend to improve
transportation systems around Fenway Park. The state will be
compensated with taxes generated by economic activity outside the
park from the million more fans the team expects to attract each
year.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Boston will contribute $212 million to build a
parking garage and buy land for the ballpark. This cost will be
defrayed by garage revenues and money from parking and ticket
surcharges, a sliver of the hotel/motel tax, and sales and meals
taxes inside the ballpark. Unlike other cities, Boston's investment
in the ballpark is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Properly, the Red Sox are liable for the biggest share of
expenses, $352 million for construction costs and responsibility
for any overruns. They will be looking for financing from private
sources. David D'Alessandro, CEO of John Hancock, and Chad Gifford,
president of FleetBoston, helped facilitate the compromise, along
with advertising executive Jack Connors. D'Alessandro and Gifford
will be providing another important civic service if they help
expedite the private financing.
</P>
<P>
   A legislative hearing will be held Friday, and ballpark
opponents will no doubt contend that the plan represents a raid on
the public purse. This is not the case. If anything, the finance
package places a heavy burden on the team, and the Legislature
would be wise to include funds to cover any overruns associated
with site preparation.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are a part of Boston's cultural identity and, like
other leisure activities, contribute to the region's economy. The
team benefits from its location in the Fenway, where other
activities are nearby. This finance plan is a mutually beneficial
embrace between the City and the Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 1828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
