u i BC-SWISS-HOLOCAUST-MONEY     07-26 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-HOLOCAUST-MONEY-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JUDGE APPROVES SETTLEMENT BETWEEN SWISS BANKS, HOLOCAUST
SURVIVORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge gave final approval Wednesday to a
$1.25 billion accord to settle claims of Holocaust survivors who
had sued a group of Swiss banks that they said had hoarded assets
deposited in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by Judge Edward R. Korman in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn takes hundreds of thousands of survivors and their family
members one step closer to collecting the money from the banks. The
ruling requires that a draft of a distribution plan be worked out
in 30 days. The money could begin to be distributed to the
plaintiffs and their heirs by Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   In the prologue to his ruling, Korman used the words of Ernest
Lobet, a Holocaust survivor who testified in a hearing related to
the case, to summarize the balance that he thought the agreement
struck between an idealized version of equity and real-life
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not say it is fair,'' the judge quoted Lobet as havid
said, ``because fairness is a relative term. No amount of money can
possibly be fair under those circumstances. But I'm quite sure it
is the very best that could be done by the groups that negotiated
for the settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The case began about three years ago, when a series of
class-action suits were filed in Brooklyn by Jews who had deposited
money in Swiss banks as the Nazis took power in Germany. The suits
said Swiss institutions, including the two largest Swiss banks, UBS
and Credit Suisse, had blocked the survivors' efforts to reclaim
money that was directly deposited in the banks or that the Nazis
had looted and stored in the banks.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary agreement was reached in August 1998. Since then,
Korman worked worked with lawyers for the survivors and the banks
to hammer out the details.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was greeted by both sides as fair and expedient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a wise and thoughtful opinion that crosses a very
important threshhold,'' said the survivors' chief lawyer, Burton
Neuborne. ``Until this settlement was approved, we were locked.
This unlocks the process, and we can start giving the money out.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger M. Witten, a lawyer in Washington who represents the
banks, said: ``We are very pleased that the judge put his stamp of
approval on the fundamental fairness of the settlement. It is an
important step in getting the money distributed to members of the
class.''
</P>
<P>
   But a handful of potential sticking points remain. One possible
pitfall concerns several private Swiss banks and banks run by the
cantonal, or state, governments, that have been reluctant to
publish the names of hundreds of accountholders or allow their
records to be placed in a database of all Swiss accounts opened
during the war.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his order, Korman said if those banks refused to open their
records, they would not be protected against future lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Korman seized on the intransigence of those banks to
make a larger point about the historical reluctance of the Swiss
banking system to relax its secrecy laws in connection with the
accounts from the Holocaust era. He said in his order that there
was no evidence that the Swiss had destroyed any records of the
victims' accounts, but added that if the Swiss authorities had been
more forthcoming decades ago, recent disputes might have been
avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``An historic opportunity was lost,'' he wrote, quoting Paul A.
Volcker, a former chairman of the Federal Reserve who led an
independent panel that investigated the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the panel issued a report that said 54,000 Swiss
accounts had ``probable'' or ``possible'' links to Holocaust
victims. As of May, 550,000 people had returned questionnaires in
an effort to be included in the class-action settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The court now turns to the task of distributing the money. A
special master appointed by Korman, Judah Gribetz, is generally
expected to file a draft distribution plan with the court by Sept.
1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
