<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BRISBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRISBY GETS ANOTHER CHANCE WITH THE PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ He is not Keyshawn Johnson, but perhaps there
was some similarity that Charlie Weis, Johnson's coach in New York,
saw in Vincent Brisby that possessed him to phone Brisby shortly
after he had been appointed the Patriots' offensive coordinator by
Bill Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie is a guy I can definitely trust,'' said Brisby. ``I
don't know how long he had been on the staff _ it wasn't very long
_ but he called me up and said he wanted me to be here and get my
status back.''
</P>
<P>
   His status used to be a No. 1 receiver. That was before Terry
Glenn was drafted and before Bill Parcells signed Shawn Jefferson
in 1996. It was then, coupled with injuries, that led to Brisby's
free-falling career. He has been here since he was drafted in the
second round in '93. He's in a class with Drew Bledsoe, Troy Brown,
Todd Rucci, and Chris Slade in terms of service to the
organization, other than Bruce Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought Brisby would have lasted this long? He
was a starter seven years ago. He is a starter again. It was all
the in-between that got so muddled and so difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Brisby demanded a trade early last season, but he doesn't
believe it ever got close to being taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was gonna happen,'' he said. ``BG (Bobby
Grier) wasn't gonna do it. He might have looked into it, but once
Troy (Brown) got nicked up, I think the idea was thrown out the
window.''
</P>
<P>
   Brisby also got into a fight with Lawyer Milloy at a nightclub
Nov. 24. It spilled over into the next day before a special teams
meeting in front of teammates and coaches, bringing Brisby's
diminishing popularity back to light. Throughout the offseason,
there was steady speculation that his $2.1 million cap number would
be one of the first to go. Instead, he watched as Ben Coates and
Armstrong were unceremoniously cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get used to the NFL stuff. You're never surprised,''
Brisby said. ``This offseason they made some statements early that
there was some changes. But it's business. It comes and goes.''
</P>
<P>
   The new coaching staff was like a cleansing breath. Brisby gets
to revive a once-promising career. He gets to be a big part of the
offense again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot to prove to myself, to the coaches, and there are
a lot of naysayers out there. I'm looking forward to proving what
kind of player I am. I've always known it. I've been injured and I
had coaches who didn't believe in me. The last three years have
been difficult. I wish I could have leaped over those years, but
they're a part of me now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go home in the offseason and wonder why things had
been so bad. I honestly didn't think it was my fault. I thought I
came out here and practiced hard and played hard when I was
healthy. It just didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what drives him is showing former coach Pete Carroll he
was way off by burying him on the depth chart and having him suffer
the humility of not being active the first two games of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to prove Pete wrong. I hope he's out there watching me
this year,'' said Brisby.
</P>
<P>
   Brisby can't help but hear those naysayers, the ones who believe
he never should have been allowed back. The ones who feel Brisby
must be blackmailing someone in the organization to keep his spot
on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have had plenty of chances to boot him, but instead
the Patriots have held on by tinkering with his contract. Before
training camp, they went to Brisby with a proposition: the team
would cut his base salary in half but allow him to make that back
and more with incentives. His salary tumbled from $1.5 million to
$750,000, but if he catches 70 passes, he could earn as much as
$2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is entitled to their opinion,'' said Brisby.
``Obviously people in this organization feel I have something to
offer. I mean, I think they know what I can do. They know I'm a
good player. So I hear it, but I don't pay any attention to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brisby, who caught 18 passes for 266 yards in 12 games (and one
start) last season, was asked to take a cut and ``any time someone
asks you play for half of your salary, that's hard,'' he said.
``But they tied in incentives, so where if I could play a lot, I'd
make the money back. I thought that was fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe once said that no receiver has ever run a slant patern
better than Brisby. At 6 foot 2 inches, 210 pounds, Brisby can
catch the ball over the middle, which is where the Keyshawn Johnson
comparison comes in.
</P>
<P>
   Brisby said he will be used this season in many roles: inside
route runner, outside route runner, etc. But, barring injury, he
will be used. He said receiving coach Ivan Fears was in his corner
last season and will be again.
</P>
<P>
   `(Fears) told me from Day 1 that it wasn't in his control,''
Brisby said. ``He just told me to come out fighting every practice
and that he would let other teams know how hard I work and the type
of receiver I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Brisby was a loyal participant of the strength and conditioning
program, missing only two of the maximum 48 workouts. All the
while, he was learning Weis's offense, taking throws from Bledsoe
and getting back into the flow.
</P>
<P>
   Brisby followed that with strong minicamps and he's had an
excellent training camp, rivaled only by his fellow starter, Glenn.
So far, Brisby is making Tony Simmons wait a little longer to
become a starter. But he doesn't feel so bad about that. After all,
he caught 169 passes the first three years of his career and only
48 the last four. His career has been on hold long enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
