<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3801 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-CISCO-LA0727-COX     07-26 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-LA0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cisco Systems plans to wire L.A.-area community to the hilt
 &HT;    By Bob Keefe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forget connecting your computer to the Internet,
Cisco Systems Inc. wants to hook up your whole home.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco announced Wednesday that it was teaming up with a Los
Angeles developer to create what is being billed as the world's
most high-tech community.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for Playa Vista, west of downtown Los Angeles, call for 6
million feet of office and retail space, 13,000 homes and 30,000
residents _ all wired to the hilt.
</P>
<P>
   When the development opens next year, Playa Vista homeowners
should be able to unlock their doors and turn on their lights from
their office computer or their Internet-based wireless phone. With
Internet-connected appliances, they'll be able to preheat the oven
from the upstairs bathroom or contact the refrigerator manufacturer
about a leaky connection. With Web cameras and audio equipment,
they can check in on their kids from the office or communicate with
delivery people who knock on the door when they're away. PCs can be
networked by plugging them into a phone jack.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the wired homes is an answering-machine-sized
device Cisco calls an ``Internet Home Gateway'' that allows
electronics _ be they computers or televisions or telephones _ to
be connected with each other through power lines, phone lines and
high-speed Internet service. Cisco announced in January it was
working on the gateway equipment along with Sun Microsystems Inc.,
Whirlpool Corp. and GTE Corp. Wednesday, it also formally opened a
1,700-square-foot model home at its San Jose headquarters that
demonstrates the system.
</P>
<P>
   The Playa Vista project is the first of many that Cisco wants to
wire with developers. But the networking giant also wants to sell
the gateway systems directly to consumers. The devices, when they
become available next spring, are expected to cost $500, plus
$1,500 more for wiring in a typical existing house. More advanced
home systems based on Cisco's equipment could cost anywhere from
$15,000 to $100,000. New homes will be cheaper to wire: At Playa
Vista, for instance, the Cisco-based systems add about $1,000 to
the cost of a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really ties into what Cisco thinks is going to happen to
Internet usage in the home,'' said Kristine Stewart, director of
market development for Cisco's consumer business. ``The Internet
will be like a utility, just as you have water, gas and
electricity. And because of that, it will be a natural extension to
do other things with the Internet . . . whether it's entertainment
or videoconferencing or home security.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco, which last year had $12.2 billion in sales, expects to
earn more than $1 billion in the home networking market within the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco became one of the world's biggest technology companies by
making servers and routers that drive the Internet and corporate
computer networks. The residential gateway equipment is its biggest
push into the consumer market. Other companies ranging from
Motorola Inc. to 3Com Corp. also are developing devices for home
networking equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Gadget-izing homes is nothing new, of course. Nationwide,
developers are touting technology _ everything from fiber-optic
phone lines in every room to theater-quality entertainment centers
_ as a selling point.
</P>
<P>
   Some communities are already way ahead of Playa Vista. At
Disney's Celebration community in Orlando, for example, almost
every home is wired to one another through a community Intranet. In
Georgia, the city of LaGrange recently began wiring its 27,000
residents to the Internet through cable lines and in Austin, Texas,
several developers are planning communities that feature high-tech
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Most consumers, however, have been reluctant _ or unable _ to
wire their homes to the Internet. At the end of last year, only
about 6 percent of all households had high-speed Internet access,
according to researcher International Data Corp., although the
number is expected to increase to 31 percent within three years.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco may run into another hurdle in rolling out its new
equipment at Playa Vista.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Los Angeles is about to embark on a four-month study
into complaints of possible health and safety risks from earthquake
faults and methane gas reportedly underneath a portion of the
1,087-acre development.
</P>
<P>
   Activists also have protested that the development will harm
nearby wetlands and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Playa Vista officials say the worries are overblown and the
development is progressing as planned.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Bob Keefe at bkeefe(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
