<HEADER>
A3802 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-CHENEY-NAT     07-26 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CHENEY-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        WITH CHENEY AT HELM, HALLIBURTON BANKROLLED GOP
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Anand Giridharadas  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (July 26) - The private sector may have taken Dick
Cheney out of politics, but it did not take the politics out of
Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking the helm at the world's largest oil services
company, Cheney has been an active financial patron of Republican
causes - and appears to have led his firm to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-based Halliburton Company - where Cheney has been
chief executive since 1995 - has become a stalwart backer of
conservative causes, pumping hundreds of thousands of dollars into
Republican war chests since Cheney's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Keith, a vice president at Halliburton, said Cheney's
position had brought the company higher visibility in Washington.
And records suggest that visibility was buttressed by a stream of
cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know him and he has been a presence up there. If you have
a personal knowledge of somebody, you might pay more attention to
them,'' she said. ``We try to persuade Congress to see things our
way. I would think his stature adds immeasurably to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Cheney took over, Halliburton has given around $400,000
each election cycle, totaling $1.2 million over six years. All but
$40,000 of it has gone to Republicans, either as soft money - the
loosely regulated gifts to parties - or through political action
committees, which fund clusters of political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Before Cheney arrived, Halliburton's political contributions
were far smaller and fell somewhat more evenly between the parties.
In the 1992 cycle, the company gave $67,000, a quarter of it to
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have seized on Cheney's selection as an opportunity to
color the ticket as an instrument of ultra-conservative corporate
interests, particularly the oil industry. Bush is also a former
Texas oilman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Cheney got to Halliburton, their donations to the
Republican party shot up,'' said Democratic National Committee
spokesman J%rBM
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3803 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SF-AIDS-FUNDING-HNS &LR;      07-26 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-AIDS-FUNDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PELOSI VOWS TO FIGHT $6.5 MILLION CUT IN S.F. AIDS FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Nancy Pelosi vowed to fight a $6.5 million cut
in San Francisco's federal AIDS program that the House passed
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot accept the premise that our region should have to
absorb this kind of cut,'' Pelosi said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was included in the five-year update of the Ryan
White Care Act, which authorizes federal money for care and
medication for people with AIDS who racted the disease through tainted blood
and died in 1990 at age 19. It serves about half a million people
each year and is expected to dole out $7.1 billion over the next
five years to states and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., a member of the House Commerce
Committee's Health and Environment Subcommittee, which oversees the
Ryan White Care Act, led the fight to reduce San Francisco's share
of federal AIDS dollars and redistribute the money to 50 other
cities hard hit by the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryan White program provides San Francisco with $5,958 a year
per AIDS case, compared to $3,055 for Oakland, $3,068 for Los
Angeles and $2,980 for Sacramento, according to the General
Accounting Office, the auditing arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, there is extreme imbalance in the amount of
funding that is going to San Francisco versus other areas,'' Coburn
told his fellow House members during floor debate.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation ``is not intended to hurt San Francisco,''
Coburn said, but the city is getting more than its fair share.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ryan White federal program began in 1991, the funding
formula was based on two factors: the density of AIDS cases in a
city (the ratio of people with AIDS relative to the city's total
population) and a city's cumulative number of AIDS cases, living
and dead. The formula gave San Francisco a huge jump in funding,
compared to other cities, because AIDS had hit the city so hard in
the early years of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Congress changed the formula so that it was based on
the estimated number of living people with AIDS in a city. That
change would have slashed San Francisco's funds because many AIDS
patients there had already died.
</P>
<P>
   However, Congress limited the funding cuts to San Francisco's
funding to avoid disrupting existing AIDS programs there.
</P>
<P>
   The House-passed bill and the Senate version would reduce the
size of that cushion, though the House version would do it faster.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., the original author of the Ryan
White program, said most members of Congress agree San Francisco
has been getting more than its fair share, but disagree over how
quickly the city's share should be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that San Francisco strongly supports the Senate bill,''
Waxman said an interview. ``Others of us have agreed we need a
faster transition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version of the Ryan White Care Act would cut San
Francisco's $35 million annual share of federal AIDS dollars by
only $1.7 million over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Both versions now go to a House-Senate conference committee that
Pelosi hopes will produce a compromise bill that is less tough on
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to do better in conference,'' Pelosi said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi noted that the $6.5 million cut for San Francisco was
less than the $8 million cut originally proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill also would direct $30 million to state and local
health officials to notify sexual partners of people who are
infected with HIV. States would determine whether to identify HIV
positive people by name or codes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said the conflict between San
Francisco and other cities over AIDS funding stems from the fact
that Congress ``puts too little money into this and therefore
create these contests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, the answer is, we ought to be taking care of
everyone,'' Frank said. ``The notion that you have to choose
between the needy is outrageous. It is a result of the meanness of
the (Republican) budgets.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
