u f BC-FARBER-PRESIDENT-BOS &LR;      07-26 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARBER-PRESIDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNS HOPKINS SCIENTIST TO HEAD DANA-FARBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dana-Farber Cancer Institute has named as its next
president Dr. Edward J. Benz Jr., a Harvard Medical School graduate
who currently holds a prestigious chair at Johns Hopkins School of
Medicine in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Benz, a hematologist and Sir William Osler Professor of Medicine
at Hopkins, will replace Dr. David Nathan, president of DFCI since
1995.
</P>
<P>
   He will also become CEO of Dana-Farber/Partners Cancer Care,
which includes DFCI, Brigham and Women's Hospital, Massachusetts
General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year Benz, 54, rejected an offer to become editor
of the New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New England Journal would have meant leaving my university
roots and not being able to continue doing my personal research,
Benz said Wednesday. ``And I thought on balance this was a closer
match to what I hope to be doing for the next decade or so.''
</P>
<P>
   Benz spoke by telephone from Maine, where he has a laboratory at
the Mt. Desert Island Biological Laboratory. He said he and his
colleagues have been studying proteins in the shark, and ``We've
been chasing a lead we think may be involved in cell growth,''
which goes awry in cancer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan, who is retiring, said in a statement, ``I have known Ed
Benz for many years, and I can't think of anyone more perfectly
prepared to lead Dana-Farber's fight against cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of the search committee that picked Benz, Harvard
Medical School Dean Joseph Martin, said, ``Dr. Benz brings much to
the Harvard medical community, and I look forward to working with
him as a close partner to foster greater research collaboration
across all of the Harvard medical institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Benz said that one of his challenges will be keeping Dana-Farber
financially strong and delivering top quality medical care while
adapting to the dictates of managed care. ``And that is getting
trickier and trickier,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Before assuming the post at Johns Hopkins, Benz was chairman of
the department of medicine at the University of Pittsburgh School
of Medicine and prior to that was on the faculty in the department
of medicine at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Margaret Vettese, has been on the faculty of
the Johns Hopkins School of Nursing. Each has adult children by a
previous marriage, and Benz said an extra lure of the Boston job
was that his daughter and his only grandchild live in New Haven,
Conn. Also, his wife's daughter lives in Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 1836EDT &QL; 
