<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILEKS-CHENEY-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY MAKES SENSE, NOW THAT YOU MENTION IT 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Wednesday, July 26, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By JAMES LILEKS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To understand why George W. Bush picked Dick Cheney for veep,
imagine this scenario:
</P>
<P>
   It's the vice presidential debate. The candidates are asked to
imagine the conditions in which they'd commit troops. Larry King
hunches into the mike and asks Al Gore's veep choice _ let's call
him Sen. Gohrveip _ if he'd send troops to save the rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Larry,'' says Gohrveip, ``you have to understand that we
live in a changing world. Of shifting paradigms. Of
interconnectedness. We have to live locally, yes, but think
globally. It depends on whether threats to the environment
constitute a threat to national security, and I think that's a
debate we need to have.''
</P>
<P>
   All right, then, Mr. Cheney: Would you send troops to save the
rain forest?
</P>
<P>
   (Long look at questioner. Long look at Sen. Gohrveip. Long look
at questioner again.)
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Bush picked him. Not for his humor, his wit, his
Roman-candle persona, his tap-dancing talent or his beefcake
physique. Dick Cheney is a man who can say one syllable and make it
sound like a stack of encyclopedias dropping on an oaken desk.
Cheney has ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, we all know what he has. It's gravitas, an ancient Latin
term that means ``the precise opposite of Richard Simmons.''
Journalists love to use the word, even though it requires
definition in every story. As understood today, it means heft,
presence, stature, the look of solid contemplative calm, with a
slight touch of emotional constipation. George C. Scott, not Robin
Williams. Mr. Spock, not Dr. Smith. Russell Crowe in ``Gladiator,''
not Jim Carrey in anything.
</P>
<P>
   Gravitas is a quality the culture admires _ but only when we're
being asked to admire it. When we're asked to assume it ourselves,
well, that's a different matter.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, all candidates had gravitas. It would have been
unthinkable to attempt to stride the political stage without it:
Let us pause to imagine Woodrow Wilson playing the saxophone on a
vaudeville stage. But we no longer elect teachers, father figures,
wiser older brothers, solons and magisterial betters; we elect
peers now, because our egalitarian culture cannot stomach the
notion of ``betters.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush isn't overly encumbered with gravitas, but that's OK; lack
of gravitas didn't keep Bill Clinton out of office. Men who
entertain questions about their underwear preference do not have
gravitas.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd feel stupid asking a man about his underwear
preference, then he has gravitas.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has gravitas up the wazoo, as the gravitas-impaired press
corps would put it. He seems like an actual adult. Of course, if
anyone just grows old, stays still and keeps his mouth shut most of
the time, he has gravitas. Ringo Starr has achieved it; Jerry Lewis
has it when photographed in black-and-white in a tux, until he
sticks hot dogs up his nose. You can fake it for a while, but not
forever.
</P>
<P>
   A safe choice for Bush? Absolutely. But of course he'll take
criticism. He's Bush's dad's pick! We'll hear this a lot _ as if Al
Gore Jr.'s rise in his father's milieu was an act of stunning
coincidence. We're supposed to fear the evil reign of George
Herbert Walker, using his malleable whelp as a surrogate for his
own dark plots. Why, Daddy Bush might use his son to further his
own domestic agenda _ raise upper-class taxes and expand the
Americans With Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Cheney recalls the reign of Bush the Elder, this
isn't exactly bad news. Mr. C. was one of three tent poles that
held up the Gulf War tent; along with Stormin' Norman and Colin
Powell, his serious, precise and noncondescending interviews
assured the public that real adults were in charge here. He was the
sort of Republican the media can accept _ moderate, practical, not
one of those vacuous godbothering Rotarian Babbitts who make the
media shudder and snicker.
</P>
<P>
   Question is, why does Cheney want the job? Isn't it worth no
more than ``a bucket of warm spit''? Cheney would give a small
slight crooked smile, and perhaps correct you: ``warm saliva.''
</P>
<P>
   That's gravitas for you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
