<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guide Helps Mac Users Get Out of the House  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the city that never sleeps, it can sometimes be difficult to
decide what to do. Vindigo, a ``personal navigation'' program for
Palm and Handspring Visor electronic organizers, can be considered
a digital replacement for the entertainment listings in the
newspaper or weekly city magazine _ with a little something extra.
</P>
<P>
   Vindigo, which is available free for download from
www.vindigo.com, made its debut in March. Recently the company
announced a Macintosh version of the program. The new application
will work on computers running version 8.0 or higher of the Mac
operating system. The PC version of Vindigo can also be found on
the Web site and will work on systems running Windows 95 or later.
In addition to New York, Vindigo offers city guides for Chicago,
Washington, San Francisco and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Users get more than just movie times, a shopping directory and
current nightlife events and restaurant reviews from Zagat.com and
NYToday.com (which is owned by New York Times Digital, a division
of The New York Times Co.). The Vindigo program will also give
walking directions from any starting point. For example, if you are
looking to catch a screening of the new ``X-Men'' movie, Vindigo
will tell you the show times and nearest movie houses showing the
film. The program will also give you a plot synopsis, the running
time of the film, who's starring in it and how to get there. Users
received updated information and listings from the Vindigo server
when synchronizing the Palm or Visor organizer with a computer
connected to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which features tiny advertisements sprinkled
throughout the listings, needs a minimum of 410 kilobytes of free
space on the handheld device. Although that may be a significant
chunk of memory for some handhelds, it still may be preferable to
hauling around the old clunky tree-based media for directions to a
fine night on the town. And just think, no more ink smears on your
nice clothes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ J.D. BIERSDORFER
</P>
<P>
   Study Claims Downloads Spur Offline Music Sales
</P>
<P>
   While the recorded music industry has kicked off a legal war
against Web-based music sharing, a study by Jupiter Communications
concludes that Napster and similar sites actually spur CD sales.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter, an Internet commerce analysis firm, says that online
music users are 45 percent more likely than nonusers to have
increased their total music purchases over the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way people interact with music is changing but in good
ways,'' said Stacey Herron, a music analyst at Jupiter. ``I don't
think music sharing technologies are a dead end for the industry.
Quite the opposite in fact. An informed consumer is a happy
consumer.
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America and several
recording companies and musicians argue that Napster and other Web
services that allow people to exchange songs as MP3 files break
copyright laws and deny musicians compensation for their work.
</P>
<P>
   Herron said a preliminary examination of a survey of 2,200
online music users Jupiter made in June shows that MP3s often
inspire listeners to go out and buy CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter is also critical of a study by the trade group that
shows CD sales in stores near colleges have dropped in areas with
high levels of MP3 usage. Stacey said the study partly covers the
time before Napster began operating and does not account for other
factors that affect sales.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Curry, a spokesman for the trade group, which is part of an
effort to obtain an injunction against Napster's service, declined
to comment on the Jupiter report until his organization receives a
copy. However, he said the trade group ``stands by'' its research.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Jupiter study, however, shows that the positive impact
is not universal. Stacey said it found that most 18- to
24-year-olds who spent less than $20 on recordings over three
months have not increased their CD shopping. However, she says that
will change. ``A couple of years from now, they are going to be
adults and buying a lot of music.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By IAN AUSTEN
</P>
<P>
   Some New Antidotes for Computer Viruses  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of this year's nastiest computer viruses have propagated
through Microsoft Outlook. As soon as the viruses hit, they get
into the software's address book and mail copies of themselves to
every e-mail address listed.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that there were some way to lock up those address books,
effectively blocking any chance for the viruses to multiply. A
company called CopyTele has recently added a feature to one of its
high-level encryption devices that is designed to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   The device called the Cryptele USS-900 plugs into a computer,
fax machine or telephone. Its primary purpose is to keep voice and
data communications private. If someone tapped the phone line, for
example, the overheard conversation would be unintelligible without
a key to unencrypt it.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, engineers added the virus-protection feature. It
does not stop a virus from inflicting damage on a computer if a
malicious attachment is opened. But it does stop the virus from
replicating. ``That virus would die on your computer,'' said Frank
W. Trischetta, senior vice president for sales and marketing. The
device, which starts at around $1,000, is priced for the corporate
market. But Copytele officials say that it could be a boon to
regular consumers, too, if it succeeds in halting viruses before
they spread out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, meanwhile, has released a software patch that it says
will make its address books less vulnerable. Once the patch is
installed, the system alerts its users when an external program is
trying to gain access to the address book and asks their permission
to continue. (The update can be downloaded from
www.microsoft.com/office/outlook/).
</P>
<P>
   Because the patch is a software solution, Trischetta argued,
virus writers may be able to devise their own computer program to
get around it.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
