<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How Bush selected Cheney more intriguing than the choice itself
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - At first glance, what is most striking about Gov.
George W. Bush's selection of a running mate is not his choice,
former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, as much as the way he was
chosen.
</P>
<P>
   This impression could be due in part to an overachieving media.
The Bush campaign has flatly denied there was anything to Dan
Rather's report of an 11th-hour attempt to get retired Gen. Colin
Powell to change his mind and take the job. Even so, Bush's account
of a gradual settling on the chairman of his search committee as
the best man for the job, and Cheney's praise of Bush's persuasive
abilities, still leave some questions.
</P>
<P>
   What was it about the Republicans Cheney interviewed during his
search that caused Bush to reject them and turn back to Cheney, who
had already turned down the job? What role if any did former
President Bush play in the decision? And what about that reported
remark that his choice was ``going to make people's eyes light up
with excitement?''
</P>
<P>
   That Cheney's name does not get that reaction is at the core of
the Bush campaign's characterization of Cheney, now that he's the
nominee. He is being held up as a solid, mature, non-political
choice, a signal that Bush already has his eyes steadily trained on
the days after his election.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, eager for Vice President Al Gore to select an
alternative with more pizzazz, fall right into the assumption that
Cheney is a predictable, dull choice. The rules of political irony
dictate that in such a situation, we can confidently expect Cheney
to pull at least a few surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Some indirect Georgia connections are worth mentioning as they
relate to a turning point in Cheney's career. When Sen. Sam Nunn
and other Democrats shot down President Bush's first choice for
defense secretary in 1989, former Sen. John Tower of Texas, he
asked Cheney to leave his Wyoming House seat and take the job. That
opened the post of Republican whip, which Newt Gingrich ran for and
won by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   One reason congressional Democrats remember Cheney more fondly
than Gingrich and Texas Rep. Tom DeLay, the current whip, is that
the Republicans were still a distinct minority when he was around.
But he has a voting record in Congress every bit as conservative as
his successors, something the Democrats have lost no time in
pointing out.
</P>
<P>
   Soft-spoken and buttoned-down though he may be, the selection of
Cheney brings up questions about the other choices Bush would make
as president.
</P>
<P>
   A recent analysis of the impact of two or three Bush appointees
to the U.S. Supreme Court suggested the court might move further to
the right on gun control and other issues, but stop short of
radical revisions such as overturning Roe v. Wade.
</P>
<P>
   Such logic is much too fuzzy for the Democrats' purposes, and
Cheney's voting record on abortion gives them ammunition with which
to attack it. In the days leading up to the convention in
Philadelphia, this is likely to lead to more discussion of exactly
what ``compassionate conservatism'' means.
</P>
<P>
   More than either campaign seems to have anticipated, this could
end up being an election divided along traditional
liberal-conservative lines.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
