<HEADER>
A3817 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-WEB-NUDITY-HNS &LR;      07-26 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-NUDITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COMPANY TAKES ACTION AGAINST WEB SITES FEATURING NUDE
CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROY BRAGG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Rackspace.com, a San Antonio technology company
that provides Web space for hire, has been hosting more than a
dozen Internet sites that feature pictures of nude children.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would pull the plug on those Web pages,
which feature explicit and sexually suggestive pictures of girls
purported to be as young as 8.
</P>
<P>
   Though no genitalia were directly exposed, most of the girls had
exposed pelvic areas. All of them were bare-chested.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the girls were smiling in the photographs; others wore
heavy amounts of makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had not previously seen it,'' Rackspace.com chief executive
Graham Weston said Tuesday of one of the sites, a day after being
notified of it by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it and ordered that we pull the plug on it. And as far
as any other Web site is concerned, if it contains pictures of
children, it will be gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weston said his lawyers have advised him that the company must
fulfill contractual obligations in the process of canceling the
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Weston called the decision a change in policy for the year-old
company, which in the past would yank a site only if law
enforcement officials found that it contained pornographic
material.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, Weston said most Web hosting companies
do not monitor the content of sites they host, and that he was
reluctant to get into the censorship business.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed after he pulled up one of the Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be in the position of judging, but we just
decided to draw the line in a different space,'' he said.
``Unfortunately, it puts us in the position of interpretation, but
we don't want to have pictures of children like that on our site.''
</P>
<P>
   Rackspace.com leases Web server space for more than 1,400 small-
to medium-size business clients who together run thousands of
Internet sites in 40 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has plans for international expansion, has
filed papers to issue stock in a public offering, though no date
has been set.
</P>
<P>
   Better A Millstone, a Monterey, Calif.-based organization that
targets the exploitation of children in sexually explicit material,
discovered that Rackspace.com was hosting at least a dozen sites
that prominently feature nude pictures of boys and girls.
</P>
<P>
   Organization officials were pleased with Rackspace.com's
decision to pull the sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am glad that they've been shown the light of day, and that
they're willing to do the right thing,'' assistant director Bryan
Givens said.
</P>
<P>
   He had initiated contact with Rackspace.com in April about the
sites, but described the company's technical staff as
uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I wish this would've been worked out earlier,''
Givens said. ``Most of the Web-hosting companies and providers
react immediately when we call them and ask them to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Rackspace had done that. I hope that their
powers-that-be and their staff have a new attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rackspace.com arrived at its decision even though law
enforcement officials say the pictures probably are able to skirt
the restrictions of the Child Protection Act of 1984, a federal law
that specifies the criteria for child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   According to federal law, children must be minors and be
involved in sexually explicit conduct for the image to be construed
as pornographic, said Charles Harrison, associate agent in charge
at the U.S. Customs Service, which investigates reports of child
pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, the key element is `sexually explicit conduct,'''
Harrison said. ``It is not as straightforward as you might expect
when you deal with pornographic issues. You deal with subjective
interpretations and community issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Scott Poth of the San Antonio Police Department's Vice
Squad said local law enforcement defines that conduct, with respect
to child pornography, as any depiction of a child in real or
simulated intercourse or other sexual activity. Any ``lewd
depiction'' of genitalia would also make a picture pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said, however, that a picture could be within the
bounds of the law _ showing a lone, nude child posed behind a desk,
for example _ but it could be construed as ``sexually explicit'' if
it runs alongside other, more hard-core pornographic pictures, or
even with text that implies explicit sexual activities.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is hierarchical, with an organized system for
assigning domains, or Internet addresses. Private companies doing
business on U.S. servers must register this domain name and its
corresponding numerical coding with Network Solutions, the Herndon,
Va.-based Internet registrar for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But records on file with Network Solutions showed inaccurate
mailing addresses for at least two of the sites, Givens said. And
that, according to Network Solutions spokeswoman Cheryl Regan,
could violate the contracts of those Web sites, meaning they could
lose the rights to their domains.
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites hosted by Rackspace.com focus primarily on girls,
though one site features boys. Each has links to other, hard-core
adult sites, as well as to Web sites that focus on ``child love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about Calvin Klein ads or something like
that,'' said Mike Echols, founder of Better A Millstone. ``We're
talking about egregious and disturbing images when we're talking
about these photos.''
</P>
</TEXT>
