<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL _A heavy burden on the border
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late last month, U.S. District Judge Royal Furgeson stepped down
from his bench to sit as a witness before a congressional
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, who presides over the Pecos Division of the U.S.
Western District, had a lot to say about life near the border.
</P>
<P>
   He told members of the subcommittee of the Committee on
Government Reform that a federal get-tough policy on illegal
immigration and drug trafficking was equally tough on the people
and facilities of the federal court system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, the first full year that I presided over the criminal
docket of the Pecos Division, 45 criminal cases were filed,''
Furgeson testified. ``Last year, 386 criminal cases were filed, an
800 percent increase. ... (I)n the first five months of 2000, 252
criminal cases have been filed in the Pecos Division, an average of
50 each month. I expect over 600 criminal cases to be filed by the
end of this year, resulting in a 55 percent increase over last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pecos Division is 30,450 square miles of West Texas that are
among the least-populated in the state. The realities of the drug
business and traffic in illegal immigrants make this area ideal for
entrepreneurs in illegal and clandestine activities.
</P>
<P>
   However isolated the Pecos Division may be, it does not lack
champions for battling its overwhelming burden. Federal judges from
California to Texas, said Furgeson, are carrying felony caseloads
10 times the national average. The numbers paint a picture of
judges forced to dispense assembly-line justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a major frustration of the judiciary that we have been
unable to adequately explain to the Congress and to the American
people that criminal activity on the border cannot be addressed
simply by increasing law enforcement efforts,'' Furgeson told the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, those arrested for crimes must come through the
rest of the criminal justice system. ...If the courts do not have
the resources to deal with the increases, the delivery of justice
is jeopardized and will be eventually impaired.''
</P>
<P>
   As a stopgap, federal judges from Louisiana are flying in to
help. But more courts with the appropriate personnel are needed and
should be created now.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, joined by colleagues
from other border states, is pushing for the creation of 13 more
federal judgeships. It would be two years, however, before the
first of those judges took office and that would occur only if the
bill passes and the politics of selecting those judges is kept to a
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, federal problems become headaches for counties along
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Sen. Elliot Shapleigh, D-El Paso, notes the federal
shortcomings have spawned an unfunded mandate for border counties.
``Federal authorities in El Paso no longer prosecute marijuana
cases under 125 pounds. This policy has shifted 500 cases to
district attorney Jaime Esparza's office.''
</P>
<P>
   That means, Shapleigh said, that counties along the border have
to pick up the costs of incarcerating those defendants, hire
court-appointed lawyers for them and bear the costs of trying them.
</P>
<P>
   So exasperated are border prosecutors that some are refusing to
accept cases federal prosecutors want to unload on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like trade, drug (trafficking) has shifted from east to west
to north to south,'' Shapleigh noted. Texas border counties are
``17th in population and 156th in tax base. These are counties that
can least afford to take these cases. We can't have border
communities bearing the burden of national justice.''
</P>
<P>
   He's absolutely right.
</P>
<P>
   Esparza was quoted in the El Paso Times as saying that the price
tag attached to prosecuting federal cases ranges from $2 million to
$8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should pay attention to these genuine fiscal concerns.
More judges, prosecutors and detention facilities are needed along
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the federal government's get-tough policy is going to
punish more border county judges, commissioners, prosecutors and
sheriffs _ not to mention taxpayers _ than it does crooks.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial appeared in the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
