<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL _ Is it a surplus or a shortfall? Both
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As they might say in a movie classic, we're in Chinatown now _ a
subtle realm where things are rarely what they seem and never
simple.
</P>
<P>
   Recent news stories about the state budget may remind taxpayers
of a moment in ``Chinatown.'' Actress Faye Dunaway confesses her
character's shocking family secret, in which two seemingly
contradictory facts are both true.
</P>
<P>
   In this summer's mythical Austin remake, she confesses ``It's a
shortfall, it's a surplus, it's a shortfall, it's a surplus, it's a
shortfall'' until viewers slowly grasp that both these seemingly
contradictory facts are true.
</P>
<P>
   State agencies are spending more money than the Legislature
authorized for the current two-year budget period. That much seems
undisputed. Rapidly escalating medical and prison costs, among
other problems, will leave the state over its budget. The exact
amount of the shortfall remains to be tallied.
</P>
<P>
   But the state also is taking in money faster than estimated in
spring 1999, when the budget became final. That creates an income
surplus. When the Legislature convenes in January, it will have to
raid the surplus to cover the shortfall, rather than rolling the
extra money forward or socking it away into the state's sadly
depleted rainy day fund. (The fund is well-named: Budget writers
figure it would cover about one day of state operations.)
</P>
<P>
   State budget developments have become a particularly hot topic
because of Gov. George W. Bush's presidential candidacy. His
critics say cost overruns prove the tax cuts he insisted on were
ill-advised and that budgets for social services were unrealistic.
They've blasted Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander, a Bush ally,
for exaggerating estimates of the surplus to save the boss
political embarrassment. And they suggest that agencies are
low-balling spending estimates for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   Rising costs, a puny rainy day fund and a budget overrun likely
to exceed $400 million on a $98 billion two-year budget don't add
up to happy news. When financial publications such as The Bond
Buyer start talking about ``the Texas-sized hole in the state's
annual budget,'' it looks bad, even if the overspending won't break
the bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Rylander and most other budget insiders predict that revenue
surplus will cover the budget deficit, barring disaster. Enactment
of a bigger than usual ``emergency spending bill'' in January will
most likely tidy up the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the budget flap rattled the governor enough for him to
dent his nice-guy image. ``It's a little early to project the
amount of money the Legislature will be dealing with,'' Bush told
reporters. ``And as you know, I hope I'm not here to deal with it.
I'm seeking another office.''
</P>
<P>
   After a lull in talk about ``the smirk,'' a much-analyzed Bush
facial expression, his supporters can't have been happy for him to
produce the expression's verbal equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Mario Gallegos Jr., for one, was unamused. ``The last
time I looked, he's still the governor of Texas,'' the Houston
Democrat remarked tartly.
</P>
<P>
   He's the governor, he's the candidate, he's the governor, he's
the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial appeared in the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
