<HEADLINE>
WHEN INSTALLING A FLOOR-MOUNTED TOILET, A TIGHT SEAL IS IMPORTANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients and a graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Installing a floor-mounted toilet _ as opposed to the type
mounted on a wall _ is not difficult, but it has to be done
carefully and methodically or else the toilet will leak.
</P>
<P>
   Before buying a new toilet, remove the old one and measure the
''rough-in'' dimension. This is the distance from the wall behind
the toilet to the two closet bolts projecting up from the floor
flange.
</P>
<P>
   The rough-in is the amount of space that you need to fit the new
toilet in. Some toilets need a 12-inch rough-in, while others
require a 13-inch rough-in. The new toilet can have a shorter
rough-in _ this will provide extra space behind it _ but it cannot
have a longer rough-in. So it is better to have some extra space
than too little.
</P>
<P>
   The most common type of floor-mounted toilet comes in two
pieces, the bowl and the tank. This is sometimes called a
close-coupled toilet.
</P>
<P>
   The other type of toilet has the bowl and tank joined in one
piece.
</P>
<P>
   The installation procedure for both types is the same, but it is
harder to install a one-piece toilet simply because the unit is
heavier than the close-coupled model.
</P>
<P>
   It is essential that an installed toilet remains fixed and
immobile. A toilet that tilts or pitches, even slightly, when
someone uses it indicates that the joists and supporting floor are
weak. These should be braced before installing the new unit.
</P>
<P>
   When you purchase a new toilet and get it home, remove the
wrapping and look carefully at all parts to make sure there are no
cracks or defects.
</P>
<P>
   Possible defects include a deformed inlet (the opening between
the bowl and tank), a warped horn (the outlet piece that projects
from the base of the toilet) or a misshapen base.
</P>
<P>
   Also make sure that all the hardware as well as the tank
mechanism is included. Keep the carton, wrapping material and
paperwork in case you have to return a defective unit.
</P>
<P>
   When you remove the old toilet, the flange will still be screwed
to the floor with two closet bolts projecting upward through slots
in the flange. You can use these, provided they are in good
condition. If the bolts are rusted or corroded, they should be
replaced. You will have to buy new closet bolts, as they are not
part of the hardware kit that comes with the new toilet.
</P>
<P>
   You will also have to buy a wax gasket. The gasket forms the
seal around the toilet horn and prevents leaks. Plumbers differ on
whether it is better to place the gasket onto the horn and then
push the toilet in place on the floor flange, or to position the
gasket on the flange and lower the toilet onto it. Either method
will work, provided you maneuver the toilet carefully onto the
flange to avoid damaging or distorting the soft wax gasket. Turn
the bowl upright and lower it slowly onto the closet bolts.
</P>
<P>
   Some books suggest that you press down hard with your full
weight to seat the bowl and shape the gasket to make a watertight
seal. If you try this, be very careful to apply even pressure to
the toilet rim. If you lean too hard on one side, you will distort
the wax gasket and it will eventually leak. Also be careful of
applying too much pressure; this could also distort the gasket.
</P>
<P>
   A better way to seat the bowl is by tightening the nuts on the
closet bolts. Start on one side and give the nut five or six turns
then move to other side and do the same. Repeat this alternate
tightening routine until the bowl is snug to the floor. Do not
overtighten these nuts or you could crack the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to mount the tank onto the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The installation procedure for the tank is straightforward;
detailed instructions should be included with the toilet hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Invert the tank so the large opening, the flush-valve outlet,
mates with the inlet opening on rear of the toilet rim. Push the
two tank bolts through the bottom the tank and bowl rim. Align the
tank so it is parallel with the rear wall, then tighten the bolts.
Hook up the supply tube to the inlet opening under the tank and
turn on the water.
</P>
<P>
   The last step is to draw a bead of caulk around the base of the
toilet and the finish floor.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good idea, however, to wait a week before doing this.
This will allow time for you to inspect the toilet base for any
leaks that may occur around the wax seal. With the caulk bead in
place, these leaks may be blocked and run under the floor where
they will remain undetected until the water damages the space
below. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
