<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HOPES TIME WILL HEAL PALESTINIAN-ISRAELI DIFFERENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After two weeks of deal-making that ended without a
deal, President Clinton said Wednesday that the key to a Middle
East peace agreement was more time for internal debate and
reflection by the Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said the U.S. envoy for the region, Dennis Ross,
would travel there in the coming weeks to gauge any
post-summit-meeting progress, but officials ruled out follow-up
negotiations in the United States any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is going to be an agreement here, it must be one
which meets the legitimate interests of both parties,'' Clinton
told reporters at the White House. ``And that requires a certain
imagination and flexibility of defining those interests and
figuring out an institutional and legal framework for them that,
frankly, just takes more time and more reflection and probably less
pressure than was available in our 15 days at Camp David.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting the historic nature of the talks, he added, ``You've got
to get used to talking about something for a little bit before you
can then entertain how you can create an edifice that you hadn't
previously imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials Wednesday refused to disclose details of
the back and forth of the closed-door negotiations. They said they
believed that they would have to build on the progress of the Camp
David talks in the coming months, and did not want to hamper future
deals by disclosing the Israeli and Palestinian negotiating
positions.
</P>
<P>
   As they looked back on the negotiations, White House officials
did describe Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel as being far more
willing to deal than Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinians, with respect particularly to the issue of
Jerusalem, were not as prepared to compromise,'' Sandy Berger, the
president's national security adviser, said in an interview on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the talks enabled Clinton Wednesday to turn his
sights back to his domestic agenda. He staged events celebrating
the 10th anniversary of the Americans with Disabilities Act and
criticizing Republican tax cut plans.
</P>
<P>
   But the president, responding to questions from reporters,
eagerly offered a post-mortem of the talks. He said a deal would
emerge only when both sides accepted partial victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any negotiation, it must be possible for both sides to say
they got most of what they wanted and needed, that they were not
routed from the field, that there was honorable compromise,'' he
said. ``The issues cannot be framed in a `you have to lose in order
for me to win' and `in order for you to win, I have to lose'
framework.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the two parties faced possible violence in the weeks
leading up to Sept. 13, the date on which Arafat has said he will
declare a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties do face a fundamental crossroads,'' Berger said.
``Down one road is confrontation and conflict. Down the other road
is an agreement and peace, and that involves compromise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
