<HEADLINE>
$ADV16  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: DOUBLE CORN POLENTA WITH SAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: For use Wednesday, Aug. 16, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's 20MINUTE-MENUS. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of 20MINUTE-MENUS _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first thing that comes to mind when you think of
Italian-American food is probably pizza. Followed, perhaps, by
spaghetti and meatballs.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many newer and more interesting ways to put the
two culinary cultures together for those who want something simple
and different.
</P>
<P>
   In this summer season when the corn is as high as an elephant's
eye _ unlike last summer when there was so little rain in the East
_ I want to use the ears on every possible occasion. (This year it
is so sweet, I've even eaten it raw.)
</P>
<P>
   What more natural combination than fresh corn to give texture
and sweetness to the Italian version of cornmeal _ polenta. The
fresh corn is all-American; the polenta, distinctly Italian. And so
is the use of sage with polenta. The powerful herb adds a pungency
to the dish.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in Parmigiano Reggiano and you have a very fresh and rustic
Italian-American creation.
</P>
<P>
   This is also the time of year to use fresh herbs wherever they
might add some fragrance and flavor to greens that otherwise seem a
bit bland. I have suggested basil, thyme and oregano for the mixed
green salad, but you can use any combination of herbs that appeals
to you: chervil, marjoram, rosemary, etc.
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLE CORN POLENTA WITH SAGE &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2 large ears corn (1 1/2 to 2 cups kernels)
</P>
<P>
   6 fresh sage leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce Parmigiano Reggiano to yield 2 tablespoons coarsely
grated
</P>
<P>
   2 cups no-salt-added chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely ground polenta or instant polenta
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Scrape the kernels from the corn. Wash, dry and cut the sage
into fine strips. Coarsely grate the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring the stock to a boil in covered pot. Slowly stir in the
cornmeal with a wire whisk so that it does not lump. Reduce heat,
add the corn kernels and continue stirring until liquid has been
absorbed and mixture is thick.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the sage and cheese. Season with salt and pepper and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   HERBED GREENS
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces mixed greens or mesclun
</P>
<P>
   6 basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 large sprig thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 large sprig oregano
</P>
<P>
   1. Whisk the oil, vinegar and mustard together in a salad bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash and dry the greens and herbs. Slice the basil into thin
strips. Remove the leaves from the thyme and oregano sprigs. Mix
the greens and herbs together with the dressing and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the polenta through step 1.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare salad.
</P>
<P>
   Finish polenta.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Parmigiano Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   No-salt-added chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   Fine-grained or instant polenta
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   2 large ears corn
</P>
<P>
   Bunch sage (6 leaves)
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces mixed greens or mesclun
</P>
<P>
   Bunch basil (6 leaves)
</P>
<P>
   Bunch thyme (1 large sprig)
</P>
<P>
   Bunch oregano (1 large sprig)
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 580 calories, 9 grams total
fat; less than 1 gram saturated fat; 10 milligrams cholesterol; 210
milligrams sodium; 85 grams carbohydrates; 10 grams fiber; 15 grams
protein.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
