<HEADLINE>
A ROVING SHOW FIXATES ON EUROPE'S BORDER OBSESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Arts Abroad) 
(Eds: Quotation in 12th graf, `At the 5 mounth I live in Italy,' is
cq) 
 By JOSEPHINE SCHMIDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LJUBLJANA, Slovenia _ Sleek electric signs appeared in late June
over the neo-Renaissance balustrades that frame the walkways of the
Tromostovje, or Three Bridges, at the heart of this capital. Had
the signs offered directions to the business district or a historic
landmark, they would have attracted scant attention in a city where
past and present mingle easily. But these signs, created by Selja
Kameric, a Sarajevo artist, are meant to conjure up the new Europe,
or one vision of it.
</P>
<P>
   In large white letters against a vibrant blue background,
evoking the notices that direct arriving passengers toward Customs
at many European airports, the words ``European Union'' beckon,
illuminated from behind at night. On the other side of the
Ljubljnica River, in black and white, is just one word: ``Other.''
</P>
<P>
   Kameric, 23, is one of 59 artists and groups from both European
Union nations and the ``other'' Europe _ countries like Poland,
Macedonia, Slovakia, Russia and Kameric's native Bosnia and
Herzegovina _ whose works are being exhibited here, near the
frontier that long divided Europe into East and West. They are part
of Manifesta 3, the European Biennial of Contemporary Art, which
continues until Sept. 24; the exhibition contains no traditional
painting or sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manifesta wants to reflect Europe,'' said Kathrin Rhomberg, an
Austrian who is one of the show's four curators. ``But it is a very
difficult thing to do because Europe is such a complex and
unhomogeneous continent.''
</P>
<P>
   Manifesta 3 offers a snapshot of a Europe where the political
distinction of East and West has given way to a web of new
divisions. Scattered among Ljubljana's public squares and museums
are works ranging from semidocumentary videos to highly conceptual
installations that address issues like inclusion in or exclusion
from the European Union or NATO; national identity; immigration;
and conflicts in the former Yugoslavia, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to stop talking about East vs. West,'' said Maria
Hlavajova, a Manifesta 3 curator who is the former director of the
Soros Center for Contemporary Art in Bratislava, Slovakia, and now
works in Utrecht in the Netherlands. ``We want Eastern artists
mingled with Western artists. You have to put all these countries
in a box and shake them up differently.''
</P>
<P>
   The roots of Manifesta go back to 1993, when a group of Dutch
arts professionals decided to organize a biennial that would create
a pan-European colloquy. They wanted the show to be nomadic, with a
new host city and new team of curators every two years, to reflect
an ever-changing Europe.
</P>
<P>
   More established exhibitions like Dokumenta in Kassel, Germany,
or the Venice Biennale have rarely included artists from outside
the European Union. And exhibitions that focused solely on art from
the former Soviet Union and Eastern Europe segregated artists,
Manifesta's founders felt.
</P>
<P>
   The first Manifesta was held in 1996 in Rotterdam. In 2 1/2
months the exhibition attracted several hundred artists, curators
and critics and 20,000 viewers. Two years later the exhibition
moved to Luxembourg and this year, for Manifesta's first foray
beyond the European Union, more than 1,000 people traveled here for
the opening during the last weekend in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go to Manifesta a lot more than to other
biennials,'' said Sonja Wilk, a curator at the Nordic Institute for
Contemporary Art in Finland, who came from her native Norway. ``I
knew that here the art would probably surprise me.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the art was created for this show. For instance,
``Exchange 2000'' is a recorded radio broadcast in which people of
different ethnicities discuss problems caused by immigration,
obliquely addressing the psychological borders erected by
nationalism. Daniel Jewesbury, who lives in Belfast, said he had
created the piece because of his ``discomfort at being a citizen of
Fortress Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   A room-size installation by Stalker, a decade-old group with
headquarters in the Campo Boario section of Rome, a magnet for
recent arrivals from Moldova, Senegal and Kurdistan, focuses on
immigration to the European Union. Called ``Transborderline,'' it
consists of a room bisected by a floor-to-ceiling spiral of plastic
tubing. As visitors shuffle through the passageway, white soccer
balls, many inscribed by the residents of Campo Boario, roll from
place to place. One, signed Mebin Biger, reads in English: ``Kurde
from Turkey. At the 5 mounth I live in Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   In another large installation, Pravdoliub Ivanov has arrayed
more than a dozen brightly colored, battered teapots and kettles on
hot plates, connecting them to a network of black electrical cords
that snake across the floor. The water in the vessels never quite
reaches a full boil. Ivanov, who lives in Bulgaria, calls his 1998
work ``Transformation Always Takes Time and Energy.''
</P>
<P>
   To create Anton Olshvang's `Battlefield,'' discarded home
photographs, rejects purchased from photo-processing laboratories
near the provincial Russian city of Samara, were enlarged to the
size of posters and mounted with the triangular corner tabs used in
old photo albums. The images create what Olshvang calls an
``unconscious'' portrait of contemporary Russian culture.
</P>
<P>
   Among the numerous videos is Agnese Bule's ``Discover Latvia,''
a wry 1950s-style faux documentary that spins a myth about the
origins of the Latvian nation. The war in Kosovo is the subject of
the 1999 videos ``Simple Instrument'' and ``How to Make a Refugee''
by Phil Collins, who lives in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   In one, an interviewer asks a series of simple questions, like
``Do you ever wear a hat?'' and ``What is a border?'' ``A border,''
says one woman, ``is something that makes you problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Borders is the theme of Manifesta 3. During the year Rhomberg,
Hlavajova and their colleagues traversed Europe to select artists
for the show, they were struck, they say, by new borders, both
geographical and psychological, reflected in the work they saw.
They were also influenced by the war in Kosovo, which was about to
break out a few hundred miles to the east of this city when the
curators met in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new borders seem to have risen in Europe's cultural
community. Olshvang, who lives in Moscow but has worked in the
Netherlands and the United States, said that much of ``the place
that is in between'' East and West was still routinely ignored by
the Western art world, a criticism shared by other artists from
Eastern Europe and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Dunja Blazevic, a curator from Sarajevo, said her country
suffered from a cultural isolation that did not exist when it was
part of the former Yugoslavia, and its artists and intellectuals
often worked with colleagues from the West. But, she said,
``Manifesta is the only international biennial in which the two
parts of Europe _ and there are really still two parts _ are
connected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
