<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-OLEMISS0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ole Miss has first legitimate Heisman candidate since Archie
Manning
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Birmingham _ The last time the University of Mississippi had a
legitimate Heisman Trophy candidate, Richard Nixon was president
and the Watergate was just a hotel complex.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday here at the SEC preseason meetings, Mississippi
officially began the Heisman campaign for running back Deuce
McAllister. It is the school's first since Archie Manning in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's got a chance,'' Vanderbilt coach Woody Widenhofer
said. ``Deuce has got all the skills you look for in a great
player. We will see him at the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   The pros agree. The National Football Scouting Service, one of
two combines for 27 NFL teams, has rated him the No. 1 prospect for
the 2001 Draft.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who was the No. 2 rusher on his team last
season. Joe Gunn led the Rebels in rushing with 978 yards.
McAllister had 930, which included four consecutive games over 100
yards.
</P>
<P>
   But the 6-1, 222-pound McAllister will get into the Heisman race
because of his amazing versatility as a runner, pass receiver and
kick returner.
</P>
<P>
   Last season McAllister set a Mississippi record with
</P>
<P>
   1,682 all-purpose yards. He broke Parker Hall's 61-year-old
record of 1,592 yards. In 1998, McAllister became only the second
Mississippi back to rush for 1,000 yards.
</P>
<P>
   This season, McAllister, from Morton, Miss., will touch the ball
in every conceivable fashion, coach David Cutcliffe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's by far the most complete player I've been around, and
I've been around some pretty good ones,'' said Cutcliffe, a
longtime Tennessee assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a 225- pounder who can run a legitimate 4.3 (in the
40-yard) dash and can bench 400 pounds,'' the coach said. ``He's a
very special talent.''
</P>
<P>
   McAllister is no ordinary Heisman candidate. He came to
Mississippi as an honors graduate from high school. He once
performed at Carnegie Hall with his high school choral group.
Earlier this year, he spent three weeks in Costa Rica in an
accelerated study program to pick up some extra credits in Spanish.
He plans to graduate in December with a degree in criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deuce is not only a great football player,'' Cutcliffe said,
``but he's the kind of guy you want to represent the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   McAllister could have turned pro after his junior season and
become financially secure. But he decided to return to lead a
Mississippi team that legitimately can compete for the SEC Western
Division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt that if I'm destined to play in the NFL, it will
be out there,'' he said. ``Getting my degree is important,
especially to my mother. I just wanted to see how good this team
could be.''
</P>
<P>
   The early favorites for the Heisman are quarterbacks Michael
Vick (Virginia Tech), Drew Brees (Purdue) and Chris Weinke (Florida
State). But Mississippi has committed significant resources to the
effort of getting their man into the minds of the voters.
</P>
<P>
   McAllister has his own Web site (thedeuceisloose.com). The
school will send out schedule cards and postcards bearing his
likeness, and Mississippi's first three games are televised.
</P>
<P>
   If McAllister is going to make a serious run at the Heisman, the
key dates will be Oct. 14 and Nov. 23. On Oct. 14, the Rebels
travel to Tuscaloosa to meet Alabama, which should be ranked in the
top five nationally. A great performance against the Crimson Tide
would go a long way towards McAllister's hopes.
</P>
<P>
   If McAllister still is a Heisman candidate in November, he will
play his last regular-season game against Mississippi State on
Thanksgiving night on national television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that we've got to win some big games, and I'm going to
have to make some plays in those games,'' McAllister said. ``It's
still about what happens on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   McAllister already has had several conversations with Manning,
who did not win the trophy, on how to handle the Heisman hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``Archie and I have talked about how to handle certain
situations and the importance of making yourself available to the
media,'' McAllister said. ``But I've grown up watching Michael
Jordan and Magic Johnson and now Tigers Woods handle themselves. I
know that all you can do is be yourself. I'm just going to let it
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
