<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER YOU GO UPSCALE, THEN WHERE?
</HEADLINE>
  By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Have you noticed how many things
are becoming upscale?
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new store, associated with khaki and adventure, and described
by promoters as upscale, is moving into one of the nearby malls.
Another shop, which majors in career clothes for the hip
professional, is the new upscale jewel in a suburban shopping
center.
</P>
<P>
   The center, as the story goes, is aiming for a Rodeo Drive feel.
The beauty parlor is moving out.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an old steakhouse known for its country music and
shot-and-a-beer image is being transformed, we read, into an
upscale Italian restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I personally prefer squash raviolis to a
T-bone and will be in line to check out the lush gardens and doors
imported from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   And those high-style stores are the type that I've often wished
we had close to home. They smell good. The clerks have expensive
haircuts. Normally found in big cities or fancy suburbs, now
they'll be next door.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, upscale means you pay more. The cost of a T-shirt in
those shops may make your eyes water, but the bag you take it home
in is chic. Upscale Italian doesn't usually include meatballs and
candles in Chianti bottles.
</P>
<P>
   But if upscale is moving in, something's happening. We're no
longer a backwater in the eyes of high-end retailers. Somebody's
marketing research has decided that we've got money to spend. And
apparently, judging from the soaring cost of Wine Country real
estate and influx of dot-com royalty, plenty of people do.
</P>
<P>
   A few of us were talking about this the other morning, and
hoping we don't get too upscale. Not only do we worry that the
housing costs are pricing out teachers and people who make music
and artists who once lived here pretty cheaply, ``upscale'' creates
an image of privilege that doesn't fit most of us commoners.
</P>
<P>
   There are dangers of growing too tony. What would happen if your
gym turned upscale and you couldn't go there in the morning with
bed hair? If the county fair went upscale would they have to ban
corn dogs and get rid of Farmers Day?
</P>
<P>
   When upscale is just part of the mix, it's a welcome addition.
When it takes over, you get stuck on yourself. They write stories
about you like they do about the Hamptons, where there are no real
people left, just people with ``buckets of money,'' spending
thousands of dollars on imported shower nozzles.
</P>
<P>
   People need an antidote to upscale so they don't forget that man
and woman cannot live on duck confit and Donna Karan alone.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, it's important to keep supporting the plain and
simple places. One of my favorites is a restaurant where they don't
worry about food trends. It's where you go when you crave home
fries that stick to your ribs and want to feel comfortable putting
ketchup on your food. Where if you start to tell the waitress you'd
like your eggs prepared any style but the three ways the menu
offers, she'll say ``remember where you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Where we are, people still like to spend weekend mornings at a
flea market and shop for clothes in discount stores where you wheel
through the aisles with a grocery cart. This is not only
economically essential for some people, but also a place to score a
designer top for under $10 by those who might also shop upscale,
where the sweaters are folded in stacks.
</P>
<P>
   Where we are, people like to sit at a counter drinking house
coffee as much as they like to go to an umbrella table and sip
fresh espresso. You can still find donut shops and barber shops and
dark bars that smell like old tobacco and where you know not to
order the wine.
</P>
<P>
   It depends on whose scale you're going by as to what is up. In
some towns, a new superstore where you can buy hot peppers in
gallon-sized jars is an upscale move.
</P>
<P>
   When I first moved to Northern California in the '70s, I was
thrilled by the ocean, hills, hippies and redwoods. I was also
relieved to find a JM store. JM, for Joseph Magnin, which no longer
exists, was to me, back then, a necessity of civilized life and an
assurance that there was style along with natural attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Now I would add theater, music, every kind of restaurant, book
stores, coffee houses and upscale bakeries with gourmet bread like
the one where my friends and I sat, calculating how much our
property is worth and hoping that things don't get too precious.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
