<HEADLINE>
HARRY POTTER FANS FIND THE WEB'S WIZARDS
</HEADLINE>
  By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   ``You've read the book, now see
the movie,'' was the way the progression used to be. Now it's:
``You've read the book, now visit the Web site.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Harry Potter fans, there are many sites available. The
July/August issue of Children's Software Revue lists five that
Hogwarts aspirants may want to visit:
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters can find out about J.K. Rowling at
www.scholastic.com/harrypotter/home.asp. Scholastic publishes the
series, and this Web site is, by far, the most professional of the
bunch. (By ``most professional,'' I mean the graphics are well
done, it is well arranged, and there are no obvious misspelled
words that seem to plague some of the other sites.) Kids can also
download a Harry Potter screensaver, write an Owl Post to their
online friends, take a wizard trivia test and join discussions of
the four books.
</P>
<P>
   Another site _ www.surfnetkids.com/harrypotter.htm _ offers
several links to other Potter-related sites, including an
encyclopedia defining some of the words used in the books. Look
under the ``related items'' at the upper left of the screen to find
a Potter crossword and a word-search game.
</P>
<P>
   The Harry Potter characters hang out at Hagrids's Hut _
www.hagridshut.com. The books' characters are described in detail.
</P>
<P>
   The official site for the Warner Bros. movie, ``Harry Potter and
The Sorcerer's Stone,'' is www.harrypotter.com. Kids shouldn't get
their hopes up when they see the offer to star in the upcoming
movie to be filmed in England this summer (with a release date of
Nov. 16). The fine print: The company is looking for English
children to send in a recent picture of themselves and a video of
them telling a joke and reading a paragraph from their favorite
Potter book. (Maybe American children could fake the British accent
after listening to some ``Monty Python'' recordings?)
</P>
<P>
   Other than an interview with the film's director, Chris Columbus
(''Home Alone,'' ``Mrs. Doubtfire''), there's not much there right
now.
</P>
<P>
   At www.homestead.com/bumbledore, kids can write reviews of the
books or leave comments and read what others have said. Children
(and adults, too) can vote on their most hated character in the
books. Currently, Draco Malfoy, Harry's antagonist in the Slytherin
house, leads, followed closely by Professor Snape, the potions
teacher who heads the Slytherin house.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
