<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-LEADERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK, ARAFAT FACE CHALLENGES AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Bible says ``blessed are the peacemakers,'' but
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat returned home from a failed Camp David summit Wednesday to
the political hell they must survive before they can be so blessed.
</P>
<P>
   Both leaders face almost impossible domestic challenges. The
atmosphere is pregnant with the possibilty of resolving the 52-year
old conflict _ but also consumed by a fear that Israelis and
Palestinians might end up fighting rather than compromising on
their claims to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Barak, who arrived home Wednesday night, will have
to move ``straight from the tarmac,'' as one put it, to rebuild his
government.
</P>
<P>
   His coalition, One Israel, collapsed the night he left to begin
14 days of negotiations at Camp David. The religious and
conservative flank, fearful that he would compromise too much at
Camp David, bolted and forced a ``no confidence'' motion that Barak
very narrowly survived.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is caught between those who say he did not move enough
toward a peace deal and those who say he raised Palestinian
expectations too high by offering so many concessions.
</P>
<P>
   He must either invite the more conservative opposition Likud
Party into a national unity government, or perhaps shift the axis
of his political future to the left and rebuild a coalition among a
traditionally secular peace camp.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, whose plane touched down in the new but hardly used
international airport in Gaza, arrived to a hero's welcome. He
stopped first in Egypt to meet with the Egyptian president, Hosni
Mubarak. Arafat's stance on Jerusalem (Barak has characterized it
as intransigence) has improved his standing not only among the
Palestinians, but throughout the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   However, if he fails to consolidate sufficient support among
Arab leaders and ordinary Palestinians to find a way to share
sovereignty in Jerusalem, he will not succeed in reaching a
comprehensive peace agreement before a Sept. 13 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has vowed on that date _ with or without a final peace
deal _ to declare an independent Palestinian state. However, if
Arafat declares statehood without recognition from Israel or the
United States he is likely to reverse many of the gains of a
seven-year peace process and a 35-year struggle for Palestinian
independence.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are no less, military strategists say, than a
military confrontation between Israel and Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, a former general who is the most highly decorated soldier
in the history of the Israeli army, blamed Arafat for failing to
seize a historic opportunity, saying, ``The Palestinians didn't
realize that for peace you have to give up some of your dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the key players in a difficult Israeli political terrain
is another former general, Likud leader Ariel Sharon. Barak was
considered likely to meet with Sharon, and some analysts suggested
he could emerge in a coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat made no speech, and does not have to worry about the
democratic process in his government. But he cannot go kept
negotiating without the support of the Arab world. And his tough
stance at Camp David seemed to go over well there.
</P>
<P>
   The West Bank, captured by Israel from Jordan in 1967, is a
vital part of a final peace process. So far, the Palestinian
Authority has full or partial control over roughly 40 percent of
the land. Barak reportedly offered to withdraw Israeli troops from
as much as 95 percent of the West Bank to Arafat in exchange for a
declaration of the end of 52 years of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement was not reached, collapsing over sovereignty in
Jerusalem. Israel declares Jerusalem its ``eternal and indivisible
capital.'' Palestinians say east Jerusalem and the walled Old City,
which Israeli captured in 1967 and annexed, must be the sovereign
capital of the future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank city of Ramallah, there were small
demonstrations in support of Arafat. A billboard of Arafat with his
arms folded in defiance loomed over the about 100 marchers.
</P>
<P>
   Nimeh Rashadeh, 52 and a mother of 10, wore a traditional
embroidered dress and a white headscarf as she lifted an Arafat
poster. ``Jerusalem is ours or it's a war and the blood will run
knee deep. We suffered in the intifadah. We suffered a lot. We
suffered in 1967. I was born in the war of 1948 when my family was
forced from its home. Yes, I want another war if that's what it
takes to get our country back.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Murad Audeh, 23, who was working at his family's jewelery
shop, ``I hope there won't be a war. I hope peace will come, but
something tells me there will be a confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling was similar on the string of Jewish settlements in
the West Bank. Paul Ross, who emigrated to Israel from California
and lives in Rimonim settlement, said, ``We are out here with the
Indians around us.''
</P>
<P>
   As bulldozers grounded away, expanding the settlement, Ross
added, ``As soon as the Indians come over the hill, we have a war
on our hands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
