<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3845 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MEATLOAF0727-COX     07-26 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEATLOAF0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VH1 movie gives 'warts-and-all' view of rocky career
 &HT;    By Kevin Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Most people are afraid of going to hell. Meat
Loaf has already been there.
</P>
<P>
   As a portly kid, the future rock star and singer of such hits as
``Paradise by the Dashboard Light'' and ``Two Out of Three Ain't
Bad'' was often teased and bullied. He was given the name Meat Loaf
(his real name is Marvin Lee Aday) because of his rotund frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children were very cruel to me because of my size,'' Meat Loaf
said during a 1995 interview. ``But you develop a strength from
cruelty. You don't go along with the crowd because the crowd won't
let you go along with them. So you learn to be your own person.''
</P>
<P>
   But that took years of hard living and soul-searching. His
mother died of cancer when he was 16. After his mother's funeral,
Meat Loaf's father, in a drunken rage, chased him out of the house
with a butcher knife. He never went back. And, like countless other
musicians, Meat Loaf had legendary bouts with drugs, alcohol and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the perfect VH1 movie, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Meat Loaf: To Hell and Back'' (today, 9 p.m.) tells the true
story of one of rock's most unlikely heroes who followed overnight
fame in the 1970s with career-destroying problems and a rise back
to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kind of warts-and-all story,'' says director Jim
McBride, who knows something about rock and rage, having directed
the Jerry Lee Lewis story, ``Great Balls of Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gaspin, VH1's executive vice president for programming and
production, says the decision to make a film about Meat Loaf's life
was a no-brainer. After all, the singer was one of the first
subjects of the wildly popular documentary series ``Behind the
Music.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, the tortured, 53-year-old rock icon is played by W.
Earl Brown, perhaps best known as Cameron Diaz's mentally
challenged younger brother in the film ``There's Something About
Mary.'' In several scenes, Brown looks eerily similar to Meat Loaf.
</P>
<P>
   Brown definitely could relate to his painful upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through the same, torturous thing of picking on the fat
kid,'' he recalls. ``And there were things that obviously still
haunt him. And I could draw on my own experience because things
still bother me from being beaten up when I was 6 years old by the
10-year-old bully.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Brown considers himself an avid Meat Loaf fan, he
studied hours of taped performances and old films to capture Meat
Loaf's larger-than-life stage presence.
</P>
<P>
   He points out, however, that it was important for him to play
the man behind the entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meat Loaf considers what he does just entertainment,'' Brown
says. ``He says, `I'm an entertainer. Like a plumber comes and
fixes your pipes, you come to my show. I entertain you.' But I
think there's a lot more to him than that. I think he's an artist
and he deals with his own issues through his performances. He is
this gregarious, funny, slap-on-the-back, always got a joke (guy),
but there's more going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown says he met Meat Loaf in person and had lengthy
discussions about his life. Meat Loaf was somewhat reluctant,
though, to talk about his tough childhood and his fractured
relationship with his mother and father.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the two really hit it off when Meat Loaf learned
Brown is a die-hard softball player.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm sitting at Meat Loaf's house, he asks me if I play
golf, and I said, `Yes, but poorly.' I said, `Softball's my big
thing,' `` Brown remembers. ``His eyes light up. He goes, `Are you
playing now?' I said, `Well, our season starts next week, but I
can't play the first five games because of the film. I don't want
to risk twisting something.' To make a long story short, Meat Loaf
ends up playing on my softball team, playing my position.''
</P>
<P>
   So, how'd he do? After all, Meat Loaf hadn't played softball in
about five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went 1-for-4,'' Brown says.
</P>
<P>
   And who's the better player?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Brown says, laughing, ``I play every week. And, you
know, I'm 17 years younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
