<SLUG> BC-AOL-BLIND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT DROPPED AS AOL SAYS SOFTWARE WILL BE ACCESSIBLE TO BLIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America Online Inc. has fended off a lawsuit that could have
compelled all Web sites and Internet service providers to make
their services available to blind people.
</P>
<P>
   AOL was sued in Boston last year by the National Federation for
the Blind (NFB). The group argued that AOL, the world's largest
Internet access provider with 22 million members, is required by
the federal Americans with Disabilities Act to make its services
accessible to blind users.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, AOL said it was already at work on a version of its
software that would be compatible with ``screen readers,'' which
can read the contents of a computer screen aloud. ``We've always
been committed to meeting the needs of underserved communities,
including the (disabled) community,'' said AOL spokesman Rich
D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it took months of discussion to resolve the dispute. NFB
attorney Joseph Davis of Adler, Pollock &AMP; Sheehan said it took time
for his client to accept that AOL was acting in good faith. ``Once
it became apparent to us that there really were committed people at
AOL, then there was a better dialogue,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The new version of AOL software, due for release this fall,
should be usable by anyone with a screen reader. AOL also has
promised to consult with the NFB on future software upgrades. In
return, the NFB has withdrawn its lawsuit, but it reserves the
right to refile the suit in a year if insufficient progress has
been made.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement leaves unresolved an interesting legal question.
Some advocates for the disabled say the Internet is now such a
pervasive part of American life that an inability to use it has
become a severe disadvantage. They argue that Internet providers
and Web site operators should be subject to the Americans with
Disabilities Act, which requires businesses to make reasonable
accommodations for disabled employees and customers.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said AOL's accessibility policy should send a strong
message to other Internet companies that they ought to do the same.
He added that the NFB is keeping an eye on major Internet
businesses and may sue others that don't make special provision for
blind users.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
