<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3850 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-COMMENTARY-WINNERS25-     07-26 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-WINNERS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Lance Armstrong and Tiger Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The corps of young Americans setting the sports world afire, and
dominating Europe at its own games this month, is a testament to
determination, hard work and the American spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's Lance Armstrong, 28, muted his detractors in Europe's
competitive bicycling circuit by winning the Tour de France for the
second consecutive time. Armstrong's inspiring story is well-known
around the world by now, but his victories didn't come without
sacrifice and a punishing training regime, something often
forgotten in the glow of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's lead early in the grinding, three-week endurance
race left the outcome assured. Hardly less certain was the other
young American victor Sunday, Tiger Woods, who won the British Open
golf tournament at St. Andrews, Scotland, to become the youngest
golfer ever to win all four major professional tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, only 24, was properly respectful about winning at the
birthplace of modern golf. But his modesty doesn't hide a fierce
competitor who practices long hours, stresses physical conditioning
and works to improve his strokes even as he dominates the game.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the month in England, 20-year-old Venus Williams won
the tennis title at Wimbledon, beating her younger sister, Serena,
on the way. The talented Williams sisters are now forces to be
dealt with on the women's professional tennis circuit and are
likely to remain so for some years.
</P>
<P>
   These young athletes are unusual sports heroes. Armstrong was
raised in difficult circumstances and was stricken by cancer just
as he was beginning to ascend in the cycling world. The Williams
sisters are African Americans from the famously poor Los Angeles
suburb of Compton and competing in a sport associated with white
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the golfing world saw Tiger Woods coming from a very
young age. But he is still a rarity, a blend of races and cultures
that made him both the first black man to win the British Open and
the first of Asian descent.
</P>
<P>
   These champions are the face of America _ black, white and
blended. They are the soul of the country, too _ intense,
hard-working and iron-willed. More importantly, they are its heart.
</P>
<P>
   America's dominant position among the world's nations today make
it an easy target. But look beneath the veneer of a rich, powerful
nation and you see that the true value of the United States is in
these young men and women, these competitors, these winners.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
