<HEADLINE>
PUTIN WINS FIGHT WITH GOVERNORS, WHO WILL LOSE SEATS IN
PARLIAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After two months of maneuvering, President Vladimir
Putin and 89 of Russia's most powerful leaders _ the nation's
czar-like regional governors _ faced off Wednesday in a
long-anticipated political showdown.
</P>
<P>
   It was not even a contest.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of hours, the governors accepted almost without
protest Putin's proposal to overhaul the federal tax code, a plan
that promises to break their control over billions of rubles in tax
receipts.
</P>
<P>
   They also voted _ as Putin had also demanded _ to abolish their
own seats in the Federation Council, the upper house of the Russian
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation approved Wednesday, the governors and 89
members of provincial legislatures whom they had handpicked will
leave by January 2002, giving way to a full-time, and somewhat more
independent, group of legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's entire proceeding belied the predictions of
politicians and pundits alike that the governors, who have run
their provinces like fiefs since the days of President Boris
Yeltsin, would fight to the end Putin's plan to curb their powers.
</P>
<P>
   Since his inauguration in May, Putin has moved to reassert
Moscow's historic grip on the regions, arguing that the governors _
some of whom have ignored the constitution and even pondered
secession _ must be subservient to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Over the concerns of some analysts that the Kremlin is
effectively rebuilding the all-powerful state of Soviet days, Putin
now seems to have accomplished much of his goal.
</P>
<P>
   The council voted 119-18 to end the automatic right of governors
and their legislative appointees to sit in the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The will of the emperor, or that of the president, is
tantamount to law,'' said the council member and governor of
Chuvash, Nikolai Fyodorov, during the debate Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the council may have had little choice. The lower
house of Parliament, the Duma, which has always bristled at the
governors' claim of superiority, had already agreed by a virtually
veto-proof margin to Putin's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The council members agreed to their own ouster after persuading
the lower house and the Kremlin to accept a compromise that holds
out the prospect of a new constitutional convention to set a final
form for the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise also allowed members to remain in the council
until their terms expire, and gave the governors the right to
appoint and remove their successors. Council members from the
provincial legislatures, who had been named in the past by the
governors, will now be elected by their peers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The lower house had already overridden the governors' veto of an
earlier law that gives Putin the right to fire governors and
dissolve provincial legislatures should they act in violation of
the federal constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's victory in the battle over tax laws was every bit
as complete, and potentially as significant.
</P>
<P>
   The Federation Council voted in unexpectedly lopsided fashion,
115-23, to adopt a package of changes that will cut the income tax
to a flat 13 percent from a top rate of 35 percent, slash a
much-derided tax on the cash flow of businesses, and marginally cut
payroll taxes for pensions and other social programs.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the bill abolishes a warren of special funds
that had been created for various taxes, giving the federal tax
service the power to collect and administer their receipts. The
move is expected to reduce corruption and favoritism in government
offices where officials had used the money more or less as personal
kitties.
</P>
<P>
   The cash-flow tax, a 4 percent levy on the revenues of
profitable and unprofitable businesses alike, will be cut to 1
percent. The Kremlin had sought to abolish the tax, but settled for
the reduction to appease the governors, for whom it has been a
major source of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Many outsiders thought the Federation Council would veto at
least some of the tax changes to protect their own sources of
revenue, especially because some of the more contentious provisions
had barely squeaked through the lower house earlier. Some said the
council would approve the law but block a second technical measure
that actually implemented it.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, a furious lobbying effort by the Kremlin _ and a
threat to put the law into effect by executive order, whether the
council approved the technical measure or not _ appeared to win
over the legislators.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are expected to reduce corporate taxes by about 20
percent overall. Putin's prime minister and former finance
minister, Mikhail M. Kasyanov, had told the legislators that
passing the tax code was crucial if the Russian economy, which
lately has been growing at a 5 percent annual clip, was to avoid a
slowdown and a potential recession.
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov said the economy has all but exhausted the benefit it
got in 1998 when the ruble was sharply devalued, making Russian
exports a bargain for foreign buyers and sparking a small
manufacturing boom. Further growth, he said, would have to be
fueled internally by lowering onerous taxes and removing government
obstacles to a free market.
</P>
<P>
   The stiffest objections of the day came from the Parliament
member and mayor of Moscow, Yuri Luzhkov, who said the changes
would effectively leave regions like his beholden to the Kremlin
for handouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone will be confined to a stall,'' he said, ``with the
government offering handfuls of hay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
