<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON FINDS IT DIFFICULT TO LEAVE WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 30)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While George W. Bush and Al Gore await the cues
that will summon one of them to stage center as America's next
president, Bill Clinton is traveling and performing as if he were
beginning rather than ending his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   The peripatetic president shuttles from one major event to
another _ such as the failed Israeli-Arab peace talks at Camp
David, Md., and the Okinawa summit of the leaders of Russia and the
world's great industrial nations. He is so involved with the
potency and perquisites of his job that one almost expects his
successor to have to wrench the scepter of power from Clinton's
tight grip when his term expires at high noon on Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the reigning superstar of American public life for
nearly eight years, shows little inclination to yield the spotlight
that has illuminated his every action, including his sordid sexual
misadventures, since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   When the White House curtain finally falls, he will be 55, in
excellent health and in search of projects to satisfy his
restlessness.
</P>
<P>
   His wife may be a newly elected U.S. senator from New York, and
he, like his recent predecessors, probably will write his memoirs
and oversee construction of a Clinton Library and Museum in
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   But that will not be enough for a man of Clinton's relentless
energy and questing intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   He has said he probably would have sought a third term if the
22nd Amendment did not limit a president to two terms. ``I like the
job,'' he explained rather plaintively.
</P>
<P>
   What he did not add is that the people would probably refuse to
re-elect the president who was impeached by the House for lying
under oath about his relations with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a week of intensive efforts to convince Israel's
Ehud Barak and the Palestinians' Yasser Arafat to enter into a
peace agreement, Clinton left Camp David and jetted across the
Pacific to his final economic summit.
</P>
<P>
   Then after two days of conferring with the other seven leaders,
he again climbed aboard Air Force One 747 and headed back to Camp
David. But before he left, his fellow summiteers toasted him as
``the great leader of the free world.''
</P>
<P>
   That accolade was tantamount to a shot of adrenalin for a weary
president who needed a stimulant to restore his energy and
alertness as he searched for an elusive Middle East peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   Critics will contend that Clinton was simply trying to burnish
his tarnished image and assist Hillary Rodham Clinton's bid to
become a U.S. senator from a state with a heavy Jewish population.
Nevertheless, he waged a desperate but futile struggle to find
common ground between Barak and Arafat before Arafat unilaterally
proclaims a Palestinian state on Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton understands how history judges presidents. He also knows
that a Barak-Arafat accord could provide security and peace for the
embattled Jewish and Palestinian peoples.
</P>
<P>
   Because the hostility between Israel and the Palestinians
reaches back to Israel's creation as a nation in 1948, the
negotiations were, by Clinton's assessment, the most difficult he
has ever participated in.
</P>
<P>
   The issue that deadlocked the Camp David talks was the control
of Jerusalem. While Clinton was unhappy with the outcome, he
recognized from the beginning that it would be almost impossible to
win an accord on the future of the holy city.
</P>
<P>
   The president's next public extravaganza will be a triumphant,
and probably nostalgic, farewell speech to Democrats at their
national convention in Los Angeles. That will be followed by
campaign appearances on behalf of Al Gore and other Democratic
office seekers across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton leaves the White House, he will be 14 years younger
than President George Bush was when his term ended 1993 and 23
years younger than Ronald Reagan when he returned to private life
in 1989. He will be 15 years younger than Bob Dole when he sought
the presidency in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, Clinton is probably the most detested
Democratic president since Harry Truman, who fired one GOP icon,
Gen. Douglas MacArthur, from his command in Korea and opposed the
presidential bid of another, Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   History must judge Clinton's shoddy personal behavior against
his intelligence, the great economic strides made during his tenure
and the influence he has exerted abroad.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet he will remain active up to Jan. 20. He will battle
Congressional Republicans to try to provide seniors with Medicare
payment for prescription drugs and he will spar with his fellow
Democrats as he seeks permanent normal trade relations with China.
He will veto tax cuts approved by Republicans and seek passage of
his own cuts for middle class Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The president will not sneak secretly out the back door of the
White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
