<HEADLINE>
JUDGE OK'S POST-EXECUTION DNA TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PERRY, Ga. _ In what is believed to be the first such order in
US legal history, a judge has authorized DNA testing of evidence
from a death penalty case to determine if the executed man was
indeed guilty, or innocent as he had said.
</P>
<P>
   The order to conduct DNA testing, issued by Judge L. A.
McConnell Jr. of the Houston County Superior Court two weeks ago,
had been sought by The Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   After the order was issued, CBS News and two Georgia newspapers,
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, and The Macon Telegraph, asked
the court for permission to join in the DNA testing. McConnell
granted the motions. The testing, which will be funded by the news
organizations, is expected to take several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis Wayne Felker was executed by the state of Georgia in
November 1996. To his death, he said he was innocent of the rape
and murder of Evelyn Joy Ludlum in December 1981. Ludlum's body was
discovered two weeks after she had been reported missing in a rural
stream near this central Georgia community 90 miles south of
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Ludlum, a 19-year-old waitress, met Felker at the Holiday Inn
where she worked. They talked, and she expressed interest in a job
at the leather-working shop he owned, according to court data.
Felker invited her to his home for a job interview, the reports
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Felker was convicted of binding, raping, and strangling her
before dumping her body in the forest stream.
</P>
<P>
   There was contradictory testimony at Felker's trial, however,
regarding the date and time of Ludlum's death. Witnesses for the
defense and prosecution differed on how long she had been dead when
her body was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Felker's defense lawyers said their client could not have had
the time to kill Ludlum and dispose of her body, because he had
been released from prison for another sexual assault conviction and
so was put under police surveillance as soon as Ludlum was reported
missing.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution and its witnesses, however, convinced the jury
that Felker could have used the few hours before the police learned
Ludlum was missing to commit the murder and to dispose of the
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Felker was found guilty, and was sentenced to death in 1983.
Weeks before he died, his lawyers employed the Georgia Open Records
Act to examine the prosecution files in the case. They found a
police rape evidence kit, scrapings from beneath Ludlum's
fingernails, and the clothing she wore when she was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence, however, was not subjected to DNA testing. And
after he was executed in the Georgia electric chair, Felker's case
became a symbol in the political and legal war now raging over the
death penalty _ one of two dozen cases frequently cited by Amnesty
International and other foes of capital punishment as a possible
case of wrongful execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``A DNA test could very well have proven his innocence,'' said
Michael Mears, the Georgia lawyer who handled Felker's final
appeals. ``We could not physically get our hands on the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne did some bad things, but I don't think this is one of
them,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   As DNA testing has freed dozens of innocent men from prison and
death row in the past few years, a nationwide ``innocence
movement'' has raised the specter of wrongful executions to spur
doubts about capital punishment. Support for the death penalty,
meanwhile, has dropped in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe saw the Felker case as one in which forensic evidence
might be available to test the theory that there have been wrongful
executions. Members of the New York-based Innocence Project, the
Death Penalty Information Center and other criminal justice
organizations said that this would be the first time such testing
has taken place.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, the Globe approached the Houston County district
attorney, Kelly R. Burke, with the request. Though Burke and other
law enforcement officials here say they have no doubts that Felker
was guilty, they were willing to search for and locate the
evidence. Lawyers for the Globe then asked Judge McConnell, under
the terms of the Georgia Open Records Act, to allow the DNA
testing.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe won its order on July 13. Five days later, CBS News
and The Atlanta Journal-Constitution filed motions seeking to
intervene. The Macon Telegraph published an article Wednesday
morning about the news organizations seeking the DNA test, then
joined the case itself later in the day. The afternoon Atlanta
Journal followed the Macon paper Wednesday with its own account of
the testing effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
