<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-SUHARTO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUHARTO ABOUT TO BE CHARGED, INDONESIAN ATTORNEY GENERAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Marzuki on 2nd reference is cq.)  
(No byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia, July 26 _ Former President Suharto will be
charged with corruption in a few days, Attorney General Marzuki
Darusman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Marzuki, who has faced death threats and a bombing at his office
while investigating Suharto, said his staff had finished compiling
a thick dossier of evidence against the former strongman and would
forward it to the state prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully before August all will have been completed,'' he
told reporters today after his staff met to draft the charges.
``Hopefully by the end of this month or early in August the
dossiers would already have been handed over to the court.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, it seemed unthinkable that Suharto, the most
dominant political figure in modern Indonesian history, could be
held accountable for his actions, let alone be hauled before a
court. The former army general, who took office in 1966 and ruled
for 32 years, was widely believed to control the country's
judiciary, as well as other institutions like Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators and critics say that in his three decades in power
Suharto abused his office to amass a fortune while also enriching
his children and business associates. He was forced to resign in
1998, when his government crumbled in the face of Indonesia's worst
economic crisis in decades, social unrest and violent street
protests that sought greater democracy and clean government.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's successor and protege, B.J. Habibie, ordered a
corruption investigation after taking office, but the case was
dropped. Officials said they lacked evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Abdurrahman Wahid, who was catapulted to the presidency in
October after the first open election here, immediately ordered
Marzuki to reopen the case. Wahid has said he will pardon Suharto
if he is found guilty and returns any ill-gotten wealth to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, 79, who has been in frail health since suffering a mild
stroke last year, is a pariah and living under house arrest here.
His political and military supporters are believed to be behind
recent unrest and violence in what may be an attempt to stop the
corruption case from proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's legal team says he has irreversible brain damage and
is unfit to stand trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
