<HEADLINE>
CLIFFHANGER.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Thursday, July 27, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By HENRY ALFORD    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Mr. King is trusting his readers to send him a dollar after
each download. ... If he does not receive payments for at least 75
percent of the downloads, he says, he will stop writing after two
chapters, and readers won't learn the end.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   on Stephen King's plans to
</P>
<P>
   publish a new book online.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   I will continue to write this e-book if ...
</P>
<P>
   ... I can be paid in cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ... I can be assured that no critic will ever again, in
connection with my work, employ the phrase ``amusing regional
miniaturist.''
</P>
<P>
   ... a reality-based television show can be built around my
writing of the book.
</P>
<P>
   ... the editorial assistant at my former publishing house _ the
tall one, with the voice _ will make a series of fawning phone
calls to my home between the hours of 5 p.m. and 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ... the next time I give a reading at a superstore, the
management will rid the environment of spitty cappuccino machines,
couples going through difficult break-ups, and storyteller-clowns.
</P>
<P>
   ... in all previous reviews and criticism of my work, the word
``effective'' will be replaced with ``canonical.''
</P>
<P>
   ... I can be assured that the book's publication will anger one
of my competitors and lead to an exchange of increasingly petty
correspondence in the letters section of a prominent book review,
the publication of a snipey memoir or a lawsuit, preferably in
London during the theater season.
</P>
<P>
   ... my computer can be equipped to create, at my prompting, the
sound of applause.
</P>
<P>
   (Henry Alford is the author of ``Big Kiss: One Actor's Desperate
Attempt to Claw His Way to the Top.'')
</P>
