<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-MIDEAST-BAKER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACE, ONE STEP AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Thursday, July 27, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By JAMES A. BAKER III    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Israeli-Palestinian peace talks ended Tuesday without a
comprehensive settlement, but there were encouraging signs that
both sides moved toward peace on some issues other than Jerusalem.
The challenge now is to see whether the parties can build on this
apparent progress, or whether they will slide back toward
recriminations and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's acceptance of Palestinian sovereignty over Gaza and
most of the West Bank is the perfect example of how far things have
come. Such sovereignty was once a taboo subject for most Israelis
and American policy makers.
</P>
<P>
   But among other issues, East Jerusalem remains outside the grasp
of the negotiators. Prime Minister Ehud Barak and President Yasser
Arafat could not escape domestic political constraints against
compromising historic claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arafat's ability to maneuver is nil,'' a Palestinian official
said over the weekend, referring to how both the Palestinians and
the larger global Muslim community demand a return of East
Jerusalem. Barak showed flexibility in talking about shared
sovereignty, but what was not enough for Arafat was too much for
many Israelis, to whom any agreement will be submitted by
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   There is no point in criticizing leaders for not making a deal
that they could not make, except at the risk of losing the support
of a majority of the people they represent.
</P>
<P>
   What next? Both sides talked _ probably too much _ about the
inevitability of fighting if the negotiations ended without a final
agreement. If this scenario plays out, the progress made at Camp
David will be seriously diminished and hopes for genuine peace, at
least in the near term, will fade.
</P>
<P>
   But if violence can be prevented or controlled, time itself may
provide an answer, just as time provided an answer on Palestinian
statehood. Peacemaking in the Middle East is a process, not an
instantaneous event. Progress is sometimes measured in small steps
_ from the original Camp David in 1978 to the 1991 Madrid
Conference to the 1993 Oslo peace agreement through the present to
the future. Time changes things, and as realities change, minds
change. What was taboo yesterday can become thinkable today and
doable tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of settling an issue so deeply rooted in Muslim
and Jewish faith and identity is not to be minimized. But the long
view is more hopeful than the short view.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton deserves real credit for convening the Camp
David talks and for offering and advocating proposals on how to
settle differences.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ...
</P>
<P>
   The administration has had seven years and six months to push
this process along. The proper function of the Camp David summit
should have been to tie up loose ends. Instead, the leaders, under
tight deadline pressure, considered many important issues directly
and face-to-face for the first time. It should not be surprising
that they could not do years of work in 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, the Geneva meeting last March between Clinton and
President Hafez Assad of Syria ended in failure. Comprehensive
peace in the Middle East cannot be achieved without peace between
Israel and Syria. Arguably, the Israeli-Palestinian issues would
have been more easily settled if Israel and Syria had made peace
first. And the principal issue with Syria _ return of the Golan
Heights _ is much less complicated than most of the final-status
issues between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Though his approach at Camp David was creative and proactive, I
fear that at Geneva, Clinton may simply have presented the Israeli
position to Assad and recommended that he accept it, because it
offered to return practically all of the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   A better approach would have been for the United States to make
its own proposal, recommending the return of all the Golan
conditioned on Assad's then agreeing to the firm security and
access arrangements on the ground that Israel required, including
restrictions on the the Sea of Galilee and on a narrow strip along
the shore.
</P>
<P>
   This compromise should have satisfied both Israeli and Syrian
political needs. Assad could have claimed to have received back
``all'' of the Golan to the June 4, 1967, lines, while Israel would
have received the protection it required for the Galilee, which
provides much of its water.
</P>
<P>
   The administration should prepare Congress and the American
people for the fact that the United States will be asked to help
finance the agreement, if it comes, by providing substantial funds
to move Israeli military bases, establish new borders, resettle
some Israelis from the West Bank and compensate Palestinians for
land taken by Israel. Within reason, we should be prepared to pay
our share of these costs. There will be no peace unless we do, and
both our national interests and our values cry out for that peace.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge now for Israel, the Palestinians and the United
States is to accept the disappointment that the talks ended without
a comprehensive settlement, recognize the progress that was made,
avoid rash actions and keep the process alive so that one day the
descendants of Abraham may live together in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Such a result would answer the Psalmist's prayer for Jerusalem.
``May those who love you be secure. May there be peace within your
walls and security within your citadels.''
</P>
<P>
   (James A. Baker III was secretary of state under President
George Bush.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
</TEXT>
