<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3869 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-BIO-V-ART-4TAKES     07-26 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BIO-V-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LEARNED MUCH FROM HIS FIRST POLITICAL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: BUSH-BIO-V-ABRIDGED will also move tonight. This is another
installment in a series of articles about the lives of the
presidential candidates.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT17 and NYT18 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ George W. Bush was seething with frustration.
Here he was, feeling as Texan as the chaw he liked to tuck under
his lower lip, and he had to smile gamely while the audience
snickered at him as an alien in cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1978, and the 31-year-old Bush was trying to get a start
in politics by running for Congress here in West Texas. A
candidate's forum was under way, and his rival was needling Bush
with an oft-repeated joke in which he was the punchline, a yarn
that reinforced a perception of him as a spoiled rich kid from back
East.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Hance, the Democratic candidate and a smooth-talking good
old boy, was telling a yarn about working in a field along a rural
road. Then along came a fancy car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Mercedes,'' drawled Hance, raising his eyebrows, and
the audience tittered knowingly at the hint that Bush was the kind
of man more comfortable in a Mercedes than a pick-up. ``The guy
rolled down the window and wanted to know how to get to a certain
ranch.''
</P>
<P>
   Hance recounted how he'd given the man directions, telling him
to turn right after a cattle guard, a metal grate ubiquitous in
rural roads to keep livestock from straying. ``Then,'' Hance
continued, ``he said, `what color uniform will that cattle guard be
wearing?'''
</P>
<P>
   The audience roared with laughter, and just to be sure that the
voters got the connection with the Connecticut-born Bush, Hance
said he had noticed something else about the Mercedes: ``It had
Connecticut license plates.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush lost that race for Congress. Yet the story of his entry
into politics, and particularly of that campaign, suggests that it
left a deep imprint on him, one evident today as he campaigns for
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Bush ran an energetic but deeply flawed campaign. He
chose a race that may have been unwinnable, and then muffed up and
let himself be portrayed to many voters as an intelligent,
over-educated phony out of touch with ordinary voters _ ironically,
a bit the way some Bush supporters now look at Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush first entered the congressional race, he was still
single and struggling to start an oil company. He was not obviously
congressional material: He lived in a bachelor's flat, his bed
frame tied together with one of his neckties, and he dressed
exclusively in ratty denim or in clothes that did not match.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to understand what a bad dresser George was,'' said
Joe O'Neill, an friend from those days. ``George didn't dress down,
which intentionally looks bad. He just dressed bad. He dressed in
the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaigned feverishly from morning to night in his white
Oldsmobile Cutlass, usually running late, his volunteers sitting
beside him and struggling to domesticate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chewed tobacco,'' recalled Lisa Nowlin, one of those
volunteers, ``and we always had to carry a spit cup so he could
spit out the tobacco before he saw the Methodist preachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Older people were sometimes put off by what they saw as Bush's
cockiness, but the young volunteers were dazzled by his enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how late the activities of the previous evening, he
was always up early the next morning and working in a way I'd
rarely seen in Lubbock,'' said J. Michael Weiss, whom Bush met
while shaking hands at a shopping mall and turned into a volunteer
county chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Weiss added reflectively, ``Lubbock is maybe not
the high-energy capital of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is often seen today as a late entrant into
politics; he is running for president after holding elective office
for just five years. Yet in another sense, young George has been
engaged in politics in one way or another since his teens and has
considered various runs for office since he was in his 20s.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was first exposed to politics at the age of 17, when his
father ran for the Senate, and later he worked full-time on Senate
campaigns in Florida for Edward J. Gurney and in Alabama for Winton
M. Blount, nicknamed ``Red.'' The lure of these campaigns was not
policy but the adventure of a statewide campaign; a friend recalls
Bush saying that he spent his time in Alabama drinking and dating.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Paul, a girlfriend of Bush's when he was in his mid-20s,
says that Bush was fascinated even then by politics and searching
for a way to run for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very active trying to see how he could get his nose
into politics,'' she said, ``trying to figure out what was going to
be his next move.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, when he was 25, Bush found a spot. A seat in the Texas
state Senate was coming open in Houston the next year, and he
chewed over the idea of running for it with friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``He explored it, he had conversations with the mayor, and he
went to a couple of functions to test the waters and talk to people
about it,'' said Donald B. Ensenat, his roommate in Houston at the
time. ``I assume he decided not to run because he thought he
wouldn't win, because he thought he wasn't ready.''
</P>
<P>
   So Bush went off to Harvard Business School and then started
business in 1975 as an oilman in Midland, the West Texas town where
he had spent his childhood. Just two years later, a terrific
opportunity seemed to tumble into his lap. George Mahon, the local
congressman, announced his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   George W. immediately leaped into the race to succeed him.
Shortly afterward, he resumed an acquaintance with a seventh-grade
classmate, Laura Welch. After a whirlwind courtship, they married
on the first weekend available.
</P>
<P>
   It was a useful marriage. For a candidate like Bush who some saw
as a rootless and immature carpet-bagger, it was helpful
politically to settle down and start a family, particularly with a
local girl who was an authentic West Texan. But the young couple
also seemed absolutely in love as they roared around the district
on the campaign trail, and so there was almost no muttering about
the sheer political convenience of it all.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What drew Bush into politics?
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he rejected the suggestion that he had followed
his father into politics, saying instead that he had been angry at
the Carter administration's policy on natural gas pricing. But in a
1995 conversation with a historian, Herbert S. Parmet, Bush
emphasized the degree to which his own family legacy pushed him
into the political world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a passing on of tradition, passing on legacy, passing
on responsibility,'' Bush said then, according to Parmet's
transcript of the conversation. ``So I don't think it's a conscious
effort. I don't think it's any of this thing where, you know, `by
God, young man, if you play your cards right you, too, may end up
in politics.' It's more of an inherent trait.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush may not have had a decent suit when he announced his
candidacy, but he had other assets _ among them a first-rate name.
``George Bush'' had been a prominent name in Texas ever since his
father had launched his political career in 1964 with an
unsuccessful campaign for the Senate and then winning two terms as
a congressman from Houston. The elder Bush had run for the Senate
unsuccessfully again in 1970, had been mentioned three times as a
possible vice president and had become famous by holding a series
of posts such as ambassador to the United Nations, chairman of the
Republican National Committee and director of the Central
Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush's key backers in the 1978 campaign were his
buddies in Midland, people like Donald L. Evans (now the chairman
of his presidential campaign). In addition, friends of the father
helped out the son or contributed money to him.
</P>
<P>
   Financial reports showed that among the donors were William
Ford, vice chairman of Ford Motor Co.; Donald M. Kendall, chairman
of Pepsico; A.W. Clausen, chairman of Bank of America; Peter
O'Malley, owner of the L.A. Dodgers; and even Mrs. Douglas
MacArthur..
</P>
<P>
   It would have been difficult to imagine Bush, an unknown
31-year-old who had barely held a job, running for Congress in 1978
if it had not been for his name and his family connections. But it
soon became apparent that there was also a downside to this
pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   The other candidate in the Republican primary, Jim Reese, the
courtly and conservative mayor of Odessa, launched attacks on Bush
using themes that still reverberate today. Some of the epithets
associated years later with Ann Richards in her contest with Bush
for the governor's job, such as ``Junior'' or ``Shrub,'' were first
used by Reese back in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to the perception that he was simply playing on his
name and background _ a sensitivity that continues to this day _
Bush asked his father not to campaign for him and downplayed the
connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need Dad in this race,'' Bush told the newspaper in
Midland. ``We don't need anyone in this race but the people of this
district.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the congressional primary became a proxy battle between two
national Republican giants, for Ronald Reagan and the elder George
Bush were dueling in preparation for the 1980 Republican
presidential nomination, and Reagan did not want a Bush family
victory in Texas. As a result, Reagan contributed $3,000 from his
political action committee to Reese's campaign and taped a
television commercial for him. This infuriated the Bush family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in getting into an argument with Reagan,''
the elder Bush told The Washington Post at that time. ``But I am
surprised about what he is doing here, in my state.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are making a real effort to defeat George,'' Bush added
indignantly.
</P>
<P>
   Young George also found himself pummeled by conspiracy-minded
right-wingers.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush was a member of the Trilateral Commission, a
group of prominent internationalists working for cooperation among
the United States, Europe and Japan, and word spread among farmers
that the commission intended to create a world government and was
responsible for depressed crop prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going broke farming, and we were fighting anything
that was keeping us down,'' recalled J.C. Lewis, an Oklahoma farmer
and retired Air Force pilot who flew down to Texas to campaign
against Bush in rural towns like Wolfforth.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald McCathern, a prominent farmer in the area, said: ``We
were always voicing the opinion, `if you support the Trilateral
Commission that your father is in, then farmers can't support you.
And he wouldn't back down. He would say `he's my father and I
support my father.'''
</P>
<P>
   The most common interpretation of the 1978 campaign is that Bush
was a wonderful campaigner and natural-born politician. But this
seems to be a gloss burnished by time and the selective memories of
Bush and his friends, for here in West Texas people say that Bush
was personable and a quick study but still made a series of
mistakes, largely through inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there was the day, early in the campaign, when
there was a candidate forum on a farm near the small town of
Dimmitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is the first time I've been on a real farm,'' Bush
announced, beaming at the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Reese, who was next to speak, began his talk by saying: ``I want
to assure you, this is not the first time I've been on a real
farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the television commercial Bush dreamed up to show
how energetic he was: It showed him jogging on a track. In those
days, joggers were about as common in West Texas as Martians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time folks around here go running,'' Hance, the
Democratic candidate, told audiences, ``is when somebody's chasing
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Angelo, a Midland businessman and prominent Republican
leader in Texas, says that people either have a natural instinct
for politics or they do not. And back then, Angelo did not see it
in the younger Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his campaign in `78, I didn't get the feeling that he had
the knack for it,'' Angelo said. Since then, Angelo has revised his
opinion and now believes Bush has tremendous political instincts.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Bush beat Reese handily in the Republican
primary, with 56 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``George has been underestimated every time,'' Reese reflected
the other day, as he sat on his couch in his home in Odessa. ``I
did it initially. Ann Richards did it in the governor's race. And
Al Gore may be doing that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knew that the winner of the Democratic primary, Hance,
would present tougher competition. A smooth-talking farmboy who had
grown up in the district, Hance was a rising political star who
represented a state senate district that largely overlapped with
the 19th congressional district that they were fighting over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kent Hance was a down-home boy, real homey, and George W.
wasn't homey like Kent,'' recalled Johnnye Davis, a Republican
leader in Odessa. ``He didn't come across to the voters as well as
Kent did, with the little jokes that Kent told.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush now is sometimes mocked for ignorance of policy
details, back then people thought he had the opposite problem: He
had a tendency in his speeches to throw in policy references that
baffled audiences. ``He was quick, a bit too quick, so that people
didn't always get it,'' Mrs. Davis said. ``He was so darn
intelligent that a lot of what he said went over people's heads.
He's learned to explain things a little better since then.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem was that while Bush never really had a clear
campaign strategy, Hance did: he focused his campaign on
emphasizing local ties and on making Bush out as a carpet-bagger
from the East. One of Hance's most effective radio spots was this
one, read by an announcer:
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1961, when Kent Hance graduated from Dimmitt High School in
the 19th congressional district, his opponent George W. Bush was
attending Andover Academy in Massachusetts. In 1965, when Kent
Hance graduated from Texas Tech, his opponent was at Yale
University. And while Kent Hance graduated from University of Texas
Law School, his opponent'' _ the announcer's voice plunged - ``get
this, folks, was attending Harvard. We don't need someone from the
Northeast telling us what our problems are.''
</P>
<P>
   Otice A. Green, a long-time political consultant who has worked
on campaigns since 1956 _ including Hance's in 1978 _ said that
Bush made a ``good entry'' into politics and was an impressive
candidate. But, he added: ``Kent Hance was one of the best I ever
saw.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have helped Bush if Republicans had united around him
and vouched for him as a genuine West Texan. In retrospect several
Republicans think Bush should have tried harder to use Reese's
support in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time I was asked, I told people I was supporting George,''
Reese recalls. ``But I don't remember him asking me to campaign for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent one-third more than Hance in the general election
campaign, but the extra spending played into the Democrats' hands.
Hance denounced Bush for getting 64 percent of his campaign
contributions from outside the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those contributions from the Northeast concern me,'' Hance
declared at one public meeting. ``The Northeast has been in direct
conflict with us on oil and gas and agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush complained that Hance's numbers were wrong. Overall, he
said, only 48 percent of the money came from contributors outside
the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been attacked for where I was born, for who my family
is, and where my money has come from,'' the Midland
Reporter-Telegram quoted Bush as saying. ``I don't think that's
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no particular ideological or policy difference between
Bush and Hance. Indeed, the Midland newspaper reported that the two
men were asked at one joint appearance what difference there was
between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Bush said finally, ``I've got more hair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I did,'' Hance, who was balding, responded wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hance would have made a good Republican,'' Bush told the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Bush would have made a good conservative Republican,''
Hance affirmed.
</P>
<P>
   So in the absence of policy differences, their differing
backgrounds and styles loomed over the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yale and Harvard don't prepare you as well for running for the
19th congressional district as Texas Tech does,'' Hance told
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers continued to ask the candidates about the Trilateral
Commission, and Hance shrewdly replied: ``I don't know anything
about it. But in 1973 when the Trilateral Commission was formed,
what were you getting for corn and wheat? And what are you getting
now?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father was appalled that his membership in the Trilateral
Commission was hurting his son's candidacy. So he wrote to
McCathern, the farm organizer and suggested a meeting to clear the
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote me a four-page handwritten letter asking me to meet
him in Houston any time that was agreeable,'' McCathern recalled.
``He wanted to help his boy any way he could.''
</P>
<P>
   They had a ``very, very affable meeting'' in Houston, and the
upshot was that Bush resigned from the Trilateral Commission a few
days before the election. But if the elder Bush kept his cool over
the issue, the son occasionally lost his.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Turner, a local radio personality and a Republican, said he
was leaning toward Bush but was troubled by the matter of the
Trilateral Commission. So, at a candidate forum at the Branding
Iron restaurant in Odessa, Turner stood up and asked Bush about the
Trilateral Commission and whether his father was working for
one-world government.
</P>
<P>
   ``He jumped like he'd been pricked,'' Turner recalled. Then
after the meeting, Turner stood at the door to say goodbye to the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior Bush comes up, refused to shake my hand, looked me
square in the eye and said, `you...''' using a crude epithet.
``Then Kent Hance came up and said, `Mel, I'll see you up at the
Tech game.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a Republican candidate stepping on the wrong toes,''
Turner said. ``He was an arrogant rich kid, a spoiled brat.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Late in the campaign, disaster struck the Bush forces.
</P>
<P>
   A university student was organizing a ``Bush bash'' to recruit
young people from Texas Tech, and he placed an advertisement in the
student newspaper promising free beer. In fact the event was tame
and ended early, but the Democrats had their ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Five days before the election, a law partner of Hance wrote a
public letter denouncing the Bush campaign for using alcohol to
lure young people. The letter went to 4,000 members of the Church
of Christ in Lubbock, and copies were put under windshield wipers
of cars of people attending church services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kent's opponent, young Mr. Bush, apparently is using tactics
to secure votes which do not indicate the same high character,''
the letter declared. ``Mr. Bush has used some of his vast sums of
money in an attempt, evidently, to persuade young college students
to vote for and support him by offering free alcohol to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The local newspapers wrote about the incident, quoting Hance as
saying: ``Maybe it's a cool thing to do at Harvard or Yale.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush called a news conference in which he fumed: ``His campaign
has been funny. First he attacked my family, then my background,
and now my morals.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Bush found out that Hance owned a building that
was leased to Fat Dawgs, a bar in Lubbock. Some of Bush's friends
urged him to accuse Hance of hypocrisy, but he refused; voters
would reward a candidate who took the high road, he told
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``His weakness was that he wouldn't go for the jugular,'' said
Jane Anne Stinnett, a cotton broker and long-time Republican in
Lubbock. Stinnett said that she was arguing for a tough response to
the beer bash accusations, but ``he just didn't want to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Bush was beaten, 53 percent to 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were glad the race was over,'' Hance said. ``He was really
improving every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bright guy, and he picked up the issues and got better
as time went on. If it'd been two weeks earlier, we would have
beaten him worse. If it'd been two weeks later, it would have been
really close.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Bush had won, it might not have been the best
thing for his career. He would have become part of the Washington
establishment, and he would not have cultivated the
beyond-the-beltway aura that has been his strength since he
re-entered politics by running for governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hance, he ran for Senate in 1984 but lost and ended up as
a Republican lawyer in Austin and a supporter of the Bushes. Hance
recalls that while in Congress, he met another young southern
Democrat, a Tennessean named Al Gore, and grew friendly with him.
After seeing both men in action, he concludes that Bush is a far
more effective campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that Bush is going to be beat him and beat him
soundly,'' Hance said. ``I served with Gore and I know him, and I
like him. But I'd hate to ride from Lubbock to Los Angeles with
him. If you rode from Lubbock to Los Angeles with Bush, it'd be
loads of fun. And Gore'd be saying things like, `I see some
mountains.'''
</P>
<P>
   So what did Bush learn from his first political contest? How did
it change him?
</P>
<P>
   He seems to have learned that a candidate needs to pick his
races, for it may have been impossible for a Republican oilman from
Midland to win in an overwhelmingly Democratic district dominated
by agriculture and the rival city of Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an interesting lesson,'' Bush said in an interview.
``Sometimes there are races you just can't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson, some of Bush's friends say, is the need to
respond forcefully to accusations, like those about the ``Bush
bash.'' The high road may be honorable, he discovered, but it does
not necessarily lead to elective office.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, that first campaign taught Bush, as his old pal
O'Neill puts it, ``don't let your opponent define you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He defined George as a carpet-bagger, and it's nonsense,''
O'Neill mused. ``So that's the lesson George learned, when someone
comes out with something, he's on it like a chicken on a June bug,
because he's not going to let someone else define him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hance's take is that he taught Bush a twofold lesson. First, he
says, he showed Bush the need to cultivate the religious right,
those church-goers whom he had largely ignored during the campaign
and who in the end voted against him on the alcohol issue. And
second, he thinks, he helped teach Bush the need to be more folksy.
</P>
<P>
   As Hance puts it: ``He wasn't going to be out-Christianed or
out-good-old-boyed again. He's going to be the good old boy next
door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
