<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3874 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-JAN-0727-COX     07-26 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAN-0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Widow of Texas Democrat will be among those introducing George
W. Bush
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - On a Thursday night next week when George W.
Bush accepts the Republican Party's nomination for president, the
widow of a prominent Texas Democrat will be among those introducing
him.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Bullock, widow of former Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, said Bush
campaign manager Joe Allbaugh extended the invitation about two
weeks ago. It's a gesture fraught with symbolism _ a nod to Bush's
late friend and mentor that also seeks to make political hay by
underscoring Bush's bipartisan popularity in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For Texans, it may well be the most emotional moment of the
convention; for those in the other 49 states, the larger context
may be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite an honor,'' Jan Bullock said. ``My husband would be
thrilled to death.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there's a good chance Bullock _ who died in June 1999,
not long after leaving office _ would have stood up for Bush
himself. Bush sought Bullock's counsel shortly after winning his
first gubernatorial race, and the two became close friends. Bullock
pushed Bush to run for president and even introduced him as a
future president at the governor's 50th birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   ``From then on, Bob told him, 'You need to do this. You owe it
to the people,' `` Jan Bullock said. ``Getting Gov. Bush elected is
unfinished business for Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   A fierce but pragmatic Democrat, Bullock _ for whom the new
Texas history museum, now under construction, is named _ was
nevertheless not beyond kicking up dust within his own party.
</P>
<P>
   He even backed Bush when the governor was running for
re-election against Democrat Garry Mauro, Bullock's protege.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad she's getting her day in the sun,'' said Mauro,
who's running Al Gore's Texas campaign. ``She's a good friend of
mine and she deserves the national press.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Mauro said Jan Bullock's speaking on behalf of
Bush wouldn't resonate much in the world outside Texas politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know all these guys are trying to come up with symbols, but
aside for a few inside players, who notices?'' Mauro said. ``I
can't remember who introduced John Kennedy or Bill Clinton, can
you? In the long term it has little impact. It's appropriate
considering what we're talking about. It's a nice gesture for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Bullock was Mr. Democrat in Texas,'' said state Sen. David
Sibley, R-Waco. ``If he were still alive, he'd be glad and proud to
have a role in the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Will Davis, a Bullock friend and former Democratic Party
head: ``I'm very pleased, the fact that the governor and Mrs. Bush
would include Jan with them. There's no doubt Gov. Bush and Gov.
Bullock were great friends. Bullock thought the world of Bush, and
Bush felt the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan Bullock said she knew the move might not be universally
popular with Texas Democrats, but said the friendship between Bush
and her husband ``transcended politics to begin with. That's how I
feel. I certainly support Democrats and Republicans alike. So
hopefully I won't get rotten eggs thrown at me. I think all Texans
are very, very proud that they're going to have a president from
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's a certain irony at work here.
</P>
<P>
   As Bullock entered his last campaign for lieutenant governor, he
told Jan her speechifying days were almost over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five thousand speeches later,'' she said, ``here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Patrick Beach at pbeach(at)statesman.com or
445-3603.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
