<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEFONICA-VILLALONGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VILLALONGA QUITS TELEFONICA UNDER PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER AND RICHARD BRAND  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Juan Villalonga, the chairman of the Spanish telephone company
planning to buy Lycos Inc., resigned under pressure Wednesday. But
his company, Telefonica SA, said it would press ahead with what it
called ``strategic operations.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Spanish company wouldn't elaborate on
whether those operations include the planned acquisition of Lycos,
a major Internet portal based in Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But Lycos shares rose 10 percent on expections the departure of
the controversial Villalonga would smooth the way for the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos chief executive Bob Davis said he has been told by
Telefonica executives and board members that its new chief
executive, Cesar Alierta, plans to complete the $12.5 billion deal
announced in May.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also said Villalonga will no longer become chairman of
Terra Lycos, the global Internet content and services company to be
created by the merger of Lycos and Telefonica's Terra Networks
division. Under the original deal, Villalonga was to have been its
chairman and Davis its chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   While Villalonga was the architect of a rapid expansion campaign
for Telefonica, his high pay and flashy lifestyle had alienated
many in Madrid. Lately those included Jose Maria Aznar, Spain's
prime minister, who appointed Villalonga to head the former
telephone monopoly in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga also faced an investigation by regulators into
insider-trading allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga had denied wrongdoing, but many saw his resignation
as an effective concession to political critics. Villalonga's
decision makes the merger plans ``easier on a whole bunch of
fronts,'' Davis said. ``Villalonga, as strong a leader as he was,
had become an overhang. His departure adds certainty to the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed to agree, driving up Lycos shares $6.0625 to
close at $65.75 in Nasdaq trading Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga ``was a controversial figure, and there were concerns
there might be more conflict if he stayed,'' said Deutsche Bank
analyst Andrea Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Shares are still trading far off the projected $97.55 level that
each holder would receive if the merger is completed. Rice cited
concerns that Alierta might not provide enough support to Terra
Lycos, such as access to Telefonica's big wireless systems.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal's prospects seemed brighter overall Wednesday, said
Lycos institutional shareholder Brian Grove, of the Vaughan, Nelson
unit of Boston-based Nvest LP, an investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like everybody's throwing up their hands and saying,
`Wouldn't it be easier if we all just got on down the road with
someone else?' '' Grove said.
</P>
<P>
   Grove said he will likely vote in favor of the merger, which is
now expected to be put to a shareholder vote in September.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, Telefonica didn't discuss the reasons behind
its management change, and a spokesman declined to comment.
Telefonica's new chairman, Alierta, was already a board member and
has been head of Spain's largest tobacco company. Alierta is also a
board member of the Terra Networks division.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica said its board of directors has ``reaffirmed the
company's commitment to carry out all the strategic operations,
which are pending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
