<P>
   WATER (Undated) - Arizona and the other six Colorado River
states have reached a tentative deal on long-term water use that
should give California time to reduce its use of the river and
still protect its thirsty neighbors. The deal, which they will
present to Interior officials in Washington Thursday, depends on
Arizona allowing Nevada and perhaps California to participate in
water banking and will occasionally lower Lake Mead by as much as
75 feet during dry years. It does not address the Mexican delta,
which environmentalists say is suffering as U.S. states suck the
river dry. By SHAUN MCKINNON. Story will move in the ``A''
category.
</P>
<P>
   MORALES (Undated) - The odyssey many face trying to cross the
border from Mexico to the U.S. often is colored by naivete about
how brutal an excursion it can be. Many dismiss the warning about
how hard it is as propaganda, so desperate are they to come to what
they think will be a better life. Using a recent desert death as a
springboard, we travel to Mexico to check out the funeral of the
man and talk to would-be immigrants. On the other side of the
border, we talk to U.S. officials and to people who have made it
and didn't realize how difficult it would be. By THERESA BORDEN.
Story will move in the ``A'' category.
