<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS SLIDE IN WAKE OF WARNINGS ON EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks tumbled Wednesday after several companies
warned that their profits would be lower than expected in the
second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox said that its third-quarter profits would come in below
forecasts and that second-quarter profits were half what they were
a year ago. Shares of Xerox dropped 2 15/16, to 15\.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler, despite an 18 percent jump in second-quarter
profits, said that new-product costs and stiffer competition in
North America would push earnings for the rest of the year below
expectations. Its stock fell 13/16, to 69|.
</P>
<P>
   After the market closed, Amazon.com reported that its
second-quarter loss had more than doubled, compared with last year,
and that its revenue had fallen a little short of market
expectations. Shares of Amazon tumbled in-after hours trading,
falling below 33, before recovering a bit to $33 11/16. Earlier in
the day an analyst from Lehman Brothers lowered her rating on the
stock. On Tuesday, the stock dropped after the announcement that
Amazon's president and chief operating officer had resigned to
become chief executive of VerticalNet Inc., a Web site manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 183.49 points, or 1.7
percent, to 10,516.48. The Dow was led lower by sharp declines in
Hewlett-Packard and J.P. Morgan. The Nasdaq composite index fell
41.85 points, or 1 percent, to 3,987.72, while the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index dropped 22.05 points, or 1.5 percent, to
1,452.42. The Nasdaq was pulled lower by declines in Nextel
Communications, Altera, Intel and Microsoft. The S&AMP;P was pulled
lower by General Electric and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, prices and yields were little changed. The
yield on the Treasury's 10-year note slipped to 6.02 percent, from
6.03 percent Tuesday, as the price, which moves in the opposite
direction, rose 2/32, to 103 15/32. The yield on the 30-year bond
was unchanged at 5.81 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices have been locked in a trading range since April and
it is hard to tell how they will break out of it as long as the
possibility looms that the Federal Reserve will continue to raise
interest rates to slow economic growth and keep inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   The overall earnings outlook for the second quarter is still
positive, with reports coming in better than expected, according to
both IBES International and First Call/Thomson Financial, which
collect analysts' earnings estimates on the companies in the S&AMP;P
500 index. But that is not helping investors at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that two negative messages are coming through to
investors at the same time. One is the possible rise in rates when
Fed policy-makers meet Aug. 22. Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman,
made that clear Tuesday when he told Congress that the August
decision would depend on whether economic data for July confirmed
that the economy was slowing.
</P>
<P>
   The other is that the growth rate of earnings will slow in the
second half of the year, especially if the Fed is successful in
taming economic growth. While a small slowdown in earnings has been
in the forecasts collected by First Call and IBES, investors may
not have focused on it yet.
</P>
<P>
   The report earlier this week that demand for personal computers
was weaker than expected in the second quarter has also weighed
down the technology sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
