<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3884 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WACO-DANFORTH27-COX     07-26 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-DANFORTH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DANFORTH TELLS CONGRESS GOVERNMENT BLAMELESS AT WACO
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a nearly empty hearing room Wednesday, John
Danforth reiterated the major findings of his 10-month, $12 million
investigation into the 1993 raid on the Branch Davidian compound
near Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is absolutely overwhelming,'' Danforth told a
Senate subcommittee. ``The government did not start the fire. The
government did not direct gunfire at the Branch Davidians. The
government did not improperly use the military. And there wasn't
any broad cover-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, a former senator from Missouri, was summoned to
Capitol Hill by Sens. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and Charles Grassley,
R-Iowa, who sit on the Senate subcommittee on administrative
oversight and the courts. They wanted Danforth to detail his
interim report into the controversial raid.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released last week, cleared the government of any
wrongdoing and said that Davidian leader David Koresh and his
followers were responsible for the fire and the death of about 80
people. The report also cleared the government of engaging in a
massive cover-up or improperly using military personnel at Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Branch Davidians started the fire. (They) spread fuel
throughout this complex. The Branch Davidians then began shooting
their own people, including children,'' Danforth told the senators.
``One of the children _ around 3 1/2 to 4 1/2 half years of age we
believe _ was stabbed to death. ... That's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter, who chairs a task force on Waco, has said he wanted to
hear from Danforth before deciding whether to hold more
congressional hearings on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Although three other senators briefly came in and out of the
hearing room, Specter for the most part was sitting alone on the
dais during the polite exchange with his former colleague.
</P>
<P>
   He asked Danforth if the use of pyrotechnic tear gas grenades at
the raid was part of the plan authorized by Attorney General Janet
Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Danforth responded. ``In fact, the attorney general was
quite concerned about the possibility of fire, and she said she
asked for and received assurances that the pyrotechnics would not
be used in the compound.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth said his investigation is 95 percent complete, but that
he is still looking into the question of who knew about the
pyrotechnics and why the information wasn't shared.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the evidence points to ``human mistakes'' and not
any conspiracy. He said, for example, that a young lawyer in the
Justice Department knew about the use of pyrotechnic devices and
failed to tell anyone about it. Aware of her mistake, she covered
it up in fear of losing her job and ruining her career, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth also told the senators that the use of pyrotechnic
devices is ``inconsequential'' and has ``nothing to do with the
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The three pyrotechnic rounds were fired four hours before the
fire broke out. They were fired in a direction away from the
building itself and they caused no damage to anybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Reno appointed Danforth to answer what he called the
``dark questions'' surrounding the Waco raid, including whether
federal agents started the fire that consumed the Davidians or
whether they fired on sect members during the standoff's last
moments.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth said the conclusions of his interim report are based on
more than 2 million pages of documents, interviews with almost 900
witnesses and examination of volumes of physical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The government was also vindicated in a civil trial earlier this
month in Waco, where a five-member jury decided the government was
not responsible for the deaths. The ruling came in a $675 million
wrongful-death suit brought by surviving cult members and the
victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said at Wednesday's hearing that
he hopes the latest investigation into the raid will be the last
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been picking the Waco siege apart for years now. Senator
Danforth's meticulous report should be the coda. Enough is
enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso's e-mail address is eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
