<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-KINA27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A soulful Tina Turner for the '00s
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take Tina Turner. Drop the last name, replace the ``T'' with a
``K'' and subtract a few decades from her age. Now what have you
got? This. Really.
</P>
<P>
   Were the soulful rocker formerly known as Annie Mae Bullock
making her bow this year rather than in 1956 (and were she doing a
better job of choosing material than she did on her recent coaster
``Twenty Four Seven''), it's pretty easy to imagine that she would
sound like Kina.
</P>
<P>
   A former member of Brownstone (``If You Love Me''), just before
that early-1990s R&AMP;B trio went away, Kina returns with a solo debut
of love-me (``Girl From the Gutter''), love-you (``Give and Take'')
and leave-me-alone (``Have a Cry'') songs roared in Tina's husky
twang. At times it becomes a little too easy for a listener to
drift away into the prominent guitars, rendered unable to make out
a hook or her seemingly straight-from-the-journal lyrics. But then,
out of this nowhere, comes Kina imitating a fiery wah-wah guitar,
on ``Hurt So Bad,'' or stabbing away with every line of
crowd-rouser ``U Don't Know.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Kina, we may not ``know you or your situation,'' as you so
snappily snarl on the first release from this album. But we can't
help but feel you. And be moved.
</P>
<P>
   'Kina'
</P>
<P>
   Kina. Dreamworks. 11 tracks. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Kina and DreamWorks Records:
www.4kina.com and www.dreamworksrecords.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
