<P>
   ILLITERACY-UNEMPLOYMENT (Pineville, Ky) _ At a time that
industry is scouring America for workers to keep it and the economy
rolling, children in Kentucky's Appalachian hills as well as many
in urban centers and impoverished stretches of the South are still
dropping out of school at high rates, only to find themselves
unequipped for any but the most menial jobs. Sounding the alarm,
politicians and advocates for the poor have begun putting
entrenched illiteracy at the root of privation in places like
Appalachia and the Mississippi Delta that economic growth has
largely ignored. By Peter T. Kilborn. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,900 words.
