<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3888 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS27-COX     07-26 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Pierre Ruhe, Richard L. Eldredge, Shane Harrison, Phil Kloer,
Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   ``Hahn Plays Barber and Meyer Violin Concertos''
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Hahn, violin, St. Paul Chamber Orchestra, Hugh Wolff,
conductor, Sony Classical.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the opening minute and a half of Hahn's recording of
Samuel Barber's lyrical Violin Concerto and you'll reach for
``replay'' on the CD player. It's a long moment to savor. In that
exposed first theme, as throughout the concerto, she phrases with
an authority and a sincerity that's disarming, tender and extremely
moving. There's bloom in her tone, and never a hint of received
interpretation. Wisely, she's also starting to explore contemporary
music. But Hahn's (or more likely Sony's) choice of Edgar Meyer's
Violin Concerto, written for her in 1999, is thin: a charming and
disposable work of forced Americana, rescued by ample opportunities
for the soloist to shine. In the future, Hahn needs to find gutsier
projects. Yet at 20, she has already moved into the front rank of
active violinists. Where will she be in a couple of decades, in her
prime?
</P>
<P>
   _Pierre Ruhe
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : Read Hilary Hahn's travel journal:
www.hilaryhahn.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Merry Go Round''
</P>
<P>
   Freddy Cole. Telarc Jazz. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell shakes off the
pressures of his job with a liberal dose of Freddy Cole. The
Atlanta jazz pianist and vocalist could teach relaxation technique
to Deepak Chopra. The way Cole's voice gently melds with tenor
saxophonist Eric Alexander's work on the standard ``It's
Impossible'' could calm any road rager on Ga. 400. The song
selection adds to the joys of taking a whirl on ``Merry Go Round''
as well. For the majority of the project, Cole has chosen rarely
recorded standards that fit snugly with his laid-back stylings. For
example, the title track, written by Herb Martin and Bobby Scott,
feels like a song you're well-acquainted with but arrives without
the cliched baggage that yet another rendering of, say, ``My Funny
Valentine'' would have brought.
</P>
<P>
   Freddy Cole opens for Natalie Cole tonight at Chastain Park
Amphitheatre.
</P>
<P>
   _Richard L. Eldredge
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More about Freddy Cole, Telarc:
www.telarc.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Horrorscope''
</P>
<P>
   Eve 6. RCA. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Eve 6 exemplifies ``modern rock'' _ aka alternative. It's slick,
palatable, occasionally engaging, but mostly faceless. Not that it
stops them from selling records. The band's 1998 debut went
platinum and sounded just as personality-challenged. The photogenic
Los Angeles trio fares best when it kicks into high gear, offering
a glimmer of individuality on ``Nocturnal'' and the appropriately
titled ``Amphetamines.'' Sadly, that's all too rare.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More about Eve 6:
</P>
<P>
   www.eve6.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy Ending''
</P>
<P>
   Dogstar. Ultimatum Music. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   If one-third of the rock trio Dogstar didn't happen to be named
Keanu Reeves, these guys would not be getting much attention, and
they're not getting that much as it is. Unlike stars of many other
laughable movie star vanity projects (Bruce Willis' ``The Return of
Bruno'' is still
</P>
<P>
   the ultimate), Reeves keeps a low profile in the band, just
playing bass. Singer-guitarist Bret Domrose is the focus (he has a
little of Reeves' stoner-surfer inflection on some songs, and
sounds like Creed's Scott Stapp on others), while Robert Mailhouse
plays drums.
</P>
<P>
   Their U.S. debut CD (they had a Japanese-only release in 1996)
is standard post-grunge alt-rock, ranging from nicely melodic
(``Enemies,'' ``Stagger'') to yawn-worthy (``Swim'') to
what-were-they-thinking (a cringe-inducing cover of Leon Russell's
``Superstar'').
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is touring with the band this summer, then heads to
Australia to make ``Matrix 2.'' Good career move, dude.
</P>
<P>
   _Phil Kloer
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More about Dogstar, Ultimatum Music:
208.41.140.110/indexnew.htm
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Moment of Glory''
</P>
<P>
   Scorpions with the Berlin Philharmonic. EMI Classics. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the sturm und drang of it: Germany's premiere bombastic
metal act teams up with what until now has been one of the most
conservative orchestras on the planet for a set of musical excess.
Think the Scorpion's 1984 hit ``Rock You Like a Hurricane'' was
overwrought? Wait till you hear the string-swamped update,
``Hurricane 2000.'' Conductor and arranger Christian Kolonovits,
who has worked with the Three Tenors, certainly whips the
philharmonic into a frenzy _ even Wagner never elicited so much
sawing and blowing. Meanwhile, Scorpions vocalist Klaus Meine's
famously thin wail struggles to rise above it all. Yet ``Moment of
Glory'' isn't unlistenable, and at times you'll find yourself
giggling with glee at the Spinal Tap-style heavy-handedness. Only a
sappy rendition of the Diane Warren ballad ``Here in My Heart''
will have you reaching for the off button.
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More about ``Moment of Glory'':
www.emiclassics.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
