<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKNOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Move over King: Rice takes first chapter of `Merrick' online
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've finished reading the first chapter of Stephen King's
online novel, ``The Plant,'' and are looking for something else
scary, click onto www.contentville.com for a first-chapter preview
of Anne Rice's next book, ``Merrick'' (Knopf, $26.95). The book's
second chapter will be posted before the novel is published Oct.
17.
</P>
<P>
   A special boutique at the site also features an interview with
the author about the novel, her writing process and some of the
issues she addresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merrick Mayfair, who is referred to in the book as an
`octoroon,' is not the first character of mixed race that I've
written about,'' Rice says in the interview. ```The Feast of All
Saints,' which was published in 1978, is about the free people of
color, as they were called before the Civil War, or the Creole _
the mixed-blood descendants of the French, the Spanish and the
African.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there are the creatures of the night. The novel
weaves together Rice's two haunting worlds of witches and vampires
when the beautiful Merrick meets David Talbot, a storyteller,
adventurer and ``almost-mortal vampire.''
</P>
<P>
   Other electronic serials and original works are planned, says
Heather Byer, senior editor for Contentville.com. Earlier in July,
the site published ``Widespread Panic,'' a collection of five
fiction and nonfiction pieces by James Ellroy (``L.A.
Confidential'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A King's royalties: Demand for King's first serialized digital
novel fell short of the numbers for his first e-book in March. More
than 400,000 downloaded ``Riding the Bullet'' within the first two
days it appeared. So far, only 41,000 copies of the first chapter
of ``The Plant'' have been downloaded from www.stephenking.com
since Monday. But King's assistant, Marsha DeFilippo, told The New
York Times that the author was ``very pleased'' with the sales.
Readers were asked to pay $1 per chapter using an honor system.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the air: Athens author Terry Kay has gotten the word that
Hallmark Hall of Fame will begin filming his novel, ``The
Runaway,'' on Aug. 16. The location hasn't been announced, but
Campbell Scott, son of the late George C. Scott, will play the key
role of the sheriff, says Kay, whose novel ``To Dance With the
White Dog'' also was a Hallmark project.
</P>
<P>
   The plot for ``The Runaway'' centers on two 12-year-old boys _
one black, one white _ who were born the same hour of the same day.
When the friends set out on a rafting trip, a discovery of a human
bone sparks an investigation that makes the people in the rural
Georgia county examine their feelings about justice and racial
equality. The show is scheduled to air Dec. 10 on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Online: CNN.com will host an online book chat with Anne Rivers
Siddons at 1 p.m. Tuesday at CNN.com/chat. Siddons will discuss her
book ``Nora, Nora'' (HarperCollins, $25). The chat will be open to
online users worldwide, and questions for Siddons will be taken
directly from the chat. A transcript of the chat will be archived
online at CNN.com/chat. In the novel, Siddons explores the life of
Peyton McKenzie, an angst-ridden adolescent who has founded the
Losers Club, where she and two other misfits share their daily
doses of unhappiness. But everything changes when her cousin Nora
shows up for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
