<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3890 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-MAGNOLIA27-COX     07-26 0276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MAGNOLIA27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A day of momentous events
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A mesmerizing tapestry about broken families, love and
forgiveness. Unfolding at fever pitch and studded with small
miracles of acting, writer-director Paul Thomas Anderson's
three-hour epic about a day in the San Fernando Valley is
exhilarating and exhausting. It's the sort of movie you live
through as much as watch.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff is well worth it. Among the stellar acting talents:
Tom Cruise, Jason Robards and Julianne Moore.
</P>
<P>
   One word of caution: According to the e-mail and conversations I
had during its theatrical run, ``Magnolia'' seemed to be the one
movie of 1999 that people either really loved or really, really
hated. That's one thing that makes it great: the power to inspire
strong feelings.
</P>
<P>
   `Magnolia'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more on ``Magnolia'':
www.magnoliamovie.com
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Beach'' (R) _ Sand, surf and a secondhand plot. In his
first film since ``Titanic,'' Leonardo DiCaprio plays a restless
young man who travels with other aimless, privileged young people
to a hidden paradise _ and they mess it up. It's hard to get
attached to characters who care about only one thing: their next
moment of pleasure. The cinematography makes the most of exotic
locations. But all the beauty in the world can't camouflage the
film's gorgeous emptiness. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
