<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SHOWS STRUGGLING DOT-COMS ARE SHEDDING WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN T. SARACEVIC   c.2000 San Francisco Examiner   SAN
FRANCISCO _ Since December, 122 dot-com companies have announced
staff cuts leaving a total of 7,952 workers out of a job, according
to a survey released this week.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And of the 122 dot-coms that announced job cuts, about 20
percent of them have shut their doors for good, according to the
survey released by the New York-based outplacement firm Challenger,
Gray &AMP; Christmas Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dot-com period of survival of the fittest could be
expected to escalate, and so it has,'' said John A. Challenger, the
chief executive of Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   One are that has been less affected by the job reductions is the
business-to-business field, known as B2B, or the direct exchange of
supplies and products between enterprises. ``As an early entry to
the Internet, B-to-B is proving to be better prepared to withstand
major changes in the marketplace than some of the newcomers,''
Challenger said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey divided the Internet industry into five major
sectors:
</P>
<P>
   _ Retail accounted for 24 percent, or 1,812, of the total job
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The service sector trimmed 1,287 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Entertainment cut 948 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Internet portals shed 786 workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The health and fitness sector furloughed 671 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 122 companies reporting job cuts were:
</P>
<P>
   _ BabyCenter.com, an e-commerce site based in San Francisco that
laid off 80 workers in February.
</P>
<P>
   _ Violet.com, a San Francisco boutique, let go all of its
workers (total unknown) before folding in April.
</P>
<P>
   _ San Francisco's HealthShop, a health food store, dismissed 60
workers before selling the company in April.
</P>
<P>
   _ ExciteAtHome, the Redwood City, Calif., portal, fired 15
people in April.
</P>
<P>
   _ Salon.com, the San Francisco Web magazine, layed off 19
people, or 9 percent of its staff, in June.
</P>
<P>
   _ eBay, the San Jose auction site, reduced its staff by 13
people in July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-24-00 1346EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-CAR-TECH0723-COX &LR;      07-26 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CAR-TECH0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    All the rage on the road
 &HT;    By Dann Stupp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Video games, DVD players and even the PC are
moving out of the home and onto the road, which has made owning a
simple CD or cassette player for your set of wheels last century's
news.
</P>
<P>
   Luxuries usually strewn about the family room are becoming
popular gadgets in cars and in roomy SUVs. Ever since Oldsmobile
introduced a videocassette player for its minivans in 1998,
car-stereo enthusiasts have been adding more dazzle to audio
systems with the addition of video. And the automotive world is
jumping on the bandwagon; every major manufacturer now offers video
in the car.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment systems, equipped with everything from video-game
consoles to TV tuners, are not only making the open road more
enjoyable but also more peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   Want to keep the kids occupied on a long road trip? Let them
watch their favorite movies on 5- to 7-inch headrest monitors or on
overhead screens in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of families bring the minivans in,'' says Jason Krimm,
owner of Stereo-In-Dash in Dayton. ``We'll hook up a VCR or DVD
player and a few screens with headphones, and you don't have to
hear Barney singing. All the noise will stay in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   The booming sales of comfy SUVs and the continuing popularity of
spacious minivans have created a growing market for video-enhanced
joy rides.
</P>
<P>
   ``In-car entertainment seems to be the most popular catch phrase
right now,'' says Sean Pate, public relations coordinator for
Pioneer, one of the biggies in the world of car electronics.
``People want to set up their cars like they would their homes with
DVD and video games and surround sound. Sales show that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the price tag for such systems isn't as exciting. Most
systems require some type of controlling head unit for the
dashboard. Add a few screens and a six-disc DVD/CD changer, and
you'll be looking at approximately $5,000 for a Pioneer system.
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic has a similar setup. Head unit ($2,000), DVD player
($1,200), a 7-inch LCD screen ($1,100) and a Dolby processor for
surround sound ($800) will run $5,100.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a display screen in the front seat? Check out
Clarion's motorized head unit equipped with a 6.4-inch LCD screen
($1,100) and audio/video inputs. Tack on another $1,000 for video.
</P>
<P>
   But these high-tech gadgets aren't all about fun. Get some work
done on the go with Clarion's AutoPC, which runs on Microsoft's
Windows CE software. The information superhighway can be accessed
while on the interstate with the mobile minicomputer's wireless
connection. E-mail and even stock quotes are a few clicks away.
</P>
<P>
   Want to groove to trendy MP3 music files? Software should be
available soon for the AutoPC to play your favorite downloads.
</P>
<P>
   But the features don't stop there. The $1,300 voice-activated
system can be outfitted to get navigation directions, check your
gas mileage or to alert you of engine problems. And though sales
are sluggish now, Krimm sees a future for in-car information
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could run a business right out of your car if you wanted
to,'' said Krimm. ``You can get full-blown computers installed in
your trunk with wireless keyboards. But you're going to pay five
times as much for the (mobile) versions. It'll probably get big in
the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   But bombarding a driver with so many distractions does have its
critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``These video systems pose the same threat as using a cellular
phone does,'' says Sergeant Eric Widmyer of the Ohio Highway
Patrol. ``If you're going to include one of these systems, be sure
that all display devices are out of the driver's view. There's too
much happening on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some states ban all display devices within the driver's
view, Ohio has no such law.
</P>
<P>
   Widmyer says that voice-activated systems provide a better
alternative than systems that require fiddling with knobs and
buttons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like with a cell phone,'' he says. ``If you need to
divert your attention, pull over and get off of the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-22-00 1359EDT &QL;
</P>
