<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-INFANTS-HEART-NYT     07-26 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INFANTS-HEART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS LINK SIDS TO HEART DISORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla.)   By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers from Italy have provided the first genetic evidence
linking sudden infant death syndrome to a rare heart disorder
called long-QT syndrome, they are reporting Thursday in The New
England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter J. Schwartz, first author of the report and chairman
of the cardiology department at the University of Pavia, estimated
that the heart problem might account for 25 percent to 30 percent
of sudden infant deaths, and he suggested that many babies could be
saved if all newborns were given electrocardiograms to screen for
the heart disorder. Those found to have it could then be given
preventive treatment, usually drugs called beta blockers.
</P>
<P>
   American experts praised Schwartz's research, but not his
suggestion to screen all newborns. They warned that it would
require testing thousands of healthy infants to save even one life,
and that some infants with ambiguous electrocardiograms would be
given unneeded treatment for the heart disorder. Critics of the
proposal also said there were not enough experts to read
electrocardiograms on the nearly 4 million babies born each year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Julian Hoffman, a pediatric cardiologist at the University
of California at San Francisco, estimated that if all babies were
screened, it would cost $500,000 to save one life.
</P>
<P>
   But Schwartz said, ``If I were a parent, I wouldn't want my son
to die just because we didn't do an electrocardiogram, and I
wouldn't give a damn if we had to screen 1,000 to save my son.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudden infant death syndrome, also called SIDS or crib death,
kills 0.7 in 1,000 babies in the United States, about 2,800 a year.
The babies, seemingly healthy, die unexpectedly in their first
year, usually in their sleep. The cause is not known, but many
cases appear related to breathing problems, and in 1994 doctors
began urging parents to put infants to bed on their backs rather
than on their stomachs, to avoid blocking their airways. In recent
years, deaths from the disorder have fallen by about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said he and his colleagues had been studying another
possible cause of SIDS since the early 1970s, heart-rhythm
abnormalities. The focus of their interest is long-QT syndrome, an
electrical abnormality in the heart that causes a greatly increased
risk of sudden death in children and young people. It is rare,
affecting only about one person in 10,000, and is caused by any one
of several genetic mutations.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the researchers studied 33,034 infants who had
electrocardiograms at birth and were followed for a year. Of 24
babies who died of SIDS, half had long-QT syndrome. Overall,
infants with the heart problem were 41 times as likely to die of
SIDS than those with normal electrocardiograms. But a majority of
babies with long-QT syndrome remained perfectly healthy. No genetic
testing was done.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Schwartz and other researchers did not recommend
routine electrocardiograms for newborns. But they did recommend
them for infants at high risk because of a family history of SIDS
or long-QT syndrome, or a near death from a heart or breathing
problem resembling SIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The paper being published Thursday shows that family history
cannot be trusted to identify high-risk babies. The article
describes one case in which parents found their 44-day-old son
blue, not breathing and with no pulse. He was taken to a hospital
and revived, and he survived without brain damage. His
electrocardiogram showed long-QT syndrome, and genetic testing
revealed a gene defect known to cause the heart problem.
</P>
<P>
   The striking thing about the case, the researchers said, was
that neither parent had the gene defect, which therefore must have
developed in the child as a spontaneous mutation. Theoretically,
such a random mutation could strike anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert J. Myerburg, director of cardiology at the University
of Miami Medical Center, said of Schwartz: ``He has demonstrated
that the long QT can be the basis for SIDS. What percentage of
cases are accounted for by that mechanism is unknown. Schwartz
probably thinks 30 percent. I think lower.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if the percentage were 10 percent, Dr. Myerburg said,
treatment could still save a significant number of babies.
</P>
<P>
   But he agreed that routine screening of all newborns was
impractical. It might become possible, he said, if software could
be developed to help analyze electrocardiograms and single out
abnormal ones needing expert analysis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
