 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Taking security to another level
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Taking the classic ``Panic Button'' concept and giving it
multi-functionality, Dakota Alert's Dial Alert ($170;
www.dakotaalert.com) will automatically dial up to nine
pre-programmed phone or pager numbers and send individual
pre-recorded voice messages to each. Designed to augment other
security devices such as their Wireless Door Contacts ($50 each),
Wireless PIR Sensor (a motion detector, $60) or the Wireless Panic
Button ($60 each), these affordable security devices are ideally
suited to the small business office, retail store or warehouse.
It's one thing to trigger a blaring alarm but quite another to have
a telephone contact-person safely detached from the alarming
situation and able to respond calmly and objectively. The Dial
Alert is AC-powered but also has a battery backup so a power
failure or disruption will not affect operation.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR CABINETS AND BRIEFCASE IN ONE
</P>
<P>
   Personal Data Management. How did we ever manage before the
digital age? Regardless, Sharp offers a nicely priced little
silicon pocket briefcase called the Wizard ($99;
www.sharp-usa.com). Equipped with three megabytes of data storage
and bundled with Sharp's custom Windows-compatible Day-Timer
Organizer 2000 software, the Wizard also offers quick
synchronization to a PC and specific interface with Microsoft
Outlook for importing day timer notes, personal address book
contact information and other pieces of data. Users activate this
feature through a one-time download available free at the MyWizard
Web site. along with other hHandy bits of software and info
including travel, sports, dining and entertainment data also are
available on the site, along withplus customizable databases from a
variety of online sources. With an ``easy-to-read,'' proportional,
two-sized font, a large 40-character-by-eight-line display and a
respectably sized diminutive keyboard for easy data entry, the
Wizard is the quite the convenient digital
briefcase/Rolodex/filing-cabinet.
</P>
