<HEADER>
A3912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-FURNISHINGS-SHOW0727-     07-26 0320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURNISHINGS-SHOW0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prestigious commercial furnishings show relocating here from
Miami
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta has landed a prestigious commercial
furnishings show.
</P>
<P>
   NeoCon South is moving from Miami to Atlanta. The show will be
April 4-5 at the Georgia World Congress Center and there is a
possibility it could settle here.
</P>
<P>
   The show is expected to draw 3,500 to 5,000 people, which is
considered moderate in size by convention bureau officials.
</P>
<P>
   NeoCon South is affiliated with one of the most prestigious
furnishing shows in the industry, the NeoCon World's Trade Fair in
Chicago, which draws more than 60,000 people annually.
</P>
<P>
   The shows attract designers, architects, facility managers and
business executives who are involved in furnishing offices,
restaurants, hotels and other commercial uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a talented and large design community in Atlanta and
it's thriving, so a regional show like NeoCon South seems to be a
good fit,'' said Barbara Copeland, an interior designer at Gensler.
</P>
<P>
   The regional show started two years ago in Miami, but was ``not
drawing the type of attendee we were looking for. There weren't
enough corporate and business users,'' said Melvin R. Schlitt, vice
president of marketing for Chicago-based Merchandise Mart
Properties, the show's producer.
</P>
<P>
   The NeoCon show in Chicago ``is without question the biggest and
most important event to this industry in North America,'' said
Jennifer Busch, editor-in-chief of Contract magazine, a trade
publication. ``Within the last few years the people who own NeoCon
have purchased or started up regional shows in markets throughout
the county.''
</P>
<P>
   Combined with the Chicago show, they ``make up a package of a
strong national show and strong regional shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
