<HEADER>
A3914 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CPT-INDIA-TECH-HNS &LR;      07-26 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INDIA-TECH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN INDIA'S SILICON VALLEY, WORKERS DREAM OF THE USA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (EDS: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATTHEW YI   c.2000 San Francisco Examiner   BANGALORE, India _
It is a familiar scene here: A young software engineer with dreams
of a big salary and a recruiter representing an American technology
company sit across the table from each other, talking about
careers, opportunities and, most importantly, money.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Annual salaries of a few thousand dollars are respectable here
but a pittance when compared to the $50,000 or more American
companies are offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a very poor family, and I want to earn enough
money to support my mother, my three sisters and my brother,'' the
29-year-old man said after his interview. ``It's my life's
ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   His desire reflects that of many young Indians working in
Bangalore, India's version of Silicon Valley _ minus the big
paychecks. With a per-capita annual income of about $1,700 in
India, it is money that lures many young talents away from their
close-knit families and into the tech centers of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Employers are more than happy to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion of the high-tech industry over the past 20 years
led to a desperate scramble for skilled workers. American companies
turned to India, known for a good education system and highly
skilled, English-speaking workers.
</P>
<P>
   Of the estimated 300,000 Indian high-tech workers employed
abroad, about 80 percent work in the United States, said Rafiq
Dossani, an economist from India who works at Stanford University's
International Studies, Asia Pacific Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   India's education system, which focuses on math and science, has
a mission to produce information technology, or IT, professionals
in great numbers. In Bangalore alone, colleges pump out 30,000
engineering graduates every year.
</P>
<P>
   Even with its latte shops, cyber cafes and
hip-by-India-standards reputation, though, Bangalore has a long way
to go to match the amenities of California living.
</P>
<P>
   There are hints of change: The technology industry has brought
new high-rise buildings to this south-central Indian city of 5.2
million people and cars to the growing middle-class, sure signs of
a boom.
</P>
<P>
   In many other ways, though, Bangalore, the capital of the state
of Karnataka, is like the rest of India, with roads shared by
automobiles, three-wheeled auto-rickshaws, cows and pedestrians.
Air pollution is so bad that a walk down the street leaves clothing
smelling like auto exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the old-fashioned American dream is pursued by IT
graduates in Bangalore and other tech-savvy cities here, making
India a magnet for high-tech recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very simple. They have an outstanding education system
there. You're able to get very, very highly qualified engineers and
programmers,'' said Vivek Ranadive, chief executive officer of
Tibco Software Inc. in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Ranadive himself made the journey, partly to escape the rigors
of India's education system.
</P>
<P>
   After a year at the India Institute of Technology in Bombay, he
transferred to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1975
because the courses in India were too difficult. At MIT, he earned
a master's degree in electrical engineering and computer science
and a master's degree in business administration from Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get someone from . . . the India Institute of
Technology, you're getting the cream of the cream of the crop,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After years of producing skilled workers only to have foreign
companies pluck away many of the brightest, there is talk that
India's technology industry has suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I do have concern of there being this heavy brain
drain in the past 10 years or so. If that talent had stayed, the
situation in India would be vastly different,'' said Yogesh Sharma,
editor of Siliconindia, an English-language business and technology
magazine for South Asians.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no sign that the brain drain will end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be happy to send them to the United States. We'll just
produce more people,'' said Vivek Kulkani, information technology
secretary of Karnataka state.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians go to America mainly through a visa program for
skilled workers called H1-B, which allows them to work in the
United States for six years. Immigration and Naturalization Service
officials estimate 40 percent of all such visas go to India each
year. Until 1998, the United States had an annual cap of 65,000
H1-Bs, but Congress increased the number to 115,000 for 1999 and
2000.
</P>
<P>
   In 2001, the number of H1-Bs is scheduled to drop to 107,500.
The cap is set to return to 65,000 in 2002, but industry groups
like the Information Technology Association of America are lobbying
Congress to expand the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every indication is that the demand will grow faster than the
supply side,'' said Harris Miller, president of Information
Technology Association of America in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Although the H1-B program enjoys high levels of support in
Congress, labor unions and many high-tech workers contend the
industry has used the visas to hold down wages and discriminate
against higher-paid American workers. Still others say that layoffs
at struggling dot-com companies should provide a new pool of
workers to meet domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
   Most workers go to the United States on temporary visas, leaving
Indian officials with the expectation they will return one day to
help fuel their own high-tech revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's an increasing trend of people going back to
India,'' Sharma said. ``There's also the liberalization of the
whole economy. There has been a slow elimination of (the
government's) licensing systems, and the old world socialist
economics are transforming into market economies.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend has encouraged more workers to return in recent years,
Dossani said.
</P>
<P>
   India's economic shift started in 1991, when the government
stopped requiring special licenses to start companies, Dossani
said.
</P>
<P>
   Banks were given freedom to approve more loans, and venture
capitalists were encouraged to invest more money, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a major shift from the government-controlled economy, India's
telecommunications industry began encouraging technology
entrepreneurs in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Although the majority of high-tech companies in India are owned
and operated by foreigners, locally owned businesses are on the
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Dewang Mehta, president of India's National Association of
Software and Service Companies in New Dehli, said the growth is
evidence that the brain drain is slowing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bangalore has helped push India's software industry from $164
million in exports in 1991-1992 to $2.5 billion in 1998-1999. About
58 percent of the exports end up in the United States. Next in line
is Europe at 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian government has played a key role in that growth. In
1991, it created a nonprofit agency that helps entrepreneurs and
foreign companies wanting to do business in India.
</P>
<P>
   Through the Software Technology Parks of India, or STPI, the
government provides a wide range of services including a
clearinghouse to start a new company and to promote products made
in India.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian government also allows duty-free import of computer
hardware for companies that want to do business here. Upstart
companies do not have to pay corporate income tax for the first 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   In the south end of Bangalore, the STPI has developed its own
400-acre industrial park, Electronics City.
</P>
<P>
   The property is a mix of mounds of dirt and greenery dotted by
large concrete buildings that house a number of software companies.
</P>
<P>
   In these buildings, young software engineers await their call to
work in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like to have a couple of years of experience here
before going to the USA, but their ultimate goal is to go to
America,'' said A. Jayaprakash, director of Zelos Technologies Pvt.
Ltd. in Madras, about 170 miles east of Bangalore. ``It's the call
of USA that they want to listen to.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-24-00 1340EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
