<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-REALITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, NETWORK HONCHOS: GET REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Remember when we could discuss the male or
female sex without blushing? Now it's ``gender'' this and
``gender'' that because ``sex'' means something else entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Same with ``gay.'' I'm a fairly jovial sort, but if you were to
say I'm a gay fella I'd have a lot of explaining to do to my life
partner, who happens to be of the female gender.
</P>
<P>
   Since language is fluid, it serves little purpose to gripe about
these changes in linguistic fashion. But it is fair to warn
everyone that another perfectly good word is being pirated by those
who have trouble calling a spade a spade.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking ``reality,'' a word now being tossed about to
describe pretty much every type of TV programming that doesn't
involve a written script or a trained actor. This might seem to
encompass an awful lot of what's on TV, but it centers on the stuff
coming to our shores from other civilizations where the invasion of
one's privacy isn't so much abhorred as it is applauded.
</P>
<P>
   Buttressed by the ratings success of ``Survivor'' on CBS,
American programmers are preparing to let loose a dose of
``reality'' not seen since a peeper named Tom got pinched for
sneaking a look at Lady Godiva in the altogether. Nowadays, you can
spend a couple of months on a deserted island with a gay guy who
likes to skip naked along the beach and win a million bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of this type of contrived reality dominated the formal
presentations and the idle chitchat at this year's summer press
tour of TV critics in Pasadena, possibly because the fall slate of
shows _ the ``real'' reason for the press tour _ looks weaker than
Gervase's backstroke on ``Survivor.'' Unlike last summer, when
``The West Wing'' and ``Once and Again'' stood out immediately as
shows to keep an eye on, nothing on the 2000-2001 prime-time
schedule has similar cachet.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, critics haven't seen everything yet. Several series
offered only trailers of coming attractions at the press tour, some
others are recasting and reshooting their pilots, and still others
have nothing to show because they have the luxury of a late start
to the fall season, courtesy of the summer Olympics. But programs
that are late to the party usually don't make a lasting impression.
</P>
<P>
   And so the networks talk about reality at the same time that
they're denying it. Indeed, if game shows are to be lumped into
this genre on the grounds that they involve ``real'' people rather
than actors, then ABC's reliance on ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire'' is the biggest denial of all.
</P>
<P>
   With four of its 22 prime-time hours each week devoted to
``Millionaire'' this fall, ABC is introducing only four new
scripted series and claiming that this demonstrates amazing
stability. My mom would call it laziness, but she's over 50, and we
all know the networks pay no attention to people in such an
unattractive demographic.
</P>
<P>
   They crave youth more desperately than Ponce de Leon at an
explorers' reunion. Even Les Moonves, president of CBS Television,
told critics last week that all the nice things he's been saying
these past few years about older viewers _ the people who tend to
watch CBS _ were not true.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves was joking. But he added: ``We have always said our goal
was to get younger while maintaining our strength in our core
audience. CBS is still the network of `Judging Amy' and `Everybody
Loves Raymond' and `Touched by an Angel' and `JAG' and `60
Minutes,' and we will continue to serve these audiences in all our
programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Grecian Formula approach. If Moonves can pull it
off, be assured that every programmer in the solar system will
follow his lead. ABC already has two ``reality'' shows in the
works, NBC has one and Fox checks in next Wednesday with ``American
High,'' another unscripted view of life, this time featuring real
students in a real high school in a real suburb of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Even The WB, which has stuck to traditional programming on its
way to capturing the hearts and minds of young female viewers, is
working on an American version of ``Popstars,'' an Australian TV
phenomenon not unlike ABC's ``Making the Band,'' in which viewers
get to witness the creation of a pop-music group, all-female in The
WB's case, from initial casting across the country to filming of a
video and release of an album. This, in spite of Jamie Kellner's
disdain for the me-too approach.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner, chief executive officer of The WB, says he has
witnessed copycat programming for 30 years. ``It's always the same
thing,'' he said. ``One thing happens, it gets big, and then you
see the me-toos, and all of a sudden there are a lot of me-toos.
And then for some reason the whole thing seems to burn out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellner doesn't seem to see any conflict in decrying the
industry's lack of originality while hedging his bets with a little
``reality'' programming of his own. Nor does Dick Wolf, producer of
``Law &AMP; Order'' and one of NBC's new fall shows, ``Deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to burst bubbles,'' Wolf said, ``but I think they're
going to run out of deserted islands. ... The one thing I've seen
time and time again is that unless you're first (with an idea),
there's no sense in doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Wolf is the brains behind a new syndicated show,
``Arrest &AMP; Trial,'' which will follow real cases from apprehension
to deposition, the way ``Law &AMP; Order'' does on the fictional side.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, quality prevails. We've seen it already with failed
clones of ``Millionaire.'' And even if you don't like the premise
of ``Survivor,'' it is well conceived and smartly produced, which
has much to do with its wide appeal. On the other hand, CBS's
second entry in the reality sweeps, ``Big Brother,'' is
monumentally boring and poorly made on purpose, as if to lend a
rugged familiarity to its brand of realism.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this whole ``reality'' thing may be an attempt to
have us forget last season's big story: the lack of racial
diversity in prime-time casting. Could it be that the networks
cooked up this reality craze as a cheesy diversion? Think about it.
It even allows them to get people of color on their schedules
without changing Hollywood's myopic casting traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Fiendishly clever of them. And, sadly, much closer to the
conventional definition of reality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
