<HEADER>
A3928 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-WOMEN-COMPUTERS-N     07-26 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WOMEN-COMPUTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER STUDENTS' RANKS GROW, BUT WITH FEWER WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study predicts that while undergraduate enrollments in
computer science will increase rapidly, the proportion of women in
that enrollment is unlikely to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are going to be left behind,'' said Dr. Tracy Camp, a
professor at the Colorado School of Mines who is co-chairwoman of
the Association for Computing Machinery's Committee on Women in
Computing, which has done several studies analyzing the proportion
of women studying computer science. Camp is the lead author of the
study.
</P>
<P>
   The new research found that women account for about 17 percent
of the undergraduate computer science majors at U.S. universities
that offer Ph.D.s in computer science. The study predicts a nominal
increase in this percentage, to about 17.5 percent for the
2000-2001 school year, followed by a drop to between 16 and 16.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly more students than in the past,'' Camp
said. ``The raw numbers are increasing. But the percentage of women
is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1983 and 1996, the percentage of women earning
bachelor's degrees at universities and colleges in computer science
dropped from a high of 37.1 percent to a low of 27.5 percent, a
25.9 percent decrease. ``Our study confirms that this trend will
continue,'' Camp said. ``There is no evidence that these low
percentages will rise.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest U.S. Department of Education figures for enrollments
of women in computer science are for 1996. ``We did the study
because the U.S. Department of Education is so far behind,'' Camp
said. ``Computer science enrollments have changed so rapidly that
we felt we needed to find out what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The percentages of women majoring in other sciences, including
engineering, biological sciences, physics and math, have risen from
the 1980s to 1996. ``It's not a huge increase, but it's there,''
Camp said. ``But in computer science, the percentage is stagnant.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, titled ``The Incredible Shrinking Pipeline Unlikely
to Reverse,'' was supported by the Association for Computing
Machinery and the National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Gurer, co-chairwoman of the association's Committee on
Women in Computing and a technologist at the 3Com Corp. in Santa
Clara, Calif., said that there was a substantial attrition rate for
women as they moved through the computer science career pipeline,
from college to work. ``It starts early,'' she said. ``Women get
turned off not only in college, but once they are at work.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons women leave computer science are complex, but one
cause is clear, Gurer said. ``The image of the white, male,
antisocial nerd who sits in front of a computer turns women off,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
