<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3929 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-0727-     07-26 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFTER CAMP DAVID: FOR ISRAELIS, PALESTINIANS, WORK FOR PEACE IS
JUST BEGINNING
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-0727.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the dust settled Wednesday from the collapse of
the Mideast summit at Camp David, President Clinton made clear that
the curtain hasn't yet fallen on his long-running quest to broker a
peace accord for the troubled region.
</P>
<P>
   The next act in the drama, he said, is for Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak to move quickly
to build a consensus for compromise among the people they
represent.
</P>
<P>
   With both sides set to resume working-level talks as early as
next week, Clinton said he remained hopeful that Arafat and Barak
could reach a final peace accord before their self-imposed Sept. 13
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be able to do it,'' Clinton told reporters at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Just when and how he might reinvigorate formal negotiations,
though, Clinton couldn't say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't yet tell what would be most in aid of the process,''
Clinton said. ``I just can't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, U.S. diplomats were already in motion,
contacting governments across the Arab and Muslim worlds, as well
as Europe, to try to build a united global front backing the
U.S.-led peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to dispatch a senior envoy to the region
over the next two or three weeks to consult with leaders there and
assess the prospects for renewed talks.
</P>
<P>
   The job of selling a potential peace accord _ and the painful
compromises that would entail _ to the region, however, is one the
White House is leaving to Arafat and Barak.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. attempts to sway public opinion not only wouldn't work,
administration officials assert, they'd likely backfire, with
Palestinians and Israelis alike regarding such efforts as
heavy-handed superpower meddling.
</P>
<P>
   The message Clinton and his diplomats hope to get out, though,
is that the Camp David talks dramatically advanced the prospects
for a comprehensive peace accord between Israelis and Palestinians,
who, for the first time ever, sat down and seriously locked horns
over the sensitive issues at the core of their dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are way beyond where they have been on this issue,'' said
the State Department's Aaron Miller, deputy Middle East coordinator
for Arab-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question now is for them to determine what happened at
Camp David and, perhaps just as important, did not happen, and to
see how the political and public elite digest what happened,''
Miller told a small group of reporters. ``What is required is a
sustainable domestic base to support leaders' decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ``You've got to get used to talking about
something for a little bit before you can then entertain how you
can create an edifice that you hadn't previously imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also wants U.S. partners abroad to discourage Arafat
from going through with his threat to declare a Palestinian state
Sept. 13 _ with or without a Palestinian-Israeli peace accord.
That, Clinton fears, could trigger violence.
</P>
<P>
   And he wants the Arab world to soften its opposition to
Palestinian concessions on the question of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The Camp David summit fell apart on Tuesday after two weeks of
talks centered on the thorny web of security and territorial issues
at the heart of 52 years of Israeli-Palestinian conflict. Both
sides were willing to deal on prickly matters like the fate of
Jewish settlers and Palestinian refugees. Gains were made also in
the area of security.
</P>
<P>
   The straw that broke the summit's back, though, was the question
of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis and Palestinians both claim the holy city as their
capital. Barak offered Arafat limited sovereignty over parts of
East Jerusalem, which Israeli troops seized during the 1967
Israeli-Arab war. Arafat, though, stuck by his long-held demand
that all of East Jerusalem be placed under Arab control.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat showed little flexibility on the issue during the summit,
and U.S. diplomats became convinced that he could move no further
without the support of the larger Arab and Muslim worlds _
including countries like Egypt, Jordan and even Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The summit, though, was not Clinton's last card.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't think the embers are out of the fire,'' said noted
Arabist Michael Hudson, of Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson suggested that Clinton look to an outside mediator _ he
mentioned former President Jimmy Carter and former U.S. Senator
George Mitchell as possibilities _ to try to help gin up support
for continuing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were to send Jimmy Carter, if he were to send George
Mitchell, an important political person with some diplomatic skill
back in, the summit might yet be salvaged,'' said Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who brokered the historic Egyptian-Israeli peace treaty
at Camp David in 1978,
</P>
<P>
   has particularly broad cache within the Arab world. The Clinton
administration has yet to reach out _ at least publicly _ on this
issue to Carter, who was en route to Venezuela this week and
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of offer hasn't been made, and I can't speculate on
what his reaction to it would be,'' said Carter spokeswoman Carrie
Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   Carter has played important roles as citizen-statesman in trying
to broker a cease-fire between Bosnians and Serbs, in breaking a
dangerous U.S.-North Korea impasse over Pyongyang's suspected
nuclear weapons program and in averting a U.S. military invasion of
Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
