<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3932 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BOSCOLL-DEAN-BOS &LR;      07-26 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSCOLL-DEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC TO NAME HELEN PETERS MANAGEMENT SCHOOL DEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHRYN TONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston College's Carroll School of Management is
expected Thursday to announce the appointment of Dr. Helen Frame
Peters as dean, making her the third female dean of a top-50
business school in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The other two female deans are Carolyn Woo, at the University of
Notre Dame and Laura D'Andrea Tyson at the University of California
at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The Carroll School has been searching for a dean since last
August when its former dean, Jack Neuhauser, was promoted to
academic vice president of the school. Robert Taggart, a professor
of finance at the business school, acted as interim dean during the
academic year.
</P>
<P>
   Before her appointment, Peters was a managing director of the
Global Bond Group of Scudder Kemper Investments in Boston, where
she managed a $150 billion bond group with 300 employees worldwide.
She has also served as chief information officer of Colonial
Management Associates, where she oversaw $17 billion in mutual fund
investments.
</P>
<P>
   As the first woman to receive a Ph.D. in finance from The
Wharton School at the University of Pennsylvania, Peters is used to
working in male-dominated situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been at an environment where there hasn't been
that many women,'' she said. ``I will continue on and do great
things so that women can go into many areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Santomero, one of Peters' former finance professors at
Wharton, remembers her to be someone who ``has never been viewed as
someone who was in the finance program as a female.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just evidence of good people rising to the top. She
just happens to be female,'' said Santomero, who is currently
president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, the first female dean at the Haas School of Business at
the UC Berkeley, who was also former chief economic adviser to
President Clinton, says that gender is not a big consideration
during the selection of a dean.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture of an institution matters. Here, the culture was
conducive to the selection of a female dean,'' Tyson said. ``Some
institutions would have cultures not conducive to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many faculty members of the Carroll School were enthusiastic
about Peters' appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``With her experience in the business community, I think that
she will be able to help move the school forward,'' said Taggart,
professor of finance who also acted as interim dean at the business
school.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major issues that business schools face in choosing a
dean is whether to find someone with a purely academic background
or with private-sector experience. In the Carroll School's final
candidate pool of eight people, four were non-academics, said Dr.
G. Peter Wilson, Joseph Sweeney chair of accounting and the
chairman of the dean search committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is riskier to bring in a non-academic, but the upside could
be very large,`` he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson pointed to top business schools like Wharton, Stanford,
and Northwestern, all of which successfully appointed deans from
the private sector in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best years at those schools had a non-academic at the
helm,`` he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Peters was one of the rocket scientists in the early
1980s who went from academia to Wall Street, she has continually
remained active with her alma mater as a member of the Trustees'
Council of Penn Women.
</P>
<P>
   Peters has always bucked the trend. When she first went into
Wall Street, her colleagues told her that ``it was not the place to
for academics to go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now everyone is going into Wall Street and I think that it is
a great time to be in education,'' said Peters.
</P>
<P>
   She says that she plans on strengthening the Carroll School's
ties with the business community and ``making sure that the school
is responding to changes in the business world,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Peters has two children, a 24-year-old son and a 16-year-old
daughter. Her husband, Judson Garrett Parker, is chief financial
officer at Risk Management Foundation of the Harvard Medical
Institutions Inc. in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2021EDT &QL; 
