<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PLATFORM0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Party eases stand on education policy
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The draft Republican platform that will be made
public today maintains the party's call for a no-exceptions ban on
abortion, while softening past GOP opposition to a federal role in
education.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues are expected to draw the most debate over the next
few days, but Republican officials are hoping that softer rhetoric
in the platform will help avoid a divisive fight and set the tone
for a convention free of harsh words and controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The platform is another demonstration that the Philadelphia
convention is firmly under the control of Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, the party's nominee-in-waiting. He has called for a positive
gathering to highlight his campaign theme of ``compassionate
conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   The 107-member platform committee will hold hearings on the
document Friday and Saturday, and is expected to adopt it Saturday.
Convention delegates will vote on the document next week, and while
a floor challenge to the platform is possible, it is considered
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sue Myrick (R-N.C.), a co-chair of the committee, said the
uplifting, progressive message is an improvement over the 1996
platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not bashing. In 1996, the platform, at least in my
opinion, had a kind of angry, bashing tone to it,'' Myrick said.
``We've spent a tremendous amount of time behind the scenes meeting
with people who have differing opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those people acknowledge that the tone is better, but
fear that the substance is out of step with the majority of the
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   On abortion, for example, the platform takes a harder line than
does Bush, who favors allowing abortion in the case of rape and
incest.
</P>
<P>
   The insistence on retaining the call for an absolute ban on
abortion will hurt Republicans in the fall, said Susan Cullman,
chairman of the Republican Pro-Choice Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the platform bogs us down,'' Cullman said. ``I think
it's a disaster for the party. You've got the vice presidential
nominee (who opposes abortion rights), why keep this in the
platform?''
</P>
<P>
   Republican abortion-rights supporters would prefer silence on
the issue, or a statement that acknowledges other opinions.
</P>
<P>
   But platform officials have made it clear that no change is
likely, on orders from the Bush camp, Cullman said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Bush's choice of former Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney as his running mate may make delegates who favor access
to abortion more willing to speak up, Cullman said. Cheney opposes
abortions in almost all circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative leaders, delighted with the selection of Cheney,
said they expect the platform to be generally acceptable and for
Bush's lieutenants to keep firm control of the process, meaning
squabbling will be kept to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Areas of concern to conservatives are most likely to be in
foreign affairs, education and other social issues, including gay
rights.
</P>
<P>
   But Don Devine, vice chairman of the American Conservative
Union, said that even if the platform no longer calls for
elimination of the Department of Education, conservatives probably
could live with language that touts local control of schools and a
limited federal role in education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect any major battles at the end of the day,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
