<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3945 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH-GADFLY-BOS &LR;      07-26 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-GADFLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONE VOICE CRYING IN THE HIGH-TECH WILDERNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM   c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Mass. _ Every group needs a gadfly. For the Silicon
Valley crowd, it's Clifford Stoll, a self-proclaimed propellerhead
who thinks the Internet is a vast sinkhole for time better spent
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   To Stoll, computers are little better than television, and they
certainly don't belong in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent book, ``High Tech Heretic,'' Stoll writes
that computers ``dull questioning minds with graphical games where
quick answers take the place of understanding.'' In his book, Stoll
skewers calculators, laptops, desktops, and cell phones as gizmos
that do nothing to provoke critical thinking. Instead, they swallow
up time and waste money that should be spent on books and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   To his critics, of which there are many in the Valley, Stoll is
a Luddite, an extremist whose philosophy is as outdated as last
year's calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``His book should have been titled, `High Tech Lunatic,' '' said
John C. Dvorak, a well-known technology pundit and writer in the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other critics of technology, Stoll is no technophobe.
After getting his doctorate in planetary science, Stoll worked for
various astronomy labs, including the Lawrence Berkeley Lab at the
University of California. There Stoll became famous in 1989 for
catching a German hacker who had been selling computer secrets to
Russia in exchange for cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   His career as computer contrarian didn't begin until 1995, when
he published ``Silicon Snake Oil: Second Thoughts on the
Information Highway,'' an unsparing attack on the burgeoning cult
surrounding the Internet. It was selected by Business Week magazine
in 1995 as among the best business books of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll, now 50, agreed to an interview last week in his Oakland
home. The first thing one notices upon entering Stoll's house,
besides a cluster of manual typewriters sitting on the floor of the
entryway, is that there are no televisions, computers, video
cassettes, or Game Boys. The most modern item in the house is a
tiny boom box in the kitchen, which belongs to Stoll's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not because of a dislike for technology, but out of a
love of technology that I wrote those books,'' said Stoll, whose
unruly head of hair gives him the look of a mad yet harmless
scientist. ``As tickled as I am by gizmos, I worry that the field
is being mired by hype. It's not computers that bother me; it's the
cult of computers that gives me the heebie-jeebies.''
</P>
<P>
   The gadgets in the Stoll household are banished to a cluttered
cottage behind the house. There, Stoll keeps two Macintoshes, along
with a collection of old mechanical calculators that he is
currently fixing as a hobby.
</P>
<P>
   He also hand-blows Klein bottles, oddly shaped flasks that
theoretically exist only in the fourth dimension because their
inside is also their outside. He advertises the bottles on a Web
site and receives an order every day or two from curious
mathematicians. ``It's fun,'' Stoll said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he likes about technology, Stoll scampers off to a
closet and, after much rummaging, emerges _ beaming like a child _
with a white cardboard box. It contains a device he built several
years ago out of two coffee cans and a handful of electrical
components that he used to measure the speed of cars on his street.
He found that 85 percent of the cars were speeding. Armed with that
data, Stoll and his neighbors petitioned the city to install speed
bumps. ``I want technology to be used to make our cities and
neighborhoods better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Stoll is a full-time father, having quit academic
research years ago. He's living off the royalties of his first two
books. (``High Tech Heretic'' is his third.) His two children
attend a school where parents agree not to have televisions in
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll, who has been in the Bay Area for over 15 years, bemoans
the changes he has seen in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chase after dot-com riches has warped the feeling of
closeness that all of us are seeking here,'' said Stoll. His
solution? ``We are seriously considering moving to Vermont.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can
be reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-25-00 1129EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
