<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3946 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH-WEB-MALLS-BO     07-26 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-WEB-MALLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALLS STAKING THEIR CLAIM ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (Eds.: Checker Flag Lightning is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON   c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet opened up a new and vibrant channel for purchasing
toys, books, and other merchandise. But for the most part,
customers still waited a few days for packages to hit their
doorsteps.
</P>
<P>
   Now, imagine ordering online from stores in your local mall, and
instantly gratifying your desire for the latest Lauryn Hill CD or
Harry Potter book. You could request same-day delivery or grab
packages at the mall drive-through. Or, you could pick up your
filled bags from a mall booth while taking the kids to see Santa.
</P>
<P>
   Those days may not be far away. After years of dismissing or
downplaying the electronic marketplace, the nation's malls are
trying to stake their claims on the Web by leveraging long-standing
relationships with thousands of retailers. Their push online will
put them in direct competition with Internet portals like Yahoo and
Lycos _ which have invested heavily in their shopping meccas.
</P>
<P>
   General Growth Properties Inc., the nation's second-largest mall
owner, is now building online versions of its shopping centers,
selling software tools and Internet space to both mom-and-pop
stores and retail chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is core business for us,'' said Charlie Graves, senior
vice president of e-business for the Chicago-based real estate
investment trust. ``We already have business relationships with
15,000 retailers, so we're already committed to helping them
improve their sales. . . . Now, we're giving our retailers a new
tool set to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first shopping centers to leap online will be Natick
(Mass.) Mall, which will start opening Net stores this fall.
General Growth has set up Web addresses, such as Natickmall.com,
for all its 136 shopping centers. Customers can access General
Growth Properties at a central site called Mallibu.com.
</P>
<P>
   General Growth wants to give its merchants templated software
tools and broadband Internet connections to help them set up their
virtual stores. At each online mall, customers will be able to pay
for all purchases in a single credit-card transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The program is clearly in its infancy. Right now, customers can
use the Natick Mall's Web site to get information on mall stores,
operating hours, directions, and the spring arrival of the Easter
Bunny.
</P>
<P>
   Even these rudimentary e-offerings need more attention. For
example, the directions link at Natickmall.com did not work last
week. And the stuffed hare has long since scurried back to his
hutch, though the site is still promoting his visit.
</P>
<P>
   Only one General Growth property is up and run-
</P>
<P>
   ning. RiverTown Crossings near Grand Rapids, Mich., introduced
the service in June along with a drive-through window. Next month,
General Growth will debut an e-commerce site for Stonebriar Center
in Dallas. Northridge Fashion Center in California and North Point
Mall in Alpharetta, Ga., follow later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, CheckerFlag Lightning, which carries NASCAR clothing and
collectibles, is the only merchant inside RiverTown Crossings
that's actually selling through the Web site. It offers just three
products, including a Dale Earnhardt Monopoly game and a Jeff
Gordon inflatable car.
</P>
<P>
   General Growth also must figure out a way to integrate its
online malls with existing e-commerce sites operated by Macy's,
Gap, and other national retail chains. Until then, big retailers
like J.C. Penney will only provide links to their online stores.
</P>
<P>
   Still, General Growth's new focus on Net sales represents a
marked departure from its position just two years ago. Back then,
mall owners and retail brokers regarded the growth in e-commerce
with suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took this job a little over a year ago, and I think I got
the job more out of a defensive position,'' Graves said. ``Before,
I think the attitude was `Oh my God, what are we going to do about
the Internet?' Now it's, `What are we going to do with the
Internet?' ''
</P>
<P>
   During last year's holiday season, Saint Louis Galleria, a
suburban mall in Richmond Heights, Mo., took the extra step of
barring tenants from promoting their Web sites on shopping bags,
storefronts, or anything on the mall property.
</P>
<P>
   The unpopular ban was dropped after it proved largely
ineffective. Many of the mall's 170 stores griped about the rules,
one merchant threatened to sue, and others blatantly ignored the
Galleria's management.
</P>
<P>
   After Christmas, mall owners also realized that the e-commerce
threat had not materialized. Sales at mall stores rose a robust 7.7
percent during the holiday selling season, according to the
International Council of Shopping Centers.
</P>
<P>
   General Growth's change in attitude has occurred against a
backdrop of consolidation in the retail industry. Under pressure to
deliver fresh and entertaining concepts, mall owners are
introducing stores such as teen e-tailer Delias.com and J. Jill _ a
catalog and online merchant _ into traditional centers like Natick
Mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business has changed tremendously in the last four
years,'' Graves said. ``Of our top-performing retail concepts,
probably eight out of 10 are new.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts note that even giants like General Growth and Simon
Property Group Inc., the nation's largest mall owner, have been
slow to migrate to the Web. And today, they say, the mall owners
continue to lag online counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think General Growth has a bigger learning curve,'' said
Malachy Kavanagh, a spokesman for the International Council of
Shopping Centers. ``There's not a lot on (Mallibu.com), but they're
working on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Mallibu.com, Simon Property's Web site, Shopsimon.com,
provides a large number of links to well-known retailers such as
Best Buy, Nordstrom, Gap, and Victoria's Secret.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, however, this is ancient stuff. Online portals
like AOL, Yahoo, and Lycos introduced their shopping areas years
ago. And they now offer sophisticated search tools that allow
customers to simultaneously sift through thousands of stores for a
single item.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a search for cufflinks at Yahoo yields more than
940 items, including silver terrier cufflinks for $11.10 and
sapphire cufflinks for $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Today, almost anyone can be a shopping mall. In a sense,
Amazon.com Inc. is the Web's biggest mall, offering books, toys,
CDs, antiques, refrigerators, and much, much more. EBay is the
Net's biggest flea market. Then there are a host of sites like
fashionmall.com, campmall.com, and jewelrymall.com trying to carve
out niches.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, everyone is a mall on the Web _ except the
bricks-and-mortar malls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the best General Growth and other mall developers can
hope for is that they're able to deepen the relationships that they
already have with consumers,'' said Ken Cassar, an analyst with
Jupiter Communications, an Internet research firm. ``I don't
believe that sites like Mallibu will ever become significant
destination points.''
</P>
<P>
   Where General Growth seems to be having some success is with
smaller retailers that want to promote their businesses without
spending millions of dollars on e-commerce sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows about the London Harness name in this area,''
said Sandra Macaluso, manager of the London Harness Company leather
store in Natick Mall. ``This would give us exposure across the
country, if not internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Monsoon Accessories, a British retail chain that opened its
first and only US store in Natick Mall, also is interested in
Mallibu.com. The company operates a Web site in the United Kingdom.
Due to customs complications, however, US Web shoppers can look but
can't buy, said manager Heather Ahlburn.
</P>
<P>
   Mallibu.com, she said, would give her a place to steer US
customers and a way to grow her revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, (Mallibu.com) is the perfect solution,'' Ahlburn said.
``For me, it would mean a massive increase in business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-25-00 1132EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
