<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3948 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-BIO-V-ABRIDGED-A     07-26 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BIO-V-ABRIDGED-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LEARNED MUCH FROM HIS FIRST POLITICAL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: A longer version is also moving. This is another installment
in a series of articles about the lives of the presidential
candidates.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT17 and NYT18 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ George W. Bush was seething with frustration.
Here he was, feeling as Texan as the chaw he liked to tuck under
his lower lip, and he had to smile gamely while the audience
snickered at him as an alien in cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1978, and the 31-year-old Bush was trying to get a start
in politics by running for Congress here in West Texas. A
candidate's forum was under way, and his rival was needling Bush
with an oft-repeated joke in which he was the punchline, a yarn
that reinforced a perception of him as a spoiled rich kid from back
East.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Hance, the Democratic candidate and a smooth-talking good
old boy, was telling a yarn about a fancy car coming down a rural
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Mercedes,'' drawled Hance, as the audience tittered
knowingly at the hint that Bush was the kind of man more
comfortable in a Mercedes than a pick-up. ``The guy rolled down the
window and wanted to know how to get to a certain ranch.''
</P>
<P>
   Hance recounted how he had given the man directions, telling him
to turn right after a cattle guard, a metal grate ubiquitous in
rural roads to keep livestock from straying. ``Then,'' Hance
continued, ``he said, `what color uniform will that cattle guard be
wearing?'''
</P>
<P>
   The audience roared with laughter, and just to be sure that the
voters got the connection with the Connecticut-born Bush, Hance
said he had noticed something else about the Mercedes: ``It had
Connecticut license plates.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush lost that race for Congress. Yet the story of his entry
into politics, and particularly of that campaign, suggests that it
left a deep imprint on him, one evident today as he campaigns for
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Bush ran an energetic but deeply flawed campaign. He
chose a race that may have been unwinnable, and then muffed up and
let himself be portrayed to many voters as an intelligent,
over-educated phony out of touch with ordinary voters _ ironically,
a bit the way some Bush supporters now look at Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush first entered the congressional race, he was still
single and struggling to start an oil company. He was not obviously
congressional material: He lived in a bachelor's flat, his bed
frame tied together with one of his neckties, and he dressed
exclusively in ratty denim or in clothes that did not match.
</P>
<P>
   But he campaigned feverishly from morning to night in his white
Oldsmobile Cutlass, usually running late, his volunteers sitting
beside him and struggling to domesticate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chewed tobacco,'' recalled Lisa Nowlin, one of those
volunteers, ``and we always had to carry a spit cup so he could
spit out the tobacco before he saw the Methodist preachers.''
</P>
<P>
   So what drew Bush into politics?
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he rejected the suggestion that he had followed
his father into politics, saying instead that he had been angry at
the Carter administration's policy on natural gas pricing. But in a
1995 conversation with a historian, Herbert S. Parmet, Bush
emphasized the degree to which his own family legacy pushed him
into the political world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a passing on of tradition, passing on legacy, passing
on responsibility,'' Bush said then, according to Parmet's
transcript of the conversation. ``So I don't think it's a conscious
effort. I don't think it's any of this thing where, you know, `by
God, young man, if you play your cards right you, too, may end up
in politics.' It's more of an inherent trait.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush may not have had a decent suit when he announced his
candidacy, but he had a first-rate name. ``George Bush'' had been a
prominent name in Texas for years, and friends of the father helped
out the son or contributed money to him in his 1978 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But it soon became apparent that there was also a downside to
this pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   The other candidate in the Republican primary, Jim Reese, the
mayor of Odessa, launched attacks on Bush using themes that still
reverberate today. Some of the epithets associated years later with
Ann Richards in her contest with Bush for the governor's job, such
as ``Junior'' or ``Shrub,'' were first used by Reese back in 1978.
The jabs struck a chord; Bush asked his father not to campaign for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the congressional primary became a proxy battle between two
national Republican giants, for Ronald Reagan and the elder Bush
were dueling in preparation for the 1980 Republican presidential
nomination, and Reagan did not want a Bush family victory in Texas.
As a result, Reagan contributed $3,000 from his political action
committee to Reese's campaign and taped a television commercial for
him. This infuriated the Bush family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in getting into an argument with Reagan,''
the elder Bush told The Washington Post at that time. ``But I am
surprised about what he is doing here, in my state.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are making a real effort to defeat George,'' Bush added
indignantly.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Young George also found himself pummeled by conspiracy-minded
right-wingers.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush was a member of the Trilateral Commission, a
group of prominent internationalists working for cooperation among
the United States, Europe and Japan, and word spread among farmers
that the commission intended to create a world government and was
responsible for depressed crop prices.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald McCathern, a prominent farmer in the area, said: ``We
were always voicing the opinion, `if you support the Trilateral
Commission that your father is in, then farmers can't support you.
And he wouldn't back down. He would say `he's my father and I
support my father.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father was appalled that his membership in the Trilateral
Commission was hurting his son's candidacy, so he resigned a few
days before the election.
</P>
<P>
   While the younger Bush was regarded as personable and a quick
study in his first campaign, he still made a series of mistakes,
largely through inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there was the candidate forum on a farm near the
small town of Dimmitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is the first time I've been on a real farm,'' Bush
announced, beaming at the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Reese began his talk by saying: ``I want to assure you, this is
not the first time I've been on a real farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the television commercial Bush dreamed up to show
how energetic he was: It showed him jogging on a track. In those
days, joggers were about as common in West Texas as Martians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time folks around here go running,'' Hance, the
Democratic candidate, told audiences, ``is when somebody's chasing
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Bush beat Reese handily in the Republican
primary, with 56 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But everybody knew that Hance would present tougher competition.
A smooth-talking farmboy who had grown up in the district, Hance
was a rising political star who focused his campaign on emphasizing
local ties and on making Bush out as a carpet-bagger from the East.
</P>
<P>
   Hance had graduated from Texas Tech and the University of Texas
Law School, and he liked to remind audiences that Bush had gone to
Yale and Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yale and Harvard don't prepare you as well for running for the
19th congressional district as Texas Tech does,'' Hance told
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the campaign, disaster struck the Bush forces.
</P>
<P>
   A university student was organizing a ``Bush bash'' to recruit
young people from Texas Tech, and he placed an advertisement in the
student newspaper promising free beer. In fact the event was tame
and ended early, but the Democrats had their ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Five days before the election, a law partner of Hance wrote a
public letter denouncing the Bush campaign for using alcohol to
lure young people.
</P>
<P>
   The local newspapers wrote about the incident, quoting Hance as
saying: ``Maybe it's a cool thing to do at Harvard or Yale.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush called a news conference in which he fumed: ``His campaign
has been funny. First he attacked my family, then my background,
and now my morals.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Bush found out that Hance owned a building that
was leased to Fat Dawgs, a bar in Lubbock. Some of Bush's friends
urged him to accuse Hance of hypocrisy, but he refused; voters
would reward a candidate who took the high road, he told
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``His weakness was that he wouldn't go for the jugular,'' said
Jane Anne Stinnett, a cotton broker and long-time Republican in
Lubbock. Stinnett said that she was arguing for a tough response to
the beer bash accusations, but ``he just didn't want to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Bush was beaten, 53 percent to 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were glad the race was over,'' said Hance, now a Republican
lawyer in Austin and a Bush supporter. ``He was really improving
every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bright guy, and he picked up the issues and got better
as time went on. If it'd been two weeks earlier, we would have
beaten him worse. If it'd been two weeks later, it would have been
really close.''
</P>
<P>
   So what did Bush learn from his first political contest? How did
it change him?
</P>
<P>
   He seems to have learned that a candidate needs to pick his
races, for it may have been impossible for a Republican oilman from
Midland, the West Texas town where Bush had grown up, to win in an
overwhelmingly Democratic district dominated by agriculture and the
rival city of Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an interesting lesson,'' Bush said in an interview.
``Sometimes there are races you just can't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other lessons, some of Bush's friends say, is the need to
respond forcefully to accusations, like those about the ``Bush
bash,'' and, more broadly, ``don't let your opponent define you,''
as Joe O'Neill, a friend from those days, put it.
</P>
<P>
   Hance's take is that he taught Bush a twofold lesson. First, he
says, he showed Bush the need to cultivate the religious right, and
helped teach him the need to be more folksy.
</P>
<P>
   As Hance puts it: ``He wasn't going to be out-Christianed or
out-good-old-boyed again. He's going to be the good old boy next
door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
