<HEADER>
A3952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LIBERACE-BOOK-REVIEW-     07-26 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERACE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIBERACE': A BIOGRAPHY AS INTENSE AS ITS SUBJECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By   JANET MASLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a discussion of the import of ``I'll Be Seeing You'' as
Liberace's signature song, the star's inexhaustible biographer,
Darden Asbury Pyron, manages to invoke Dante's Beatrice, ancient
Jewish elders, the Greek goddess Artemis and ``The Sound and the
Fury.'' All this is by way of contemplating the meaning of
``seeing,'' and it blessedly is not accompanied by any great claims
for Liberace's theoretical wisdom on the point.
</P>
<P>
   But Pyron, who previously trained his hyperanalytical eye on
Margaret Mitchell (in the well-received ``Southern Daughter'') and
``Gone With the Wind,'' is daffily intent on making a scholarly
study of the performer famed for introducing rhinestone-studded hot
pants to Las Vegas. And at the very least, he winds up making his
own biographical impulse understood. There may be no urgent need to
plumb ``the inner vision adumbrated in the lyrics of ``I'll Be
Seeing You,''' but Pyron makes a reasonable connection between
Liberace's carefully created persona as ``Mr. Showmanship'' and the
cultural climate in which he sustained his gaudy, big-hearted brand
of celebrity for 50 years. It was a career fittingly immortalized
in ``Bartlett's Familiar Quotations,'' which cites Liberace for
coining the phrase ``laughed all the way to the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Pyron's stupefyingly serious ``Liberace'' carries too
much baggage (including 54 pages of chatty footnotes on top of a
dense 427-page text) to resemble ordinary show-business
hagiography, it does reveal that Walter Liberace first wowed
listeners as a 3-year-old playing ``Yes, We Have No Bananas'' on
the family upright piano in his Wisconsin home. ``The first
manifestation of his genius is legendary,'' notes Pyron, who claims
to have approached Liberace without any great affection but
obviously warmed to his subject, just as readers may.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy who loved to entertain, to make silk flowers and to
carve animals out of soap, one who spoke ``in a voice you don't
often hear at football games,'' little Wally shaped his nascent
stage personality to blunt classmates' enmity, escape a domineering
father and brighten the workaday gloom of the Depression. Pyron,
who lards his thoughts about Liberace with as many larger
references as possible, especially when Greek mythology is an
option, notes the entertainer's lack of satisfaction with his early
success by saying: ``When asked what labor wanted, Samuel Gompers
supposedly cried `More!' It was an American idiom. Liberace spoke
it with his soul.''
</P>
<P>
   So he created a piano act featuring candelabra inspired by a
movie about Chopin, classical-sounding renditions of popular music,
piano lessons for audience members, frequent references to his
mother (he solicited tuna recipes for her benefit) and outrageous
visual trappings that became legendary in their own right. And the
essence of his performance, even in the years when it marked him as
``a cultural Antichrist,'' was its delight in being square.
``There's a whole, big, wonderful country between L.A. and
N.Y.C.,'' he proclaimed with typical gusto. ``It's full of lots of
smart people with opinions and tastes of their own. You have to be
prepared to please that whole country. You have to be prepared to
entertain everyone. If you have something for everybody, they'll
have something for you . . . their love and appreciation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Liberace's homosexuality was not liable to please everyone.
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
And public awareness of it could have done great damage to a career
based on his appeal to women as ``the greatest lover since
Valentino,'' in the words of one delusional Chicago newspaper, or
at least as a friendly figure who approached consumerism with
religious fervor. ``The main thing about Liberace,'' one fan told a
reporter, ``is that he is through and through a Continental. When
he kisses your hand, you know he isn't going to chew off your
arm.'' He needed to sustain that aura, as well as the gaudy
caricature of wealth and high culture that appealed so successfully
to middle-class America, as a professional matter of life or
death. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though Liberace was so glittery a star in the early 1950's that
the book includes a picture of Elvis Presley gazing up at him
delightedly as part of a Las Vegas audience, his career hit an ugly
patch in the latter part of that decade. Innuendoes from
publications like Hollywood Confidential (``Why Liberace's Theme
Song Should Be `Mad About the Boy''') nearly did him in. And it was
an extraordinary sign of the times that he chose to sue an English
newspaper for hinting at his homosexuality, replying, ``No, sir,
never in my life'' when asked in court, ``Have you ever indulged in
homosexual practices?'' Pyron is at his best in explaining why, for
a man with an incongruously conservative, even retrograde vision of
Americana, a lie like that was a curious, backhanded way of telling
some larger truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he grew more artificial, he became more genuine,'' Quentin
Crisp commented about Liberace. And this biography, in refracting
the life of ``the showman'' (a virtual pronoun as Pyron uses it)
through such watershed American events as World War II, the birth
of television, the creation of Las Vegas style, the Stonewall
uprising and the scourge of AIDS (which killed Liberace in 1987,
though he refused to acknowledge the disease), makes that point in
a larger sense.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, so imprisoned by vanity that he nearly refused a
face-lift if it meant removing his wig, Liberace had become a true
American bellwether, a man whose life was fraught with signs of his
times even if his memoirs, contrary to Pyron's claim, do not
warrant comparison to Benjamin Franklin's. He had achieved a
strange and enduring feat of self-creation. And ``finally,'' in the
words of one person quoted here, ``it was impossible to make fun of
Liberace because he was having too much fun making fun of
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LIBERACE'
</P>
<P>
   An American Boy
</P>
<P>
   By Darden Asbury Pyron
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 494 pages. The University of Chicago Press. $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of first chapters, including excerpts from new books
by Jane Alexander, W.S. Merwin and others, are available at The New
York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com/books
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
