<SLUG> BC-TOYSMART-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE LEANING AGAINST TOYSMART IN CUSTOMER DATA CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A bankruptcy judge says she has ``fundamental
problems'' with a Federal Trade Commission settlement allowing
failed Web retailer Toysmart.com to sell customer data.
</P>
<P>
   The toy seller withdrew the controversial database from auction
during a court hearing in Boston, avoiding a possible ruling
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Toysmart.com and its creditors rejected current
bids as too low in price, though they hope to sell the data at a
later date.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Carol Kenner indicated that she believed opponents of
the deal have a strong case against the company. And she promised
Wednesday that her concerns over the settlement ``will be difficult
to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   If the retailer had not withdrawn the sale, Kenner said she
would have backed 40 states that have registered objections to the
auction. Attorneys general and privacy advocates say Toysmart.com,
which promised consumers it would never sell their personal
information, should be blocked from selling such data.
</P>
<P>
   Kenner plans to address the FTC settlement in another court
hearing. No date had been set.
</P>
<P>
   State authorities, consumer advocates, and Internet firms are
anxiously awaiting Kenner's decision, which could set a precedent
in an industry that is grappling with growing concerns over
consumer privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com closed its Internet doors in May after its majority
owner, Walt Disney Co., pulled its support. Last month, the company
filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the US
bankruptcy code.
</P>
<P>
   Although Toysmart.com posted a policy on it Web site clearly
stating it would never sell personal information about its
customers to a third party, it collapsed and soon began advertising
the sale of its assets in The Boston Globe, Wall Street Journal and
other publications.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC sued Toysmart.com earlier this month in US District
Court in Boston, seeking to block the sale of the database. But
last week the two sides reached a settlement that permits the
online retailer to sell customer information under certain
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Toysmart.com must delete about 2,000
records allegedly collected in violation of the Children's Online
Privacy Protection Act of 1998. It can sell the data only to a
family-oriented business that purchases the entire Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``What harm can fall from that?'' Harry Murphy, an attorney for
Toysmart.com, asked Kenner.
</P>
<P>
   Eric London, an FTC spokesman, said the commission helped craft
an agreement that ``balances the ability of a company to sell
itself with consumers' privacy rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys general, however, have rejected the settlement, saying
it does not go far enough in protecting the rights of consumers.
The states argue that all customers should be notified of the sale
and given the opportunity to have their files deleted.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Kogut, assistant attorney general for Massachusetts, said
she also objects to the possible sale of the customer database to a
unit of Disney. If no suitable buyer emerges, the subsidiary has
offered to pay $50,000 for the list and have it destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toysmart made a very specific promise to consumers that it
would never sell the list,'' Kogut said. Selling the list to Disney
``gets to the right result in the wrong way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2032EDT &QL; 
