u a BC-CIR-CELLPHONES-RISKS-     07-26 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CELLPHONES-RISKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CELL PHONE USE EXPLODES, DEBATE OVER HEALTH RISK GROWS
</HEADLINE>
  By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many people, Tim Keck, the publisher of two weekly
newspapers in the Pacific Northwest, has come to depend on his cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   And like many other cell phone users, he has begun to worry
about possible health risks connected with its use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sometimes scared my brain is getting boiled,'' said Keck,
whose newspaper in Seattle, The Stranger, is known for its jaded
humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's so convenient that I couldn't imagine not using it,''
he said, ``so I push these worries to the back of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   After several of the world's largest cell phone manufacturers,
including companies like Nokia, Motorola and Ericsson, said last
week that they planned to release more information on the radiation
levels of their devices, it will be harder to ignore the debate
over health risks and mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   Even though federal agencies, relying on the results of various
studies, say cell phones are safe, it is not surprising that
concerns about the possible risks are increasing. Cell phones are
emerging as perhaps the best-selling electronic device in the
world. More than 400 million units are expected to be sold this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the debate has to do with the amount of radiation
emitted.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the Federal Communications Commission in
1996 established a level of 1.6 watts per kilogram _ or 2.2 pounds
_ of human tissue as the highest amount of radio waves a device can
emit when held against a given part of the body.
</P>
<P>
   Although devices currently available meet the FCC standard,
there is a lot of confusion as to what the level means.
</P>
<P>
   That has prompted the Cellular Telephone Industry Association, a
group representing wireless companies, to provide more information
on what the watts per tissue level means on pamphlets inside each
package.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, manufacturers will offer information on the
packages that let consumers know that the device has been approved
by the FCC, and will list addresses of government and corporate Web
sites that provide more information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found there is a great deal of misinformation out there, so
our aim is to provide as much transparency as possible,'' said Tom
Wheeler, the president of the industry association, which is in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the topic of cell phones and health risks can be
confusing. Almost all studies conducted have failed to show any
conclusive evidence that cell phone use can cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a few studies have linked cell phone use to the risk of
brain cancer in laboratory animals. One study showed that mice
genetically predisposed to a type of cancer developed twice as many
such cancers when exposed to cell phone radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, all sides in the debate have called for
additional research. The industry association recently said it
would spend $25 million to study possible cancer risks from cell
phones.
</P>
<P>
   In light of recent rulings against tobacco companies, phone
manufacturers may be able to shield themselves from the possibility
of future legal action if they can show that they have tried to
make users aware of any information related to radiation levels and
cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is simply smart for the companies to show they've done
everything possible to ensure their devices are safe,'' said
Mitchell Lazarus, a lawyer at Fletcher, Heald &AMP; Hindreth in
Arlington, Va., which specializes in telecommunications law.
</P>
<P>
   There are skeptics regarding the safety of cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these people point to the need to conduct long-term
research, since cell phones have only been available on a
widespread basis since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``On numerous occasions, microwave radiation from sources
similar to cellular phones has been showed to increase the chances
of cancer,'' said C. Ross Adey, a former professor of physiology at
the Loma Linda School of Medicine. ``It is far too early in the
game to say that cell phones are the harmless little objects the
industry makes them out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, anyone concerned with the potential health
risks can take several steps to lessen the possibility of cancer,
however distant it may be.
</P>
<P>
   Earphones can keep the phone away from the brain, although it
could expose a different part of the body to radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Or, cell phone users could simply opt to have shorter
conversations, which would lower their exposure to radio waves.
There are also a increasing number of shields being sold that are
designed to protect the user from radiation, although some critics
say the shields might actually increase exposure because some
phones may need more radio-frequency energy to communicate with
nearby towers.
</P>
<P>
   As for comparing the radiation levels of each phone,
manufacturers and scientists seem to agree that this is somewhat of
a useless exercise since the amount of radiation emitted can wary
widely depending on where the device is used.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a cell phone used in Manhattan could have a higher
radiation level because more energy is needed to communicate with a
tower given the interference from buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But even in these situations, the devices are below the FCC
limit of 1.6 watts per kilogram of human tissue, according to the
Cellular Telephone Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wheeler, the head of the manufacturers' association,
said, few devices reach that level because it was established with
a 50-fold margin of error and the energy they need rarely reaches
that threshold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand behind scientific consensus that no health risks have
been demonstrated,'' said Norman Sandler, director of global
strategic issues at Motorola. ``But we support the need for more
research into the matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
