<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ARAB-LEADERS-     07-26 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ARAB-LEADERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPT WELCOMES ARAFAT FOR BRIEFINGS ON CAMP DAVID 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Trying to mine some hope from the failed Camp
David peace talks and prepare for new negotiations, Egyptian
officials Wednesday welcomed the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat,
for consultations on his way home from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat did not treat himself immediately to an enthusiastic
homecoming in Gaza, but instead flew to Alexandria, the summer
retreat of the Egyptian government. There he briefed President
Hosni Mubarak and Arab League officials on his two weeks of
intensive negotiations with Israel over the contentious issues of
Jerusalem, land and refugees.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly three hours of meetings, Arafat emerged and spoke
defiantly at a news conference, accusing Israel of inflexibility
and promising his host that one day they would both pray in an
Arab-run Jerusalem, ``whether some people like it or hate it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have run out of patience,'' he added. ``In fact, we are far
beyond the limits of patience.''
</P>
<P>
   But his decision to fly directly to Mubarak, his closest ally in
the ranks of often hostile Arab leaders and the one with the best
relations with American officials, indicated that Arafat was
already beginning his preparations for another plunge into
negotiations before Sept. 13, the deadline he has given for his
declaration of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not in Arafat's interest _ and it for sure is not in
Egypt's interest or Jordan's or America's _ to have a unilateral
declaration of statehood without a broader framework agreement,''
said an Egyptian official involved in the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have to act to limit the sense of despair about Camp
David and prevent a deterioration of the situation,'' the official
added.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt is expected to sponsor a round of consultations among Arab
leaders to build support for Arafat as he and the Israelis try to
rescue some accord from Camp David in the next seven weeks. King
Abdullah II of Jordan, as well as several leaders of Persian Gulf
states, are expected in Alexandria for meetings with Mubarak next
week.
</P>
<P>
   If past crises in Palestinian-Israeli negotiations are a guide,
Mubarak may also meet with Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel to
try to defuse tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak has long played a pivotal role in garnering Arab support
for talks with Israel. After 19 years in office, he has developed
good relations with the United States and has acted as a mediator
in Israel's sputtering negotiations with the Palestinians and with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   During the Camp David talks, he spoke with Arafat and with Barak
by telephone. While many American officials in Washington have
expressed disappointment that Mubarak did not press the
Palestinians to accept a compromise on the difficult issue of
Jerusalem, he did present the options on Jerusalem to other Arab
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak flew to Saudi Arabia, for example, last weekend, when
the the talks appeared to have reached a particularly intense stage
as specific proposals for partial administrative control over some
sites in Jerusalem were offered by the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts in Cairo said Mubarak was testing the waters
with Crown Prince Abdullah on the Israeli offer of partial
Palestinian self-rule in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudis, keepers of Islam's two holiest sites, Mecca and
Medina, apparently responded coolly to any compromise on full
Palestinian sovereignty over East Jerusalem and its Old City. After
the trip, Mubarak gave his full support to Arafat's rejection of
the Israeli plan, Mubarak's aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the issue of negotiating the status of
Jerusalem, Arafat is too weak, personally and politically, to act
on his own,'' said Wahid Abdel Maguid, the deputy director of Al
Ahram Center for Political and Strategic Studies in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is too weak even to take a decision to delay a decision,''
Abdel Maguid added. ``To make a decision you need a consensus
between three or four big Arab countries, because it's a matter of
historical responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that Mubarak, who still fears an Islamic
fundamentalist insurgency at home, is interested in seeing Arafat
accept less than full Palestinian sovereignty over the Arab part of
Jerusalem and its mosques, which are sacred to Muslims all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
   But Mubarak does have the credibility to explore options that
Arafat, who has a long history of rocky and mutually suspicious
relations with his fellow Arab leaders, does not. As Egyptian
president, Mubarak also has more influence over Arafat than any
other leader, in part because Egypt has the least troublesome
history with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, under the late King Hussein, fought off an attempt by
Palestinians under Arafat to take control of the country. Syria,
under the late President Hafez al-Assad, sheltered and financed the
radical Palestinian opposition to Arafat. Lebanon's civil war grew
out of its battles with Palestinians. The Gulf countries expelled
most Palestinian residents in 1990 to punish Arafat for support he
offered to President Saddam Hussein of Iraq, who invaded Kuwait
that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Arafat and for most Palestinians, Egypt is the only Arab
country which supported the Palestinians in their cause without
interfering in their internal affairs and without committing any
crimes against them,'' said Abdel Maguid. ``The Palestinians know
Syria, Jordan, even forces within Lebanon, are responsible for many
crimes. So there is a great confidence that Arafat can feel with
Egypt that he cannot feel with any other Arab leader.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
