<HEADER>
A3960 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WATER-THROCKMORTON072     07-26 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-THROCKMORTON0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Progress rapid on water lifeline for North Texas town
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Scooping up parched earth with donated
equipment, residents, out-of-town volunteers and inmates from
nearby prisons have, in just 10 days, nearly finished a 14-mile
trench that will bring an emergency water line to the small North
Texas town of Throckmorton.
</P>
<P>
   Throckmorton's 1,036 residents have less than two months before
Lake Throckmorton, their sole water source, runs dry. Their plight
has brought hundreds of volunteers to the town and given local
leaders new confidence that the pipeline connecting the town to a
water supply company's lines in Elbert will be finished before the
lake runs out of usable water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be ready before we run out of water,'' said
Throckmorton public works director Steve Bowlin, who organized the
project. ``I feel pretty confident saying we're going to have all
our pipe in the ground by this weekend. So we're way ahead of
schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowlin said they expect to have the pipeline ready to transport
water by Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Much work remains. Workers must fill the ditch with a layer of
sand, assemble the pipe segments and bury the pipeline. And
Throckmorton must still install storage tanks and a pump station to
get the water flowing.
</P>
<P>
   The town, located between Wichita Falls and Abilene, is paying
for much of the project with an $800,000 grant from the Texas
Department of Housing and Community Affairs. But the grant didn't
cover the cost of equipment or labor, so Throckmorton is building
its own lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   Since digging began July 17, residents have been joined by as
many as 115 volunteers a day from other parts of Texas, Oklahoma
and as far away as Chicago and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had quite a few folks from the Austin area come up,''
said Mayor John Kunkel. ``It just kind of exploded on us, and it's
been wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Donated digging equipment has come from Grapevine, Dallas,
Arlington and nearby communities. A family from Mesquite that runs
a construction company showed up with two dump trucks and an
excavator and worked for 30 hours straight, Bowlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Bottled water for the workers has poured into Throckmorton by
the truckload. Nearby towns, an H-E-B grocery and country music
star Billy Ray Cyrus have all sent shipments of water, which are
passed out to work crews by local teen-agers , Kunkel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Baptist Men have been preparing two meals a day for
the workers. The Red Cross is on site to deliver the meals. In
return, Throckmorton residents with spare beds have opened their
homes to the volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Dave Harmon at dharmon(at)statesman.com or
445-3645.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
