<HEADER>
A3965 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DANCE-LINCOLN-FESTIVA     07-26 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-LINCOLN-FESTIVAL-ART-$ADV30-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARLIT MOMENTS ON THE PLAZAS AT LINCOLN CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: S.C., N.J. Ghana, Korea)  
(EDS: Words in boldface should be set in italics.)  (For release Sunday, July 30)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Leonard de Paur became Lincoln Center's director
of community relations in 1970, two things concerned him: the lack
of community participation in the center's activities and the vast,
empty plazas.
</P>
<P>
   As a black conductor who had broken down racial barriers in
music throughout his distinguished career, he was not about to
accept the status quo. In short order, he created a program that
solved both problems and now entertains New Yorkers every summer _
Lincoln Center Out of Doors. The extravagant festival of free
dance, music and theater, this year titled Celebrate Good Times,
starts on Saturday and runs through Aug. 29. The public quickly
responded to de Paur's revolutionary idea, flocking to Lincoln
Center in August to watch both the famous and the unknown local
artists perform under an open sky; attendance now reaches 200,000
every summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The festival started as community outreach,'' said Jane Moss,
vice president for programming at Lincoln Center, ``and it's still
strongly connected with New York's communities. Artistic director
Jenneth Webster's achievement is having given it a distinctive
artistic identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Webster, who has been in charge for nearly 20 years, believes a
chief benefit of the festival is that so many artists are exposed
to one another's work. ``I don't know where else you get so much
variety,'' she said, citing some of the highlights among this
year's more than 100 performances: the celebrated Indian singer Ali
Akbar Khan, a Taiwanese dance performance accompanied by a tea
ceremony and Pauline Oliveros' musical tour of seven ancient
cities, complete with rock bands, soothsayers and Tibetan lamas.
</P>
<P>
   Established choreographers like it for their own reasons. Paul
Taylor compares it to a joyous street fair. David Parsons, whose
troupe performs at the festival for the first time this year, said,
``I'm always after the largest possible public.''
</P>
<P>
   As the city's residents left on their annual vacations early
this month, participants in the festival's dance concerts worked up
a sweat in studios all over town while artistic directors mulled
over repertory and dealt with costumes and music.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they would have it any other way. For many of them,
it's the rare chance to show off their talents to sizable audiences
in a series that boasts both big-name artists like the Paul Taylor
Dance Company and relatively unknown troupes representative of New
York's diverse population.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there is the 25-member Harambee Dance Company
established by Frank W. Molloy III, 35, and his wife, Sandella
Molloy, 33, the artistic director and choreographer, in their
native Charleston, S.C., in 1993. They hoped to share their vision
of African dance with a wide public _ harambee means ``let's pull
together'' in Swahili _ and moved to New York four years ago for
more opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a big, airy studio in Harlem, waiting to begin
rehearsal, the Molloys report that things weren't that simple.
``People expected authentic re-creations,'' Molloy says, ``although
that was never our intention.''
</P>
<P>
   While they both studied dance in Ghana when Molloy was in the
Peace Corps in 1988 and regularly revisit Africa, they're much more
interested in capturing its spirit than in copying specific
movements. ``I add moves from hip-hop and Southern hand clapping
and foot stomping,'' Molloy says. ``We want to show how our way of
life connects with the African.'' Their son, Frank, 8, who drums
along with his father and five others, insists vigorously, ``Well,
it  &UR; does. &LR; '' Purists may wish the Harambee Dance Company duplicated
African dances, but audiences at the city's public schools and
libraries and at the Bronx Zoo are definitely happy with the troupe
as it is. In the last two years, it has put on 51 shows just at the
Bronx Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   When the dancers show up, the women in long skirts with vibrant
African patterns, Molloy takes them through exercises that combine
stretching, strengthening _ sit-ups and push-ups _ and a series of
bravura jumps, calling on their backgrounds in a variety of
disciplines. The lead dancer, Vanessa Faye, whose 3-year-old son,
Babacar, races around the studio in time to the drums, specializes
in Senegalese dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use their individual strengths,'' says Molloy, as her group
forms two diagonals, hands on hips, and struts across the floor.
``Don't look like chickens,'' she cautions, joining them in the
dance called ``Harmony,'' swaying to the floor, her arms flowing
around her like water. Then the dancers make a circle, each one
taking a turn in the center. When it comes his time, the only male
dancer, Yahi-I Tafari, dreadlocks flying, jumps in like a lion
attacking prey, the beat driving him on. Soon the floor is shaking
with the pounding of drums and feet. Two hours later they're still
going strong, and promise to do so until their festival appearance
on Aug. 25. (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   In a nondescript office building in midtown, headquarters of
another troupe, the 10-year-old Korean Traditional Performing Arts
Association, dancers and musicians prepare for their festival
appearances on Saturday and Aug. 20 without their director, the
folk musician and dancer Sue Yeon Park, 46, who is in Korea buying
instruments and costume material. The room is small but cheerful,
with gleaming wood floors, and a whole array of elaborate,
hand-painted drums lining one wall. A dancer goes through a bag
full of fierce masks, trying them on for effect. Four of his female
colleagues, in long flowing skirts, diaphanous scarves attached to
their wrists, assemble in the center of the room to begin a section
of a gentle harvest dance, led by the teacher Chang Soo Kim and
accompanied by musicians playing drums, a large gong and a zither.
</P>
<P>
   Following Kim, the dancers curve their arms in arcs as if
gathering rice _ the repertory consists almost solely of works
celebrating agricultural life and ritual Buddhist dances. This
dance is quite unlike the thunderous processional that opens their
outdoor performances. ``Much too loud to practice for a long time
inside,'' says Kim, who explains that it's especially popular with
``the little kids who play the drums,'' many of them Korean
adoptees from Camp Friendship in New Jersey, regular performers
with the 30-member group.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Harambee Dance Company, the Korean association wants
to preserve traditional dances and has found receptive audiences at
schools and at Lincoln Center's Alice Tully and Avery Fisher halls.
``We're not as explicit as Westerners in our expression of feelings
in our music and dance,'' says the dancer Jennifer Yim. ``But if
you take time, you see the beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether seeking to invent a new style or to keep an old one
alive, the overriding mission of these companies is to gain bigger
audiences, not easy in a city as culturally competitive as New
York. What Lincoln Center Out of Doors offers them is the
opportunity to build a following outside their own communities,
which was the goal of de Paur, who died in 1998. Anthony Rodriguez,
25, artistic director of the three-year-old, 20-member La Santa Luz
(Holy Light) Dance Company, dreams especially big. ``I want to do
for Hispanics,'' he says, ``what Alvin Ailey did for
African-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   He's rehearsing for his troupe's Aug. 16 performance in a studio
at LaGuardia High School on the West Side, where he teaches, rather
than at the troupe's base at the Police Athletic League in the
Bronx, because his studio there is flooded. He grew up in the Bronx
and studied at the Performing Arts High School and Ballet Hispanico
and, as he got older, danced until dawn in clubs for fun, the
origin of his penchant for house music. Inspired by a deaf sister,
he incorporates sign language into much of his work, calling his
dance style ``todasi,'' a word he coined to mean to dance and to
sign.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's outfit _ red headscarf, white T-shirt and mid-calf
black sweat pants _ starts the dancers giggling. ``You look like a
pirate,'' says Marlyn Ortiz, who first danced with him when she was
6 and, like the other members of the company, is familiar with
ballet, tap, flamenco, hip-hop and Latin, modern and African dance.
</P>
<P>
   Smiling, he switches on the tape, the hypnotic ``Hyperballad''
sung by the Icelandic pop star Bjork, for the first section of his
``Hyperballet,'' a sensation when the company performed it last
year at the Kit Kat Club, the original venue of ``Cabaret.'' More
recently, the troupe took part in the New York Hip-Hop Theater
Festival at P.S. 122 last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz and the dancer Shane Mercado walk forward, hips swinging,
arms akimbo, only to spring apart suddenly and do back flips in
opposite directions, all to an electric, jazzy rhythm. Then moments
later, the pace slows as Mercado takes Ortiz's hand and pulls her
into a tender embrace. ``Make it sweet,'' Rodriguez requests, not
about to let them leave for at least another hour.
</P>
<P>
   Do they mind spending hot July days holed up in a studio? ``Not
at all,'' Ortiz says. ``Rehearsal feels like coming home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
