<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTE0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    International Soccer Notebook
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Transfer records continue to fall. And the staggering
amounts of money being spent on some of the world's most valued
players could play into efforts to abandon the current fee
structure.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Barcelona and Portugal midfielder Luis Figo's
world-record $56.1 million move to Real Madrid on Monday came at a
good time for European Union officials who want to eliminate
transfer-fee regulations for players under contract.
</P>
<P>
   The EU granted unrestricted free-agency to out-of-contract
players in its member nations less than five years ago. Now its aim
is FIFA and UEFA provisions on buyout clauses and other incentives
for players to stay.
</P>
<P>
   But the move by Figo and new Real Madrid president Florentino
Perez prove that money is no object for the world's richest teams.
Figo leaves Barca for its hated soccer and cultural enemy, the
reigning European Cup champion.
</P>
<P>
   If the EU has its way, clubs could not impose any buyout clause,
an unsettling prospect, because the European bureaucrats have not
set any formulas for providing compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Perez has plunged the club into even deeper debt than usual, an
estimated $250 million in the hole. Even the sale of French striker
Nicolas Anelka to Paris-St Germain for $31.6 million can't cut into
the deficit. Figo has pledged to play for six years, for
approximately $5.6 million a season, but he signed an extension
with Barcelona only last year.
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona's new president, Joan Gaspart, campaigned to bring
Arsenal midfield tandem Emmanuel Petit and Marc Overmars. The club
sold Dutch midfielder Boudewijn Zenden to Lazio for $12 million
before Figo's departure.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian Serie A champions from Lazio had set a
world-transfer record two weeks ago when they purchased Argentine
striker Hernan Crespo from Parma for $54 million. Then they bought
his countryman Claudio Lopez from Valencia for another $33 million.
Lazio is loading up for a title defense and for the European
Champions League with more than $100 million in new spending and
isn't finished yet. Lazio also has picked up Inter Milan goalkeeper
Angelo Peruzzi and will get new Italian midfield sensation Stefano
Fiore from Udinese next year.
</P>
<P>
   Their crosstown rivals at AS Roma have spent a bundle as well,
luring Gabriel Batistuta from Fiorentina for $33.8 million. On
Tuesday, they made the long-awaited move of Brazilian midfielder
Emerson from Bayer Leverkusen for a German club-record of $19
million.
</P>
<P>
   France: Paris in spotlight
</P>
<P>
   France might be the World Cup and now the European champions,
but the domestic game has languished. Its top stars ply their trade
in England, Italy and Spain. Le Championnat, which begins anew on
Friday, was won easily by AS Monaco last season. But the club has
unloaded unhappy keeper Fabien Barthez to Manchester United and
sent striker David Trezeguet, to Juventus. Trezeguet scored the
thrilling goal in overtime to beat Italy in the Euro finals. The
center of attention has shifted to the capital, where unheralded
Paris St-Germain is poised to earn only its second crown. The
signing of Anelka, France's only national team regular playing at
home, could push PSG over the top, as long as he doesn't go into
one of his long brooding fits. The midfield of Ali Benarbia and
Jay-Jay Okocha was strengthened by the transfer of Stephane Dalmat
of Marseille.... Monaco added strikers Shaboni Nonda of Rennes and
Xavier Gravelaine and could be among the top four, along with Lyon,
which picked up Cameroonian forward Marc-Vivien Foe from West
Ham.... Marseille, once the dominant French club, barely avoided
relegation after finishing a humiliating 15th. New coach Abel
Braga, late of Vasco da Gama, has been charged with picking up the
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland: Rangers roll unstoppable?
</P>
<P>
   For the 11th time in the last 12 years, the Glasgow Rangers won
the top flight in Scotland. And that trend doesn't appear to be
changing anytime soon. Celtic, their bitter enemies, are reeling
from an inept run last year. American midfielder Claudio Reyna is
back for his second full season, and the addition of Dutch defender
Bert Konterman means that Reyna can go back to his more natural
position. Striker Kenny Miller has arrived from Hibernian, another
indication that it will be virtually impossible to catch the
Rangers. Celtic's fifth boss in the last seven seasons is Martin
O'Neill, formerly of Leicester City. Henrik Larsson of Sweden has
recovered from a broken leg and might team up front with Chris
Sutton, a bust at Chelsea last year. Hibernian and Hearts,
Edinburgh's equivalent to the Rangers-Celtic feud, are the only
other clubs with a chance to be nominally competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Toluca, America favored
</P>
<P>
   Toluca left no doubt about its dominance during the Verano
(summer) championship that ended in June. But Mexico's revolving
door of player transfers could provide more competition when the
Invierno (winter) season starts Saturday. The Red Devils lost
striker Jose Abundis to Atlante but still have lethal Jose Cardozo
up front. Atlante was the worst team in the league last year, but
has gained Carlos Hermosillo and goalkeeper Jorge Campos, in
addition to Abundis.... Club America could not hold on to Mexican
national team striker Cuauhtemoc Blanco any longer, selling him to
Valladolid of the Spanish Primera Liga, but it still has plenty of
firepower. Colombian striker Frankie Oviedo is on board to help
America, the most popular team in Mexico, try to end an 11-year
title drought.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: River on a rolll
</P>
<P>
   After winning both season titles last year, River Plate has been
able to stave off interest by European clubs in some of its
high-profile players. It is favored to win the Apertura tournament
that begins on Sunday. Strikers Javier Saviola and Juan Pablo Angel
figure to increase their value, especially if midfielder Pablo
Aimar, being targeted by Barcelona, sticks around.... Boca Juniors,
River's Buenos Aires big rival, won the Copa Libertadores but sold
valuable defender Walter Samuel to AS Roma. Striker Martin Palermo
should invigorate the club after a disappointing Clausura
campaign.... Independiente was second to River in the Clausura, but
auctioned off five top players to French, Spanish and Italian
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
