<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3968 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ILLITERACY-UNEMPLOYME     07-26 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILLITERACY-UNEMPLOYMENT-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLITERACY BECOMES ISSUE AS BOOMING ECONOMY RETAINS POCKETS OF
POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT23,24 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEVILLE, Ky. _ Statisticians call Marsha Hendrickson, the
mother of four and a coal miner's daughter, functionally
illiterate. With the national economy bubbling along, soaking up
workers and spreading wealth, she and much of Appalachia live not
only with poverty and unemployment but with the humiliation of
being taken for ignorant.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson dropped out of school in the eighth grade, at 15.
Now 28, she reads. On shelves by her television set, she has a set
of dictionaries, two romance novels and a Bible. At the Pic Pac
grocery store, she tallies her purchases as she pushes her cart
through the aisles. But she stumbles on long words, subtraction and
division, and says the lack of skills make her feel inadequate. So
far, they have also contributed to making her unemployable.
</P>
<P>
   At a time that industry is scouring America for workers to keep
it and the economy rolling, children in Kentucky's Appalachian
hills as well as many in urban centers and impoverished stretches
of the South are still dropping out of school at high rates, only
to find themselves unequipped for any but the most menial jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding the alarm, politicians and advocates for the poor have
begun putting entrenched illiteracy at the root of privation in
places like Appalachia and the Mississippi Delta, which economic
growth has largely bypassed.
</P>
<P>
   In his presidential campaign, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has
declared illiteracy a ``national emergency,'' a view that his
opponent, Vice President Al Gore, has said he shares. To tackle it
under a federal-state program called Even Start, Congress and the
Clinton administration have increased aid to state literacy
projects by nearly 50 percent, to $150 million, in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Paul Patton of Kentucky, a Democrat, who observes that his
state has the nation's lowest percentage of high school graduates,
is doubling expenditures on literacy programs, like Even Start, to
$34 million over two years.
</P>
<P>
   Across Eastern Kentucky's rural, time-worn cities and towns,
government agencies, foundations and charities have opened
storefront learning centers to coax people to study for the general
education development test, the GED, the equivalent of a high
school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky is also tightening enforcement of the law requiring
students to stay in school until at 16, supporting counseling to
discourage dropping out and discouraging social promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the functionally illiterate often struggle with all
but the simplest arithmetic, reading a recipe, a map or the words
on the keys of a McDonald's cash register. Often they cannot fill
out a job application, type data into a computer, punctuate a
paragraph, balance a checkbook or take a written test for a
driver's license. (Kentucky lets people take the test orally.) In
time, such difficulties can shred their self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson, a GED student at the Sister Marjorie Learning
Center in Pineville, is one of the people the literacy programs are
trying to reach. Cheerful, well-groomed and a fastidious
housekeeper, she said she had long wanted a job, and she is now
under pressure to find work before she loses her welfare benefits
under the 1996 welfare law.
</P>
<P>
   On her kitchen wall, Hendrickson has hung a certificate
testifying to her completion of a job-readiness program that states
have urged welfare recipients to take as they move off the rolls.
But she remains stymied and stigmatized by the schooling she
missed. ``What hurts me,'' she said, ``is I got no job history.''
</P>
<P>
   In applying for work at McDonald's, she was allowed seven wrong
answers on the restaurant's food-handling test. ``I got eight,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She applied for a telemarketing job, soliciting sales on the
telephone. ``I stayed for one day of training'' and gave up,'' she
said. ``I felt those people watching me. I felt people laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, people trying to earn the high school equivalency
diploma in Kentucky are few. Janet Hoover, a spokeswoman in the
state's Workforce Development Cabinet in Frankfort, Ky., says that
each year the literacy programs are reaching only 5 percent of the
state's 1 million functionally illiterate population.
</P>
<P>
   That illiteracy is linked to poverty, unemployment and
Appalachia's weak economy is hardly a secret. But for decades
politicians attributed the region's poverty to its topography,
isolation and the demise of coal mining. So they cut hundreds of
miles of highways through the hollows and hills to bring in
prosperity and well-paying jobs. But few jobs came, and the most
employable workers used the highways to flee.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey published seven years ago for the Department of
Education, the Educational Testing Service found that more than one
in five adults 16 and older, 40 million people across the United
States, could read and calculate at no better than the lowest of
five levels of literacy, called Level 1.
</P>
<P>
   About a quarter of those 40 million people are non-English
speaking immigrants. The rest grew up speaking English. Many are
blacks who live in large cities and rural Southern communities.
Several million others live in Appalachia, which is almost entirely
white. The national survey, and one three years ago by the state of
Kentucky, found that about 30 percent of the adults in Appalachian
counties were functionally illiterate.
</P>
<P>
   With the new attention to literacy, groups that serve the poor
are casting doubt on the social programs born in in the 1960s. The
programs fed, clothed, nursed and sheltered a destitute population.
But with the checks continuing until a family's children were
grown, the advocates say, welfare institutionalized illiteracy and
a low standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average job here pays a little over $6'' an hour, said
Richard L. Witherlite, executive director of Interfaith of Bell
County Inc., a church-sponsored agency in Pineville that serves the
poor. ``There's been no boom because there are no jobs. There're no
jobs because people are illiterate.''
</P>
<P>
   Witherlite said welfare supplanted coal mines that began closing
and automating in the 1960s. Before that, Witherlite said: ``A boy
could quit school at a young age and make a good living. Then
through the generations kids thought, `Dad made it without an
education, so I can make it.' That was OK as long as the coal mines
were here.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the Salvation Army in Middlesboro, Capt. Edward Binnix, the
commander, said he no longer helps the poor until they first go
next door to the learning center of the Bell County Council on
Illiteracy for testing. The illiterate need to start thinking about
working on a GED, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get people in here who can't fill out a job application,''
Binnix said. ``We get people who don't have a first-grade
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, catching up after years out of school is no easy chore.
``I finished the eighth grade,'' said Darrell Brock, 42, of
Middlesboro. ``Fifteen I was. I thought I knew everything about
everything. I started working, mowing lawns.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock married and went to work for the highway department. He
had two sons, now 11 and 14. But the 11-year-old is handicapped and
uses a wheelchair, he said, and ``my wife died of cancer.'' She was
33. ``I quit my job,'' he said. ``I couldn't find anyone to take
care of my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brock's children will keep their welfare benefits, but with the
changes in the system, he could soon lose his. He said he would
like to get a janitorial job at his boys' school so he could be
around when they needed him. For that, he most likely needs a GED,
and he has not yet been able to pass the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can read,'' Brock said. ``I read the newspaper, the Bible,
magazines, newspapers.'' But math and writing are tough. ``My
weakest area is writing essays. I have to add in all that
punctuation, capitalization.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Bell County, 52 percent of the 24,000 residents 16 and older
have not finished high school or earned an equivalency diploma.
Just 9 percent have a bachelor's or master's degree. Twenty-eight
percent fall into the first level of literacy.
</P>
<P>
   Bell County's unemployment rate seems low, at about 5 percent.
But more than half the adults are neither working nor looking for
work, compared with a third of the nation's adults. Some are
disabled, some are in school, some are homemakers, and some are too
illiterate to consider a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unemployment rate in Kentucky is artificially low,'' said
Ron Couch, director of the state data center at the University of
Louisville. One result, Couch said, is that about a third of Bell
County's households live in poverty, about three times the national
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're not stupid,'' Wylene Payne said of the county's
residents. Payne is assistant manager of Bell County's Middlesboro
office of the Kentucky Department for Employment Services, where
clients go to great lengths to deny their illiteracy or compensate
for it. A sign at the clerk's window says job applications ``must
be filled out in this office.'' The forms are not allowed to be
taken out because someone other than the applicant could fill them
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll say, `I don't have my glasses today,''' Payne said.
``I have people drawing their names.''
</P>
<P>
   They memorize the lines of cursive script without learning the
letters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sitting in the kitchen of her rented, two-bedroom ranch house in
a Middlesboro hollow, Evelyn Muncy, 54, said: ``My mother went to
the fourth grade. My dad was in and out of school and went to the
coal mines when he was 13. But nobody could cheat him with his
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Muncy is doing as her mother did in her 40s and getting a
GED. She keeps a journal, written in pencil, in perfectly legible
script. On the math pages of her GED workbook, she has progressed
from subtracting 0 from 1 to subtracting 648 from 6949.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Zimmerman, 64, has built an arsenal of coping skills. He
was born in Maine and became an orphan at 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed up in the mountains,'' sleeping in a cave, he said.
``When I needed clothes, I'd come down and take them off
clotheslines.'' He stole milk and eggs that had been delivered on
back porches. He took to the road. He could not read a map, but he
did not need one. He reads the sun. He settled for a while in
Indio, Calif., and washed windows. He never married or had
children.
</P>
<P>
   Now in Middlesboro, he has earned a GED and is studying at the
learning center so he can go to college. But the years of
illiteracy took a toll. On a job application, he said, ``I could
read the words, but I couldn't comprehend what they meant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to love to paint,'' he said. But unable to read labels,
he said: ``I thought I was buying oil paint and bought a whole set
of acrylics. You just can't use acrylics on top of oil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
