<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK AND ARAFAT PLEDGE TO CONTINUE TALKS DESPITE BREAKUP AT CAMP
DAVID 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MIDEAST-ASSESS) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Ehud Barak and Yasser Arafat each pledged on
Wednesday to keep working at their halting quest for peace despite
the breakup of the Camp David summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But the Israeli prime minister and the Palestinian leader both
received homecomings that, while orchestrated events, still
illustrated the difficulties they will continue to face as they try
to forge a compromise on the highly emotional issue of Jerusalem,
which proved to be the sticking point in the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Barak returned to a somber, subdued ceremony at the
airport near Tel Aviv, greeted by his close political allies. As he
was driven up the hilly road to Jerusalem, it was lined with
protesters, many in the knitted skull cap favored by settlers,
holding signs saying: ``Barak You Are Weak,'' in reference to his
willingness to make concessions on Jerusalem to the Palestinians.
But later, he was visibly moved by the throngs of supporters he
found waiting to welcome him at his official residence.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, by contrast, received a hero's welcome from start to
finish as he arrived in the Gaza Strip _ precisely because he had
refused to compromise on Jerusalem. Looking tired, he was hoisted
up on the shoulders of his supporters, cheered by a crowd of some
5,000 and hailed, according to one of the slogans, as a modern-day
Saladin _ the Moslem warrior who recaptured Jerusalem from the
Crusaders in 1187.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome you home with honor, heroic leader of the
Palestinians,'' read a banner painted on a bedsheet. ``We hail your
heroic stand in not surrendering a single centimeter of Palestinian
land, and in not giving up Jerusalem. You are a great leader of the
Palestinian people.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the initial gloom and finger-pointing over the breakdown
of the summit meeting, there was a sense among both Israelis and
Palestinians that even by attempting to grapple with the previously
taboo subject of Jerusalem, the leaders had moved the peace process
to a new level of seriousness. That they would press on was
implicit in the remarks by both leaders as they returned home.
</P>
<P>
   Barak told the small crowd at the airport, ``In your names, in
the names of the millions of eyes still looking, hoping and
praying, I promise not to despair, not to tire, not to stop
pursuing peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, in both Alexandria, Egypt, where he stopped en route
home to confer with President Hosni Mubarak, and in Gaza, he told
reporters that ``the American side said they would continue with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an agreement between us and the Israeli government
made in Sharm el-Sheikh that we continue negotiations until Sept.
13, the date for declaring our independent state with Jerusalem as
its capital whether people like it or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the senior Palestinian negotiator, Saab Erekat, said he
hoped to resume negotiations with his Israeli counterpart as early
as Sunday. Erekat has been consistently upbeat following the summit
breakup, declaring that ``prospects for agreement on all permanent
status issues are stronger then at any time in the past nine
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread Israeli jitters that the breakdown of the
Camp David talks might touch off a new round of violence by
Palestinians, Wednesday passed quietly. The Israeli newspapers have
been carrying reports, citing intelligences sources, that
Palestinians were stocking up food, water, medicine and ammunition
in anticipation of renewed confrontations, and after the Camp David
talks broke up, the Israeli army was put on extra alert.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinian officials appeared determined on Wednesday to
avoid clashes. Faisal Husseini, the top Palestinian leader in
Jerusalem, urged calm here before traveling to Gaza to greet
Arafat, and a planned march from his headquarters at Orient House
through Saladin Street, the main Arab business district of the
city, was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no violence from us,'' said Nabil Shaath, a
ranking Palestinian official in Gaza. ``Not unless the Israelis
make violence, unless the settlers turn to it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Barak arrived at the airport on Wednesday, he appeared
close to tears as he stood stiffly at attention while an army
played the national anthem, ``Hatikva.'' He hugged a line of
waiting supporters, including bereaved parents from the Four
Mothers movement, the first group to urge unilateral Israeli
withdrawal from Lebanon, and spoke of the journey to Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went knowing there is no peace at any price, but that there
is also no peace without a price,'' he said. ``A painful, difficult
and heart-wrenching price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I return from Camp David and look into millions of eyes
in whose name I went and say with a pained heart: we have not
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not succeed because we did not find a partner prepared
to make decisions on all issues,'' he continued. ``We did not
succeed because our Palestinian neighbors have yet to internalize
that in order to obtain true peace, some of one's dreams must be
conceded; one has to give, not only request.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I look today into the eyes of millions in whose name I was
sent and say that we did everything we could,'' Barak said. ``We
turned over every stone, we exhausted every possibility to bring
about an end of the conflict and a safer future for Israel. And we
still hope.''
</P>
<P>
   When Barak arrived at his residence, he was met by a welcoming
rally organized by Peace Now _ across the street from a settler's
protest. In the background, songs were played, including the ``Song
for Peace,'' which Israel's former prime minister, Yitzak Rabin,
sang just before he was assassinated in Tel Aviv in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you all for coming here to strengthen us on our way to
peace,'' he said getting out of his car and lingering with the
crowd despite the protests of his bodyguards. He appeared
overwhelmed by the throngs who waved banners praising him, and
joined them in singing the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are long distance runners,'' he told the crowd. ``We know
what difficulties lie along the way, we know what it is to run
uphill, we know there are moments when you lose your strength and
you want to toss everything away. But we will not give up.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, the Israeli army chief of staff said that he,
too, ``assessed the issue of negotiations has not stopped
entirely.'' While keeping close watch on the Palestinians, he urged
his troops to keep open channels to the Palestinian security forces
that could have ``an important effect on calming the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have given guidelines to the forces in the field,'' said
Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz, ``to conduct themselves in a responsible and
and restrained manner, with the presence of high-ranking officers
in the field, to prevent mistakes that could cause friction that
could lead to one kind of outburst or another. I hope that this is
also what is happening on the Palestinian side.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the army has distributed additional
weapons, including machine guns and sniper rifles to increase the
arsenals already maintained by the sometimes volatile settlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come for the settlements themselves to gird their
loins and mobilize as one in carrying out security,'' the commander
of the Samaria Brigade, Col. Yehuda Shaked, wrote in a letter to
the 32 settlements in his district. They would be called for
additional training as communications operators, medics and machine
gunners he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaked also said in his letter that the tiny number of settlers
who had been banned from carrying weapons because of extremist or
criminal behavior shoud now reapply for permits because the
criteria for distributing arms had been eased.
</P>
<P>
   A group of rabbis in the settlements is preparing to issue a
religious ruling on when it is permissible to open fire if
Palestinians march on their homes. Another group of rabbis has
already issued a ruling saying it is permissible to desecrate the
Sabath by shooting at people approaching a settlement, even if one
is not sure of their intentions, because they might cause the death
of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Barak is home, his immediate problem is assembling a
new governing coalition. He now has only a minority of 42 seats in
the 120-member parliament, or Knesset, after the walkout by Shas,
the party of Sephardic Jews , the orthodox National Religious Party
and Natan Sharansky's party of recent Russian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Knesset is to debate two motions of no
confidence in the prime minister on Monday. One was introduced,
predictably enough, by the opposition Likud party saying his
negotiating position has endangered Israeli interests, including
Jerusalem. The other motion was submitted by the United Arab List
saying he had estranged himself from Palestinian rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
