<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-CORPORATION-A     07-26 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-CORPORATION-ART-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NONPROFIT THEATER RISES FROM BASEMENT TO NEW TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT4 and NYT5 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK ] Not so long ago the nonprofit Roundabout Theater
Company was performing plays for 150 people in a supermarket
basement on West 26th Street where a scene from Ibsen or Shaw might
well be accompanied by the sound of rolling meat carts rumbling
through the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the company will open its first show _ a revival of
``The Man Who Came to Dinner'' _ in its elegant new 750-seat
theater, the once-crumbling Selwyn on West 42nd Street, transformed
at a cost of $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   The showplace was named the American Airlines Theater in
exchange for an $8.5 million payment from American. Patrons who
contribute $1,500 or more to the Roundabout each year can relax
befkre the show over cocktails and Oreo cookies in the Nabisco
lounge (so named in exchange for $500,000). The rest of the
theater's subscribers can catch the sunset from the balcony of the
new penthouse lobby (name still for sale at $1.5 million).
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout, which produces seven shows each season, has
built its subscriber base to 46,000 from 17,000 in 1983 through
customer-friendly programs like wine tastijgs and early-bird
curtain times, and a sophisticated fund-raising operation in which
20 to 30 people work the phones to generate new subscriptions,
renewals and outright contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The theater spent $60,000 last year on lobbying the city and the
state, more than the Metropolitan Museum of Art, which spent
$49,000. When the Selwyn was not finished in time for ``Uncle
Vanya'' to go in as planned last spring, the Roundabout placed the
play in Broadway's Brooks Atkinson Theater at a cost of about $1.5
million, a figure that by itself is more than the annual budget of
most nonprofit theaters. The artistic director, Todd Haimes, earns
an annual salary of $275,000.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, the journey of this one nonprofit theater _ from
basement to Broadway, from bankruptcy to becoming the country's
second-largest nonprofit theater with an annual budget of $20
million _ stands as a powerful example of how much the world of
nonprofit theater has changed.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``almost a metaphor for the progress of the not-for-profit
theater,'' said Bernard Gersten, executive producer of Lincoln
Center Theater, the largest nonprofit, with a budget of about $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time that the New York Shakespeare Festival in 1971
took its first play to Broadway _ for the past 29 years _ there has
been an evolution that's been marked by the invasion of the
for-profit theater by the not-for-profit theater,'' Gersten
continued. ``I view it as irrevocable, irresistible, inevitable and
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is as enthusiastic about some of the qualities of
the Roundabout's success, epitomized by its new theater in the
heart of the new Times Square. Several commercial producgrs resent
that the theater's productions are eligible for Tony Awards (tley
have won 13) without having the financial burdeos of repaying
investors or paying the labor costs required under Broadway union
contracts. And some nonprofit stalwarts cuggest that, by peddling
naming rights in its theater to corporations and 0erforming
palatable Broadway fare, the Roundabout has sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be an unpredictable, dangerous energy in the
air,'' said Jim Niesen, who worked for the Zoundabout as a stage
manager 20 years ago and left to start his own experimental theater
company, the Irondale Ensemble Project. ``Now it's so
cookie-cutter.''
</P>
<P>
   Haimes, who has led the Roundabout since 1983, makes(no
apologies for his theater's growth. ``As you get bigger, perhaps
you have to leave the highly experimental prkductions behind for
smaller companies to do, and that, I guess, is an institutional
loss,'' he said. ``But I think it's a loss that's far outweighed by
having the resources to do first-class productions of classics and
musicals on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it seems that most of the Roundabout's nonprofit peers
_ and a few commercial ones as well _ appnaud the Roundabout's
success as good for the city and the theater overall. ``The demand
is large enough that they need a Broadway theater,'' said Neil
Pepe, artistic director of the Atlantic Theater Company. ``It's
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Where nonprofit theaters like the Wooster Group and LaMaMa ETC
have emphasized experimental work, the Roundabout has always
defined its mission as staging revivals, often of the classics.
Over |he years, that repertoire has expanded from the works of
Ibsen, Shaw and Strindberg to contemporary work by Arthur Miller,
Brian Friel and Harold Pinter as well as musicals.
</P>
<P>
   The last few years have been particularly successful ones for
the company, with the theater winning Tony Awards for ``Anna
Christie'' in 1993, ``She Loves Me'' in 1994, ``A View From the
Bridge'' and ``Cabaret'' in 1998, and ``Little Me'' and ``Side
Man'' in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's show _ a revival of the Kaufman and Hart comedy
that stars Nathan Lane and Jean Smart under the direction of Jerry
Zaks _ is consistent with the Roundabout's history. And while it
may seem like a safe choice, Haimes said it was actually risky to
do a play with 29 actors (musicals with large casts appeal to more
people and are therefore considered less of a gamble).
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Roundabout's defenders say, the company does the
kinds of classics and musicals that Broadway would shy away from,
like Chekhov's ``Uncle Vanya'' and ``Little Me,'' which starred
Martin Short in the role originated by Sid Caesar.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the plays they're producing won't be produced in the
commercial theater anymore _ can't be produced according to
producers,'' said Roche Schulfer, executive director of the
nonprofit Goodman Theater, which is about to build a $44 million
theater complex in downtown Chicago. ``When Broadway starts doing
what the Roundabout is doing, then they can say the Roundabout is
becoming crassly commercial. But at this point, I don't see that
happening.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While some commercial producers criticize the Roundabout for
becoming too much like Broadway _ Rocco Landesman, president of
Jujamcyn Theaters, recently wrote that Haimes ``has had a more
pernicious influence on English-speaking theater than anyone since
Oliver Cromwell'' _ other producers say they need nonprofits to
take the chances they cannot afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two worlds are irrevocably interconnected and
interdependent and I think for the good,'' said David Richenthal, a
Broadway producer who brought the hit revival of ``Death of a
Salesman'' to Broadway last season from the Goodman. ``I haven't
done a commercial production that doesn't have some nexis with one
or more not-for-profits. I don't see anything noxious about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout has accepted increasingly popular ``enhancement''
money, which is controversial within the nonprofit world.
Enhancement money is contributed to nonprofit productions by
commercial producers who want to test their potential for future
commercial runs. For its production of ``Cabaret,'' Haimes said,
the Roundabout received enhancement money from SFX Theatrical in
exchange for the right to own the tour. ``We wanted that because
the costs were so huge,'' said Haimes, who added that SFX had no
creative role in the show. ``Cabaret'' has cost the Roundabout a
total of $4 million to stage.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer figures that the Roundabout deals in these days could
hardly have been imagined earlier in its troubled life. ``If you
had placed money on the next theater that might fold in the 1980s,
it would have been the Roundabout,'' said Ben Cameron, executive
director of the Theater Communications Group, a support
organization for nonprofit theaters. Founded by Gene Feist in 1965,
the theater declared bankruptcy in 1978 and voted to close down in
1983. It moved from the supermarket, now a Food Emporium, to what
became a movie theater in Chelsea to a former union hall in Union
Square to the Criterion Center on Broadway and 45th Street, where
it first became Tony eligible because of location. It was served
with an eviction notice at the Criterion just as Haimes decided on
the Selwyn.
</P>
<P>
   Although Haimes is clearly proud of the progress, he is also
anxious about sustaining the high expectations, he said. ``I think
about how much money this theater has to generate on a weekly basis
to break even,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That would be about $400,000 per week, according to Ellen
Richard, the Roundabout's managing director since 1984. When Haimes
first came on board in 1983, the break-even figure was $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout raises 25 percent of its budget in contributions.
To build its new theater, Haimes said the Roundabout received $9
million from the city and more than $1 million from the state
</P>
<P>
   ``If our subscriptions went down from 45,000 to 30,000, it would
be devastating,'' Haimes said. His next goal is to build up the
endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Haimes said corporate arrangements like his with American
Airlines, which is spread out over 10 years, helped ward off
financial insecurity. ``As long as the corporation is not
interested in affecting the artistic decisions,'' he said, ``I'm
happy to have their name on the lounge or on the building.''
</P>
<P>
   With government money far harder to come by than it was a few
years ago and costs continually rising, arts institutions like the
Roundabout have no choice but to tap new resources, some nonprofit
executives say. ``It's the next logical step,'' Cameron said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are those who are troubled by corporate
labeling in nonprofit cultural venues in particular, saying it
creates the appearance that a theater is presenting shows in some
substantial part to serve the commercial purpose of a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many nonprofit and commercial theater
professionals who attribute criticism of the Roundabout to envy.
``It's too easy to point the finger at them; it's motivated by
jealousy,'' said David Herskovits, the artistic director of Target
Margin, an off-Broadway theater company with an annual budget of
$300,000. ``We are all engaged in commerce all the time. We're all
concerned about getting bucks into the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, nonprofit executives say, their nonprofit roots have
been romanticized, as if they must continually struggle financially
to remain true to their origins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the process of life _ you leave your little one-bedroom
and you buy a house and people say you betrayed the fact that you
were once a hippie,'' said Gordon Edelstein, the artistic director
of A Contemporary Theater (ACT), which recently built a $32 million
complex in Seattle. ``Just as it's our children's job to keep us
honest and to be rebellious, it's the job of smaller, funky
theaters to carry on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
