<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3984 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CHENEY-OIL-ART-2TAKES     07-26 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-OIL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING THE GULF WAR PREPARED CHENEY WELL FOR THE OIL BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also CHENEY-SANCTIONS) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 This article was reported by LESLIE WAYNE, RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr. and
JAMES RISEN and written by RISEN.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four years after helping to win the Persian Gulf
war and liberating the oil fields of Kuwait, former Secretary of
Defense Dick Cheney went from fighting for oil to running a
Dallas-based firm that he has helped transform into the world's
largest oil field services company.
</P>
<P>
   As chief executive of Halliburton Co. since 1995, Cheney has
been able to rely heavily on the high-level contacts in the Middle
East he made as defense secretary to win business in the roughneck
world of international oil.
</P>
<P>
   And now, as he re-emerges from the business world to become the
running mate of likely Republican presidential nominee George W.
Bush, Cheney's corporate experience has made clear the Republican
ticket's roots in the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the firm in 1995, Cheney's background as a leader
in the gulf war has seemed tailor made for Halliburton, since much
of its business is done with Arab governments. Almost 70 percent of
Halliburton's nearly $15 billion in annual sales come from
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney quickly established himself as Halliburton's outside man,
a globetrotting rainmaker, while his deputy and now successor,
David Lesar, handled internal operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney could go to the Middle East, he had a reputation there,
and most CEO's don't have that,'' said David Gribbin, a longtime
friend of Cheney who now serves as Halliburton's vice president of
government affairs in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Adelman, a former Reagan administration official and
longtime Cheney friend, agreed that ``Halliburton played to his
strengths, which were contacts in the Arab world and dealing with
governments.''
</P>
<P>
   Under his leadership, the value of the company's stock has
fluctuated dramatically. In August 1995, when he arrived, it was
trading at around $21 a share. Within two years, the value had
nearly tripled but more recently has fallen back, closing Wednesday
at 43 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was a surprise choice when he was named chief executive
of Halliburton, since he had virtually no experience in the
business world and had not held a full-time job since leaving the
Pentagon. In 1993 and 1994, Cheney had spent his time giving
speeches, joining corporate boards, and campaigning for Republican
candidates while he decided whether to run for president himself.
</P>
<P>
   But by early 1995, Cheney had decided against a presidential
bid, and began considering his next move. The business world,
largely unknown to Cheney, became ``a more attractive option after
he gave up on running for president,'' recalled Sean O'Keefe, who
served as secretary of the Navy during the Bush administration and
remains close to Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity came in the kind of power-networking event that
is so typical in corporate America today: a fly-fishing trip with
Halliburton chairman Thomas Cruikshank, who came away impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after Cruikshank decided to retire and was disenchanted
with the list of his possible successors drawn up by a Halliburton
search committee, he began pushing Cheney for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was instant backing for Dick when his name was brought
to our attention,'' said Anne Armstrong, former ambassador to
England in the Ford administration and then a member of the
Halliburton board. ``We all wondered why we hadn't thought of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several friends and business associates said they do not know of
any role former President Bush played in helping Cheney obtain the
post at Halliburton.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Staubach, the former Dallas Cowboys quarterback who was a
member of Halliburton's board at the time of the selection, said
that Cheney's history of heart problems were ``not an issue anyone
worried about,'' although it was ``brought up in passing'' by the
board.
</P>
<P>
   Appointed chief executive of Halliburton in August 1995, Cheney
took over a company that analysts said was trying to adapt to big
changes in the oil industry, including a collapse in oil prices in
the late 1990s that dampened exploration.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100,000 employees, Halliburton's main business is
to provide oil producers with the technology and equipment to find,
drill for, and pump oil out of the ground, including everything
from sophisticated computer software that helps locate underground
oil fields to drill bits and pressure pumping systems.
</P>
<P>
   Its customers include the world's largest oil producers as well
as oil-producing nations. It also has large engineering and
construction businesses, and has pursued other lines of business,
such as construction work for the U.S. military abroad, including
logistical support to U.S. forces in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving at Halliburton, Cheney has sprinkled the company
with a few longtime, loyal aides.
</P>
<P>
   Gribbin, a high school friend from Wyoming who had worked for
Cheney in Congress and at the Pentagon, is now vice president of
government affairs in Halliburton's Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Adm. Joe Lopez, who was Cheney's military aide while he
was secretary of defense, is now chief operating officer of Brown
and Root Services, a Halliburton subsidiary that has government
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's most important move at Halliburton was to orchestrate
the 1998 acquisition of one of its largest competitors, Dresser
Industries. Overnight, the merger made Halliburton the largest oil
services firm in the world, moving past France's Schlumberger.
</P>
<P>
   According to Staubach, the company had kicked around the idea of
buying Dresser before Cheney's arrival, but ``he definitely
reignited it. He brought it back as a real opportunity when he was
CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Dresser deal has received mixed reviews from industry
analysts. The merger took place at time when oil producers,
Halliburton's main customers, were facing declining oil prices and
were trimming their spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had what then seemed to be a brilliant deal with the
merger of Dresser, which made a lot of sense in a lot of ways,''
said Arvind S. Sanger, an industry analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette. But ``the cycle turned down viciously for the oil
services group.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like other big oil companies, Halliburton does business in some
of the roughest parts of the Third World, providing oil services in
the Caspian region in Central Asia, the North Sea, offshore fields
in West Africa, the Middle East, Venezuela, and now Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over the firm, Cheney has sharply increased its
reliance on international operations. Since 1994, the year before
Cheney became chief executive, the percentage of Halliburton's
revenues from domestic operations fell from about 59 percent to
just 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company's most recent annual report said that it did
business in more than 120 companies; the report did not list all of
the nations, although it noted that Halliburton operated in such
politically unstable nations as Algeria, Angola, Nigeria and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's role as the chief executive of a multinational oil firm
has given him the chance over the past few years to weigh in on
controversial foreign policy issues. At the top of his list has
been ending the use of trade sanctions as a tool of American
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at an oil industry conference in Canada last month,
Cheney called for the lifting of U.S. sanctions on Iran,
</P>
<P>
   He called relations between Iran and the United States a
``tragedy,'' adding that one of the best ways to improve ties with
Iran would be ``to allow American firms to do the same thing that
most other firms around the world are able to do now, and that is
to be active in Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kept out of there primarily by our own government, which
has made a decision that U.S. firms should not be allowed to invest
significantly in Iran, and I think that's a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Cheney, Halliburton has become one of the leading
corporate members of USA Engage, a lobbying group that seeks to
lift sanctions. Halliburton is also member of the board of the
National Foreign Trade Council, a lobbying group that recently won
a victory in the Supreme Court, which struck down a Massachusetts
state law imposing state-level sanctions on companies doing
business in Myanmar, the former Burma.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's company has already done business in countries still
facing American sanctions, including Libya and Iraq, the enemy
Cheney helped vanquish during the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Dresser-Rand and Ingersoll-Dresser Pump Co., joint ventures that
Halliburton has sold within the past year, have done work in Iraq
on contracts for the reconstruction of Iraq's oil industry, under
the United Nation's ``oil for food'' program. That program exempts
some Iraqi oil sales from U.N. sanctions as long as the proceeds
are used to pay for food and medicine for the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Halliburton's Brown and Root construction services
subsidiary has been the project manager for a massive irrigation
pipeline project in Libya for the government of Col. Moammar
Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   The work is done through European subsidiaries that were already
operating in Libya when U.S. sanctions were established, and so
were grandfathered in.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Cheney arrived at Halliburton, the firm also settled
a longstanding investigation by the Commerce Department concerning
exports of U.S.-produced oil field equipment to Libya.
</P>
<P>
   In the July 1995 consent agreement, Halliburton agreed to pay a
$2.6 million fine for selling oil field equipment through Italy or
Kuwait to Libya without required export licenses, and for selling
U.S. spare parts for logging equipment through Italy to Libya
without proper licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton and other oil service firms have faced consistent
criticism from environmental groups and a wide range of domestic
regulatory issues as well. One environmental issue it is fighting
now is a move to prevent ``hydraulic fracturing,'' a procedure that
opens underground chambers to make it easier to get to oil or
natural gas. An environmental group has been fighting the oil
industry on the matter in Alabama, where it is now tied up in the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has said that he will take a financial ``bath'' by giving
up his lucrative post at Halliburton to run for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he earned nearly $1.3 million in salary, and
documents filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission show
that Cheney owns nearly 1.1 million shares of Halliburton,
including 860,000 options to purchase Halliburton shares at a
reduced price.
</P>
<P>
   The market value of this package is around $43 million, based on
today's stock price of Halliburton shares.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney would get somewhat less than that depending on the
financial terms of the options he holds.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999 alone, he was granted 300,000 options, which the company
estimated in an SEC filing would be worth between $7.5 million and
$18.9 million, depending on how Halliburton's stock does over the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
   In May, when Halliburton's stock was trading near a 52-week
high, Cheney dipped into his Halliburton holdings and sold 100,000
shares at $50.97 a share, netting him nearly $5.1 million. He sold
the shares just before Halliburton's stock began to tumble to its
current trading range of around $40 a share.
</P>
<P>
   As vice president, Cheney would earn $181,400 a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
