<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FUNDS-MARKETPLACE-NYT     07-26 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: EXCHANGE-TRADED FUNDS GAINING GROUND WITH INVESTORS 

</HEADLINE>
   By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Exchange-traded funds are gaining favor among investors and may
soon evolve into a viable alternative to a broad range of
traditional mutual funds, two new reports predict.
</P>
<P>
   Exchange-traded funds, or ETFs, are investment pools that are
similar to mutual funds but trade like stocks, and have been around
since 1993. Perhaps the best known is called the Spider, which
represents the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index. But this year
their ranks have swelled to 59 offerings from 30, all of which
trade on the American Stock Exchange. While the stock market
treaded water in the first six months, the assets of the ETF. group
nearly doubled, to $52.6 billion from $35.8 billion, according to
Strategic Insight, a New York fund consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   While that is a speck compared with the $7 trillion mutual fund
industry, Strategic Insight's report and a report from the
Financial Research Corp., a Boston consulting firm, see much growth
from the expected introduction of actively managed versions of the
funds. So far, investors buy a set pool of stocks, either based on
an index or some predetermined industry list.
</P>
<P>
   Both reports see the funds shaping up as a logical area of
expansion for mutual fund companies but less likely to drain money
out of mutual funds than out of individual stock portfolios. ``This
is a real product with distinctive advantages,'' said Avi Nachmany,
president of Strategic Insight. ``Everyone is trying to figure out
how it works.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the only major mutual fund company to enter the
business is the Vanguard Group, of Malvern, Pa. Vanguard, the
nation's largest manager of index mutual funds, recently filed with
regulators to add exchange-traded versions of five of its index
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the actively managed ones, as opposed to the index
products, are going to a more significant degree cannibalize
traditional mutual funds,'' said Burton Greenwald, a mutual fund
industry consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that you can get them at attractive prices,'' he
said, ``trade them and avoid built-in tax liabilities of
traditional funds will cause a significant number of shareholders
to opt out of traditional funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Nachmany predicts that actively managed versions of the funds
will be available in one or two years. A survey of industry experts
by Financial Research sees 2002 as a more likely target, and
forecasts that ETF assets will hit $500 billion to $1 trillion by
2007.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are actively pursuing the research and development of
actively managed ETF products,'' said Lee T. Kranefuss, an
executive who oversees the funds for Barclays Global Investors, the
Barclays PLC unit that manages index funds for institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The American Stock Exchange also is ``exploring rather
aggressively'' an actively managed version of the funds, according
to Robert Pendine, a spokesman. ``We're looking at the near term,
the next 18 to 24 months.''
</P>
<P>
   What difference would this make to the average investor? The
Strategic Insight report points out that fees on the traded funds
tend to be lower than on mutual funds, and that they can be traded
throughout the day. The traded funds also forgo much of the taxable
capital gains distributed to investors in mutual funds, though
Nachmany cautions that these tax advantages might come under
scrutiny from the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there are three varieties of exchange-traded funds.
Spiders, or Standard &AMP; Poors Depository Receipts, were created by
Amex, a unit of Nasdaq, and State Street Global Advisors. Spiders
are unit investment trusts, which do not have a board and are
prohibited from using futures and options.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays iShares are mutual funds, have boards and can reinvest
dividends more frequently than investment trusts. The third type is
Merrill Lynch's HOLDRs, baskets of stocks that are not tied to a
changing index, but which can be exchanged for the underlying
securities.
</P>
<P>
   Sorting out the varieties will get more confusing. Barclays has
46 traded funds that track indexes as basic as the S&AMP;P 500 and as
esoteric as a Malaysian index, and it is adding 10 iShare varieties
on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
