u a BC-COLO-FIRES-ARCHAEOLOG     07-26 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-FIRES-ARCHAEOLOGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS UNEARTH ANASAZI ARTIFACTS A STEP AHEAD OF FIREFIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORTEZ, Colo. _ Even the darkest clouds have a silver lining,
and Mesa Verde National Park officials are clinging to such
optimism as firefighters struggle to contain a wildfire that has
burned 23,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be redefining what Mesa Verde means,'' the
park's public affairs officer, Will Morris, said. ``We will have to
reconsider the way we approach natural and cultural resources.
There may be a silver lining in archaeological finds to this really
dark cloud.''
</P>
<P>
   As the fire has raced through the park, archaeologists have
scrambled ahead of it, working to identify previously undiscovered
ancient native American sites. By Wednesday, at least a dozen new
ones had been found.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the archaeologists are working just ahead of crews
building fire lines, trying to prevent a false step or stray swing
of a pickax from crushing a bit of antiquity. The scientists fear
that both the flames and the firefighters may destroy vital
artifacts before the fire is tamed. Usually, they have had time
only to mark the sites on a map or in the field. Sometimes, they
help dig fire breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the time to be doing any kind of extensive
study,'' Linda Towle, Mesa Verde's chief archaeologist, told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists said they will try to return and study the sites,
hoping they uncover more insight into the lives of early
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa Verde is best known for being home to the largest preserved
Anasazi cliff dwellings in the country, and is the only national
park devoted solely to protecting cultural remains. About 800 years
ago, ancestors of the Apache, Navajo, Hopi and Pueblo tribes,
farmed the land and built their homes in what is now southwestern
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The wildfire, which has burned about a third of the park, was 25
percent contained by Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Rain and winds the night before helped extinguish some hot
spots, but also made some areas flare up.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the fire, the value of the park and its proximity to
the communities around it have made it a priority, said Justin
Dombrowski, information officer with the Rocky Mountain Incident
Command Team, which is overseeing the operation. Wildfires have
consumed more than 100,000 acres west of the Rocky Mountains this
year, and the season is shaping up to be one of the worst in five
years. Crews, equipment and other resources were stretched so thin
that fire managers will organize and train military crews to help.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, the cost of fighting the large fires burning in
the West was $26.3 million, according to the National Interagency
Fire Center in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, the 52,000-acre park is surrounded by private land,
Bureau of Land Management areas and the Ute Mountain Ute
Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   The fire is believed to have started last Thursday after a
lightning strike on private land.
</P>
<P>
   As they work, archaeologists at Mesa Verde are aware that they
have been through this at least once before. After a 5,000-acre
fire in 1996, archaeologists discovered 400 previously unknown
archaeological sites to add to 4,000 known sites.
</P>
<P>
   Those sites provide more insight into the lives of the early
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned they were controlling water more than we thought,
and that they were here for a lot longer time than we thought,''
said Julie Bell, an archaeologist at the park.
</P>
<P>
   They also have discovered that the area might have been more
populated than previously thought. For example, Battleship Rock, a
significant petroglyph (rock drawings) site was largely burned in
1996. But with the surrounding brush and trees gone, archaeologists
found evidence of a larger community around the rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mesa Verde is famous for its cliff dwellings _ Cliff Palace,
Balcony House _ and that's only one small part of it,'' Bell said.
``Those were built in the last 100 years of 800 years of
occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   Four more cliff dwellings were found after the 1996 fires, but
they were small storage units, not as impressive as the large
apartment structures. Archaeologists also found earlier homes _
pithouses that were built in holes, remnants of stonewalls and one
wall that was about four-feet tall, and ancient trash piles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double-edged sword,'' Bell said of the post-fire
discoveries. ``The fire will uncover a lot of more sites, but the
after effects of the fire are going to threaten all of the sites
because if we don't have the vegetation to stop the water, runoff
erosion is going to be a huge problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell was one of 18 archaeologists who worked ahead of fire crews
this week, trying to avoid potentially important sites as they dug
fire lines.
</P>
<P>
   As thunderstorms rolled in Wednesday afternoon, again providing
a chance for cooler temperatures and more humidity, talk turned to
when the park might reopen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next process and goal is to open the park,'' said Larry
Wiese, the park superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   And although it appeared by late Wednesday that the park's crown
jewel cliff dwellings would not be touched by the fire, experts
said the resources were invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our living legacy for many, many generations to
come,'' a park archaeologist, Faith Duncan, said with a backdrop of
a ceremonial kiva and charred hills beyond. ``I look at it as an
American thing so we can show the rest of the world about
preservation and caring for a finite resource.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
