u i BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      07-26 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMP DAVID: FRESH FOCUS ON THE PRICE OF PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the inconclusive conclusion of the Camp David
summit meeting on Tuesday, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel may
not have won a peace agreement, but he did win the presidential
award for best camper. President Clinton concluded the meeting by
asserting that Barak was more creative, flexible and determined to
reach a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, in the event that Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, is compelled to fulfill his pledge to declare a state in
September, he may find himself with less international sympathy and
financial aid than he may have hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   If that creates new pressure on Arafat, then this would be a
canny achievement for Barak, who pushed for the meeting, which
Arafat considered premature.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Arafat has been the peripatetic Palestine Liberation
Organization chairman, traveling from capital to capital in pursuit
of legitimacy and backing. During the rightist Israeli
administration of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, he found
particular success, especially in nurturing a relationship with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During those three years, Israel developed the taint of a
somewhat outlaw state for not climbing aboard the peace platform,
or at least not with proper enthusiasm and good intentions. While
Palestinians perceived that the Americans were always on Israel's
side first, Arafat made considerable headway in tugging the gorilla
superpower closer to his viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   When Barak took office a year ago, he immediately took to the
skies himself, assiduously working to tilt world opinion back
toward Israel. He courted the English, the Germans, the French, but
especially the Americans. It was last July that he spent his first
late night chatting at Camp David with Clinton, scouting out the
retreat to which he fully intended to return as a peacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   And this week, his advisers say, he believes that he capped his
mission to make Israel seem the more reasonable party in the peace
effort, perhaps even bolstering Israel's strategic ties with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The summit meeting consciously mimicked the Israeli-Egyptian one
that took place 22 years ago at Camp David. Then, the Israelis and
the Egyptians defied all expectations by emerging with the first
Israeli-Arab peace agreement. With that perspective, some thought
that the unthinkable could happen this time, too, that the Israelis
and the Palestinians could really sort it all out.
</P>
<P>
   But everything in this seven-year incremental process has taken
time, inching forward and slipping back. And maybe, in the best of
lights, however long it takes to get back to the negotiating table,
Camp David will have served well the cause of peace. Maybe both
sides needed to walk away empty-handed in order to set the stage
for the future.
</P>
<P>
   During this Camp David meeting, for the first time, ordinary
Israelis and Palestinians focused on what might be the price of
peace.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, the previously taboo idea of reconstituting _ that
is, dividing _ Jerusalem got a full airing. Barak, who as Clinton
noted is the most decorated soldier in Israeli history, gave his
``Mr. Security'' persona a full workout.
</P>
<P>
   In the name of making peace to ensure Israel's security, he
entertained a sizable transfer of West Bank territory (from 88 to
95 percent), the evacuation of settlements, a land swap, a small
resettlement plan for Palestinian refugees and the ceding of some
Jerusalem neighborhoods to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   This was a rapid-fire, neck-swiveling adjustment in the Israeli
boundaries of acceptable compromise. It was not enough for the
Palestinians, but it probably went to the absolute limits of what
Israeli public opinion could stomach. And judging by the polls
during the summit meeting, they were stomaching it, and maybe
months down the road their capacity for absorbing compromises could
expand further.
</P>
<P>
   Because of what Barak was willing to do, Arafat probably lost
ground in the eyes of the Americans and his relative standing in
the eyes of the European nations that have been bankrolling the
development of a Palestinian infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   But with his domestic support at a low, Arafat needed a big win
at home and in the Arab world, and he secured one. ``Arafat was
depicted perhaps as the bad boy of the talks, but his people will
increase their backing for him,'' Zohir Andreas, editor of an
Israeli Arabic weekly, wrote Wednesday. ``Arafat was not ready for
there to be a Palestinian uprising against himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Having never prepared public opinion for any concessions on
refugee rights or East Jerusalem, Arafat would not have been on
solid ground in making sudden shifts.
</P>
<P>
   But it would have been a real shock for the Palestinians if,
after all his unyielding statements, he succumbed in one sitting to
American and Israeli pressure to abandon his demands for the
Palestinian refugees' right of return and to accept less than full
sovereignty over East Jerusalem. As far as most Palestinians are
concerned, having conceded the land that is now Israel, they have
no wiggle room left. East Jerusalem is part of their national soul,
and the refugees are family.
</P>
<P>
   Now Arafat has the time to try to alter this perception. It is
believed that despite what he tells his people, he may be willing
to make some concessions on the refugee issue, provided that
international compensation and resettlement relieve him of the
burden of absorbing most of the refugees into the West Bank and
Gaza Strip. Would he be willing to acknowledge this, if it is true?
</P>
<P>
   It is very difficult to imagine Arafat as accepting limited
sovereignty in East Jerusalem, even as better than nothing. But
perhaps he could change his mind to consider deferring resolution
of the contested city's status, and find a way to secure Arab
backing for that decision.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way to interpret hopefully the failure at Camp
David. It assumes that talks will eventually resume. But the
Israeli prime minister is politically weak, the American president
is retiring, and the Palestinian leader is not getting any younger.
</P>
<P>
   The failure not only heartens the anti-peace camps in both
Israeli and the Palestinian world, but raises a question that even
doves will ask themselves: Is the peace process all process? Is
peace itself attainable or just a goal post at the end of a path
that will keep getting longer?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
