<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVIS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BEHIND LEVI'S NEW CAMPAIGN, HOPEFUL HAND-WRINGING 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems appropriate that an ambitious new campaign for Levi's
jeans carries the theme ``Make them your own'' because the ads are
most likely a make-or-break effort for the maker of the campaign,
if not also for the maker of the jeans.
</P>
<P>
   The multimillion-dollar campaign, which begins this week, is the
most recent in a series of multimedia blitzes for the jeans maker,
Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., by the San Francisco office of TBWA/Chiat/Day,
the agency that was rocked last week by the loss of its large Taco
Bell creative assignment. The initial efforts can be seen in a
52-page supplement to the August issue of Vogue magazine and on the
Web site www.levi.com.
</P>
<P>
   The previous campaigns for Levi's jeans from TBWA/Chiat/Day have
generally been dismissed as lacking in appeal to consumers 18 to
24, the core audience being courted so desperately by Levi Strauss
to return as customers. The weakness of the campaigns to date _
does anyone remember ``Opt. For the original,'' ``Calvin wore
them'' or ``Our models can beat up your models''? _ has been
exacerbated by the failure of Levi Strauss to produce apparel in
styles popular with younger shoppers. For example, so-called hard
jeans languished unsold on store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a serious slump in Levi Strauss sales, down
6.4 percent in the quarter ended on May 28 compared with sales in
the period a year earlier. In 1999, sales tumbled to $5.1 billion,
down 28.2 percent from a peak of $7.1 billion as recently as 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope the caliber of the work will be a heck of a lot higher
than where it has been,'' said Chuck McBride, executive creative
director at TWBA/Chiat/Day San Francisco, part of the TBWA
Worldwide unit of the Omnicom Group. He was interviewed on Tuesday
by telephone from London, where he was working on additional
commercials for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives close to the relationship between Levi
Strauss and the agency, TBWA/Chiat/Day San Francisco was on the
verge of being dismissed until McBride, using the agency's own
money, produced on his own a batch of commercials to demonstrate
how the ``Make them your own'' theme would work.
</P>
<P>
   McBride demurred at a suggestion that his unconventional tactic
had saved the account for TBWA/Chiat/Day. He offered two words with
a laugh, ``The beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What this brand needed was to hold still and do some great
work that would be consistent over time, so kids could sit down and
say: `Oh, so that's what it means to wear Levi's jeans,''' McBride
said, ``which I don't think a lot of young people necessarily
know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This proposition has really lit a fire under the
organization,'' he added, referring to the new theme.
</P>
<P>
   That assessment was echoed by Sean Dee, brand marketing director
for Levi's at Levi Strauss in San Francisco, who joined McBride for
the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've now got our chance to leverage the brand over time,''
Dee said. ``It's not about the company, but the people who wear the
pants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not about everybody being the same,'' he added,
taking a veiled dig at recent campaigns carrying the theme
``Everybody in . . .'' from a major competitor, Gap Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids want to be associated with brands that let them be
themselves,'' Dee said, ``so they can say `I can embrace them and
make them my own.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest difference is that we actually can now back up any
brand claims with the right products,'' he added. ``If you don't
hit that, it's just advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial television commercial in the campaign, titled
``Dressing Room,'' was shot on videotape, for a more realistic
look, by Spike Jonze, the hot young director of music videos and
movies. The spot resembles a voyeur's dream come to life:
Attractive young male and female models try on Levi's in front of a
dressing room mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our big challenge is to have things resonate with young people
but not alienate the 25-plus crowd,'' the traditional buyers of
Levi's jeans, Dee said. Tests showed that ``the work we've done
with Spike is unbelievably appealing to older consumers,'' he
added, as well as their younger counterparts. At least two other
commercials are planned, one for Levi's corduroys and the other for
Levi's 569 jeans.
</P>
<P>
   McBride's unusual save-the-account initiative also included the
production of offbeat commercials for a new product, known as
Levi's Engineered Jeans. The four spots manipulate still
photographs to produce an effect similar to strobe lights,
borrowing a technique used in performances by the Icelandic
musicians known as GusGus.
</P>
<P>
   Can the venerable Levi's brand be reinvigorated by the campaign?
Dee was sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy job,'' he said, ``but yes, we think we can do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, kids don't like Levi's,'' he added. ``They were more like
`Levi's are pretty cool but haven't done much for me lately.' This
is a great opportunity for us.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, he and McBride might join the Taco Bell Chihuahua in
wearing signs that proclaim ``Will Work for Food.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
