<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3991 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-ART-8     07-26 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-ART-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST-MINUTE ENGINE REPAIRS DELAYED CONCORDE TAKEOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GONESSE, France _ The Concorde that crashed into a hotel near
Charles de Gaulle Airport outside Paris on Tuesday, setting off a
fireball and killing 113 people, had been delayed from taking off
by last-minute repairs to the engine that burst into flames,
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials investigating the crash said they had not yet linked
the repairs to the crash. But on Tuesday they said that the engine
that caught fire as the supersonic jet began its takeoff, more than
an hour behind schedule, was the No. 2 engine.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday Air France officials said in a statement that
ground crews had unsuccessfully searched for spare parts for the
No. 2 engine and eventually repaired it with parts taken from
another Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   According to Elisabeth Senot, who is in charge of the judicial
investigation into the crash, it was the control tower that first
warned the captain that one of his engines was on fire, 56 seconds
after takeoff. In this scenario, the cockpit alarm system had not
given the pilot any warning.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, however, Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot
refused to confirm Senot's account that the control tower was the
first to alert the pilot of a problem.
</P>
<P>
   According to Senot, the pilot tried to direct the jet to the
smaller Le Bourget Airport nearby for an emergency landing. But the
airliner, unable to gain altitude, banked heavily to the left and
then slammed into a small wooden hotel here surrounded by fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can say that we are looking at a technical problem
here and can put aside notions of sabotage of any kind,'' Senot
said. She said she based her account on a preliminary review of the
information in the plane's ``black boxes,'' which record details of
the flight and have been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, roads leading to the crash site, about nine miles
northeast of Paris, were cordoned off by the police as workers
combed the singed fields, trying to identify bodies and locate
debris from the plane that could provide clues to the cause of the
crash. Everyone on board, mostly German tourists heading to New
York to board a luxury cruise, was killed. Four people in the hotel
also were killed and 12 others on the ground were injured, one
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Wreathes of flowers, placed by mourners, were laid around the
area. Bits of wreckage were scattered far and wide.
</P>
<P>
   Christianne Turpin, the owner of a Shell station 500 yards down
the road, had one blackened chunk tucked behind her cash register.
She said she had found it by her diesel pump. Turpin said she had
owned the gas station for 23 years and had never worried before
about being near an airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you I'm thinking about it now,'' she said. ``It
will be on my mind every day from now on. I don't think it will
ever go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Air France continued the indefinite grounding of its elegant,
needle-nosed jets, planes often used by celebrities willing to pay
about $11,000 to cross the Atlantic in 3 1/2 hours, half the time
of other commercial airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, however, British Airways _ the only other airline to
fly Concordes _ resumed its normal service Wednesday after getting
preliminary information from crash investigators in France and
conducting extensive technical checks of the fleet's engines,
hydraulic systems and airframes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there is no technical, safety or operational
evidence to suggest that Concorde should not operate safely in the
future,'' said Mike Fleet, a spokesman for British Air.
</P>
<P>
   But not all passengers were eager to get on the planes. Bill
Boster, a CNBC executive, told The Associated Press that he had
exchanged his ticket for a ride on a slower plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have total confidence in the engineers and the pilot of this
Concorde, but I just can't face it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Air France, in its statement, described a series of events
before the crash that led to the delay of flight AF4590. The
statement said that the pilot who landed the plane in Paris on
Monday reported that the jet's reverse thrusters, used to brake the
plane, were not functioning.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said that according to ``technical tolerance
authorized by the manufacturers'' the plane could have taken off
without being repaired. Under Federal Aviation Administration
regulations, which applied since the plane's intended destination
on Tuesday was New York, the Concorde had to be capable of landing
without thrust reversers in order to make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   But when the situation was reported to the plane's captain,
Christian Marty, he decided that he wanted the repairs made. At
that point, a replacement part for the plane was obtained from a
spare Concorde and installed within about 30 minutes. The plane was
also delayed by baggage handling problems, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   But it did not say whether the repairs could have been connected
to the crash, which occurred within minutes of the jet's 4:31 p.m.
takeoff.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The crash was a particular blow to French pride. The Concorde,
developed by the French and British in the 1960s, was the world's
first supersonic passenger jet in regular service. In more than 20
years of commercial flying, however uneconomical and however noisy,
a Concorde had never crashed.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac joined grieving victims for an
emotional memorial service in Gonesse late in the day. Families and
friends of the passengers, many of whom were retirees, wept and
held hands during the 30-minute service. Scores of townspeople also
gathered outside the service to show their support.
</P>
<P>
   At Charles de Gaulle Airport, Air France closed off a passenger
terminal usually used for charter flights to make bereavement
counseling available to the victim's friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder also attended a service
and said his nation was in shock over the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape televised on France's LCI news station, apparently
shot by a Spanish truck driver, showed that the left side of the
plane was engulfed in flames long before it even hit the ground.
But witnesses said they heard a series of explosions after the
crash and a huge plume of black smoke rose into the air.
</P>
<P>
   One of guests in the 40-room hotel, the Hotelissimo, managed to
escape with minor injuries by jumping from her first floor window.
</P>
<P>
   The guest, Alice Brookings, 21, a British student, said she
heard a noise growing louder and louder and then felt the whole
building shake as the plane hit the back side of the hotel. When
she opened her door, flames leapt into the room. The only way out
was the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very, very lucky,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, inspectors had found tiny cracks in more than
half of the 13 Concordes in service in both the French and the
British fleets. But the airline has already ruled out any link
between the crash and those cracks.
</P>
<P>
   French officials said they had opened at least two
investigations into the crash _ one the equivalent of a criminal
investigation, another the official accident investigation.
</P>
<P>
   At a late afternoon news conference, Gayssot said that officials
had not finished examining the plane's black boxes and would not
release any details until Thursday. But like Senot, he said the
investigation was focusing on the engine problems.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the news conference, Pierre Graff, the director general
of civil aviation, warned that the conclusions of the technical
investigation might not bear out the account given by Senot.
</P>
<P>
   Gayssot also said he wanted a series of meetings and technical
consultations before he would put the French Concordes back in
service. But he said the planes were far from ready for the scrap
heap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Concorde represents the technology of the future and of
modernity,'' he said. ``Supersonic technology is still the
technology of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-six of the passengers on board the Concorde were from
Germany _ 13 from the town of Moenchengladbach, on the border with
the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   The flight had been chartered by a German tour operator to take
the passengers to New York to join a 15-day cruise to the
Caribbean, through the Panama Canal and on to Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   There were also two Danes, one Austrian and one American. The
American was a retired Air France employee, but the company has not
yet released a name. The victims on the ground included two Polish
employees of the hotel, a British tourist and a French woman.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the day, authorities said they had recovered 105 bodies
from the site. But they said identifying them would be a long and
difficult process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
