<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3996 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEFENSE-CHENEY0727-CO     07-26 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFENSE-CHENEY0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheney known as take charge typeBy Gary Susswein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ During Dick Cheney's four years as Secretary of
Defense, the lifelong civilian made it clear to his military
subordinates that he was in charge of the armed forces and his word
would rule.
</P>
<P>
   When he wanted it to.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, the Wyoming Republican running for vice
president with Gov. George W. Bush left military matters up to the
military and allowed generals and admirals under his command to
work out policies.
</P>
<P>
   As public attention focuses on Cheney's record as Secretary of
Defense from 1989 to 1993, colleagues and Pentagon observers paint
a picture of a even-keeled and detail-oriented manager who helped
guide the American success in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   But the picture becomes less clear and sometimes-contradictory
when it comes to how much control Cheney exerted in the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The same man who fired the Air Force chief of staff as one of
his first moves and told General Colin Powell to butt out of policy
decisions also visited military bases and met with soldiers far
less than other defense secretaries and left some decisions about
military downsizing to politicians and generals.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, voters are likely to judge Cheney on the
United States' overwhelming victory in the Gulf War, rather than
his management style. ``The most important measure for any
secretary of defense is whether he succeeds in the ultimate test,''
said Edwin Dorn, dean of the Lyndon B. Johnson School of Public
Affairs and an Undersecretary of Defense under President Clinton.
``The war that Cheney had to preside over was the Gulf War and the
U.S. forces were wonderfully successful at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were obviously prepared and you have to credit the
civilian and military leaders for that,'' Dorn said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees on the amount of credit Cheney deserves. For
example, Lawrence Korb, a former assistant secretary of defense
under President Reagan, suggests that the Gulf War success came as
much from the Reagan-era military buildup as from Cheney's skills.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is widely credited for convincing Saudi Arabia to allow
American ground troops and war planes in their country, vital
elements to the U.S victory. He also lobbied within the Bush
Administration for a large military operation.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney took over at the Pentagon after former President Bush's
first choice for the job, former Texas Sen. John Tower, failed to
receive Senate confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week, Cheney fired Air Force Gen. Larry Welch for
privately negotiating with Congress to update the Air Forces'
nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He clearly did that merely to show he was in charge,'' Dorn
said. ``Larry was doing what every service chief does. Cheney knew
that, but he, I believe, wanted to send a message to the
services.''
</P>
<P>
   That message was understood by the time the United States
mobilized for the Gulf War. When Powell, chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, questioned the policy of going to war, Cheney
privately told him to ``stick to military matters,'' according to
Powell's 1995 memoir.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, Cheney was showing that he could be a
team-player and reach consensus with other foreign policy leaders _
including Powell.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a respect for each other that allowed them and us,
their assistants, to accomplish a lot,'' said Texas A&AMP;M chancellor
and retired-three star general Howard D. Graves, who was Powell's
assistant from 1989 to 1991. ``In times of conflict like the Gulf
War . . . there are immediate issues at hand so there's a sense of
immediate urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Gulf War, Cheney deferred to Congress on efforts to
increase the role of women in the armed forces and deferred to
military leaders, who opposed gays in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   With the Soviet threat gone, American officials also were
figuring out how to downsize the military. Cheney personally
cancelled a $57 million naval weapons program and oversaw 25
percent cuts in the armed services.
</P>
<P>
   But the long-time backer of a large military took the lead from
Congress in developing incentives for soldiers to retire early. And
he let Powell decide how much each branch of the military should be
cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He let the military control how the downsizing went,'' said
Korb, the Reagan-era assistant secretary of defense, who now works
at the New York-based Center for Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
   At least one old soldier interviewed Wednesday said that was a
wise move.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deferred to the military in their judgement,'' said Paul
Braim, a retired army colonel and professor emeritus of military
history at Embry-Riddle University in Florida, ``but he was the man
in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
