<HEADER>
A3998 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CHENEY_RECORD-HNS &LR;      07-26 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY_RECORD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY RECORD &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By BENNETT ROTH 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    Democrats tried to strip Republican vice presidential contender
<TEXT>
Dick Cheney of his moderate image Wednesday by launching an assault
on his congressional voting record _ a record Cheney defended as
one of which he is ``generally proud.''
<P>
   But Cheney also admitted there were votes he would ``tweak'' if
he had them to do over again.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush dismissed the
criticism of Cheney: ``I'm not surprised. To try to belittle the
pick _ typical.''
</P>
<P>
   While Democratic presidential contender Al Gore avoided
personally attacking Cheney's record, he stood beside the Rev.
Jesse Jackson in Chicago as Jackson warned that Cheney's moderate
image is undercut by the votes he cast while representing Wyoming
in the U.S. House from 1979 to 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick Cheney has an image that is palatable,'' Jackson said.
``Jesus warned us to be aware of wolves in sheep's clothing.''.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before members of his Rainbow/Push Coalition, Jackson
specifically cited Cheney's opposition to a resolution backing the
release of South African anti-apartheid leader Nelson Mandela from
jail.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also noted that Cheney had voted to cut funding for the
Head Start children's nutrition program, against the Equal Rights
Amendment and against economic sanctions against South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's criticism was clearly encouraged by the Gore campaign
and underscored their belief that Bush's choice of Cheney will
accomplish something that the Democratic candidate has been unable
to do so far: energize his base voters of women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   They contend that Cheney's conservative record will convince
these voters that Bush is not as moderate as his rhetoric has led
some voters to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made a brief reference to Bush's vice presidential pick,
suggesting that his rival was still relying on advice from his
father's generation. Cheney served as Defense secretary under
President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be absolutely no doubt that when the American people
go to the polls this November they will be choosing between two
very different visions for our people,'' Gore said. ``It is a
choice between the Old Guard that gave us deficits, divisions and
social injustice and a new vision of prosperity and progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also warned the mostly minority crowd that Republicans will
be attempting to show that they are an inclusive party at their
national convention that convenes July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have concocted a strategy of phrases and photo
opportunities to convey the impression of inclusion and
moderation,'' Gore said. ``I expect even more of it when the
Republicans gather in Philadelphia next week. I bet it's going to
be quite a show.''
</P>
<P>
   For their first joint appearance since Cheney was named as
Bush's running mate, the pair returned to Cheney's hometown of
Casper, Wyo., for a rally at his alma mater, Natrona County High
School.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief news conference on the tarmac at the local
airport, Bush and Cheney defended the running mate's voting record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously thought about the record,'' Bush said. ``This is a
conservative man. So am I. The thing that distinguishes Dick Cheney
is he can get along with others.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who served in the administration of Bush's father and
also served as President Ford's chief of staff, has considerably
more government experience than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It speaks volumes that I'm willing to pick somebody who is as
strong a man as he is, that I am comfortable having excellence by
my side,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said he was ``generally proud'' of his voting record. But
he declined to answer questions on specific votes, saying he would
have to review the circumstances of each vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure if I were to go back and look at individual votes I
could probably find something I might tweak and do a bit
differently,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He sometimes voted against bills because they increased federal
spending in a time of budget deficits, he said. He also voted
against economic sanctions against South Africa, he said, because
he opposes the concept of unilateral economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   To questions about whether the Bush-Cheney ticket is a ``big
oil'' ticket, Cheney said he is proud of his work with the
Halliburton Co., an international oil-field services firm based in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel any need to apologize for the way I've spent my
time over the last five years as the CEO and chairman of a major
American corporation,`` Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, Texas governor and a former oil man, said the attack is an
attempt to ``divert attention away from the fact they have no
energy policy'' in the administration of President Clinton and Vice
President Gore.
</P>
<P>
   As to questions about his health, Cheney said he has released
information from his cardiologist that says he is in good health
despite three heart attacks and bypass surgery more than a decade
ago. He said he has no plans to release any more medical records.
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming Gov. Jim Geringer referenced Cheney's heart while
introducing him to a crowd of 1,200 in the high school gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have Vice President Cheney with his heart than
President Gore with no backbone,'' said Geringer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the crowd that he and Cheney were westerners. And then
he poked at Clinton's denial that he had a sexual relationship with
an intern named Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West is a place where people understand what the meaning
of the word is is,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, this campaign is not just about campaigning,''
Bush said. ``It's about leading America.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was the class president in 1959 and his wife, Lynne, was
the homecoming queen. Cheney, who lives in Dallas, reclaimed his
Wyoming heritage last Friday by switching his voter registration.
</P>
<P>
   Calling their campaign a ``crusade,'' Cheney said victory is
essential to restoring pride in government to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX
</P>
