u p BC-GA-SENATE0727-COX     07-26 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SENATE0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's GOP's Senate pick uncertain
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt and Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Republican struggle to settle on a U.S. Senate
candidate continued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And while the field narrowed among possible candidates from
Congress, other Georgia Republicans appeared to be interested,
including state school Superintendent Linda Schrenko.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's eight congressional Republicans met for the second day
Wednesday afternoon without publicly announcing a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, one of the three most prominent choices, Rep. Saxby
Chambliss of Moultrie, said Wednesday he will not run for the
unexpired term of Sen. Paul Coverdell, who died last week.
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss announced his decision not to run on a tape-recorded
telephone answering machine message for all who called his Georgia
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I can do more for my state and country working for
the 8th District,'' he said. ``And I'm not about to walk away from
the district I cherish and the job I love.''
</P>
<P>
   A special election to fill the remaining four years of
Coverdell's term is scheduled for Nov. 7. Former Gov. Zell Miller
will be sworn in at 11 a.m. today to temporarily fill the seat to
which he was appointed Monday by Gov. Roy Barnes. Miller plans to
seek election to the remainder of the term. Reps. Bob Barr and Jack
Kingston were said to be considering a challenge to Miller.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders had feared House seats held by Chambliss and other
Georgia Republicans could become vulnerable to Democrats if they
stepped down to run for the Senate, thus jeopardizing the
Republicans' slim five-seat House majority.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgians also must weigh leaving reasonably safe House
seats to run against a heavily favored Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Schrenko said Wednesday she is seriously
considering a run. National Republican leaders have encouraged her,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Zell Miller, and he's always been good to me,''
Schrenko said. ``But I believe Paul Coverdell would have wanted
that seat to stay Republican. I think Paul would literally roll
over in his grave'' if his seat changes party without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Schrenko's stature increased last week as her vocal opposition
to Barnes' education reform plan, and her work against those who
supported it, helped unseat three legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Others discussed if the congressmen opt out are former Sen. Mack
Mattingly, state Sen. Sonny Perdue, former state Sens. David
Ralston and Clay Land, House Minority Leader Bob Irvin and state
party Chairman Chuck Clay.
</P>
<P>
   A decision must come within days, state GOP leaders acknowledge.
Candidate qualifying for the race will open Wednesday, but
Republicans leave at the end of this week for their national
convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would certainly like to go to Philadelphia with a pretty
good candidate in tow,'' said Clay. ``We need to get that person up
there and showcase'' him to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans continue to assess their options today, Miller
will take his seat in the Senate, fulfilling a boyhood dream. But
as he departed Atlanta on Wednesday, Miller said he did so with no
great anticipation. ``I just wish that it were Paul Coverdell
getting on this plane instead of me,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller will take the oath of office from Senate President Pro
Tem Strom Thurmond (R-S.C.) in a ceremony shown live on C-SPAN 2.
Miller is expected to address the Senate briefly.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a short week in Washington for the two-term governor,
who left office two years ago as one of Georgia's most popular
leaders ever. After Friday's session, the Senate recesses through
Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
