u p BC-CHENEY-SANCTIONS-NYT     07-26 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-SANCTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVER THE YEARS, CHENEY OPPOSED U.S. SANCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During his early years as a White House official
and member of the House, Dick Cheney, the expected Republican vice
presidential candidate, consistently opposed unilateral U.S.
sanctions against nations including Iran, Cuba and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, as the chief executive of the Halliburton Co., an
energy services company that is in the top 100 U.S. concerns in
revenues, Cheney became a lobbyist for lifting most sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to ``my favorite hobbyhorse, the question of
unilateral sanctions,'' Cheney argued in a 1998 speech that ``they
almost never work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard to find specific examples where they actually
achieve a policy objective,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a new official in the Ford White House in 1974, Cheney saw
the U.S. government, under pressure from Congress, impose sanctions
against Turkey over Cyprus. The action came not because it made
sense from a policy standpoint, Cheney said, but ``because the
Greek-American lobby was significantly bigger and more effective''
than its Turkish-American counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, while serving in the House, Cheney twice voted
to oppose sanctions against the apartheid government of South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, as Congress moved twice to increase sanctions
against Cuba, Cheney said, he would have preferred setting up a
West Berlin-type enclave of democracy and free enterprise at the
U.S. naval base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney did back the multilateral sanctions against Iraq
after the Persian Gulf war, which were aimed at curbing Iraq's
production of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   After he became chief executive of Halliburton, Cheney joined
other members of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and pro-trade groups
under the rubric of USA Engage. The lobby led a failing effort to
block the Iran and Libya Sanctions Act, which bars American
investment in those oil-rich countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our government has become sanctions-happy,'' Cheney said in
his 1998 speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
