<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4007 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUSIC-BLUEGRASS-MONRO     07-26 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BLUEGRASS-MONROE-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By TONY SCHERMAN    c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   So closely is
the late Bill Monroe identified with his musical creation,
bluegrass, that it's almost as if man and music called each other
into being. The notion of a pre-Monroe bluegrass obviously makes no
sense, yet it's almost as hard to imagine a pre-bluegrass Monroe.
What? Without his big white Stetson? Without the Blue Grass Boys,
deployed in their immutable formula of guitar, banjo, fiddle and
bass?
<TEXT>
<P>
   So to bluegrass fans who haven't probed country-music history _
indeed, to anyone aware of Monroe's stature as one of America's few
founders of a musical genre _ the newly issued CD ``What Would You
Give in Exchange for Your Soul?'' (Rounder 1073) packs a powerful
surprise. The first in an eventual four-CD series, it contains 15
of the 60 songs Bill Monroe recorded as the mandolinist, harmony
vocalist and junior partner in the Monroe Brothers, a red-hot duo
that scorched the Carolinas in the mid-'30s. In 1936, Bill, 25, and
his lead-singing, guitar-picking brother Charlie, 33, released
their first record, the song that gives this CD its name. ``What
Would You Give in Exchange for Your Soul?'' became one of the
biggest country-music hits of the '30s, popular throughout the
South. A decade before he presided over the birth of bluegrass,
Bill Monroe was already a star.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, a few anthologies have offered tantalizing
glimpses of the Monroe Brothers, and a two-LP set, long extinct,
came out in 1975. For the most part, the Monroes' music has
remained a rumor, unavailable in the United States. When Rounder's
collection is fully released _ the remaining CDs will appear this
fall and next year _ one of the high points of early country music
will no longer be a secret.
</P>
<P>
   The '30s ushered in a new kind of hillbilly recording artist
(until about 1950, country music was known by the disparaging
near-epithet ``hillbilly.'' Unlike their forebears _ casual pickers
for whom record-making had been a lark _ the new breed were
full-time, self-proclaimed entertainers, young, polished and
ambitious. Steeped in tradition, they were also impatient with it.
Members of the first generation to grow up on radio and records,
they were eager to incorporate the sounds of modernity, of jazz
bands and smooth pop crooners, into their music.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie and Bill Monroe's sound matched their beautifully
tailored suits; a streamlined whoosh, it brought intimations of
big-city speed and excitement to their rural audiences. The
Monroes' relationship to country music parallels that of Bill's
exact contemporary Robert Johnson, with his self-aware
professionalism, supercharged technique and nervous intensity, to
the blues of the Mississippi Delta. Like Johnson, the Monroe
Brothers prodded a rural idiom out of a sleepy past into a
hardboiled, hopped-up present.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Bill and Charlie came to record, they had kicked
around plenty. Native Kentuckians, they had busted their backs in
an oil refinery outside Chicago and barnstormed the Midwest with
their brother Birch, who left the group in 1934. Heading south in
1935, Bill and Charlie worked the North Carolina-South Carolina
line; radio performers by day, by night they rode the bad roads to
schoolhouses, churches, town halls: any place big enough to hold a
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Big Charlie was the frontman, a gregarious crowd pleaser, but it
was the sounds Bill wrenched from his mandolin _ an absurdly
unlikely vehicle for heroics _ that distinguished the Monroes from
every other hillbilly act. Before Bill Monroe, the mandolin was an
inessential instrument in country music, a prop you gave the singer
so he could do something with his hands. Out of sheer stubbornness
and, as it happened, something like genius, Monroe invented
something like a language for it, made it a blistering solo
instrument. Moving his pick rapidly up and down across the strings,
he was able to play double- and quadruple-time runs, and when the
tempo was as fast to begin with as it was on ``Watermelon Hangin'
on That Vine'' or ``New River Train,'' Bill's 16th-note runs drove
people half-wild, made them jump out of their seats, throw their
hats in the air, stamp their shoes, holler like crazy fools.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie used the pick-strum style he'd no doubt learned from
Carter Family records, but Maybelle Carter never played this fast.
Charlie Monroe must have been a powerful man, to whip his right
wrist up and down on the strings as speedily and relentlessly as he
did yet with enough finesse to pick out lickety-split little bass
runs. The first Monroe Brothers song I ever heard (the title
escapes me) was one of the fast ones. As the guitar-mandolin intro
came on, I grumbled to myself: somebody had sped up the turntable
(yes, this was back in the LP days). But in came the voices,
relaxed and resonant. Nobody had fooled with the turntable; this
was merely a case of next-to-impossible musicianship. To this day,
whenever I feel like laughing out loud with the giddy pleasure of
hearing something ridiculously difficult pulled off with nonchalant
aplomb, I listen to the Monroe Brothers playing fast.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill and Charlie weren't merely speedsters. When the Monroe
Brothers played religious songs, which they considered their stock
in trade, they slowed the tempo way down, shifting the emphasis to
their closely harmonizing voices. ``What Would You Give in Exchange
for Your Soul?'' was slow and bone-sparse; unflashily played, it
sails aloft on the brothers' voices _ Bill's especially, an eerie
falsetto moan.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Monroe's voice and the Monroe Brothers' music in general
have a bluesiness, a kinship with Southern black musical feeling,
that's plainly audible in most early country music. While the
Monroes are at their bluesiest in religious tunes _ a song like
``Do You Call That Religion?'' wouldn't have been out of place in a
black prayer meeting _ their entire sound has a strong blues
component. If I had to characterize the Monroes' music, I'd call it
hillbilly soul: Southern white music deeply in touch with the black
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Charlie went their separate professional ways in 1938,
but during their four short years together, they must have been
something to see. ``The Monroe Brothers blow away anything Bill
ever did on his own,'' said the guitarist and musicologist John
Fahey recently. That's hyperbole, although it shows just how
excited people still get over this music. Here's how I'd put it.
Bill Monroe died in 1996, world-famous and full of honors. If,
perish the thought, he'd died in 1938, he would still have affected
the course of country music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
