<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ARAFAT-880(2T     07-26 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ARAFAT-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT ARRIVES HOME TO HERO'S WELCOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip _ As Yasser Arafat returned to this
hardscrabble territory, he was given a hero's welcome on Wednesday
for holding fast at Camp David to Palestinian demands that Israel
surrender sovereignty over all of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat was hoisted onto supporters' shoulders and hailed by
thousands waving flags and banners and carrying his portrait. It
was a rare moment of adulation for Arafat, whose popularity has
been eroded by the hardships and corruption that have been
hallmarks of life under the rule of his Palestinian Authority in
the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   At Gaza airport and again outside his headquarters in Gaza City,
the 70-year-old Palestinian leader responded, despite evident
fatigue, by clambering atop the roof of his armored Mercedes
limousine and raising his fingers in a victory salute.
</P>
<P>
   One of many banners outside El Montada, the handsome stone
building overlooking the Mediterranean in Gaza City where Arafat
has his headquarters, put the matter squarely. ``We welcome you
home with honor,'' it said. ``We hail your heroic stand in not
surrendering a single centimeter of Palestinian land, and in not
giving up Jerusalem. You are a great leader of the Palestinian
people.''
</P>
<P>
   As frenzied as it was, the welcome appeared to involve only a
tiny fraction of the one million Palestinians living in Gaza. It
also appeared to have been carefully orchestrated by the Fatah
movement, Arafat's faction of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   A similar story unfolded on the West Bank, where a rally in
support of Arafat in the town of Ramallah attracted only 200
people. One reason for the small crowd was that Arafat's plane
landed at the height of the working day. But many Palestinians
appear deeply disillusioned with their leader for failing to
deliver better living conditions in the six years since the
Palestinian Authority assumed responsibility for most of Gaza from
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But from the voices among the 5,000 people at the airport, and
amid the tumult of a similarly-sized gathering at the Gaza
headquarters, it seemed that Arafat had done the only thing he
could in holding out for all of the Old City of Jerusalem, which
contains ancient sites sacred to Arabs, Jews and Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-age boys, Muslim clerics, middle-aged shopkeepers,
policewomen, small children scampering cheerfully through police
security lines of comic-opera efficiency, all were of a single
accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should never give up any part of Jerusalem, never'' said
Eyad Daoud, a 17-year-old high school student.
</P>
<P>
   A 50-year-old official working in Arafat's religious affairs
ministry, Abdul Fattah, stood back serenely from the hubbub in the
city, a model of clerical propriety in a gold-trimmed robe and a
loose white hood. ``All Arabs, and all Muslims, need Jerusalem, and
acknowledge it as the Palestinians' rightful capital,'' he said.
``If the world wants peace, Eest Jerusalem must return to the
Palestinians. There is no other way.''
</P>
<P>
   On its face, the welcome appeared to endorse Arafat's rejection
of the compromise urged by President Clinton, involving limited
Israeli concessions to Palestinian autonomy in the eastern parts of
the city as part of an overall peace settlement. It would also have
allowed the return to Israel of a few thousand of the more than
three million Palestinian refugees dispersed around the region.
</P>
<P>
   But things on this sun-scorched day were not necessarily quite
as appearances suggested.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Arafat emphasized during a brief stop at
Alexandria for talks with the Egyptian president, Hosni Mubarak,
and again in remarks at Gaza airport, that he was still hopeful of
resuming negotiations with Israel before the Sept. 13 deadline he
has set for unilaterally declaring a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   The date, a possible trigger for renewed violence between
Israelis and Palestinians, is the anniversary of the signing of the
Oslo accords in 1993 on the White House lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the unlikelihood of Barak or any other Israeli
leader coming forward within the next seven weeks with sweeping
concessions on Jerusalem, Arafat's eagerness for negotiations
suggested that he, at least, has not ruled out a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility would be the one raised at Camp David, under
which the thorny issue of Jerusalem's status would be deferred
while other issues, including the West Bank and Palestinian
statehood, are settled.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, Arafat is sticking to the position he
took at the peace talks: there can be no final peace, nor even an
interim settlement, without Israel conceding sovereignty over East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem is not only for the Palestinians, it is for the Arab
nation, for Muslims everywhere, for Christians,'' he told reporters
at the airport. He added, ``Jerusalem is the capital of the
Palestinian state, like it or not. Whoever does not like it, let
him go and drink from the sea.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Part of Israel's calculation in negotiating with Arafat has been
that Palestinians might be willing to trade their historic links
with Jerusalem for a quick transition to full statehood,
international aid and more relaxed ties with Israel. American
officials have said Clinton dangled the prospect of generous
Western aid in the closing hours of the Camp David summit, only for
the Palestinian leader to remain immovable on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hubbub on Wednesday, there may be a sizable
proportion of Palestinians who are not willing to wait another
generation or more for the benefits of peace, even if a compromise
on Jerusalem is part of the price.
</P>
<P>
   One long-term Gaza resident said that, at age 35, he could wait
no longer for the benefits of a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this posturing brings us nothing, or less than nothing,''
he said. ``What do we have to show for six years of Palestinian
autonomy here? No jobs, terrible shortages of electricity and
water, bad schools, bad hospitals, bad everything _ worse even than
when the Israelis were here. And now we say, 'Jerusalem or
nothing.' It's a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was one point of agreement among the Palestinians, it
was that the events in Camp David should not be the signal for
renewed violence, and especially not of a ``second intifada'', or
uprising, like the one that caused widespread mayhem in the late
1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat implied as much by speaking of the hope of resuming
negotiations, and one of his chief lieutenants, Nabeel Shath, who
accompanied the Palestinian leader to Camp David, made it explicit.
``There will be no violence from the Palestinians, not unless
Israel makes violence, or the settlers turn to it,'' he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Some young Palestinians have spoken menacingly of a resumption
of attacks by Hamas, the radical Islamic group that engaged in a
terror campaign in the mid-1990s. But Palestinian analysts say
Arafat's Fatah group has largely emasculated Hamas by arresting or
exiling many of its leading figures. In any case, Israeli military
officials have said that they have alerted army and police units to
be especially vigilant in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   In the circumstances, Arafat and his associates in the
Palestinian leadership seem set on making the best of what, after
years of working toward unchallenged Palestinian statehood, has
unarguably been a setback. Shath, the senior Arafat aide who
participated in the Camp David talks, said that despite the
appearance of failure, the Palestinians had left Camp David
convinced that they had achieved a major breakthrough simply by
getting the Israelis and the Americans to concentrate on Jerusalem
as the main obstacle to peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not disappointed,'' he said. ``The talks were very
useful, very important, because all the issues that have been taboo
all these years _ above all, Jerusalem _ are now on the table.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
