u a BC-FUEL-ECONOMY-ART-1075     07-26 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUEL-ECONOMY-ART-1075(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD APPEARS SET TO RAISE MILEAGE FOR ITS SPORT UTILITIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich.)   (EDS: Also moving in `f' news file) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Ford Motor Co. has decided to increase the average
fuel economy of its sport utility vehicles by 25 percent over the
next five years, people involved in the company's plans said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The increase, amounting to roughly five miles per gallon, would
be the first significant change in the fuel economy of any class of
passenger vehicle in almost two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is convinced that Americans want to buy more fuel-efficient
vehicles and will steer their purchases to companies they perceive
as environmentally responsible, the people said. The company's new
stance is also a response to environmental concerns about the
automobile's role in global warming.
</P>
<P>
   At least at first, the company does not intend to pass the extra
cost of producing more fuel-efficient vehicles directly to American
customers, two people familiar with the plan said.
</P>
<P>
   The automaker is betting instead that improved fuel economy will
increase sales more than enough to offset lower profits on each
vehicle. Better gas mileage and lower operating costs for Ford
sport utilities could eventually increase demand enough to allow
the company to sell them with fewer rebates, and possibly even
raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   Ford executives hope that the more fuel-efficient sport
utilities will give all of their brands an image of environmental
responsibility, people familiar with the company's plans said. That
could help sales of the company's cars, minivans and pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Ford _ which sells 800,000 sport utilities a year,
representing about a fifth of its total domestic sales _ is a sharp
reversal. The company started and led the decade-long trend toward
sport utility vehicles, the biggest of which consume more than
twice as much gasoline a mile as the average car. The Ford
Excursion is the world's largest sport utility, getting 10 miles to
the gallon in the city and 13 on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to improve mileage comes even as recent efforts in
Congress to mandate an increase in fuel economy have failed, partly
because of lobbying by Ford and other automakers.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the mileage improvement will be achieved through changes
to Ford's larger sport utilities: the Ford Explorer, Expedition and
Excursion, the Mercury Mountaineer, the Lincoln Navigator and the
Range Rover.
</P>
<P>
   Ford engineers say that there are many small steps that they can
take to improve fuel economy, from making auto parts lighter to
adjusting engines. But lighter auto parts are usually more
expensive, because they need to be made from aluminum instead of
steel, while engine design alterations must be made with great care
to avoid reducing vehicles' towing capacity. Ford executives
declined to estimate the cost of these changes.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the improvement in Ford's average fuel economy will come
from the introduction in September of the Ford Escape, which is
slightly smaller than the Ford Explorer and uses a lightweight car
underbody instead of a heavy, pickup-truck underbody. With a
four-cylinder engine, the Escape gets up to 28 miles a gallon on
the highway
</P>
<P>
   Ford will not achieve its fuel-economy improvement by taking
advantage of either of the loopholes that it and others have used
in recent years: building vehicles like the Excursion to be so
large that they are excluded from the federal averages, and
building vehicles that qualify for alternative-fuel mileage
credits. The Excursion will be counted as Ford pursues its 25
percent improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, General Motors and DaimlerChrysler are building huge
numbers of minivans, pickup trucks and midsize cars that can burn
either gasoline or nearly pure ethanol. These vehicles are counted
in the averages as though they have triple their actual milage,
even though only 100 of the nation's 170,000 service stations sell
ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Nasser, Ford's chief executive, is scheduled to fly to
Washington on Thursday to announce the company's decision at the
National Press Club, people involved in the company's plans said.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler and GM, Ford's main rivals in the sport utility
market, declined to comment on Ford's move, saying only that some
of their models were already fuel-efficient. Detroit automakers,
including Ford, have said in the past that improved mileage for
sport utilities will require sacrifices in engine power and vehicle
size that American consumers will not tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, GM and DaimlerChrysler have a quarter each of the sport
utility market. Foreign automakers divide up the remaining share.
</P>
<P>
   GM has just finished improving the gas mileage of its full-size
sport utility vehicles and pickup trucks by 5 percent over the last
three years by completely redesigning them for the first time in a
decade. But GM and other automakers have not improved their
fuel-economy averages, increasing the power, size, and gas
consumption of some models even as others have become more
efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Ford voluntarily cleaned up its sport utility vehicles' tailpipe
emissions two years ago to make them as clean as cars' emissions.
While the cost has approached $100 a vehicle, and while many rivals
have not yet followed suit, Ford officials say that decision has
been a selling point.
</P>
<P>
   William C. Ford Jr., Ford's chairman since the start of last
year and a great-grandson of Henry Ford, is an outspoken
environmentalist who has called for the auto industry to address
global warming. At the company's annual meeting two months ago in
Atlanta, he acknowledged the environmental and safety drawbacks of
sport utilities.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few small signs in Washington that federal
fuel-economy standards, little changed since the mid-1980s, might
be reconsidered next year. But there is no indication that the
government will require nearly as big an improvement as Ford is
planning. Nasser intends to present the plan as an example of how
the auto industry can improve fuel economy voluntarily and will not
call for tighter federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers are required to sell cars with an average fuel
economy of 27.5 miles a gallon and so-called light trucks with an
average fuel economy of 20.7 miles a gallon. Sport utilities, vans
and pickup trucks are all counted as light trucks and now represent
half of the American auto market, partly because manufacturers have
switched production away from cars as low gasoline prices and a
strong economy in the 1990s produced a soaring demand for large but
gas-guzzling vehicles.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Ford has barely met the regulatory averages, and its
sport utilities have done especially badly _ balanced by more
efficient minivans and pickups.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton raised the fuel-economy standard for sport
utilities, minivans and pickup trucks by two-tenths of a mile per
gallon in 1993 and 1994, to 20.7 miles per gallon. When Republicans
took control of the House and Senate in 1995, they began amending
the federal budget each year to prevent the Transportation
Department from spending any money to study the issue or tighten
standards. Each annual budget since then has included the same
prohibition, but support for the provision has dwindled as light
trucks have increased as a share of the market.
</P>
<P>
   High gasoline prices prompted an effort this spring by Western
senators, whose constituents drive long distances, and by
environmentalists, to overturn the ban. Under a recent Senate
compromise, the freeze on fuel-economy standards will remain for
another year while the National Academy of Sciences reviews federal
fuel-economy policy.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Knollenberg, R-Mich., a member of the House
Appropriations Committee, has blocked fuel-economy changes on the
House side. His chief of staff, Paul Welday, said that Ford's
latest move was a good one if it helped sell sport utility
vehicles, but would strengthen those who wanted tighter standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside the Beltway, it will only fuel the fires of those who
believe that if Ford can do that, everybody else should be forced
to do that,'' Welday said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Becker, the energy policy director at the Sierra Club,
said environmentalists would use Ford's decision in their lobbying.
``This shows that the people who say you can't make cars cleaner
and more fuel-efficient are wrong,'' he said. ``This shows that a
company that wants to improve fuel economy can do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials believe that they can improve mileage while
maintaining the safety of their vehicles' occupants. Occupants of
lightweight, subcompact cars tend to fare poorly in collisions. But
a variety of recent studies have found that vehicles weighing 3,000
to 3,500 pounds _ the weight of a midsized or large car _ tend to
be very safe; further weight provides only a little additional
safety for the occupants, while tremendously increasing the risk to
other motorists during collisions. Ford's current sport utilities
weigh from 3,700 pounds for a two-wheel-drive Explorer to 7,200
pounds for an Excursion with four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser's plans have provoked some nervousness within Ford that
the automaker may be limiting its ability to respond if gas prices
fall or if consumers begin demanding even more powerful vehicles.
``There is a lot of struggle within the company over whether this
is the right number and the right time frame,'' a person involved
in the plan said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
