<SLUG> BC-CONCORDE-AMERICAN0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Concorde crash victim looked to retire in Florida
 &HT;    By Michael Coren
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The lone American aboard the Concorde that
crashed Tuesday was on his last flight to the United States before
he planned to retire in Vero Beach, Fla., his sister said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The supersonic jet that had carried Chris Behrens, 64, an
employee of Air France, around the world four times also carried
him to his death when the Air France jet he was on crashed in
Gonesse, France, killing 113 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was coming to New York,'' said his sister Therese
Fredericks, 75, who has lived with her husband, John, in Vero Beach
for four years, when she found out about the crash while watching
TV. ``And I knew there was only one American on board. It had to be
him,'' she said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fredericks anticipated Behrens returning to the Vero Beach area
and settling down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved Vero,'' she said. Fredericks' daughter, Joy, who also
recently died, was a real estate agent in Vero Beach and had
arranged for him to buy a house in the area, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the deal fell through,'' she said. ``I think he was still
dreaming of living in Vero.''
</P>
<P>
   He vacationed on the Treasure Coast frequently, making trips to
the beach to go swimming and touring the mall, she said. Behrens'
most recent visit to Vero Beach was less than a month ago when he
attended the funeral of his niece, who died of a brain aneurysm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to comfort me,'' Frederick said.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens, who was fluent in both French and German, lived in
Frankfurt and had worked for Air France ``for many years,'' said
his sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always liked flying,'' Fredericks said. She described her
brother as a young boy in love with planes while growing up in
Annandale, N.J. His fascination with jets eventually drew him to
the fastest one of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He completely loved the Concorde,'' she said about his
favorite jet. The 185-ton aircraft cruises faster than the speed of
sound at 1,350 mph, by the far the fastest commercial airliner in
existence. The 12 Concordes still operating are used by British
Airways and Air France almost exclusively to carry passengers
between New York and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had many friends,'' she said pointing to one of the photos
of him adorning her wall. ``And as you can see, very good looking.
He was very kind, very generous,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fredericks said she was close to her brother who always came to
``visit his favorite sister.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was born on my birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
