<HEADER>
A4019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-LONG-BEACH-NYT &LR;      07-26 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-LONG-BEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH, IN LOS ANGELES' SHADOW, YEARNS FOR THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ To hear municipal officials here tell it,
there is no more enduring, supportive relationship than the bond
between this industrious, muscular port and that livable but tough,
even troubled, city just north, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Scratch that happy surface, however, and Long Beach will concede
somewhat more complex feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Taboada, Long Beach's city manager, summarized the
prevailing view when he recalled going to Washington with Los
Angeles officials last year to seek financing for a major rail link
to the cities' adjacent, sometimes bitterly competitive ports.
</P>
<P>
   As they entered a congressional hearing room, the huge Los
Angeles delegation took literally every seat at the table, Taboada
said, forcing him to almost physically remove one of the aides so
there would be a seat for the only other person in the Long Beach
delegation, the mayor, Beverly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that or get no seat at the table,'' Taboada said.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, Long Beach is a substantial city. With roughly
450,000 residents, it is larger than St. Louis, Atlanta, Pittsburgh
or Minneapolis. It has the largest container port in the country, a
huge Boeing manufacturing center and a university. It has more than
five miles of beaches. And, perhaps most important, it has clawed
its way back from a series of economic calamities, including the
loss of more than 50,000 aerospace job and military base closings
that made the last recession all the more fierce here.
</P>
<P>
   But Long Beach also has a complex, a product of its sense of
always resting uncomfortably in the shadow of the flashier, more
prosperous and, truth be told, infinitely more effervescent
neighbor to the north.
</P>
<P>
   It is a struggle Long Beach officials know they cannot win, and
so they put the best face on things. Los Angeles will be thrust
into the spotlight as host to the Democratic National Convention
from Aug. 14 to Aug. 17. And Long Beach? From Aug. 9 to Aug. 13, it
will play host to the Reform Party convention, a role that some
city officials admit reinforces their poor-stepchild image, at
least in the eyes of the media, but does put their town on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some officials make a virtue of the city's second-tier
status. Los Angeles is preparing nervously not just for tens of
thousands of delegates, politicians and journalists, but also for
well-organized and aggressive demonstrators. The embattled Los
Angeles police have already been criticized for a crowd-control
plan yet to be put in effect.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Dale L. Brown, deputy police chief in Long Beach,
said his city was anticipating exactly zero demonstrators at what
is expected to be a sedate Reform Party gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're right, there are times we feel we don't get the
recognition we deserve,'' Brown said. ``But sometimes it's nice to
be in the shadows.''
</P>
<P>
   Taboada added: ``We won't get the attention Los Angeles will. On
the other hand, there are only three presidential conventions, and
we have one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said that in her view, the problem was a matter of
perception and nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want,'' she said, ``is to help people realize that
when you say Los Angeles County, you don't just mean Los Angeles. I
don't grumble about it, maybe because I've gotten used to dealing
with this my whole life. But we're not an appendage, and we just
want people to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she did an uncanny impression of Ross Perot, who led the
Reform Party when it held its last convention here four years ago
and who, she said, offered this compliment: ``Your city is very
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach is no stranger to ups, downs and identity crises. It
was founded in 1882 as Willmore City, named for an English
developer who put up about a dozen houses and then failed. A few
dozen more buildings were thrown up, and the settlement was reborn
in 1888 as Long Beach. Today it covers about 50 square miles that
comprise one of the most heavily industrialized areas in the
region. On the drive south from Los Angeles on the freeway, the
first sign that one has arrived is a huge oil refinery; indeed, the
city still produces substantial amounts of oil.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Long Beach became home to a Navy base, a
naval shipyard and a big Navy hospital. These, along with big
airplane factories, became the mainstay of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But Long Beach was hit with a triple whammy during the 1990's:
the recession, base closings and military procurement cutbacks sent
the unemployment rate soaring to 9.2 percent in 1993. An ugly
racial incident, in which the police were filmed putting the head
of a black suspect, himself a former police officer, through a
plate glass window, almost led the city to dissolve its police
force and bring in the county sheriff's department to keep the
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not have just a death knell,'' Taboada said. ``It was
one death knell after another.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill became mayor in the bleak days of 1994 and has worked
not just to revive the city but to transform it. In addition to
technology, she has pushed tourism along the waterfront, where the
most notable symbol is the Queen Mary, docked there and used as an
entertainment center.
</P>
<P>
   The success has been mixed, but unquestionably the city is back
on its feet; today the unemployment rate is 5 percent, compared
with 4 percent nationally. ``We've been celebrating everything,''
O'Neill said. ``We celebrated the first store opening. We
celebrated the beginning of new construction. We celebrated
anything that said hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Navy hospital has been transformed into a gigantic
mall, although it does not have a major department store. (Indeed,
there is none anywhere in Long Beach.) The city obtained government
financing to build the Aquarium of the Pacific, a big tourist
attraction on the refurbished waterfront, but it lost about $7.5
million from late 1998 through this March.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the investment continues. Several acres of unsightly
blacktop just behind city hall are to be torn up soon for apartment
complexes, the first such residential construction in the area
since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill and other officials say their concern now is not so much
to ensure that the Reform delegates see the transformation as to
get the media to take note of the successes as Long Beach's own,
not Los Angeles'.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long Beach in the middle of the Mojave Desert would be a great
media story,'' Taboada said. ``But because we're on the underbelly
of Los Angeles, when we get attention it's negative _ or it has
been. We feel like we can't get our message out, but maybe this
will help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
