<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTRACOASTAL-LOSS0727     07-26 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTRACOASTAL-LOSS0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials: Intracoastal may run out of money
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Intracoastal Health Systems is draining
its cash reserves to operate Good Samaritan and St. Mary's medical
centers and will be out of money within a year unless it makes
drastic operating changes, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They said the company, which had been losing $2 million a month,
dropped $8.2 million in June, pushing its losses to about $41
million for the budget year just ended. Intracoastal lost $22.6
million in the previous budget year, which ended June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The main factor in last month's dive was a $6 million decline in
expected revenue, attributed to doctors diverting patients to other
hospitals because of low morale and uncertainty over the fate of
Good Sam and St. Mary's.
</P>
<P>
   Cash reserves are down to $43 million and are expected to shrink
to $21 million by January, according to Intracoastal's chief
financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very anxious,'' CFO Michael Loscalzo told members of a
community hospital rescue committee at their first meeting. ``If we
don't do significant restructuring, this business will be out of
cash by this time next year, and it will have begun to fail two to
three months before that.''
</P>
<P>
   What would happen to the West Palm Beach hospitals under such
conditions is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really no answer that we can give at this point,''
Intracoastal board member Jon Moyle said in an interview. ``All
avenues would have to be explored, and I prefer not to waste time
focusing on that. If we get this turned around and start to make
money, then all the projections go out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   Cambio Health Solutions, a Tennessee-based firm, has been
running the hospitals under contract since Intracoastal's board
gave up on its own managers in January. Cambio has proposed closing
St. Mary's, expanding Good Samaritan and consolidating services
there to turn the company around.
</P>
<P>
   That plan provoked an investigation by the state Attorney
General's Office and inspired community leaders to coalesce to
demand a voice in the hospitals' fate. Intracoastal agreed to hold
up consolidation plans until the state finishes its probe and to
cooperate with the community group's own review.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue committee, calling itself the Community Advisory
Board, elected as its chair Jeannette Corbett, chief executive of
Quantum Foundation and former chair of the JFK Medical Center
board.
</P>
<P>
   Corbett called the committee's goal of reaching a conclusion on
the hospital plan by Sept. 15 a ``monumental task.'' She set a
meeting for 3 p.m. today to select a national health care
consulting firm to review Cambio's data, study local health care
needs and determine whether both hospitals can continue to exist in
some fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The Quantum Foundation, created with the proceeds of the sale of
JFK Medical to the Columbia/HCA hospital chain, has offered
$500,000 to pay for such an independent study, but Corbett said the
foundation's board would find it ``more palatable'' if other groups
shared the expense.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Grady, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Palm
Beaches, pledged to raise $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Attorney General's Office said it supports the efforts of
the Community Advisory Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no downside to it,'' said Cecile L. Dykas, assistant
deputy attorney general heading the investigation into what happens
to charitable contributions made to St. Mary's if the hospital is
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Dykas said she sees some overlap, but no conflict between the
state's investigation and the community group's examination of
Intracoastal's records.
</P>
<P>
   Intracoastal board and management officials pleaded with the
advisory group Wednesday to find a solution quickly to alleviate
the growing losses of money, patients and personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This problem is becoming more and more serious with each day
that passes,'' said Intracoastal board member Moyle. ``We need to
start rebuilding. ... It's really critical if we're going to have a
continuing not-for-profit community hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Catholic Health East, which holds a $150
million mortgage on the hospitals and is Intracoastal's most
powerful board presence, said the Pennsylvania-based health care
consortium is willing to consider alternatives to closing St.
Mary's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not be here if we weren't,'' Dan Russell said. ``I'm
just asking that you do it sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   The Franciscan Sisters of Allegany, who owned St. Mary's before
it joined with Good Sam to form Intracoastal in 1994, combined with
two other Catholic hospital networks to form Catholic Health East.
The nuns still are involved, and their commitment to serve the poor
still drives the firm, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been given my marching orders by the sisters,'' Russell
said. ``They own the company of which I'm the CEO. . . . We pledge
to cooperate in any way we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Intracoastal named Paul Bremer, recently retired managing
partner of accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young's local office, to be its
liaison with the committee. Bremer's firm did a study for
Intracoastal in 1995 that recommended Good Samprovide wellness,
ambulatory, and outpatient services and short-stay in-patient care,
and that St. Mary's focus on acute care and emergency services.
</P>
<P>
   Bremer said Intracoastal offered to pay him for working with the
committee, but he refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just do anything to make this work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
