<HEADER>
A4030 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TRINITY0727-COX     07-26 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRINITY0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Operator of women's clinic accused of bilking clients
 &HT;    By Sanjay Bhatt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A controversial South Florida clinic
operator faces allegations it wrongly kept the deposits of more
than 80 poor pregnant women in St. Lucie County and that its chief
executive gutted its bank account to pay his own debts.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for Trinity Medical Inc. chief executive Dr.
Kenneth Kassin said Wednesday his client had ``no knowledge'' of
the women's claims. Attorney Robert Harris also downplayed
allegations, made in court, by Trinity's former chief operating
officer that Kassin used the firm to pay his personal bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's much more than is being said there,'' said Harris, who
didn't elaborate. ``I don't want to litigate it in the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, from Deerfield Beach, was hired last week after Kassin's
Fort Lauderdale lawyers resigned, citing ``irreconcilable
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the state Agency for Health Care Administration
ordered Trinity to ``promptly'' return the deposits of eight
Okeechobee County women, all migrant workers, who had their babies
delivered by Trinity doctors. The clinic had been reimbursed by
Medicaid for the deliveries but withheld the women's deposits _ a
form of double-dipping that violates state and federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   But so far only one of the women has received a refund, and she
got only $90 of the $200 she put down, said Miriam Harmatz, an
attorney with Florida Legal Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a desperate situation,'' Harmatz said. ``Someone needs to
go in and freeze the guy's bank account.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the women Trinity saw have moved to other states to
harvest crops, Harmatz said.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvie Kramer, director of Healthy Start, which pays for
pre-natal care in St. Lucie County, said she supplied 80 to 100
more names of women with complaints to the AHCA earlier this month.
The poor women, all seen at Trinity's Fort Pierce clinic, gave
deposits ranging from $200 to $1,300, Kramer said. Kramer said her
case manager's records show that Medicaid paid Trinity for
delivering their babies _ some as far back as 1997 _ but the women
say they never got their deposits back.
</P>
<P>
   After a seven-year relationship, Healthy Start ended its
contract with Trinity on July 1 for pre-natal care because of the
women's complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``AHCA needs to do something here,'' Kramer said. Kim Reed, an
AHCA spokeswoman, said the agency is checking Kramer's list against
Trinity's records. She could not explain why the eight Okeechobee
County women have not received full refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity had told the agency those women were sent refunds, Reed
said. But the agency hasn't received copies of cashed checks. The
agency has it imposed any sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said Trinity has been ``extremely cooperative'' in
providing records and that the state could reach a compromise with
it over an unrelated dispute. In March, state officials notified
Trinity that Medicaid had overpaid it $188,000 for lab tests.
Trinity appealed to an administrative judge.
</P>
<P>
   AHCA was investigating the claims of the Okeechobee women when
Trinity's chief operating officer, Peter Feldman, resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman filed suit in Palm Beach County Circuit Court last month
against Trinity, Kassin and his private practice in Fort
Lauderdale. The suit seeks more than $106,548 in unpaid loans,
wages and other benefits. Feldman claims in court records that
Trinity has become bankrupt because Kassin transferred money,
sometimes deceptively, from the firm's bank accounts to pay his
practice's bills and ``personal expenses,'' including American
Express credit card charges, dental bills and family car expenses.
Even though Kassin's private practice and Trinity shared office
space, staff and other overhead, only Trinity paid these expenses,
the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Kassin, Trinity's sole shareholder, was the only one who could
sign the firm's checks, the lawsuit said, and he didn't reimburse
Trinity.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, Kassin's attorney, said his client will file a lawsuit
against Feldman for gross negligence. ``Kassin was practicing
medicine and this guy was responsible for running the business,''
Harris said. ``This is a case of the pot calling the kettle
black.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinity Medical Inc., based in Deerfield Beach, closed clinics
in Pahokee and Belle Glade in August of 1999 and told hundreds of
patients they would have to travel to Okeechobee or Fort Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
