<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WINDOW-SECURITY0727-C     07-26 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDOW-SECURITY0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Window film slammed as `false sense of security'
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Palm Beach County's chief building official
is asking the Florida attorney general to investigate whether
window film makers and distributors are exaggerating the strength
of their products.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Holt sent the information to the attorney general's
office Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to . . . let them decide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holt has been collecting newspaper advertisements, comments from
callers and literature from makers, distributors and code
organizations. He's turning his findings over to the attorney
general because he has virtually no clout over hurricane coverings
for existing structures; while new construction in the county must
meet building codes, no permit is needed to apply window film at
existing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Holt's advice to homeowners: Demand literature and
specifications and run it past a county or city building department
before buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my concern, that people will get a false sense of
security, thinking they have full protection,'' Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   Window film _ usually made of types of plastic, metals, Mylar
(the silvery material used in party balloons) or combinations _ is
permanently applied to windows using a strong adhesive. Some film
is sold just for sun protection. The stronger film, usually sold as
a security tool, is designed to keep the panect. Costs for window
film on both sides of a 3-by-8-foot sliding glass door range from
$350 to $465.
</P>
<P>
   Most makers and distributors contacted last week said their
product is effective for some storms but isn't as good as plywood,
storm panels or shutters. Still, they argued the reduced
effectiveness may be worth the added aesthetics and convenience.
</P>
<P>
   One firm has claimed in a newspaper ad that its film is as
strong as window coverings, but the owner said this week the film
works only with a certain kind of window frame. And one distributor
acknowledged some of his literature may be misleading and is at
least confusing; he has promised to change it.
</P>
<P>
   Building officials, and the companies themselves, point out that
any window film or impact resistant window is only as strong as the
window frame, which could blow out in a storm and send the whole
window assembly flying. And, they say, some film doesn't cover the
whole pane, leaving exposed areas.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach, Martin and St. Lucie counties follow the Southern
Building Code. All windows in new construction must withstand a
wind force of 100 to 110 mph. Everything above 30 feet also must
withstand a ``small missile test,'' which judges the impact of 30
2-gram steel balls traveling at 130 feet per second. The height
limit was based on the likelihood that large pieces of debris
wouldn't get as high into the air. But the first 30 feet of a
structure's height _ most single-family homes in South Florida are
one-story _ must withstand the ``large missile test,'' which
measures the impact of an 8-foot-long, 2-by-4 board fired at 50
feet per second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not in my 22 years have I heard of window film passing the
`large missile test,' '' said Rob Martin, president of Westar
Window Films in Largo and vice president of the Virginia-based
International Window Film Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the window film manufacturers take the position that the
product has limitations,'' Martin said. ``We constantly refer our
distributors to the FTC (Federal Trade Commission) advertising
guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Panels &AMP; Shutters are !!Obsolete!!'' says an advertisement
that ran July 9 in The Palm Beach Post for Glass Sentinal of Palm
Beach. Literature provided by the maker of Glass Sentinal says it
``passed Florida hurricane tests for wind velocity, pressure and
missile impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Kitchen, owner of Glass Sentinal, said last week his film
passed small and large missile tests, but only ``in certain
applications, depending on the thickness of the film and the
thickness of the glass as well.'' And, he said, those successful
tests were made using special frames designed to hold the shattered
glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would it pass 1/8-inch glass, like a normal bedroom window?
No,'' Kitchen said last week from the firm's offices in Altamonte
Springs, near Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen said he does not believe the ads are misleading and he
directs distributors to be clear to each potential customer about
what the film will and won't do for that particular home.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Kitchen said he had told his Palm Beach County
distributor to change the ``panels and shutters are obsolete'' ad
``instead to reflect our product as a `glass protective system.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Another firm Holt contacted, West Palm Beach-based Palm Beach
Security Film, provided him literature saying its film _ Glass
Gard, made in St. Petersburg _ met the small missile impact tests.
The sales literature also says, ``You'll never have to worry about
getting home in time to roll down the shutters or nail up the
plywood.''
</P>
<P>
   When the passages were read to Gary Shapiro, president of Palm
Beach Security Film, he said they'd been copied from literature
created by his partners on Florida's Gulf coast and he agreed they
may suggest window films are the equal of window coverings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll change that if that's the implication people are
getting,'' he said. ``We try not to intimate that it replaces
hurricane shutters. There's no film on the market that will.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to give people affordable protection for an
average hurricane. I did not want to intimate that we were fooling
anybody. If people ask us, `Does this meet the code?' No, it
doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lankford, senior building technician for the Martin County
Building Department, said: ``We can't accept film as a substitute
until the days when the film is attached to a window and we can
test it as a combined assembly.'' But, she said, ``It's better than
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
