<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AMAZON-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-26 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON SEES GAINS IN ITS LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAUL HANSELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amazon.com said Wednesday that it had lost $317 million in the
second quarter of the year, slightly less than analysts had
expected, and asserted that it had staunched the massive drain on
its cash reserves that raised doubts in the minds of many
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The company, the largest online retailer, posted sales of $578
million, up 84 percent from a year earlier. But that was less than
analysts had expected and below the company's own internal target
of 90 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bezos, Amazon's chief executive, downplayed the shortfall,
noting that the company's operating profits exceeded its forecasts
because of lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a multibillion dollar business, growing sales by 84 percent
is rapid by any measure,'' Bezos said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the company has shifted its primary objective from
expanding sales to cutting costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two big buckets where we can invest: growth and
productivity,'' Bezos said. ``We instituted a strategy a year ago
to deploy more resources to improving operating efficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has many initiatives, including reducing excess
inventory and putting multiple-item orders into a single box,
rather than shipping them from separate warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Amazon made a 10 percent profit on its shipping and
handling charges in the most recent quarter. In the first quarter,
its shipping costs exceeded shipping revenue by 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Bezos said that Amazon would not completely halt its
rapid expansion. He told investors in a conference call that it
planned to expand its international operations into a number of
additional countries over the next year and a half. Currently it
has operations in Germany and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than the $317 million loss determined by generally
accepted accounting principles, Amazon wants analysts to use its
own formula, which calculates its loss at only $116 million. This
figure excludes $110 million from its share of the losses in the
other Internet companies in which it owns major stakes, such as
Drugstore.Com. It also excludes $80 million in charges related to
acquisitions and $8 million in employee stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding those items, Amazon's loss comes to 33 cents a share.
Analysts had been expecting an operating loss of 35 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon took pains to counter the views of some analysts who have
said that if it continues to lose money at its current rate, it
could run out of cash as soon as the end of this year. The
company's cash did decline to $908 million at the end of the
quarter, from $1 billion at the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Jenson, Amazon's chief financial officer, said that by
the end of the year, the company should be back to $1 billion in
cash. But, he acknowledged, that is largely because Amazon, like
all retailers, benefits from the cash from Christmas sales, but
does not have to pay its vendors for two months. Accordingly, its
cash balance will dip in the first quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen declined to predict whether the company would add or lose
cash next year, or for that matter whether it would have a profit
or a loss. He did say, however, that he expects the company's
losses as a percent of sales to decline steadily.
</P>
<P>
   The company boasted that its loss, using its preferred formula,
was 15 percent of sales in the recent quarter down from 21 percent
of sales a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Becker, an analyst with Lehman brothers, praised the
company for the increased efficency, but said investors would
penalize it for the revenue shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors love predictable sales,'' Becker said. ``The fact
the revenues are hard to predict may have a long term effect on
their valuation.'' Becker downgraded Amazon's shares Wednesday
before the earnings were released.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Amazon shares fell by $1.56 to $36.06, on word of
Becker's downgrade and perhaps in continued reaction to the
resignation of Amazon's president Joseph Galli, who said Tuesday
that he would become chief executive of VerticalNet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. STORY CAN END HERE) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &QL; 
Amazon has grown so quickly, but its ambitions are so vast, that it
engenders strong opinions among investors both positive and
negative, although the later have predominated lately, with its
stock off 53 percent for the year.
<P>
   Amazon has become a huge business, with a total of 22.5 million
customers, up 2.5 million in the last quarter. Indeed the company
estimates it has done business with 8 percent of households in the
United States. And its first business, books, has become a major
force in the publishing industry. In July, it sold 410,000 copies
of ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' accounting for nearly
10 percent of the print run for the book
</P>
<P>
   The big debate among investors has been the wisdom of Amazon's
expansion strategy, now that it has moved to offer a broad range of
items.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the most recent quarter, Amazon's combined book,
music and video business in the United states made a a $10 million
profit based on sales of $385 million. A year earlier that business
lost 11 million on sales of $280 million.
</P>
<P>
   The German and British units, lost $35 million on sales of $73
million. A year ago they lost $16 million on sales of $31 million.
</P>
<P>
   And the new business together lost $65 million on sales of $119
million. A year ago, the company was just entering the toy and
electronics businesses, which lost $40 million on sales of 3
million.
</P>
<P>
   Bezos said he was heartened that these new product lines posted
sales at an annual rate of $500 million a year, and he noted that
sales of consumer electronics were growing particularly briskly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question was could we move beyond media products,'' Bezos
said. ``Now the question is how much of the $5 trillion retail
market can we address.''
</P>
<P>
   But Becker said she was not impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should expand into other categories, but it may take more
time and will be more expected than I had hoped,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
