</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- July 26, 2000 -- CIR-DIGITAL-ORGANS-2 --
The issue of the true sound of a pipe organ and its replacement by
electronic counterparts  is at the center of a deeply passionate
debate.  It is one thing, many musicians argue, to improve the sound
of a pipe, but another entirely to abolish it. The Fifth Avenue
Presbyterian Church in Manhattan recently overhauled its main pipe
organ, adding some 'electronic voices' to the pipe sounds. (David
Corio/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- July 26, 2000 -- NY-LOST-NEIGHBORHOOD --
Since early June, researchers have been poking and prodding the
gentle, grassy slopes of Central Park with electrical currents,
electromagnetic waves and ground-penetrating radar looking for
remnants of Seneca Village, a community of more than 260 people that
once stood between Seventh and Eight Avenues from 82nd to 89th
Streets, was razed to make way for Central Park in 1857. Researchers
will release their findings on Thursday. (Ruby Washington/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MONTCLAIR, N.J. -- July 26, 2000 --
CIR-CELLPHONES-RISKS -- After  several of the world's  largest cell
phone manufacturers, including companies like Nokia, Motorola and
Ericsson,  said last week that they planned to release more
information  on the radiation levels of their devices, it will be
harder to ignore the debate over health risks and mobile phones. A
man took a call from his wife while his daughter played soccer in
December. (Susan Farley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- July 26, 2000 --  CIR-BACH-ONLINE -- Even
among serious students of Bach, only the most privileged ever hope to
examine the composer's handwritten scores. Starting later this week,
using I.B.M. technology and timed to the 250th anniversary of Bach's
death, the Staatsbibliothek in Berlin and six other repositories of
Bach manuscripts will inaugurate online access to some of the
composer's documents, scanned and digitized from high-quality color
slides. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ST. PETER, Minn. -- July 26, 2000 --
CIR-DIGITAL-ORGANS -- Charles Hendrickson, president of Associated
Pipe Organ Builders of America, and the Hendrickson Organ Company in
St. Peter, Minn., stands in fornt of the Tracker action pipe organ
which he and his company custom built in 1977 for St. Peter's First
Lutheran Church. Hendrickson is trying keep the use of pipe organs
alive in America and stem the tide of conversion to digitally
synthesized electronic replicas. (Matthew F. Witchell/The New York
Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- July 26, 2000 -- CIR-LIBRARY-OF-COMMERCE
-- The Library of Congress is charged with collecting the creative
work of the American people. But now the nation's creativity extends
to  Web sites, electronic journals and magazines, and CD-ROM's of
every sort. And the library is lagging in collecting and archiving
that digital material, according to a report released Wednesday.  The
dome of the Jefferson Building of the Library of Congress at left in
1997. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- July 26, 2000 -- COLUMBIA-RESEARCH -- The
rush is on by universities to cash in on the intellectual work of
their professors. Leading the pack is Columbia University, which
earns more than any other university in research and patents. Micheal
Crow, Columbia's executive vice president and provost, in his office
on the school's campus. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PORTLAND, Maine -- July 26, 2000 -- FOOD-PORTLAND-BOS
-- Street vendor Perry Mogul supplies hot dogs and a good laugh in
Portland.  Fast-talking, funny, incurably cheerful, and startlingly
observant, Mogul operates Perry's Sidewalk Cafe Almost Famous Since
1994, a mobile hot dog stand. Once you've met him, you won't easily
forget him. (Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- July 26, 2000 -- MASS-UFUND-BOS --  U. Fund,
a state-sponsored program of mutual funds run by Fidelity
Investments. The plan is one of dozens that have sprung up nationwide
since 1998, fueling a fast-growing $6 billion college-savings
industry. Pardaman Bahan and his wife, Harpal, with Sonya, 4, and
Aman, 12. The Bahans decided to invest in the U. Fund to pay for
their children's college tuition.  (David L. Ryan/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- July 26, 2000 -- THEATER-CORPORATIONS-2 --
Not so long ago the nonprofit Roundabout Theater Company was
performing plays for 150 people in a supermarket basement. Thursday
night, the company will open its first show in its elegant new
750-seat theater. The showplace is named the American Airlines
Theater,  in exchange for an $8.5 million payment from American
Airlines. Todd Haimes, the theater's artistic director, in the
theater during renovations.  (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- July 26, 2000 -- THEATER-CORPORATIONS-1 --
Not so long ago the nonprofit Roundabout Theater Company was
performing plays for 150 people in a supermarket basement. Thursday
night, the company will open its first show in its elegant new
750-seat theater, seen Tuesday. The showplace is named the American
Airlines Theater,  in exchange for an $8.5 million payment from
American Airlines. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LANAI CITY, Hawaii -- July 26, 2000 --
TRAVEL-LANAI-LADN-2 -- Lanai, a former pineapple plantation that is
minimally developed, is an island of wide open spaces, an nowhere is
it more evident than on the Koloiki Ridge Trail. The payoff for a
hike here is a sweeping overlook that takes in the neighboring
islands of Molokai and Maui. (Eric Noland/Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LANAI CITY, Hawaii -- July 26, 2000 --
TRAVEL-LANAI-LADN-1 -- Serenity is issued with the room key at the
Manele Bay Hotel on Lanai. The pool overlooks idyllic Hulopoe Beach,
a nice spot for sunning, swimming or walking. There isn't much danger
of rain spoiling your vacation here since Lanai is much drier than
its Hawaiian island cousins, and Manele Bay barely gets to double
digits in annual rainfall. (Eric Noland/Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- July 26, 2000 -- CHENEY-PROFILE-B&AMP;W--
Dick Cheney as White House chief of staff under President Gerald Ford
in 1975. Cheney was just 34. Before turning 50, Cheney had had three
mild heart attacks and a quadruple bypass operation. (The New York
Times) *LITE
</P>
