<P>
   (NYT29) CORTEZ, Colo. -- July 26, 2000 --
COLO-FIRES-ARCHEOLOGY-2 -- As a wildfire continues to race through
Colorado's Mesa Verde National Park in Cortez, Colo., and
firefighters battle the 22,000-acre blaze, archaeologists have
scrambled ahead of it, working to identify previously undiscovered
ancient native American sites. By Wednesday, at least a dozen new
ones had been found. Faith Duncan was among the archaeologists
working to preserve the Paleo-Indian sites that are threatened as
fire crews try to extinguish wildfires raging through the park.
(Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) CORTEZ, Colo. -- July 26, 2000 --
COLO-FIRES-ARCHEOLOGY-1 -- Brush fires burn down a hillside in
Colorado's Mesa Verde National Park in Cortez, Colo., where
firefighters continued to battle a 22,000-acre blaze ignited last
Thursday after a lightning strike on private land. National Park
Service archaeologists have found both positive and negative in the
situation, finding new archaeological sites and seeing increased
erosion in the area. (Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) PHILADELPHIA -- July 26, 2000 --
REPUBLICAN-CONVENTION-FLOATER -- Philadelphia is exuding the anxious
headiness of a theater production in the final throes of rehearsing a
command performance for the nation. This year's gathering of
Republicans will be Philadelphia's first national political
convention since 1948, and many residents are eager to show off the
city's revival. At Philadelphia's First Union Center, carpenters
prepare delegate seating signs. Preparations are proceeding on
schedule for the start of next week's Republican National Convention.
(Jim Wilson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) EAST BRUNSWICK, N.J. -- July 26, 2000 --
NY-KOREA-ADOPTEES-2 -- Today, international adoptions are being
handled with more guidance. Would-be parents are screened for
cultural sensitivity and join adoption support groups. The children
are being sent to culture camps and play groups with the goal of
helping them navigate the psychological journey to their new homes.
Thomas Masters, 46, a Korean-American adopted at an early age, serves
as a guide to help other adopted Koreans assimilate to their new
lives and surroundings. Masters, with a picture of his adoptive
family. (Richard Perry/The New York Times) Eds note: Story moved on
July 25, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- July 26, 2000 -- NY-KOREA-ADOPTEES-1 --
Today, international adoptions are being handled with more guidance.
Would-be parents are screened for cultural sensitivity and join
adoption support groups. The children are being sent to culture camps
and play groups with the goal of helping them navigate the
psychological journey to their new homes. Dottie Enrico, left, and
Greg Dankert with their daughter, Eleanor. (Andrea Mohin/The New York
Times) Eds note: Story moved on July 25, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) PINEVILLE, Kent. -- July 26, 2000 --
ILLITERACY-UNEMPLOYMENT-2 -- Sounding the alarm, politicians and
advocates for the poor have begun putting entrenched illiteracy at
the root of privation in places like Appalachia and the Mississippi
Delta that economic growth has largely ignored. Marsha Hendrickson
reads with her daughter Crystal Turner, 7, and her son Jacob Debusk,
4, earlier this week. Hendrickson participated in a program to help
her prepare for finding a job. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MIDDLESBORO, Kent. -- July 26, 2000 --
ILLITERACY-UNEMPLOYMENT-1 --  Sounding the alarm, politicians and
advocates for the poor have begun putting entrenched illiteracy at
the root of privation in places like Appalachia and the Mississippi
Delta that economic growth has largely ignored. Evelyn Muncy studies
for her general equivalency diploma with the help of Joe Miracle, a
member of AmeriCorps Volunteer In Service To America, at the
Middlesboro Learning Center at the Salvation Army building in
Middlesboro earlier this week. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SARASOTA, Fla. -- July 26, 2000 --
DISABILITIES-ACT-ANNIVERSARY -- Wednesday marked the 10th anniversary
of the signing of the Americans With Disabilities Act which bars
discrimination based on physical limitations and requires wheelchair
ramps and other accommodations for the disabled. Matt Hightower 44,
left, an employee at Sweet Tomatos Restaurant in Sarasota, greeted
customers earlier this week who were stopping for lunch at the
restaurant. (Rod Millington/Sarasota Herald Tribune)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- July 26, 2000 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W --
Installing a floor-mounted toilet -- as opposed to the type mounted
on a wall  -- is not difficult, but it has to be done carefully and
methodically or else the toilet will leak. Before buying a new
toilet, remove the old one and measure the "rough-in"  dimension. (Ed
Lipinski/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- July 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JULY 23--
DANCE-LINCOLN-FESTIVAL --  "Lincoln Center Out of Doors" aims to
increase community participation in the center's activities and make
use of the vast, empty plazas in and around the music complex. Kyung
Wook Chung, a Korean dancer, practices the mask dance at the Korean
Traditional Performing Arts Association studio in Manhattan. This
humorous mask dance orginates from Shamanic rites and ritual dances
from Northern Korea. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- July 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JULY 30 --
EBAY-ART-2 --  There is a growing and radical phenomenon of people
who are buying art from the virtual world from sellers they can't
see. EBay, an online auction site, lists almost 4 million items
organized into 2,900 categories for just this type of buying. Victor
Vasarely, who popularized the Op-Art movement which flourished in the
1960s, is now snubbed by most serious collectors. This Vasarely
print, titled "Vertigo," was purchased for $225, frame included, from
eBay. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LUBBOCK, Texas -- July 26, 2000 --
SUB-BUSH-BIO-V-2-B&AMP;W -- In 1978, George W. Bush, then 31,  was trying
to get a start in politics by running for Congress here in west
Texas. Bush lost that race for Congress. Yet the story of his entry
into politics, and particularly of that campaign, suggests that it
left a deep imprint on him, one that is evident today as he campaigns
for the White House. (The Midland Reporter-Telegram)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LUBBOCK, Texas -- July 26, 2000 -- SUB-BUSH-BIO-V-B&AMP;W
-- In 1978, George W. Bush, then 31,  was trying to get a start in
