House. (The Midland Reporter-Telegram)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- July 26, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JULY 30 --
EBAY-ART-1 --   There is a growing and radical phenomenon by people
who are buying art they can't see from sellers they can't see. EBay,
an online auction site, lists almost 4 million items organized into
2,900 categories, one of which is fine art. A search for Vincent Van
Gogh yields hundreds of items ranging from a supposed original
painting priced at $1 million, to this pinkish rubber object
described with typical eBay poetry as "Van Gogh's Ear -- squish it,
squeeze it!"   (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 26, 2000 -- CIR-DIGITAL-ORGANS-3 --
The issue of the true sound of a pipe organ and its replacement by
electronic counterparts  is at the center of a deeply passionate
debate.  It is one thing, many musicians argue, to improve the sound
of a pipe, but another entirely to abolish it. At the Fifth Avenue
Presbyterian Church in Manhattan, organist Terence J. Flanagan plays
the church's main pipe organ, which was recently overhauled adding
some 'electronic voices' to the pipe sounds. (David Corio/The New
York Times)
</P>
