<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of
tonight's New York Times Photo Package, moving Wednesday, 07/26/00.
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
213-237-4577 or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) CORTEZ, Colo. -- July 26, 2000 --
COLO-FIRES-ARCHEOLOGY-2 -- As a wildfire continues to race through
Colorado's Mesa Verde National Park in Cortez, Colo., and
firefighters battle the 22,000-acre blaze, archaeologists have
scrambled ahead of it, working to identify previously undiscovered
ancient native American sites. By Wednesday, at least a dozen new
ones had been found. Faith Duncan was among the archaeologists
working to preserve the Paleo-Indian sites that are threatened as
fire crews try to extinguish wildfires raging through the park.
(Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) CORTEZ, Colo. -- July 26, 2000 --
COLO-FIRES-ARCHEOLOGY-1 -- Brush fires burn down a hillside in
Colorado's Mesa Verde National Park in Cortez, Colo., where
firefighters continued to battle a 22,000-acre blaze ignited last
Thursday after a lightning strike on private land. National Park
Service archaeologists have found both positive and negative in the
situation, finding new archaeological sites and seeing increased
erosion in the area. (Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) PHILADELPHIA -- July 26, 2000 --
REPUBLICAN-CONVENTION-FLOATER -- Philadelphia is exuding the anxious
headiness of a theater production in the final throes of rehearsing a
command performance for the nation. This year's gathering of
Republicans will be Philadelphia's first national political
convention since 1948, and many residents are eager to show off the
city's revival. At Philadelphia's First Union Center, carpenters
prepare delegate seating signs. Preparations are proceeding on
schedule for the start of next week's Republican National Convention.
(Jim Wilson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) EAST BRUNSWICK, N.J. -- July 26, 2000 --
NY-KOREA-ADOPTEES-2 -- Today, international adoptions are being
handled with more guidance. Would-be parents are screened for
cultural sensitivity and join adoption support groups. The children
are being sent to culture camps and play groups with the goal of
helping them navigate the psychological journey to their new homes.
Thomas Masters, 46, a Korean-American adopted at an early age, serves
as a guide to help other adopted Koreans assimilate to their new
lives and surroundings. Masters, with a picture of his adoptive
family. (Richard Perry/The New York Times) Eds note: Story moved on
July 25, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- July 26, 2000 -- NY-KOREA-ADOPTEES-1 --
Today, international adoptions are being handled with more guidance.
