<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4051 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-THEATER-SHAKESPEARE-U     07-26 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-SHAKESPEARE-UTAH-$ADV30-2TAKES(Trims)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE LAND OF SHAKESPEARE AND BRIGHAM YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR CITY, Utah _ Flags on Main Street here proclaim ``Tony
2000.'' At the town's Utah Shakespearean Festival, not far from the
majestic Bryce Canyon and Zion national parks, the organizers,
actors and volunteers are still a bit dazed about having won the
regional theater Tony Award last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began in 1962 with just about nothing, a budget of $1,000
and lots of volunteers,'' said Fred C. Adams, 69, the buoyant
founder and executive producer of the festival. ``This Tony Award
was a validation of what we've been striving for over the last four
decades.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a validation of a resilient regional theater that
was virtually unknown in New York until the Tonys but well known
among a Shakespeare underground in the heartland. As many as
155,000 theatergoers, mostly young families and older people from
the Midwest and Far West, surge into this sedate mountain town in
the southwestern corner of Utah each summer for afternoons and
evenings of professional theatrical productions.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that there is a substantial and adoring audience ``out
there'' for Shakespeare as well as other dramatists _ not in New
York or Chicago or Los Angeles but in Utah _ might surprise the
Broadway and Off Broadway crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is destination theater,'' said Anthony DeFonte, who is
performing three roles this summer, including Shylock in ``The
Merchant of Venice,'' and has appeared in a number of television
series. ``It's a place where people decide to take a vacation _ to
see six plays in a few days and visit the national parks nearby.
And they're a wonderfully attentive and responsive audience. They
love the ritual of theater and we frequently get standing ovations.
They are really moved by Shakespeare's work.''
</P>
<P>
   Another actor at the festival echoed DeFonte. ``Audiences gasp
openly, they laugh openly, they applaud, there's deep silence,''
said Kathleen McCall, who is playing Portia to DeFonte's Shylock.
``And they are willing to be challenged,'' she added, seated on the
theater's lawn in the pulsing heat before rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's daunting for me,'' McCall said, ``as for all of us,
because they know their Shakespeare so well. Some will come with
the plays, actually reading them as you perform. They'll look at
you strangely if you say a wrong word. They really know the text.
I'm sure at some point I'm going to have people from the audience
saying `the quality of mercy' speech with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Like some of the other 18 Equity actors who have the top roles
this season, McCall has worked on Broadway, Off Broadway and in
regional theaters. Auditions are held in January and February in
major cities like New York, Chicago and Los Angeles. Some roles are
cast with undergraduates; actor-interns are hired for nonspeaking
parts and musical choruses.
</P>
<P>
   The mood at the festival, with its two theaters _ outdoor and
indoor _ its behind-the-scenes tours, lectures and festivities on
the lawns of Southern Utah University (part of the festival grounds
are on the campus), seems ebullient _ almost innocent. The
afternoon that Adams and other executives of the theater returned
from New York after the Tony ceremony, the 350 members of the
festival's company and 400 volunteers lined up around the theaters
and passed the award from one person to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were the hands that made it possible,'' Adams said. ``It
was a very moving hour.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, nearly 200 people were sitting on the lawn at dusk,
waiting to enter the 888-seat outdoor Adams Memorial Shakespearean
Theater. It is modeled after the Globe Theater in which
Shakespeare's plays were produced in London, and it is named after
a major benefactor of the festival, Grace Adams Tanner (a distant
cousin of Adams'), and her parents. The audience, which would see
``The Merry Wives of Windsor,'' was being entertained by ``The
Greenshow,'' half a dozen dancers and singers in Renaissance
costume.
</P>
<P>
   Watching them, Nancy Lindon, who grew up in suburban New York,
and her husband, Arthur, who retired in 1992 as director of public
works for the Village of Old Westbury, N.Y., said they had been
visiting the festival for three or four years and loved the plays _
at least most of them. The retired couple live in Pinehurst, N.C.,
but spend their summers in Park City, Utah, in the northern part of
the state, the home of the Sundance Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The caliber of acting is first-rate,'' Lindon said. ``We saw
`Peter Pan' today, and it was fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife nodded. ``We come here for two days and see four shows,
and I love it. I'm from New York. I've seen a lot of theater.
That's top-drawer theater. Well, so is this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lindons voiced one qualification. ``The musicals _
sometimes,'' Lindon said. ``Last year we saw `Damn Yankees' and it
was not good. Doing a musical is not easy. We did see `A Funny
Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum' here. That was excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Heather Hill, an electronics teacher in Bountiful, Utah,
and her husband, Warren, a dean at Weaver State University in
Ogden, Utah, north of Salt Lake City, said they had been making the
five-hour drive from Ogden to the festival for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All kinds of people come here; you meet a lot of teachers and
people interested in the theater and Shakespeare,'' said Hill, who
with his wife used to live on the East Coast and in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``These plays are utterly timeless,'' Hill said. ``I remember
going to Stratford, Ontario, to see `Henry V.' It was during the
Vietnam War. He made the speech to the soldiers going into battle
and they were asking, `What are we fighting for?' And I thought,
`My goodness, nothing has changed.' Last year we saw `King Lear'
here. The dynamics of the family is absolutely the same today as it
was back then.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   A typical visitor can see all six productions in three days by
choosing matinee and evening performances in both theaters. The
roster this 39th season _ from June 26 to Sept. 2 _ is, in many
ways, typical of the selections each year. In addition to ``The
Merchant of Venice'' and ``The Merry Wives of Windsor,'' the third
Shakespearean production is ``The War of the Roses'' (an adaptation
of ``Henry VI: Parts 1, 2 and 3'' by Howard Jensen, a festival
director).
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare may dominate the calendar but other authors, of
usually mainstream dramas, comedies and musicals, are equally
popular. This year the festival is presenting Chekhov's ``Cherry
Orchard,'' Michael Frayn's farce ``Noises Off'' and an adaptation
of ``Peter Pan'' by Adams, who is also directing. A separate fall
season, held indoors in the Randall L. Jones Theater, runs from
Sept. 14 to Oct. 14. The productions there this season will be the
musical revue ``Always . . . Patsy Cline'' and ``Driving Daisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the festival takes place in a conservative state founded
by Mormons, the selection of non-Shakespeare plays has stirred some
delicate issues for the organizers, many of them Mormon themselves.
Dramas, comedies or musicals with sex, blunt language or edgy
themes can be unwelcome. In ``Noises Off'' this season, the
festival received permission from Frayn to alter the line ``Oh, my
God.'' Now it reads, ``Oh, my Lord.'' Tennessee Williams' ``Glass
Menagerie'' was a big hit several years ago, as was Arthur Miller's
``Death of a Salesman.'' But while ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' has
been done, Tony Kushner's ``Angels in America'' (in which a main
character is a gay Mormon) would very likely be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   A festival press representative put it this way: ``We don't
restrict ourselves because of the content of plays but rather
because of whether the audience would go. So we wouldn't do `Angels
in America' because we probably wouldn't get an audience to watch
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it would be inaccurate to label the festival tradition-bound
and cloaked in the culture of conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Ina Marlowe, the director of ``The Merchant of Venice'' this
year and the managing director of the Organic Theater in Chicago,
said: ``I didn't know any of these people when I came here and it's
been an amazing experience. They have been totally open and
welcoming to me as a woman director. I don't often get that in
larger cities. I was not expecting it.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen F. Conlin, who staged ``The Cherry Orchard'' this
summer and is the festival's casting director, put it another way:
``When you look at the history of Utah, right from the beginning
the church was pro art, music and drama. Brigham Young said drama
was the best way to teach moral values _ especially for those
people who couldn't read. One of the first major buildings
constructed in Salt Lake when the pioneers arrived was a theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Adams, the festival's founder, said that
Shakespeare's dramas struck a chord for audiences in general: ``We
haven't changed since Shakespeare's time. The same longings, the
same cravings, the same desires.'' Mormons, he said, were
especially stirred by Shakespeare: `` `The Merchant of Venice' is
one of the popular plays for Mormon audiences. They see the victim
in Shylock. Having been victimized themselves in their own history,
Mormons take great comfort in seeing this portrayal of humanity
victimized by people who profess to be Christians.'' (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   By every account, the festival owes its birth and growth to
Adams, a friendly and exuberant former actor. A Mormon, he grew up
in central Utah, yearning to be an actor. After a stint in the Army
he went to New York, where he worked in several Off Broadway shows
and was a ``swing'' dancer, an understudy, in the 1953 Cole Porter
musical ``Can-Can.'' By the late 1950s, though, he had moved back
to Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York didn't need me and it was important to find a place
that did,'' he said. He took a job in Cedar City at the small
junior college that grew into the university. His task was to set
up a drama department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community was going through a real letdown,'' he recalled.
``The iron mines had closed. The economy was shattered. At that
point I said to the mayor and the city council that I wanted to
start a Shakespeare festival. They thought I was crazy. The idea of
Shakespeare didn't seem to impress any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a local Lions Club, Adams began the festival in
1962 with ``Hamlet,'' ``The Merchant of Venice'' and ``The Taming
of the Shrew.'' Students and local townspeople played the roles on
a makeshift stage. Most of them made their own costumes. They also
put on productions of ``On Borrowed Time'' by Paul Osborn and the
Jule Styne musical ``Bells Are Ringing.'' The festival made a
profit of $2,000 _ and Adams was home free.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the budget has climbed to more than $5 million, nearly 80
percent of it from the sale of tickets, which cost from $18 to $40.
The rest of the money comes from foundation support and private
donors, mostly in Salt Lake City, Las Vegas, Los Angeles and
Phoenix. In 1989, the company opened its second space, the stylish
Randall L. Jones Theater (named after the father of tourism in the
region), at a cost of $5.5 million. And now there is a Web site:
www.bard.org.
</P>
<P>
   The festival's appeal has started to lure travelers from the
East Coast. ``I was dubious at first about Shakespeare in Utah _
and very reluctantly I went,'' said Kenneth Adelman, a director of
the Arms Control and Disarmament Agency during the Reagan
administration, who has taught Shakespeare courses at Georgetown
and George Washington universities. ``And it blew me out of the
water. This place is in the middle of nowhere. And what you get is
extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Adelman and his family began attending the festival a dozen
years ago. This year, he and about 35 friends from New York,
Chicago, Washington, Buffalo and other cities are attending.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the Tony Award has given the festival a visibility it
never had, and Adams said he expected audiences as well as
fund-raising to surge.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he still seemed almost overwhelmed by the
award. At the festival's opening night this summer, Adams described
walking along the red carpet to enter Radio City Music Hall to
accept the Tony.
</P>
<P>
   For the man who didn't make it on Broadway nearly 50 years ago,
it was an especially sweet triumph. ``At long last,'' he said.
``We've been recognized!'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
