<HEADER>
A4054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-CORNERS0727-COX     07-26 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CORNERS0727-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Friends share it all
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Ray Buchanan wasn't kidding when he said he
rolled in the grass when he heard that the Falcons were going to
sign Ashley Ambrose. Buchanan's life was going to improve in two
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose is his best friend, dating back to their days together
as Indianapolis Colts, 1993-95. Their families take vacations
together, they have dabbled in rap music side by side, and they are
roommates in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   And on the football field, Ambrose figures to take a load off
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Both have been Pro Bowl cornerbacks. So now, instead of Buchanan
chasing an opponent's best receiver, he can share the duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was difficult,'' said Buchanan, who followed his
1998 Pro Bowl season with a slow start in 1999. Other teams ``knew
what I was going to be doing in certain situations, and that made
it easy to pick on.''
</P>
<P>
   In offseason telephone conversations, Buchanan told Ambrose,
``Hey, if I don't get somebody in here quick, I ain't going to last
that long.'' Ambrose was about to become a free agent in his
hometown of New Orleans,
</P>
<P>
   When Dan Reeves met with each Falcon player after last season,
Buchanan had a message for the coach: ``I said. 'Sign Ashley
Ambrose.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who made a soft run at Ambrose when he was a free
agent in 1999, wasted little time going hard after him this year.
</P>
<P>
   Early on Feb. 11, the first day of free-agency, Ambrose and his
wife, Monica, were getting ready to leave for the airport when the
telephone rang. Ambrose's agent, Kennard McGuire, said the Falcons
not only were interested but also were waving around a lot of
money.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose wife flew to Cincinnati for a wedding, but he flew to
Atlanta. By the time Ambrose's flight landed at Hartsfield, McGuire
had fielded calls from the Cowboys, Bears, Chargers and other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerback already had made up his mind, even if another
team beat the Falcon's offer. The five-year, $22.5 million contract
already had been worked out. It included a $7.5 million signing
bonus that tied the team high for running back Jamal Anderson a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy and content here,'' he said. ''I thought maybe
this could be a great team and we could do a lot of great things
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose did not show signs of greatness for a while in the NFL.
The Colts drafted him in the second round in 1992, but in four
seasons he started just 12 games and had five interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   After signing as a free agent in Cincinnati in 1996, however, he
instantly worked well with secondary coach Ron Meeks, who later
coached in Atlanta 1997-99.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose had eight interceptions that season, defended 20 passes
and made All-Pro.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, whom the Colts drafted in the third round in 1993,
became a full-time starter in 1994 and had 16 interceptions in four
seasons with Indianapolis. He joined the Falcons as a free agent in
1997, and has started all 48 games with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Ambrose, a free agent, could have made a lot of money
by returning to Cincinnati, but he wanted to get out.
</P>
<P>
   He signed in New Orleans for a two-year, $6.95 million deal so
heavily backloaded that $5.25 million of it was due this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints tried to re-work Ambrose' contract during the season
and offered a five-year, $25 million deal with a $6 million signing
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were thinking about it'' said Ambrose, who has started 63
of his past 64 games, ``but then (Saints owner Tom) Benson pulled
it. I don't think he was comfortable, because he knew he was going
to let (coach Mike Ditka, his staff and the front office) go.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose was released after the season because his contract would
not work with the salary cap. But the Saints made another run at
him before free-agency began.
</P>
<P>
   By then, his wife, a native of Indianapolis, had seen enough of
the Crescent City. ``She didn't like the crime,'' Ambrose said.
</P>
<P>
   The door was open for the Falcons, who quickly barged through.
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle, a Falcon for 14 years, thinks
Ambrose, 29, and Buchanan, 28, form the best corner combination he
has played with. They are better than Deion Sanders-Bobby Butler
and Sanders-Tim McKyer, according to Tuggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got two corners now who can cover,'' coach Dan Reeves
said. ``You can put them in isolated situations, something you have
to be careful of doing unless you have real good corners.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons should be able to blitz more often this season,
because they won't have to worry as much about double-teaming on
the side away from Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who is in the last year of his contract, wants to
return. Team officials have said they want to sign him to an
extension before he becomes a free agent. His agent, Atlanta's
Hadley Englehard, could meet with Falcons general manager Harold
Richardson next week to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Ambrose's presence won't do anything to reduce
Buchanan's chatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not like Beavis and Butthead, but we act silly,''
Buchanan said. ``It's kind of hard to find best friends, people you
can trust. But that's the way he is, and I'm glad he's here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are glad, too. And as long as they keep opposing
receivers from making a lot noise, Ambrose and Buchanan can act as
silly as they want to.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
