<HEADLINE>
ROUX MAKES HIS MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GERRY GITTELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Officially, Lionel Roux of France is the
Mercedes-Benz Cup's ``lucky loser'' because he lost late in
qualifing but he was a late replacement for Andre Agassi, who
withdrew because of a back injury.
</P>
<P>
   But Roux is playing like he belongs. After knocking off Taylor
Dent of Newport Beach in the first round, Roux eliminated Jan
Kroslak of Slovak Republic 6-3, 7-6 (7-2) Wednesday to advance to
the quarterfinals at UCLA's L.A. Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Roux, 27, has been ranked as high as 48th in the world and has
reached two ATP finals in his career, the last in 1997. But he was
ranked 255th in the world in 1998 and 190th last year.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently rejuvenated, Roux conquered Kroslak by taking
advantage of a huge first serve; he converted nine aces and won 83
percent of his first-serve points.
</P>
<P>
   He erased a 5-4 disadvantage in the second set, winning in 75
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   __ Spadea drops out: Vince Spadea, a member of the United States
Davis Cup team, withdrew because overhydration.
</P>
<P>
   He was examined early Wednesday by tournament doctor George
Fareed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' Spadea said. ``I was looking forward to
playing here. I really wanted to start the hard-court season off in
good fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   __ First time's a charm: Making his first Los Angeles appearance
as a professional, Paul Goldstein of Maryland beat Switzerland's
Lorenzo Manta in three sets.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, formerly of Stanford, overcame 10 aces. He hasn't
been spectacular on the ATP Tour, entering with a 13-15 career
singles record, but he's looking to parlay some momentum after
reaching Wimbledon's third round.
</P>
<P>
   __ In a rush: It hadn't even gotten hot yet, but Belgium's
Laurence Tieleman sure seemed in a rush to win his morning match
against Israel's Harel Levy. He needed just 51 minutes to triumph
6-4, 6-0, thanks to an overpowering first serve that helped him
record nine aces and win 27 of 32 first-serve points (84 percent).
</P>
<P>
   __ Neighborhood bully: Austalia's Mark Philippoussis, who
entered as the No. 2 seed but became the favorite when top-seeded
Agassi withdrew, defeated Colorado's Scott Humphries 7-5, 7-6 (7-2)
in a first-round matchup Wednesday. Philippoussis is seeking a rare
California trifecta after winning at Indian Wells and San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   __ Add Philippoussis: Philippoussis almost was ``discovered'' by
actor Anthony Quinn, who saw Philippoussis at the U.S. Open two
years ago and wanted him to appear in a movie as Quinn's son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthony called my agent and said he liked my looks,''
Philippoussis said. ``I was going to do the movie but they changed
the scheduling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4061 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-26 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS DRILL FOR OIL: No sooner had Dick Cheney been selected
as Gov. George W. Bush's running mate than the Democratic National
Committee put up a Web site, www.bush-cheney.net, as a parody of
the team. With a graphic of an oil well gushing dollars, the Web
site says the two men are ``covered with money from Big Oil'' and
features statements that Cheney's congressional voting record is
more conservative than that of Jesse Helms. A committee spokesman
said the site went up minutes after Cheney's selection was
announced and, so far, it has received more than 15,000 hits. ``We
like to think of our site as like `Dragnet,''' the spokesman said.
``It's just the facts, ma'am.'' The Bush campaign, which has
acquired a large number of domain names to prevent parody sites,
had apparently never purchased the Bush-Cheney combination. A
previous parody Web site by the Democrats was called ``Millionaires
for Bush'' and mocked Bush's tax cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Leslie Wayne
</P>
<P>
   THE HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   THE NEWEST REPUBLICAN: Rep. Matthew G. Martinez of California
became the latest party-switcher in the House on Wednesday in a
year marked by two other defections, one to each side. Martinez,
who was trounced in his Democratic primary earlier this year,
announced he was becoming a Republican, saying he was disappointed
that Democratic leaders did not do more to help him win
re-election. With his defection, Republicans hold a 223-to-210
advantage over Democrats in the House, not including two
independents. After 18 years in the House, Martinez was defeated by
Hilda Solis, a state senator, who portrayed him as out of touch
with his district. Since his primary defeat, Martinez, 71, has been
siding with Republicans, even on close votes like a
Republican-sponsored prescription drug plan, which passed by three
votes. ``Voters in this country won't forget in November how the
Democratic leadership has treated them for the last two years,''
said House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Lizette Alvarez
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   KEYES BACKS BUSH TICKET: He did not win a single presidential
primary or caucus, but Alan Keyes, the hard-right radio talk show
host, stayed on the campaign trail long after it was certain that
Gov. George W. Bush was going to be the Republican nominee. Winning
or losing was not as important to him, he insisted, as spreading
his message that the nation must rededicate itself to moral
principles and especially to outlawing abortion. But late Tuesday
in Boston, Keyes, the only black candidate in the 2000 presidential
field, pulled out. Asked if he still considered himself a candidate
with just a week to go before Bush is formally nominated in
Philadelphia, he replied: ``I am not.'' He said he would back the
Bush-Cheney ticket, noting that Bush and his running mate, Dick
Cheney, were strong opponents of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY PLAN PASSES RULES COMMITTEE: The Republican Party moved
a step closer Wednesday to adopting a presidential nomination plan
in which small states would vote first and big states last. The
rules committee of the Republican National Committee, which adopted
the proposal in May, reaffirmed its support of the plan, which was
intended to forestall a drift to a national primary, encourage more
candidates to stay in the race longer and ensure that more votes
matter than did this year, when the nominations were settled in
early March. The full national committee will vote on Thursday. The
most serious opposition is expected on Friday when the national
convention's rules committee takes up the proposal. Big states that
fear irrelevance from coming last, and traditional opponents of
giving the Republican National Committee more power, which would be
required to implement the plan, are joining to fight it there.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Adam Clymer
</P>
<P>
   THE MONEY RACE
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING AN EYE OUT FOR LOOPHOLES: The sponsors of new
legislation requiring financial disclosure by secretive political
fund-raising committees are worried that politicians have already
found a way around the new law. Sens. Joe Lieberman, D-Conn., and
John McCain, R-Ariz., have written to the Treasury Department and
the Internal Revenue Service to make clear that they intended the
new law to cover the fund-raising activities of all political
action committees. The issue arose because some lawyers suggested
that the new law, intended to require financial disclosure from
so-called Section 527 groups, named for a provision in the tax
code, might not apply to committees that raised both hard and soft
money. Hard money can be used for any political purpose; soft money
cannot be used to advocate the election or defeat of a specific
candidate. The lawyers said the law might not cover so-called
leadership PACs, which are fund-raising vehicles formed by
congressional leaders. The letters were signed by 17 senators and
four House members.
</P>
<P>
   _ By John M. Broder
</P>
<P>
   THE STATES
</P>
<P>
   GORE AHEAD IN NEW JERSEY: In New Jersey, which both parties view
as a crucial electoral battleground, Vice President Al Gore
continues to hold a slight lead over Gov. George W. Bush, according
to the latest Quinnipiac University poll. The survey of 910
registered voters taken July 19-24, with a margin of sampling error
of 3 percentage points, shows Gore with a lead of 46 percent to 41
percent in a one-on-one race. When small-party candidates are
included, Gore's lead is 42-38 over Bush, with 7 percent for Ralph
Nader and 2 percent for Patrick J. Buchanan. The survey was taken
before Bush's choice of Dick Cheney, who opposes abortion rights,
as his running mate, but the poll suggested that choosing a vice
presidential candidate who favored abortion rights would have done
little to help Bush in New Jersey: 15 percent said they would have
been more likely to vote Republican, 15 percent less likely, and 66
percent said it would have made no difference.
</P>
<P>
   _ By David M. Halbfinger
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
