LUMINENT FILES TO GO PUBLIC &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   CHATSWORTH, Calif. _ Luminent Inc., a company spun off from MRV
Communications in April, filed for an initial public offering
Wednesday to raise up to $207 million.
</P>
<P>
   Luminent will join a batch of new Internet infrastructure
component makers gone public, including Moorpark's Accelerated
Networks, which went public in June. Luminent counts among its
competitors giants like IBM, Lucent and Agilent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   MRV, also based in Chatsworth, said Credit Suisse First Boston
would lead the underwriting group with CIBC World Markets,
Robertson Stephens, U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray and First Security
Van Kasper serving as co-managers.
</P>
<P>
   The exact number of shares and their price range has not been
determined. MRV will own an undisclosed percentage of the company
when the IPO is finished but it plans to disperse its Luminent
holdings to MRV shareholders within six to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   News of the filing was not enough to sustain investor enthusiasm
throughout a trading day that saw most technology stock prices
drop. MRV finished the day down 19 cents to $71 a share on volume
of 7.1 million shares after trading as high as $76.75.
</P>
<P>
   Luminent, with 650 employees, makes fiber-optic network
components for communications networks. Before the Luminent
spinoff, MRV launched companies including router makers Zuma
Networks and Charlotte's Networks, communications infrastructure
maker Zaffire Inc., optical components companies RedC Networks and
Optical Crossing Inc. and business-to-business service provider
Hyperchannel.
</P>
