<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ford to Lift Fuel Economy Of Sport Utility Vehicles
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor has decided to increase the average fuel economy of
its sport utility vehicles by 25 percent over the next five years,
people involved in the company's plans said. The increase would be
the first significant change in the fuel economy of any class of
passenger vehicle in almost two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is convinced that Americans want to buy more fuel-efficient
vehicles and will steer their purchases to companies they perceive
as environmentally responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Argues for Its Day in Appeals Court
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft filed a legal document arguing that the government's
antitrust case is ``completely unsuitable for direct appeal'' to
the Supreme Court because it is complex and because the trial judge
made ``serious and substantive procedural errors.'' Microsoft wants
its appeal to go first to the federal appeals court in Washington,
which ruled in favor of the company in a related case.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox Shares Fall as Profit Declines
</P>
<P>
   Xerox said that its second-quarter profit fell by half on lower
sales and that efforts to turn around operations would take longer
than expected. Although the results met analysts' lowered
expectations, shares of Xerox fell $3.1875, to $15. Xerox is facing
increased competition and is trying to recover from a failed
reorganization that prompted the ouster of its chief executive in
May.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors Criticize Consulting Plan
</P>
<P>
   At a Securities and Exchange Commission hearing, representatives
of three major accounting firms strongly criticized a proposal to
restrict the types of consulting work that the firms can provide
for the companies whose financial statements they audit.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Fall on Profit Warnings
</P>
<P>
   Stocks tumbled after several companies warned that their profits
would be lower than expected in the second half of the year. The
Dow Jones industrial average dropped 183.49 points, or 1.7 percent,
to 10,516.48. The Nasdaq composite index fell 41.85 points, or 1
percent, to 3,987.72, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
decreased 22.05 points, or 1.5 percent, to 1,452.42.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler Posts Stronger Earnings
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler posted stronger second-quarter net income but
warned that full-year operating profit would face pressure as it
disclosed plans to cut costs. ``We will not fully match last year's
level,'' the company's chief executive, Juergen Schrempp, said in a
statement, referring to operating profits. The results beat
forecasts that were adjusted after previous warnings from the
automaker. Its shares rose $1.3125, to $53.5625.
</P>
<P>
   Sale of Japanese Bank Postponed
</P>
<P>
   Japanese regulators postponed by one month the sale of the
nationalized Nippon Credit Bank to a group of investors led by
Softbank, one of the world's largest Internet investment companies,
after some of Japan's most powerful politicians applied intense
pressure to the Financial Reconstruction Commission.
</P>
<P>
   German Bank Merger Is Called Off
</P>
<P>
   Two of Germany's largest banks, Dresdner Bank and Commerzbank,
said that they had abandoned negotiations on a merger, unable to
agree on the terms. The talks could have led to a deal worth at
least $19 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Exchange-Traded Funds Gain Favor
</P>
<P>
   Exchange-traded funds _ investment pools that are similar to
mutual funds but trade like stocks _ are gaining favor among
investors and may soon evolve into a viable alternative to a broad
range of traditional mutual funds, two new reports predict.
</P>
</TEXT>
