<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: TAX PLAN ATTACKED
</P>
<P>
   A proposal by president-elect Vicente Fox to eliminate sales-tax
exemptions for medicines and most groceries stirred an outpouring
of criticism on radio and television talk shows. Fox also proposed
eliminating taxes on new cars under a plan to simplify Mexico's
fiscal laws. He said he would use the new revenues to increase
welfare payments to Mexico's poor.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: CONSERVATIVE TO RUN
</P>
<P>
   Joe Clark has decided to run for Parliament in a by-election
expected for mid-September, seeking a central Nova Scotia seat seen
as safe for his party, the Progressive Conservatives. Clark, an
Albertan who briefly served as prime minister two decades ago,
announced the run one week after a similar election bid was
announced by his rightwing rival, Stockwell Day, the new leader of
the Canadian Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA, PAKISTAN: KASHMIR OFFER REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   The Mutihadda Jihad Council, an alliance of Pakistan-based
militant groups active in Kashmir, has suspended one of its leading
members _ the Hizbul Mujahideen _ after that organization made an
unexpected cease-fire offer to India. The militants vowed to
continue their struggle against Indian forces in the disputed
region.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA, IRAQ: PUSH END SANCTIONS
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin said after a meeting in Moscow with
Iraq's deputy prime minister, Tariq Aziz, that he would press for
an end to United Nations sanctions against Iraq. But he also urged
Iraq to allow United Nations weapons inspectors to resume their
work. Iraq owes Russia billions, which it would be able to repay if
it were able to freely export its oil. Russian companies are eager
for business in Iraq if sanctions are lifed.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: REFORMER SEEKS RE-ELECTION
</P>
<P>
   President Mohammad Khatami, elected on a reform platform that is
promising increased social freedoms, said for the first time that
he would seek a second term in elections next May. Khatami's
attempts since his landslide election in 1997 to promote a free
press and democratic reforms have been stymied by conservative
forces.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON: MISSING DECLARED DEAD
</P>
<P>
   A Lebanese government commission said it has concluded that some
17,000 people who disappeared during the 1975-1990 civil war are
dead. A seven-month investigation concluded that only a few of
those reported missing were actually alive and said that most
bodies found in mass graves will never be identified.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOMALIA: AID WORKERS ABDUCTED
</P>
<P>
   Two workers from Action Against Hunger were kidnapped in
Mogadishu and the French aid group issued a statement in Paris
saying it was negotiating for the release of the two employees,
Francoise Deutsch, 46, of France, and Jonathan Ward, 31, of
Britain. The Somali capital has been split by competing warlords
since the central government collapsed nearly a decade ago and
western aid agencies have repeatedly been targets for kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA: FIGHTING FOR CATTLE
</P>
<P>
   Rustling in the remote northeast of Uganda has claimed 95 lives,
the Ugandan army reported. Fights among the Jie and Dodoth members
of the Karimojong tribe over cattle are common, though a battle
last weekend between the two groups was more deadly than most. The
army reported that the Jie killed 15 Dodoth in a raid, then the
Dodoth killed another 80 Jie as they pursued their stolen cattle.
The Ugandan government has announced plans to disarm fighters in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: SENATOR INVESTIGATED
</P>
<P>
   The Senate president, Chuba Okadigbo, and several of his top
aides are under investigation for misappropriating public funds and
taking kickbacks from government contractors. At a Senate hearing,
Okadigbo was accused of misspending $370,000 on his new official
residence in the capital, Abuja.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
