<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4068 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-SPI &LR;      07-26 1717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING, AIRBUS READY FOR BATTLE OVER SUPER JUMBO JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARNBOROUGH, England _ Enough talk. It's time for Boeing and
Airbus to put on the heavy gloves and slug it out.
</P>
<P>
   A3XX vs. 747X Stretch. Twelve rounds. Heavyweight fight for
supremacy as the world's top commercial airplane maker.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, it doesn't look like a fair fight. How can Boeing take
an airplane design that is 30 years old and step into the ring
against an Airbus giant that won't even fly for the first time
until at least 2004?
</P>
<P>
   Better stop the fight before it begins. Boeing's first 747-100
lifted off from Paine Field in Everett, Wash., in February 1969.
It's now an aging museum piece at Boeing Field in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews with the Seattle Post-Intelligencer, Boeing's
leaders, the best and brightest of its engineers, even the father
of the 747 himself, all said a stretched version of the company's
flagship 747, with an improved wing, a new interior and other
modifications, will more than hold its own against the coming A3XX
super jumbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fifth generation (of the 747) is probably close to the
ultimate development of the airplane,'' said Joe Sutter, who was
chief engineer for the 747 program in the 1960s and is often called
the father of the jumbo jet.
</P>
<P>
   Though he retired from Boeing some years ago, Sutter has been
actively helping the company with the new design and came with the
Boeing team to the air show here.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter also recently accompanied Boeing executives to Singapore
on a mission to help convince Asia's most influential airline that
the 747X Stretch is a better option than the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Chairman Phil Condit said again Tuesday at Farnborough
that Boeing could launch its new and improved 747 within six to
nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus says it will launch the A3XX by the end of the year. So
it could be only a matter of months before the battle is joined _
``the final showdown'' between Boeing and Airbus, as a leading
industry analyst has put it.
</P>
<P>
   To set the stage for the coming battle, Airbus and Boeing have
been running large ads touting their respective planes in European
newspapers and industry publications that are distributed daily to
the thousands of air show participants.
</P>
<P>
   It's an expensive advertising campaign, but the stakes are high.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus does not have a plane that can fly more than 400
passengers. It needs the A3XX _ the baseline version of which will
seat about 555 passengers in three classes in a double deck
configuration _ to break Boeing's monopoly that it has enjoyed for
three decades with its 747.
</P>
<P>
   But the A3XX will cost $12 billion to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing says the market for planes bigger than the 747 _ the
latest version of which is the 747-400 that seats about 416
passengers in three classes _ is not big enough to justify the cost
of developing a new and bigger plane from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   So it has decided to go the derivative route and take the
current 747-400 and significantly improve the plane. This strategy
is far less costly.
</P>
<P>
   The project will likely cost $4 billion to $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   When Boeing decided to build the 747 in the 1960s, it was a
bet-the-company proposition. The $2 billion in development costs
was more than the entire company was worth.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Boeing has revenues of more than $50 billion a year. So
spending $4 billion to $5 billion does not carry the same risks.
</P>
<P>
   But if Boeing is wrong about the size of the market for a plane
bigger than the 747, then its strategy is wrong and it could take
years to recover with an entirely new big airplane, while the A3XX
firmly establishes itself in the market place.
</P>
<P>
   Condit knows the risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to believe very strongly that the way you are
successful is to put your money where your mouth is,'' he said in
an interview. ``Just doing what your competitor does is not the
road to success. ... What you do is make a decision that says, `I'm
going to put my product where I think the heart of the market is,'
and if your competitor doesn't think that's where the heart of the
market is, then one of you is going to be right and one of you is
going to be wrong. Just being equally wrong is not a good
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has made its decision. Much of the preliminary
engineering design work, in fact, is done.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to stretching the body of the existing 747-400,
Boeing plans to utilize overhead space in the rear for such things
as storage of galley carts. This frees room for as many as 18
additional seats in the main cabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important feature of this model,'' said John
Roundhill, vice president for product strategy and development who
is leading the 747X effort.
</P>
<P>
   When this extra room is combined with the additional seats from
stretching the fuselage, the 747X Stretch will be able to carry as
many as 520 passengers in three classes. That gets it close to the
seating capacity of the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   The stretch also will be fitted with the 777-style interior,
with its larger passenger baggage storage bins, and a more modern
cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important changes will be in the longer wings.
</P>
<P>
   A root insert where the wing joins the body will improve the
aerodynamics. The wing also gets what is called a ``trailing edge
wedge,'' which was developed by McDonnell Douglas for its MD-11.
</P>
<P>
   It essentially ``tricks'' the air foil and improves drag
characteristics by as much as 1.5 percent, Roundhill said.
</P>
<P>
   The 747-400 is already the fastest commercial jetliner today,
with a cruising speed of Mach .85 (Mach 1 is the speed of sound).
</P>
<P>
   The wing improvements will make the 747X Stretch even faster,
Roundhill said.
</P>
<P>
   The 747X Stretch would enter service in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus claims its A3XX will be on the order of 15 to 20 percent
more efficient than the 747-400.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing doesn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are showing an improvement in the A3XX that is beyond
anybody's imagination,'' said Seddik Belyamani, executive vice
president of sales and marketing for Boeing who got his engineering
degree in Toulouse, France, home of Airbus Industrie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are convinced it can't be done,'' he said of the claimed
A3XX operating efficiencies. ``They are dreaming ... any engineer
will tell you. Ask Joe Sutter. He would never design a double
decker. You are carrying around too much empty weight until you get
up to about 800 passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing looked at a double-decker design in the mid-1990s, when
it actually worked with rival Airbus on a study called the Very
Large Commercial Transport.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing eventually pulled out of the project. Airbus says
Boeing's real motivation for getting involved in the project was to
stall the A3XX project.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing says a double decker does not make sense as a 500- to
600-passenger plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were chief engineer (for Airbus), it would not be a
double decker,'' Sutter said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the actual operating improvements the A3XX will have
over the 747-400, Boeing says the 747X Stretch will be at least as
efficient as the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   And the freighter version of the 747X Stretch will be even
better than the freighter version of the A3XX, according to Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The 747X Stretch freighter will be able to carry as much cargo
as the A3XX, but have less weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to be able to match the 747X Stretch freighter
for 25 or 30 years, Sutter said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Boeing has to sell the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Waggener, Boeing's deputy director of product marketing,
has spent much of his time on the road in recent months, educating
airlines on the changes that are in store for the 747.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus has been aggressive in trying to launch the A3XX,'' he
said. ``In our view, they are pushing the market. What we are
hearing is that a majority of customers would just as soon see
neither airplane happen for a while. But if something is going to
happen, they want the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The key airline for Boeing and Airbus is Singapore Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are clearly the standard, the trend setter,'' said one
industry analyst who did not want to be quoted by name. ``Singapore
has the admiration of other airlines. If Airbus can convert
Singapore to the A3XX, everyone on the Boeing program understands
the implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Singapore is one of nine airlines that have expressed interest
in the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   After Singapore did so a couple of months ago, Boeing dispatched
a high-level team to talk to the airline about the 747X Stretch.
The team included Sutter and Larry Dickenson, Boeing's senior vice
president of sales.
</P>
<P>
   It was a productive trip, said Dickenson.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Singapore Airlines now has 53 747-400s in its
fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The airline is trying to access where it would need a plane
bigger than the 747-400, Dickenson said, and a good business case
can be made for a larger plane on the airline's twice-daily London
to Singapore route.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the 747X Stretch would be a natural fit there,''
Dickenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ozimek, Boeing's director of product marketing, said the
company is not out to simply knock down the A3XX with customers
such as Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been laying in the bushes on this program (747X) for
sometime, waiting to make sure we know what Airbus is doing before
we declare,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are serious. This is not some arm waving in front of a
whole bunch of people to convince them they should not buy the
Airbus plane. ... If the airlines are serious and they show
sufficient interest, that's where we are going next.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, according to Boeing's chairman, Airbus and Boeing
will both sell some planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we are all done, they will have sold several hundred,''
Condit said. ``But I don't think they will have sold 1,000 or any
number like that. Their ability to say in the end that this (A3XX)
has been a good investment, a proper use of shareholder funds,
well, they are going to have a real challenge there. That's what
the market is telling us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutter has no doubt that his baby, the 747, will still be
standing in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could be chief engineer on either of these projects, I'd
pick the 747X Stretch because I would be with the winner,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
