<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTING RECORD DOGS CHENEY AS GOP TEAM CAMPAIGNS
</HEADLINE>
  By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASPER, Wyo. _ Gov. George W. Bush and his new running mate,
Dick Cheney, made a whirlwind visit to the vice-presidential
contender's home state Wednesday, defending Cheney's conservative
voting record and vowing that the ticket would ``renew America's
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   In their first campaign trip, Bush struck more partisan tones
than usual, hammering away at the integrity and trustworthiness of
the Clinton administration. He presented the all-Western Republican
ticket as the antidote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick and I both have roots in the West,'' Bush of Texas told a
chanting crowd packed into the gymnasium of the high school that
Cheney, 59, attended. ``The West is a place full of straightforward
people who usually say what they mean and mean what they say.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bush reached back to one of President Clinton's well-known
evasions in the Monica Lewinsky scandal. ``The West is full of
people who understand the meaning of what the word is is,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Bush announced that he had selected his father's
former defense secretary as his running mate, the Texas governor
was quickly hit with questions about Cheney's voting record in his
decade in the House. He and the Gore campaign engaged in a fierce
cross-country competition to define what voters thought about
Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously thought about the record,'' Bush said. ``And this
is a conservative man. So am I.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor and his aides said the selection of Cheney showed
that Bush was putting political considerations aside to make a
sober-minded decision on a running mate who could serve as
commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings some strength to the administration,'' Bush said in
a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It speaks volumes that I'm willing to pick somebody who is as
strong a man as he is,'' Bush said, ``that I'm comfortable with
having excellence by my side.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also said the choice spoke volumes, about whether
Bush really is a new kind of Republican or a throwback to the past.
They pointed to Cheney's conservative voting record as well as his
service in the administrations of Presidents Richard M. Nixon,
Gerald R. Ford and George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's record included votes against the Head Start education
program, against banning so-called cop-killer bullets, against
imposing economic sanctions on the government of South Africa and
against a nonbinding House resolution calling for the release of
the anti-apartheid leader Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm generally proud of my record in the House,'' Cheney told
reporters. He said that he could ``probably find some'' votes
``that I might tweak and do differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney defended his votes, largely cast in the Reagan
administration, as appropriate to the 1980s ``when we had huge
budget deficits, no money and when we really had to be concerned
about controlling federal spending.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we're in a different era,'' he said. ``We've got a
surplus. We've got the opportunity now, I think, to go do some
things we could not have done 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by reporters to explain his stance on Mandela, Cheney
said he had voted against sanctions on South Africa because he has
generally opposed unilateral sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also turned aside Democratic questions about
their links to the oil industry. Cheney is stepping down as the
chief executive of the Halliburton Co., a worldwide oil services
company based in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of Halliburton,'' Cheney said. ``I have nothing
to apologize for.'' He described it as a company that had started
small as the brainchild of one man and become ``the quintessential
American success story.'' Bush said his opponents were trying to
``divert attention from the fact that the Democrats have no energy
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign presented the trip to Natrona High School as a
sentimental journey to the hometown where Cheney met his wife,
Lynne. He was the class president and a captain of the football
team. She was the prom queen, and as Bush added Wednesday, a
``nationally ranked champion baton twirler.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not a long and lingering homecoming. The appearance in
the school, the lone rally of the day, lasted about 45 minutes.
Aides said Cheney had to return to Dallas for a business meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A cheering crowd in the hundreds packed the gym and another
1,000 people waited in a spillover room.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Geringer warmed up the audience and dismissed the talk
of Cheney's voting record. ``I'd rather have Vice President Cheney
with his heart, than President Gore with no backbone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney gazed out at the crowd and said, ``They never treated me
this well when I was their congressman.'' And he joked that his
high school classmates would have been more likely to expect his
wife to return one day as a candidate on a national ticket. ``But
they never would have guessed it was going to be me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bush, not his running mate, who seemed in a feisty mood.
As he brought Cheney down the aisle of his campaign plane,
reporters asked the governor what he thought of the Democrats'
reaction to Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was it?'' he asked. ``Belittling? I'm not surprised that
they would try to belittle the pick. Typical.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
