<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COL-GONZALEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME MAT IS OUT, BUT WILL JUAN SEE IT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good morning, Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Wake up, sleepy head. Hope you slept well last night now that
you're back home in Texas. Here, let me open those curtains for you
and let some Lone Star sunshine back into your life.
</P>
<P>
   I brought up your newspaper _ the ``Star-Telegram'', of course _
some freshly squeezed orange juice and greetings from your old
friends, the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Anything else you need? Wash your Mercedes? Mow the lawn (I can
get to it right after I finish Galloway's). I'd massage that sore
foot of yours, but it seems that Luis Mayoral has that job well
handled, as always.
</P>
<P>
   Just wanted to let you know, Juando, that nobody around here
thinks you burned any bridges after the trade last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Folks in the Rangers' front office can't officially talk about
you and your impending free agency, because that would be tampering
you know, but I can assure you, as an outside source, that no one
bears you any ill will here.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, you had your occasional ``misunderstandings'' with the
manager, but you know Johnny Oates. He's as sweet a guy as you'd
ever hope to meet. He knows you have a good heart and mean well.
Besides, he has had guys 10 times worse than you pass through his
clubhouse, one or two since you've been gone.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, you were never a major problem, except maybe when your
pants didn't fit right or you wanted to skip the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the club was a little embarrassed over that situation,
but, hey, let bygones be bygones. That's all in the past now, and
it just so happens that the Rangers will go into the off-season
looking for a power-hitting, run-producing outfielder-DH.
</P>
<P>
   Duuuhhhh. Doesn't that just fit your description to a tee?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it did anyway before you went to Detroit. You've had a,
shall we say, forgettable season there. Not sure how smart it was
for you to stand up in front of your locker in the Tigers'
clubhouse at Comerica Park this week and suggest that maybe you'd
stick around if they'd just consent to cutting that left-field
power alley down to Yellowstone Park dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   I know, it's ridiculous. It's like the architect took a look at
left field one day during construction and said, ``Hmmm, why don't
we biggie-size it?''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, by now you should know that players, no matter how
good they are, can't dictate the dimensions of the playing field.
Just won't work and it doesn't sit well with the fans, especially
when you've spent a third of the season out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   I see where one of the Detroit papers ran a chart on your time
spent on the disabled list the other day. Looked pretty familiar,
actually.
</P>
<P>
   Your old buddies, Raffy and Pudge, have already suggested the
Rangers should get you back this off-season, and a Detroit
columnist irrationally said that the Tigers should send you back to
Texas before the trade deadline. I can assure you, that ain't going
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers are going to be doing anything this week, it'll
be dumping salary, not taking it on.
</P>
<P>
   But it could be another story this winter. Interested in coming
back home?
</P>
<P>
   They tell me you've never really been a good fit in Detroit,
which comes as no surprise to those who know you. There was never
any real expectation here that you'd be staying on with the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got this big new clubhouse there, a real major-league
clubhouse, with a big-screen TV and some couches and chairs down at
one end,'' a Detroit sportswriter friend was telling me the other
day. ``There's always a group of players down there. Then way down
at the other end of the clubhouse, there's Juan, all by himself
except for that entourage of his.''
</P>
<P>
   I've read where you, or more likely Mayoral, insist that you're
``happy'' in Detroit. Sorry, I'm not buying that. I know you too
well. I know with the paltry numbers you've put up, you can't be
very happy.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's the deal, Juando. There ain't gonna be no $140
million contract this winter. You had your chance at it and let it
go. Good for you. Money's not everything. But you're dead wrong if
you believe someone else out there is going to pony up that kind of
bread after the season you've had.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly won't be the Rangers. They might like to have you
come home, but it'll have to be at a price they're comfortable with
paying. And it almost surely won't include a job for your trusted
adviser, the affable Mayoral.
</P>
<P>
   You might not have burned any bridges here, Juan, but Luis most
likely did when he was quoted in ``Sports Illustrated'' blaming
poor John Blake, the Rangers' vice president in charge of media
relations, for the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Let me let you in on something: John Blake is probably the best
PR director in the history of professional sports, but he doesn't
have that kind of power. If he didn't like you, he never let me
know it, and I was around him regularly throughout your career in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   LAJ _ Life After Juan _ hasn't been so good for the Rangers.
Their outfield production this year stinks. Even if they decide to
come back next year with the three starters they opened with in
April, they'll still need a productive DH, part-time outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   You might need a job. They're going to have an opening.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes life actually looks as if there's some sort of grand
plan at work, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Go out there tonight and wow them, Juando. Make 'em remember
what the good times were like.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the first day of the rest of your life.
\Ntagtop:Jim Reeves, (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:revo\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
