<HEADLINE>
FERREIRA INTO QUARTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GERRY GITTELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We learned two things about Wayne Ferreira on
Wednesday: He's a slow starter, but more important he's a fast
finisher.
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira, South Africa's No. 1 tennis player, lost five of the
first seven games in his second-round match against Thailand's
Paradorn Srichaphan but triumphed 7-6 (7-1), 4-6, 7-5 to make the
Mercedes-Benz Cup quarterfinals at UCLA's L.A. Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   In an afternoon match lasting two hours, 17 minutes in
100-degree heat, fifth-seeded Ferreira was at his best at the end,
winning eight of the last nine points to take the final two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it just took a while to get my rhythm,'' Ferreira
said. ``He came out hitting hard from the very beginning and I
started kind of slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Thailand's Srichaphan is a Bjorn Borg disciple, preferring to
plant himself near the baseline and wait for passing-shot
opportunities or for his opponent to make the mistake. But toward
the end of the third set he changed his strategy _ perhaps even
panicked _ and foiled an opportunity for the tournament's first
major upset. Srichaphan began charging the net, and Ferreira,
stroking more confidently than ever in the latter stages, took
advantage with some wicked passing shots that clinched the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I was leading, I felt nervous, like Wayne was gonna
get me,'' Srichaphan said. ``I try not to think that way, but I
just didn't think I'd win. I tried to go for it too much at the end
and finish the points a little too fast, but I couldn't get them. I
tried my best, but Wayne's a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Srichaphan's collapse wasn't because he was fatigued. He pointed
out that practicing in sticky Bangkok is more grueling than any
conditions Los Angeles has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Ferreria impressed with his stamina. With some of the ATP's
biggest names not competing in this tournament _ top-seeded Andre
Agassi is among several impact players who bowed out because of
injuries _ Ferreira's victory might be just the platform he needs
to steal his first singles title in more than two years. His best
Los Angeles finish was last year when he reached the quarterfinals.
Wednesday's victory upped his ATP record to 25-13 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a long tough match, but I actually feel pretty
good,'' Ferreira said. ``I'm feeling confident and more positive.
It was hot today, but I've been here for a few days and I'm used to
the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira, 28, said he hasn't done much of anything since losing
in the fourth round at Wimbledon a month ago. He took a break from
tennis, deciding hanging out with his infant son and giving him his
6 a.m. feedings was more important than brooding about the way he
lost at Wimbledon _ to 237th seed Vladimir Voltchkov.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided to be a dad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He did make a resolution before coming to Los Angeles, vowing to
forget about rankings and concentrate only on winning the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you haven't won in 2 years, winning starts becoming
extremely important,'' he said. ``For me, that's my focus now.
Plus, when guys like Andre Agassi and (Gustavo) Kuerton drop out,
it makes it a lot easier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
