<HEADER>
A4182 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-OLY-DR.-DOT-SOFTBALL-     07-26 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DR.-DOT-SOFTBALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. DOT BECOMES AMERICA'S FIRST NAME IN SOFTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Let's see ... Sports for $200, Alex.'' ``Answer: Dot
Richardson plays this sport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is softball?'' ``Correct.''
</P>
<P>
   For most casual sports-trivia fans this is an automatic; many
people have heard of Dot Richardson. To the answer of this actual
``Jeopardy!'' question, it is a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the answer in a crossword puzzle once, too,'' Richardson
said. ``It's really awkward and very humbling.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity seems to grace the brow of anonymous athletes every
four years during the Olympic Games. For most Olympians, the ripple
of popularity hits the edge of the pond when the Games end. For a
few, the ripple turns into a wave.
</P>
<P>
   So it has for Richardson, 38, who will be in Fort Worth on
Saturday with the U.S. team for two exhibition games at Gateway
Park. The darling of the 1996 gold medal-winning U.S. softball team
has become the rarest of Olympians. While Richardson has made a
career from two weeks of Olympic fame, her fame also has reflected
on her teammates and her sport.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Dot Richardson is synonymous with softball. Maybe it's
because of her Web site, drshortstop.com, or her book, ``Living the
Dream''. Or maybe it's because aspiring young players have watched
some of her instructional videos. Or heard her speak at clinics. Or
seen her on the Family Channel. Or used her official softball bat
or glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little girl asked me once, `Wow, how does it feel to have
your name on a bat?' '' Richardson said. ``What's more incredible
is to see a person use your bat or other countries use our bats. As
they are holding that bat they are truly holding the incredible
evolution of women in sport. They know now it's possible to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1996 Olympics, Richardson already was an accomplished
softball player. She was selected the NCAA player of the decade for
the 1980s, won countless gold medals in international competition,
was a four-time All-American at UCLA, and was a 15-time
all-American Softball Association selection. The Olympics made
Richardson and her teammates golden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dot is probably the greatest ambassador softball has ever
known,'' Nike U.S. sports marketing program director Eddie Brown
said. ``In the U.S. she is a legend. On top of that, she is now a
surgeon, which speaks volumes about the types of athletes who are
competing for the U.S. There are stories like this in other sports;
these are extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   They are ordinary people pursuing extraordinary feats, whereas
most glorified professional athletes lead lives few can comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time this is an athlete's once-in-a-lifetime shot
at glory. People recognize that dedication and sacrifice,'' NBC
spokesman Mike McCarley said. ``There always seems to be an athlete
the vast majority of the viewing audience doesn't know and because
of some remarkable feat or amazing story they become a household
name.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was because Richardson had the first hit, run and home
run in Olympic softball competition. Maybe it was because she hit a
home run in the United States' gold-medal victory against China.
Maybe it was because NBC host Bob Costas interviewed her on
national television. Or maybe it was because she had the
captivating name ``Dr. Dot.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, a practicing orthopedic surgeon from Los Angeles,
who completed her medical training while playing softball, still
drives a car with more than 120,000 miles on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dented in the front,'' she said. ``There are some other
dings in it from softball.''
</P>
<P>
   The $26,000 stipend for medical school, however, has been
replaced by heftier checks for speaking engagements and
endorsements from companies such as Xerox, Louisville Slugger and
Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the Olympics, I would lose money on softball almost
every year just on travel,'' Richardson said. ``It took me a while
to buy that car. I lived in a dorm room at med school. I lived with
my parents while I trained for Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Those days, however, are gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really have to worry about \Rmoney\S anymore,'' she
said. ``It's almost all attributable to those two weeks in
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally, softball was not intended to be covered live in
1996, but the team's success mandated coverage. For the 2000 Sydney
Olympics, every U.S. softball game will be carried by one of NBC's
three outlets (NBC, MSNBC and CNBC).
</P>
<P>
   Nike has its own signature shoe for pitcher Michele Smith. Major
League Baseball is considering getting involved with the four-team
Women's Professional Softball League.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, meanwhile, prepares for one more shot at a gold
medal, which likely will mean more exposure, another trip to the
White House, more interviews, more speaking at clinics and
motivational speeches to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in high school I had to get up in front of class
and speak in Spanish,'' Richardson said. ``I went back to my seat
and said to God, `I will speak in front of however many people you
want, just let it be in English.'''
</P>
<P>
   With her rise, Richardson is making good on that promise. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
