<SLUG> BC-NJ-ABORTION-RULING-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. APPEALS PANEL SAYS NEW JERSEY CAN'T BAN ABORTION PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A federal appeals panel here struck down as
unconstitutional New Jersey's ban on so-called partial-birth
abortions. The decision Wednesday mirrored a U.S. Supreme Court
ruling in June.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous 40-page decision by a panel of the 3rd Circuit
U.S. Court of Appeals was seen as a victory by abortion-rights
groups that had challenged the 1997 law. It was a vindication as
well for Gov. Christie Whitman, whose conditional veto of the
measure pointed to its constitutional flaws as well as to ways of
remedying them, but was overridden by the Legislature in an
emotionally charged debate.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Legislature spent nearly $500,000 on private
lawyers to defend the law, which was not enforced while it moved
through the courts.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the three-judge appeals panel upheld a 1999 U.S.
District Court ruling, agreeing that the New Jersey law was
``unconstitutionally and incurably vague'' in its ban on a
late-term procedure that opponents call ``partial-birth abortion.''
And in that vagueness, the panel said, the act imposed an ``undue
burden'' on the constitutionally protected right of a woman to an
abortion and could be construed to ban all abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, we, as was the District Court, are left to wonder
whether the drafters chose a path of deliberate ambiguity, coupled
with public outrage based largely on misinformation, in an attempt
to proscribe legitimate abortion practices,'' the ruling said.
``The Legislature could have passed a statute of more limited reach
and still achieve its supposed objective. Instead, it decided to go
farther.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Maryanne Trump Barry, writing for the panel, noted that it
had reached and written its opinion in the case before the U.S.
Supreme Court struck down a similar law in Nebraska on June 28.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The high court said the Nebraska law was vague, that it put an
undue burden on a woman's right to an abortion and that it lacked
any exception for the life and health of the woman involved. But
because ``nothing in that opinion is at odds with this court's
opinion,'' Barry wrote, the panel issued its opinion without
revisions or changes.
</P>
<P>
   The other panelists were Judge Leonard I. Garth and Judge Samuel
A. Alito, who wrote a separate but concurring opinion. Alito said
he favored finding the New Jersey law unconstitutional, stressing
that any limits on abortion must have an exception for the
preservation of the health of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   Currently about 30 states have similar bans on the procedure,
which opponents describe as any procedure in which the person
performing the abortion partially delivers vaginally a living
unborn child, then kills it and completes the delivery.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, the state Legislature paid a private lawyer
$412,759 to defend the law, which they passed over the governor's
veto and which the state attorney general and their own legislative
counsel had warned them was flawed. Rae Hutton, a spokesman for
Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, who along with the Assembly
speaker pressed the override of Whitman's veto, said Wednesday that
the ruling had come as no surprise in light of the Supreme Court's
ruling last month. But she added: ``We are looking at it to decide
how to proceed and whether to appeal it.''
</P>
<P>
   Talcott Camp, a lawyer with the Reproductive Freedom Unit of the
American Civil Liberties Union who represented Planned Parenthood
of New Jersey and the state's ACLU chapter in their challenge of
the law, called the ruling a vindication of women's constitutional
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now doctors can continue to provide New Jersey women with the
best care possible without this dangerous law that had a complete
disregard for women's health,'' Camp said.
</P>
<P>
   Pete McDonough, a spokesman for Whitman, pointed out that she
had not simply vetoed the Legislature's measure, but had utilized
the state's conditional veto to highlight flaws and suggest changes
that would meet her approval. He noted that much of what the court
said in its ruling had been recommended by the governor in her
veto. Whitman's support of a woman's right to an abortion has put
her at odds with many in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was style over substance and a symbolic gesture,''
McDonough said. ``If they had done that we would have had a law
that was constitutional on the books for the last two years and
wouldn't have poured $400,000 down a rat hole.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's law, unlike those in Nebraska and some other
states, would have imposed civil rather than criminal penalties.
Doctors who violated it could have faced a loss of license and a
$25,000 fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
