u s BC-BERKOW-TOUR-DE-FRANCE     07-26 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERKOW-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ARMSTRONG SEES BEYOND A HANDLEBAR
</HEADLINE>
  By IRA BERKOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ See his picture on the front page of newspapers and
magazines, catch him on the network news, read about him in
newspaper editorials usually reserved for world-imposing figures
and events and shake out the contents of a cereal box with his
image on the front, and the theme is invariably the same: Lance
Armstrong is a hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what a hero is,'' he said Wednesday, ``but I
don't call myself a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dealt an unfortunate situation,'' he said. ``I did what
came naturally, and try hard. Hero? Some people might think I'm a
jerk. I push myself, and I push others _ like my teammates. Maybe
that's part of the striving. Maybe that's a significant part of the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong showed up in New York Wednesday on his own two
feet, which is and is not a surprise. He did not arrive on two
wheels, which, for the winner of the Tour de France for the last
two years, he is accustomed to doing. And the mere fact that he is
around at all is a testament to those two good feet, and his heart,
and, surely, modern medical science.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong, lean, short-cropped hair, yellow shirt symbolic
of the leader of the great bicycle race, younger-looking than his
28 years, appeared at the Niketown store in Manhattan for a news
conference, with fans packed in the atrium. It was part of a busy
day that included the morning talk shows and the banging of the
gavel to close trading at the New York Stock Exchange. And it came
three days after his victory, which ended with him whisking down
the Champs-Elysees in Paris, completing the grueling three-week,
2,774-mile outing.
</P>
<P>
   It is now a nearly commonplace story _ if a story endlessly
inspiring to many can be termed commonplace _ how Armstrong was
diagnosed in 1996 with testicular cancer, how it spread to his
lungs and brain, and how he was given a 50 percent chance of
surviving. He underwent brain surgery, then chemotherapy, lost his
hair, lost his strength, lost 20 pounds, but did not lose hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't going to be around people who thought I was
going to die,'' said Armstrong. ``And there were those in medicine
and out of it who thought I would. I switched to doctors who
believed I could make it. I had to be around positive-thinking
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get letters and comments, from cancer survivors and others,
with people saying they admire me,'' said Armstrong, ``and I
appreciate that. But I can truthfully say I've never admired anyone
I didn't really know well, know deep down. I mean, you read about
athletes, for example, who are great in their fields, but you don't
know how they act at home, how they are when the spotlight isn't on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been compared in recent times to some of the most
compelling athletes of our time: Michael Jordan, Wayne Gretzky,
Tiger Woods. ``It's for others to say,'' he says, when asked for a
comment on that.
</P>
<P>
   The view here is that in one significant aspect he transcends
Jordan, Gretzky and perhaps even Tiger Woods. The reason is, he is
actively promoting and representing something beyond his sport,
something above the sinking of a hoop or a putt. He has the Lance
Armstrong Foundation for cancer research _ to which Nike
contributed $25,000 Wednesday _ and he consistently talked about
the overcoming of obstacles, life-threatening and otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   (One is reminded of his mother, Linda, who raised him as a
single mother, telling him when he was feeling insecure in a race:
``You're going to win this race. Don't let anybody intimidate you _
you put your head down, and you race.'') If there is an athlete in
recent memory that Armstrong most resembles in attitude and
stature, it is Muhammad Ali, who made his personal beliefs a
priority in the face of great obstacles and challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know about Ali is what I've read,'' said Armstrong. ``I
was too young to have known what he was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not too young to appreciate Jordan's basketball skills
and approach to his profession. ``And while I said you can't admire
someone fully that you don't know, you can admire certain qualities
in them,'' Armstrong said. ``And hard workers are people I look up
to. Jordan was one of the hardest workers, as I understand it, and
he drove the other guys on his team to achieve. He was tough on
them. I try to do the same thing with my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Which has been plenty good not only for him, but for the winning
U.S. Postal Service team that he led.
</P>
<P>
   He may also lead in perspective. ``It's important for me to know
that something like the Lance Armstrong Foundation will be here in
20 years,'' he said, ``whereas the Tour de France will not be here
in 20 years _ at least it won't for Lance Armstrong.''
</P>
<P>
   What next, though, for Lance Armstrong, cyclist? ``The
Olympics,'' he said. ``That's big stuff. I go back into training on
the weekend. I can't stop now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
