<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATIONS INTENSIFY TO ELICIT TESTIMONY IN AUCTION HOUSE CASE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., England)  By RALPH BLUMENTHAL and CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Discussions to win the cooperation of Sotheby's
former president and chief executive, Diana D. Brooks, in the
three-year-old federal antitrust investigation of Sotheby's and
Christie's have intensified, lawyers and others close to the case
said this week.
</P>
<P>
   The talks, they said, are aimed at getting Brooks to testify
that she colluded in anti-competitive deals with her counterpart at
Christie's at the direction of the former chairman at Sotheby's, A.
Alfred Taubman. Taubman, a shopping center magnate who bought the
controlling interest in Sotheby's in 1983, resigned in February,
along with Brooks. He has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department inquiry centers on accusations that the
world's most powerful auction houses conspired as far back as 1991
to fix the fees they charged buyers and sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Documents from Christopher M. Davidge, who abruptly resigned as
Christie's chief executive on Dec. 24, support accusations of
collusion between the two auction giants, Christie's has said in
court filings. Lawyers for Christie's turned the documents over to
the government as part of a conditional amnesty agreement in
December and last week they were distributed to a select group of
lawyers under court confidentiality orders.
</P>
<P>
   People who have seen the approximately 150 pages of documents
said they contained notes from Davidge to Anthony Tennant,
Christie's chairman, about discussions with Brooks along with memos
from Tennant to Davidge about talks with Taubman. Both Davidge and
Brooks say they were acting on orders from their chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant, who lives in London, also denies any wrongdoing and has
not cooperated in the investigation, people close to the inquiry
say. Tennant and his lawyer, Richard Taylor, reached by telephone,
refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Issues discussed in the documents, people who have seen them
say, center on the fees charged to buyers and sellers. They also
include notes about talks concerning interest rates that both
Sotheby's and Christie's charge sellers who receive financing in
the form of loans that are to be paid back to the auction house.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to the Justice Department investigation said that
prosecutors interviewed Davidge about those interest rate
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   If the case should result in indictments and come to trial, the
documents could well be offered as evidence under rules allowing
the introduction of records maintained in the normal course of
business, some lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Davidge would presumably be a central witness under his and
Christie's amnesty agreements with the government. In addition,
people close to the investigation have said, the government is
seeking the cooperation of Brooks who, they say, has signaled
through one of her lawyers, Stephen E. Kaufman, that she might be
amenable to testifying for the prosecution in return for leniency.
</P>
<P>
   The talks, often stalled, have gone on for months, with
prosecutors taking a hard line on Brooks' possible exposure to
prison and Kaufman seeking guarantees that would spare her
incarceration. Several people close to the investigation said that
discussions had clearly intensified in recent weeks but that an
agreement was not yet in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman denied that any deal had been struck and declined to
comment further. John J. Greene, who is leading the antitrust
investigation in New York, did not return a call left with his
office.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the investigation said that prosecutors were
evidently trying to secure Brooks' testimony against Taubman.
Whether Taubman's lawyers have been approached for his possible
cooperation is not clear but he has consistently taken the position
that he knew of no wrongdoing and has nothing to contribute. His
lawyer, Scott W. Muller, was out of town and unreachable, his
office said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to facing the criminal investigation, Sotheby's and
Christie's are targets of a federal class action civil lawsuit by
more than a hundred former buyers and sellers who contend they were
defrauded by collusive practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
