<HEADLINE>
REILLY IMPRESSES COWBOYS PLAYERS, COACHES WITH OFFENSIVE CALLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ All eyes will be on Jack Reilly's
play-calling ability in Sunday night's exhibition game against the
Pittsburgh Steelers, but for now there have been nothing but rave
reviews for the Cowboys' first-year offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly has impressed players and coaching peers alike with his
innovative thinking, expanded passing-game playbook ... even his
dry sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Question: How much of Reilly's fingerprints will be on an
offense that is actually a hybrid of what Norv Turner runs with the
NFC East favorite Washington Redskins and what Mike Martz runs with
the defending Super Bowl champion St. Louis Rams?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: ``A lot,'' said quarterback Troy Aikman. ``To a certain
degree, Jack's fingerprints already are on those other offenses,
too. Mike Martz was Jack's receivers coach when \RReilly\S was
offensive coordinator for the Rams (1995-96).''
</P>
<P>
   There's also a Martz-Turner connection as well as an ongoing
Reilly-Ernie Zampese connection, which enters its fourth
consecutive season. Zampese is the Cowboys' offensive consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a \RReilly\S influence to where this offense has
evolved,'' Aikman said. ``Now he'll have his own version of what we
want to do with it, based on the personnel we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman sees the Cowboys' passing game more closely resembling
St. Louis because of the Cowboys' speed at wide receiver, but he
says the Emmitt Smith running game will be closer to the Redskins
(Stephen Davis) than to the Rams (Marshall Faulk).
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dave Campo also has borrowed from Reilly and Zampese a
practice technique that emulates a particular game situation. One,
it breaks up practice and grabs the players' interest. An example
the other day: ``Defense is down six points. Offense is up six
points. Four minutes left in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack and Ernie have done this situational \Rscripting\S in the
past,'' Campo said. ``It goes all the way back to Bill Walsh, and I
really like it for our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo, a former defensive coordinator, also thinks that Reilly's
``unpredictability'' would give him a headache if he had to go up
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned. That will begin to play itself out Sunday night at
Texas Stadium against the Steelers. \Nsubheds:Briefly Running back
Emmitt Smith was held out of practice because of a ``not serious''
toe injury that occurred when he stubbed his left big toe while
walking out of a building Tuesday night. X-rays showed no damage.
Said Dave Campo: ``It's nothing like Deion \RSanders' 1998-99 toe
injury\S. It's just the tip of the toe. It's day-to-day.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle Erik Williams' holdout enters Day 10 with no
end in sight. Owner Jerry Jones said yesterday that ``nothing is
new,'' plus that there has been no dialogue ``and we don't expect
there to be.'' Williams' agent has said his client wants to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Jones sat in on a personnel meetings among coaches and
front-office staff last night to evaluate players.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
