<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEFONICA-CEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEFONICA CHAIRMAN RESIGNS  
</HEADLINE>
  By BENJAMIN JONES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID _ The chairman of Telefonica, Juan Villalonga, resigned
on Wednesday, leaving the once-stodgy Spanish monopoly he
transformed into a telecommunications giant with fast-growing
holdings in the Internet and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation had spread that Villalonga, 47, would resign after
Wednesday's board meeting in the wake of an abandoned $58 billion
merger with the Dutch phone company Royal KPN. The failure of the
deal in May, because of Spanish government opposition, humiliated
Villalonga, people close to the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Alierta, 55, chairman of the Spanish-based tobacco company
Altadis was named to succeed Villalonga. ``The appropriate time has
come for a change in the company's leadership,'' Telefonica said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica's $12 billion planned acquisition of Lycos, the
American Internet portal, will not be affected by the change,
executives said. Lycos' shares gained 10 percent Wednesday, to
$65.75.
</P>
<P>
   Alierta will be following a remarkable act on the European
business scene. Villalonga took the helm of Telefonica in 1996,
when the company was still state-owned. Under the direction of a
new center-right government, it was privatized a year later and
Villalonga quickly moved to transform Telefonica into a stellar
performer, outpacing other newly privatized European phone
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Under Villalonga's leadership, Telefonica made some $21 billion
in acquisitions, gaining a huge share of the Brazilian market, as
well as chunks in Argentina and Peru, and became the largest
supplier of telecommunications services in the Spanish- and
Portuguese-speaking world. Telefonica says it reaches a potential
market exceeding 550 million customers in 24 nations through
affiliates in Europe, the United States, Latin America and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga also spun off cellular phone and multimedia
businesses, as well as the Internet arm, Terra Networks. The
spinoffs _ taking advantage of the market's voracious appetite for
such businesses _ and Villalonga's aggressive, flashy style won
over investors.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Telefonica have risen nearly sevenfold since
Villalonga took over, but declined somewhat in recent weeks. On
Wednesday, the company's American depository receipts rose $1.875
in New York, to $67.3125.
</P>
<P>
   The change of leadership seemed largely a relief to investors
and analysts, who said Telefonica was likely to maintain its
course. ``Over the medium term, there might be some volatility in
Telefonica shares,'' said Glen Spencer Chapman, an analyst with
Ibersecurities here. ``But it's a good company and cheap compared
to other telecoms in Europe. It would appear that Telefonica will
go ahead with the deals it has on the horizon.``
</P>
<P>
   ,
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In May, the government and two of the banks represented on
Telefonica's board, Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria and La Caixa,
helped scotch the KPN merger. While Villalonga had sought a deal to
create a pan-European network of fixed-line, data and wireless
services, Madrid officials opposed the linkup, arguing that the
Dutch government would be the biggest shareholder in the new
company. The government threatened to use its golden share in
Telefonica to torpedo the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga `` was maybe too independent for BBVA and La Caixa,''
Chapman of Ibersecurities said. ``Sometimes, Villalonga was
perceived as too aggressive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
