<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-THOMAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS FULLBACK ROBERT THOMAS TRYING TO PICK UP MOOSE-LIKE
NUANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ With his linebacker pedigree, fullback
Robert Thomas' ability to level a defender with a devastating block
is not at issue on the Cowboys' practice field at Midwestern State
University.
</P>
<P>
   His daily goal is to hone that aggression, while picking up the
nuances of the position that made his predecessor, Daryl ``Moose''
Johnston, special.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys want Thomas, who moved to fullback from linebacker
during the final days of camp last year, to work on chip blocking
and picking up defenders when the line breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, 6-foot-1 and 270 pounds, who is generously listed at 252
pounds by the Cowboys, is proving to be a quick study in his first
full training camp as a fullback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased with Robert,'' Cowboys running backs coach
Clarence Shelmon said. ``He is starting to pick up the nuances of
the game that Daryl had. A lot of times plays break down because a
lineman misses an assignment or misses a block. The fullback is
sort of like a bodyguard. He has to abort his assignment to do
what's necessary to help the play become successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several times in practice this week, he did that. He is
starting to pick things up. We are not worried about Robert.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys aren't concerned about Thomas because they know his
history. And if hard work and being a student of the game are the
necessary ingredients to become successful, they know Thomas has
what it takes.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas made the team in 1998 as an undrafted free-agent
linebacker out of Henderson State (Ark.). Entering training camp
last year as a long shot, Thomas appeared set at linebacker again
before the Cowboys decided to move him to fullback.
</P>
<P>
   Nine games into the season, Thomas found himself in the starting
backfield with the team's biggest stars, running back Emmitt Smith
and quarterback Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Thomas is stunned by the events of the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows how good God is,'' Thomas said. ``But I'm not
comfortable. I've still got a lot of work to do and a lot to learn.
I'll always be a linebacker at heart and play with a linebacker
attitude, but I'm focused only on being the best fullback I can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas didn't wait until training camp to further his fullback
education.
</P>
<P>
   After spending much of last season listening to the words and
wisdom of Johnston _ who became Thomas' tutor after suffering a
season-ending injury _ Thomas spent the off-season studying
videotapes of Johnston's ``greatest hits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we're going to the offense that complemented his
style, I was trying to learn what he did,'' Thomas said. ``He's
given me enough insight about what he was thinking that watching
the film helped me say, `OK, he saw this or that and that's why he
did what he did.' He was successful in this offense and I wanted to
see what worked for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as remarkable as Thomas' transition is the Cowboys'
confidence in him. The Cowboys came to training camp preaching the
benefits of competition, yet they brought no one in to challenge
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Dave Campo said that is partly because the
fullback position does not play as large a role in the offense as
it once did. Campo said the Cowboys will use the one-back,
two-tight-end set as much as they use the two-back set.
</P>
<P>
   Campo, however, said that has more to do with the team wanting
to take advantage of tight end Jackie Harris and shouldn't be
looked upon as a negative for Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the combination of the two sets are fine for us,''
Campo said. ``But we are pleased with Robert. He's doing a
remarkable job. We knew he would when we moved him there last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Johnston, Thomas can catch the ball and will be used as a
pass receiver. In addition, Thomas hopes to do something that's
mostly foreign to fullbacks in this offense _ carry the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll give the old dog a bone a few times,'' said
Thomas, who had eight carries for 35 yards in the final three games
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he knows he will be measured by the same yardstick used for
Johnston: the ability to block for Emmitt Smith. Thomas said
helping Smith surpass the 1,397 yards he gained last year is his
primary focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Emmitt has a good year and goes to the Pro Bowl, then I had
a good year,'' Thomas said. ``Emmitt's job is to carry the ball. My
job is to create a roadway for him.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
