<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC TO TURN ITS WORST PUBLIC SCHOOLS OVER TO PRIVATE MANAGERS IN
2001 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City plans to hand over control of some of
its worst-performing public schools to private companies or
nonprofit agencies in the fall of 2001, the first such effort in
the city's history and one of the largest programs to privatize
education in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Schools Chancellor Harold O. Levy issued a request Wednesday for
proposals to help the Board of Education convert the failing
institutions into charter schools, freeing them from many of the
state and local regulations that now govern them. If the schools'
conversions to charter status are approved by the State Board of
Regents, the school's new managers will be able to renegotiate some
union contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Education officials said that the program was likely to
focus on five to seven schools in its first year and could include
as many as 20 schools depending on the number and quality of
applications the board received.
</P>
<P>
   There are roughly 50 New York City schools _ 80 percent of them
elementary and middle schools and the rest high schools _ that are
eligible for the program.
</P>
<P>
   The program is a victory for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has
pushed for the privatization of parts of the city's educational
services and who has feuded with two previous schools chancellors
over nontraditional approaches to education. This year, he set
aside $60.8 million of the Board of Education's $11 billion budget
to pay for private management of some of the worst-performing city
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony P. Coles, deputy mayor for planning, education and
cultural affairs, said the plan ``should give the parents whose
children have been trapped in failing schools some real hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Far less happy was Randi Weingarten, president of the United
Federation of Teachers, which represents the city's 78,000 teachers
and which could lose influence in the schools run by outsiders. She
cautioned that the plan looked like ``a political diversion,'' and
said there was no evidence that privatization of education worked.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Levy said he was ``cautiously optimistic that this
effort will yield positive results for some of our
poorest-performing schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that ``many people have placed a great deal of hope'' in
privatization, he added, ``Under the right circumstances,
privatization can be a useful tool in improving performance, but it
is not a magic bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   Such experiments have failed miserably in some cities,
particularly Baltimore and Hartford, Conn., which several years ago
each hired a for-profit company to run the public schools. The
efforts did not produce the desired results, and the two cities
retook control of the schools.
</P>
<P>
   More limited efforts, where private companies have managed a few
schools in a district, have proved workable. But studies of their
effectiveness have found mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Board of Education's announcement Wednesday
drew praise from business and political leaders and cautious
optimism from people within the school system.
</P>
<P>
   Robert R. Kiley, president of the New York City Partnership, a
group of civic and business leaders that has pushed for education
reform, said the plan ``is a great door swung open that to this
point has pretty much been closed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
