<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     07-26 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODEN DOES IT AGAIN IN A VICTORY VS. ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Something was missing from the Yankees in the first
three months of this season, and maybe it was desperation. The
Yankees had been desperate to establish themselves in 1996,
desperate to make their mark on history in 1998 and desperate to
play through the horrible personal traumas in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But they have added a few desperate souls in the last month,
like Dwight Gooden, and they are beginning to pull away from their
American League East rivals. Gooden garnered his third victory
since joining the Yankees, shackling Baltimore, 4-1, Wednesday
night with help from the relievers Jeff Nelson, Mike Stanton and
Mariano Rivera. Paul O'Neill and David Justice each drove in two
runs.
</P>
<P>
   That's four consecutive victories for the Yankees (54-42) and 16
in their last 22 games. They are three games ahead of the Toronto
Blue Jays and three and a half ahead of the Boston Red Sox, whose
game with the Minnesota Twins was rained out.
</P>
<P>
   Showers fell steadily here during the entire day, eased and then
ceased about an hour before the game. A misty shroud descended on
Camden Yards in the fifth inning, and the last few innings were
played in drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees drubbed the Orioles by 18 runs on Tuesday,
Baltimore's most one-sided defeat in Camden Yards, an embarrassment
that apparently made no impression on Albert Belle. He was hitting
in the first inning Wednesday night, in Baltimore's first
opportunity to rebound from that awful defeat, with Will Clark at
first base, and Belle pulled a hard grounder into the shortstop
hole.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter lunged to intercept the ball, an astounding play,
and if you were watching the action as it happened, you were
thinking Jeter might be able to throw out Clark at second _ which
he did, with second baseman Jose Vizcaino stretching at the bag,
like a first baseman, to make the catch. If you were watching the
action as it happened, it would never have occurred to you that the
Yankees might turn the double play.
</P>
<P>
   But Vizcaino is a former teammate of Belle's, and it occurred to
Vizcaino that he had a chance. He turned and threw to first,
completing the double play easily. Scouts in attendance timed
Belle's saunter to first at 4.9 seconds _ eons, by baseball
standards, over the major league average for right-handed hitters
of 4.1 or 4.2 seconds. Old and aching catchers run to first base in
4.9 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   While playing right field, Belle _ making $13 million as the
highest-paid member of the organization _ would bend over and place
his hands on his knees as Sidney Ponson pitched, and sometimes
would not move, even slightly, for several pitches at a time, as if
he were still catching his breath from his first-inning jog.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden is competing with more anxiety than that, having found a
beachhead for his career, now seven victories shy of 200.
</P>
<P>
   The change in Gooden was evident in how he maneuvered through
trouble, how he threw off-speed pitches in situations when his
instinct _ reinforced through years of blowing away hitters with
his fastball _ might have been to simply throw harder.
</P>
<P>
   After B.J. Surhoff doubled to lead off the second inning, Gooden
used either a split-fingered fastball or a changeup to strike out
Harold Baines _ the ball sank low and away _ and after walking
Charles Johnson, he retired Luis Matos on a fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led by 3-1 at the time, for Paul O'Neill had slammed
a two-run single through the middle with two outs in the top of the
second. David Justice drove in O'Neill in the first inning by
ripping a double into the gap in left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden clung to his advantage, whiffing Baines again with a
runner at second in the fourth inning, with the same downward
breaking pitch, to stunt that Baltimore rally, and Gooden retired
the side in order in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   After Gooden struck out Clark to lead off the sixth, the last of
his five strikeouts, Belle doubled. Gooden fell behind Surhoff two
balls and no strikes and went with his off-speed pitch again,
getting Surhoff to line out softly to second.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden then worked carefully, walking Jeff Conine. Baines fouled
off several two-strike pitches _ the last going into and out of the
glove of Jorge Posada, for a foul ball _ and he walked. Gooden
jabbed both hands into the air in frustration as Manager Joe Torre
emerged from the dugout to call for relief.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson took over and retired Johnson to end that inning, but he
contributed to problems in the seventh, allowing a double and a
walk with one out. Stanton took over and Clark flied to left for
the second out. Belle hacked mightily at a fastball, and he lifted
a fly into short center, but his swing appeared to fool Bernie
Williams, who broke back for an instant before sprinting in,
sliding, reaching for the ball and then making the inning-ending
catch.
</P>
<P>
   Williams provided an insurance run in the top of the eighth,
leading off with a long drive to center field, over the wall,
beyond the reach of Matos, who slammed against the fence. The ball
caromed onto the field and umpires ruled the ball was in play _
wrongly, as replay showed clearly _ and despite an argument from
Torre, Williams ended up with a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Justice lifted a drive off the top of the right-field
scoreboard, the ball clanging against the alloy facing, and
Williams trotted home with the Yankees' fourth run. Stanton pitched
the bottom of the eighth and Rivera, the Yankees' closer, came on
to throw the ninth inning for his 24th save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
