u p BC-NY-LAZIO-SENATE-330&AMP;A     07-26 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-SENATE-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO SOW GOOD WILL, LAZIO DONATES TO LOCAL POLITICIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rep. Rick Lazio, a relative newcomer to statewide
politics, went on something of a philanthropic binge this month,
giving a total of $72,500 on the same day to all 62 Republican
county committees in New York state. And for good measure, he sent
an additional $4,000 to four Conservative Party county committees.
</P>
<P>
   In making the contributions, Lazio, a Suffolk County native, was
adopting a traditional strategy of candidates trying to expand
quickly beyond their local fortresses of support: sow good will
across the state by financing grass-roots party cadres. In Erie
County, which includes Buffalo, Lazio gave $4,000. In tiny Franklin
County, the gift was $500.
</P>
<P>
   The donations, though, did not put a dent in Lazio's U.S. Senate
campaign treasury. The money came from an obscure state political
action committee that effectively allows him to get around strict
federal fund-raising limits.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, shortly before his PAC made the donations, several
Lazio benefactors gave $2,000, the maximum allowed by law, to his
official Senate campaign and then wrote checks to the PAC for as
much as $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   According to campaign finance records, the PAC, which is called
Friends of Rick Lazio, then sent the money to the local party
committees, which are expected to receive it in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, it would be illegal for Lazio to use the PAC
to finance his Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton
directly by, for example, paying for advertising. But the donations
to the party committees, which come under the rubric of so-called
party-building activities, fall under a vague area of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Dan McLagan, a spokesman for the Lazio campaign, said he
expected that the donations would be used for voter drives, phone
banks and other expenses intended to help local candidates and the
Republican ticket in general. Lazio ``is eager to help with
party-building efforts, and help local candidates who share his
position on the issues,'' McLagan said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (In a curious oversight, the PAC listed Republican committees in
61 of the state's 62 counties as receiving money, excluding the one
that includes Plattsburgh _ Clinton County. Evidence of hostility
to anything that connotes the opposition? No, replied McLagan, that
donation was inadvertently left off the contribution report.
``There's a check,'' he said, ``even for Clinton.'')
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Giarrusso, the Republican chairman in Onondaga County,
which includes Syracuse, said the donations allowed Lazio to
demonstrate that his interests extended beyond Long Island. ``It's
showing that he is taking his money and he is sharing it with other
than downstate,'' said Giarrusso, whose committee is receiving
$4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Such dividends have led other politicians to take a similar
tack, most notably Jon S. Corzine, the Democratic U.S. Senate
nominee in New Jersey, a former investment banker who used his
personal fortune to disburse tens of thousands of dollars to local
committees and candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio set up Friends of Rick Lazio in 1995, soon after the
Republicans gained control of Congress and he became chairman of a
housing subcommittee, which made him a more attractive recipient
for donations. The PAC has collected $127,320 this year. The Senate
campaign has taken in $5 million. While that is a sizable amount,
Clinton is far ahead in fund-raising, and Lazio is under
considerable pressure to fill his Senate treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in contribution limits is stark. An individual
can donate a maximum of $2,000 to a Congressional campaign, and a
maximum of $76,500 annually to a New York PAC. Corporations can
donate to PACs in New York but not on the federal level.
</P>
<P>
   Many other elected officials have also formed these so-called
leadership PACs, including New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
Gov. George Pataki and members of Congress of both major parties.
Earlier this year, Clinton contended that Giuliani, at the time her
rival for the Senate, was illegally using PAC money to finance his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani called that ludicrous, adding that Clinton was being a
hypocrite because she was allowing Democratic committees to spend
the largely unregulated contributions known as soft money on her
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21, an advocacy group in
Washington that is seeking tougher campaign finance rules, said
these PACs were being used so often to circumvent contribution
limits that they should be prohibited. ``They simply become a way
of getting around the federal campaign finance limits,'' Wertheimer
said.
</P>
<P>
   McLagan, the Lazio campaign spokesman, disputed that criticism,
saying the two committees were distinct. Friends of Rick Lazio was
playing no role in the Senate campaign and was a vehicle for Lazio
to funnel support to people he believes in, McLagan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are completely separate,'' he said. ``But I don't think
that it's unusual for people to support Rick so he can help
candidates and causes that he supports.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
