<HEADLINE>
COURT APPROVES NEW YORK CITY'S SPRAYING FOR WEST NILE VIRUS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J., Conn., Mass.)  By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge Wednesday cleared the way for New
York City to continue spraying pesticides to control the spread of
West Nile virus, but steady rain forced the city to postpone for a
day its plans to spray much of Manhattan and Roosevelt Island.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of environmental groups had sought an emergency
order to halt the spraying of Anvil, a pesticide that had already
been used in Central Park, across Staten Island and in parts of
Queens and Brooklyn, in areas where the virus was found in birds
and mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   But after two hours of testimony by witnesses for the city and
the environmentalists, U.S. District Judge Harold Baer Jr. ruled
that the environmental groups had not presented enough evidence to
require a temporary restraining order to stop the spraying.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentalists, represented by the Pace Environmental
Litigation Clinic at the Pace University School of Law in White
Plains, filed a lawsuit last week, contending that the spraying
campaign violated environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani harshly criticized the environmentalists
Wednesday, saying their effort to stop the spraying was a
``mindless attempt to frighten people.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``They are so far over on the other side in their
zealous advocacy that they are missing the importance of human
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The mosquito-borne virus killed seven people in the New York
region last year and made 55 others seriously ill. No human cases
have been reported this year, but the virus has been found in 11
mosquito samples in the region, including three pools in New York
City and one in Connecticut. The virus has also been found in more
than 50 birds in New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental groups argued in court Wednesday that the city
was not using the pesticide properly and that the minimal risk of
humans' contracting the virus did not justify spraying throughout
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, people are very confused,'' said Mitchel Cohen, a
leader of the No Spray Coalition, one of the plaintiffs in the
lawsuit. ``On the one hand, they are worried about spraying, but
there's an orchestrated hysteria around the West Nile virus, as if
it's a health emergency. Where's the health emergency around the
flu?''
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, West Nile virus was discovered in Boston, the
first time the disease was found outside the New York metropolitan
region since it surfaced last year. The 1999 outbreak, which began
in northern Queens, was the first in the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts health officials said the virus caused the death
of a crow found in a park in Jamaica Plain, a neighborhood in
southwest Boston. Dr. Ralph J. Timperi, director of the State
Laboratory Institute at the Massachusetts Department of Health,
said it was unclear whether the bird had come from another state or
was infected in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have been testing sick birds for several months, and
after finding the virus in the crow, they said they would begin
spraying larvicide in the area to kill mosquito eggs and would
intensify their surveillance and monitor hospitals to check for
reports of symptoms of the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Most often, infection with West Nile virus in people leads to a
mild illness that feels like influenza. But the virus can also
cause encephalitis, a deadly swelling of the brain, with symptoms
including severe headache, high fever, stiff neck, confusion, loss
of consciousness and muscle weakness. Those most at risk are the
elderly, those with weak immune systems, and children under 5.
</P>
<P>
   New York City health officials said that, weather permitting,
they would conduct ground spraying in Manhattan and Roosevelt
Island from midnight Thursday to 5 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The rain forced Suffolk County, where the West Nile virus was
confirmed late Tuesday in three mosquito samples, to cancel
spraying planned for Wednesday night in Ocean Park, Summer Club and
Davis Park. The spraying was rescheduled for later Thursday and was
expanded to include three areas in and around Babylon, where the
virus was detected in mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Spraying was also scheduled in Westchester and Rockland counties
for the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County, where the virus has been found in birds but not
in mosquitoes, has held off on spraying.
</P>
<P>
   Officials there said that while they had stepped up their
surveillance along the border of the two counties, they did not
think spraying was necessary because they had not found infected
mosquitoes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
