<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON URGES END TO AID IF ARAFAT DECLARES STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying that she may have gone beyond the White House
position on the charged issue of Middle East peace, Hillary Rodham
Clinton said Wednesday that she spoke out of her own conviction
when she called for cutting off U.S. aid if the Palestinians
unilaterally declared statehood.
</P>
<P>
   After the Middle East peace talks broke down on Tuesday at Camp
David, Clinton issued a statement urging both sides to continue
negotiations and called for a cutoff in assistance to the
Palestinian Authority should Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader,
move to declare a state on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be clear that any unilateral declaration of
Palestinian statehood would be entirely unacceptable and should be
met with a cutoff of United States assistance,'' she said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Wednesday if she was going beyond what the Clinton
administration had called for, she said flatly: ``I may be. It's
what I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Rep. Rick Lazio, her opponent for the U.S. Senate, said
he had already signed on as a sponsor to a bill that would do the
same thing. A similar bill is being sponsored by Sen. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., one of Clinton's strongest allies. Both bills were
scheduled to be introduced Wednesday evening. The Palestinian
Authority received $100 million in American aid in fiscal year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has suggested that he may declare Palestinian statehood
if no agreement is reached by September 13. The Clinton
administration has not called for the severing of aid, but has
instead pressed both sides to resume peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who was lambasted last year for her embrace of Arafat's
wife, Suha, Wednesday explicitly distanced herself from the
Palestinian cause, singling out Ehud Barak, the Israeli prime
minister, for showing ``enormous courage and vision and an
extraordinary commitment to these peace talks.''
</P>
<P>
   What about Arafat, she was asked. ``He participated,'' Clinton
said simply. `And I hope he will continue to participate in the
ongoing discussions that were promised.''
</P>
<P>
   Her reflections on the peace talks came during a campaign stop
Wednesday afternoon at the Florence Nightingale Health Center, a
nursing home in East Harlem. Clinton introduced a $500 million
proposal to raise staffing levels and safety standards in nursing
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a recent federal study that found perilous levels of
understaffing in nursing homes nationwide, Clinton's proposal would
use the money to reward nursing homes that met federal standards
and penalize those that did not. The proposal also calls for
publishing on the Internet the staff-to-patient ratios and the
safety records of all nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many places in our country are failing to honor our duty
to American seniors,'' she told an audience of frail, elderly
nursing home residents.
</P>
<P>
   She pointedly attacked Lazio for voting, along with his
Republican colleagues, for a 1995 bill that would have eliminated
national nursing home safety standards. Lazio's spokesman, Bryan
Flood, said the bill would have turned Medicaid into a block grant
program, leaving states responsible for creating their own nursing
home standards. The bill ultimately did not pass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
