<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW IDEAS FOR 2012 OLYMPIC MOTORSPORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been a week since officials of the committee seeking to
bring the 2012 Summer Olympics to Dallas announced that they would
like to stage an international auto race as a demonstration sport
at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   As much as I love motorsports, I don't believe race cars belong
in the Olympics, the ultimate proving ground for the human athlete.
</P>
<P>
   I fully believe that race-car drivers are athletes, who possess
extraordinary levels of hand-eye coordination, ability to
concentrate in a hostile environment and bravery. But their
performance goes hand-in-foot with a motor vehicle, which must take
into account all the variables inherent with motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, deciding on what genre of race car and what type
of race circuit would create a ``level playing field'' for the
world's greatest drivers in 2012 is foremost among the tasks facing
Eddie Gossage. The executive vice president and general manager of
TMS, Gossage is a charter member of Dallas 2012 and a proponent of
motorsports in the Olympics. He is preparing a questionnaire for
hundreds of movers-and-shakers in the motorsports industry
worldwide on these thorny subjects.
</P>
<P>
   I've told Gossage that I don't believe motorsports belong in the
Olympics. But if we must include them, here are some suggestions
that would give America its best opportunity to medal.
</P>
<P>
   My first choice as form of motorsports would be drag racing. And
my first choice of vehicle would be nitro-burning Funny Cars.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because to me, drag racing is even more inherently American
than oval-track racing. Americans invented drag racing, Americans
are forever raising the bar in drag racing and ``nobody will ever
beat America in drag racing''. In fact, if drag racing were
approved for Olympic competition, I would advise The Rest Of The
World to not even show up in Fort Worth. Americans would win the
gold medal, the silver medal and the bronze medal ... and Miss
Congeniality.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a quarter-mile drag strip does not exist at this time
at TMS, The Great ``American'' Speedway. But Gossage has until 2012
to build one, assuming that he and track owner Bruton Smith really
want to help America kick some butt in Olympic demonstration
motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   But let's say that Dallas 2012 decides it would rather see
motorsports demonstrated on either TMS' 1.5-mile quadoval or its
2.5-mile combination oval/road course _ just so The Rest Of The
World doesn't start whining.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some ideas, stolen from America's traditional Saturday
night short tracks.
</P>
<P>
   First, I'd like to propose an Olympic Demolition Derby open to
all countries who manufacture full-sized, four-door sedans.
Naturally, each country's drivers would compete in models built in
their respective lands. The competition would be conducted using
Demo Derby rules that have been enforced at Cowtown Speedway in
Kennedale for nearly 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   What red-blooded American sitting in the frontstretch
grandstands at TMS wouldn't stand up and cheer as a Ford Crown
Victoria driven by some future NASCAR star from Darlington, S.C.,
backs squarely into the chrome radiator of a Mercedes-Benz or a
Volvo or a Lexus driven by some overpaid Formula One driver from
Monaco?
</P>
<P>
   If Dallas 2012 still doesn't approve, I'd like to propose an
Olympic Figure-8 demonstration race, again using full-sized sedans
from each participating nation. Gossage and Smith would need to
have an ``X'' pattern paved into the TMS infield, just like the one
that put Islip (N.Y.) Speedway on the motorsports map.
</P>
<P>
   What red-blooded American sitting in the frontstretch
grandstands at TMS wouldn't stand up and cheer as a Buick Regal
driven by some future IRL star from Muncie, Ind., T-boned the
right-side doors of a BMW or a Saab or a Honda driven by some
transplanted CART driver from Brazil?
</P>
<P>
   I can almost hear the chants of ``USA!-USA!'' already.
</P>
<P>
   That would be followed by something they don't see over in
Europe every day _ a 2,012-lap Legends Car feature race _ and a
Humpy Wheeler-inspired display of fireworks and blowin' stuff up.
</P>
<P>
   I can almost hear the Olympic theme song in the background, and
the dulcet voice of Al Michaels inquiring: ``Do you believe in
motorized miracles? Yesssss!''
SPOTLIGHT ON ...
TMS road course winds toward completion
</P>
<P>
   Work on the infield road course at Texas Motor Speedway is on
pace for a mid-August completion and the scheduled arrival of the
inaugural Grand Prix of Texas on Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A concrete base is being poured this week on a layout that has
been carved into the east side of the infield. It will be allowed
to cure so that final paving can begin Tuesday on a course that
will play host to the American Le Mans Series on Sept. 2 and the
BFGoodrich Tires Trans-Am Series on Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be done by mid-August, with no questions or
concerns on our part,'' said TMS general manager Eddie Gossage, who
has been watching the course take shape from his office window at
The Speedway Club. ``The course looks great from the sixth floor.
The cool thing is you can sit in Turn 1 and see every inch of this
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said his primary concern is to get the paving completed,
so the curing process can begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This heat doesn't help the curing, so as soon as they get the
asphalt down, they'll hit it with a water truck,'' Gossage said.
``We're using a granite compound asphalt, instead of limestone
base, to give it strength and durability. It's got a polymer in it
as well, so it should be very durable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said that while ALMS officials have been kept informed
of the progress, he is not sure when the first race car will turn a
wheel on the entire 2.5-mile layout. All but approximately 60 yards
of the 1.5-mile oval will be implemented into the course.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth's Bobby Archer, the reigning Speedvision World
Challenge GT champion, said lack of track time will not present a
major hurdle to his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of drivers in the series, at least in the front, can
adapt quite well,'' said Archer, who is seeking primary sponsorship
for the No. 32 Viper Speed Viper. ``We're going to a new street
course in Montreal that no one's ever seen and another in San
Diego. Since I live here, I might be able to go out to TMS and walk
around the course and get a little bit of a sneak preview. I don't
think that's an advantage you can carry into the race. But I'm
going to try to come up with an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The layout under construction differs from the one put on
display during TMS' Media Day in January, Gossage said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this design,'' Archer said after reviewing a faxed copy
of the course. ``With the space that they have, I think it's going
to be a real nifty track. Most infield road courses do not allow
for much passing. But you'll be able to do passing under braking,
and I think it's going to be quite exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They dealt themselves a tough hand initially \Rbecause of
limited space\S, but it's going to be great. Using the rest of the
oval, you're going to see some high speeds, which people at Texas
Motor Speedway expect. This should be a good track for us, much to
my competition's dismay.''
PIT STOPS Motorplex lobbies NHRA Texas Motorplex general manager
Elon Werner says the drag strip in Ennis may still have a ``40 or
50 percent'' chance of retaining its spring National Hot Rod
Association national event in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Completion of the NHRA schedule hit a snag when officials of
Virginia Motorsports Park decided to switch to the rival
International Hot Rod Association beginning in 2001. Previously,
NHRA president Tom Compton had announced that the spring Castrol
Nationals in Ennis and the fall event at Houston Raceway Park in
Baytown would be trimmed from the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Werner said that as of Monday, the 2001 NHRA schedule had not
been finalized. Werner said he has been dealing with Jerry
Archambeault, the NHRA's vice president of public relations and
communications, on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been letting the NHRA know we're still interested and
have sponsors ready to go,'' Werner said. ``I didn't get the
impression I was wasting my time. Jerry said that \Rreturning to
Ennis\S was one of options they're looking at. I think they have
three or four options with the schedule. I also told them that no
matter what happens, we'll still be 100 percent supportive of the
NHRA.'' Juan's stock hot again Reigning CART FedEx Series champion
Juan Montoya's thrilling victory over Michael Andretti in the
Michigan 500 on Sunday has turned up the heat on Montoya's
impending move to Formula One in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya reportedly will leave Target/Chip Ganassi Racing for
Frank Williams' F1 operation as teammate to Ralf Schumacher. Jenson
Button, Williams' current No. 2 driver, is rumored to be a
candidate at Jaguar and Benetton.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya stirred suspicion Tuesday, when he skipped two scheduled
media obligations _ CART's weekly teleconference and an appearance
on ``RPM 2Night'' alongside Bobby Rahal, CART's interim president
and chief executive officer. The question of Montoya's contract
status certainly would have been broached during both interviews,
and apparently Montoya did not want to answer just yet. Dodson
disses aero-match Veteran NASCAR Winston Cup crew chief Barry
Dodson doesn't have the budget to run a full-scale wind tunnel
aerodynamics program for rookie driver Mike Bliss at Eel River
Racing. But Dodson still is not in favor of NASCAR introducing a
common template to ``aero-match'' the four body styles that will be
in use beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know every manufacturer wants to identify their brand,''
said Dodson, crew chief for Rusty Wallace when he won the Cup
championship in a Pontiac Grand Prix in 1989. ``We're very close to
having an IROC race, where all the cars are equal. We might as well
send our money in to pay for our car, let them \RNASCAR\S unload
'em and we race 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR has always found a way to find parity in the brands.
I'm not in favor of a common template being an answer to that. I
know the \R2001\S Dodge is being built off the Taurus, and that's
not good for Pontiac. That's not good for Chevrolet. I count eight
or nine Dodges coming on board; that's like eight or nine more
Fords coming on board.'' The last word
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got the same zip code as the speedway, so I've got the
world's greatest racetrack in my back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Fort Worth's Bobby Archer, anticipating the inaugural Grand
Prix of Texas sports car weekend at Texas Motor Speedway
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
