<HEADLINE>
DEFENSEMAN LUKOWICH HAPPY TO BE IN STARS' FOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A wild off-season for defenseman Brad Lukowich ended with a
measure of stability yesterday when he accepted the Stars'
qualifying offer and signed a one-year deal worth $385,000, plus an
incentive clause worth up to $82,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also signed backup goalie Marty Turco and defenseman
Jeff Tory, who played for Philadelphia of the American Hockey
League last season, to one-year deals.
</P>
<P>
   For a period in late June, Lukowich, 23, thought his days with
the Stars had ended. The club traded him, along with goalie Manny
Fernandez, to the expansion Minnesota Wild before the expansion
draft. However, once the expansion Columbus Blue Jackets selected
defenseman Jamie Pushor from the Stars' roster, Stars general
manager Bob Gainey completed a prearranged deal with the Wild to
reacquire Lukowich.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all sounded like I was going \Rto Minnesota\S,'' Lukowich
said yesterday from his home in Canbrook, British Columbia.
``Getting traded back, I'm playing with the best organization in
the league and with the best players in the league. I'm looking
forward to a great season.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukowich played 60 games last season. He scored three goals
among four points and had 50 penalty minutes _ all career highs. In
78 career NHL games, Lukowich has four goals and four assists with
71 penalty minutes.
</P>
<P>
   An everyday player before the Stars traded for veteran defensive
help in Dave Manson and Sylvain Cote, Lukowich has the opportunity
to win a job as a third-pair defenseman behind Derian Hatcher and
Richard Matvichuk and Darryl Sydor and Sergei Zubov.
</P>
<P>
   Lukowich's incentive clause will pay him $10,000 for every 10
games he plays. If he is sent to the minors, his salary drops to
$125,000. The one-year deal allows him to become a restricted free
agent eligible for arbitration after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good deal for everybody,'' Stars assistant general
manager Doug Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   Turco, 24, a fifth-round selection by the Stars in 1994, played
55 games last season for the Michigan K-Wings, the Stars' former
minor-league affiliate. He posted a record of 21-24-7 with a 2.46
goals-against average and a .916 save percentage. He set an
International Hockey League record with four consecutive shutouts
last season. Financial terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Tory, a defenseman with some offensive pop, will likely play for
the Stars' minor-league club in Salt Lake City. He will earn
$400,000 if he remains on the Stars roster or $100,000 if he's
optioned to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Tory, 27, posted 17 goals and 41 assists in 76
games. He played the two previous seasons with the Houston Aeros of
the IHL, scoring 30 goals among 93 points in 153 games.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
