<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUFFALO-STAMPEDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFALO LEAVE THEIR HOME BUT FIND NO PLACE TO ROAM 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were still a few buffaloes roaming around the woods
Wednesday, but the northern New York town of Malone was managing to
recover from four days in which 16 of the animals stampeded through
potato, corn and dairy farms.
</P>
<P>
   Seven buffaloes, which had escaped from a nearby farm where they
were kept as pets, were shot and killed Tuesday by U.S. Border
Patrol agents after attempts to herd them away from a busy state
highway failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't herd buffalo,'' said Mark R. Henry, assistant chief
of the Border Patrol in Swanton, Vt. ``You can't direct them like
cattle. These things go wherever they want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The 16 buffaloes escaped Saturday from their home in Malone, a
down-at-the-heels town 17 miles from the Canadian border that is
home to three state prisons and miles of rolling farmland.
</P>
<P>
   When Maria Byrnes, the woman who raised the animals, realized
she could not coax them back home, she called a buffalo farmer from
nearby St. Lawrence County and offered to sell him her pets if he
would round them up, said Trooper Bernie Perry of the state police.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, the farmer, John A. Putnam, shot and killed
the herd's two bulls, thinking it would be easier to corral the
buffalo cows if the males were no longer leading them astray. He
managed to load another five into a truck, but then the remaining
nine took off, following a female, Agent Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   But 1,500-pound animals cannot hide for long. Later that
morning, half a dozen came charging across the fields of a dairy
farm, about two miles down the wooded road from where they had last
been seen. About a dozen of the farm's dairy cows were trotting
behind.
</P>
<P>
   A farmhand raking and baling hay was startled to see the
stampede heading toward his tractor. He ran into the farmhouse,
where the farmer, James Tavernier, 58, had just sat down for a cup
of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   The farmhand ``come flying in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Said, `Buffalo!''' Tavernier told The Press-Republican, a
daily newspaper that covers the Plattsburgh area.
</P>
<P>
   Tavernier, afraid the buffaloes would charge through his fence
and lead his entire herd of dairy cows onto State Route 11, called
the police, then got into his truck, drove toward the animals and
tried to herd them into another field. Instead, he scared them back
into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to corral buffalo,'' Trooper Perry said. ``I've seen
them walk through three strands of barbed wire like it was
cobwebs.''
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, six buffaloes had been shot as they came out
into the hay fields. Later that day, a seventh was killed. Their
carcasses were taken to a meat rendering plant to be used in dog
food.
</P>
<P>
   Two buffaloes are still at large, roaming around in the woods,
Agent Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sorry we had to shoot them,'' said the agent, whose
co-workers are more accustomed to patrolling the border with Canada
and keeping out contraband than riding herd on buffalo. ``We
discussed tranquilizing them, but we thought they'd go into the
woods. How do you get a 1,500-pound animal out of the woods into a
truck?''
</P>
<P>
   A buffalo stampede is unusual in these parts, but not unheard
of.
</P>
<P>
   ``In June '97, we had the same thing, some buffalo got loose,''
Agent Henry said. ``A tractor-trailer hit a buffalo, and it tore
that tractor-trailer right up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
