<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMARANCH SAYS IOC `HAS A NEW PHILOSOPHY' 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With only 50 days remaining before the opening ceremonies of the
Summer Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia, Juan Antonio Samaranch,
the president of the International Olympic Committee, was
interviewed Wednesday by Christopher Clarey of The New York Times.
The interview took place in Samaranch's office overlooking Lake
Geneva at the IOC's headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland, and it
covered a wide range of topics, from preparations for the Summer
Games to the continuing investigation into possible bribery and
fraud in Salt Lake City's bid to be host of the 2002 Winter
Olympics. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: How important do you think Sydney is for the future of the
Olympics and how important is the success of Sydney after the
problems of the last couple years?
</P>
<P>
   A: I would not like to link what happened in Salt Lake City with
Sydney. Because what happened in Salt Lake City, the IOC really was
affected. It affected some of our members, the organization, myself
and so on. But I can assure you the Olympic Games was not affected
and I can tell you for example that now we are waiting for the
candidates for 2008. That decision will be made next year. We have
10 candidates, 10 very strong candidates, and that means that the
prestige of the Games are not affected.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with regards to Sydney, we want to have a great Games.
If it's possible, the best one. We don't know. The day before
yesterday I was in Athens. I had a lovely tea with the president of
the organizing committee of the Sydney Games, Michael Knight. And
he's very happy, and if he is very happy, I am very happy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the positive aspects of Sydney from your point of
view at this stage, and what are the aspects that concern you?
</P>
<P>
   A: The positive aspects is that they work very well. They work
on time. All the sports facilities were ready one year before. We
could have pre-Olympic events to test these events at all the
Olympic sites and Australia is a country which is crazy about
sport. They expect great results from their team, around 60 medals.
This is fantastic for a country of 19 million people and the bad
thing for me regarding the Games is that they are in the spring (in
the Southern Hemisphere). Spring is not very warm. It could be
cold. We could have rain, and that is, for me, the main problem.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has there been progress on the idea of having South Korea and
North Korea marching together in the opening and closing ceremonies
in Sydney?
</P>
<P>
   A: I wrote to the two presidents to have the possibility of a
joint team with the same uniform maybe and they discussed it during
the visit of the president of South Korea to North Korea, and we
got the official answer from South Korea: They agree. But as of
today we have not had an answer from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you expect you will have one soon?
</P>
<P>
   A: We need it soon. In two weeks it will be too late. Not to
parade together but to parade together in the same uniform, it will
be too late in two weeks. Because the IOC offered to present the
same uniform for both teams. It was a present of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will the IOC do in Sydney to attempt to project a more
open, accessible approach, to combat the image it has as a closed,
pampered club?
</P>
<P>
   A: The most important thing is that the IOC has a new philosophy
and that inside the IOC we must have many members coming from
international federations, many members coming from national
Olympic committees. And also we have a fourth partner now, a very
important partner, those are the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   At this moment, we have 113 members and 30 of these members,
they took part in the Olympic Games and 16 of these 30 members,
they won medals in the Games. And that means that more than 25
percent are athletes or ex-athletes. In Sydney, during the Olympic
Games, we will elect eight new members of the IOC coming from
active athletes. They will be elected by 10,000 athletes in the
Olympic Village. And one of these eight will even sit on the
executive board of the IOC, which means the government of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How will the IOC project itself in Sydney? Will you still be
in the finest hotels and driving around in chauffeured cars?
</P>
<P>
   A: We will be in a hotel, a normal hotel. I will have my bedroom
and a living room to meet with the people from the delegations who
want to see me. That is what I need.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And for transportation around town?
</P>
<P>
   A: We will have a van to have some people with me, and we'll
see. Listen, I need a car, don't I? But it will be a van.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any research that shows the effect of your
reforms on public opinion of the IOC?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think the situation is much more quiet. This very big
scandal that you mentioned was a very big scandal in the United
States and some other countries but I can assure you that this was
not the case in all the countries.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There are very likely to be Aboriginal protests of some form
in Sydney. Are you concerned there will be any negative impact on
the Games?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think so. Because all the Aboriginal people are
Australians. Maybe they will demonstrate on the occasion of the
Games because they have a very important showcase, but also I think
they are very much interested in the success of the Games. I will
arrive in Sydney on the third or fourth of September. If I can meet
with them again, I am ready.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene are not going to be
running in the 200 meters in Sydney, because of what happened in
the American Olympic trials. Would the IOC ever consider giving a
wild-card berth to defending champions as the International Amateur
Athletic Federation has done with track and field world
championships, or do you believe the system is fine the way it is
now?
</P>
<P>
   A: The wild cards are not the responsibility of the
International Olympic Committee. It must be a request coming from
the IAAF. If the IAAF makes this request, I think the International
Olympic Committee is ready to study this request in a positive way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the IOC want to ensure the best athletes are at the
Games in their best events?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is an American problem, 100 percent. If Greene and Johnson
are not there, then two other Americans will be there, and as you
know, in your country, you have a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Tom Welch and Dave Johnson have been at the center of the
Salt Lake City scandal and now they have been indicted. Is that a
sign of Salt Lake City's failings or the IOC's failings? And how do
you view their indictments on a personal level?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was not surprised, because all the people said that Welch
and Johnson would be indicted, but personally I can say that with
them I had a very good relationship. They were very friendly and
very cooperative always with me and the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But is it primarily a failure on the Salt Lake City end or
IOC end?
</P>
<P>
   A: What I have a right to say is that it was a mistake by some
members of the I.O.C. and also, it was a mistake on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
