<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALSTAD-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY STADIUM PLAN ESCALATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE HUNT  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Galaxy's soccer stadium project in
Carson, Calif., continues to evolve and grow, and if approved will
turn Cal State Dominguez Hills into a multisport venue and national
training center for four sports, team officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Leiweke, now president of the Los Angeles Kings, Staples
Center and Anschutz Sports Holdings, said in a conference call that
the cost of the project has nearly doubled. From the original
estimate of $50-60 million, the cost has grown to $100 million.
Leiweke said the entire project, if approved, will be privately
financed and built by Galaxy owner Philip F. Anschutz and his
Anschutz Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has played its home matches at the Rose Bowl in
Pasadena since Major League Soccer's inaugural season in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-March, Leiweke said the Cal State Dominguez Hills site
would feature a soccer-specific stadium for the Galaxy, a tennis
stadium and would bid to become the training center for U.S.
national soccer teams. Wednesday, he said plans for the 80-acre
site, which would be leased from Cal State Dominguez Hills, have
been expanded to include a new cycling velodrome, as well as a
6,000-11,000-seat track and field stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The ambitious project isn't a done deal yet, however. In
contrast to Leiweke's enthusiasm, Cal State Dominguez Hills
president Dr. James E. Lyons Sr. appeared somewhat cautious in his
comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our discussions with the Staples Center about their
construction of an athletic complex at our university, we have
reached a conceptual framework that allows us to move forward,''
Lyons said. ``This conceptual framework, which allows a stadium
soccer and a tennis stadium, a jogging course with exercise
stations and a new velodrome, is responsive to our community and
bolsters our financial foundation as a place of higher learning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
