<DOCNO> NYT20000726.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-2NDTAKE     07-26 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: other side. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: You have been to Athens recently. How is the situation
evolving there since you expressed your concerns publicly about the
organization there?
</P>
<P>
   A: Much, much better. The day before yesterday I was with the
prime minister, Costas Simitis, and I also had a short talk with
the president of the country, and the appointment of the new
president of the organizing committee is Madame Gianna Angelopoulos
and I think it was the best decision. She was a great victor when
she brought the Games to Athens for 2004. Now she is there and she
is running the team she had during the bid and we are confident now
that things are going in the right way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have been quoted as saying you wish you had stepped down
after the Barcelona Games. Is that true and if so, why?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it is true. Because after the great success of Barcelona
in my city, I was at that moment 71 or 72. It was the right moment
maybe to leave. But on this occasion, I allowed myself to ask for
re-election for four more years, because in the four years to come
there would be the centennial of the IOC and a big congress in
Paris and to be the president of the IOC was a great honor on the
occasion of the centennial. But after, there came the last election
in 1997, and maybe yes, that was a mistake. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Six of the seven IOC presidents have been Europeans and there
has been one American, Avery Brundage. Do you think it is desirable
to have a greater geographical representation in the future?
</P>
<P>
   A: Maybe yes, but Europe is very important in the Olympic
movement. Speaking of the Summer Games, maybe 60 percent of the
medals and 60 to 65 percent of the participants are from Europe and
for the Winter Games, maybe 85 percent of the medals and
participants are coming from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What sort of qualities do you think your successor will need
to succeed in the role of president in the years ahead?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it serves no purpose to give advice or to recommend
certain types of qualities for the next president. After you're
gone, you're gone. But maybe one important thing is that the next
president must be a full-time president, like me, and living in
Lausanne, because if not, you are giving all the powers to the IOC
staff. And the staff of the IOC and also in all the other
organizations must be responding to the decisions of the elected
people.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think that unlike you, he or she should draw a salary?
</P>
<P>
   A: Why not? If he does not have the economical means to not be
paid, he must be paid, like many international federation
presidents and international organization presidents are paid.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some people believe that the 2008 Games will be the last in
which the Internet does not play a major role in viewing and the
last before the sports program evolves. Do you agree and how do you
envision the IOC negotiating this transition?
</P>
<P>
   A: Maybe the next president can change many things in the
program. Maybe. I couldn't, because to accept new sports is very
easy, but to get rid of sports is quite impossible. But maybe the
next president can succeed where I did not. As for the Internet, we
don't know. That is something which is a mystery for us about the
future of television and the Internet and for this reason in
November we are organizing a big congress to have some light shed
on what the future of the Internet and television will be. What we
have to guard against is not to pit the Internet against
television. I'm speaking for today. I don't know what can happen
one or two years from now. At this moment, I believe we have to put
the Internet and television together.
</P>
<P>
   Q:There has been an increasing number of prominent athletes
switching nationalities. Eunice Barber, the heptathlon world
champion who was born in Sierra Leone, became a French citizen
shortly before winning. Lyudmila Engquist became a Swedish citizen
shortly before winning a gold medal in the hurdles in Atlanta. Does
it concern you that as nationality becomes a commodity, it might
dilute the impact of the Games?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the IOC we have a rule and the rule is that if you are to
change nationality, there must be an agreement between the two
Olympic committees and if there is no agreement, you must wait
three years. If a boy is marrying a German girl and gets German
nationality, normally he can compete for that new country. I think
in your country, you have a good example with your professional
leagues. They are full of foreign people. We have our rule that's
all, and we are respecting this rule.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You said last year that ``I used to be happy to open the door
of my office. Now, I am happy if I close it behind me.'' How do you
feel about your door now?
</P>
<P>
   A: I said this because last year was not an easy year for me, to
be the leader, to try to get through these reforms, because the
members of the IOC, when they were elected, they had a lot of
powers and prerogatives and to convince them it was time to change
and to give up many prerogatives, like the visits to the bidding
cities for the Olympic Games and so on, was not easy.
</P>
<P>
   So that means at that moment, it was not easy. Now, it's a
pleasure again, but I'm also thinking that this pleasure will not
last very long.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're referring to the end of your term next year?
</P>
<P>
   A: In 11 months, I will be an ex-president. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
