<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-FOST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA BYTES: SAM DONALDSON VIEWING POLITICAL CONVENTIONS
FROM  CYBERSPACE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although his stentorian voice and pointy
eyebrows made him a political reporting legend, Sam Donaldson won't
be on television during the approaching party conventions. The
66-year-old newsman will be online.
</P>
<P>
   There's no more enthusiastic _ or more unlikely _ dot-commer
than Donaldson, who will Webcast two interviews a day from
Philadelphia and Los Angeles, where Republicans and Democrats
convene next week and next month, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pioneer,'' he said in an interview this week. ``Someday,
everyone will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential campaign is one more event that allows sites
like Donaldson's ABCNews.com to demonstrate that online journalism
has come into its own _ and in many cases is even better suited for
political reporting than other media.
</P>
<P>
   Take the conventions. The candidates were chosen long ago.
Platform fights are tedious. Most of what appears in prime time is
so orchestrated that viewers tune it out or turn it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Precious little happens; that's why we're not covering it
these days,'' said Donaldson, speaking with his network news hat
on.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Web, viewers who want all the nitty gritty can find
it, live and archived, all day and all night, with links that offer
incredible depth and e-mail that provides at least the potential
for true interactivity.
</P>
<P>
   The political parties, to their credit, get it, too. They are
setting up ``Internet alleys'' at the convention halls, where
online media can set themselves apart.
</P>
<P>
   And the online media are different. It's not all political vets
like Donaldson. Among those credentialed for this year's
conventions are former Sex Pistol Johnny Rotten (working for
eYada.com), comedian Will Durst (doing commentary for Mother Jones
magazine's MoJo Wire), and Arianna Huffington, who will not only
contribute to Salon.com but will also have her own sites stirring
things up, like  &LR; www.shadowconventions.com &LR;  and
 &LR; www.overthrowthegov.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Even giants of the Web like Yahoo will be there. Although Yahoo
mostly aggregates the content of other companies, it has hired
journalists like former KNTV anchor Lorna Ho and former Wired News
reporter Lindsey Arent to cover the conventions from a Net-centric
point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo is frustrated that there is not enough video in online
political coverage. To solve the shortage, it is making its own, at
least for now. ``Our intention is not to get into the
news-gathering business,'' said Eric Scholl, a CNNfn veteran who is
now executive producer of Yahoo FinanceVision. ``Sometimes you need
people to bridge the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson is online because his star power draws people to the
Web site, even if they are mostly techies.
</P>
<P>
   He knows they are techies, because when he interviews former
British leader John Major or historian Stephen Ambrose, no one
watches, but when he talks to Silicon Valley whizzes Marc
Andreessen or Bill Joy, the hit count soars.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I use the word `techies,' it's not demeaning,'' Donaldson
said. ``I love 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Salon.com uses some of the newfangled tools of
the Web, too, like streaming video.
</P>
<P>
   The Web's biggest edge, however, is immediacy. In fact, when I
talked to Washington bureau chief Kerry Lauerman, he was
frantically editing six stories on the breaking news of Dick
Cheney's selection as George W. Bush's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps Salon's greatest assets are more old-fashioned in
nature. ``It's really going to be the reporting that distinguishes
what we do,'' Lauerman said.
</P>
<P>
   NO FOOLING: It started with a press release disseminated on
April Fool's Day: MoJo Wire, the online arm of Mother Jones
magazine, was going to jump on the dot-com bandwagon by issuing
public stock. It was going to have a hip e-commerce component,
selling gas masks for protesters and gallon jugs of wheat paste.
</P>
<P>
   Well, satire is a dangerous business. Not only did a couple of
newspapers print the release as fact, but now MoJo Wire itself is
taking its prank seriously.
</P>
<P>
   At the Web site,  &LR; store.yahoo.com/mother-jones &LR; , Web explorers
can now actually buy Swedish army helmets and German-made, fully
functional gas masks, stenciled with the Mother Jones logo.
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for the political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   GO GROTTO: When Ethan Watters and Noah Hawley start playing
handball on the roof of their new suite of offices near San
Francisco's Civic Center, it's not hard to imagine what it looks
like from the office towers above: more dot-com workers, frolicking
on one of their frequent breaks.
</P>
<P>
   But Watters, Hawley and other occupants of the former Dog and
Cat Hospital on Fell Street aren't raking in stock options.
Instead, they are free-lance writers who have built a community by
renting office space together.
</P>
<P>
   The office has what Watters laments as a misleadingly
pretentious name, the Writer's Grotto. ``It's a terrible name,''
Watters says. At the outset, when they adapted it from a small
cavelike space in writer Po Bronson's house, ``we thought it was
ironic enough.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in fact, it still seems plenty ironic. The Grotto has grown
from six writers in a small Victorian flat on Duboce Triangle about
six years ago to a renovated two-story building with more than a
dozen writers and artists and a small film company today.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the place is still too funky to really be pretentious.
</P>
<P>
   The tile floor and fluorescent light fixture in the office of
writer Lisa Margonelli speaks to its past use as a pet operating
room. Margonelli sees the bright side: ``If the writing doesn't
work out, I can spay cats in here,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Oppenheimer, a regular contributor to the Atlantic Monthly,
took the grottiest office in the place. But by polishing a skylight
and painting the walls a peachy terra-cotta, he now has a bright,
upscale environment. ``At first, I said, who cares about painting
it, I'm here to write,'' Oppenheimer says. ``Now I feel so good
being in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Watters, Bronson and novelist Ethan Canin formed the first
Grotto, and even though all three were in the same room the other
day, they had trouble agreeing on who had the idea to rent a place.
They all concurred that the chief motivator was Canin's decision to
quit a medical residency and pursue writing full time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was risky,'' Canin said. ``I thought, what the hell were we
doing? We had to sign a lease.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, they can see how risk-free the proposition was.
``In those days, you could take your pick of any warehouse south of
Market,'' Canin said. ``We should have bought one.''
</P>
<P>
   REST IN PEACE: There will be a memorial service for Aaron
Bunnell, the former head of UpsideToday who died last week at age
26 of an apparent overdose, at Glide Memorial Church at 1:30 p.m.
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Dan Fost at  &LR; fostd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
