<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-OFFICER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO CASE OFFICER NOT LIABLE IN EARLIER DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the four police officers who shot Amadou
Diallo has been cleared of wrongdoing in another fatal shooting,
prompting that man's father to denounce the judicial process
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of the second victim, Patrick Bailey, a 22-year-old
black man from Brooklyn who was killed in 1997 by Officer Kenneth
Boss, had sued four police officers and the city for $2.5 million
for their roles in Bailey's death. The trial began in U.S. District
Court in Brooklyn on July 17, and the jury cleared the defendants
of any wrongdoing on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my son was murdered by Kenneth Boss,'' Lloyd Bailey,
the father of the slain man, said at a news conference Wednesday.
But, he said, after Boss and three others were acquitted in
Diallo's death, ``I figured it would be slim justice for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the jury to go out with five whites, one Latino and two
blacks and come back with a verdict in less than two hours was a
gross miscarriage of justice,'' he said. ``We are outraged, but
once again, justice does not work for black people in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gail Donaghue, a city lawyer, said she ``was pleased that a
jury was able to overcome a lot of public sentiment and feelings
and doubts about police officers that may be out there and sort out
the facts of a particular case in a very careful way.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 25, a jury in Albany acquitted the four white officers
of criminal wrongdoing in the death of Diallo, a Guinean street
vendor who was shot at 41 times in the vestibule of his Bronx
apartment building last year. The officers said they mistook a
black wallet that Diallo was holding for a gun. Diallo was hit 19
times.
</P>
<P>
   In the killing of Bailey, Boss said he opened fire after the
young man raised a sawed-off shotgun in a hallway. The officer was
one of four who had gone into Bailey's apartment building in East
New York to investigate a complaint that Bailey had threatened a
neighbor with a shotgun. Last year, the Brooklyn district
attorney's office decided that Boss had acted properly and chose
not to prosecute him.
</P>
<P>
   In the civil trial, lawyers for Bailey's family tried to prove
through witnesses that the dead man had not been holding a shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Bailey said he planned to appeal the verdict and would ask
the U.S. Justice Department to open a federal grand jury
investigation into what he called civil rights violations in the
shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
