<HEADER>
A4225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-425&AMP;A     07-26 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC PROSECUTORS SAY POLICE ARRESTED WRONG MAN IN BRICK ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Manhattan prosecutors said Wednesday that they were
virtually certain that police had arrested the wrong man in the
attack on a young woman with a chunk of concrete in Midtown,
despite his confession and two eyewitness identifications.
</P>
<P>
   And by the end of the day, police reluctantly agreed that their
case was unraveling.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a Manhattan judge ordered the release of the man,
Bently Louis Grant, 35, from the Rikers Island Detention Complex at
the request of prosecutors, who said new evidence seemed to clear
him. Wednesday, they said security videotapes showed Grant inside
the Virgin Megastore in Union Square at the time of the assault on
July 9.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Morgenthau, the Manhattan district attorney, called the
evidence overwhelming. ``We definitely do not think Grant was the
perpetrator,'' he said. ``Do you think we would make that decision
on something other than the evidence?''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had looked for Grant on the videotapes after
learning that he had claimed to be in the store on the day of the
attack. With detectives, they reviewed 15 hours of tapes from 31
surveillance cameras inside the store, Morgenthau said. The attack
probably took place between 12:05 and 12:08 p.m., he said, and the
tapes clearly show that Grant was in the store at Broadway and 14th
Street from 11:41 a.m. to 12:22 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``He carried this milk crate wherever he went, so it's not hard
to find him,'' Morgenthau added.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, who carried all of his belongings in the crate, has been
homeless since last November, said friends, who described him as a
quiet and sweet-tempered man. He was arrested last week after a
10-day investigation, and charged with the attempted murder of
Tiffany F. Goldberg, 25, the woman who was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:40 Wednesday morning, he was released on the judge's order
from the Rikers Island jail and sent to Elmhurst Hospital Center in
Queens for psychiatric evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   But for much of Wednesday, Police Department officials insisted
that their investigation continued to focus on Grant. Detectives,
who interviewed no new suspects, spent much of the day trying to
determine the value of the tapes, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent disagreement was noted by Grant's lawyer, Natasha
Lapiner-Giresi. ``I think the Police Department might be in a
little bit of a conflict with the district attorney's office,'' she
said. ``I can understand that the police would say that he
continues as a principal suspect, because they don't have any other
suspects.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Early in the day, Deputy Chief Thomas Fahey, a department
spokesman, said: ``We have not eliminated Grant, that's for sure.
His charges have not been dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   But by nightfall, it was clear the police were beginning to
agree with prosecutors. ``There is evidence that has caused
concern, and we are continuing the investigation,'' Fahey said.
``We certainly do not want to convict the wrong person.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his release, Grant had little opportunity to relish his
freedom. While at Elmhurst on Wednesday, family members, including
a younger brother, civilly committed him for psychiatric evaluation
and treatment, and he will remain there for the foreseeable future,
Lapiner-Giresi said. He has the legal right to contest his
commitment, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Through his lawyer, the family issued a statement saying that
the decision to commit Grant was a painful one. ``You tell them we
did it because we love him,'' the statement said. ``We want him to
get help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
