 COMPUTING Q&AMP;A: SLICK WAY TO PRINT ADDRESSES  &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: Is there any way to print out my America Online address book?
I've tried everything I can think of.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You can't print the AOL address book, and you can't export it to
another program that would let you print it. AOL's just peachy,
isn't it? But where there's a will, there's a way, and here it is:
You can print out a ``picture'' of the AOL address book just as it
appears on screen. Open the address book and maximize it by
clicking the middle of the three icons at the right end of the
title bar. The maximized window should contain all the information
for each contact, including the name, e-mail address and any notes
you've written about them.
</P>
<P>
   Now hold down the ALT key and press the Print Scrn key (it's
near the right end of the top row of keys on your keyboard). This
will take a picture of the screen and copy it to the Windows
clipboard. Open up a program that can handle graphics _ Microsoft
Word is a good one _ and use the paste function to copy the image
into a blank document. Then just print the document. If your
address book takes up more than one maximized window, you will have
to repeat the process after scrolling down to display additional
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   If any readers have discovered easier ways to print out the AOL
address book, I'd be happy to pass them on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-Mail by Cell
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'm going out of the country for six months, and I want to stay
in touch with my parents via e-mail. The problem is that they live
in a remote area along the Humboldt County coast, where they can
only be reached by cell phone. They also have satellite TV. What's
their best option for getting e-mail?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: It sounds as if they have only one possibility: the cell phone.
If they had a regular telephone line, they could subscribe to the
DirecPC service and get the Internet, and e-mail, via satellite. It
won't work without a phone connection because you need the phone
line to send keyboard and mouse commands to the Internet service,
which beams Web pages back to you via the satellite. (You can get
satellite TV without a phone line, as your parents do, but you
can't use your remote control to order pay-per-view programming.)
</P>
<P>
   Have them check out which, if any, cellular carriers in their
area provide Internet capabilities such as e-mail. If it's
available, they may have to spring for a new phone that includes a
browser. And the Internet service will add to their monthly
cellular bill. But I guess that's a small price to pay to stay in
touch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Sanity-Saving Printer
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: My wife and I are going nuts trying to decide on a portable
printer priced below $300. We won't use it that often, and we're
not overly concerned with speed, but print quality could be an
issue. We are considering the Canon BJC-80 series or the
Hewlett-Packard DeskJet 350C. Which one would you buy? Or is there
another printer out there that we haven't come across that might be
even better?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Canon and HP are the leading contenders in the market for
portable inkjet printers, which you can take anywhere and connect
to your laptop.
</P>
<P>
   The Canons offer slightly better resolution (720x360 dpi for
color versus HP's 600x300). But that's not enough to make a
noticeable difference when you are printing out things like Web
pages, and neither the Canon nor the HP portables comes close to
photo quality.
</P>
<P>
   For $300, your best bet may be the $299 HP 350 CBi, which
features a rechargeable battery and an infrared adapter for a
wireless hookup to a computer. But if you are willing to spend a
little more, the $349 Canon BJC-50 is pretty cool. It has
everything the HP has, but in a much smaller package. It's about
the size of a cigarette carton and weighs just 2 pounds, compared
with nearly 41/2 pounds for the HP.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Suppose you want to save a portion of a document for later use. You
can do it quickly by creating a ``scrap'' on the Windows desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how: With the document open, use your mouse to select the
text you want to save. Then drag the block of highlighted text to
any empty area of your desktop. This will create a separate file on
the desktop containing the scrap. You can open and edit it just by
double-clicking the file's icon. Or, you can paste the scrap into
another document by dragging the icon into an open document window.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Einstein at  &LR; computers(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
