<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLD MOVER PINCH-HITS AT SARATOGA OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Up until Tuesday afternoon, Mark Hennig
was going to scratch Gold Mover from the Schuylerville Stakes. His
filly had already won all three of her races, including a gritty
upset of colts at Churchill Downs, and he wondered if running a
2-year-old after just 18 days of rest was the right thing to do.
Besides, he had another undefeated filly, With Ability, ready to
go.
</P>
<P>
   But his plans changed Wednesday when With Ability came down with
a cough on Tuesday. She was scratched, and Gold Mover was led to
the gate, turned loose in a field of five and romped home a winner
in the very first stakes race of the 132nd Saratoga meet. A meet
that, despite gray skies and intermittent sprinkles, got off to a
record-breaking start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't want to run those two against each other and
With Ability was a little fresher, but then she coughed and looked
a little flat so we changed up,'' said Hennig, who, with the
victory in the Grade II $108,200 race, now has four stakes
victories in the 2-year-old filly division this year. ``It's nice
to know that if one of them gets sick, there is another who can
come in and be a great backup.''
</P>
<P>
   Hennig's original plan was to run With Ability in the
Schuylerville, Gold Mover in Monmouth Park's Sorority on Aug. 12
and his stakes-winning filly Raging Fever in the Adirondack at six
and a half furlongs here on Aug. 14. Now it looks as if With
Ability will go to Monmouth, on the Jersey Shore.
</P>
<P>
   The Schuylerville was roughly run by everyone but Gold Mover,
the daughter of Gold Fever. She broke first from the No. 1 post
while behind her, Seeking It All and Miss Doolittle pinballed off
each other. Her rider, Craig Perrett, found himself alone on the
lead as he crested the turn in the six furlong sprint. But Robbie
Davis, aboard Miss Doolittle, settled his filly after the rough
start and then zoomed her up the rail to get eyeball to eyeball
with Gold Mover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of surprised when Robbie made that inside move. I
thought it was a bit premature,'' Perrett said. ``But I had so much
horse and I took the race right at him. We put her away quickly and
discouraged that other filly.''
</P>
<P>
   With Doolittle dispatched, Gold Mover withstood a late charge
from Aaron Gryder and Seeking It All, a New York-bred who was sent
off at long odds and came within a neck of the upset. ``She was
running the best of any of them,'' said Gryder. ``She was reaching
out to win at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Gold Mover won by a neck in 1:11.1, paid $3.20 for $2 to win and
earned $64,920 for her owner, Edward P. Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a glimpse of Hennig's accomplished stable of young
fillies, the crowd of 27,810 _ a record for a July opening day _
got a first look at the more than $8 million in renovations to the
grand old track, as well as a pretty good indication that those who
came into the meet hot will remain so.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bailey, who won the Belmont spring riding title with 66
victories and an astounding 38.6 percent winning percentage, rode
two more winners yesterday. He was also named to replace Jorge
Chavez on the multiple stakes winner Behrens in next week's Whitney
by the trainer James Bond.
</P>
<P>
   And the trainer Joe Orseno, whose charges for the Frank Stronach
stable include the potential champions Golden Missile, Red Bullet
and Perfect Sting, unveiled another budding star with 2-year-old
Macho Uno. The son of Holy Bull demolished six other 2-year-olds in
his debut, which was some consolation after Orseno said he was not
running Red Bullet in the $1 million Haskell Invitational next week
at Monmouth because of a viral infection that has plagued the
Preakness winner.
</P>
<P>
   With 34 stakes remaining with purses totaling more than $8.6
million, the New York Racing Association is intent on bettering the
records it set last year. In 1999, on-track attendance rose 3.7
percent to 920,218 for a daily average of 25,562, and the on-track
handle increased by 5.4 percent to $111,969,548. The on-track
handle of $3,061,913 Wednesday was down slightly from last year's
opening day.
</P>
</TEXT>
