<SLUG> BC-MORTGAGE-ASSISTANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MORTGAGE PLAN AIDS LOW-INCOME BUYERS  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In an effort to encourage low-income families to
buy homes, a major mortgage company and a community group have
joined forces to offer cheaper loans in 10 cities nationwide,
including Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The program, announced Wednesday, will offer $360 million in
loans over the next three years to people with limited resources
and poor credit histories. The loans are available through an
agreement between Ameriquest Mortgage of Orange County, Calif., and
the Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now, a
national organization that tackles a wide range of issues for
low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem of predatory lending has been a huge one in the
neighborhoods where our members live,'' said Steve Kest, executive
director of ACORN. ``This pilot program is really going to make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   To get a loan, potential home buyers must first go through
counseling offered by the ACORN Housing Corp. Those who may qualify
for a loan will be referred to Ameriquest.
</P>
<P>
   The loans will be half a percentage point below the average
mortgage rate that other lenders charge low-income borrowers. The
loan agreements will include a set of new Ameriquest guidelines
that, among other things, give customers seven days to change their
mind instead of the three required by law.
</P>
<P>
   The loans, to be offered beginning in September, will be
available in six ZIP codes per city. The ZIP codes for Oakland have
yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities in the program include Chicago, Los Angeles and
Philadelphia. Nearly 10,000 families are expected to benefit from
the program.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, ACORN has signed agreements with several lenders to
broaden their loan guidelines to include more low-income families.
However, ACORN's Kest said the pact with Ameriquest marks the first
agreement he knew of between a community group and lender that went
as far as the one announced yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The loan program follows several months of negotiations between
Ameriquest, one of the nation's largest retail lenders to
low-income home buyers, and ACORN, which has been very critical of
the home-loan industry. It and other consumer groups have
complained for more than a year about how lenders take advantage of
low-income people by charging high interest rates and unfair fees.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ACORN filed a complaint with the Federal Trade
Commission in March on behalf of 30 Ameriquest customers, charging
unfair business practices. Kest said that those customer problems
are now being fixed and that his group's complaint will be
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Supinski, a policy advocate with the California
Reinvestment Committee, a San Francisco umbrella organization for
groups that advocate increased credit in low-income communities,
called the agreement between ACORN and Ameriquest a good beginning.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said the program is too small to have much effect
considering Ameriquest provides $4.2 billion in loans a year. She
said she is also skeptical about the company's statement that it is
reforming its lending practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's nice, it doesn't solve the problem,'' Supinski
said. ``Maybe it's a see-it-to-believe-it program.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
