<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-FINES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-TAILERS FINED FOR BROKEN PROMISES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Federal Trade Commission slapped Macys.com,
Toysrus.com and five other e-tailers with $1.5 million in fines
Wednesday for guaranteeing shipments to consumers last holiday
season and then failing to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement covers tens of thousands of consumers and $39
million worth of purchases that were not shipped by the promised
date or failed to arrive at all, said Jodie Bernstein, director of
the FTC's Bureau of Consumer Protection, in a telephone interview
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics complained the settlement amount was low,
particularly because the FTC found that some e-tailers had no
``reasonable basis'' for believing they could meet the Christmas
deadlines they advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Many e-shoppers were outraged during the holidays when Web sites
reneged on promises to quickly deliver toys and other gifts,
leaving consumers empty-handed on Christmas Day. Some 30 percent of
holiday Web shoppers experienced late deliveries last year, while
15 percent said their orders never arrived, according to
BizRate.com, which tracks e-tailer performance.
</P>
<P>
   Macys.com, headquartered in San Francisco, was one of three
e-commerce companies hit with the highest fine, $350,000. The
company, a unit of Federated Department Stores of Cincinnati, must
also fund an online advertising campaign to educate consumers about
their e-shopping rights; it is the only e-tailer required to do so.
Macys.com did not respond to requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   KBKids.com and Toysrus.com were also assessed $350,000. CDNow
was fined $300,000 but is only required to pay $100,000 because of
its financial problems. CDNow almost went under before agreeing to
be acquired by Bertelsman AG last week. Patriot Computers was
assessed $200,000 while the Original Honey Baked Ham Co. must pay
$45,000. The seventh Web site, Minidiscnow.com, was not fined but
agreed to reimburse customers who never received their orders.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors were taken into account in determining
settlement terms, according to the FTC. KBKids, Toysrus and the
Honey Baked Ham Co., for example, were given credit for sending
coupons or taking other steps to make up for delivery problems,
Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the e-tailers, Macys.com, KBKids, Minidiscnow and
Toysrus, were found to have made delivery guarantees with no
``reasonable basis'' for believing they could fill their orders on
time. For example, some of the e-tailers promised quick delivery of
goods they did not have in stock, Bernstein said. This counted
against them.
</P>
<P>
   All of the companies except CDNow failed to send notices that
shipments would not arrive by the promised dates. FTC rules require
such notification to give shoppers a chance to cancel their orders.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates said the level of the fines appears low. For
example, Federated Department Stores generated $795 million in
profits last year, which is 2,271 times the Macys.com fine.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the settlement sends a signal that the FTC ``is keeping a
very close eye,'' said David Steer, a spokesman for TRUSTe, an
Internet watchdog. `Clearly, there were quite a few consumers
during the holiday season who had their trust betrayed online'' by
untrue shipping claims, he said.
</P>
<P>
   FTC rules allow the agency to assess as much as $11,000 for each
day that each consumer fails to receive his or her order, said
Bernstein. That would have added up to ``a huge, huge, huge
amount,'' she said. The FTC must consider a company's ability to
pay and any steps taken to redress problems, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a settlement, (the e-tailers) don't get
everything they want and we don't get everything we want,''
Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Macys.com, the e-tailer is a separate legal
entity from its parent, and Federated was probably not privy to the
Web site's inner workings, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, FTC staff conducted initial investigations of 20
e-tailers they had received complaints about, either directly or
through the Better Business Bureau. The seven participants in
Wednesday's settlement were found to be in egregious violation of
the agency's Mail and Telephone Order Rule, which governs remote
selling.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
