<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SECOND BASEMAN ALICEA LIKES HIS ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CARLOS MENDEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Luis Alicea's agent made a case for the
second baseman with Rangers general manager Doug Melvin yesterday
and said Melvin was receptive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the trade deadline and so much that is going on at
this time in baseball, I just wanted to have a general conversation
with Doug and talk a little bit about Luis,'' said Barry Meister,
Alicea's agent.
</P>
<P>
   Meister said Alicea, who is in the final year of his contract,
likes his role with the Rangers as the No. 1 second baseman and
leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I told Doug is what Luis has told everybody, that he'd
like to return to the Rangers and be a catalyst for this year and
beyond,'' Meister said. ``Doug said what he has said in public,
that the Rangers are pleased with what Luis has done this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicea went into last night's game hitting .310, best among
American League second baseman, with 45 runs batted in, one shy of
his career high. \Nsubheds:Oliver velocity Darren Oliver spent time
on the disabled list in part because of what he believed was a dead
arm. His velocity didn't appear to be improved Tuesday night in his
second start since being activated.
</P>
<P>
   The radar gun reading at The Ballpark in Arlington showed
Oliver's fastest pitches at about 84 mph during a 42/3-inning
outing.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Dick Bosman said that while some of the gun
readings reflected hard changeups, Oliver isn't throwing as hard as
he has in the past. Oliver said he felt strong, which led Bosman to
suspect mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy tells you his arm is fine, that's where you go,''
Bosman said.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, who struck out two while giving up five runs on eight
hits against the Angels, is scheduled to start Sunday against
Detroit. \Nsubheds:The Haselman plan Bill Haselman, the Rangers'
starting catcher in the wake of Ivan Rodriguez's thumb injury, said
he believes in basics when it comes to directing a pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get ahead of the hitters,'' he said. ``Nothing we haven't done
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Haselman, who has never started more than 62 games in a season,
is a 10-year veteran who caught Roger Clemens' 20-strikeout game
for Boston in 1996. But he doesn't have any exotic ideas for the
Rangers' pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been the type of player that studied the game,
that knew the game. If I can bring some of that extra knowledge to
the pitchers, great,'' he said. ``Sometimes you're right, sometimes
you're wrong with suggestions. If you can find a little edge, maybe
it will help on one or two hitters, and that might be enough to
help win a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Haselman had hit safely in four consecutive games before last
night. He said it's just a matter of timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a hitter, you see pitches and get a chance to get your
timing,'' he said. ``I wouldn't say mentally it's different, but
physically, being in there every day helps.'' \Nsubheds:Green feats
Scarborough Green provided another breathtaking display of his
speed in Tuesday night's game against Anaheim, scoring the go-ahead
run in the eighth inning by forcing an errant throw to third and
running around an umpire to score.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the game for that reason, and while he's glad to be a
pinch runner and defensive replacement, the Rangers' fifth
outfielder said he's waiting for the chance to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take pride in my whole game,'' he said. ``It's something
people might think I can't do, play a whole game at this level. But
this is the way I'm being used right now. That's my role, and I
accept that. But through my whole career, I've been a player that
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, hitting .191, said he understands that the Rangers have
questions about his bat. His 47 at-bats are second-fewest on the
team.
</P>
<P>
   But few question his ability on the bases. Monday, he made it
back to first base safely after a pitch-out, and two months ago in
a game at Minnesota, he stole home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's God-given ability,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``He's
got pretty good instincts, too.'' \Nsubheds:Yeah, so? Johnny Oates
likes to talk about his team, but he rarely wastes a lot of words
talking about other players, even when it's Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The former Rangers slugger was activated by Detroit yesterday.
Asked if he had a reaction to the news, Oates offered only a polite
shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah. He's on the other team,'' he said. \Nsubheds:Briefly
Rafael Palmeiro, who homered Monday and Tuesday, is two home runs
behind Johnny Bench for 37th on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro moved past Ruben Sierra into third place on the
Rangers' career RBI list Tuesday night. He has 657 in a Texas
uniform. Juan Gonzalez is the club leader with 1,075.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Alicea and Kenny Rogers will join some Detroit Tigers
players at 1 p.m. today at the Dallas Zoo, which houses two
Sumatran tigers originally from the Detroit Zoo. The players will
pose at the tiger exhibit to promote tonight's game. The first
20,000 fans at The Ballpark will receive a voucher for free
admission to the Dallas Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's game against Anaheim was the Rangers' last game
against an American League West opponent until Sept. 22, when
Anaheim returns for a three-game series at The Ballpark. The
Rangers have nine games remaining against AL West opponents, all to
close out the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Sierra homered for Oklahoma City on Tuesday night in a 7-3
victory against Colorado Springs, giving him two homers, a double
and seven RBI over two games. \Nsubheds:Good eye Rafael Palmeiro
had 13 more walks than strikeouts going into last night, the
fourth-best figure in the American League. The rundown: Name, team
