</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYMENT-P2P-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 P2P PAYMENTS TRANSFERRED QUICKLY, CHEAPLY  &HT;     By BECKY WARING 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The phrase ``please send money'' is taking on a
whole new meaning thanks to Web sites that specialize in
person-to-person (P2P) payments.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, sometime soon you'll get an e-mail requesting
money. And, no, it won't be a junk mail solicitation. It will be be
from your roommate requesting this month's rent; from a co-worker
asking for your share of yesterday's lunch date; from an eBay
seller requesting payment for an auction you won; or from your
college kid asking for book money.
</P>
<P>
   Six sites _ PayPal, eCount, PayMe, ProPay, eMoneyMail and
MoneyZap _ offer services that help you pay another individual on
the Web. No cash necessary, and no more writing checks or
addressing envelopes. The services are either free or low cost.
</P>
<P>
   One service, PayPal, even works on Palms and other handheld
devices; you can send money to another organizer just by entering
an e-mail address and amount, then beaming it. It also works on a
Web-enabled cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   While it's natural to be skeptical about trusting finances,
however small, to upstart Web sites, we tried most of the major
players without a serious hitch. The main complaint was occasional
processing delays, but the money always came through.
</P>
<P>
   Most P2P payments simply use your e-mail address and checking or
credit card number. When you send money, the funds are debited from
one of these accounts, and when you receive it, the money is
deposited into your checking account.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hagen, an analyst with Forrester Research, expects these
systems to catch on quickly. The alternatives, such as sending a
check or using the Western Union wire, are too slow and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he points out the increasing importance of online
auctions. More than 35 percent of online shoppers purchased goods
through auctions in 1999..
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he cites the self-propagating aspect of P2P payment
services: To send or receive money from a user, you have to sign up
for an account.
</P>
<P>
   PayPal.com (part of the X.com family of online financial sites)
is by far the largest such service with millions of accounts. It
offers users $5 for referring new members.
</P>
<P>
   The other secret to PayPal's success is its concentration on
auction services. On July 14, almost 2 million eBay listings bore
the PayPal logo, versus 400,000 for BillPoint, eBay's own payment
service. BillPoint is handicapped in two big ways: It charges
transaction fees to the seller, and it only works for auction
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the six services stack up:
</P>
<P>
   PayPal -- Industry leader PayPal has the most flexible features.
There are special forms for auction payments, and you can bill
groups of people at once, such as for a special event.
</P>
<P>
   PayPal lets you use credit cards, bank transfers or paper checks
to deposit money in your account and withdraw funds via transfer or
paper check. . No other payment site accepts checks.
</P>
<P>
   While other P2P sites have per-day spending caps (typically
$500), PayPal offers higher limits after certain conditions are
met. And, of course, there are those $5 bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   eCount -- ECount is a newcomer that just premiered in April, but
is striving mightily to emulate and extend PayPal's robust feature
set. As with PayPal, you can send and request money via e-mail, and
the system keeps an online account for withdrawals and deposits
just like a bank account.
</P>
<P>
   But eCount adds other valuable features. First, you can use
money in your account to make purchases at any online vendor that
accepts MasterCard, a huge convenience. Also, eCount lets you tie
your account to up to five e-mail addresses, whereas PayPal only
allows one.
</P>
<P>
   One limitation is that you can only deposit money in your
account via credit card, not bank transfer or paper check. To take
money out, a mailed check is the only option, although the company
expects to add bank transfer soon.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, you must deposit money from your credit card before
spending it, whereas PayPal will automatically bill your credit
card when you spend more than you have.
</P>
<P>
   PayMe -- PayMe feels much like PayPal on the surface, except
that there is no online intermediary account. You can send and
request money, and there are special tools for auction payments. To
deposit money, you use a credit card; payments are deposited
directly to your bank account. There's no paper check option.
</P>
<P>
   Transaction limits are fairly standard: $500 per transaction,
$1,000 per day and $10,000 per six months.
</P>
<P>
   We liked the fact that with PayMe, money goes straight to our
checking accounts, rather than languishing online. This will be a
key point for many, especially auction sellers who don't want to
pay for PayPal's premium service (which includes automatic bank
deposit).
</P>
<P>
   PayMe.com was acquired in April by PayMyBills.com, a leading
online bill-paying service.
</P>
<P>
   ProPay --- While it also offers basic P2P payments for free,
ProPay is really oriented toward merchants who don't have credit
card processing capabilities, much like eBay's BillPoint service.
Transactions are 3.5 percent, plus 35 cents. Credit cards are
billed directly, with the proceeds deposited in your bank account.
The maximum per transaction is $250, although premium services are
available. One key point with ProPay is that from the buyer's point
of view, it looks like a regular credit card transaction. You don't
have to sign up as a member of ProPay, as with the other services.
</P>
<P>
   EMoneyMail -- EMoneyMail, sponsored by Bank One, definitely has
a banklike feel. There is a $1 fee per transaction, charged to the
sender. You can send and receive money via Visa or checking account
transfer; the recipient can opt for a paper check for $1 extra.
There's a $500 daily limit and no special support for group or
auction payments, as with some of the other sites. The $1 fee is a
stumbling block when most P2P sites are free, as is the fact that
Visa is the only credit card accepted.
</P>
<P>
   MoneyZap -- Western Union's MoneyZap is quick and easy, and a
good choice for occasional one-time payments when you don't want to
set up a running account with a site like PayPal or eCount. There
are no bells and whistles, just basic pay and go. You enter your
credit card or bank account info, send the money via e-mail, and
the recipient ``picks it up'' by entering a bank account number for
transfer. You can also request money from one person or a group.
Transactions are limited to $500 each, $900 a day and $2,000 per
month. The service is free for now.
</P>
<P>
   You can't pick up MoneyZap cash at a physical Western Union
office. Instant cash can be sent for a fee via Western Union's Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Note that thus far, none of these sites lets you send and
receive payments internationally, but most hope to offer this
service in the future.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of heavy hitters are set to enter the fray later this
year. Yahoo will launch PayDirect, and AOL is teaming up with
Citigroup to offer P2P services. Assuming these Web giants match
the current services in features and ease of use, they should be
formidable competitors.
</P>
<P>
   While eMoneyMail and ProPay charge nominal fees, the others cost
nothing. How can they afford to offer such services for free? Some,
like PayPal and eCount, maintain intermediary accounts for you,
rather than depositing receipts directly to your checking account.
They expect to earn interest on the money in your account to help
recoup their costs. They also offer premium services to businesses,
filling a huge need for inexpensive credit card processing by small
online merchants and auction sellers.
</P>
<P>
   If you think all this is a little too good to be true, you're
not alone. Many analysts doubt that sites like PayPal can continue
to offer P2P services completely free of charge. But until the
industry shakeout happens, consumers should by all means take
advantage. Some form of P2P payment system is sure to hold on.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Becky Waring at  &LR; becky(AT)waring.org &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2340EDT &QL; 
