<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIPHASE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JDS UNIPHASE FOURTH-QUARTER PROFITS EXCEED ESTIMATES
</HEADLINE>
  By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The JDS Uniphase Corp., a fast-growing maker of
components for fiber optic networks, reported fourth-quarter
earnings Wednesday that exceeded analysts' estimates when excluding
charges for the company's wave of acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended June 30, JDS, based in San Jose, Calif.,
and Nepean, Ontario, posted a net loss of $419 million, or 54 cents
a share, compared with a loss of $194.3 million, or 60 cents a
share, in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding merger-related charges and other special items, JDS
Uniphase reported profit of $114 million, or 14 cents a share. In
the period a year earlier, the combined profit of JDS Fitel and the
Uniphase Corp. _ which merged in June 1999 _ was $41 million, or 6
cents a share. Sales grew 173 percent, to $524 million from $192
million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected the company to earn 12 cents a share,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Although JDS Uniphase reported its results after the markets
closed, investors anticipated a strong quarter and drove the
company's shares up $5.75, to $135.9375, in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase traded more shares in a single day than any other
U.S. stock _ just more than 200 million _ as money managers added
it to their holdings before it became part of the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index. The stock was added to the S&AMP;P 500 after exchanges
closed.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call, executives of JDS Uniphase predicted that
revenue growth would accelerate and increased their estimates of
quarter-to-quarter growth to the high teens from 15 percent, not
including the effects of acquisitions. Revenue in the most recent
quarter grew 33 percent from the previous quarter, or 25 percent
excluding acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Although JDS Uniphase's explosive revenue growth was expected,
``it shows you how powerful this industry is,'' said Jim Kedersha,
an analyst with SG Cowen. The company also benefits from a market
where demand exceeds supply and the barriers to adding supply are
high, he said.
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase's rapid growth and aggressive acquisition strategy
had already given it a high profile, but the spotlight has shown
more brightly on the company since reports that the Nortel Networks
Corp. might sell its optical components division to Corning Inc.
for about $100 billion. Nortel and Lucent Technologies, which has
said it will spinoff a similar components business, are large
customers of JDS Uniphase as well as competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The future of Nortel and Lucent components businesses of Nortel
and Lucent adds an element of uncertainty, Kedersha said. ``I think
people are going to be concerned about how will the competitive
environment change if these two big captive suppliers get spun
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph Strauss, the president and chief executive of JDS
Uniphase, said the market was sufficiently dynamic to support many
suppliers. ``I think there is enough to eat for a long time,'' he
said in a telephone interview. ``The Internet is just getting
going. We need many, many suppliers to meet this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase's results included those of Epitaxx Inc., Sifam
Ltd., Optical Coating Laboratory Inc., Cronos Integrated
Microsystems Inc. and Fujian Casix Laser Inc., which were acquired
between Nov. 15, 1999, and May 8. Results for the quarter do not
include those of E-Tek Dynamics Inc., which was acquired on June
30.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting separately, E-Tek had sales of $123 million for the
quarter that ended June 30 and pro forma net income of $23 million,
or 32 cents a share. Pro forma sales combining JDS Uniphase and
E-Tek were $641 million, the company said. Pro forma net income was
$137 million, or 14 cents a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
