<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4240 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-Saints-HNS &LR;      07-26 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-Saints-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Benson entrusts Haslett, Mueller to rebuild Saints
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THIBODAUX, La. _ New Orleans Saints owner Tom Benson knew something
had to be done. His team was suffering through a dreadful 3-13
season. His players seemed to invent new ways to lose. Fans were
outraged. The media was unforgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Trading eight draft choices for running back Ricky Williams was
turning into a disaster. Everyone but Archie Manning was taking a
turn as the starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   More embarrassing than the players' performance was the behavior
of coach Mike Ditka. Each time Ditka stepped on the field, there
was the threat of spontaneous combustion. He scolded reporters and
reacted to fans who ridiculed the Saints as they left the Superdome
field by grabbing his crotch and extending his middle finger.
</P>
<P>
   The Fleur-de-lis was wilting.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it wasn't the kind of positive environment conducive
to getting a more favorable lease. A change had to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Fulfilling a promise he made to fans and media in early December
``to take whatever steps necessary to reestablish the Saints as a
winning organization,'' Benson ended the Ditka error by firing the
coach and president/general manager Bill Kuharich, both of whom had
received contract extensions in preseason.
</P>
<P>
   When housecleaning at the Superdome had been done, it cost
Benson $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it cost a lot of money, but the Kuharich/Ditka thing
didn't work, so we stepped up and made the change,'' the
72-year-old Benson says in his office at the team's campus
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The sweeping changes in the front office brought in a new regime
of general manager of football operations Randy Mueller, head coach
Jim Haslett and director of administration Arnold D. Fielkow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten a lot of feedback from fans,'' Benson says. ``They
say they like what they see, and they believe it's going to work.
But I know from experience that if we have another 3-13 record _
and I don't think we will _ those same fans will forget they ever
said that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if we win, Jim and Randy will be kings of Mardi Gras.''
</P>
<P>
   In another move to convince fans of his sincerity, Benson moved
training camp from La Cross, Wis., to Nicholls State in Thibodaux.
It is the first time since 1987 the Saints have trained in
Louisiana. Attendance at practice has been phenomenal, and 10,000
attended a Saturday night scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the greatest fans, and they hurt when the Saints
lose,'' Benson says. ``I can understand that because they take
losing personally. They feel like they're part of the Saints.
That's a great thing. They live and die with us. Since the club's
been down so much, they're hungry to win.''
</P>
<P>
   After compiling a 15-33 record in Ditka's three seasons, they
Saints are starving to win. In 33 years, they have never won a
playoff game. The only time they even made the playoffs was in the
Jim Finks/Jim Mora era. Finks, the general manager, died after a
long illness. Mora quit, went into television and resurfaced in
Indianapolis in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Benson would like to recapture some of that playoff magic.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller, 38, spent his entire life and NFL career in the Pacific
Northwest until he came to New Orleans in January. He spent all of
his 17-year NFL career with the Seahawks, advancing to vice
president of football operations. It was culture shock going from
Seattle to New Orleans. And humidity was something he had only
experienced on road trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, well, it is kind of hot, isn't it?'' Mueller says with a
smile from a covered golf cart. ``We've been here about six months,
and we love the area and the people. They've made us feel so
welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson's support and the fans' enthusiasm have blown Mueller
away. After being in Seattle and competing with the Sonics and
Mariners for attendance and attention, Mueller loves being the only
game in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom's been so supportive,'' Mueller says. ``He said, ``You do
whatever it takes, and I'm going to back you. All I want is to
win.' He just said to not call him after 9 p.m. That's a lot of
rope for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saints fans are great. They're so passionate about football.
When it comes to pro sports, it's the Saints and only the Saints.
We're in the spotlight all the time. When we get it straightened
out, everybody will be on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller, who interviewed Haslett before Mike Holmgren was hired
in Seattle, hired the Pittsburgh defensive coordinator as head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim and I are new, and we don't care about the past,'' Mueller
says in reference to the team's legacy of failure. ``I don't say
that with disrespect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's committed. We've put in a lot of long hours and a
lot of hard work. There's been so much to do in a relative short
period of time. I don't know if we're there yet. I wish we had
another offseason. We know we can't solve it all right away, but we
will promise that our guys will play hard, and we'll be
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get all our new people on the same page. If we
don't get off to a good start, people are going to say we're the
same old Saints, but we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Haslett, 44, was an outstanding linebacker for the Bills who
ended his playing career with the Jets. He was an assistant with
the Raiders and Saints before joining Bill Cowher's Steelers staff
as defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience as a player and assistant coach has helped
prepare me to become a head coach,'' Haslett says. ``I've respected
Randy for a long time. Since I was a coach for the Saints, I think
I understand what everyone's gone through here. I think this is a
unique situation.''
</P>
<P>
   After a strenuous offseason program under Haslett, the players
were so excited to get to camp that two veterans _ quarterback Jeff
Blake and defensive tackle Le'Roi Glover _ tried to report with the
rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to tell them they couldn't because league rules won't
allow it,'' Haslett says. ``But it's a good sign. Usually players
hate going to camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller, whose younger brother, Rick Mueller, left Jacksonville
to become the Saints' director of player personnel, has made so
many changes on the roster that only 30 of the 87 players were in
training camp last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints signed such veteran free agents as Blake, receiver
Jake Reed, defensive tackle Jon Hand, linebacker Darrin Smith,
cornerback Steve Israel, free safety Darren Perry, linebacker
Charlie Clemons and receiver Joe Horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we had some cap room, and I knew if we used that
money wisely, we'd have a chance,'' Randy Mueller says about
bringing in so many new players. ``We haven't mortgaged any of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the draft's still the best way to build a
team. We targeted young players we thought were ascending, and we
consider them our draft choices. We're headed in the right
direction, but there's still a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson, who had been feeling the heat _ literally and
figuratively _ is happy now to sit under the shade tree and watch
his team practice. He can't get over the number of fans who are
attending practice.
</P>
<P>
   Benson is convinced that he has made the correct decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Randy I don't like surprises, to keep me informed so I
don't have to read about us getting rid of a player,'' Benson says.
``I told him I don't like bad news, but I'd rather hear it from
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy's intelligent and he has loads of energy. He'll stay at
the office all night if he has to. He and Jim work well together.
Jim coaches, and Randy handles personnel. They communicate well.
It's a great combination I'm very comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mueller and Haslett are future kings of Mardi Gras, what
would that make Benson?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Benson says, ``Tom's getting a little old for Mardi
Gras, so he'd be happy just to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
