<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ACCOUNTING-SEC-NYT     07-26 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTING-SEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 BIG ACCOUNTING FIRMS ASSAIL SEC'S PROPOSED RESTRICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Representatives of three major accounting firms
strongly criticized a proposal Wednesday to restrict the types of
consulting work that the firms can provide for the companies whose
financial statements they audit.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing here by the Securities and Exchange Commission, its
first public hearing on an accounting issue in more than 20 years,
representatives of KPMG, Arthur Andersen and Deloitte &AMP; Touche
argued that there were no proven cases in which an audit had been
compromised because the auditing firm had other relationships with
the company.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the SEC, Arthur Levitt, said he hoped a decision
could be reached that would satisfy everyone involved. But he also
said he was convinced that action was needed in part because of a
perception that auditor independence had been limited by such
relationships. ``We cannot dismiss perception as being a terribly
important issue for the industry,'' Levitt said.
</P>
<P>
   While accounting firms are already barred from providing many
consulting services to auditing clients, the SEC is proposing two
extensions of those prohibitions.
</P>
<P>
   One would forbid internal audits of companies _ those normally
performed by company employees for the use of management _ when the
same accounting firm is to conduct the outside audit, an
independent examination in which the responsibility is to
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents argue that external auditors would be reluctant to
criticize their colleagues' work. And the comptroller of the
currency, John D. Hawke Jr., said bank regulators were worried
about the practice and that seven of the nation's 50 biggest banks
had retained their outside auditors for such work.
</P>
<P>
   The other area that would be barred is information services
consulting _ which has grown as consultants, many from auditing
firms, design and install large management information services. If
such systems provide incorrect information, critics say, the
auditors whose firms designed the systems may be less vigilant in
reviewing the reports.
</P>
<P>
   The two accounting firms that have indicated greater willingness
to accept such rules, PricewaterhouseCoopers and Ernst &AMP; Young, did
not testify Wednesday. Both are divesting themselves of their
consulting practices, and KPMG is in the process of doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules drew some support Wednesday. John Biggs,
chairman of TIAA-CREF, the huge pension fund manager, called for
``adoption of one unalterable rule: independent public audit firms
should not be the auditors of any company for which they
simultaneously provide other services; it's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Auditors would not be prohibited from offering the disputed
services to people other than their own auditing clients. But the
auditing firms that oppose the proposed rules said they would be
forced to sell their consultancy arms because they could not
compete, for clients or for staff members, with consulting firms
that could serve any company.
</P>
<P>
   Robert R. Garland, national managing partner of Deloitte &AMP;
Touche's auditing service, said: ``Given what is at stake, and the
fact that there is no demonstrated problem, it would be
irresponsible to take on the considerable risks surrounding the
proposed rule. There is no evidence that broad scope of services
has an adverse effect on audit quality. My own personal experience
has caused me to conclude just the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Terry Strange, global managing partner for auditing at KPMG,
said ``nonaudit services enhance audit effectiveness.'' And he
maintained that the SEC action was rushed, with only a 75-day
comment period.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt clearly wants to complete action before a new president
can replace him as chairman, and opponents want to delay a decision
in the hope that a new chairman will reverse course.
</P>
<P>
   While firms opposed to the rules repeated that there was no
evidence any audits had been compromised, some proponents insisted
that such evidence would be rare as no auditor was likely to write
a memo saying he had approved a bad audit because he feared losing
revenue for his firm.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas R. Carmichael, an accounting professor at Baruch
College, who served as research director for an investigation into
the issue by a commission headed by Manuel Cohen, a former SEC
chairman, said there had been such cases. He cited a 1978 audit of
the Westec Corp., which the Cohen panel concluded had been
compromised because of consulting services. And he said a 1998
civil suit that raised suspicion of such conflicts had been settled
by the accounting firm involved, with the evidence sealed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-26-00 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
