<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-26 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4265 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-ASHE-SCULPTURE-34     07-26 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ASHE-SCULPTURE-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ESSENCE OF A TENNIS CHAMPION, CAST IN BRONZE 
</HEADLINE>
  By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The U.S. Tennis Association is set to unveil a statue
commemorating the late tennis champion Arthur Ashe by the American
neo-expressionist artist Eric Fischl.
</P>
<P>
   The statue will be revealed on Aug. 28, the first day of the
U.S. Open. A 7-foot tall figure of a nude black man, it is cast in
the heroic tradition of ancient Greek statues of athletes. One arm
soars toward the sky as if tossing a ball to serve and the other
arm is behind the figure, as if weighted down by an imaginary
racket. It will stand outside the Arthur Ashe Stadium at the
National Tennis Center in Flushing Meadows-Corona Park, in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The statue, made of roughly modeled bronze, is not intended to
be a likeness of Ashe, said Fischl, but rather a metaphor for his
bravery and spirit. Ashe, the only black man to win Wimbledon and
the U.S. and Australian Opens, died of complications of AIDS in
1993 at the age of 49. ``I was trying to find a way through the
language of tennis and the language of the body to express some of
what I thought were the attributes and values he represented,''
Fischl said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashe campaigned against discrimination and on behalf of those
suffering from AIDS. At the base of the statue are carved his
words: ``From what we get, we make a living; what we give, however,
makes a life.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when few major contemporary artists are creating
commemorative work, the commission of Fischl is unusual. He was
chosen from a group of about 12 artists by a panel led by Ashe's
widow and by Michael Ainslie, the former president and chief
executive of Sotheby's, and a tennis association board member.
``When I saw it, I thought it was just stunning,'' Jeanne
Moutoussamy-Ashe, Ashe's widow, said of the mock-up of the statue
that Fischl showed to the committee. ``It carried tremendous grace
and power and form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that people will respond that way and that they will
get a sense of immediacy and power that we as a committee received
ourselves,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The figure of the man in the statue seems to emerge from the
ground, and with the outstretched arm, the entire work reaches 14
feet. It is to be the centerpiece of the Arthur Ashe Commemorative
Garden, near the principal entrance to the Arthur Ashe Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Fischl said that he drew inspiration from the Greek statues of
``The Discus Thrower'' and the ``Javelin Thrower,'' and
Michelangelo's ``David.'' When asked about the subject's nudity,
Fischl said that he originally considered creating a clothed figure
as a memorial, but decided against it. ``I wanted something that
was not time-specific, but of a more universal kind of time, a
historical time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought, no, I'm not interested in that. If they want
clothes they should get another sculptor,'' he said. ``There's a
form that represents the genitals. It's incredibly modest. The body
is being formed as it moves up. That's the way I got around the
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Levering, president of the tennis association, said that in
considering the statue's nudity, the committee ``felt that Eric
very tastefully handles that and we were not upset about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The statue is being paid for by friends and family of Ashe,
individual donors and the tennis association. The budget was about
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fischl, an enthusiastic tennis player who never met Ashe but saw
him play, came into prominence in the 1980s for his paintings
depicting the sexual tensions and neuroses of suburban life.
</P>
<P>
   One painting, ``Sleepwalker'' from 1979, showed a naked boy in a
shallow pool who is apparently masturbating. Another, ``Bad Boy,''
was of a naked woman lying on a bed while a young man reaches into
her purse. His painting ``First Sex'' suggested a woman
masturbating, and in ``Dog Days,'' he showed a boy and girl on a
balcony seemingly on the brink of having sex.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years Fischl's work has undergone a change. His
most recent show was of large-scale, Caravaggio-like portraits of
his celebrity friends, including the director Mike Nichols, and one
of his dealers, Mary Boone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent years there has been much less sexual narrative,''
Fischl said of his work. ``I've always been a psychological
painter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
