A4270 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-WOMEN-GYMNASTICS-     07-26 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMEN-GYMNASTICS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Common goal helps Karolyi mesh new, old
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID BARRON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. LOUIS _ As the hours tick away before today's USA Gymnastics
women's national championships, Kristen Maloney, the defending
all-around national champion, and Elise Ray, the top all-around
performer at last year's world championship team trials, sit alone
and relatively undisturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney and Ray are champions at the peak of their game in an
Olympic year, and yet they have been overshadowed by gymnastics'
equivalent of the senior tour.
</P>
<P>
   And, actually, they don't mind it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the likes of Maloney, Ray, Vanessa Atler and Alyssa
Beckerman are the more logical choices to make the 2000 Olympic
team, most of the attention during the selection process that
begins today will be on the comeback efforts of Shannon Miller,
Dominique Moceanu and three other veterans from the ``Magnificent
Seven,'' the 1996 Olympic gold medalists in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem to be prime territory for generational strife,
jealousy and intrigue, and yet that doesn't seem to be the case.
And much of the credit, strangely enough, goes to the past master
of gymnastics intrigue, Bela Karolyi.
</P>
<P>
   It was Karolyi, appointed earlier this year as national team
coordinator, who arranged a series of monthly training camps at his
New Waverly ranch to mesh the old and new into what USA Gymnastics
hopes will be a medal contender for the Sydney Olympics. And he
seems to have bridged the generation gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're kind of melding together,'' said Ray, 18, from
Columbia, Md., the defending national champion on floor exercise.
``I know that the (1996 Olympians) have a lot of experience under
them and in that since we're a little different, but we're all
going for the same goal. And I think that their comeback has been
an inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the monthly camps at Karolyi's ranch, ``I think I would
have felt a little more intimidated by them,'' Ray said. ``But now
that we've all worked together, it's a more personal feeling toward
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Maloney, 19, from Pen Argyl, Pa., is the first gymnast since Kim
Zmeskal of Houston in 1990-92 to win back-to-back national
all-around titles, and a victory this week would make her only the
third gymnast in history to win at least three in a row. But with
so much attention focused on the former Olympians, she has a chance
to sneak in under the radar screen that normally is trained on the
defending champ.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes the pressure off, especially when everything is
focused on a lot of other people and spread out,'' she said. ``I
think I like it better. I like going in as an underdog or whatever
to show them I can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition begins today at the Kiel Center with preliminary
rounds in the all-around competition, which concludes Saturday
night. Today's scores also will be used to determine the individual
champions on each apparatus _ vault, balance beam, uneven bars and
floor exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Event finals and all-around finals will make up 40 percent of
the score used to determine the top candidates for the Olympic
team, with the bulk of the scores coming from next month's Olympic
trials in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   However, the final word on selection of the six-member team will
fall to a committee headed by Karolyi in consultation with USA
gymnastics president Bob Colarossi.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time of the truth. There is nothing to hide,''
Karolyi said. ``There are nice surprises, very pleasant surprises,
coming around, and now they are coming even more strongly from the
former ones, the ones we are so proud of, the Olympic champions who
are filling the gap on the competitive side, getting into
competitive shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very interesting to see. Here is the younger
generation. Here is the older generation. How is it going to shape
up?''
</P>
<P>
   For Miller, the seven-time Olympic medalist who is the most
decorated women's gymnast in U.S. history, that may remain unclear
for awhile. Miller is recovering from a leg injury suffered in
early July and was a long shot to compete today. However, her
coach, Steve Nunno, said Miller had a good workout Wednesday and
could compete on uneven bars or vault.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any kind of competition allows her one more competition under
her belt, so it's essential she be allowed to compete here,'' Nunno
said. ``She vaulted for the first time (Tuesday) night and was able
to do uneven bar dismounts, which was one of the missing links in
being able to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the spotlight also will fall on Moceanu, the 14-year-old
sprite of 1996 who has grown 10 inches in four years and went
through a protracted legal battle with her father, Dumitru, and
mother, Camelia. She later reconciled with her mother and moved to
Cincinnati, where she is training with coach Mary Lee Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, as with her 1996 teammates Amy Chow, Jaycie Phelps,
Miller and Dominique Dawes, struggled during the first weeks of her
comeback attempt but is confident of her chances for another
Olympic team berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm older, I know what to expect, and I want it and want it
bad for me and for my future,'' she said. ``I know so much more. I
was so young the last time around. Four years is a long time, and
it covers a lot of experience and knowledge, both mental and
physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy said that maturity, coupled with the new code of points
that govern how the sport is judged, ensures that viewers will see
a much different Moceanu than the one they remember from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her style has changed. She's a mature and happy athlete,''
Tracy said. ``I think that the code that we are under now allows
for enough flexibility that you can be older and more mature and
can get your degree of difficulty without being 4-6 and 60
pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
