u k BC-EDIT-NKOREA-MISSILES-     07-26 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NKOREA-MISSILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A MISSILE MESSAGE FROM NORTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, July 27:
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin of Russia came back from North Korea
recently reporting a tantalizing offer. The North, he said, would
give up its menacing long-range-missile program if other countries
would launch at least two North Korean space satellites a year. If,
as Putin believes, Pyongyang envisions sending its satellites
abroad for launching, the proposal merits serious consideration.
But if North Korea expects other countries to provide it with
advanced rockets it could learn to copy, the risks are
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea now appears to be in the early stages of a
transformation that Washington should actively encourage. After
decades of belligerence and self-imposed isolation, Pyongyang has
reached out in recent months with words and gestures of
reconciliation, most notably toward its former archenemy, South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   But it is too soon to conclude that North Korea has joined the
community of peaceful nations. Its nuclear weapons and missile
programs have been suspended, not abandoned. Reckless foreign
missile sales and human rights abuses continue, as do allegations
of international drug trafficking. America must use caution in
engaging North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's efforts to develop long-range missiles have
alarmed Japan and have driven U.S. efforts to build a limited
national missile defense. Washington's next step should be
clarifying what Pyongyang has in mind. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright can begin that exploration when she meets with North
Korea's foreign minister in Bangkok on Friday. Past experience with
North Korea suggests that its initial bargaining proposals can be
vague and unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   Besides confirming that North Korea is proposing satellite
launches from outside its territory, Washington needs to find out
whether the satellites would be used for military and intelligence
purposes and who would pay the launching costs. It should also seek
a North Korean commitment to stop exporting missile technology.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
