u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      07-26 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' three homers in sixth sink Reds
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CINCINNATI _ The wins are back _ and so is the music.
</P>
<P>
   What has bordered on a funeral-like atmosphere in the Astros
clubhouse this season quickly turned into Party Central on
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on top of the world, man,'' manager Larry Dierker said
after the Astros again came from behind to beat the Cincinnati Reds
3-2, completing their first three-game sweep at Cinergy Field in
nearly 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had barely put the finishing touches on their
season-high fifth consecutive victory when pitcher Jose Lima popped
a CD _ his own naturally _ into a boom box and the Astros began a
sing-along.
</P>
<P>
   In a season that has produced the worst record in baseball,
there were plenty of reasons for the Astros to celebrate. They rode
a three-homer barrage in the sixth inning, a solid seven-plus
innings from righthander Scott Elarton (10-4) and a clutch relief
performance from newly anointed closer Octavio Dotel to complete
their first three-game sweep of the season and first in Cincinnati
since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The sweep also was the first for the Astros since taking three
from the Cubs last Sept. 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning makes everybody happy,'' said Jeff Bagwell, who hit
his 28th home run as the Astros rallied from a 2-0 deficit. ``When
you're losing every single night the way we've lost, you're not
going to see this kind of atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds blew a lead for the third straight game as the Astros
hit three bases-empty home runs off Steve Parris (5-13) during a
span of eight pitches in the sixth inning. Rookie Julio Lugo led
off with a first-pitch homer, his second of the season, and Bagwell
followed two pitches later with a shot off the right-field foul
screen to tie the score at 2.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, who also hit a go-ahead, two-run homer in the ninth
inning of Tuesday's 7-4 victory, has homered in five of his last
six games.
</P>
<P>
   After Daryle Ward struck out, Moises Alou hit his 16th home run
_ a towering blast that landed several rows into the upper deck at
Cinergy Field. It was only the 33rd red-seat homer in the stadium's
30-year history, and Alou was the first Astro to reach the upper
deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good. I knew it was gone when I hit it,'' said Alou,
who hit the only other upper-deck shot of his career in 1993 at New
York's Shea Stadium off Dwight Gooden while with the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton, who lasted only 3 innings in his last start July 21,
became the Astros' first 10-game winner. He allowed two runs and
five hits before exiting the game with two out in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing a solo home run to Michael Tucker in the second
inning and a run-scoring double to Ken Griffey Jr. in the third,
Elarton retired 14 of the next 15 batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I pride myself on is getting stronger as the
game goes along,'' said Elarton, who has won six of his last seven
starts. ``I just feel so much better than I did earlier in the
season. Things are starting to fall in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton allowed consecutive two-out singles in the eighth before
Dierker decided to insert Dotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Elarton) told me he thought I was making the wrong
decision,'' Dierker said. ``Afterward, he told me it worked out,
but he still thought I made the wrong decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Elarton: ``I didn't want to come out. Everything worked
out. Dotel did a great job in a tough situation.''
</P>
<P>
   With runners at first and second, Dotel retired Griffey on a fly
to center field. He allowed a single in the ninth before striking
out the final two batters for his second save.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel hasn't allowed a run in eight relief appearances covering
9 innings since replacing injured lefthander Billy Wagner in the
closer role July 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is going to help my career as a starter being in
these tough situations,'' Dotel said.
</P>
<P>
   During their five-game winning streak, the Astros are hitting a
collective .365 with 14 home runs. They have reached double-digits
hit totals in each game, including 11 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you some confidence,'' Dierker said of the club's
recent success. ``When you play as poorly as we have this year,
generally you don't have things go your way. You're expecting
things to go wrong. Now that we've had some things go right maybe
we'll start to believe they will go right.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, a 3-0 start to a 10-game road trip has put the
hop back into the Astros' dance step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody in the clubhouse knows we can play and
should have played this way the whole year,'' Elarton said. ``Now
we feel more relaxed and are able to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
