<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-Cowboys-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
High school coach Seder battling for roster spot as Cowboys kicker
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WICHITA FALLS _ Cowboys kicking coach Steve Hoffman is constantly
soliciting videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   Those he likes end up in a stack on his desk. Those he doesn't
like end up in his VCR for re-recording. He's particularly fond of
old John Wayne flicks.
</P>
<P>
   On rare occasions, a tape leads him to a future Cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Seder hopes to be that rare one.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's still hard for him to believe he's here. He
expected to be on a football field this fall. That field, however,
wasn't at Valley Ranch or Texas Stadium, but at Lucas High School
in Ashland, Ohio, where Seder coached the offensive line and
special teams.
</P>
<P>
   He had dreamed of kicking in the NFL and had made the tape for
Hoffman three years before after his coach at Ashland University
had bent Hoffman's ear at the scouting combine. Three years later,
Seder didn't know the tape still existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was done,'' Seder said. ``I still kept working
out, doing things because I was coaching. But at that point, I
thought I was moving on in a different direction with my career,
teaching, coaching, that type of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Seder received a call from Hoffman, who hadn't seen him in
person. Up to that point, Hoffman was going off a recommendation
and a short video, made on a home camera, that featured Seder
kicking into a net at the high school gym.
</P>
<P>
   He'd kept in shape, but there was snow on the ground in Ohio, so
the indoor net was the only practice he'd had. And he had no shoes.
The closest thing he had was a pair of indoor soccer shoes, which
Seder had lent to a student. He got them back and made the trip to
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Are you going to kick in those?''' Hoffman said. ``He
said, `They're all I've got.' He's a real humble guy. I'm sure he
wasn't making $100,000 a year in coaching to buy others. And I
said, `OK, do whatever you have to do to warm up,' and his first
kick wasn't so good and I thought, `Oh, boy, here we go,' then his
second kick was right down the middle and way up in the net. Then
he did it the whole workout.''
</P>
<P>
   He went home and eventually told his students about the
opportunity. They then helped him get into shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think that I pushed them to make them better and
they try to do the same thing for me,'' Seder said. ``Especially
when they heard I was going to be playing. They knew I needed to
get myself in shape and they pushed me as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Seder still had to compete with several others to earn a spot on
the training camp roster. He did, and is now one of only two
kickers in camp. Rookie Rian Lindell out of Washington State is the
other candidate. Neither has pulled away as the favorite 10 days
into camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like humble guys,'' Hoffman said. ``I like guys who keep
their mouth shut and just do their job. You've got to find the guy
who is capable, the guy who has the proper technique to keep from
getting in a slump, and you have to find the guy who's strong
enough mentally to handle it. And ever since I've been around
(Seder), I get the feeling more and more he can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He's made improvements as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We changed the way he came out of his stance,'' Hoffman said.
``He had a little hop step, a little hop and a jab step. A lot of
kickers have these little quirks, but I always try to convince a
guy to get rid of that because it leads to inconsistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Seder's coaching experience is one of his biggest assets,
Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think being a coach has probably helped him _ a lot,''
Hoffman said. ``You're preaching discipline and hard work to your
kids and now you're on the other side of it. His character is that
way. He's just that kind of guy. He won't go off track much.''
</P>
<P>
   At 25, with a few of years of coaching behind him, he's a
smarter player, Seder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My approach is a little bit different,'' he said. ``I think
it's important that you pay attention to detail. You learn as you
get a little bit older to pay attention to detail, do a lot of
little things (to get) yourself ready, the mental approach.''
</P>
<P>
   The two kickers would never be confused in a lineup. Seder looks
the part, at 5-9 and 180 pounds. Lindell fits in better with the
linebackers, standing 6-3 and weighing 235.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rian's biggest advantage is his strength,'' Hoffman said.
``You see a lot of kickers in the summertime who can kick 53-yard
field goals. But some make 53-yard field goals by a yard. Rian's
making it by 15 yards. The guy who's making them by a yard isn't
going to hold up in December in the Meadowlands, because now his
40-yarders are making it by a yard. Rian, when he gets a hold of
it, just clobbers it because he's so big and strong. When he
mishits a ball, he still has the strength to get it there.''
</P>
<P>
   Seder has good strength as well. He made a 60-yarder at Texas
Stadium before camp opened, then hit a 52-yarder Wednesday that
could have gone another 15. The job, therefore, isn't expected to
be won on strength, but consistency.
</P>
<P>
   And if neither is deemed the answer, there are plenty waiting in
the wings. Eddie Murray, who joined the Cowboys midway through last
season, is still out there, as is Richie Cunningham, who was cut to
create that vacancy for Murray. Chris Boniol, Jeff Jaeger, Michael
Husted and Chris Jacke are among a list of about 10 veterans who
could come in on a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to try to get a young guy for (the rookie minimum)
$193,0000,'' Hoffman said. ``We're going to try to orchestrate
their success. But at the end of August, hopefully Tim or Rian has
convinced us and they're good enough and confident enough. I feel
pretty good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seder admits the dream won't be complete unless he makes the
team. He does know, however, he has a really nice life to return to
even if the dream isn't realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that is what I do, but it's certainly not who I
am,'' Seder said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
